<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-ROBERTSON-COL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York TimesNews Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   Only Sampras left &QL; 
to carry U.S. flag
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
WIMBEDON, England _ ``How does it feel,'' the sad-faced British
sportswriter asked Wednesday, ``to be in a country that's in
mourning?''
</P>
<P>
   Being a compassionate person, I expressed my proper condolences
for England's demise on a penalty shootout in the World Cup. But it
wouldn't be until much later in the day before I could honestly
feel the man's pain. When Venus Williams went down kicking and
screaming _ mostly the latter _ at Wimbledon, the massacre was
complete.
</P>
<P>
   The quarterfinal round began with three American women still
competing for tennis' most prized title and ended with every one of
them out on their uh, ears. While I doubt the entire U.S.
population went into a big funk over this, a certain U.S.
television network with tailfeathers probably has as much empathy
with how down the English fans are today.
</P>
<P>
   As the headline in the Daily Mirror screamed, ``IT'S JUST TOO
CRUEL TO TAKE.''
</P>
<P>
   The peacock gang needn't break into sobs, though. At least
Pistol Pete Sampras lives to fire again, as opposed to our
yanked-out Yank lassies. Sampras' bid to establish himself as the
most accomplished player in the history of men's tennis continues.
His outslugging Mark Philippoussis left him two match victories shy
of his fifth Wimbledon title, which would then leave him trailing
only Roy Emerson in career Grand Slams won. But to claim his 11th,
tying him with Rod Laver and Bjorn Borg behind Emmo's 12, he must
go through Britain's Tim Henman on Friday. Yikes. I don't know how
the Brits will react if their Tim follows their Lions down the
tube, Sampras or no Sampras opposite him. They might do something
really drastic, like overthrow the monarchy or endorse the Euro.
Has an entire kingdom ever been put under a suicide watch?
</P>
<P>
   Nothing to see here
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of overthrows, that's pretty much what happened among
the women. We could have had Monica Seles vs. Lindsay Davenport in
one of the semis today, sending an American _ albeit a naturalized
one in Seles' case _ to Centre Court on the Fourth of July.
Instead, we've got Natasha Zvereva vs. Nathalie Tauziat.
</P>
<P>
   That's two players who define the term journeywoman.
</P>
<P>
   That's also TV ratings as in dead.
</P>
<P>
   Throw in Jana Novotna, the queen of England's also-rans, and you
have 39 prior Wimbledons they've played fruitlessly, although
Novotna has made two finals, blowing both.
</P>
<P>
   Tauziat, who first came to Wimbledon in 1984 when the defending
champion, 17-year-old Martina Hingis, was 3, had never advanced
beyond the quarters in her first 42 Grand Slams. Guess 43's a
charm.
</P>
<P>
   Zvereva? Her last venture this deep into a major a decade ago as
a finalist in the French Open opposite Steffi Graf ended with her
incurring the most lopsided thrashing ever in a final Slam dance,
male or female, since the Open Era began.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, the weather is supposed to stay dicey through the
weekend. Henman by his lonesome is left to salvage this most dreary
of fortnights for the Brits. But ditto Sampras for us in the
Colonies.
</P>
<P>
   Davenport, Williams and Seles all appeared on track for
breakthroughs. That none could even manage the semis is somewhat
astounding, particularly given the pedigrees of those who did _
save, of course, for Mighty Miss Hingis.
</P>
<P>
   An unlikely story
</P>
<P>
   Zvereva possessed gaudy doubles credentials, but she began the
tournament a combined 0-21 against Graf and Seles in singles play.
John McEnroe said it reminded him of the late Vitas Gerulaitis, who
upon finally defeating Bjorn Borg after 17 consecutive losses to
the Swede, said: ``Listen, nobody beats Vitas Gerulaitis 18 times
in a row.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Zvereva is 2-21 against them, having taken out Seles after
bouncing Graf, a rare tournament double accomplished before only by
Zina Garrison here in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   At least Tauziat, a Wimbledon quarterfinalist in 1992 and again
last year, is considered a grass-court diva of minor note despite
having roots deep in French clay. Asked if she thought she would
put a 6-3, 6-3 pounding on a woman, Davenport, ranked No. 2 in the
world, Tauziat appeared miffed by the question.
</P>
<P>
   ``On grass, yes,'' Tauziat replied coldly.
</P>
<P>
   Novotna obviously held a huge experience advantage over
Williams, but Venus is such a promising talent that her reputation
greatly exceeds her rsum.
</P>
<P>
   Any time now, we expect her to blow by everyone, Hingis
included, and take control of the tour.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, though, she couldn't even control her emotions.
Three line calls made her go crazy (she was right about one of
them) to the point that she began screeching at the chair umpire:
``I know it's out. She knows it's out. Everyone knows it's out. But
you don't know it's out.''
</P>
<P>
   We've never seen Williams behave thusly before. She sounded like
all of England _ and NBC _ must have felt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
