<SLUG> BC-GLF-LPGA-FRUHWIRTH-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRUHWIRTH PACKS BIG PUNCH HEADING INTO WOMEN'S OPEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL HUFFMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A year ago, Amy Fruhwirth would have been a long shot at best to
win the U.S. Women's Open on a treacherous course such as the one
being used this week for the national championship.
</P>
<P>
   Blackwolf Run, with fairways and greens that weave their way
through the thick forests near Kohler, Wis., would have eaten her
alive.
</P>
<P>
   But Fruhwirth, who once upon a time was golf's version of Little
Red Riding Hood, is packing a new weapon these days that keeps the
big, bad wolf at bay. It's called a PING TiSI driver, and she never
leaves home without it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's made a huge difference in my game,'' said the 5-foot-2
Fruhwirth, a former Arizona State All-American who lives in
Scottsdale. ``Last year, I was averaging about 210 yards (off the
tee), whereas this year, I'm in the 220 to 230 range.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of having to hit a 3-wood into the long par 4s, I'm
hitting a 7-wood. At other times, I'm getting to hit a 5-iron
instead of the 7-(wood). Everything is shorter with a lot more
loft. It's just really changed everything, because most of that
yardage with the driver is carry, not roll, something you have to
have when you're playing out here.''
</P>
<P>
   That partially explains why Fruhwirth, who has been on the LPGA
Tour for six years, finally broke through two weeks ago, making the
Friendly's Classic her first professional victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was all unexpected,'' admitted Fruhwirth, 29, who always
has had a brilliant short game. ``I didn't think I'd ever win out
here because I'd been hoping it would happen for so long, and when
it didn't . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Frustration set in. Despite ``good years'' in 1996 and '97, when
she finished 30th and 37th on the money list, this season had been
just so-so: one top-10 finish in Tucson and an 11th at the Dinah
Shore. In the previous six tournaments before her win, she made
only two cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was getting down on myself,'' said Fruhwirth, who many felt
didn't have the length off the tee as a pro to match her success in
college, when she won the 1991 U.S. Amateur and '92 U.S. Public
Links championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't like I was snap-hooking everything and getting in
all kinds of trouble. Just subtle things kept leading to a lot of
bogeys.
</P>
<P>
   ``I finally said, `Don't be so hard on yourself.' I was fully
prepared to write this season off and go on, and then just when I
least expected it . . . the unexpected.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, 1998 has been a year to remember for Fruhwirth, and not
just because the $90,000 check she earned at the Friendly's nearly
tripled her biggest payday ever. She also got married in January to
Paul Hornung.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of changes,'' she said of the union to Hornung, who just
happens to work for Phoenix-based Karsten Manufacturing, makers of
that PING driver.
</P>
<P>
   ``For one thing, it's more difficult being on the road than I
thought. I really miss him.''
</P>
<P>
   But there's good news, she said. ``He's flying in (today), and
I'm really psyched to see him.''
</P>
<P>
   Fruhwirth said she'll need all the help she can get because
Blackwolf Run is extremely long (6,412 yards, par 71).
</P>
<P>
   ``There are three or four par 4s that are difficult to reach in
two (strokes),'' she said. ``Plus, the greens are big and
undulating.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really do think that even-par will be a great score. Maybe
even the winning score.''
</P>
<P>
   Thank goodness for the new PING driver, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just that I'm getting more distance, I'm also hitting
it very accurately,'' said Fruhwirth, who is leading the tour in
driving accuracy by hitting 82 percent of her fairways. ``The
combination of the new (titanium) head and the new (grafalloy)
shaft have been a perfect fit for for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Fruhwirth said she originally had another shaft in the driver,
but that a switch has proved dramatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something that most amateurs don't realize, how
important the shaft is,'' said ``Giggles,'' whose nickname comes
from a happy-go-lucky attitude that sometimes is plagued by
nervousness.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can take 20 shafts and the same head, and just one of
those shafts might fit just right. It can make all the difference
in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Will the new driver, plus her success in past U.S. Golf
Association-sponsored events, allow her to compete against the
likes of Open favorite Annika Sorenstam this weekend?
</P>
<P>
   ``The driver will definitely help, but the Open is so different
(than the Amateur or Publinks) because of the format (stroke vs.
match play),'' she said. ``I'm going to have to be at the top of my
game and really chip and putt well.''
</P>
<P>
   Who knows? Perhaps the ``other Open'' even helped her in a
roundabout way, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``To win is the best feeling in the world, even though it's a
relief more than anything,'' she said. ``At the same time, I've
been able to take (the victory) in stride because there wasn't
really a lot of attention focused on me.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the same weekend of the men's (U.S.) Open, so there
was no TV or real media attention on me winning. It kept me
grounded.''
</P>
<P>
   At least until she gets home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, that's going to be fun,'' she said of her triumphant
return to the Valley. ``I guess there are a lot of cards waiting
for me, and a lot of people are real excited. That's probably when
the win is really going to hit me.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
