<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-MERCURY-GILLOM-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERCURY GETS BIG LIFT FROM AGELESS GILLOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jennifer Gillom thought she'd forgotten what she learned all
those years ago in Abbeville, a town of 500 tucked into
northwestern Mississippi, an hour's drive from Memphis.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, there was much she retained. Such as the values that
had been drilled into her by her mother, Ella Ree Gillom; her older
brothers, who replaced the father who died when she was 3; and the
extended congregation at the Providence United Methodist Church.
And the hearty smile and laugh that draw children to her like some
sort of Pied Piper.
</P>
<P>
   But what seemed to have escaped Gillom soon after she left
Abbeville for stardom 12 miles up the road at the University of
Mississippi in Oxford were the one-on-one basketball moves
practiced, hour after hour, on a dirt court in a pasture with her
nine siblings and especially her cousin, Terry Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, she enjoyed a successful four years at Ole Miss _
earning Southeastern Conference female Athlete of the Year in
1985-86 and ranking second to her sister, Peggie, in career
scoring. But those who enjoy watching Gillom play today _ flashing
across the lane like a 6-foot-3 land-to-air missile; executing a
picture-perfect baseline fade; feeling the pressure of her younger
and taller opposition, then spinning past it; spotting up for a
three-pointer _ might not have recognized her in college.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to do those moves all the time when I was little,'' she
recalled. ``We would get out there at least three or four hours a
day, just practicing on different moves, counting down the clock,
different things like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like I'd forgotten it when I was in college, but then
it's like it just all came back to me, those days when we used to
watch the NBA and just practice on the dirt court. It's like it's
all coming back to me late in life, which I can't understand
because I had it all the time, but I just didn't use it. Now it
seems like it's come back.''
</P>
<P>
   What the WNBA and Mercury are seeing is Gillom playing like a
34-year-old kid. A decade after she won an Olympic gold medal and
12 years after she and her Mercury coach, Cheryl Miller, were U.S.
teammates during the summer of 1986, she is averaging 15.9 points,
fifth best in the league through Tuesday. &QL; 
`I feel like I'm 24' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel like I'm 34. I feel like I'm 24,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me like I'm getting better with age, like the wine
deal. That's totally shocking to me. It's like I'm in a dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot believe after all these years I'm able to keep up
with that same performance. I think perseverance is the key word
here. I used to just go out and play. Now I think about what I need
to do before a game. I prepare myself better. The main thing I can
say is I've been blessed.''
</P>
<P>
   Blessed never to have been seriously injured, unlike Miller, who
is only five months her senior but whose knees essentially gave out
after 1986, ending a Hall of Fame playing career.
</P>
<P>
   Miller jokingly blames her premature retirement as a player on
Gillom, retelling a story from their teammate days in Moscow that
nearly rocks the accused to the floor in laughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big thing on our (1986 World Championship) team was to try
to see who you could scare to death,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that time, it was truly Big Jen, she was a ``big'' girl. I
slipped under her bed, waiting for her to come in, and as soon as
she was halfway asleep jump out and scare her.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were sleeping on cots, so when she laid down, the cot came
all the way underneath, and she pinned me. Finally I started
moaning, and that's when she started screaming. That's exactly what
ended my career, Jen laying on me.''
</P>
<P>
   Gillom said, ``I had no idea she was under there. All of a
sudden I saw this hand come from under my bed, and I just started
screaming and running. But I got her back.''
</P>
<P>
   And so we get the rest of the story, though it was not
volunteered by Miller.
</P>
<P>
   It seems Gillom organized a middle-of-the-night raid with the
co-conspirators, including 6-8 Anne Donovan, dressing in long
hooded raincoats and painting their faces white with facial cream.
``We had candles in our hands, surrounded Cheryl's bed and tapped
her on the foot,'' Gillom said. ``She just freaked out. I got her
really bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller doesn't hold a grudge. She remains one of Gillom's
biggest fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jen is the same today as she was 80 years ago,'' she said.
``Just soft-spoken, great personality, silent leader, quick to
encourage, quick to listen, slow to speak and slow to anger.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's one of the many players I'm so glad this league came for
when it did, because they did more than just put in their time.'' &QL; 
Praise from college coach &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Her college coach, Van Chancellor, now directing the WNBA
champion Houston Comets, recalls a game against Louisiana Tech when
Gillom had 26 points and 16 rebounds but drew his ire for poor
defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``After I thought about what a poor statement that was on my
part, I called her up to the front (of the bus) and apologized,''
Chancellor said. He asked her why she quietly took his harsh
comments. ``She said you were the coach and you were right, I
didn't guard anybody. I'm just telling you what a wonderful person
and easily coachable person she is.''
</P>
<P>
   After college, Italy became a first home of sorts for Gillom.
She spent two-thirds of the year there from 1987 to '96, making a
living and praying for her country to turn on to the women's game
before it was too late for her to benefit.
</P>
<P>
   Gillom and many of the 1986 U.S. teammates won a Pan American
Games gold medal in 1987 and the Olympic gold in '88. But mostly
they toiled in obscurity overseas, seeing the world but not being
seen by those who mattered most to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe going overseas helped me to get mentally tough,'' said
Gillom, who also played a season in Greece before the first year of
the WNBA and cashed in her All-WNBA second-team credentials for a
six-figure salary in Turkey during the most recent off-season. ``I
can see where that has been a factor in my career. All of the
issues I had to go through, it says a lot. It helps you to grow and
to learn.''
</P>
<P>
   When the WNBA made its first player allocations in January 1997,
the Mercury was assigned Australian point guard Michele Timms and
Gillom, a forward. Both have lived up to their cornerstone
expectations, leading Phoenix to the Western Conference title last
year and triggering a much deeper team to a 6-2 start this season
heading into today's 4 p.m. game in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love playing with Jen, especially when we get the two-man
game going really well together,'' Timms said. ``She never ceases
to amaze me how she can score that big bucket.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially because Gillom has never been known as much of a
practice player.
</P>
<P>
   ``She likes to practice, but she likes to practice by getting
out there on her own and doing what she wants to do,'' said Peggie
Gillom, who recruited Jennifer to follow her at the University of
Mississippi and helped to coach her there.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we had her, she was never good in practice, but my God,
when the lights come on, that's what counts for her.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, as Timms said, ``When she crosses the white line, she's
superwoman.'' &QL; 
Playing tougher defense &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gillom's statistics are slightly better in the first quarter of
this season than last year, especially rebounding (6.4 average) and
steals (1.75), where she's in the league's top 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's playing defense this year,'' Timms said. ``I know the
goal in Jen's head is to be the MVP, and to do that she's got to
play at both ends.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's not individual honors that drive Gillom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never looked at myself as a star, and I still don't,'' she
said. ``That's what kept me humble, to continue to dream, to
continue to get better and better. A lot of people get satisfied
with themselves at a younger age. I've never been like that.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
