<HEADLINE>
MACHINES TO SELL CARDINALS TICKETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ZUCKERMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, ARIZ. - The Cardinals announced plans Wednesday to begin
distributing tickets through the ETM Entertainment Network, ending
their 10-year partnership with Dillard's ticket outlets.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets for all 10 home games this season will go on sale Monday
and can be purchased at ETM ticket machines located at selected
Safeway stores, over the phone or via ETM's website. The ETM ticket
machines operate like a bank automatic teller machine and
distribute tickets through self-service kiosks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think fans are going to be excited about having ticket
outlets much closer to their homes,'' said Michael Bidwill,
Cardinals vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Bidwill said the advanced technology and convenience associated
with the ETM machines made the company a logical choice to take
over the ticket distribution. The machines utilize a touch screen
that allows fans to specify the game, seat location and price of
tickets they are interested in, and can complete the average
transaction in less thn a minute.
</P>
<P>
   Fans wishing to buy their tickets the old-fashioned way still
can do so by calling ETM at (888) 386-8497. Those connected to the
Internet can purchase tickets at www.etm.com on the World Wide Web.
Whether purchased over the phone or the Internet, all tickets can
be picked up via the ``will call'' feature of the ETM kiosks at the
fans' convenience.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets are also available at the Cardinals ticket office in
Tempe, 8701 S. Hardy Drive, and at Sun Devil Stadium on game days.
</P>
<P>
   There is no maximum number of tickets that can be purchased by
one person at the machines, but Bidwill said only eight may be
bought per transaction.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals are expected to announce 1998 season ticket
figures by Monday, just as single-game tickets go on sale. The team
will once again offer a ``FlexPack'' ticket plan in which fans can
buy tickets for the same seats to three games. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
