<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-DODGERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHEFFIELD PULLS ALL-STAR REVERSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ One day and one impassioned meeting with
general manager Tom Lasorda later, Gary Sheffield agreed to
represent the Dodgers at Tuesday's All-Star Game in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield originally planned to spend the three-day break in
Tampa, Fla., with his family, whom he hasn't seen since spring
training. He was acquired May 15 in the Mike Piazza trade with
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   But Lasorda spoke to Sheffield before Wednesday's 7-5 Dodgers
victory and convinced him that the club wanted him there _ for the
National League, and his own reputation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know, ask the boss,'' said Sheffield, who was named to
his fourth All-Star team. ``We talked and I'm going.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of Lasorda's appeal to Sheffield was that this is the right
fielder's first year with the struggling club. Sheffield is in the
first season of a six-year, $66 million contract that includes $5
million to compensate for tax differences between Florida and
California.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to tell you what I told him,'' Lasorda said.
``If I wanted you to know what I said, I would have left the door
open.''
</P>
<P>
   Lasorda provided one concession for Sheffield, who was selected
by Jim Leyland, his former Marlins manager. Sheffield will fly in
the day of the game and not have to attend Monday's workout, which
is All-Star policy.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers called the National League and the request was
approved. Seattle's Ken Griffey Jr. also will not attend the
workout.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, Sheffield returns to Los Angeles but will not
have to participate in Wednesday's workout at Dodger Stadium. The
season resumes Thursday at home against the division-leading San
Diego Padres.
</P>
<P>
   One for two: Lasorda wasn't quite so successful convincing Eric
Young to go on the disabled list after the second baseman strained
his right thigh muscle for the third time in six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Lasorda said Tuesday he was placing Young on the DL and calling
up minor-league infielder Joey Cora. Trainers said Wednesday
Young's condition had improved, and Young was not pleased with
Lasorda's announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Young, the NL leader with 32 stolen bases, will miss five games,
then use the three-game All-Star break to rest the leg. Young has
missed a total of 10 starts at second, including six straight from
June 18-24.
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi understands: Unlike Sheffield, Raul Mondesi wanted to
the go to the All-Star Game. He leads the team with 18 homers and
is batting .390 (14 for 36) in his last nine games.
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi, who made the NL All-Star team in 1995, will spend the
break in his native Dominican Republic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a great time, but that's OK,'' he said. ``To me, I am an
All-Star. That's the important thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Quick hit: Matt Luke started in left and had a double in two
at-bats. But he was ejected in the fourth for arguing with
home-plate umpire Rich Garcia after getting thrown out at the
plate. Replays showed Luke was not tagged by Rangers catcher Ivan
Rodriguez.
</P>
</TEXT>
