<HEADLINE>
ANGLERS HEAD FOR HILLS  
 ENJOY COOL JULY 4, BUT DON'T EXPECT GREAT FISHING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARRY BURKHART  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOREST LAKES, ARIZ. _ The days have become uncomfortably warm at
times on the Mogollon Rim, but when the sun disappears, all is well
again. A sleeping bag feels good as temperatures fall.
</P>
<P>
   And even during the hottest part of the day, the pines provide
shade and comfort as you sit against one and devour a sack lunch.
</P>
<P>
   With the arrival of blistering heat in the desert, highways to
the mountains will be glutted with vehicles by this afternoon as
Valley residents rush to escape the pizza oven and refresh
themselves over the long July Fourth weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Many of them will spend at least some time fishing for trout.
It's unfortunate that during the heat of summer, when most people
do their trout fishing, results are the poorest.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, the Arizona Game and Fish Department planned to
attempt to improve fishing by stocking the state's mountain lakes
just before the holiday. Two of the state's most popular fishing
lakes _ Woods Canyon and Willow Springs near here _ were marked for
frequent visits by hatchery trucks carrying trout. Both were to
receive double stockings.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Sorensen, head of hatcheries for Game and Fish, said the
pH factor, which measures the balance of acid to base, is starting
to rise rapidly in the mountain lakes. When the two are perfectly
balanced, the pH reading is 7. If the count is below 7, the acidity
is rising. That almost never happens in Arizona lakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never see acidic water here unless there's a mine spill or
something like that,'' Sorensen said. ``What happens is that the
level of base content rises. I think Arizona is all calcium (a base
material).''
</P>
<P>
   That means the pH level rises, and when it does, fish start to
become lethargic.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it reaches 9.2 to 9.5, we start to some problems,''
Sorensen said. Somewhere above that, fish will begin to die. At
shallow, weedy lakes such as Sierra Blanca northeast of Big Lake,
the pH reading is rising quickly, he said, but it hasn't risen
substantially at most area lakes.
</P>
<P>
   When monsoon rains arrive, they will bring acid from the air
into the lakes and ease the problem somewhat. ``But it would have
to be a heavy, localized storm cell to make much difference,''
Sorensen said.
</P>
<P>
   But because of substantial precipitation during the winter and
spring, lakes should be in a little better condition than they
normally are at this time of year, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Stream fishing should be better than usual, too. There is more
water running, and pH factors generally are good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normally, the East and West forks of the Black River would be
getting up there by this time of year,'' Sorensen said. ``But we've
had no trouble at all so far this summer.''
</P>
<P>
   Weedy lakes suffer the most. The rise in pH is a byproduct of
plant photosynthesis _ a chemical process that plants use when
exposed to light.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why fishing is at its best in the early morning at this
time of year,'' Sorensen said. ``During the night, the
(photosynthesis) stops, and so the water is in the best shape for
fishing in early morning.''
</P>
<P>
   He said most lakes on the Mogollon Rim are in good shape. Big
Lake, probably the deepest of the mountain lakes, seldom is
affected much. Trout just go deeper there.
</P>
<P>
   This could be pretty good weekend in the mountains for anglers.
</P>
<P>
   And remember, campfire and smoking restrictions were imposed in
parts of all six National Forests in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   In the affected areas, smoking, campfires and charcoal are
banned except for developed campgrounds. Until monsoon rains
arrive, fire danger will continue to increase. &QL; 
Barry Burkhart can be reached at 602-444-8454 or at
barry.burkhart(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
