<SLUG> BC-WILD-WILD-WEST-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WARNER SADDLES UP `WILD WILD WEST' REMAKE FOR SUMMER '99 RELEASE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE McNARY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Warner Bros. has made it official, staking its
claim to next year's Fourth of July weekend with ``Wild Wild West''
as a way of telling rivals to stay away from the lucrative date.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's announcement that Will Smith's next comic adventure
movie will open during the Independence Day weekend ``is the
studio's way of saying, we're so confident that everyone else
should beware and not release their big films at the same time,''
said Paul Dergarabedian, head of tracker Exhibitor Relations Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a smart move if they can back it up,'' he added. ``Making
the announcement now creates some good early buzz.''
</P>
<P>
   Independence Day weekend is the prime release date for
Hollywood's big-budget projects, or at least has been in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Independence Day'' and ``Men in Black'' -- both coincidentally
starring Smith -- posted five-day openings during the 1996 and 1997
July Fourth weekends, respectively, that topped $84 million.
Disney, which claimed this weekend well over a year ago, opened
``Armageddon'' at 20 theaters late Tuesday and took in an
impressive $115,448, then moved it into 3,070 more sites Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Production on ``Wild Wild West'' began in May under ``Men in
Black'' director Barry Sonnenfeld with co-stars Kevin Kline,
Kenneth Branagh and Salma Hayek. It's based on the offbeat TV
series, which ran from 1966-69 and starred Robert Conrad as
debonair government agent James West during the presidency of
Ulysses S. Grant.
</P>
<P>
   The script calls for Arliss Loveless, played by Branagh, to plot
a government overthrow with the aid of a massive walking weapon
called The Tarantula.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Bucksbaum, president of the Reel Source forecasting
service, said Warner's rivals may still mount a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though it's got Will Smith, I don't think the idea grabs
you the same way as (`Independence Day')'' he said, adding that
other contenders for the slot include Universal's ``edTV,'' a
comedy similar to ``The Truman Show,'' and Sony's ``Joan of Arc,''
with Milla Jovovich.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
