<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ALLSTARS-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS ISN'T A TRUE ALL-STAR GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO - Excuse me, but Devon White isn't worthy. Neither is
anyone else in a Diamondbacks uniform. And if the Florida Marlins
had a legitimate All-Star, he would've been pawned off months ago.
</P>
<P>
   No surprise, but baseball whiffed again Wednesday. It rewarded
mediocrity. It selected a former scab. It ignored a phenomenon. It
made the All-Star Game a joke.
</P>
<P>
   And if you're not laughing, you're in the middle of a big yawn.
</P>
<P>
   Here's all you need to know: Kerry Wood is not going to the
showcase event. Rick Reed, a former replacement player pitching for
the New York Mets, is the second from his team to make the guest
list.
</P>
<P>
   ``He went?'' the Chicago Cubs' Mark Grace asked, jaw dropping.
``Come on.''
</P>
<P>
   The logic is baffling, and Marlins Manager Jim Leyland and
National League President Len Coleman squandered a golden
opportunity. All Wood did Wednesday was strike out 13 Diamondbacks,
raise his record to 8-3 and further a legacy that has helped
resuscitate the sport.
</P>
<P>
   Visionaries would've seized the moment, promoted the most
dominating pitcher in the game, a 20-year-old who leads the league
in strikeout ratio and opponent batting average. They would
recognize that, aside from Mark McGwire, he probably leads the
league in curious spectators drawn to the ticket window. They would
flaunt his staggering talent and hand him the ball, especially
since Wood won't pitch again until after the break.
</P>
<P>
   ``What better thing for baseball than take the kid and start
him?'' Grace said. ``He's the guy people want to see. Kerry Wood in
Colorado against the best hitters in the American League would've
been a great story for baseball. I know the ratings would've been
very high, and it would've been a great marketing tool.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, visionaries wouldn't have invited Albert Belle to
Cleveland last year, where he refused to take part in workouts,
wouldn't lend his face to the team picture and basically disgraced
the event. And they certainly wouldn't have embraced a work
stoppage that almost killed the game.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, they don't get it.
</P>
<P>
   ``People come from miles around to see Kerry pitch,'' Grace
said. ``Kerry has turned baseball upside down. He is special, a
captivating player who can dominate like nobody in the game today.
He's more deserving than just about anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem is a silly rule that states every team must
have a representative. It is counterproductive, backwards and
responsible for the selection of White, a nice player enjoying a
nice season and nothing more. It is responsible for Fernando Vina,
an average sort who has been caught stealing 10 times in 21
attempts, whose only fling with infamy remains the forearm he took
from Belle. It is responsible for Ugueth Urbina, Edgar Renteria and
Rolando Arrojo.
</P>
<P>
   Gentleman, this is not Little League, where tender psyches must
be protected and every uniform must be on display. All the while,
Grace and the St. Louis Cardinals' Brian Jordan will sit home with
averages hovering around .350.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, I went because one of us crummy Cubs had to go,''
Grace said. ``The only disappointment is, I thought for sure I
could help the National League in the home run hitting contest. So
I guess they'll miss out on the fireworks.''
</P>
<P>
   While there is criticism over the merits of a popularity
contest, the All-Star vote should belong to the fans. Each league
names its reserves to correct any glaring mistakes, which is fine
in theory. Except the quota system only makes the problem worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it happened, it would've been an honor. But it didn't,''
Wood said. ``Maybe next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is one year too late. This is supposed to be a marquee
event for the fans, and more than anything, the suits should give
you whom you want to see.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry Wood or Andy Ashby?
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, they held signs in the bleachers in Chicago for
every strikeout. And while they reached double digits for the fifth
time in 15 starts, a few K's were left over when Wood called it a
day.
</P>
<P>
   Hang 'em anyway. For Leyland, Coleman and a game that could use
a crash course in marketing. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at 602-444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
