<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-MAIN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HR in 9th rescues Braves
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG _ Russ Springer was initiated into Atlanta's
Order of the Torch Wednesday night. Due only to Chipper Jones and a
ninth-inning bolt from the blue, the newest Brave found himself
with his first win too. Wilted, but valid.
</P>
<P>
   Moments after Springer had blown away a one-run lead (and John
Smoltz's win) in a two-run eighth, Jones lined a low-flying two-run
homer to right off Tampa Bay closer Roberto Hernandez with Walt
Weiss on base to give the Braves a 6-5 victory over the Devil Rays.
Hernandez hadn't given up a run in 22 appearances, Jones hadn't hit
a homer before this night in 13 days and the Braves had come from
behind in the ninth only once before all season.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a player, you don't get a chance to do that very often,''
said Jones, playing before a large group of family friends from his
hometown of DeLand, Fla., two hours away. ``When you do it, it's
special.''
</P>
<P>
   The homer was Jones' second of the night and his 20th this
season, giving him two two-HR games this year and six in his
career. Kerry Ligtenberg then finished the game for his eighth
save, ending it on a double-play by Wade Boggs.
</P>
<P>
   Springer came in to guard a 4-3 lead for Smoltz (six innings,
five hits) but he coughed up two runs on a pair of singles by John
Flaherty and Dave Martinez, a Gerald Williams throwing error and
Rich Butler sacrifice fly for a 5-4 Tampa Bay advantage. The blown
save was the bullpen's ninth in 27 opportunities and its third in
the last 18 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``A good win for the team,'' said Springer, now 5-3 but
chagrined by the win. ``Obviously if you go in there and you give
up the lead like I did, the next thing is damage control, to try to
keep it close and give your team a chance in the ninth.''
</P>
<P>
   That chance was not vast. Hernandez, who entered the game with
17 saves, had yielded just one homer all year and no runs in his
previous 24 1/3 innings pitched. Weiss singled to open the inning
before Keith Lockhart struck out to bring up Jones, who had hit a
monstrous solo over nearly 420 feet in the first.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the guy throws hard and you just try to get the head
(of the bat) out and hope that one falls,'' said Jones, who
connected on a 1-1 fastball on the outer half of the plate. ``I
think I hit it 370 and a half (over the 370-foot mark). It was a
line drive that had a little top spin on it.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory was the Braves' fourth straight and restored their
division lead over the Mets to 9 1/2 games, as large as it has been
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
