<HEADLINE>
D-BACKS' WHITE MAKES NL ALL-STAR TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
 LL-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Devon White is 35, but he has played like a young colt
for the Diamondbacks this season, tracking down virtually
everything hit to him in center field and supplying punch with the
bat.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, he was recognized for his efforts by being named
the first player to represent the club on the National League
All-Star team for the game Tuesday at Coors Field in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   It will be the third All-Star appearance for White, first in the
NL. He played for the American League in 1989 while with the
California (now Anaheim) Angels and in 1993 while with the Toronto
Blue Jays.
</P>
<P>
   The switch-hitting White, who did not start Wednesday's game
against the Chicago Cubs but came up with an RBI infield single as
a pinch-hitter in the ninth inning, is hitting .290 with 12 homers,
45 RBIs and 10 stolen bases. He has hit primarily from the left
side (241 at-bats) with a .273 average, 11 homers and 38 RBIs. From
the right side (80 at-bats), he is hitting .338 with one homer and
seven RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very happy. I'm healthy and I think I've been playing good
ball,'' White said. ``You always think about it in the back of your
mind, but I've always been the type to wait for things to happen.
It will be good to see some of the guys I haven't seen in a
while.''
</P>
<P>
   That includes the man who selected him, Jim Leyland, who managed
White with the World Series champion Florida Marlins last season.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Travis Lee, who also is having a solid season, just as
easily could have been selected to represent the Diamondbacks,
White said. Lee will travel to Denver to participate in the rookie
skills challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tossup,'' White said. ``He's played very well on the
field and been a good example off the field. Maybe it's because
I've paid my dues, I don't know. I just feel pretty good about the
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Diamondbacks Manager Buck Showalter said: ``He's the right guy
to go from our club. We're awful proud of him. He started slow, but
he got it going and has been consistent ever since.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that he has been in the NL (this is his third season), which
league does White think is superior?
</P>
<P>
   ``For years, I thought the American was best, but now I think
the National is the best because it is a pitching and defense
league,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The All-Star Game annually adds fuel to the ``Which is best?''
debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The players always get together and joke around before the
game, but when the game starts, it gets serious. The players take a
lot of pride in that,'' White said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
