<SLUG> BC-NY-CHILD-ABUSE-SCENE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CLUTTERED ROOM HIDES DARK SECRETS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (With NY-CHILD-ABUSE)   (sw) 
 By KIT R. ROANE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The daughters' room is nestled inside a cramped
second-floor walk-up in Brooklyn, behind a metal door and past
great bales of clothes, toys and stuffed animals.
</P>
<P>
   On the walls and in photo albums, the girls, now 13 and 14,
smile back from pictures. Sometimes they are hugging their father,
Daniel Robacker, and mother, Theresa Fremgen, and other times they
are with a family friend, Curtis Elam James. But the pictures belie
a dark secret, the police say.
</P>
<P>
   All three of the adults, along with Ms. Fremgen's two brothers,
Ezra and Vincent Fremgen, are suspected of sexually abusing the
couple's teen-age girls and two other 8-year-old boys, the police
say. All five are in custody and awaiting arraignment.
</P>
<P>
   Only the children's grandmother, Helen Robacker, remains at her
son's Bushwick home, where the family has lived for eight years.
Hard of hearing and faint of sight, she spent Wednesday in a chair
in her living room, taking calls from reporters and looking up at
the family portraits.
</P>
<P>
   ``My son's no troublemaker because I raised him right, just like
my six other kids,'' the 75-year-old woman said as two dogs and a
cat roamed around the small three-room apartment.
</P>
<P>
   ``This thing is going to be thrown out. This is just phony
baloney. He don't do things like that.''
</P>
<P>
   In her son's bedroom, boxes of clothes, toys and bills are piled
high on top of a mattress. Sleeves for pornographic videos rest
near the door, juxtaposed against a father-of-the-year award
hanging on the wall. A sleeve for another pornographic video sits
by the doorjamb of his daughters' room, next to a stuffed bear with
``I love you'' written on its chest. And under the multitude of
photograph albums in the kitchen, two magazines devoted to swinging
peak out for anyone to see.
</P>
<P>
   In the daughters' room, three cages, all filled with hamsters,
sat on the dresser, which overflowed with teen magazines. On a
wall, small stuffed animals were hung up by string.
</P>
<P>
   Monique Morris, a homemaker who was sent to the apartment by
child welfare officials over the last eight months to help take
care of the household, said that she never felt right about the
children. On occasion, she chided Robacker, who is on disability,
about leaving his pornographic videos out for the girls to see and
also told him not to curse so much in front of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``These children just came back from the city because of neglect
in that house and I gave them my number to call if they wanted to
talk,'' she said. ``But I don't know what happens after 4 o'clock
because that's when I leave. It's sad, just so sad. The girls never
called.''
</P>
<P>
   Both girls have been placed with the city's Department of
Children's Services.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
