<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-CUBS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROOKIE UPENDS D-BACKS  
 WOOD FRUSTRATES ARIZONA WITH 13 K'S 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ KKKKKKKKKKKKKerry Wood did it again Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   For the second time, the rookie right-hander for the Chicago
Cubs struck out 13 Diamondbacks on the way to a victory. He
scattered three hits through eight innings and watched his bullpen
survive a shaky ninth as the Cubs held on for a 6-4 win over
Arizona at Wrigley Field.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks fell to 29-55, while the Cubs improved to
44-39. The teams meet again today in the finale of the three-game
series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wood was outstanding,'' said Diamondbacks Manager Buck
Showalter, whose team was victimized by Wood's 13 strikeouts in
seven innings on May 11 at Bank One Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Wood, who turned 21 a week ago, had a fastball that topped out
at 98 mph Wednesday. But it was his breaking ball that kept the
Diamondbacks off-balance and allowed him to raise his record to
8-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you gear up for that fastball, try and cheat a little bit
so you can get to it, it makes it difficult to pull the trigger,''
Showalter said. ``It just comes on a different plane at a different
speed.''
</P>
<P>
   Diamondbacks first baseman Travis Lee, who is Wood's primary
rival for the National League Rookie of the Year Award, struck out
twice against him in Phoenix and three times on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was zoned up for the fastball, and I didn't swing at any
high stuff, but he threw me plenty of breaking pitches,'' Lee said.
``He threw me three different kinds of sliders. There was a
12-to-6, where the hand comes over the top like at 12 o'clock and
the pitch starts out like a fastball, then comes down. There was a
back-door slider that froze me and a Frisbee slider, with some
weird spin that I had never seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Wrigley's high sky and breezy conditions were a factor in the
Cubs scoring their first run in the second inning off right-hander
Amaury Telemaco (2-3), who was waived by the Cubs on May 15.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Rodriguez led off the inning with a shallow high fly to
the opposite field in left. Diamondbacks shortstop Tony Batista,
filling in for Jay Bell (stiff back), and left fielder Yamil
Benitez converged on the ball, but it dropped and caromed off
Batista's leg into foul territory. Rodriguez wound up at second
with a double and later scored on a sacrifice fly by Tyler Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks tied it, 1-1, in the top of the third.
</P>
<P>
   Wood hit catcher Kelly Stinnett to lead off the inning, and
Telemaco grounded into a fielder's choice. Andy Fox bounced a
single over the head of first baseman Mark Grace and Telemaco took
off for third, surprising Cubs strong-armed right fielder Sammy
Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   As he neared third, Telemaco attempted to slide, but his foot
slipped, and he tumbled to the ground awkwardly, finally rolling
safely into the bag. He later scored on Batista's grounder that
third baseman Manny Alexander booted for an error.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw it on the replay and that was one of the ugliest slides
I've ever seen,'' Telemaco said. ``It was actually kind of scary
the way I fell. But things worked out.''
</P>
<P>
   Things worked out at least for the moment, but not in the bottom
of the third.
</P>
<P>
   With one out, Telemaco (2-3) hit Mickey Morandini in the foot,
and Sosa brought Morandini home with a rocket off the ivy-covered
brick wall in center for a double. Sosa, who set a major league
record with 20 home runs in June and was selected to the NL
All-Star team on Wednesday, had another run-scoring double in the
seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Grace hit an RBI single in the fifth, and a throwing error by
Benitez allowed another run to score to make it 4-1.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona's David Dellucci tripled to lead off the seventh and
scored on Karim Garcia's sacrifice fly to make it 4-2, but Chicago
increased its lead to 6-2 in its half of the seventh on Sosa's
second double and another RBI single by Grace.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Terry Adams replaced Wood in the ninth, and Cubs
closer Rod Beck replaced Adams. Arizona scored twice, on a grounder
by Brent Brede that went for an error by Grace, and an infield hit
by pinch-hitter Devon White. But Beck got Lee on a fielder's-choice
grounder to pick up his 19th save.
</P>
<P>
   Showalter said Telemaco was up in the strike zone with many of
his pitches, ``but he still kept us in the game.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
