<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-GOMEZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG CHANGES IN WINGS FOR ORIOLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Baltimore Orioles, who have not been afraid to spend money
since  &UR; Peter Angelos bought the club in 1993, may be on the verge
of dealing several of their high-salary free agents-to-be.
</P>
<P>
   Slumping badly and barely ahead of the expansion Tampa Bay Devil
Rays, Angelos is finally admitting that sweeping changes may be on
the way for what amounts to one of the most stagnant and least
versatile clubs in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   Topping the list of players on the block are second baseman
 &UR; Roberto Alomar _ who is playing as if he has lost interest but you
can bet would play like the All-Star he is after he is traded
(possibly to Atlanta), and first baseman  &UR; Rafael Palmeiro, who
could add some punch to a contending club lacking at first base,
perhaps San Diego or Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still a little too early to think about that, but the
time is rapidly approaching,'' Angelos said. ``Will we make moves
to obtain younger players for the future? If it improves our team
in the long term, of course we will. Why not? But we will also
continue to spend what it takes to put a competitive team on the
field.''
</P>
<P>
   General Manager  &UR; Pat Gillick, who built Toronto into one of the
finest organizations and has been with the Orioles the past three
years, is probably on his way out after this season, the last year
of his three-year contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's gone,'' one Orioles official said. ``He's told us he's
going to retire. He doesn't like the attitudes throughout baseball,
and he doesn't like some of the attitudes in our clubhouse.''
</P>
<P>
   Montreal Manager  &UR; Felipe Alou offered a biting assessment of the
Orioles after the Expos swept their three-game series last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``You really didn't see much heart out there,'' Alou said, ``but
we'll take three wins against anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore entered play Wednesday 22{ games behind the
division-leading New York Yankees, who are showing no signs of
slowing down. The real dagger through the heart for the Orioles is
their trailing second-place Boston, the wild-card leader, by 12{
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``All this agonizing and hand-wringing over what's happening is
unnecessary,'' Angelos said. ``Some of the players are out there
not hustling. But they're only human. It's simple: Look at our
pitching. It gets discouraging after a while.'' &QL; 
Trouble in Tampa Bay? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Strong rumors continue to persist that Devil Rays Managing
General Partner  &UR; Vince Naimoli is fighting off attempts from
several minority owners who are upset with the loose-lipped point
man of the expansion club.
</P>
<P>
   There has even been talk that some of the minority owners tried
to push Naimoli out of the limelight. Two of them apparently told
Naimoli they were not pleased with some of his recent comments,
several of which have infuriated fans, business leaders and area
officials.
</P>
<P>
   Naimoli apparently has taken the threat seriously enough that he
no longer refers to Tampa Bay's average attendance of 30,000 as
``disappointing.'' &QL; 
Keep looking for cassettes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia pitcher  &UR; Ken Ryan, rehabilitating an injury,
recently had his truck broken into while it sat at Philadelphia
International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   The thief (or thieves) rummaged through his glove compartment
and actually left behind a  &UR; Cal
 &UR; Ripken autographed baseball, which could be worth $200. ``Maybe
they couldn't read,'' Ryan joked. &QL; 
Hit redial again &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland Manager  &UR; Mike Hargrove took himself to task for
leaving in pitcher  &UR; Bartolo Colon too long during a start last
week. Colon, who is emerging as an elite pitcher in the AL, wound
up throwing 139 pitches over eight innings in what turned out to be
an 11-0 rout over the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Hargrove explained that he thought Colon had thrown only 90
pitches after seven innings, not the actual 110. Hargrove had set a
120-pitch limit for Colon. One possible explanation for Hargrove's
mix-up with pitch counts could be attributed to his tendency to get
caught up with trying be the official scorer for Indians games.
</P>
<P>
   A few games earlier, Hargrove called the press box eight times
to complain to the official scorer about a decision in the fifth
inning on a grounder by  &UR; Sandy Alomar that was booted by St. Louis
shortstop  &UR; David Howard.
</P>
<P>
   Official scorer  &UR; Rick Rembielak, the head baseball coach at Kent
University, stood his ground and refused to change the call. &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Pedro Gomez can be
reached at 602-444-2364 or at pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
