<HEADER>
A7173 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BELL-SNUBBED-HNS &LR;      07-02 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BELL-SNUBBED-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Alou named reserve for NL
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bell forced to deal with another All-Star Game snub
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By ALAN TRUEX &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
Even though the Astros are playing perhaps the best baseball in
their history and are sitting on a plush cushion atop the National
League Central, their clubhouse was not joyful Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The All-Star selections were out, and only two of the National
League's 30 were Astros. Second baseman Craig Biggio was in the
starting lineup via fan election, and left fielder Moises Alou was
added as a reserve by his former manager, Jim Leyland of the
Florida Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   Alou had ``mixed feelings'' about the honor. He had been looking
forward to a rare trip home to the Dominican Republic. Instead, he
will go to Denver next week ``and have fun and see some of my
ex-teammates.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked for more comment about his reunion with former
Marlins, Alou brought the interview session to a close. ``I'm not a
Marlin anymore,'' he said. ``I don't want to talk about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Like most of his Astros teammates, he was disappointed at the
size of Houston's delegation to Tuesday's 69th All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's got to be more All-Stars with our record,'' Alou said.
``We're not in first place just because of me and Craig.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astro with the strongest argument is probably right fielder
Derek Bell, who lost out to Dante Bichette of Colorado and Gary
Sheffield of Los Angeles. The three have similar offensive
statistics, but Bell, batting .331 with 11 home runs and 60 RBIs,
is having a better year defensively than the other two.
</P>
<P>
   It's still possible Bell could be chosen, since Colorado
outfielder Larry Walker, who was voted into the starting lineup by
the fans, is on the disabled list with an elbow injury.
</P>
<P>
   Astros general manager Gerry Hunsicker suggested Bell, closer
Billy Wagner and center fielder Carl Everett were having
All-Star-caliber seasons, but he added, ``I look at the National
League team, and I could not fault any of the selections.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell felt snubbed for the second time. He felt he could have
been selected in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``I come out every game and play hard, but unfortunately I was
snubbed again,'' he said. ``But I know I'm an All-Star in the
Houston community, and that's more important to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Wagner said an All-Star invitation ``would have been nice,'' but
he did not expect it.
</P>
<P>
   When pressed about Sheffield, who is the only Dodger on the
team, Hunsicker said, ``I guess you could make an argument that was
somewhat of a sentimental vote. But Sheffield is having a solid
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield played for Leyland last year, causing suspicions of
bias. But Astros manager Larry Dierker said, ``You've got to pick
your own guys if it's close. It's natural to want to help out a
friend, especially when there's an All-Star bonus involved.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Bichette, who benefits from the power-boosting altitude
of Denver, he may have been chosen to appease the local fans. No
doubt Leyland would face an inquisition in Colorado if he had
omitted Bichette, who is batting .336.
</P>
<P>
   Said Dierker, ``Every manager wants to go to the World Series,
but the price you pay is you have to pick the All-Star reserves the
next year, in which case you can make some enemies. They shouldn't
make the manager do that. Maybe all the managers should vote.''
</P>
<P>
   In a recent conversation with Leyland, Dierker recommended Alou,
Bell and Wagner, adding that Everett and pitcher Mike Hampton would
deserve consideration if they had appeared in more games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every year, there's at least 10 guys who deserve to be on the
team who aren't on it,'' Dierker said, ``and there are usually a
couple of guys on the team who shouldn't be.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sad thing is you get some who have been on the All-Star
team 15 times, and they don't care whether they're on it or not.
But the fans vote them in, even when they're not having their best
year. And you get a Devon White (of Arizona) or a Fernando Vina (of
Milwaukee) who has to go because every team has to have a
representative.''
</P>
<P>
   Alou said the All-Star roster should be increased to 40 or
``they should change that rule about picking one player from each
team. It shouldn't be a given that every team has an All-Star.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hunsicker said, ``If you expand the roster, you somewhat
dilute the value of being on the team. It's never gonna be a fair
process.''
</P>
<P>
   It's especially unfair to the National League, which has 16
teams and cannot be as choosy as the American League with its 14
clubs.
</P>
<P>
   And while Hunsicker wasn't knocking Leyland, he said, ``There's
nothing fair about the fans' selections; it's who can stuff the
most ballots. It's a difficult process at best.''
</P>
<P>
   And it always causes disappointment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
