<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUG-MONEY-LAUNDER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDS SMASH DRUG-MONEY RING AT CHECK-CASHING SITES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JESSE HIESTAND  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Federal agents smashed a major drug-money
laundering ring with the arrests of nine people, including four
suburban Reseda residents who allegedly helped funnel $3.2 million
through a chain of check-cashing businesses, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Acting on a federal indictment, FBI agents raided Supermail
International offices in Reseda, North Hollywood and the company's
Sacramento headquarters, seizing documents and other evidence, said
Tim McNally, assistant director of the FBI's Los Angeles field
office.
</P>
<P>
   Among the nine arrested Wednesday were the company's three top
officers, who police say not only condoned the illegal transfers
but advised undercover agents on how to launder illicit funds, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who ran this business knew drug money was coming in
and they did not resist it,'' McNally said. ``They basically took a
legitimate financial service and corrupted it.''
</P>
<P>
   The two-year investigation, code-named ``Operation Mule Train,''
was sparked by a tip from Los Angeles narcotics officers, who
repeatedly saw drug-ring couriers going to Supermail's store in the
6700 block of Reseda Boulevard, McNally said.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI then sent undercover agents posing as drug traffickers
into the business. According to the indictment, the store's manager
knowingly agreed to launder drug money for a cash fee.
</P>
<P>
   In dozens of subsequent transactions, store employees converted
what they believed to be drug money to cashier's checks or wired
the money to a bank account in Miami, which was in fact an FBI
account, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Reseda store was the hotbed of the money-laundering
conspiracy, FBI Special Agent Leslie Gardner stated in the search
warrant.
</P>
<P>
   Other Supermail stores were enlisted as the undercover agents
presented larger sums of money, McNally said.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the agents were introduced to the company's
corporate managers, including Christine Annette Umbertino, 42, the
chief executive officer, and her brother, Albert Joseph Umbertino,
39, the company's president. Both were arrested Monday at their
homes in Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   McNally said the Umbertinos authorized their employees to accept
the drug money and even accepted it themselves. They are also
accused of advising the undercover agents on different ways to
launder money, including buying Supermail stock, which is traded on
the Nasdaq market.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one thing when you have people who conspire within a
company and merely fail to file currency transaction reports,''
McNally said. ``It's another when you have executive leadership
that has knowledge as well as provides advice on how to conduct
illegal activity.''
</P>
<P>
   The Umbertinos were named in the indictment, as was Supermail's
senior vice president, Mercedes Veiga, 45, of Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   Those arrested in Reseda were Rogelio Merlose Jordan, 34, a
former manager of the Reseda store; Salvador Jose Sanchez, 34, the
Reseda store's manager until May 1998; Alberto Dominguez Acosta,
59; and Adelina Acosta.
</P>
<P>
   A fifth Reseda resident named in the indictment, Fernando
Malagon, 27, is in custody in Mexico, according to federal agents.
</P>
<P>
   In all, agents funneled $3.2 million through the company before
taking the case to a federal grand jury in Los Angeles, McNally
said. A 67-page indictment was returned June 11 and unsealed
Wednesday, along with the search warrant.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Police Department narcotics investigation that
preceded Operation Mule Train is separately credited with the
arrests of 333 people on various drug charges; the seizure of 1,000
pounds of cocaine and 1,293 pounds of marijuana, among other drugs;
204 firearms; and $2.3 million in cash, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
