<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CHINA-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON PRAISES CHINESE BID TO CLEAN UP AIR, WATER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Updated material included) 
 
By CRAGG HINES 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GUILIN, China _ President Clinton flew to this famous nature
spot Thursday to play enviro-tourist and review Chinese attempts to
stem decades of ecological degradation.
</P>
<P>
   The scenic stop contrasted with Clinton's two full days in
bustling Shanghai, the country's commercial capital, where the
president was surrounded by skyscrapers, hard-charging
entrepreneurs and a stock market at the heart of China's growing
economy. But the message for both locales was the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe China has a huge opportunity to avoid some of the
terrible mistakes we made,'' Clinton told environmentalists in this
provincial town, which some Chinese believe is the most beautiful
of their vast nation.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Clinton told U.S. and Chinese business leaders in
Shanghai:
</P>
<P>
   ``As we go forward, we must ensure that economic development
does not lead to environmental catastrophe.''
</P>
<P>
   He returned to the issue in an interview with Central Chinese
Television, the national government-owned network, which is to air
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to find a way to grow the economy and replenish the
environment,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Sino-American ecological initiatives include the Environmental
Protection Agency working with the Chinese on a nationwide air
quality monitoring project.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton predicted that in 10 years people will say the
environmental cooperation is ``one of the biggest things they
did.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton began his eight-hour visit to the Guilin region, in
south-central China, by discussing environmental issues with U.S.
and local specialists.
</P>
<P>
   James Steinberg, Clinton's deputy national security adviser,
said the Chinese have ``a growing sense of citizens being able to
be active'' in issues such as environment quality without fear of
reprisal.
</P>
<P>
   An industrialist was also scheduled on the program, a Guilin
brewer whom Steinberg credited with sound environmental techniques,
including wastewater disposal.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton planned an afternoon boat ride down the Li River to
wonder at stone formations that have been the favorites of Chinese
painters and poets for hundreds of years.
</P>
<P>
   But the Li, like other major Chinese rivers, for years was
treated as an open sewer. Some of the hills along the president's
route were stripped of trees by villagers desperate for firewood.
</P>
<P>
   The river has been the focus recently of a cleanup program, and
some local residents now turn animal and farm waste into bio-gas
for cooking and fuel so they do not need to denude nearby forests.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a real sea-change in attitude,'' Steinberg said.
</P>
<P>
   After his boat ride, Clinton was to fly on to Hong Kong, the
final stop of his nine-day tour of China, for meetings with
political leaders. The former British colony reverted to Chinese
rule a year ago this week. Clinton was to make a bit of history by
being the first foreign leader to fly into Hong Kong's new
international airport, Chek Lap Kok, three days before its official
opening.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton planned a trip-closing news conference Friday before a
17-hour flight back to Washington, which includes a refueling stop
in Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   In Shanghai, Clinton ticked off the alarming data that frame
China's environmental challenges, including the fact that
respiratory illness from air pollution is the nation's biggest
health problem. Steinberg said China has five of the 10
most-polluted cities in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every major body of water is polluted,'' Clinton said. ``The
water table is dropping all over the country. China is about to
assume the unfortunate distinction of replacing the United States
as the largest emitter &UR;  &LR; of greenhouse gases that are dangerously
warming our planet.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said, however, that sound environmental policy and
slower economic growth did not necessarily go hand in hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have example after example after example of countries whose
economies are doing well as they adopt more sensible environmental
and energy practices,'' Clinton said. ``And energy companies in the
United States are making a significant share of their profits
through conservation and the implementation of technologies.''
</P>
<P>
   Pollution may also have played a part in Clinton's sometimes
raspy voice after five days in Beijing and Shanghai, where there is
almost always a haze in the air caused at least in part by
industrial and automotive exhaust.
</P>
<P>
   More than 6 million Chinese travel annually to Guilin to take
the Li cruise, famous for the limestone outcroppings known as
``karsts.'' The formations jut up to 600 feet above fruit orchards
and rice fields and bear such evocative names as ``Painted Hill of
Nine Horses'' and ``The Frog Crossing the River.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
