<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 00:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7193 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-US-RADIO-SPIES-JAPAN-     07-02 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-RADIO-SPIES-JAPAN-ASAHI-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. BOMBED JAPANESE AIRWAVES WITH RADIO SHOWS, RESEARCHER FINDS  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This 650-word ``separate buy'' article is from the Asahi News
Service.)  
  
 (EDITORS: Get your news from Japan and the Pacific Rim straight
from the source _ the Asahi News Service. Its Monday through Friday
report of news, features and distinctive analysis is culled from
The Asahi Shimbun, Japan's foremost newspaper, renowned for its
integrity and thoroughness (with a daily circulation is 12
million.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
fax her at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``i'' international news files.)  
  
 By THE ASAHI NEWS SERVICE  
 c.1998 Asahi News Service  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Aiming to dampen Japanese citizens' enthusiasm for war,
the U.S. military aired disheartening radio programs in Japanese
shortly before World War II ended.
</P>
<P>
   Taketoshi Yamamoto, a Hitotsubashi University professor of
psychology, spent two years studying espionage activities and
propaganda carried out by Japan and the United States during the
World War II era.
</P>
<P>
   He discovered scripts and documents related to the radio
broadcasts at the National Archive and Records Administration of
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   According to Yamamoto, a total of 124 episodes of a program
called ''The Citizens' Voice'' were aired between April and August
of 1945. The programs were broadcast from Saipan after the American
military seized the island.
</P>
<P>
   Under the surveillance of the Office of Strategic Services
(OSS), the former body of the Central Intelligence Agency, groups
of Japanese-Americans were gathered in studios outside of New York
and Washington to produce the program.
</P>
<P>
   The OSS also brought in three Japanese prisoners of war to
describe the situation in Japan so that the program's contents
would not contradict actual conditions.
</P>
<P>
   The scripts were written in Japanese under the guidance of
authorities, translated into English for checking by the U.S.
military, and then recorded in a studio in San Francisco. Two weeks
worth of programs were then flown to Saipan for broadcasting.
</P>
<P>
   The first broadcast was aired at 7 p.m. on April 23 local time.
</P>
<P>
   According to the scripts, a ``patriotic Japanese'' named Oishi
denounced Hideki Tojo, the prime minister at the time, and the
Japanese military, saying they were jeopardizing the nation. He
called out for citizens to unite and salvage the country with their
own hands.
</P>
<P>
   Letters sent from a woman to her husband at war were read aloud
and popular music, prohibited by the Japanese military, was played
during the 30-minute program.
</P>
<P>
   During times of war, nations have been known to broadcast
programs in the enemy's language. At first, broadcasts were aired
by shortwave to reach lands several thousands of kilometers away.
</P>
<P>
   The Office of War Information began airing ``Voice of America''
from February 1942. At around the same time, Japan Broadcasting
Corp. (NHK) began airing an English-language program on shortwave.
</P>
<P>
   Female announcers, taking the name of Tokyo Rose, conveyed
messages in English to American soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   But programs like ``VOA'' were only available to
government-related officials in Japan since the government banned
its citizens from listening to foreign broadcasts and from
possessing shortwave radios.
</P>
<P>
   Medium-wave broadcasting, on the other hand, was widely
available to citizens so that they could receive air-raid warnings.
About 7 million radios existed nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   With this in mind, the U.S. military planned to air ``The
Citizens' Voice'' through medium-wave broadcasting, but the program
could not reach Japanese shores from the American mainland. But the
U.S. occupation of Saipan in July 1944 enabled the military to
begin broadcasting ``VOA'' on medium wave. The programs began in
December 1944.
</P>
<P>
   The following April, using the same wavelength as NHK's, the
military began broadcasting ``The Citizen's Voice.'' Within the
military, the covert program was called ``black radio'' in contrast
to ``white radio,'' which referred to the public broadcasting
program ``OI.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Akiko Takeyama, former professor of media history
at Showa Women's University, NHK documents reveal that NHK tried to
sabotage the broadcast by airing disturbing noises such as the
sound of people talking.
</P>
<P>
   Interference was sent out through radio stations nationwide, but
residents in some areas on the Pacific coast were able to tune in
to the programs.
</P>
<P>
   Norio Tamura, Tokyo Keizai University professor of
communications, said the secret programs were an excellent military
strategy, ``because they were aired through the only waves Japanese
citizens were allowed access to.'' &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 650-word article from the Asahi News Service, it
must be purchased _ the rate is not prohibitive _ from New York
Times Syndicate sales representative CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
