<SLUG> BC-BBO-RANGERS-DODGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS LOSE THE HANDLE, AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHHNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ It appeared to be another harmless ground
ball.
</P>
<P>
   Opposing hitter puts ball in play.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers second baseman Mark McLemore retires hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Happens every time. Right?
</P>
<P>
   Wrong.
</P>
<P>
   McLemore did not field the ninth-inning ground ball off the bat
of Los Angeles Dodgers designated hitter Jim Eisenreich cleanly,
and the National League visitors parlayed the extra out into three
unearned runs en route to a 7-5 victory last night at The Ballpark
in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   The defeat marked the Rangers' fourth in succession, and poor
defensive play contributed significantly in two of those.
</P>
<P>
   That does not please Rangers manager Johnny Oates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell you what: I'm frustrated, and I'm tired of explaining
it,'' Oates said. ``Let them explain it tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers entered the ninth inning with a one-run advantage
and an All-Star on the mound. Rangers closer John Wetteland (2-1)
retired pinch hitter Roger Cedeno on strikes before surrendering a
one-out single to second baseman Wilton Guerrero.
</P>
<P>
   No problem.
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland induced a ground ball from Eisenreich, and McLemore
strayed to his left for what appeared to be the inning's second
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to do too much _ not necessarily getting a double
play, but trying to keep the tying run from scoring position,''
McLemore said. ``I know better than that.''
</P>
<P>
   McLemore wanted to retire Guerrero at second base, yet he
retired no one by failing to field the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked like he booted it to me,'' Oates replied when asked
to assess the play. ``I've seen Mac make that play and get the
force at second many, many times. I'm not sure if he had a shot or
not. In hindsight, I'd rather see him get the out at first. Strike
out \RRaul\S Mondesi, and we're in here celebrating.''
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland, whom Cleveland manager Mike Hargrove selected for the
American League All-Star team earlier in the afternoon, retired
Mondesi on strikes with a 2-2 fastball up in the zone.
</P>
<P>
   That brought Gary Sheffield to the plate, and Wetteland quickly
threw two strikes past the right fielder. Sheffield, though, lined
Pitch No. 3 into center field for a game-tying single. Dodgers
first baseman Eric Karros then delivered a two-run double that
scored Eisenreich and Sheffield.
</P>
<P>
   The out McLemore gave away proved costly and strapped the
Rangers with their first defeat in 43 games when leading after
eight innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my job to nail the game down regardless,'' said
Wetteland, who failed to convert a save opportunity for only the
third time in 25 opportunities. ``I was ineffective in doing that
tonight. The record shows that I was one pitch away from getting
the job done, but I didn't get the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither did the Rangers' defense. The ninth-inning problems
spoiled the home debut of Todd Van Poppel, who would have been the
winn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-98 0104EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
