<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980702.0030 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 01:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7201 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-COLUMN-THIEL-SPI &LR;      07-02 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-COLUMN-THIEL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PITCHING WOES RETURN MARINERS TO FAMILIAR SPOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The relief pitcher, a former All-Star, finished a
wretched first half of the season with a 2-5 won-loss record,
almost no saves and an earned run average above 7.00. Name the
pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Heathcliff Slocumb? Wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Norm Charlton? Yes.
</P>
<P>
   But not in 1998 as an Oriole, or 1997 as a Mariner _ in 1995, as
a Philadelphia Phillie.
</P>
<P>
   In the first half of '95, Charlton was so lousy that a moribund
team like the Phillies waived him in mid-July.
</P>
<P>
   The desperate Mariners, on the verge of moving out of Seattle,
picked him up. Three months later, Charlton more than any single
Mariner had turned around a franchise, brought it a division title
and initiated the momentum that is creating America's most
expensive ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   The point? Charlton's two stellar months in '95 are about the
last time anything unexpectedly good happened to Mariner pitching.
</P>
<P>
   More than anything else, the breathtaking inability to find,
keep or improve pitching is why the Mariners find themselves so
distant from Anaheim they mustnext draft the Hubble telescope.
</P>
<P>
   In the accounting of the Mariner decay in Tuesday's P-I, one
statistic leaped out: In the past four seasons, including this one,
the Mariners have used 54 pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of teams have short stays for pitchers during emergencies.
The Mariner churn is relentless, profound and annual.
</P>
<P>
   In '95, the Mariners used 24 pitchers, including 16 who won at
least one game. In '96, they had 20 pitchers, 18 of whom won at
least once. Last year, 16 of the 24 won games. This year, they have
settled down to 15 pitchers, nine with victories. They've also
settled into last place.
</P>
<P>
   Here's another teaser: Based on number of starts, name the No. 4
starter in the Mariner rotation in each of the last three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Believe me, you'll never get it without multiple media guides.
Salomon Torres had 13 starts in '95. Bob Wells had 16 in '96. Last
season Bob Wolcott had 18.
</P>
<P>
   Torres and Wolcott are gone, and after a horrendous spring
training Wells would have been gone except the Mariners had no one
else. So he and his 5.52 ERA sit in the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the Nos. 2 and 3 starters for the first two years of
contention also are gone (Chris Bosio and Tim Belcher in '95,
Sterling Hitchcock and Wolcott in '96), and as with Torres, the
Mariners have nothing in exchange for them on the major league
roster.
</P>
<P>
   No club can flourish with this kind of flailing in the game's
most important element. Rather than flourish, the Mariners were
blessed with long-overdue good fortune that in 1998 has vaporized.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Mariners won 90 games. In '96 they won 85. In the
strike-shortened season of '95, they would have projected to a
full-season total of 87. Good seasons, but nothing indicative of
greatness. Aside from a 19-8 September in '95 and a 20-7 June in
'97, the Mariners have been average over the previous three
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   This average team was elevated in '95 by three forces: a weak
division led by the collapse of the Angels, career-best years by
several hitters, and a good bullpen. None of that is happening this
year.
</P>
<P>
   In '95, Charlton pitched 47 innings in 30 appearances and had a
1.51 ERA. Also in the 'pen was Jeff Nelson (78 innings in 62
appearances, 2.17 ERA) and Bill Risley (in 60 innings in 45 games,
3.13 ERA).
</P>
<P>
   But Nelson and Risley were traded, Charlton returned to his
Phillie form and the 'pen began to circle the drain.
</P>
<P>
   The blame game for this pitching debacle is universal: Ownership
has made penny-wise and pound-foolish decisions with the budget and
has sometimes interfered in baseball decisions, talent has been
squandered in unproductive trades by Woody Woodward, and manager
Lou Piniella has little tolerance for pitchers in general and
almost no capacity to develop youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   Four pitching coaches in Piniella's six years, combined with
respectable success by pitchers after they have left Seattle (see
Mike Jackson, Belcher, Nelson, Andy Benes, Omar Olivares,
Hitchcock, Risley, Derek Lowe) offers evidence that Piniella and
the organization don't know what they want, and can't keep it even
if they find it.
</P>
<P>
   The problem also goes beyond the current leadership to the
historic baseball dilemma in Seattle and many markets of unstable
ownerships and unbalanced industry economics. The club has invested
relatively little in its system foundation because of the almost
annual desperation to win big, sell tickets and get out.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hear a lot about what is spent on the major league
level,'' Woodward said Tuesday. ``But teams like Atlanta, Toronto
and others have done a very effective job throughout their
organizations in spending money to build their systems.''
</P>
<P>
   The current owners invested in a homer-happy lineup that has put
fans in the seats, a stadium in the ground and a temporary curtain
over the club's fundamental weaknesses. But with so many regulars
having sub-par offensive and defensive seasons, the curtain is gone
and the Mariners are exposed.
</P>
<P>
   The question of this season is not, ``How did this happen?''
</P>
<P>
   The question is, ``What took so long to return to normal?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
