<HEADLINE>
THOUSANDS FLEE AS WILDFIRES SURGE IN FLORIDA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: The following story is an added starter on The New York
Times front page) (sw) 
 By MIREYA NAVARRO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ More than 18,000 people were evacuated in northeast
Florida late on Wednesday as wildfires whipped by high winds burned
dozens of homes and businesses bringing a threat that had affected
mostly rural areas to the midst of population centers.
</P>
<P>
   Evacuations were taking place in the counties of Volusia,
Brevard, and Flagler, with 15,000 residents forced out of their
homes in the city of Ormond Beach north of Daytona Beach in Volusia
County alone.
</P>
<P>
   The evacuations are the largest since fires began on Memorial
Day, burning more than 250,000 acres in northern Florida,
temporarily closing highways and causing sporadic evacuations of
hundreds of residents. The fires around the state have caused $190
million in damage.
</P>
<P>
   Florida officials said commercial areas in Ormond Beach and
Daytona Beach are threatened. Thirty homes and several cars were
reported to have been destroyed in Brevard County, to the south of
Daytona Beach.
</P>
<P>
   The fire and smoke forced the closing of all major roads leading
into Ormond Beach, a city of about 35,000 people, and forced the
closing of Interstate 95 from Titusville to Jacksonville, about 125
miles. Other roads were also closed, including State Road 40.
</P>
<P>
   State emergency management officials said 112 new fires started
on Wednesday when late afternoon winds, clocked at 15 miles per
hour, scattered sparks over several miles in the affected counties,
starting about 4:30 p.m. Dozens of firefighters, many of them
exhausted from days of battling brush fires, were unable to keep up
with the new blazes, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Volusia County officials called for assistance on Wednesday
night from nearby Orlando and other communities to send available
firemen and police.
</P>
<P>
   Residents forced to leave have been put up in six shelters and
others drove to neighboring cities in Florida. No injuries or
deaths were reported.
</P>
<P>
   But Volusia County hospitals reported treating 150 people for
respiratory problems, asthma and heart ailments in the last week.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Lawton Chiles is scheduled to visit the area Thursday
morning. Last week he ordered a ban on individual use of fireworks
this Fourth of July because of the extreme drought conditions
caused by meager rain and relentless heat, the driest the state has
been in more than 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has declared the state a disaster area and
nearly $35 million in federal money has been spent fighting
hundreds of wildfires that have sprung up mostly in rural areas of
northern and central Florida since May. More than 80,000 acres have
been destroyed in Volusia County _ about 10 percent of the county _
in the last two weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
