<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-INQUIRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE OFFICIALS INVESTIGATE POSSIBLE COVER-UP IN CHOKING DEATH 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By CHARLE LeDUFF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Six days after former Police Officer Francis Livoti
was convicted in federal court of violating the civil rights of a
Bronx man who died in his custody, the Police Department announced
on Wednesday night that it had placed his former partner and
another officer on modified duty.
</P>
<P>
   The action was taken as the department investigates allegations
that the two officers had perjured themselves and colluded to cover
up for Livoti.
</P>
<P>
   Sgt. William Monahan, 34, and Police Officer Mario Erotokritou,
32, were both present on Dec. 22, 1994, when Anthony Baez was taken
into custody by Livoti after his football hit Livoti's police
cruiser.
</P>
<P>
   Baez died after a confrontation with the officers outside his
family's home in the University Heights section of the Bronx that
night. At Livoti's criminal trial in 1996, the officers testified
that Livoti never used a chokehold on Baez.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government said it had testimony from a police
officer that other officers had concocted a cover story to protect
Livoti, saying that a black man had choked Baez to death before
running off.
</P>
<P>
   A Bronx judge eventually acquitted Livoti of criminally
negligent homicidee, but not before the judge called the testimony
of Livoti's fellow officers ``a nest of perjury.''
</P>
<P>
   Police Commissioner Howard Safir had said that the department
would wait until the federal civil rights had concluded before
considering action against any of the officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We take this investigation very seriously,'' Safir said on
Wednesday night. ``This investigation will go forward wherever it
leads.''
</P>
<P>
   He said it was ``in the best interest of the department'' that
Monahan and Erotoktiou be placed on modified duty while the
investigation was under way.
</P>
<P>
   Monahan and Erotokritou will have their guns and badges taken
away and will be assigned to administrative tasks until the
investigation is completed, the commissioner said. He would not say
why another officer who testified, Officer Anthony Farnan, was left
on patrol duty.
</P>
<P>
   Monahan, who was specifically asked to supervise Livoti at the
46th Precinct because of the high number of civilian complaints
that had been brought against Livoti, is a seven-year veteran of
the force.
</P>
<P>
   Erotokritou has been with the department for eight years. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
