<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 01:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7215 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-YANKS-PHILLIES-NY     07-02 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-YANKS-PHILLIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES BEAT PHILLIES, 5-2 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The scoreboard message begged the fans to make some
noise in the fifth inning on Wednesday night at Yankee Stadium, but
the electronic plea was unnecessary. The decibel level had started
to increase when Tino Martinez sauntered to the plate with the
bases loaded. Martinez had homered off Philadelphia's Matt Beech
three innings earlier, so everyone affiliated with the Yankees was
hoping he could go deep again.
</P>
<P>
   The noise might have unnerved the 26-year-old Beech. He tossed
one, two, three balls out of the strike zone and the din got
louder. Finally, the Phillies left-hander threw a strike. But when
Beech uncorked another hittable pitch, Martinez rapped it sharply
between first and second base for a two-run single. The hit was
more effective than the scoreboard at eliciting a raucous response.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez's timely and well-placed grounder turned a one-run lead
into a three-run margin that David Wells and the Yankees made stand
up for a 5-2 victory over Philadelphia. Wells celebrated being
appointed to the All-Star team earlier in the day by pitching seven
stellar innings and improving to 11-2. Martinez celebrated coming
through in the sort of spot that he has not thrived in often enough
to his liking this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't set any numbers goals,'' Martinez said. ``I want
consistency. I want to be consistent from week to week and month to
month. I want to hit the ball hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells has found consistency. The Yankee left-hander gave up one
earned run and seven hits, and extended his streak without a walk
to 36 innings, though he did not have an effective curveball. Since
Wells is on schedule to pitch next Tuesday, is on the elite team in
the major leagues and has a perfect game on his resume, he will
most likely start the All-Star Game for the American League.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thrilled to make the team, but I couldn't show any
emotion today,'' said Wells, who used his split-finger fastball and
sinker in place of the curve. ``I had a job to do. This game is
more important.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez was not among the five Yankees named to the All-Star
team on Wednesday, but he was valuable on Wednesday night with a
homer, a single and four runs batted in. He entered the game with
only 18 hits in his last 101 times at bat since being drilled in
the back by a pitch from Armando Benitez of the Orioles six weeks
ago. But on Wednesday night, Martinez exhibited the kind of bat
speed and compact stroke that makes him such a lethal hitter. He
leads the Yankees with 12 homers and 61 runs batted in.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needed one like this, hitting the ball hard and getting
four rbi's,'' Manager Joe Torre said. ``I think he'll be able to
sleep better than he's been able to sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   When Martinez was reminded that his statistics translate to 25
homers and 128 rbi for a full season, he said: ``That's not bad. I
wouldn't say I'm struggling. It's consistency I want.''
</P>
<P>
   Beech had stymied left-handed hitters this season, limiting them
to a .167 average while not yielding a homer in 42 straight at-bats
before last night. That changed in the second inning. After Beech
walked Tim Raines, Martinez blasted a shot over the right-field
fence to put the Yankees in front, 2-0. It was Martinez's second
homer in the last four games.
</P>
<P>
   Raines singled home a run to make it 3-2 in the fifth before
Martinez's two-run single.
</P>
<P>
   Wells retired 10 of the first 11 Phillies he faced, but Scott
Rolen disrupted his rhythm by hitting a 3-2 pitch into the
center-field bleachers in the fourth. The ball traveled 422 feet
and made Rolen only the 13th player to knock a ball into the black
part of the bleachers since the Stadium was renovated in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies tied it, 2-2, on two singles, Chad Curtis' error in
center field and a grounder. But Wells struck out Mark Lewis to
strand the go-ahead run at third and never faced another situation
as perilous.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it is the Indians at Jacobs Field, the Braves at Turner
Field, the Mets at Shea Stadium or the Phillies at Yankee Stadium,
the selfless Yankees keep winning at a historic pace. They are
57-20 and sprinting, not hobbling, to the All-Star Game break. It
does not take a scoreboard message to show that is worth cheering
about.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we would be this good,'' Torre said. ``The record,
that's another story. The record is incredible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
