r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-DODGERS-LADN     07-02 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS' RALLY BEATS RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ For the first three months of the season, the
Dodgers walked away from a game like Wednesday night's with a loss
and a sense there were plenty to follow.
</P>
<P>
   They just didn't win in the ninth inning with two outs and two
strikes.
</P>
<P>
   That all changed after Gary Sheffield fell behind Texas All-Star
closer John Wetteland, who had just blown away Raul Mondesi on
three fastballs. Sheffield also saw Wetteland's heat, but drilled
it into center field to tie a game the Dodgers would win 7-5 when
Eric Karros followed with a two-run double.
</P>
<P>
   Karros got the game-winning RBI, but this was Sheffield's
victory and one the Dodgers hope is the start of something big.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see where it leads,'' Karros said. ``Maybe nothing
happens, maybe we get on a winning streak. Maybe it will help us
with our wild-card chances.''
</P>
<P>
   What is certain is that the Dodgers have won two straight to
begin the final trip before the All-Star break. They also know that
the Rangers were 42-0 heading into the ninth inning with a lead and
they were 1-38 when trailing after eight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has been waiting to catch a little luck,'' Sheffield
said.
</P>
<P>
   The victory kept the Dodgers 12{ games behind the NL
West-leading San Diego Padres, who beat Oakland 8-4 on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield, the club's lone representative at next Tuesday's
All-Star Game in Denver, knows the Dodgers caught a break when
Rangers second Mark McLemore booted Jim Eisenreich's grounder to
second with Wilton Guerrero on first.
</P>
<P>
   There was no chance for a double play, but McLemore could have
kept the potential tying run out of scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen Mac make that play and get the force at second many
many times,'' Texas manager Johnny Oates said. ``I'm not sure if he
had a shot. In hindsight, I'd rather see him get the out at first,
strike out Mondesi and we're in there celebrating.''
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi's strikeout should have ended the game, but there was
Sheffield with one final shot.
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland started him off with a breaking ball, then came back
with a fastball for strike two. The third pitch was up in
Sheffield's eyes and he whacked it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw what he did to Mondy and I wanted to be ready,'' said
Sheffield, now batting .333 in 40 games as a Dodger. ``On the first
pitch, I was surprised to see a slider. I thought he tried to be
aggressive and was just able to make contact.''
</P>
<P>
   For Wetteland, the former Dodger who now is one of the game's
premier closers, it was the second blown save in his last six
appearances. The Rangers now have dropped four straight and 13 of
the last 20 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was one pitch away from getting the job done,'' Wetteland
said. ``I didn't get the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory went to Scott Radinsky (3-4), who pitched a
scoreless eighth inning. Antonio Osuna walked Tom Goodwin with one
out, but picked him off. He then struck out Roberto Kelly to end
the game and earned his sixth save.
</P>
<P>
   It was Goodwin, who gave the Rangers a 5-4 lead in the sixth
inning when he scored from third on a double steal with two outs.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers took a 4-0 lead against Rangers right-hander Todd
Van Poppel and Mondesi was responsible for most of it.
</P>
<P>
   He hit a two-run homer in the first, then tripled home a run in
the third and scored on a sacrifice fly. It was his 18th homer of
the year.
</P>
<P>
   But Dodgers starter Dennis Reyes gave it back in the bottom of
the third when he allowed a RBI double to Kelly, a run-scoring
single by McLemore and an RBI double by Ivan Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   Greg McMichael took over for Reyes to start the sixth and
allowed three base hits with two outs, including an RBI single by
Kelly that tied the game at four.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, Reyes was optioned to Class-A San Bernardino so
he can continue to pitch during the upcoming All-Star break. He
will pitch Tuesday for the Stampede, then make his next Dodgers
start Sunday against San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Triple-A catcher Paul LoDuca, who was called up for two days
when the team was in Denver, takes Reyes' place on the roster.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
