<HEADER>
A7223 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS &LR;      07-02 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Alou, Berry, Bagwell 
lead rout of White Sox
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOSEPH DUARTE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
Moises Alou is not going to hit a home run every game, and the
Astros are not going to score in double figures all the time.
</P>
<P>
   But 3-for-3 isn't too bad.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few hours after only one Astro was named among the
National League All-Star reserves, the Astros made a statement
Wednesday night with their third consecutive rout of an American
League club, a 10-4 victory over the Chicago White Sox at the
Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   The way things have gone the last three games, the Astros might
want to petition a move into the AL. In winning 10 of 13
interleague games so far, they have outscored their opponents 99-40
and have scored 39 runs in their last three games against Cleveland
and Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we score 10 runs a game, we will run away with the
division,'' Astros catcher Brad Ausmus said. ``Unfortunately for
us, that's not the way it works. The one through eight spots (in
the batting order) are feeling pretty good at the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   Beginning with Alou.
</P>
<P>
   Alou, selected to the NL All-Star team for the third time
earlier in the day, proved his worthiness by hitting his fourth
home run in three games and driving in four runs as the Astros won
their fourth straight game and extended their lead in the NL
Central to seven games. He hit a two-run double in the first inning
and added a two-run homer in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're having a good year, so hopefully things will continue
working for us,'' said Alou, who is 11-for-23 with 12 RBIs over the
last five games. ``It's a matter of staying healthy and lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros may have only two All-Stars _ second baseman Craig
Biggio was picked in fan voting _ but on Wednesday they showed they
are much more than a two-star club.
</P>
<P>
   Sean Berry tied his career high with four hits, including his
sixth home run in the sixth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Bagwell hit his third homer in two days, a two-run shot in
the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Bell, snubbed for an All-Star bid for the second time in
his career, went 2-for-5 with two RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Gutierrez had two hits and drove in a run.
</P>
<P>
   ``We only have four guys that play every day _ Alou, Bell,
Bagwell and Craig Biggio _ and the other guys have to share time,''
Astros manager Larry Dierker said. ``It's pretty hard to make the
All-Star team sharing time.''
</P>
<P>
   A day after erupting for 17 runs and 18 hits off Chicago, the
Astros kept up their offensive onslaught off White Sox starter Jim
Parque (2-2), who lasted only four innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros built leads of 4-0 and 6-2 before the White Sox
pulled within two runs in the seventh on a solo home run by Charlie
O'Brien and a truly strange play.
</P>
<P>
   Astros reliever Doug Henry threw a wild pitch that bounced into
home-plate umpire Gerry Davis' front shirt pocket, allowing Ray
Durham to score from third while Ausmus searched around home plate
for the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are the odds of that?'' Ausmus said of the seventh-inning
play. ``I've seen balls go in people's shirts but never seen them
hit into a pocket. I had no idea where it went. When he said to me
that the run scores, I asked, `What am I supposed to do? Grab you
and throw you in front of the baserunner?'''
</P>
<P>
   Davis himself wasn't immediately aware where the ball hopped to.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the first time anything like that's happened in my 23
years,'' he said. ``No, I didn't know the ball was in my pocket at
first. Then, Henry started yelling, `In his shirt! In his shirt!'
That's when I realized.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Astros once again made things relatively easy for
their starting pitcher as Pete Schourek (5-5) overcame a pair of
home runs by Chicago. He allowed four runs and eight hits in 6
innings.
</P>
<P>
   Schourek's fifth victory matches his 1997 total. The lefthander
did not allow a Chicago run until the fifth, when pinch hitter Jeff
Abbott doubled and later scored on Mike Caruso's groundout.
</P>
<P>
   Albert Belle trimmed the Astros' lead to 4-2 in the sixth with a
426-foot home run into the rainbow-colored seats in the upper deck
of left field. It was only the 12th homer to reach the upper deck
of the Astrodome, although Mark McGwire accomplished the feat June
18.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros responded in the bottom half of the inning as Berry
hit a solo homer to left and Biggio added a sacrifice fly to push
the Astros' lead back to four runs. Berry also had three singles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I'm back to normal,'' Berry said. ``I've been struggling
the last month and a half. I've been battling away, and I hope to
get a few games like this. And maybe I'll be able to contribute
like everybody thinks I can.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
