</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-WIZARDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION STUCK IN REVERSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ After watching his team lose eight
consecutive Major League Soccer games, Revolution coach Thomas
Rongen outlined the things he wanted to see from his team in
Wednesday night's match against the Kansas City Wizards. In a terse
speech to his players at their pregame meal, Rongen used words like
``sacrifice'' and ``hard-nosed play'' and ``concentration'' and
``patience'' as the keys to a desperately-needed victory.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, after the Revolution dropped their ninth in a
row, a 1-0 loss to the Wizards before 5,304 at Arrowhead Stadium,
Rongen must have felt like talking to himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, sure,'' said Rongen, his Dutch humor and sarcastic wit
still intact after the Revolution matched their own MLS record set
last year with nine consecutive losses. ``I have experience. I went
through this last year. It seems like I'm getting accustomed to
this. We've been here before, and we've seen the good side and the
bad side, and we just have to say, `Hey, listen, guys,
unfortunately this is nothing new to us.' We came out of this hole
last year and we've just got to do the same thing this year with a
team I think is remarkably a better team than last year.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the Revolution were vastly improved on defense over
their last two losses _ a 4-3 shootout setback against the Dallas
Burn; and a 5-3 loss to the NY/NJ MetroStars. For the better part
of the first 65 minutes, they heeded Rongen's words and submitted a
disciplined effort on defense and exhibited patience in possession
of the ball.
</P>
<P>
   But after surrendering nine total goals in those last two
losses, a solitary goal in the 66th minute by Wizards midfielder
Predrag Radosavljevic _ Preki, for short _ was all it took to send
the Revolution (4-12) reeling toward their ninth consecutive loss.
</P>
<P>
   After hardly breaking a sweat with the US national team at the
World Cup in France, Preki logged a full 90 minutes in his first
game back with the Wizards and, despite being noticeably winded,
summoned enough legs to score the winning goal. After Revolution
goaltender Jeff Causey deflected a right cross by Paul Wright,
Preki swept in and outraced midfielder Ivan McKinley to the rebound
and chipped in a weak grounder from 6 yards out past Manny Motajo,
who had retreated into the net to try and make a desperation save.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter,'' said Preki, when it was suggested his
goal didn't rank as one of the prettiest of his MLS career. ``They
all count the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Causey, who ostensibly drew the start when Ian Feuer's wife went
into labor Wednesday, faced six shots on goal and made eight saves
in his first start since last Sept. 9 against the MetroStars.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't that far away from me and he just got a real quick
shot on it,'' Causey said of Wright's shot. ``I knew they had
runners coming through, and (Preki) was just playing breakaway.
Normally, that would be a good save, but he had runners in there.
They were able to follow up and clean up.''
</P>
<P>
   That was something Wizards goalkeeper Mike Ammann did not allow.
After Preki's score, Ammann, who recorded his fourth shutout of the
season after making six saves and faced nine shots on goal, made a
brilliant stop on a header by Joe-Max Moore in the 71st minute.
Then, with time winding down, Moore caught Ammann off-guard when he
redirected a goal-mouth cross, but Ammann made an off-balance stab
to deflect it over the crossbar.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference in this game is very clear, guys,'' said
Rongen. ``We weren't putting our chances away and they get one-half
a chance and they do. That was the difference in the game. We got
five great opportunities, but we ran into a hot goalkeeper and
Ammann made some key saves that great goalkeepers make.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had three point-blank shots from about 5-6 yards out,'' he
added, ``I mean, it was incredible. But that's the story for us
right now. We just don't get a break when we need one.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
