A7256 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      07-02 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
M'S OPEN JULY WITH A BANG; GRIFFEY'S 34TH LEADS HR BARRAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ To get from where they are to where they want to be,
it is going to take the Mariners time, effort, some luck and a
confidence-building stretch of games, a combination that has been
missing for most of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``One game is not going to do it,'' first baseman David Segui
said.
</P>
<P>
   But a few more like Wednesday night's powerful 9-5 victory over
the Colorado Rockies at the Kingdome, where Segui hit two home
runs, Ken Griffey Jr. slugged his league-leading 34th and starting
pitcher Ken Cloude ended a two-month winless drought, can only help
reverse an up-til-now dreadful season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too many people have lost confidence in themselves and
forgotten how to win,'' Segui said. ``We have been waiting to lose
instead of doing the things to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Decent pitching. Clutch hitting. And defense.
</P>
<P>
   See how easy it is?
</P>
<P>
   Cloude won his first game since April 24. Segui looked like an
All-Star, although he wasn't selected to the team, Griffey put up
an All-Star performance with three doubles and a home run, and
designated hitter Edgar Martinez slugged a go-ahead homer in the
first inning, leaving the woes of an awful June (8-21) in the
rear-view mirror.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good way to start a new month,'' manager Lou Piniella
said. ``Let's hope this month treats us better than the month of
June.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey led a 16-hit fireworks show.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)His three doubles tied a club single-game record.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)He has homered in six of his past eight games, and his 56
extra-base hits lead the majors.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)His 34 homers is a personal career best prior to the
All-Star Game. Only Mark McGwire (37, this season) and Reggie
Jackson (37 in 1969) have hit more.
</P>
<P>
   But Griffey had some help. The seven doubles matched a season
high and Segui's two-homer night was the fourth of his career _ and
third this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The challenge for us is to come out here and do it again,''
Segui said. ``So many times this year I thought we would (get on a
winning streak), but we came out flat.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners have won back-to-back games only once since May 29.
Their last three-game ``streak'' was May 2-6.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to see how we do over a 10- to 15-game stretch,'' Segui
said. ``I don't think anybody in here has given up on the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Segui's second homer of the game came during an explosive fifth
inning when the Mariners expanded a one-run lead into a five-run
cushion at 9-4.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey pushed the rally button with a leadoff double. Martinez
came within a foot or two of hitting his second homer of the game,
but had to settle for a ground-rule double. A fan in right-center
reached between the railing and caught Martinez's drive before it
had a chance to carom off the wall.
</P>
<P>
   An alert first base umpire, Bill Miller, immediately ruled a
ground-rule double. Griffey scored anyway and soon so did Martinez,
on Segui's second homer.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle added another run in the inning as Russ Davis singled
and scored when Glenallen Hill drove a double into the gap in
left-center, also driving Rockies starter Mike Saipe from his
second big-league start.
</P>
<P>
   The right-hander received a quick introduction to the majors'
most powerful lineup. After an unearned run gave him Saipe a 1-0
lead in the top of the first inning, Alex Rodriguez singled with
one out, advanced to second on an infield out.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez put Seattle in front with his 13th homer of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey's 34th _ a wicked line drive to right field _ came with
Rodriguez aboard in the third inning and, one out later, Segui hit
his first homer of the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners had seven hits Wednesday before the Rockies had
any, but the four-run lead Cloude carried into the fourth inning
began disappearing the same way it was produced.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado came back with its own power barrage.
</P>
<P>
   Vinny Castilla, selected to the National League All-Star team
earlier in the day, pounded his 24th homer of the season into the
right field seats, giving the Rockies their second run and first
hit.
</P>
<P>
   Cloude's lead dwindled to three runs and then one on Todd
Helton's two-run homer.
</P>
<P>
   It was Helton's 12th of the season and the 17th Cloude has
allowed.
</P>
<P>
   But Cloude recovered and struck out four of the next five
batters he faced before running into more trouble in the sixth. The
Mariners bullpen, starting with left-hander Greg McCarthy, came to
the rescue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good to see Ken Cloude win a ballgame,'' Piniella said.
``It has been awhile and we need to get him on a roll. He gave up
some runs but we scored more.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Cloude (4-7): ``Hopefully, it's a sign of things to come.
It has been a long time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-98 0242EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
