<HEADER>
A7257 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN     07-02 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS LOSE TO GIANTS IN 10 INNINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ It's something the Angels say they have become used
to, but not necessarily something they are happy about.
</P>
<P>
   Before their 6-3, 10-inning loss to the San Francisco Giants
Wednesday night in front of 24,299 at Edison Field, the Angels
learned which of their players would be participating in next
week's All-Star game.
</P>
<P>
   To them, however, what was noteworthy wasn't so much who was
named to the American League team _ first baseman/outfielder Darin
Erstad and pitcher Troy Percival _ but who was left off the team.
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Gary DiSarcina, center fielder Jim Edmonds and pitcher
Chuck Finley have been All-Stars in the past, but not this year.
What makes it wrong, the Angels say, is that the club's performance
so far this season is being ignored.
</P>
<P>
   To add injury to insult, Tim Salmon _ already hampered by a
partially torn ligament in his left foot _ was hit on the inside
part of his left knee by a line drive hit by teammate Justin
Baughman. Salmon, who was on third base but standing in foul
territory, was diagnosed with a contusion of the knee. He had the
knee drained after being replaced by a pinch runner.
</P>
<P>
   The two other division leaders in the American League _ the
Yankees and Indians _ have five players each going to the All-Star
game. The Angels, the AL West leaders, have just the two.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without a question,'' Erstad said after being asked if more
Angels deserved to go. ``Ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   Erstad and Percival spoke to the media during a news conference
Wednesday afternoon and appeared embarrassed that they were going
without any other teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole team deserves to go,'' said Percival, 1-2 with a
2.80 ERA and a major league-leading 25 saves. ``Whether a guy's
hitting .240, we've got guys that grind it out every day. I think
our going is representative of everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys we have are grunts,'' he said. ``We don't have flashy
guys like Derek Jeter and Omar Vizquel. We don't have a lot of
pretty players. I think that's a testament to our team. We're in
first place and we don't have six guys on the All-Star team.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't pretty the way the Angels lost Wednesday, either. They
scored two runs in the eighth inning to tie the game at 2, only to
lose it after Bill Mueller hit a three-run homer off losing pitcher
Greg Cadaret (1-2) in the top of the 10th. The Giants added a
fourth run in the inning on J.T. Snow's RBI single.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Nen (6-1) gave up a run in the 10th but still got the win in
relief for the Giants. Despite the loss, the Angels maintained a
3{-game lead over Texas in the AL West.
</P>
<P>
   Angels starter Steve Sparks wouldn't have made a minor league
All-Star team this season, going a combined 0-8 at double-A Midland
and triple-A Vancouver this season before being called up to the
Angels June 15.
</P>
<P>
   But he went into Wednesday's game with three victories in three
starts. He pitched well again against the Giants, giving up two
runs and seven hits in 71/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants' only runs off him came on a sacrifice fly by Brent
Mayne in the fifth and a Barry Bonds homer in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Giants starter Danny Darwin, however, was just a little bit
better. Darwin shut out the Angels on four hits in 61/3 innings,
getting relief help from John Johnstone, who escaped a
bases-loaded, one-out situation after replacing Darwin in the
seventh.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels, though, tied the game in the eighth on RBI doubles
by Edmonds and Orlando Palmeiro.
</P>
<P>
   DiSarcina, hitting .307 and playing outstanding defense, said he
has no problem being overlooked by AL manager Mike Hargrove for an
All-Star selection.
</P>
<P>
   ``Speaking from the shortstop position, if I don't deserve to
make it, I don't think Omar should make it,'' DiSarcina said of the
Indians' shortstop. ``Nomar (Garciaparra of the Red Sox) hands down
is the better shortstop. I understand a manager taking care of his
own players. I have no problem with that. But Nomar should have a
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Edmonds (.307, 14 homers, 48 RBIs) and Finley (8-4, 3.05 ERA)
have put up All-Star numbers, but DiSarcina says a lack of national
recognition exists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe there is something there,'' he said. ``Jimmy's very
deserving, Finley without a doubt is very deserving and you could
make a case for me. But we're not in a big market. We don't get a
lot of publicity. There's a three-hour time change to the East
Coast, so they don't see a lot of our games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a lot of guys hitting .330 every year. We just
have guys grinding every day. Darin, Jimmy, Troy, Chuck have played
like All-Stars every day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-98 0245EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980702.0054 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 03:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7260 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRUGAL-GOURMET-SETTLE     07-02 1272
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRUGAL-GOURMET-SETTLEMENT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FRUGAL GOURMET' AGREES TO SETTLEMENTS IN ALLEGATIONS OF SEXUAL
ASSAULT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JACK HOPKINS  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TACOMA, Wash. _ Celebrity chef Jeff Smith, an ex-chaplain who
won national recognition as the Frugal Gourmet on public
television, has agreed to pay an undisclosed amount of money to
seven men who say he forced them to have sex with him while they
were teenagers.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, reached quietly this week during out-of-court
negotiations between lawyers for Smith and the men who filed civil
suits against him last year, avoids a messy trial that was to begin
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, host of the most-watched TV cooking show ever and author
of 12 cookbooks that sold an estimated 7 million copies, declined
comment on the settlement when reached at his Pike Place Market
condominium and test kitchen Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry. I'm cooking lunch for my staff. Call my lawyer in
Tacoma. Thank you,'' was all the 59-year-old celebrity would say
before hanging up.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, through his attorney, has denied any wrongdoing in the
past.
</P>
<P>
   No criminal charges were filed against him in connection with
any of the alleged assaults and the statute of limitations has
expired on all of the alleged incidents.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's attorney, Ed Winskill, confirmed Wednesday that the case
has been settled. But he would not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   F. Mike Shaffer, the Tacoma lawyer who represents the men who
accused Smith of sexually assaulting them, said he will file a
notice today in Pierce County Superior Court, canceling the trial.
Terms of the settlement don't require judicial approval, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Shaffer declined to say whether the settlement includes an
apology or admission of wrongdoing by Smith.
</P>
<P>
   But all of the men who said they were sexually assaulted by
Smith will receive monetary payments, Shaffer said. ``The terms of
the settlement are confidential. That's all I can say,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   According to one source familiar with the case, Smith had few
personal assets left and the main question in negotiations centered
on the monetary limits of his insurance policies.
</P>
<P>
   Six of the men had alleged that Smith sexually assaulted them
while they were working for him at the now-defunct Chaplain's
Pantry he owned and operated in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   They contended that in the course of hiring and directing
employees for his restaurant and catering business, Smith pursued a
pattern of grooming high school-age boys for sexual intercourse and
used alcohol, seduction and coercion as part of the practice.
</P>
<P>
   A seventh man claimed he was hitch-hiking as a 14-year-old in
Tacoma when, according to the man, Smith picked him up and raped
him in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The men claimed they only became aware of the full extent of
their physical and psychological injuries in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement doesn't affect the case of still another man, a
37-year-old Eatonville man who contends Smith coerced him into
having sex and participating in ``sexually oriented parties with
other adult pedophiles and other minor boys'' more than 20 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton Smith's claim was dismissed by a judge in February and
now is under appeal in the state Court of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton Smith, who is not related to Jeff Smith, played a key
role in urging the other alleged victims to step forward and take
legal action against the television chef. Clinton Smith began
contacting the media about his claims in the early 1990s and aired
them on radio talk shows in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton Smith alleged that Jeff Smith agreed in 1990 to pay him
and another man $1.5 million each to keep silent about the alleged
abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton Smith said he was paid $300,000, but the rest was
withheld after an acquaintance told Jeff Smith that Clinton Smith
had talked about the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Shaffer, the Tacoma attorney representing the seven men who just
settled with Jeff Smith, filed a copy of the purported agreement as
an attachment to lawsuits filed on behalf of those plaintiffs.
However, Winskill, Jeff Smith's attorney, has denied the agreement
exists.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton Smith was sentenced to four years in prison in 1981,
partly for stealing money from Jeff Smith's restaurant. At the
time, Clinton Smith said he took the money in retaliation for being
sexually assaulted, according to police records.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Smith has bitterly contested the allegations made by the
men and the trial was expected to be unusually hard-fought, as have
been the pre-trial battles.
</P>
<P>
   Most recently, the two sides clashed over the question of
whether Jeff Smith's wife, Patty Smith, should be required to
testify about her husband's sexual conduct.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's lawyers contended that the legal concept of marital
privilege allowed her to refuse to respond to such questions. But
Shaffer contended the court could require her to testify because if
she saw her husband performing a sex act on an employee, she saw
that not as a wife, but as an employee of their business and a
stockholder in their concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Shaffer contended she shared responsibility for what happened
because, he said, she either knew or should have known about her
husband's sexual misconduct with teenagers.
</P>
<P>
   During pretrial depositions, however, Patty Smith said her
involvement with the restaurant operation was minimal. She said she
made cheesecakes and occasionally did laundry, but was seldom
around the restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Pierce County Superior Court Judge Fred Fleming ruled Patty
Smith must answer the questions. But that decision was appealed to
the state Court of Appeals which still had the matter under
consideration when the trial was averted by this week's settlement.
</P>
<P>
   The Frugal Gourmet appeared on 300 public television stations
and was watched by as many as 15 million viewers at its peak. But
it is seen on only a handful of stations now.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ceased feeding the Frugal Gourmet series to local stations
in late December of last year when our rights to the library (of
Frugal Gourmet shows) expired,'' Stu Kantor, communications
director for the Public Broadcasting System in Washington, D.C.,
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Some local stations still have the rights to air Frugal Gourmet
programs until October and those stations will independently decide
whether to keep running the cooking programs in the wake of the
settlements, he said.
</P>
<P>
   It is unlikely that PBS will seek the rights to new Frugal
Gourmet programs in the future, Kantor said. But that's unrelated
to Smith's legal problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were told in January 1996 by the series' producers that
they had no plans to create any new programs,'' Kantor said.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle's public television station, KCTS/Channel 9, has not
broadcast the Frugal Gourmet for several months. It stopped running
the program when PBS' rights to the program ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not broadcast it for some time and have no plans for
broadcasting it in the future,'' Kay Ingram, KCTS' chief program
executive, said last night.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Smith's Frugal Gourmet cookbooks were published by William
Morrow &AMP; Co., and Avon, book divisions of the Hearst Corporation.
Division spokespersons weren't available for comment last night.
</P>
<P>
   His books, however, have been highly successful in past years.
He was the first cook ever to have two cookbooks on The New York
Times best-seller list at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Before entering the restaurant business and becoming a
television chef and author, Jeff Smith was a chaplain at the
University of Puget Sound in Tacoma.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporters Ed Penhale and Steve Miletich contributed to this
report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-98 0304EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
