</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPECIALS-BUDGET-NYTSF </SLUG>
  
 NEWS &AMP; FEATURES SUMMARY No 2460 - JULY 2, 1998  
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. HONG KONG'S LEADER : ``OUR FUTURE WILL BE BETTER''
</P>
<P>
   INTERVIEW WITH TUNG CHEE-HWA A year has passed since Hong Kong
reverted to Chinese control. It has been a difficult year for the
former British colony, which is now undergoing its worst financial
crisis in years. But Tung Chee-hwa, the head of the Hong Kong
government, says in this interview that he is fully confident the
economy will improve, and that Hong Kong will maintain its freedoms
and its considerable autonomy from the Beijing government. From Der
Spiegel. 1,000 words. (English translation available.) 2.
PREVENTING WAR IN THE TAIWAN STRAIT Although Beijing is usually
thought of as the villain, Taipei, provocatively moving toward
independence, must be reined in. By Chas W. Freeman Jr. Foreign
Affairs magazine. 1,500 words. 3. WOMEN AND HEART DISEASE : IT'S
NOT JUST FOR MEN Could you have heart disease and not know it?
Gurney Williams III looks at the warning signs, and tells you how
to find out if you or a family member are at risk. From Family
Circle magazine. 1,400 words. 4. VACCINATION : SEVEN MYTHS AND THE
FACTS YOU SHOULD KNOW Lisa Collier Cool talks to the experts about
which vaccines your child should have, which ones are problematic
and how you can tell the difference. From Child magazine. 1,400
words. 5. MICHELANGELO'S HEARTBREAK COMES TO LIFE IN NEW LIGHT
Scientists, armed with special photography equipment, lasers, X-ray
machines and the most powerful computers in America, are attempting
to help shed light on one of the most intriguing mysteries of
Renaissance art : what caused Michelangelo to take a sledgehammer
and smash his Florentine Pieta sculpture. By Michael Specter. New
York Times Science Times. 1,600 words + photo.
_______________________________________________________________ 6.
QUICK TEST FOR DOWN'S SYNDROME CALLED PROMISING Researchers report
on a new test for Down's syndrome which can provide results on the
same day (instead of the present 15 day waiting period.) By Michael
McCarthy. The Lancet News Service. 1,000 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 7.
DON'T COUNT THREATS, COUNT CAPACITY Foreign policy watchers bemoan
the lack of a coherent, consistent western strategy to deal with
the world after the Cold War. The sense of a unifying Soviet threat
has been replaced by the evocation of too many threats of greatly
assorted dimensions and credibility. There is a web of
inter-related problems, political, economic, military and
environmental, and the simple guideline must be to seek what helps
without causing greater unintended damage. By Flora Lewis. 1,000
words. 8. From WIRED MAGAZINE :  &QR;  WHOSE INTERNET IS IT, ANYWAY :
Geeks, lawyers, capitalists and bureaucrats are fighting over the
Net's holy temple - the root server. By David Diamond. 4,000 words.
 &QR;  DRESS CODE Wearables (e.g. a tiny personal computer concealed in
a shoe or a belt-mounted system for customs officers) are already
bringing us ``heads up, hands free'' augmented reality in the
workplace. By Thomas Bass. 1,500 words.  &QR;  FROM ANTS TO EINSTEIN
Harvard biologist Edward O. Wilson explains how Nature's law and
Moore's Law point to a unified theory of everything. Interview by
Paul Bennett. 1,000 words.  &QR;  THE HOT NEW MEDIUM IS ... EMAIL List
publishing is not merely information delivered to your mailbox,
it's the devolution of mass media into the hands of everyday
people. And it's growing faster than the Web. It is a pure example
of the peculiar way new markets of cyberspace function. Reaching
one person is as easy as reaching a million. By David S. Bennahum.
4,000 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 9.
TIPS FOR GROWING AND USING BASIL Martha Stewart explains how to sow
and use this irresistible, aromatic herb. 1,000 words + photo.
_______________________________________________________________ 10.
WHAT'S DOING IN SANTA FE Santa Fe, the city of Holy Faith, this
year celebrates the 400th anniversary of Spanish settlement in New
Mexico. What really sets this city apart is its extensive art scene
: Within a single square mile, more than a million pieces of art
are concentrated, and that doesn't include 400 years of sacred
images in the churches and missions. Judith Anderson tells where to
go, what to see, where to eat and where to stay. 2,000 words +
photo.
</P>
