<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SEES CHINA'S TRADEOFF BETWEEN DEVELOPMENT AND ENVIRONMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GUILIN, China _ Here along the banks of the Li River, China's
environmental challenge looms as dramatically as the majestic
limestone formations that soar hundreds of feet into the misty air.
</P>
<P>
   The steep green hillsides overlooking the river's muddy waters
bear the scars of clear cutting as rural villagers harvest the
ancient forests to provide firewood to heat their homes and cook
their meals.
</P>
<P>
   With the forests gone, villagers have been forced to turn to a
new source of fuel. They are using so-called bio-gas _ flammable
methane produced by fetid underground pits of decomposing pig
manure and rice husks and delivered to a kitchen burner by rubber
tubing.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton came face-to-face with the challenges
afflicting China's peasants Thursday when he visited this
picturesque region and urged China to forego the mistakes of the
West's pollution-producing, 150-year industrial revolution.
</P>
<P>
   However, Chinese environmentalists sympathetic to Clinton's
cause warned that impoverished peasants in the nation of 1.2
billion are willing to inflict further environmental damage on
their polluted homeland if that's what needed to lift their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Zhou Dadi, an expert on energy efficiency and climate change who
serves as director of the Beijing Energy Conservation Center, told
Clinton during a roundtable discussion here that China's rural poor
stubbornly resist their leaders' appeals for anti-pollution
measures.
</P>
<P>
   China's rural villagers say, ```We are moving into your house
and you people come here and live in this forest and see whether
you can stop the logging and have a decent life,''' Zhou told
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton urged China to take advantage of technological
breakthroughs that are being used in the West to cut pollution or
energy use by vehicles, buildings and factories.
</P>
<P>
   He cited fuel injection vehicle engines that cut energy waste by
80 percent; long-lasting lightbulbs; and the use of wasted heat
from power plants to heat, cool and light public facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that China has a unique opportunity _ because you're
developing rapidly but later in time than other countries _ to
avoid some of the terrible mistakes we made,'' Clinton told the
seven environmentalists during a round table discussion that took
place in this one-time communist stronghold during China's civil
war.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton hailed China's effort to clean up the Li River to keep
its luster as a tourist attraction that draws 6 million Chinese and
500,000 foreigners each year. He noted that reforestation projects
have sown young pine trees across some of the once-forested
landscape that was denuded by desperate peasants during the
Cultural Revolution in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now is the time to join our citizens and our governments, our
businesses and our industries in the fight against pollution and
global warming _ even as we fight for a brighter economic future
for the people of China and the people of the entire world,''
Clinton declared.
</P>
<P>
   Air pollution is so prevalent in China that respiratory
illnesses claim more lives than cancer or heart disease. China is
expected to surpass the United States within 20 years as the
world's chief producer of climate-changing greenhouse gases.
</P>
<P>
   American officials said that Clinton's interaction with
environmental activists was designed in part to highlight citizen
activism.
</P>
<P>
   The fledgling environmental movement ``really is a reflection of
the growing sense of citizens being able to be active here,''
explained James Steinberg, deputy national security adviser.
``There is beginning to be a grass roots effort throughout China
which can be a very important factor for change.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS - STORY MAY END HERE)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The stopover gave Clinton a vivid look at the landscape and
meager livelihoods of many Chinese. His motorcade into Guilin swept
past lush green fields of rice being cultivated by bent Chinese
peasants in pointed straw hats.
</P>
<P>
   Water buffaloes grazed on high ground over looking fields
crisscrossed by irrigation canals of muddy green-brown water.
</P>
<P>
   Fingers of limestone, known as karst formations, rose up to 600
feet or more above the fields and nearby tangerine orchards.
</P>
<P>
   The fantasy landscape has inspired Chinese poets and ink
paintings for thousands of years. An emperor more than 1,000 years
ago was so awestruck that he proclaimed Guilin ``the first under
heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, like tourists before him, boarded a boat to take the
40-mile river cruise down the river to Yangshuo past peaks bearing
legendary names such as Paint Brush Hill, Cock Fighting Hills,
Painted Hill of Nine Horses and the Frog Crossing the River.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
