<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN-1STLEDE-$ADV05-CO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: TURN 65, SEE YOUR MEDICAL RIGHTS CURBED
 &HT;    Eds: Adjusts language in 4th graf to clarify rights of seniors
to pay privately.
 &HT;    For release Sunday, July 5
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ By all accounts, President Clinton repeatedly urged
his Chinese hosts to relax their tight grip on the lives of their
people. But back home, when it comes to the rights of Medicare
beneficiaries, Clinton seems more comfortable with the Chinese
Communist model.
</P>
<P>
   Consider that, after you turn 65, your doctor can go to jail for
health care fraud if you decide to sidestep the Medicare
bureaucracy and pay his fee directly.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the vast majority of the 38 million Americans under
Medicare would have scant reason to pay for covered health care
services out of their own pockets. In nearly every case, doctors
accept Medicare reimbursements as payment in full for their
services.
</P>
<P>
   Although seniors can order a physician not to submit their
Medicare claim, for example to protect their privacy, they face the
threat of being denied treatment by a specialist in high demand
even when they are willing to pay privately. While Congress or the
courts may yet return matters to they way they were when Medicare
was enacted in 1965, such choices have been barred since January.
</P>
<P>
   When Medicare officials, acting on their own, put the squeeze on
doctors who billed their Medicare patients directly for services
delivered outside the government-paid insurance plan, Congress
stepped in. The Senate voted 64-35 to uphold such private
contracts, provided safeguards against double billing were in
place.
</P>
<P>
   Fearful that some doctors would fill their appointment books
with high-paying seniors at the expense of Medicare beneficiaries,
Clinton reacted by threatening to veto the entire federal budget
unless the proviso was excised.
</P>
<P>
   Thereupon, Congress enacted a so-called compromise that obliges
physicians to opt out of Medicare entirely for two years in order
to enter into even one private patient agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two-year exclusion presents your doctor with a very
difficult choice,'' Sen. Jon Kyl, R-Ariz., said. ``He can either
treat you, his patient of, say, 30 years on a private contract
basis and dump all of his other Medicare patients or refuse to
treat you in favor of his current Medicare patients.''
</P>
<P>
   Since about 96 percent of doctors accept Medicare patients, few
would likely be willing to impose such a hardship on their current
senior rosters. So, as Kyl sees it, the two-year option amounts to
``an almost meaningless choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Kyl and Rep. Bill Archer, R-Tex., are leading the effort to
change the law. Noting that there aren't any such limits under
Medicaid or the health plans that cover federal workers, including
members of Congress, 51 senators have backed a resolution upholding
the right of seniors to contract privately for care.
</P>
<P>
   For doctors who would treat well-off seniors in this way, such
an arrangement would parallel the cost-shifting that is seen in
hospital bills. By accepting higher fees from some seniors, the
doctors could afford to expand the number of lower-fee Medicare
patients they see.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, so far as we know, White House has no plans
ask Congress to bar private markets that accept food stamps from
also selling their goods to shoppers at listed prices. Perhaps that
will make the Chinese leaders take more heed of the blessings that
our free system has to offer.
</P>
<P>
   (Andrew J. Glass is a Washington, D.C.-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
