A7427 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CROPS-DROUGHT03-COX     07-02 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CROPS-DROUGHT03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ranchers hurt by poor hay crop
 &HT;    By Pamela Coleman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COUPLAND, Texas _ Melvin Poldrack loaded up the bed of his
pickup truck this week with tubs of sweet-smelling liquid protein
for his cattle, something he usually doesn't do until winter.
</P>
<P>
   But this year, a hot sun and dry wind have shriveled fields of
grass and stolen most of the year's hay crop, leaving the cattle
dependent on other sources of nutrition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without any hay, if you let (the cattle) get in bad shape,
going into the winter your death loss will be great,'' Poldrack
said, watching as 30 or so Simmental cattle gathered around his
truck, parked in a parched field east of Coupland. ``You have two
options _ feed them or sell them.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the Texas Agriculture Extension Service, the loss
in hay production this year will cost an estimated $175 million
statewide. A dry spring devastated the early hay crop, preventing
many area farmers and ranchers from making a first baling. The
shortage has ranchers looking to Oklahoma and New Mexico for hay _
an expensive prospect.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't find any in the state,'' said Poldrack, 65.
</P>
<P>
   That's why he's turned to the liquid protein, whose main
ingredient is cane molasses. But in a field of 30 cattle, one $57
tub will last only a few days. And Poldrack, who runs Poldrack
Grain &AMP; Cattle with his son Terry, has about 2,000 head of cattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just something to keep them going,'' he said. ``But it's
more work and more expense.''
</P>
<P>
   By this time of the year, about 50,000 acres of coastal and
other types of high quality hay usually have been baled in
Williamson County, said County Extension Agent Ron Leps. This year,
only about 2,000 or 3,000 acres have been harvested.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of that was oat and wheat straw, and that's probably
about as good as a snowball or good for elephant bedding,'' Leps
said. ``It has no nutritional value.''
</P>
<P>
   There's no relief in sight, either. ``With the way the wind
isblowing and hot as it is, I don't see us making a baling of hay
until this fall,'' Leps said.
</P>
<P>
   That means there may be no hay to tide the cattle through the
winter _ unless farmers have it trucked in from other areas or
soaking rains come. And even if the skies open up, the hay problem
won't immediately go away, said Don Kuker, director of livestock
marketing for the Texas Department of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could rain today really good and there would not be any hay
cut for another 30 days,'' Kuker said. ``And when it was cut, the
people who cut it are not going to sell it, they're going to hang
on to it.''
</P>
<P>
   To put ranchers in touch with hay suppliers, the Texas
Department of Agriculture has set up a hay hotline. More than 100
people a day, most of them looking for hay for their cattle, have
called the line since started Monday, Kuker said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most calls we're getting are from southeast of Austin all
the way to northeast Texas,'' Kuker said.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, a large round bale of hay sells for $25 to $35, Kuker
said. This year they're going for $45 or more _ when they can be
found. Small square bales that normally sell for $2.50 are selling
for $4.50 and up. And while hay is available in parts of New Mexico
and Oklahoma and further north, ranchers must pay about $1.50 a
loaded mile just to have it trucked in.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a lot of people from the Midwest wanting to sell
hay,'' Kuker said. ``They're overrun with hay. But transportation _
that's the only kicker. The trucking expense.''
</P>
<P>
   Many farmers, including Poldrack, are considering mowing down
their cornstalks after harvest and baling them to feed to the
cattle. Most farmers lost most of the corn crop because of the
drought anyway, and they say this is a way to salvage some of that
disaster.
</P>
<P>
   But there's a danger in feeding the stunted cornstalks, too. If
the soil was too dry early in the planting season, the corn may
have high nitrate levels, which can poison the cattle, said Dr.
John Reagor, head of department of toxicology at the Texas
Veterinary Medical Diagnostic Lab in College Station.
</P>
<P>
   He encourages farmers and ranchers to bring forage samples to
laboratories for nitrate analysis before feeding their herds. His
lab tested about 120 samples in the first two weeks of June, and
expects to handle about 400 tests a week before long if the drought
continues.
</P>
<P>
   Leon Schrank, executive director of the Williamson County Farm
Service Agency, said the situation this year is made worse for
ranchers because many of them sold off parts of their herds during
the drought two years ago because they had nothing to feed them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our problem this year is that they still haven't bought back
all the cattle they sold in 1996,'' Schrank said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
