 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE JULY 4 WEEKEND COMMENTARY BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These columns for release Friday, June 3, 1998, are moving today
to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   Two July 4-themed columns are being resent today for those who
need them:
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN04 _ Soon, we will be inundated with newspaper
inserts and television commercials telling us to rush down to this
department store or that appliance store on the Fourth to buy,
purportedly on sale, anything from washing machines and television
sets to brassieres and blue denim jeans.
</P>
<P>
   I don't recall that John Adams said anything about that type of
observance when he read the Declaration of Independence to the
people gathered in Philadelphia in 1776.(Kleinberg, Cox News
Service)
</P>
<P>
   MURRAY-COLUMN04 _ Best Fourth of July I remember is the only
Fourth of July I remember crying. It was 1990. I was in Moscow.
(Murray, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   Because of the long holiday weekend, the rest of our report
today comprises columns normally sent on Thursdays and Fridays:
</P>
<P>
   GLASS-COLUMN _ WASHINGTON _ By all accounts, President Clinton
repeatedly urged his Chinese hosts to relax their tight grip on the
lives of their people. But back home, when it comes to the rights
of Medicare beneficiaries, Clinton seems more comfortable with the
Chinese Communist model. (Glass, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ I'm afraid no end of mischief will flow from the
proposal by a group of scientists that an ongoing process be set up
for examining of UFO events. (Teepen, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN05 _ Ever since Lyndon Johnson fabricated the
Gulf of Tonkin attack, I've stopped blindly accepting whatever my
government is telling me. Particularly when it comes to threats
against us, and military success. (Kleinberg, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   LATHAM-COLUMN _ MT. LANIER, Tenn. _ Looking out over the side of
Mt. Lanier down a valley that stretched for miles, the history of
this place does not matter. It has the power to overwhelm you. The
scene is so spectacular that I found myself drowning in my own
insignificance. It was a meaningful lesson in humility. (Latham,
Marshall News Messenger)
</P>
<P>
   MINTER-COLUMN _ My wife has a theory about local TV news.
``They're faking witnesses,'' she said. ``Haven't you noticed that
when television reporters go to the scene of a murder, a tornado, a
fire or a wreck on the expressway all the people they interview
look and talk alike? They're all overweight, use terrible English,
wear tank tops and need to wash their hair.'' (Minter, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
