<P>
   EDITORS NOTE: Because of the long holiday weekend, our report
today comprises features normally sent on Thursdays and Fridays.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS (e category)
</P>
<P>
   TVSURFER-COLUMN _ Starting July 4, TNT's Monstervision with Joe
Bob Briggs carries a summer school theme for 10 weeks. (July 4:
Physics and Trig _ ``Back to the Future'' and ``Time After Time'';
July 11: Animal Husbandry _ ``Beastmaster'' triology; etc.). A
roundup of July 4 fireworks on television. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). ETA: 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-NOTES _ Inspired while watching ``Midnight Run'' on
television one night, Janet Evanovich created Stephanie Plum, a New
Jersey department store lingerie buyer turned bounty hunter. Her
first novel, ``One for the Money,'' sold to the movies for nearly
$1 million, and Evanovich was on her way to becoming a best-selling
author. In Atlanta this week to promote her fourth book, ``Four to
Score'' (St. Martin's, $23.95), Evanovich says she tries to lace
her mysteries with lots of humor. (O'Briant, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-MEMOIRS _ Reviewing ``Freedom's Child: The Life of a
Confederate General's Black Daughter'' and ``Battlegrounds of
Memory: A Memoir of Southern Family.'' (Warmbold, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
