<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 10:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7437 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARMAGEDDON-REVIEW03-C     07-02 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARMAGEDDON-REVIEW03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'Armageddon' best American movie of the year
 &HT;    By Chris Garcia
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Armageddon'' is slam-bang sensory overkill. It's loud. It's
heavy-handed. It's melodramatic. It's an explosion of baroque
excess that splats on the screen and bludgeons the audience into a
collective migraine.
</P>
<P>
   It's the best American movie of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Here's why: In this asteroid-is-coming comic thriller, director
Michael Bay (``The Rock'') demonstrates the euphoric possibilities
of filmmaking. We're not talking about the robust humanism of Elia
Kazan or the experimental elan of Godard. We're talking about
rapturous visual delirium, the mad, pictorial exactitude of John
Woo.
</P>
<P>
   Even the most banal shots are mathematically calculated wonders.
Bay cut his teeth on TV commercials and rock videos, and the scenes
here ooze the syrupy gloss of those huckster mediums. Rock songs by
Aerosmith, ZZ Top, Bon Jovi and Journey _ a roster of tacky '80s
power-pop bands _ underscore several sequences. Nothing could be
more apt for summer blockbusters, the ultimate advertisements. And,
besides, any action flick that can use Curtis Mayfield's
``Pusherman'' tastefully can't be all bad.
</P>
<P>
   Bay has a golden eye for riveting composition, and he keeps the
images pulsing with multiple swooshing cameras and crackling
editing. You spin at the sheer artistry, even if you're watching a
simple conversation between two actors. With John Schwartzman's
sumptuous cinematography, ``Armageddon'' is one of the best-looking
movies in a very long time.
</P>
<P>
   Taking another cue from Woo, Bay and screenwriters Johnathan
Hensleigh and J.J. Abrams slather on as much cheap emotionalism as
the story can bear before buckling under its overabundance. After
we're numbed by its visceral pounding, the movie finally wants us
to feel. The forced emotional twinges arrive like the faint tingles
in a limb that's fallen asleep. They don't feel right, but they're
still kind of neat-o.
</P>
<P>
   ``Armageddon'' _ how shall we say it? _ rocks. It is a movie
made by people high on their craft, standing naked on a mountain
top, arms raised to heaven, singing heavy-metal anthems with all
their might.
</P>
<P>
   Such exuberance invites blunders, and the sci-fi romp has its
share. You nearly suffocate on the clamor of the film's finale,
which gives way to bathos that's comical in its Hallmark-ad
gravity. But the sap suits a movie so fueled by gross surplus, in
the same way the maudlin end of Woo's ``Face/Off'' was the only
punctuation mark befitting that grand opera.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the material is surprisingly smart; a hip undercurrent
whips below the film's straight-faced surface. The rote plot _
imminent catastrophe averted by all-American heroes _ is spiked
with keenly funny writing, not just Bruce Willis-ready wisecracks,
and a hugely entertaining ensemble cast that's a fascinating mix of
Hollywood A-listers (Willis, Billy Bob Thornton, Ben Affleck) and
quirky indie fixtures (Steve Buscemi and Peter Stormare, who played
the killers in ``Fargo'').
</P>
<P>
   An asteroid the size of Texas is blazing toward Earth, and NASA
has 18 days to stop it. Since blowing up the rock with missiles
would trigger a deadly asteroid shower, NASA decides it must
implode it by jamming a nuke down it. Thornton is superb as the
NASA director who enlists the help of the best deep-core oil
driller in the world (Willis, lending the film muscular thrust).
</P>
<P>
   Willis' Harry Stamper brings with him a motley bunch of
roughneck oil drillers, many of them ex-cons, who wreak hilarious
havoc on NASA decorum. The sequences in which the clownish ensemble
trains for space flight yield huge laughs.
</P>
<P>
   Since we know from the get-go Earth won't be obliterated by the
asteroid, dramatic stakes are provided by a love triangle between
Affleck, his young fiancee Tyler and Tyler's overprotective father
Willis. Willis learns how to be a good dad. Tyler learns how to be
a good daughter. And Affleck scores. There's also some Army vs.
civilian showdowns tossed in, as if our little hearts could take
more pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Armageddon'' piles on the money shots, each one outdoing the
next in spectacle and physical kick. The movie is a 2 1/2 -hour
crescendo. Not a performance fails to entertain, as the characters
grow bigger and fresher and things throttle forth. Scenes of the
group in space trying to harness the asteroid are relentlessly
spectacular. The special effects, especially when Manhattan goes
down like fiery bowling pins, surpass all those blurry effects seen
in recent disaster films.
</P>
<P>
   This is a summer movie after which I might offer the box office
a couple of more bucks in gratitude for such a richly visceral
experience. Exhaustion and exhilaration set in like a hangover, the
cool dividend of massive cinematic drunkenness.
</P>
<P>
   Starring: Bruce Willis, Ben Affleck, Liv Tyler, Billy Bob
Thornton, Steve Buscemi
</P>
<P>
   Director: Michael Bay
</P>
<P>
   MPAA rating: PG-13 for intense action, language.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Garcia is the film critic for the Austin
American-Statesman.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
