<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 10:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7440 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN05-CO     07-02 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: The side of the barn is safe
 &HT;    (For release July 7, 1998.)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ever since Lyndon Johnson fabricated the Gulf of Tonkin attack,
I've stopped blindly accepting whatever my government is telling
me. Particularly when it comes to threats against us, and military
success.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, in another of what are becoming routine flareups
involving the United States and Iraq, we were informed that an
Iraqi radar locked onto a patrolling British plane over the
southern no-fly zone and that an accompanying American F-16 fired a
missile at the anti-aircraft battery thought to be the source of
the radar lock-on.
</P>
<P>
   Wars of words usually follow these actions, and the Iraqis lost
no time in claiming that the anti-aircraft battery the Americans
supposedly fired at was, instead, a water reservoir. They fished
bits of what they claimed to be the missile from the reservoir.
</P>
<P>
   We have a choice here of selecting from two well-known
practitioners of overstatement, the Americans and the Iraqis, and
it's not a pleasant choice to make. Did or did not the missile get
fired at an anti-aircraft battery, and if it did, what was it doing
in the middle of a water reservoir in a demilitarized zone where,
reportedly, there are no military installations?
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time American (and allied) claims of
military strike precision have been challenged. The glowing reports
of missile success against Iraqi targets during the Gulf War lost
much of their gloss when it was later uncovered that much of our
hardware went astray, off course, into things they weren't supposed
to hit.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, the delayed news of American troop deaths and
injuries caused by ``friendly fire'' made you begin to wonder who
was at war with whoM.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Arnett, the CNN reporter who visited a bombed target
outside Baghdad during the Gulf War and proclaimed it to be a baby
milk factory, was condemned by many as treasonous. (Arnett isn't
even American; he's a New Zealander.) But you don't hear too many
rebutting his on-the-scene observation any more.
</P>
<P>
   What worries me most about these flareups is not so much the
political twists put on them, usually to place pressure on an enemy
or relieve pressure from the U.S. government, but the fact that our
military strike capability is suspect.
</P>
<P>
   One has only to recall the exuberance in this nation over the
ability of the Patriot anti-missile missiles that we shipped to
Israel to defend it from Iraqi Scud attacks. Never was a weapon so
celebrated since we dropped the nuke on Hiroshima. Later, however,
we discovered the Patriot was a flawed weapon, lacking the speed to
overtake Scud missiles, unable to vaporize them and suffering from
computer glitches.
</P>
<P>
   We learned a deadly lesson when the Iraqis sent one into Saudi
Arabia, killing 28 U.S. troops. Belatedly, it was reported that the
Patriot computer would lose track of incoming Scuds if it was
operating for a long period of time.
</P>
<P>
   George Washington may never have told a lie, but he didn't pass
on that virtue to others who followed him into the seat of U.S.
power. I still can't explain to anyone why Ronald Reagan unleashed
an invasion of Grenada, or why George Bush invaded Panama just to
apprehend a drug lord, or why we do so many of the strange things
we do under the guise of defender of human rights, or world
policeman.
</P>
<P>
   Idealism has been swept beneath the floor in many areas of
American life because reality has come along and shown things to be
otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   This is very true with American strike capability. We're not the
military surgeons we like to think we are.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
