<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 10:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7441 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LATHAM-COLUMN03-COX     07-02 0653
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATHAM-COLUMN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    What I learned on top of a really big hill
 &HT;    By Phil Latham
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MT. LANIER, Tenn. _ As I was trying to catch my breath _ surely
the last breath that I would ever breathe _ the man to the right of
me was telling his son that this wasn't really a mountain.
</P>
<P>
   What?
</P>
<P>
   Was he saying that I had pulled myself up on this piece of rock,
20 easy miles by automobile and one hellish half-mile by foot, and
it was just a hill?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a really big hill,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The guy spoke with one of those foreign accents, you know, Ohio
or somewhere, so I figured that he had seen the Alps or the
Himalayas. I'll grant you, if you are accustomed to Mt. Everest,
the Great Smokeys probably aren't all that great.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, I'll admit that on certain days walking to work I'd
swear I climb several mountains between home and the office.
</P>
<P>
   Still, a rock that is more than 6,000 feet tall is not a hill
and I did not name this place Mt. Lanier. If science calls it a
mountain, it is, by golly, a mountain.
</P>
<P>
   Being atop a mountain, however, does not lend one to think of
science, though the most practical would consider all of this range
a huge geologic laboratory. You can read the description of how the
Great Smokey Mountain range was formed in the ranger's headquarters
if you so desire. I passed.
</P>
<P>
   Because, looking out over the side of Mt. Lanier down a valley
that stretched for miles, the history of this place did not matter.
It has the power to overwhelm you. Even if you aren't as out of
shape as I am, you'll find it difficult to catch your breath
looking at the panorama. The scene is so spectacular that I found
myself drowning in my own insignificance. It was a meaningful
lesson in humility.
</P>
<P>
   That is when I noticed an area of landslides on an adjacent
mountain. In several places, the terrain became so steep near the
top that the trees had given way. Those trees had knocked down
others and so on for a thousand-foot drop, leaving scars on the
side of the mountain.
</P>
<P>
   I spent a long time looking at those scars, trying to dissect
exactly how they got there and what they meant before I realized
how typically human I was being.
</P>
<P>
   All of this beauty surrounded me, there to be reveled in, and I
was spending my time analyzing the scars. I had done the same thing
on the half-mile hike up the mountain, rating my fellow hikers as I
am sure they
</P>
<P>
   were rating me (that tubbo is never gonna make it).
</P>
<P>
   What difference does it make what scars or imperfections we
might carry? We're all on the same journey up the mountain. If
someone can't make it, what we ought to be doing is giving them a
helping hand, not judging what caused them to fail. Helping doesn't
mean carrying them on our backs, though we might have to do that
sometimes; often just a word of encouragement is all it takes.
</P>
<P>
   On my way back down the mountain _ oh, yes, down is so much
easier than up _ I told at least a dozen people, ``You're almost
there,'' or ``You've made it more than halfway, you might as well
go the distance,'' or just, ``If I can do it, you can do it.''
</P>
<P>
   What I got in response was a smile and, in every instance, an
extra spring in their step. Funny thing is, giving that
encouragement helped me as much as it did them.
</P>
<P>
   All mountains have scars. Some are plain for view and some are
hidden by the regrowth of trees. Mountains aren't perfect, but it
doesn't make them any less a mountain. If anything, it gives them
character, something to set them apart.
</P>
<P>
   As we were driving out, making our way closer to sea level, I
noticed that the landslides never occurred on the flatter terrain.
No, it takes a mountain to have a scar _ or at least a really big
hill.
</P>
<P>
   (Phil Latham is editor and publisher of the Marshall News
Messenger.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
