</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINTER-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wrestle with this: TV news is all faked
 &HT;    By Jim Minter
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAYETTE COUNTY, Ga. _ An old farmer friend in our neighborhood
went to his grave absolutely convinced of two things:
</P>
<P>
   1. Neil Armstrong's moon walk was faked in a television studio.
</P>
<P>
   2. Professional wrestling is for real.
</P>
<P>
   While I learned early in life not to doubt the wisdom of old
farmers, I was never quite in agreement. Because of all the changes
in the weather, I'm fairly well convinced we really have been
sending people and other items into space. I've long harbored
nagging doubts about the authenticity of the grunting, groaning and
throwing each other around we see on television from fat
middle-aged men squeezed into bikini trunks.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps my skepticism about wrestling stems from an earlier life
as a sportswriter, when I occasionally was dispatched to the old
City Auditorium in Atlanta to cover Friday night matches. The
wrestlers, being hit, and sometimes kicked, in the face, bled
profusely in the ring. When I went backstage to interview them
after they showered and dressed, I was always amazed to notice that
despite all the public bleeding they had no visible cuts or
bruises. Rumors were they used tomato juice, but I wouldn't say one
way or the other. Some people are fast healers.
</P>
<P>
   My doubts were further fueled when I visited the local
promoter's office to interview the White Savage, a crazed ex-Marine
who had been captured in the jungles of Guatemala and brought to
Atlanta in chains to challenge the reigning champion. The White
Savage, after losing his mind on an extended tequila spree and
spending all those years living with wild animals, spoke no
language and ate only raw meat tossed to him from a safe distance.
</P>
<P>
   Under the circumstances, including his handler's warnings to
stay out of his reach, I was puzzled by the sunglasses and package
of Camels in his shirt pocket. Otherwise, I've had no reason to
doubt the veracity of professional wrestling until I read the story
about the African-American who is suing promoters because he's
dissatisfied with his ``scripting.'' He claims that because he is
black, promoters refuse to ``script'' him for a championship. I
hate to admit it, but it sounds an awful lot like he's saying the
wrestling we see on TV is not exactly on the up and up. I'm
thankful my farmer friend didn't live to hear it.
</P>
<P>
   Personally, I've never been high on conspiracy theories and
such. A lot of my neighbors think the Braves lose on purpose when
they get ahead in the World Series, just so they can play more
games and make more money. I think they lose because they have such
a sorry bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Until the African-American, who is in a position to know, said
in so many words that professional wrestling is fixed, I had not
worried excessively about what's real and what isn't on television.
I'm the trusting type, and in fact, have been a little embarrassed
by my wife's suspicions about local news.
</P>
<P>
   She thinks a lot of what we see on local television news is
fixed. In fact, she has suggested that I try to do something about
it, after I have fixed a broken door lock, repaired an ailing
air-conditioner, and performed several other chores requiring an
advanced degree from Georgia Tech.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could become an investigative journalist and expose what
they're doing,'' she said. ``You could win a Pulitzer Prize and be
famous.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you think they're doing?'' I asked. ``I've always
thought television newspeople were honorable folks.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're faking witnesses,'' she said. ``Haven't you noticed
that when television reporters go to the scene of a murder, a
tornado, a fire or a wreck on the expressway all the people they
interview look and talk alike? They're all overweight, use terrible
English, wear tank tops and need to wash their hair.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' I said. ``I have sort of noticed that, but I passed it
off to coincidence.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You would think that when they interview people involved in
one of the daily pile-ups on I-85 they'd occasionally run into a
doctor, or a lawyer, or an articulate insurance salesman,'' she
said. ``Maybe even a schoolteacher who gets verbs right.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Seems like that would happen,'' I agreed. ``But how could
television reporters rushing out to film an expressway pile-up find
people to interview unless they just happened to be there?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Simple enough,'' she replied. ``When they go out on assignment
they take the people they're going to interview with them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How would they do that?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Haven't you seen those panel trucks with the big channel
numbers that show up anywhere something bad happens?'' she asked.
``The things they call mobile units.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure,'' I said. ``That's how the television news teams
transport cameras and communications equipment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What they really have in those vans are the people they
interview when they arrive on the scene,'' she insisted.
</P>
<P>
   ``That makes some sense,'' I replied. ``Television reporters are
under a lot of deadline pressure. It can be awfully time-consuming
and expensive rounding up brand-new witnesses for every crime and
accident scene in the whole metropolitan area.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a central labor pool where all the TV stations send
their trucks every day to pick up the people they're going to
interview,'' she said. ``Take a good look at 6 and 11 o'clock and
tell me if I'm wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Minter is a former editor of The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
