</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURRAY-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: This Fourth of July, think of the
Soviet Union
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Best Fourth of July I remember is the only Fourth of July I
remember crying.
</P>
<P>
   It was 1990. I was in Moscow. This was back when it was still
the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   I'd been there two weeks, staying with Russian friends in their
cramped little apartment _ this in a complex of buildings dating
back to the 1950s and known as Khrushchev's teeth, yellow and
crooked as they were.
</P>
<P>
   My friends were breaking the law simply by having me as a guest.
Russians were forbidden even from being seen on the street talking
with Westerners. Such were the bad old days of communism.
</P>
<P>
   I'd brought a suitcase full of American cigarettes, the coin of
the Soviet realm. That, too, was illegal _ something on the order
of contraband.
</P>
<P>
   Not that anybody ever actually smoked them. They were too
valuable. Russians swapped packs of cigarettes for luxuries
available only through the black market. Food, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   But you couldn't buy a beer in Moscow for any price, except at a
small foreign-owned grocery that catered to diplomats and their
families.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about exclusive. You had to show an American Express card
to get in the door. No kidding.
</P>
<P>
   What I missed most were Cokes over ice. Coca-Colas I could buy
at the diplomat mart. You couldn't find ice anywhere. This in the
country that boasts of Siberia.
</P>
<P>
   But each Fourth of July the U.S. Embassy hosted a celebration at
its country estate, what's called a dacha (rhymes with gotcha.)
Anybody American _ even journalists _ were welcome.
</P>
<P>
   There was baseball, hamburgers, hot dogs, cold beer and, thank
heaven, even Cokes on ice!
</P>
<P>
   Kids were running barefoot. Guys were tossing frisbees. I
remember a pretty lady sitting beneath the shade of a tree, reading
a Danielle Steel novel.
</P>
<P>
   It was like a miracle. It was like America.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Marine color guard marched in, the brass band struck up
``The Star-Spangled Banner'' and everybody stood in reverence as
Old Glory of the United States fluttered in a summer breeze from
atop the flagpole.
</P>
<P>
   There I was, half a world away from home, hand over my heart,
the words of the National Anthem on my lips, and tears rolling down
my cheeks.
</P>
<P>
   Communism has since disappeared from what was the Soviet Union.
For that matter, so has the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   The New Russians _ Yuri the Yuppie, if you will _ drive Jeep
Grand Cherokees, pronounced sure-ROCK-yees.
</P>
<P>
   Billboards advertise Wonder Bras.
</P>
<P>
   You can buy a Coca-Cola on most any corner, or coke if that's
what you're into.
</P>
<P>
   Cell phones are everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   So are food stores, with giant neon signs that say ``Food
Stores'' in good ol' American English.
</P>
<P>
   Forget the KGB. Think KFC.
</P>
<P>
   In a way I guess it's a miracle. But it's not America.
</P>
<P>
   There's more to freedom than fast food, fancy cars and franchise
operations. It's a matter of the heart.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure Russia will ever get it right. But being there all
those years ago taught me a lesson in patriotism I'll never forget.
</P>
<P>
   This Fourth of July, be thankful you're an American.
</P>
<P>
   Salute the flag.
</P>
<P>
   Sing the National Anthem.
</P>
<P>
   Shoot off a firecracker.
</P>
<P>
   Shed a tear.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
</P>
<P>
   AWEW18A(at)prodigy.com; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108,
Lufkin, Texas, 75915.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
