<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: UFO studies not a serious line of inquiry
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I'm afraid no end of mischief will flow from the proposal by a
group of scientists that an ongoing process be set up for examining
of UFO events. If UFO buffs were hard to keep in the woodwork when
science universally scoffed at tales of flying saucers and little
green men, you may be sure they will swarm now that science seems
to have slipped one shoulder strap and winked.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that the international panel emphasized it was
issuing no come-hither look to kooks eager for a hot date at the
local polytechnic. There is, its members wrote, no evidence we are
being watched, much less being visited, by space creatures. (They
seem to have overlooked the guests on the Jerry Springer show, but
then alien lore always assumes we could be visited only by beings
of superior intelligence, so perhaps Springer is a false lead after
all.)
</P>
<P>
   Many supposed UFO incidents, the panel says, can be explained by
natural forces like electrical activity high above thunderstorms
and radar ducting (don't ask). Even so, there remains a stubborn
residue of reports that are honestly attested to and that resist
obvious explanation by known natural phenomena. Perhaps, the panel
says, they bear witness to extraordinarily rare natural phenomena
that could be winkled out of hiding by scientific study, and if so,
we presumably would be better off for knowing.
</P>
<P>
   Well, yes, I suppose, but what is to be made of all this by us
folks who are just trying to get safely through life without being
abducted either by space aliens or by university researchers?
</P>
<P>
   The study was conducted by members of the Society for Scientific
Exploration and was published in the society's Journal for
Scientific Exploration. This may seem a bit incestuous and
suspiciously helpful with peer review, but the involved scientists
carry impressive pedigrees and their society is based at Stanford
University, which is not famous for any institutional whimsy.
</P>
<P>
   Still, riff through the journal's past articles and you find
them busy with water witching, ESP, remote viewing and all the rest
such business. If the journal had a centerfold, you'd expect to
find Shirley MacLaine there, month after month.
</P>
<P>
   These excursions meet the academic sobriety test of dull writing
and la-de-da titles that are meant not to scare off respectable
folk and perhaps even, with luck, tease a grant or two out of
awestruck foundation boards: ``Society and Scientific Anomalies:
Common Knowledge About the Loch Ness Monster,'' is one.
</P>
<P>
   Another explores the ``psychokinetic action of young chicks.''
There was a time when I, too, given my keen scientific curiosity,
was interested in the psychokinetic action of young chicks, but for
some years now my wife has discouraged inquiry along those lines.
</P>
<P>
   Von Eshleman, an expert on the atmosphere of planets and a
co-chairman of the UFO review, was asked whether the report might
invite ridicule. He said, ``We may be opening a Pandora's box of
some kind, but I'm a professor emeritus. I don't care.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure what to make of that attitude scientifically, but
as I tumble toward my dotage like a satellite that has slipped
orbit, the comment seems wonderfully sane and even sage.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
