<HEADER>
A7446 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-PICNICS-COX     07-02 1316
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-PICNICS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cool picnic ideas for a blazing Fourth
 &HT;    By Kitty Crider
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ It's a hassle to organize your family and
friends, gather up all that food and navigate the traffic, all the
time knowing it's going to be hot as blazes until the sun goes
down.
</P>
<P>
   But it's worth it. That's why 65,000 to 70,000 locals annually
wind their way to the Auditorium Shores of Town Lake for the Austin
Symphony's Fourth of July celebration.
</P>
<P>
   It's a fun family/friends venue. It's red, white and fireworks.
Food and music, too.
</P>
<P>
   Peggy Gunn, whose family has celebrated the Fourth this way for
more than a decade, traditionally spreads her red and white quilt
over the grassy banks and serves a picnic for six to 12 people.
``I've got a sister from North Carolina coming this year, who is
bringing her 12-year-old daughter.'' Add to that her husband, two
grown daughters, and local friends bringing young children, who
always add magic to the evening, and the quilt fills up.
</P>
<P>
   Gunn likes it that way. The best relationships are built around
the dinner table or picnicking on quilts, says the Southern-born
hostess, who, while rearing her children, always kept a picnic
basket packed for impromptu family outings.
</P>
<P>
   Her Fourth of July menu varies each year, with the exception of
the mandatory deviled eggs. This year's spread will include
crudites with tzatziki, marinated beef tenderloin, artichoke-rice
salad and spirited watermelon. All cold. All dishes that can be
prepared ahead. In fact, the salads are better made at least two
days before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Gunn likes to cook and spread a menu of dishes with family
meaning, but other revelers opt for take-out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't ever prepare the food myself,'' says Jeani
Sandefer-Smith, who has been July Fourthpicnicking on Auditorium
Shores since 1976. ``I go to Whole Foods or Central Market and get
cool stuff.'' Melons, Greek salad, shrimp cocktail, tarragon
chicken salad, cold pastas, French bread and always some kind of
sinful individual desserts such as tortes loaded with cherries and
whipped cream.
</P>
<P>
   She packs everything in a large ice chest with wheels, attaching
other items to the cooler with a bungee cord so nothing has to be
carried. Arriving at the picnic site about 5:30 p.m. to get her
favorite spot, she puts down a canvas first, then a blanket,
staking the corners with small flags and making it easier for the
dozen or so family and friends to find the spot.
</P>
<P>
   If the summer keeps up its heat wave, there is no question that
it will be a hot time in the old town on July Fourth. But cannons
will boom, as the Symphony's new music director Peter Bay directs
Tchaikovsky's 1812 Overture. Rockets will flare, as fireworks have
their 15 minutes of fame in the Austin skies. And people will oooh
and aahhh.
</P>
<P>
   For Gunn, Sandefer-Smith and thousands of other picnickers, the
patriotic evening will be worth the effort.
</P>
<P>
   Peggy Gunn's Fourth of July fireworks picnic
</P>
<P>
   Crudites with Tzatziki
</P>
<P>
   2 cups low-fat yogurt, drained
</P>
<P>
   1 cucumber, seeded (but not peeled), grated and drained
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup finely chopped sweet onion
</P>
<P>
   4 cloves minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vinegar
</P>
<P>
   Pinch dried mint
</P>
<P>
   Assorted raw vegetables: red pepper strips, carrot sticks, onion
brushes, jicama slices, celery sticks, etc.
</P>
<P>
   Combine yogurt, cucumber, onion, garlic, oil and seasonings. Mix
well and chill overnight. Serve as a dip with the raw veggies. (The
tzatziki also is good on gyros, pitas or as a salad dressing.)
Makes 3 cups.
</P>
<P>
   Chilled Beef Tenderloin with Horseradish Sauce
</P>
<P>
   4-6 pounds beef tenderloin
</P>
<P>
   Marinade:
</P>
<P>
   2 cups dry red wine
</P>
<P>
   3 shallots, minced
</P>
<P>
   6 sprigs parsley
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons mixed fresh herbs (thyme, marjoram, rosemary,
basil), minced
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons salad oil
</P>
<P>
   Combine all marinade ingredients. Place tenderloin in a large
zippered plastic bag, add marinade and refrigerate 6 to 8 hours,
turning occasionally. Preheat broiler, remove meat from liquid, pat
dry. Broil tenderloin 4 inches from fire, turning and cooking until
desired doneness, about 20 minutes for rare. Chill. Slice and serve
with sauce of choice. Serves 12 -16.
</P>
<P>
   Horseradish Sauce
</P>
<P>
   About 2 ounces of grated prepared horseradish
</P>
<P>
   1 pint low-fat sour cream
</P>
<P>
   Combine the two ingredients and serve as a sauce. Makes 1 pint.
</P>
<P>
   Artichoke-Rice Salad
</P>
<P>
   2 8-ounce boxes chicken-flavored rice/vermicelli mixture
</P>
<P>
   2 6-ounce jars marinated artichoke hearts
</P>
<P>
   6-ounce bottle stuffed green olives
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch green onions, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup low-fat sour cream
</P>
<P>
   1/2 to 1 cup each of green peas, broccoli florets, water
chestnuts, thin carrot rounds
</P>
<P>
   2 to 3 tablespoons curry powder
</P>
<P>
   Parboil peas, broccoli, carrot rounds. Chill.
</P>
<P>
   Cook rice mixture according to box directions.
</P>
<P>
   Drain artichoke hearts and add curry powder to liquid. Stir
liquid into the combined mayonnaise and sour cream.
</P>
<P>
   Chop onions, olives and other vegetables into small pieces. Add
dressing to rice mixture while it's warm. Blend in other
ingredients and chill. Serve cold. Serves 8 to 10.
</P>
<P>
   Cold Szechuan Noodle Salad
</P>
<P>
   1 pound spaghetti or Chinese noodles
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds chicken breasts
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons peanut oil
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   1/4 to 1/2 cup spicy peanut satay sauce
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup mayonnaise or low-fat sour cream
</P>
<P>
   1 pound snow peas or sugar snap peas, blanched and julienned
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound baby corn, cut on diagonal
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound carrots, cut on diagonal, matchstick
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces jicama, julienned
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces bamboo shoots
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch green onions, chopped, including tops
</P>
<P>
   Simmer chicken breasts in water or stock until done. Remove
chicken from liquid, reserving liquid. Chill chicken and dice.
</P>
<P>
   Bring reserved liquid to a boil and cook spaghetti al dente.
Drain and toss with the peanut oil. Place in a zippered plastic bag
and add the soy sauce. Marinate, chilled, overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Mix peanut sauce with mayo or sour cream. Toss veggies, chicken,
noodles and sauce all together. Chill. Serves 12.
</P>
<P>
   Peanut sauce: Buy or make your own by combining 1/2 cup crunchy
peanut butter, 1/4 cup freshly squeezed lemon juice, 1 cup coconut
milk, 2 teaspoons brown sugar, 4 cloves garlic (minced) and 1/2
teaspoon hot chili oil.
</P>
<P>
   Spirited or Festive Watermelon
</P>
<P>
   1 large watermelon
</P>
<P>
   1 pint vodka or liqueur such as Midori or Casis (for an
adults-only gathering) OR 1 quart ginger ale (for a family outing)
</P>
<P>
   Cut a 4-inch plug out of the end of the melon and remove enough
flesh to pour in the liquid of choice. Remove the red flesh from
the plug, reseat plug in melon and refrigerate until ready to
serve. Slice melon as usual to serve or sip juice through straws
sunk into the melon through the rind. Serves 12 people.
</P>
<P>
   Picnic tips
</P>
<P>
   It's gonna be hot, so dress cool in cotton and hats (a must).
</P>
<P>
   Bring sunscreen
</P>
<P>
   For a refreshing touch: Have a clean, damp, chilled washcloth in
a plastic bag, labeled or a different color for each person, to pat
on faces or hands.
</P>
<P>
   Spread a quilt, blanket or throw of some kind to sit on. (If you
have a canvas, spread it first, then the quilt. Sometimes the
ground is damp from watering.)
</P>
<P>
   Bring plenty of water: plain, carbonated or flavored.
</P>
<P>
   Cook or pick up a picnic. But, because of the heat, choose a
cold menu.
</P>
<P>
   Consider a separate cooler for drinks so the one containing
perishable food won't be constantly opened.
</P>
<P>
   Take along a spare trash bag to police your area at evening's
end.
</P>
<P>
   Low chairs provide back support without blocking the view of
others.
</P>
<P>
   Kitty Crider is the food editor for the Austin
American-Statesman
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
