<DOCNO> NYT19980702.0072 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 10:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7447 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD04-COX     07-02 0573
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    As in life, plan ahead
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I have seen some curious things on rec.woodworking, the Internet
newsgroup for those involved in our craft. But the following query
is the strangest I've ever seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm making a simple coat rack with some cutoffs,'' a gentleman
wrote. ``It's the free-standing coat/hat rack kind. I've cut the
legs straight at 45 degree angles on each end. Now I have to attach
them to the post and am wondering what's the best way to do it.
I've thought of a few ways, but none seem that great.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any suggestions? I have a drill press, a router (no table), a
benchtop bandsaw and some hand tools.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a great lesson here, and it has nothing to do with how
to connect the legs of a coat rack to the stem. I can only suggest
that it's good this fellow didn't decide to build a boat instead of
a coat rack; he'd probably be asking how he's supposed to get it
out of his basement.
</P>
<P>
   Planning is a wonderful thing in most endeavors, and no less so
in woodworking and furniture making. One simply does not embark on
a project before deciding how everything is going to be done _ and
when. A project's dimensions, among other things, are predicated
upon the joinery.
</P>
<P>
   That's the first thing this fellow has failed to grasp. Another
thing is that for a woodworker of his inexperience, there is no
pretty simple coat rack. Oh, sure, it seems simple at first. After
all, it's just a long stick with some kind of base or legs, isn't
it? Cut a few pieces of wood and there you are.
</P>
<P>
   And indeed, there he is, with one long piece of wood and a few
short pieces and not much of an idea what to do with them.
</P>
<P>
   Now, I happen to have experience with coat racks. I built one
once, for my eldest daughter. Unfortunately it has been a long
time, and she and the coat rack are now in Buffalo, N.Y. I can't
remember the exact way I joined the legs to the upright. Vaguely I
recall it was a fairly fancy joint discovered in a book or
magazine, specific to the joining of coat rack legs.
</P>
<P>
   This fellow doesn't say how many legs he's planning on attaching
_ three or four _ but I suspect it's four. Judging from his list of
equipment, it's unreasonable to expect that he can prepare the
upright to receive three legs, although three would be the more
desirable configuration.
</P>
<P>
   Did someone ask why? Because the tripod is self-leveling. Four
legs may wobble on an uneven surface, but three are not likely to.
</P>
<P>
   On to the joinery. If his dimensions are critical, and one
assumes that since he has cut both ends of the legs to a 45-degree
angle that they are now at those dimensions, then there is only one
feasible method of joining them to the upright. That's with
splines, separately cut slices of wood about a quarter of an inch
thick to be glued into slots in both the leg and the upright.
</P>
<P>
   This may, in fact, be the best practical method he has. The best
way available to him at this point would be sliding dovetails, but
since he has no router table I wouldn't suggest it. Mortise and
tenon, the next best route, is almost as impractical with the
equipment at hand. Next week we'll look at the best way to do it
with the tools he's got.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: jwarner(at)ajc.com. We want to hear from you but are
unable to acknowledge every message.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
