<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 10:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7475 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOFTUS-COLUMN-$ADV09x     07-02 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOFTUS-COLUMN-$ADV09xx-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONNECTING: A MARRIAGE FOR ALL TO SEE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Thursday July 9)  
 By MARY J. LOFTUS   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was an ambitious experiment.
</P>
<P>
   The Hartford Courant chose one family _ culled from a hundred
who called the paper to volunteer after a request for a ``happily
married couple'' was posted _ to follow for several months in the
course of their daily lives.
</P>
<P>
   They selected Tom Kelly and Cynthia Wolcott, a New Britain
couple with four small children.
</P>
<P>
   Reporter Anne Farrow and photographer Michael McAndrews spent
about four months with the family, capturing the moments that
define a marriage: a stolen kiss on the couch, a tickle fight with
the boys, a dinnertime confrontation, a rare night out.
</P>
<P>
   The result was a six-day series that ran Feb. 8 to 13, and is
breathtaking in its celebration of the simple daily rituals that
families lovingly conduct behind closed doors, in parks, at bedtime
and mealtime.
</P>
<P>
   One of the early scenes begins in their cozy kitchen in October,
on Cynthia's 40th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cynthia and Tom, married for 16 years and lovers for two years
before that, are alone at the table with Thomson, their infant.
They have had a glass of red wine with their cake, and seem
contemplative, almost dreamy. It has been a hard year, and they do
not move from this quiet room with its falling light. Tom neatly
spoons beige, macerated fruit into Thomson, a genial, attentive
baby. He so often appears to be following conversations, it is hard
not to invent sentences he might voice, and both his parents do.''
</P>
<P>
   Farrow shows the reader everything.
</P>
<P>
   She reads Tom and Cynthia's mail, relives their courtship,
settles in during the baby's nap time to hear tales from their
shared history.
</P>
<P>
   With the chaos of caring for four children under 6 _ Coleman,
twins Sammie and Atticus and baby Thomson _ Tom and Cynthia
struggle to keep time for themselves and each other.
</P>
<P>
   They struggle to do it the right way: no TV as babysitter,
ragouts of autumn vegetables and homemade cranberry-pear bread for
dinner, paying attention to the other's moods and unspoken needs.
Tom, a salesman of doors, windows and other building supplies,
takes a French course in the evenings; Cynthia, a singer, works
part-time in a library. Their house is often filled with music,
from Tom's acoustic guitar to Etta James on the CD.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the countless, unceasing demands drain them.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few days earlier, Tom had come home in midafternoon to find
the usually napping Thomson wide awake and roaring, the twins in
Dutch because they had broken a cardinal rule of the household and
awakened the baby with their noisy play, and Cynthia sitting on the
floor of the foyer, weeping with exhaustion.''
</P>
<P>
   The text is sprinkled with poems about marriage, including this
one by farmer, doctor and poet Wendell Berry:
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes our life reminds me
</P>
<P>
   of a forest in which there is a graceful clearing
</P>
<P>
   and in that opening, a house, an orchard and a garden,
</P>
<P>
   comfortable shades and flowers, red and yellow in the sun,
</P>
<P>
   a pattern made in the light for the light to return to.
</P>
<P>
   The forest is mostly dark, its ways to be made anew day after
day,
</P>
<P>
   the dark richer than the light and more blessed
</P>
<P>
   provided we stay brave enough to keep on going in.''
</P>
<P>
   The series reads like a novel, rich in detail, intrigue, even
suspense. How can the portrait of a marriage _ not unlike most,
better than some _ be this complex, this touching, this inspiring?
</P>
<P>
   It is one of the first stories, retold with each person who
enters ``The Country of Marriage,'' as the series is titled.
</P>
<P>
   Near the end, Farrow asked the couple why they did it. Although
Tom admitted to knowing ``how the lions feel when the Range Rover
pulls up and the shutters start clicking,'' he saw chronicling a
successful marriage as an endeavor ``full of potential.''
</P>
<P>
   Are secrets revealed?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps only this, an excerpt from Tom and Cynthia's favorite
poem: ``I love you. I love this fool's walk. The thing we have to
learn is how to walk light.''
</P>
<P>
   (Mary J. Loftus is a feature writer for The Ledger in Lakeland,
Fla.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
