<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Thursday, July 2, 1998      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Friday. If you have questions, call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   NUCLEAR-SHIPMENTS (San Francisco) _ Highly secretive shipments
of deadly radioactive nuclear fuel rods are scheduled to begin
passing through the Bay Area this month, U.S. Department of Energy
officials confirm. By KEAY DAVIDSON.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-TURKEY (Albany, N.Y.) _ Neighborhood residents and the
U.S. Postal Service have agreed on a plan that allows an attack
turkey to continue residing in nearby woods. Homeowners agreed to
move their mailboxes to the curbside, thus enabling the postman to
deliver mail without getting out of his truck and risking a turkey
attack. By ELIZABETH BENJAMIN.
</P>
<P>
   GINGRICH-ALAMO (San Antonio) _ House Speaker Newt Gingrich,
former history professor, took a private tour of the Alamo. By
JAIME CASTILLO.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LOUNGE-SINGERS (Undated) _ This is an incredible book. Editor
Steve Knopper has put together the most readable and informative
reference book on pop singing in this century that you will ever
see. By EDVINS BEITIKS.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ANNE-KLEIN (San Francisco) _ Ever since Anne Klein's money men
got rid of Louis dell'Olio for not being relevant enough to the
so-called ``modern'' woman, the company has not fared too well. But
now, with two new designers, Ken Kaufman and Isaac Franco, Anne
Klein is back to square one. By CYNTHIA ROBINS.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BKN-PERKINS (Albany, N.Y.) _ If Sam Perkins' career with the
Seattle SuperSonics is over, the affable giant with the sleepy
expression will leave the National Basketball Association with only
one regret. He hasn't played on an NBA champion. By MARK SINGELAIS.
</P>
<P>
   BOX-TYSON (San Francisco) _ Mike Tyson served 38 months for
rape. He did his time, but the National Organization for Women
wants him banned from boxing indefinitely. Meanwhile, a federal
judge in Phoenix handed down a 46-month sentence against the man
who arranged a point-shaving scheme at Arizona State. By GWEN
KNAPP.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-LESSON (San Francisco) _ We have much to learn from China.
Unlike many government officials in America, their counterparts in
China recognize and acknowledge their problems and have a plan for
addressing them. By STEVE PHILLIPS.
</P>
