and bank at one bank.
</P>
<P>
   It is not on big things, like religious and historical loyalties
that we divide, but on simple choices in tastes and temperament and
whether our women wear jeweled sandals and our men white socks.
</P>
<P>
   Now we are into the summer travel season when it is important to
keep an open mind and remember that we are all emissaries of our
own state as well as guests in another's.
</P>
<P>
   If we can trade tofu for corn dogs and do it without prejudice,
we can show the world how regional peoples can get along.
</P>
<P>
   I helped pass on these differences to the next generation when a
branch of the Massachusetts family recently visited. They were two
California first timers, Laura and Chris.
</P>
<P>
   They attended a Giants game, a rodeo, shopped Haight Street
where the sixth-grader scored 10-inch heels that would make a drag
queen sigh and the eighth-grader a velvet beret that had people
nodding with respect.
</P>
<P>
   They decided they like California, they said, although they
think pizza with pesto sauce is weird and were horrified to
discover that some hot dogs are not made from beef. They split on
the rodeo (one would have been outside with the protesters) but
they both were awed by the giant redwoods.
</P>
<P>
   Out of all the souvenir shops and food stands, water rides and
oddnik people they were most impressed with the big trees. Long
after they lose the baseball cap with Orel Hershiser's autograph
and the incense burner, they will dream of trees tall as the sky,
old as the earth, of green light on ferns that look prehistoric.
</P>
<P>
   When someone starts to slam California for considering bicycle
shorts formal wear maybe they will defend us by saying, ``but the
trees out there were made by a wizard.''
</P>
<P>
   We all have to struggle with regional image. Joe, a newspaper
guy in Ohio, says people are always misinterpret-ing his state, and
the worst are the ones who've never been there. I say it's the same
here in wacky California where we all surf and have Baywatch
breasts.
</P>
<P>
   Some national politician called Ohio the roast beef state, which
people like Joe don't take as a compliment, knowing how some
outsiders scorn red meat and food that requires gravy. I agreed
with Joe it was a cheap shot. I went to college in Ohio and you
can't beat its hoagies. Besides, in October it smells better than
musk, like no other place.
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, while driving through North Carolina, my companion
and I stopped at a roadside market to buy lunch supplies. As he
tells the story, I insulted not only the store, but the town
at-large and probably the whole state by walking into the market
and remarking out loud, ``I wonder if you can get any decent cheese
in this place.'' If I ever run for public office this story will be
used to show I am really Leona Helmsley and not of the common folk
like I pretend to be.
</P>
<P>
   The other night this story of the woman who offended Appalachia
was repeated to our young visitors after they gamely sampled the
guacamole, thereby demonstrating that snootiness does not run in
the family. It's just a California thing.
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Swartz is a columnist for The Press Democrat in Santa
Rosa, Calif. Her e-mail address is sfswartzpressdemo.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
