<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 11:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7493 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-HISTBX_7-03     07-02 0677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-HISTBX_7-03 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    HONG KONG GROWS FROM EMPTY ROCK TO INTERNATIONAL FINANCE CENTER
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With CHINA-CLINTON-MAIN 
 &HT;    By MARCIA KUNSTEL and JOSEPH ALBRIGHT 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service (at)
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ From a sparsely-settled rock in the sea to China's
beacon of capitalism, here is Hong Kong's history:
</P>
<P>
   1840-1842 - Opium Spoils. British determination to continue
illegal importation of opium into China leads to the Opium War that
China loses. The Treaty of Nanjing cedes undeveloped Hong Kong
island -- population 6,000 -- to the British.
</P>
<P>
   1843 - New Colony. Hong Kong is proclaimed a British colony and
Sir Henry Pottinger is appointed its first governor.
</P>
<P>
   1859-1860 - Second Opium War. Another bout of hostilities,
spurred by Chinese making a supposedly illegal search for opium on
a British ship, results in Britain taking over the Kowloon
Peninsula across from Hong Kong, under terms of the Beijing
Convention.
</P>
<P>
   July, 1898 - Britain Expands. Britain doubles its Hong Kong area
presence in a negotiated 99-year lease for the New Territories, the
largely empty land extending north from Kowloon. Britain also takes
over 235 islands.
</P>
<P>
   1931-39 - Population Billows. Refugees fleeing Japanese invasion
of mainland China crowd into Hong Kong, where the 1931 population
of 875,000 nearly doubles to about 1.6 million by 1939.
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 8, 1941 - Japanese Invade. The same day Japan invades the
United States at Pearl Harbor, it also launches a successful attack
on Hong Kong. After a week of bitter resistance the colony
surrenders. British are interned and many Chinese deported.
</P>
<P>
   1945 - Japanese Depart. Japan loses the war and Hong Kong goes
back to British control.
</P>
<P>
   1948-49 - Flight From Communism. Civil war on the mainland
drives thousands of refugees fearing communist victory over to Hong
Kong. The ultimate success of Mao Tse-tung's forces sends
additional huge waves of anti-communist Chinese from the new
People's Republic of China to the British colony. In 1950 the
population reaches 2.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   1967 - Revolt Blunted. The mainland's Cultural Revolution brings
Red Guards and street riots to Hong Kong, but British soon clamp
down with tough new restrictions on civil liberties.
</P>
<P>
   1972 - China Restakes Claim. Confidence bolstered by joining the
United Nations and re-engaging with America, China begins efforts
to get back prospering Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   1982 - British Rethink. Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher visits
Beijing and explores the role Britain should take when its 99-year
lease expires in 1997 on the New Territories, the bulk of the Hong
Kong colony that is becoming Asia's financial powerhouse.
</P>
<P>
   December 19, 1984 - Return Agreed. Negotiations finally produce
the Sino-British Joint Declaration that requires Britain to hand
back the colony of Hong Kong in 1997, while China pledges to permit
civil rights, capitalism and autonomy in everything except defense
and foreign affairs for 50 years. Chinese proclaim this ``one
country, two systems'' pattern can be followed with Macao and
Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   June, 1989 - Tiananmen Fears. Thousands of Hong Kong Chinese
travel to Beijing to take part in the Tiananmen Square democracy
movement. When tanks crush the student and labor movement, a
million people fearing their future under China come out to protest
in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 18, 1995 - In the first and last democratic elections
under British rule, democratic candidates sweep the vote for new
legislature. China vows it will dissolve the body.
</P>
<P>
   December, 1996 - Beijing chooses Hong Kong shipping magnate Tung
Chee-hwa to be the first chief executive of what will be called the
Hong Kong Special Administrative Region.
</P>
<P>
   July 1, 1997 - Just after midnight, Hong Kong returns to Chinese
rule in handover ceremonies, and within hours troops of China's
People's Liberation Army march into the colony to show who's boss
now.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
