<HEADLINE>
AFFABLE SUPERSONIC, 37, AWAITS SHOT AT NBA CHAMPIONSHIPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK SINGELAIS  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ If Sam Perkins' basketball career is over, the
affable giant with the sleepy expression will leave the National
Basketball Association with only one regret. He hasn't played on an
NBA champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the only thing that's keeping me around,'' Perkins said
this week during a high school basketball camp here. ``I've been
close a couple of times. That's the only thing I've wanted _ to
have a ring. If we had won it last year or the year before, I might
have quit a little earlier.''
</P>
<P>
   Perkins just completed the 14th season of his NBA career, the
last five with the Seattle SuperSonics.
</P>
<P>
   The forward's future is uncertain because his Seattle contract
expired after this season, making Perkins a free agent. Perkins,
37, doesn't know if he fits into the Sonics plans because the
franchise changed coaches after this past season.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Westphal replaced George Karl, whom Seattle decided not to
re-sign. The Sonics already have decided not to pick up the
one-year contract option on Perkins' teammate Dale Ellis, who is
also 37.
</P>
<P>
   ``I met (Westphal) on Sunday, but he didn't tell me anything
sound,'' Perkins said. ``We didn't talk about all the little
intangibles.''
</P>
<P>
   Further complicating matters is the NBA lockout that began
Tuesday. League owners want to negotiate a new collective
bargaining agreement with the players. While the lockout is in
effect, Perkins and other free agents are forbidden to negotiate
with any club.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm just going to wait and assess everything until the
lockout is lifted,'' Perkins said, adding that he thinks it will
end in September. He doesn't believe predictions that the work
stoppage will last into next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's (NBA Commissioner) David Stern's way of letting guys
know that they'd better hurry up and make a decision,'' Perkins
said. ``There's a lot at stake, with players who have to pay their
mortgages and feed their families. But I don't think (the lockout)
will last that long. If it does, I'll be surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   Perkins, who is 6-feet-9-inches tall and 260 pounds, indicated
that he would like to return to the NBA next season. However, he
said he would not be satisfied with being a benchwarmer, no matter
what team he's on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've thought about (retiring), too,'' Perkins said. ``I don't
think I will, but if I don't go somewhere that I really like, or if
I don't have a choice, then I probably will go ahead and retire.''
</P>
<P>
   This season, Perkins had the lowest scoring average (7.2) and
the lowest rebounding average (3.1) of his career. As he's gotten
older, he has become more apt to linger behind the 3-point line,
shooting jumpers. He made 87 3-pointers last season, almost as many
as he made inside the 3-point arc (109).
</P>
<P>
   Perkins said he wasn't sure if he would accept the league
minimum, which right now is $272,500 per year, in order to keep
playing.
</P>
<P>
   He said he felt badly about the departure of George Karl, adding
that it was a clash of personalities with management that led to
Karl's ouster.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the things Coach Karl does, he does it like a regular,
normal guy. A beer guy,'' Perkins said. ``Corporate doesn't do
that. That was probably the bottom line.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Perkins visited the basketball camps that he owns.
He said he's always taken pride in doing the little things that
some other players don't like to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the story of my life,'' he said. ``I don't try to be
the big star or ask for a lot of attention. I just try to stay
within my limitations.''
</P>
</TEXT>
