<SLUG> BC-CHINA-EXILES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINESE EXILES SEE POSITIVE EFFECTS IN CLINTON VISIT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES A. RADIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chinese exiles and expatriates, whose fortunes rise and fall
with the whims of the Communist Party leadership, are nearly as
pleased as members of the presidential entourage with Bill
Clinton's China trip.
</P>
<P>
   But, they say, it is too soon to conclude that the trip bodes
any deep or lasting change in Chinese domestic politics or in the
US-China relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Chinese President Jiang Zemin both surpassed exiles'
expectations for the American president's visit to China's capital
_ Clinton with his remarks on human rights, democracy, and the
Tiananmen massacre of 1989 and Jiang with his statement on Tibet
and, especially, his decision to engage Clinton on live television.
</P>
<P>
   However, expectations were low to begin with. Exiles and others
who followed the events closely point out that both political
leaders had much to gain and little to lose.
</P>
<P>
   ``They scratched each other's back,'' said Shen Tong, a veteran
of 1989 democracy demonstrations on Tiananmen Square. China-US
relations went into a deep chill, and Jiang rose to power, amid the
bloody repression of those protests by the Chinese army. ``Jiang
... gave Clinton big face, and Clinton returned the favor.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's appearance at Tiananmen Square, his saluting the army
there, his tact, and restraint in expressing his differences with
the Chinese leadership are seen by many exiles as pluses for Jiang
in China's domestic politics.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang's allowing Clinton to communicate directly with the
Chinese masses via television, his explicit denial of any Chinese
efforts to influence American elections, and his statements on
Tibet are seen as pluses for Clinton in the US political arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``Still,'' Shen said, ``I was moved and excited by the whole
thing.'' The widespread sentiment among exiles and expatriates is
that, whatever narrow political agendas may be served, there is
little to criticize about the China trip.
</P>
<P>
   Chai Ling, a top leader of the 1989 demonstrations who has been
living in Boston for five years, said the live television exchange
between the leaders could have occurred only after a debate among
the chiefs of the Chinese Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``The voice of reform succeeded in convincing the rest to let it
proceed,'' Chai said. ``That means very good things about
progressive thinking within the party. This sort of open public
exchange is what'' we ``were requesting nine years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Lobsang Sangay, a Tibetan activist, said he was surprised by the
prominence accorded Tibet by Clinton, and even more surprised by
Jiang's statements about the central Asian country, which was
conquered by China nearly a half-century ago.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang referred to Tibet before the Chinese takeover as a
theocracy. (The usual Chinese characterization is that it was a
``feudal society.'') He refrained from the usual Chinese charge
that the Dalai Lama, Tibet's spiritual leader, is plotting to split
China. Perhaps most significantly, he demanded only that the Dalai
Lama recognize that Tibet is now an inalienable part of China,
dropping the insistence that it always has been.
</P>
<P>
   ``These were dramatic differences,'' indicating that the level
of hostility has lowered and resolution is more possible, Sangay
said. The Dalai Lama, he said, is willing to forgo struggling for
an independent Tibet now, but has long rejected China's attempts to
repress Tibet's history of independence.
</P>
<P>
   Sangay praised Clinton for referring to the Dalai Lama, during
the live television appearance, as an honest person who is
considered a holy man by many in the West who do not share his
Buddhist faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will have some impact, a jolt among the Chinese people,''
Sangay said, because Chinese leaders and media typically refer to
the Dalai Lama as ``a fraud, a liar, a cheat.''
</P>
<P>
   Chinese exile Yang Jianli, a doctoral candidate at Harvard's
Kennedy School of Government, said the trip has demonstrated
dramatically the effectiveness of democracy in America, and of
pressure in China.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the beginning'' stages of preparation for the trip, Yang
said, ``I think Clinton would not have said these things. He was
just ... saying that going to Tiananmen Square was a usual thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``But before he went,'' he continued, ``there was tremendous
pressure from Congress, the American people, and the dissidents in
China. Democracy really works in the United States. The most
important lesson is that pressure really pays off in China. All the
progress in China has been achieved with pressure, not with
appeasement.''
</P>
<P>
   Many observers share the view of Zhang Nongji, bibliographer of
East Asian legal studies at Harvard Law School, that ``the fact
that there was a live broadcast is very significant, perhaps even
more significant than the content.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The government should not be afraid of open discussions and
debates,'' said Zhang, who sympathizes with democracy activists but
is neither an exile nor a dissident. ``This was a good experience
for them. It is quite a new thing for the Chinese government. It
shows them that policies can be discussed in front of the people
and nothing will happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of this, she said, Clinton's visit ``will bring some
political and economic outcomes, but the psychological and
ideological influence will last longer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
