<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-SUPPORT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPATRIATE KOSOVO ALBANIANS PUT MONEY ON WAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELIZABETH NEUFFER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ As fighting intensifies in Kosovo, ethnic Albanians
from the Serbian province who live in Europe are preparing for war
by sending their savings home to aid the Kosovo Liberation Army,
the rebels fighting for independence against Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo Albanians in Germany and Switzerland, where most live in
exile, are abandoning hope for a peaceful settlement. Instead, they
getting ready to ``defend their fatherland.'' In recent months,
scores have quit Europe to return home and join the Kosovo
Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peaceful means don't work anymore. That's why I went home to
fight,'' Samed Syli, 19, said at a Red Cross counseling session in
Berlin. ``I came back only because my brothers thought one of us
should stay alive.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many who have gone to Kosovo to fight,'' said Bujar
Bukoshi, the Kosovo leader who describes himself as the prime
minister in exile, and who now lives in Bonn. ``It's a phenomenon
which is getting bigger every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Germany's Kosovo Albanians in particular are contributing large
sums to help the outgunned Kosovo Liberation Army to wage war
against the Serbs. Serbia and Montenegro are the remaining
republics of the Yugoslav Federation.
</P>
<P>
   In the past month, the amount sent from Germany to the group has
shot up from about $5,600 early in June to almost $170,000 later,
said Ibrahim Kelmendi, the director of the ``Fatherland is
Calling'' fund. These numbers could not be verified.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've saved up a lot of money, and now they are spending
their savings,'' Kelmendi said by telephone from his headquarters
near Bonn, where he runs a group called the Democratic Association
of Albanians in Germany. ``People don't see any way other than
supporting'' the Kosovo Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   Kelmendi said the money raised goes directly to the movement,
which he said ``uses it, and I guess they use it to buy weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   But neither Kelmendi's fund nor his open support for the Kosovo
Liberation Army necessarily reflects the position of Kosovo
Albanian leaders, who seat a ``government in exile'' in Germany and
Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   Scores of other funds are managed by the exiles, headed by
Bukoshi, who was elected in 1992 in a vote that Belgrade refused to
recognize. One need only open the Kosovo Albanian language daily
Rilindja, published in Frankfurt and Zurich, to see a long list of
bank accounts from Denmark to Slovenia to which people can
contribute money.
</P>
<P>
   There is a large refugee and immigrant community, with resources
to tap. Since Milosevic stripped Kosovo of its autonomy in 1991,
more than 650,000 Kosovo Albanians have fled the province. Human
rights groups charge that the Kosovo Albanians, who make up 90
percent of the province, have been brutally repressed by the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   About 140,000 Kosovo Albanians have come to Germany seeking
asylum. In all, they say, there are 400,000 in the country. Again,
there is no way to confirm their figures. The Verfassunschutz, the
German intelligence agency that monitors foreign extremist groups
in Berlin, including the Kosovo Albanian community, estimates there
are closer to 100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Bukoshi, who joined Rugova for recent talks with
President Clinton in Washington, will not say if the money he is
raising goes to the Kosovo Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   ``My government is raising money to help Kosovo with all
means,'' he said. ``As to the other, I have no comment.'' According
to Kelmendi, the government-in-exile has raised $112 million.
</P>
<P>
   Most Kosovo Albanians believe that their contributions are going
to the rebels, regardless of which fund to which they contribute.
``I'm sure 100 percent of my money is going'' to the Kosovo
Liberation Army, said Besim Hajdim, a 38-year-old art teacher who
gives $280 a month to a fund based in Switzerland. ``I hope they
use it for weapons. They don't have enough.''
</P>
<P>
   The growing radicalization of Kosovo Albanians here comes while
European countries struggle to decide if the Kosovo Liberation Army
should participate in any negotiations for peace in the province.
Wednesday, Germany was among the first to support the United
States, which has called on diplomats from the six nations
concerned with the Balkans called the Contact Group to negotiate
with Kosovo Liberation Army rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Amid fear that the situation in Kosovo is spiraling out of
control, Germany, France, Britain, the United States, Italy, and
Russia will meet next week in Bonn to discuss the crisis. But these
countries remain divided over what to do.
</P>
<P>
   The Kosovo Liberation Army, dismissed just weeks ago as a band
of disorganized rebels, has seized nearly one-third of Kosovo _
less by military might than by knowledge of the terrain. Its ranks
are increasing with each crackdown by Serbian security forces. But
the group still appears to have no clear leader or defined chain of
command. This makes negotiations with it difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Contact Group nations fear that to recognize the
Kosovo Liberation Army will undermine peace efforts by a moderate
Kosovo Albanian leader, Ibrahim Rugova. Others, like Turkey,
concerned with its own Kurdish separatists, worry that recognition
would set a precedent and embolden other splinter movements.
</P>
<P>
   There remains the thorny question of how to reconcile the
rebels' aims for independence with European and US support for
Kosovo autonomy instead.
</P>
<P>
   Military options to halt the brutal security crackdowns by
troops and special police forces launched by Yugoslav leader
Slobodan Milosevic against the Kosovo Liberation Army have been
drawn up by NATO. They range from the deployment of troops along
key borders to air strikes against selected targets.
</P>
<P>
   But until Western leaders agree on a political strategy for
Kosovo _ and a role in it for the Kosovo Liberation Army _ NATO can
do little. ``The problem isn't on the military side. It's on the
political side,'' a NATO diplomat said in Brussels. ``Are we
dealing with the UCK or not?'' UCK are the Kosovo Albanian initials
for the Kosovo Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   All agree that tensions in Kosovo are heightening. Clashes that
had been limited to the Kosovo Liberation Army and Serbian police
now include civilians on both sides. The Kosovo partisans are
``getting arms to a lot of different villages,'' one Western
diplomat said. ``And there is some indication in the past couple of
days that Serbian civilians have brand new weapons. Overall, the
situation is getting worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Fighting broke out earlier this year when Milosevic launched a
brutal police assault against the Kosovo Liberation Army. Two major
Serb security sweeps thus far have caused deaths on both sides,
escalated the conflict and wrecked peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Bukoshi says he is under increasing pressure from his own
community to send them to fight in Kosovo. ``We see the commitment
of people to defend Kosovo, but we are not organizing such
actions,'' said Bukoshi, who says that he is waiting to hear from
the government in Pristina, Kosovo's capital, about such plans.
</P>
<P>
   But others are sounding the alarm. ``We've been called to fight,
by the radio, by the newspapers,'' said Syli, at the Red Cross
center. ``Every volunteer should come to fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, inside the Kosovo Albanian language newspaper Bota Sot
(The World Today) is a notice for a June 30th meeting in the German
town of Hannover. In addition to discussion about the ``current
situation in the Fatherland,'' the ad says that ``the Board of
Associations is calling on all branches in the West to be in
position of readiness to defend the fatherland.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside the Kosovo Albanian Club in the Neukoeln section of
Berlin hangs a massive red banner with a double-faced black eagle,
the flag of Kosovo. While men play chess or table soccer, others
gather to discuss the fighting back home.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all ten people interviewed said they donate between $50
and $170 a month to Kosovo, convinced that the money will be used
either to help refugees or purchase weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were hoping for the democratic way of Rugova, but it proved
impossible,'' said Rexer Hoti, 31, a bricklayer from Drenica, a
region in Kosovo where much of the fighting has taken place. ``Now
we have the UCK.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-98 1254EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
