<DOCNO> NYT19980702.0090 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 12:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7622 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-02 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILDLIFE'S RIGHT TO PRIVACY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Our new neighbors are driving me crazy. They're the noisiest
family I've ever seen in my life. The kids holler at the top of
their lungs from morning to night, but they don't speak English and
I can't make out whether they're calling for their mother or
raising a ruckus because they're hungry. Their parents, who aren't
there nine-tenths of the time, show up every once in a while and
try to shut them up, to no avail.
</P>
<P>
   The adults haven't even introduced themselves. In fact, if they
see me coming, they head the other way. It's perfectly clear to me
they're avoiding me, though I pride myself on being a fairly
tolerant neighbor. Their racket carries right into our open bedroom
windows and there's no way I can ignore their constant carryings
on. Anyone with less patience would have called the authorities
long before this. Sometimes when the adults are away, I walk over
to their house, but short of breaking in and doing something about
those kids myself, there's nothing I can do.
</P>
<P>
   I can only hope that when the babies learn to fly, the whole
family of sparrows will abandon their nest in the eaves outside our
bedroom door and peace will reign in this house again.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, I'm hooked. I peek out from behind the screen
door in our bedroom and watch mom and dad make 90-second pit stops.
I brought my grandchildren out onto the small porch on the second
floor and we stood entranced, listening to the incessant chirping.
I pulled a chair over and let them climb up so that the nest was at
their eye level, but the straw was piled so high in front (to keep
the baby sparrows from falling out, I suppose) that none of us
could see a thing.
</P>
<P>
   I learned as a kid that you must never touch a baby bird because
the mother may then abandon it. Still, the other day my curiosity
got the best of me and I gently poked at the straw with a long
stick. To my surprise it's solid as brick, spun together with a
miraculous super glue made out of sparrow spit. There was no easy
way to push it aside. I really wanted to peek at those babies, but
I restrained myself and went back inside.
</P>
<P>
   They say curiosity killed the cat, but I suspect it's killed
mice and birds and the moles the cat dragged home in far greater
numbers. Human curiosity kills too. Just think of all the shells
with living creatures inside that we haul back from the beach.
</P>
<P>
   I witnessed a more disturbing example.
</P>
<P>
   My husband and I took our kids, then 8 and 10, to visit a farm
in Vermont. We were peering into a rabbit hutch when a family with
a whiny 6-year-old arrived. The child pleaded to hold the rabbit so
the dad hauled one of the bunnies out of the hutch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't let your daughter hold it,'' I said, stepping forward.
``Rabbits have sharp nails and powerful back feet. She'll only drop
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The man ignored me and placed the rabbit in his daughter's arms.
One wriggle and the rabbit was on the ground, hopping away into the
tall grass. A dog suddenly appeared out of nowhere and with one
bite, pierced the rabbit's lungs. Our family stood there, stunned,
as the parents quickly herded the girl back into the car so that
their offspring _ unlike ours _ wouldn't be marked for life by the
sight of an animal's death throes. We had to go to the people in
charge and report the demise of their pet.
</P>
<P>
   Here's another story that is almost too awful to believe. Long
after elephant seals were thought to be extinct, a naturalist came
upon a half-dozen of them swimming in some distant cove. Thrilled
with this startling discovery, he killed them all, (he thought),
and brought them back to ``civilization,'' as proof, I suppose, to
be studied, stuffed, and displayed in a museum.
</P>
<P>
   All the little girl wanted was to interact with a small bundle
of fur. The scientist was probably dreaming of educating the
population at large. I'm sure stories like these are the rule
rather than the exception, with man being the proverbial bull in
nature's china shop, but it isn't only out of greed, or
selfishness, or ignorance, that we destroy the living creatures
around us. Ironically, curiosity mixed with affection often has the
same disastrous effect.
</P>
<P>
   I remind myself of that when I'm tempted to intrude upon our
sparrows' lives. I have to accept that my grandkids won't be able
to observe those little open beaks, or count how many sparrows are
chirping their hearts out. I hope, though, that by giving up a
direct encounter with our feathered neighbors, they'll learn a far
more valuable lesson.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes caring about the natural world means letting Mother
Nature care for her own.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
