<HEADLINE>
HANCOCK REPLACES FUND CHIEF DICARLO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY AND STEVEN SYRE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Michael DiCarlo, one of Boston's brightest investment stars of
the early 1990s, was replaced as the manager of his flagship John
Hancock Special Equities mutual fund yesterday after two years of
poor performance.
</P>
<P>
   DiCarlo, who has managed the $1.5 billion fund for 10 years, is
known for investing aggressively in small stocks with big
expectations for growth. He stuck with that ``momentum'' style even
though it fell dramatically out of stock market fashion in recent
years and his fund dropped far behind the pack.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock Special Equities, which gained an astounding 84.49
percent in 1991 and 50.44 percent in 1995, has returned a total of
1 percent in the two years ended June 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``I totally accept it and totally understand their decision,''
said DiCarlo. ``The group of stocks come in and go out of favor.
There's nothing I can do about that.''
</P>
<P>
   DiCarlo left John Hancock in 1996, perhaps at the height of his
popularity, to form a new firm to operate a hedge fund, DFS
Advisors. But he signed a contract to remain an independent manager
of his old Hancock fund for five years.
</P>
<P>
   Though DiCarlo and Hancock said they reached a mutual decision
on the change Wednesday, performance benchmarks in their agreements
gave the company the ability to switch managers. Hancock could make
a change if the fund underperformed the growth stock component of
the Russell 2000 index for a two-year period. The contract DiCarlo
signed with Hancock when he left the company reached its two-year
anniversary on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Special Equities fund lost 6.81 percent annually over a
two-year period ended May 31, and ranked in the worst 2 percent of
funds in its category, according to Lipper Analytical Services Inc.
The Russell 2000 Growth benchmark earned 4.69 percent annually
during the same period.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel badly because I've managed the fund for 10 years,''
said DiCarlo. ``But these things happen, I see it happen all the
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Management of the Special Equities fund was turned over to Laura
J. Allen, who worked at Wellington Management Co. for 17 years
before joining Hancock in March.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock officials said they were disappointed to replace DiCarlo
but believed performance of Special Equities in recent years
demanded a change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have relatives who are in the fund and I get beat up by
them,'' said Edward Boudreau, chief executive of John Hancock
Funds. ``The performance was disappointing.''
</P>
<P>
   DiCarlo was by far the biggest draw for Hancock funds for years.
His Special Equities fund was temporarily closed twice, in 1993 and
1994, because money flooded in faster than he could put it to work
in small stocks.
</P>
<P>
   His performance soared or muddled along on the performance of
go-go stocks like America Online Inc., which remains the
portfolio's biggest investment today.
</P>
<P>
   Special Equities, which invested nearly $2.2 billion at its
peak, has been slowly shrinking through shareholder redemptions for
most of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   DiCarlo said he would focus his attention exclusively on his
hedge fund _ a private vehicle for wealthy investors. He declined
to say how the hedge has performed in the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
More on Hancock
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR;  Not long ago we wrote about our ``Boston Plan,'' an idea to put
together two or three of the city's big financial players into a
behemoth that could survive in a world where only the biggest need
apply.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, the American Banker reported that John Hancock Mutual
Life Insurance Co. had held informal merger talks with BankBoston
Corp. and Fleet Financial Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper, citing unnamed sources, said the Boston insurer
was eyeing a deal around the time of its demutualization and
initial public offering, expected late next year.
</P>
<P>
   The story is baloney, Hancock said flatly Wednesday. ``The
company is not for sale and there are no merger talks. There is no
truth to it at all,'' said Hancock's president, David D'Alessandro.
``We are going through a demutualization. Period.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Fleet and BankBoston declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
The Red Herring
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR; John O'Connor, managing partner for the Boston operations of
Coopers &AMP; Lybrand since 1996, has been appointed office managing
partner for the merged PricewaterhouseCoopers.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor was also named US Northeast region leader for the
firm's Assured and Business Advisory Services. The new firm was
created by the merger between Coopers and Price Waterhouse
announced last September. The Boston office of the combined firms
will have more than 2,400 employees, including 190 partners.
</P>
<P>
   Boston Capital to John O'Connor: Can you do something about that
awful name?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Steve Bailey and Steven Syre can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
