<SLUG> BC-CHINA-LESSON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICA CAN LEARN IMPORTANT LESSONS FROM CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEVE PHILLIPS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Fresh from his tour of China, President Clinton
can return home with valuable lessons that could improve the
quality of life for families in America.
</P>
<P>
   We have much to learn from China. Unlike many government
officials in America, their counterparts in China recognize and
acknowledge their problems and have a plan for addressing them.
</P>
<P>
   There is a palpable national commitment to, and momentum toward,
transforming the educational system. This is manifest in the pride
and enthusiasm of the students, the diligence and dedication of the
teachers and the creativity and flexibility of school
administrators.
</P>
<P>
   I spent two weeks in China in April as a part of a delegation
sponsored by the San Francisco-based United States-China
Educational Institute. It coordinates exchanges between health and
education officials in the respective countries as a way of
improving public policies for families and promoting international
understanding and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   I am aware that all is not perfect in China, and that I only saw
a portion of the full picture. It is very hard, however, to
fabricate intelligence, commitment and curiosity. I can say with
complete conviction that there is genuine enthusiasm and innovation
occurring at the local level in China.
</P>
<P>
   Too often, government bureaucracy results in safe thinking and
cautious thinking. I was startled by the incredible intellectual
dynamism and genuine curiosity of what, in this country, would be
middle-level bureaucrats.
</P>
<P>
   As one elementary school principal told me, ``We don't care
where the ideas come from. We just want to do what works.''
</P>
<P>
   As someone who has to constantly fight for government resources
for politically powerless children, I was astounded to witness the
level of public investment in programs and facilities for them.
</P>
<P>
   The Children's Palace in Shanghai is a newly constructed,
state-of-the-art building that provides a wide range of cultural
and artistic classes.
</P>
<P>
   Neighborhoods have after-school Juvenile Science and Technology
Centers where students conduct science experiments and explore
applications of technology.
</P>
<P>
   There is an air of innovation in the realm of education. The
Sichuan Normal University faculty members coordinate research with
the public schools so that the solutions they explore will be
useful.
</P>
<P>
   Each year, the faculty produces more than 400 research papers
examining problems in education. Given the common challenges of
youth development, our nation would be enriched by learning from
their research _ and they by sharing ours.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton should establish the relationships and build the bridges
that can connect the most innovative thinkers in China with
policy-makers in America.
</P>
<P>
   Here in the San Francisco school district, we will be trying to
improve the quality of education by working with the United
States-China Educational Institute to develop partnerships and
exchanges between educators in San Francisco and China.
</P>
<P>
   While China has its problems, so do we, and we should exercise
restraint in issuing condemnations lest we appear inconsistent, or,
even hypocritical.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond all the acrimony about China becoming the next ``enemy''
is the fact that the Chinese are one-fourth of humanity with whom
we share a very real bond.
</P>
<P>
   When I hear of the threat the Chinese pose to national security,
I can't help remembering that the worst terrorist bomb this country
has ever suffered was from within, at the hands of an American in
Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   In protecting ourselves and in moving forward, the most
important steps we can take are toward building trust, partnership
and collaboration.
</P>
<P>
   I hope that Clinton's visit will determine not only what we can
control but also what we have to learn.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Steve Phillips is a member of the San Francisco Board of
Education.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
