<SLUG> BC-BOX-TYSON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN SHOULD LET THE SPORTS WORLD DEAL WITH TYSON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GWEN KNAPP  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The score is 46-38, in case anyone is counting.
The National Organization for Women should be, but it doesn't know
how to play the game.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Tyson served 38 months for rape. He did his time, but NOW
wants him banned from boxing indefinitely. Next week will be the
one-year anniversary of the date he had his license to do business
in the ring revoked for nibbling on Evander Holyfield's ear. Tyson
can apply for reinstatement then, and NOW plans to protest his
attempts.
</P>
<P>
   The group should take its signs and shoe leather elsewhere, to
Phoenix, where a federal judge handed down a 46-month sentence
against the man who arranged a point-shaving scheme at Arizona
State. The judge, Robert Broomfield, called sports part of the
``fabric of this country'' when he gave Benny Silman four months
more prison time than the prosecutors had requested.
</P>
<P>
   Interfere with the final score of a basketball game. Get 46
months, federal time, which means little chance for parole. Rape a
woman. Go free eight months sooner.
</P>
<P>
   There's no point anymore in debating whether Tyson should have
spent more time behind bars. There's even less point in trying to
keep him out of the ring. Boxing rejected him only because he
violated its fraternal canons. If his ban is extended, it will be
out of respect for the Marquess of Queensberry, not a woman's right
to say no.
</P>
<P>
   And that's the way it should be. The last thing we need is the
Nevada Gaming Commission passing judgment on anything of real
importance.
</P>
<P>
   That job really belongs to Broomfield, who seems dangerously
preoccupied with the trivial. If he truly understood the value of
sports, he would have kicked the case out of court.
</P>
<P>
   The criminal charges misdirect public outrage, turning athletic
effort into a measure of citizenship. Let the National Collegiate
Athletic Association sue Silman for undermining its product. Let
Arizona State demand its scholarship money back from the two
players who confessed to shaving points. But leave the feds out of
it.
</P>
<P>
   These cases squander taxpayer money and, ultimately, protect
only the sanctity of gambling _ the Justice Department keeping the
collegians in line for the Vegas oddsmakers.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, everything gets warped. An athlete commits a rape or
beats up his girlfriend, and he thinks a .300 batting average
offers redemption. That's why NOW goes after Tyson. His boxing fame
survived his prison term, remained part of the ``fabric of this
country'' and netted him a fortune.
</P>
<P>
   But the women's groups should leave him alone. The people who
pay Tyson, who make money off of him, the people who watch him _
they're not going to listen to NOW. They've already made up their
minds, and they care a lot more about Iron Mike than Citizen Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   He finally offended them last year by messing with the sport.
That's when they started calling him a savage. For years, they paid
him to bash men's skulls. Then they turned on him for chewing on a
bit of cartilage and prematurely terminating their $59.95
pay-per-view show.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, the best thing NOW could do is petition the gaming
commission to return his license. As long as he's fighting, Tyson
will be subject to constant scrutiny. The ring is the only place
where blinkered sports fans will ever hold him accountable.
</P>
<P>
   It's possible, too, that he can never be a great boxer again,
that sports won't reward self-destructive people for very long. His
ear-bite was an admission that he couldn't beat Holyfield fairly.
If he comes back to the ring, Tyson will have to show that he can
still fight or that he can go down with some dignity.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, he will probably have to call on the resources of a
mature adult. In obscurity, he's less likely to have that sort of
reckoning.
</P>
<P>
   In football, Lawrence Phillips is in a similar spot. He beat up
his ex-girlfriend in college, scaling a three-story apartment
building at 5 in the morning to reach her. He knew that if he hurt
her, he could be kicked off the Nebraska team, but he did it
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Purist football fans argued that this incident shouldn't
interrupt his career. They forgot how tough the game really is. In
the National Football League, Phillips continued to get into legal
trouble, and he couldn't gain much yardage, either. That happens to
athletes who can't keep their eye on the ball.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Phillips was accused of hitting a woman who refused
to dance with him in a bar. If it turns out that he is guilty, the
Miami Dolphins might give up on him. NOW will be happy, but the
Dolphins will only pretend that they care about that. They will be
more worried that Phillips lacks the proper discipline and respect
for coach Jimmy Johnson and that, as a result, he will gain about
35 yards a game.
</P>
<P>
   The sports world usually polices itself that way. Most of the
major leagues test for cocaine on the pretext that they want to
present role models to the public. What they really want is
athletes who aren't too high to get to practice on time.
</P>
<P>
   It's not exactly justice, but sports obsession leads to all
sorts of craziness. And until someone shaves a lot of points off
that 46-38 score, it will have to do.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
