<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANNE-KLEIN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACK TO BASICS FOR ANNE KLEIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CYNTHIA ROBINS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Face it. Ever since Anne Klein's money men got
rid of Louis dell'Olio for not being relevant enough to the
so-called ``modern'' woman, the company has not fared too well.
</P>
<P>
   Dell'Olio, who was Donna Karan's design partner at Anne Klein
when the original Anne died of cancer, was replaced by the hip
Richard Tyler, who cut his clothes so narrow that he lost Klein a
lot of its classic customers. He, in turn, was replaced by Patrick
Robinson, who fared even worse. And now, with two new designers,
Ken Kaufman and Isaac Franco, Anne Klein is back to square one.
</P>
<P>
   Only this time, Klein is coming out with a new ad campaign and
two designers who refer to dell'Olio with every stroke of the
chalk. The Anne Klein II line now becomes Anne Klein, a bridge line
to compete head-to-head with DKNY, Ellen Tracy and Dana Buchman.
And the A-Line still skews younger and slimmer.
</P>
<P>
   To announce the change, Anne Klein is showing its clothing on
non-models _ 30 multigenerational, multiracial women who, says
Laura Wenke, senior vice president of marketing and communications,
``Ken and Isaac and our committee felt should be our customers and
whose talents they admire. They were chosen as much for what they
didn't have in common, for their diversity, as well as their
general spirit of achievement.''
</P>
<P>
   Taking its cue from Annie Leibovitz's stunning gatefold tableaux
for Vanity Fair's Hollywood issue, Klein hired Leibovitz to shoot
the finalists _ women from the age of 24 to former Texas Gov. Ann
Richards (no age given) who could afford the time to go to New York
to be photographed and who could wear the clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Klein's ``Significant Women'' campaign kicks off in the August
issue of Elle and is said to cost in the $5 million range.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately, these ads have got to be about the clothes,''
Wenke says. ``There is nothing cutting-edge about them. They are
collectibles, basics. But they are classics given a fashionable
twist. The fabrics are all state of the art. You'll see a lot of
bi-stretch wools.''
</P>
<P>
   The new designers, Wenke says, ``cut rather generously. Their
silhouettes are more forgiving.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Significant'' women in the campaign are dressed in the
fall line, which is very New York, very urban, ``very urbane,''
Wenke says. The line is a collector's dream: turtlenecks and
blazers (albeit very nipped-in-waist blazers that fondle the body);
crisp, white, tailored shirts and stylish menswear gray coats
(Richards looks particularly fetching in that one); very, very
sophisticated black evening wear; leather jackets; blanket-fringed
sarongs; silver anoraks and camel corduroy suits. All of it: a
vindication of dell'Olio's classicism.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
