<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 14:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7730 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOUNGE-SINGERS-HNS &LR;      07-02 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOUNGE-SINGERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GREAT READ ON EASY LISTENING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDVINS BEITIKS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Using no fewer than 60 contributors from all over the United
States and Europe, Steve Knopper has put together the most readable
and informative reference book on pop singing in this century.
</P>
<P>
   ``MusicHound Lounge: The Essential Album Guide to Martini Music
and Easy Listening'' (Visible Ink Press, Detroit, 1998; 590 pages;
$24.95) isn't some cold, fact-spewing dictionary or an over-the-top
compendium of personal favorites.
</P>
<P>
   This is an insightful look at the careers, best and worst
albums, the influences and legacies of 500 lounge and
easy-listening singers from Abba to Zamfir, a category generously
defined to include the likes of Mose Allison, Teresa Brewer, Cab
Calloway, Sinead O'Connor, Elvis Costello, Gordon Lightfoot, Denny
McLain, Gladys Knight and the Pips, the Squirrel Nut Zippers, Elvis
Presley and Tom Waits.
</P>
<P>
   From the front of the book, a foreword by Martin Denny of
``Quiet Village'' fame, to the back, a ``Welcome to the Ultra
Lounge'' sample CD, Knopper's pacing is a pure delight.
</P>
<P>
   Denny writes, ``I started out playing piano in bars, ranging
from a lounge in Eureka, California, to the Surf Room of the Royal
Hawaiian Hotel in Honolulu. In 1957, I performed with my group at
Las Vegas' Flamingo Hotel, on an elevated circular stage that
revolved like a merry-go-round. ... In the background you could
hear the clinking of glasses and the noise of bartenders blending
drinks.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Ultra-Lounge'' CD has 24 fine cuts, including ``Mr.
Lucky'' from Si Zentner; a medley of ``One Step Beyond'' and ``The
Twilight Zone'' from the Ventures; Nelson Riddle's ``My Three
Sons'' theme; Billy May doing ``The Look of Love''; Peggy Lee's
version of ``The Boy From Ipanema''; Bobby Darin's ``Charade'';
Dinah Washington, ``Is You Is or Is You Ain't My Baby?''; Martin
Denny's ``Cool'' from West Side Story; ``Balinese Bongos'' from Les
Baxter; ``Squatty Roo,'' the John Buzon Trio; and Al Caiola sliding
between ``Big Noise From Winetka'' and ``Midnight Swim.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a look-see at each artist's career, followed by
recommendations of which albums to buy first, which to buy next and
which to avoid, page after page highlighted by rich photographs and
Cocktail Classics, pop boxes listing the best and worst renditions
of a given song.
</P>
<P>
   Knopper's lounge music falls into three main categories _
``Crooners,'' ``Space-age bachelor pad music'' and ``Elevator
music.''
</P>
<P>
   To Knopper, the editor of the book, lounge music ``refers to a
place where people gather to hear music and drink martinis, not a
style. ... In the end, `MusicHound Lounge' is simply a book of good
stories.
</P>
<P>
   ``MusicHound has a bit of junkyard dog in it, too,'' Knopper
adds. ``It likes to start fights.''
</P>
<P>
   There may, indeed, be fights over certain sections. Julie
Andrews is given more space than June Christy and Richard Harris
gets as much play as Phil Harris, which is crazy. And they like Jim
Nabors a lot more than is good for them.
</P>
<P>
   But if some of the choices in ``Lounge'' aren't choice, the
writing is solid all the way through. Here, for instance, is a
slice of Cab Calloway, written by David Menconi, music critic for
the News &AMP; Observer out of Raleigh, N.C.:
</P>
<P>
   ``If more people were as purely entertaining as Calloway, the
world would be a much better (not to mention hipper) place.
Calloway was the key transitional figure during the 1930s and
1940s, when the big band era was giving way to R&AMP;B. He was there to
goose it along every step of the way with acrobatic performances
that predated Jackie Wilson and James Brown by decades.''
</P>
<P>
   Or here's Knopper on Rosemary Clooney: ``Because she was a
straightforward pop singer instead of a rock 'n' roll belter or a
jazz chanteuse, Clooney's incredible hitmaking career is frequently
dismissed by critics and historians with their noses upturned. Yes,
she sang many novelty tunes, including the surprisingly forceful
and sexy `Mambo Italiano' ... but, while she doesn't communicate
with quite the expression of Billie Holiday, Clooney's clear,
perfect voice is a marvel.''
</P>
<P>
   From its descriptions of Frank Sinatra (``the model of all
things lounge'') and Lonnie Donegan (``undisputed King of
Skiffle'') to casual facts like the crew of the space shuttle
Challenger asking that their wake-up call on April 6, 1983, be
``Teach Me Tiger'' by Nino Tempo and April Stevens, ``MusicHound
Lounge'' bursts with good bits.
</P>
<P>
   Add dozens of Cocktail Classics and it just gets better. The
18-carat ``Volare'' belongs to Dean Martin. The ``Bombsville''
version? Alex Chilton. ``Thunderball?'' Tom Jones at ``18-Carat,''
Xavier Cugat at ``Bombsville.'' ``Nature Boy,'' best version? Nat
King Cole. Worst? The Association. ``Let's Call the Whole Thing
Off?'' Fred Astaire and Harry Connick Jr. ``The Girl From
Ipanema?'' Astrud Gilberto coupled with Denny McLain. ``C'est Si
Bon?'' Eartha Kitt and Ann-Margret.
</P>
<P>
   For a lot of entries, the tongue of ``Lounge'' is way back in
its cheek. The Jerry Vale essay starts with, ``All right, so he's
not Al Martino.'' The one on Frankie Yankovic says, ``When you
think of Christmas ... you probably don't think of polka. Well, all
that will change the minute you buy the delightful `Christmas
Memories.''' Bobby Darin's biography includes the fact that he
believed so strongly in the heartbreak of his album, ``Born: Walden
Robert Cosotto,'' that ``he refused to wear his toupee while
recording it.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a fine book. More than that. It's indispensable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
