</P>
<P>
   FLA-FIRES _ ORMOND BEACH, Fla. _ Atlanta Journal-Constitution
lead on the Florida wildfires. In Brevard County, Fire Chief Mark
Francesconi said firefighters did not have enough equipment and
help to keep the blazes away from homes. In Volusia, the early
count was at least 10 homes and as 20 business. In Brevard, about
50 homes were destroyed along with many businesses. The Pepsi 400
Daytona NASCAR race has been postponed until October. (MWilliams in
Florida/Marlon Manuel in Atlanta, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   FIRES13 (developing) _ ORMOND BEACH, Fla. _ Dozens of homes and
buildings were destroyed overnight; 35,000 people fled their homes
and the fires ravaging two counties are expected to get bigger
Thursday. (Jenny Staletovich, Sonja Isger, John Holland, Susannah
Nesmith and Shirish Date, Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   FIRES-PEPSI3 (developing) _ DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ The Pepsi 400,
the first night NASCAR race ever at Daytona International Speedway,
was postponed Thursday because of wildfires burning out of control
in Florida, officials said. The race, scheduled for the Fourth of
July, was billed as the largest night sporting event ever. The race
was rescheduled for Oct. 17. (By Jenny Staletovich, John Holland
and Jorge Milan, Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   FIRES-CERABINO3 (developing) _ Local News columnist is driving
from West Palm Beach to Jacksonville Thursday and will report on
detours and smoke. (Cerabino, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   FIRES-BOX3 (developing) _ Where are the fires? Number of acres
burned? (Staletovich, Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   NORTHUP _ LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Speaker Newt Gingrich raises funds
Thursday for Rep. Anne Northup, R-Ky., whose district is deeply
affected by tobacco legislation pending in the House. (Sherman, Cox
News Service).
</P>
<P>
   ECOLI _ Updating the numbers, checking to see if an Athens, Ga.,
cluster has been identified, whether new genetic tests are
complete; will fold in children's conditions. (McKenna, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   ECOLI-TREATMENT _ Patients being treated at Emory's Egleston
Children's Hospital in Atlanta for E. coli complications are being
offered an experimental therapy considered the best hope in slowing
the toxic infection. (Guthrie, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   RURAL-HOSPITALS _ MONTICELLO, Ga. _ When Sara Deleza's heart
stopped 10 months ago, she was rushed to Jasper County Memorial
Hospital, where the local doctor brought her back to life,
stabilized her and sent her on her way to a major medical center to
await a heart transplant. ``If it hadn't been there, I wouldn't be
here,'' she said. Deleza was among the most dramatic of the
hospital's 2,600 emergency calls last year. More often, patients
arrive at the low-slung brick building with snake bites, allergic
reactions or broken bones. But her survival illustrates how
important a hospital can be to the people living in a rural
community. In Jasper County, that role is in danger. Across the
country, hospitals in rural communities are finding it increasingly
difficult to stay in business, and Jasper County Memorial is no
exception. (Carr, Cox News Service 850&AMP;add.)
</P>
