<DOCNO> NYT19980702.0099 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 14:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7747 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-WHATNEXT-$ADV     07-02 1643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-WHATNEXT-$ADV05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CHINA TRIUMPH BEHIND HIM, CLINTON FACES TOUGHER FIGHTS AT HOME
 &HT;    1050&AMP;add. For release Sunday, July 5
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Still dealing with jet lag after a nine-day China
tour, President Clinton returns to the Oval Office on Monday to
face partisan squabbles and policy headaches that may well leave
him nostalgic for the Middle Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   Awed by ancient wonders, inspired by the promise of change and
buoyed by having carried a message of freedom and hope to 1.2
billion Chinese, Clinton would like to use the momentum of his
historic state visit to help reinvigorate a troubled domestic
agenda.
</P>
<P>
   But as he tries to advance a slate of bread-and-butter issues
ranging from child care tax credits to a minimum wage increase,
Clinton returns to a White House under siege by influences largely
beyond his control.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican-led Congress is spoiling for showdowns over tax
cuts, education spending and health care to help highlight their
political differences with Democrats before November, when all 435
members of the House and a third of the Senate will be up for
re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a long list of foreign policy matters demands
Clinton's attention. They include ethnic fighting in the
Yugoslavian province of Kosovo, the continuing economic crisis in
Asia and the growing risk of instability in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   And there's Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr's inquiry, now in
its sixth month, into whether Clinton had an affair with former
White House intern Monica Lewinsky then later urged her to lie
about it under oath, allegations the president has denied.
</P>
<P>
   Add to all that the coming dog days of August _when Congress
will be in recess for almost the entire month _ and it's clear it
won't be easy for Clinton to translate his China successes into
political victories at home. He could be hard-pressed to simply
keep his domestic objectives alive.
</P>
<P>
   ''He'll come back reinvigorated,'' said analyst Erwin Hargrove,
who teaches political science at Vanderbilt University in
Nashville, but in trying to score points domestically, ''foreign
trips don't help much.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was clearly lifted by his China tour, which gave him
unexpected opportunities to showcase his rhetorical gifts before
the largest audience in the world.
</P>
<P>
   So remarkable were Clinton's performances during a
nationally-televised press conference from Beijing with Chinese
President Jiang Zemin, a televised give-and-take with students at
Beijing University and a live radio call-in show in Shanghai that
even some of his harshest critics were forced to acknowledge his
achievement.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think if you reach out to a billion people and talk about
open markets and expand the zone of freedom on the planet, that's a
pretty good investment for the world,'' House Speaker Newt
Gingrich, R-Ga., said Wednesday at a Republican Party fund-raising
event in San Antonio. As an advocate for increased liberties for
the repressed Chinese, Gingrich said, Clinton did a ''good job.''
</P>
<P>
   Praising Clinton, however, seems an easy habit to break in this
town, particularly for Republicans fighting to maintain control of
both houses of Congress come Nov. 3. Many will try to do so largely
by differentiating themselves from Clinton's priorities, beginning
as soon as the Senate returns from its mid-summer break on Monday,
and the House on July 13.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're not going to cooperate (with Clinton) on anything,''
predicted Hargrove, author of the just-published book ''The
President as Leader: Appealing to the Better Angels of our
Nation.''
</P>
<P>
   In the political firmament, at least, it's a season when halos
are in short supply.
</P>
<P>
   White House strategists, as well as many Republicans, were
stunned last month when Senate Republicans killed an omnibus
tobacco bill that would have raised cigarette taxes by some $60
billion a year and hit the industry with comprehensive regulations
aimed at ending marketing efforts that target teenagers.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was counting on the increased revenues to fund at least
a third of his proposals for beefing up Head Start preschool
programs for poor children, increasing child care subsidies for
low-income families and expanding medical research, among other
priorities.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans had hoped to use the cash to finance a new cut in
the capital gains tax on profits from the sale of property, stocks
or other investments, as well as tax-free savings accounts of up to
$2,000 a year to fund a child's education.
</P>
<P>
   With or without a tobacco bill _ the House is working on a
stripped-down version _ Clinton still wants his spending increases,
and Republicans still want their tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has opposed both the proposed tax cuts _ he could be
forced into a veto showdown as early as this week over the
education savings accounts, proposed by Sen. Paul Coverdell, R-Ga.
_ saying the breaks favor wealthy Americans over low-income and
middle-class workers and threaten efforts to keep the federal
budget in balance.
</P>
<P>
   Seven years into the greatest U.S. economic expansion in
history, the federal government is only now beginning to balance
its budget, after three decades of deficit spending that has left
the country $5.5 trillion in debt.
</P>
<P>
   Before rushing to cut taxes, Clinton insists, any surplus
revenues _ projected to top $40 billion this year _ should be set
aside to help shore up Social Security. The national retirement
insurance program will begin paying out more than it takes in when
Baby Boomers begin leaving the workforce in the year 2010, and its
reserves could be depleted by 2032 under current projections.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton wants to avoid politicizing the explosive issue between
now and Election Day, and has proposed taking it up as a national
priority early next year.
</P>
<P>
   Many Republicans on Capitol Hill, however, have asked him to
name a bipartisan commission to make recommendations much sooner, a
plan Clinton has thus far resisted.
</P>
<P>
   Even without control of Congress, Clinton is hardly without
resources on Capitol Hill. Much as he went around China's
repressive leadership in Beijing to take his message directly to
the people of China, he's been formidably effective at taking his
campaign directly to the American people, 61 percent of whom still
regard him favorably, according to a June 7 Gallup/CNN/USA Today
poll.
</P>
<P>
   ''One of the best features of the presidency is the bully
pulpit,'' White House political counselor Paul Begala said in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   ''The story of this year will be either progress or
partisanship, and that really is up to the Republican leadership,''
said Begala. ''I think they're going to either move on the
president's agenda or wish to goodness they had, come November.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Political equations aside, Clinton also faces the prospect of a
deepening security crisis in Kosovo, a province of what's left of
Serb-dominated Yugoslavia, whose troops have waged a months-long
campaign of violence against ethnic Albanians, who make up 95
percent of the population.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is leading diplomatic efforts, yet to bear
fruit, to negotiate peace, even as NATO members move forward with
contingency plans to use military force if necessary to prevent the
conflict from spreading.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton faces other international challenges, including trying
to prevent the troubles in Asia from dragging down the global
economy, struggling to breathe life into the staggering Middle East
peace process and helping to prevent the Russian economy from going
down the tubes.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional challenges and international ills are not unique
to the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   ''Presidents are never in control of their own agenda,'' said
Thomas Mann, director of governmental studies at the Brookings
Institution, a Washington research center. ''Seldom in American
history have presidents dominated the Congress and, especially in
periods of divided government, it's always a negotiation.''
</P>
<P>
   What Clinton has to deal with that others haven't, though, is
the daily deluge of proceedings and pronouncements from Starr's
investigation, which has generated thousands of hours of television
commentary, acres of newsprint and a sprawling scandal that has
distanced Clinton from the news media, throttling one engine of
influence he had formerly used to great effect.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's no question but that his position is dramatically
weaker now than it was at the beginning of January,'' said Mann.
''This whole Lewinsky-Starr matter has certainly hurt him.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr's own image took a hit last week, when U.S. District Judge
James Robertson threw out tax evasion charges Starr had filed
against longtime Clinton friend and former Associate Attorney
General Webster Hubbell, claiming that Starr had exceeded his
authority and violated previous immunity guarantees granted to
Hubbell.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson, a Clinton appointee, railed at Starr, accusing him of
using his subpoena power to pry documents from Hubbell as part of
''a quintessential fishing expedition.''
</P>
<P>
   The ruling gave teeth to the claims of Clinton defenders such as
Begala, who have long maintained that Starr's investigation is less
about justice than about derailing Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ''Part of the goal, maybe the entire goal, is to distract him,''
said Begala, who insisted that he and his White House colleagues
have been ''roped off'' from the Lewinsky matter and are focused on
policy.
</P>
<P>
   ''But I'm not going to lie to you, it certainly can be
distracting,'' Begala said. ''It's maybe a sad commentary, but one
thing we've become quite good at is this phrase,
'compartmentalizing, carry on regardless.' We've got vast
experience with that.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
