<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR FRIDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Friday, July 3:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   NIGERIA (United Nations) _ Nigeria's new military government has
promised to release all political prisoners, including Moshood
Abiola, the nation's leading opposition figure, Secretary General
Kofi Annan says. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-CLINTON (Hong Kong) _ Clinton's day in Guilin and Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
   Other China stories as appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-GAZPROM (Moscow) _ After a day of drama and uncertainty,
the Russian government reaches agreement with Gazprom, the nation's
biggest taxpayer, on future tax payments after threatening to seize
company assets, freeze bank accounts and replace the board. By
Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   SWISS-BANKS (Undated) _ Sanctions are outlined against Swiss
banks, and the Swiss are not pleased. By David Cay Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-BLAIR (Belfast) _ Prime Minister Tony Blair of Britain
flies to Northern Ireland to try to quell sectarian tensions that
were intensified overnight by the burning, apparently by
Protestants, of nine Roman Catholic churches in the province. By
James F. Clarity.
</P>
<P>
   DIANA-MUSEUM (Great Brington, England) _ The Diana museum is
open for business. What do visitors, and the locals, say? By Sarah
Lyall.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-STARR (Washington) _ Linda Tripp returns to the grand
jury; other developments in Kenneth Starr's investigation of the
president.
</P>
<P>
   VIAGRA-MEDICAID (Washington) _ The Clinton administration tells
states to pay for Viagra under Medicaid. Governors object, saying
they weren't consulted. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   JULY4-RISKS (Washington) _ Fireworks and raw hamburgers may
menace modern Independence Day revels, but in the early days of the
Republic, a historian reveals, the risks when competing parties
celebrated were even bloodier. By John H. Cushman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL-GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   AMISH-DRUGS (Philadelphia) _ Developments in the arraignment in
a drug case involving Amish youths, which has all of Lancaster
County talking. By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   FLA-FIRES (Ormond Beach, Fla.) _ Thirty-five thousand people are
evacuated, 125 miles of I-95 closed, and heavy winds are expected
today as Florida's wild fire nightmare continues. By Mireya
Navarro.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   FLA-FIRES-GRIDLOCK (Somewhere along I-95) _ What happens when
125 miles of interstate are closed on a Fourth of July weekend.
</P>
<P>
   CATHOLICS-REACT (Undated) _ Roman Catholic priests and lay
people react to Pope John Paul II's action to stamp out debate on
liberal issues like the ordination of women. By Nadine Brozan.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEW YORK &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   NY-METROCARD (New York) _ New York City prepares for a
revolutionary change in its transit fare structure, with monthly
and weekly passes to go into effect Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   NY-CHILD-ABUSE (New York) _ Folo on a case of child abuse in
Brooklyn in which five adults are being held on sex charges
involving two teen-aged girls and two 8-year-old boys.
</P>
<P>
   NY-TAXIS (New York) _ Ruling on the mayor's controversial taxi
rules is expected today.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ The economy added jobs at a more subdued
pace in June, and the unemployment rate rose to a three-month high.
Labor costs remained in check. Payrolls expanded by 205,000 jobs
last month, near expectations, smaller than May's increase, which
was revised to 309,000 jobs from the 296,000 reported initially.
The unemployment rate increased to 4.5 percent in June from 4.3
percent in May. A separate report shows that the number of workers
filing for state unemployment benefits rose last week as the strike
against General Motors put thousands out of work. By Sylvia Nasar.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-ECON (Tokyo) _ Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto approves a
sweeping plan to restore Japan's banking system to financial
health, including the use of 30 trillion yen, or $217 billion, in
public money to close insolvent institutions. The plan comes amid
mounting investor optimism that the country's ailing economy could
be turning the corner; stocks rose again in Tokyo, with the
benchmark average climbing 0.7 percent. By Sheryl WuDunn.
</P>
<P>
   CHICKEN-SOUP-PUBLISHER (Deerfield Beach, Fla.) _ There is little
about Health Communications, a publishing house, that is
conventional except that it ladles up bestsellers. It had three
entrants on the New York Times paperback bestseller lists last
weekend, including the 17th book in its warm and goose-bumpy series
of inspirational tales, ``Chicken Soup for the Teenage Soul.'' The
company rarely pays author advances, loathes advertising, binds its
own books, offers executive-level yoga and made one critical
business decision based on the teary emotional response of its
founder and president, Peter Vegso. He recalls being so overcome by
the original manuscript of ``Chicken Soup for the Soul'' that he
could not continue reading. But that did not stop him from making a
calculating business judgment that has resulted in sales of more
than 30 million of assorted ``Chicken Soup'' tales. By Doreen
Carvajal.
</P>
<P>
   FED-REPORT (Washington) _ The Fed makes public the minutes of
the May meeting of its policy committee. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   GART-SPORTS-AUTHORITY (Undated) _ Gart Sports, a sporting-goods
retailer that is owned 61 percent by the Los Angeles investor
Leonard Green, offers to buy Sports Authority for $20 a share,
outbidding Venator (formerly Woolworth), which is offering $18.40 a
share. By Jennifer Steinhauer.
</P>
<P>
   CREDIT (New York) _ Credit market developments. The market
closes early today. The long bond was up 17/32 at midday. By Robert
Hurtado.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-AIDS-VACCINE (Geneva, Switzerland) _ New evidence is casting
serious douts about the safety of what has been called the most
effective experimental AIDS vaccine to date. This setback leaves
the quest for a vaccine where it was when the epidemic was first
recognized in 1981. By Lawrence K. Altman.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ASTEROID (Undated) _ Astronomers have discovered a new type
of asteroid, whose orbit lies entirely inside of the Earth's orbit,
where astronomers had never looked before. Most asteroids have
orbits that extend beyond the Earth, and search efforts are
therefore directed in the opposite direction. By Malcolm Browne.
</P>
