<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POP-BEAT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOMAS THROWS DEBUT INTO DRIVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Mellow rocker Scott Thomas says he sequenced his
debut disc ``as a soundtrack for driving.''
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean you can't listen to the Scott Thomas Band's
``California'' (Elektra/EEG) at home or elsewhere. But the
singer-guitarist says he especially likes ``road trip records''
that can be played from start to finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``The story should start when you turn on the ignition and then
be good to the last drop,'' Thomas explained. ``When I got ready to
put the finishing touches on the album, I got in the car and drove
along Mulholland Drive into Calabasas and along Pacific Coast
Highway and figured out what order I'd like to hear the songs.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas was just 15 when he left home in Northern California and
moved to Los Angeles. By the mid-'90s, he was performing his songs
at the Hollywood club Largo, where he met the musicians who would
become the Scott Thomas Band.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played every Tuesday night, always sitting down,'' Thomas
recalled. ``We never stood up. Our chairs would be almost at
audience level.''
</P>
<P>
   The band's haunting single, ``Black Valentine,'' was recently
among the top 30 songs at rock radio across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas lives in Laurel Canyon but spends a good deal of time in
the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I shop there,'' he said. ``That's where my video store is. I
rehearse in the Valley. The Valley has the folk-rock vibe.
Hollywood's gotten to be such a weird place.''
</P>
<P>
   BLACK SHEEP: No Depression: Is it a magazine, a book, a roots
music scene or a way of life?
</P>
<P>
   All of the above, says Peter Blackstock, co-editor with Grant
Alden of ``No Depression: An Introduction to Alternative Country
Music (Whatever That Is)'' (Dowling Press; $16.95).
</P>
<P>
   The softback anthology collects pieces from No Depression
magazine, launched three years ago by Alden and Texas-bred
Blackstock, Seattle writers tired of that city's grunge scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both of us were fans of these artists and we were certainly
into a lot of independent and underground stuff in the '80s,''
Blackstock said. ``Like a lot of our readers, we found ourselves
appreciating roots music as we got older and punk-rock got co-opted
by the mainstream.''
</P>
<P>
   The book highlights 35 artists, including Son Volt, 16
Horsepower, Steve Earle, Whiskeytown, Waylon Jennings, Gillian
Welch, the Jayhawks and Charlie Louvin, people ``too old, too loud
or too eccentric for country radio,'' Blackstock said.
</P>
<P>
   NEW MUSIC: Coming next month are new albums from Senegal's Baaba
Maal and Jamaican guitar pioneer Ernest Ranglin. Maal's ``Nomad
Soul'' and Ranglin's ``In Search of the Lost Riddim'' are the first
two releases from Palm Pictures, Island Records founder Chris
Blackwell's new entertainment company.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
