<DOCNO> NYT19980702.0106 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 14:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7761 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MTV-MUSIC-LADN     07-02 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MTV-MUSIC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MTV LENDS HAND TO IDOL PURSUIT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Buddy Eason was at work at the Guitar Center in
Sherman Oaks when a camera crew burst through the door.
</P>
<P>
   It was MTV and they were gunning for him.
</P>
<P>
   Eason, 23, had been chosen for MTV's new Monday-night show
``Fanatic,'' where fans are given a chance to interview their
favorite stars.
</P>
<P>
   Eason, who also lives in Sherman Oaks, hung out with his fave
band, Huntington Beach thrash-metal outfit Korn, at a recording
studio in North Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're everyday people,'' he said. ``I found out they're just
like me.''
</P>
<P>
   Uh-oh. Maybe that close identification isn't exactly what MTV _
or Korn _ had in mind.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, stars already hooked up with their No. 1 fans for
the show include Jennifer Love Hewitt, the Wallflowers, Boyz II
Men, Wesley Snipes, Backstreet Boys, Cindy Crawford, Eddie Van
Halen and Bruce Willis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very lengthy screening process,'' explained ``Fanatic''
co-executive producer Ed Connelly. ``We search for the biggest fan
through the Internet, then they send tapes and we decide who is the
most inspired and devoted fan.''
</P>
<P>
   The candidates are asked to make a video about their life and
send it to the show's producers. Post-``Truman Show'' attempts to
falsify daily existence will be spotted immediately, MTV promises.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look for the person who has the most healthy interest in
the celebrity,'' Connelly said.
</P>
<P>
   We suppose that might rule out John Hinckley Jr. meeting Jodie
Foster. Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   Once the fan is chosen, MTV works with an accomplice to make the
announcement a surprise.
</P>
<P>
   That's how the camera crew came to burst through the Guitar
Center's doors in search of Eason, who said he really hit it off
with the members of Korn and promised he wouldn't stand around
outside their homes on evenings and weekends and days when Guitar
Center lets him off early.
</P>
<P>
   ``At any moment, an MTV crew could come and pluck them from
their lives and 24 hours later they're meeting the celebrity,''
said Deborah Norton, another ``Fanatic'' co-executive producer.
``Some of the more dramatic moments occur when the fan actually
tells the celebrity what they inspire. It's interesting when the
fan and celebrity connect on a human level.''
</P>
<P>
   That proverbial human level. Much better than two people
connecting on the canine level. Somehow, we can't imagine dog
friendship rituals playing on TV, even the cable channel that
brings us ``Road Rules.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Fanatic,'' which features two celebrities and fans per show,
premieres at 11 p.m. Monday.
</P>
<P>
   MTV has traveled great distances to tape the first 20 episodes.
To meet Snipes, his fan was flown to Saudi Arabia, while another
went to London to greet Willis.
</P>
<P>
   We're not sure if this is because the celeb was actually running
away from the fan or they just happened to be in those faraway
places.
</P>
<P>
   ``Celebrities get nervous about things like this, but this is
such a controlled, highly screened situation,'' Connelly said.
``It's really a once-in-a-lifetime thing for fans to connect with
their heroes.''
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Van Halen, the fan not only got to meet the band,
but was invited on stage to perform with the rockers. Now, that's a
career in need of some serious re-evaluation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had this dream-come-true quality,'' said Norton, speaking
either about Van Halen or the kid. Maybe both.
</P>
<P>
   Celebs from all fields, including sports, politics, music and
film will be booked,'' Connelly said, adding that he has even
considered booking ex-Vice President Dan Quayle.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to the most worrying question for parents and
employers of potential ``Fanatics'': How you gonna keep 'em down on
the farm once they've met Dan Quayle? &UR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-98 1418EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
