<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980702.0107 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 14:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7762 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-GRADES-COX &UR; $ CONGRESSMEMBERS   07-02 1028
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-GRADES-COX </SLUG>
   $ADV05  AS ELECTIONS NEAR, CONGRESS
MEMBERS AWAIT INTEREST GROUPS' REPORT CARDS
 &HT;     For release Sunday, July 5.
 &HT;     By KIMBERLY MARSELAS 
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It's report card time again _ not for students, but
for members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The cards are issued by nearly 100 special interest groups from
across the political spectrum. And with congressional elections
less than four months away, lawmakers are paying close attention to
their grades and what they mean to voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``In an election year, it's difficult to find very many people
who say they are for destroying the environment or building up the
deficit,'' said Rep. Lloyd Doggett, D-Texas. ``Voters sometimes
will rely on some kind of independent verification to discern the
truth.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, voters for whom abortion is a key issue can track
ratings by the National Right to Life Committee, an anti-abortion
group, or the National Abortion Reproductive Rights Action League,
which favors abortion rights. Similarly, gun control legislation is
tracked by both the National Rifle Association and Handgun Control
Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Most groups grade members according to how they voted on bills
the group considered important. But once compiled, the report cards
are used in ways as varied as the groups that issue them.
</P>
<P>
   Some groups tell lawmakers in advance that certain votes will be
graded, hoping to sway their votes.
</P>
<P>
   The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People
uses its report card in the re-election campaigns of low-scoring
lawmakers, distributing copies to its 1,700 local branches and 1
million members. The Concord Coalition, an anti-deficit group,
sends its grades to all the members of Congress and any of its own
members who request copies.
</P>
<P>
   The Christian Coalition follows pro-family votes and distributes
lawmakers' rankings to its members, lawmakers and grassroots
activists. The American Conservative Union uses its report card to
select lawmakers that its political action committee (PAC) will
support with campaign contributions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking for a guide to determine what the ideology of a
member is,'' explained Tom Katina, executive director of the ACU.
``We're not partisan.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Hess, a senior fellow who specializes in governmental
studies at the Brookings Institution, a Washington research
facility, agreed: ``They're not partisan, but they're certainly not
non-ideological.''
</P>
<P>
   Project Vote Smart, an independent organization that tracks
interest group report cards on its Internet site
(http://www.vote-smart.org), warns that the ratings can be biased,
favoring one political party over another.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ron Paul, R-Texas, shares the concern about bias.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think most members (of Congress) are interested in them,''
Paul said, ``but some are designed just as a demagogue or to
support a position.''
</P>
<P>
   The League of Conservation Voters declares itself non-partisan,
but of the six candidates recently targeted by the pro-environment
group for defeat in the fall elections, five are Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers' reactions to the report cards vary. Doggett, who has
received consistently good grades from the Concord Coalition, likes
to tout his rating as a ``deficit hawk'' in news releases.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, ``there's none that I pay attention to
whatsoever,'' said House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas. ``I
don't represent the people who do those ratings.''
</P>
<P>
   However, ``I have felt injured on occasion'' by ratings, Armey
admitted. ``This real liberal group gave me a 5 percent vote once,
and I was discomforted.''
</P>
<P>
   Others also claim that their legislative actions are based on
principle, not pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Casting votes in Congress may have the appearance of running
across a bomb-cratered battlefield of special interests and other
influences, including various lobby groups' report cards,'' said
Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas. ``But for members who have a firm grasp
of their constituents' will, it is a confident stride down Main
Street.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the more aggressive interest groups _ particularly those
connected with PACs _ use report cards as lobbying tools by telling
lawmakers in advance that they will be including certain votes in
their calculations. Sometimes, this tactic works.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more obscure the issue, the more impact they might have,''
Doggett said.
</P>
<P>
   Advance notice made a difference this spring when a music
licensing bill came before the House, Doggett said. The National
Federation of Independent Business sent out a notice that it was
supporting a ``yes'' vote and would count the vote on its report
card.
</P>
<P>
   ``There wasn't much information out about this bill, and some
(House) members came onto the floor and knew a national
organization would be counting it,'' said Doggett. Knowing that the
NFIB and its 600,000 members were backing this relatively unknown
bill helped some members to make up their minds, Doggett said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd prefer to know about it in advance,'' he said of votes
being rated.
</P>
<P>
   Interest groups aren't alone in using upcoming report cards to
pressure lawmakers into voting a certain way. Lawmakers sometimes
pressure the interest groups to rate specific votes, counting on
the added weight to push their colleagues one way or another.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do that sometimes as a matter of strategy,'' said Armey.
</P>
<P>
   Some groups won't honor lawmakers' requests or inform lawmakers
in advance of the votes being watched. Katina said the American
Conservative Union believes that surprise plays an important part
in determining the true ideological attitudes of lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's an important component of our ratings,'' said Katina.
``We do not use our ratings as a lobbying tool.''
</P>
<P>
   The Concord Coalition's communications director, Craig Cheslog,
said that the group sends out letters to alert lawmakers to all
legislation they see as important. However, they don't reveal
whether a particular vote will be a key vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``We urge them to vote our way,'' Cheslog said, ``whether the
vote counts in the ratings or not.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-98 1418EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980702.0108 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 14:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7763 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DISCS-MUSIC-LADN     07-02 0987
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISCS-MUSIC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GATTON FINALLY HITS RIGHT CHORD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
DANNY GATTON/``Untouchable''
<TEXT>
<P>
   This album was begun 10 years ago but interrupted when late
rockabilly-jazz guitar virtuoso Danny Gatton signed with a major
for two discs. Few recordings have done this guy justice, but
``Untouchable'' (NRG) comes closest to capturing the delicate chord
voicings and shimmering, lightning-quick runs that made Gatton a
Maryland roadhouse legend long before he took his own life several
years ago. Among the best moments are Gatton's tribute to jazz
guitarist Lenny Breau, ``One for Lenny''; a solid nod to Motown
with ``Ain't That Peculiar'' (featuring late Washington, D.C.-area
jazz diva Eva Cassidy on backups); and the tongue-in-cheek
``Untouchables'' theme. The only thing missing here is a little
more gutbucket blues. 3 Stars. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
LINDA RONSTADT/``We Ran''
</P>
<P>
   We can imagine the closed-door meeting high above Hollywood.
``Linda, sweetie, we loved the Mexican stuff, really we did. And
the Broadway and big-band tunes. The kids' lullabies _ genius,
sheer genius. But, please, doll, give us some pop music. Give us
some product we can move.'' The unspoken warning _ one more
ludicrous attempt to make ``art'' and you're gonna be selling your
homemade CDs out of the trunk of the station wagon _ obviously
worked. So, for her 31st album, Ronstadt returns to the terrain
that established her as a top rock interpreter. ``We Ran''
(Elektra), coming from somewhere near the town of Last Chance, is a
goodie. Whether covering Bob Dylan (``Just Like Tom Thumb's
Blues''), John Hiatt (``When We Ran''), Bruce Springsteen (``If I
Should Fall Behind'') or Irma Thomas (``Ruler of My Heart''),
Ronstadt, backed by some top local players, is in tip-top shape. 3
Stars. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
WES MONTGOMERY/``Ultimate''
</P>
<P>
   Here's a fun proposition: George Benson chooses his favorite Wes
tunes. Or favorite Wes tunes on Verve, that is. ``Ultimate'' turns
out to be a joy, unless, of course, you already have these 14
tracks _ including such classics as ``Twisted Blues,'' ``Caravan,''
``Tequila,'' ``West Coast Blues,'' ``Impressions'' and ``Four on
Six'' _ on other reissues. In any case, the liner notes are
revealing. Benson points out something I didn't know _ that the
late Montgomery had a big old ``corn'' on his thumb that helped
give his guitar playing its distinctive hard-soft sound. ``That's
why no one will ever match Wes,'' Benson insists, forgetting that
Montgomery didn't own the patent on finger warts. Because, in
actual fact, it could only have been a wart since corns generally
appear on feet. Unless Wes' thumb was really a big toe. In which
case, yes indeedy, no one will ever match Wes thumb for thumb. 4
Stars. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
PURE SUGAR/``Pure Sugar''
</P>
<P>
   If you're turned onto L.A.'s coolest station _ Groove 103.1 _
you've heard local dance-pop outfit Pure Sugar's hits, ``Hands to
Heaven'' and the appropriately titled ``Delicious.'' Although
``Pure Sugar'' (Geffen), starring the heartfelt vocals of onetime
club kid Jennifer Starr, offers more than disco and synth-r&AMP;b
sounds, there's enough of it to keep any raver happy. No matter
what your tastes, you'll have to admit ``Delicious,'' based on a
chunk of A Taste of Honey's 1978 smash ``Boogie Oogie Oogie,'' is
pure exhilaration. 3 Stars. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
CHUCHO VALDES/``Bele Bele en la Habana''
</P>
<P>
   Latin-jazz trailblazer Valdes here inserts his Afro-Cuban piano
style into a selection of straight-ahead jazz material. Leading an
imaginative and energetic trio of young Havana-based players,
composer-pianist Valdes offers sizzling dance tracks and lush
ballads, touching on a variety of indigenous Cuban rhythms in the
process. ``Bele Bele en la Habana'' (Blue Note) lives up to its
translation _ ``Something's Happening in Havana.'' 3{ Stars. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
GRACE JONES/``Private Life: The Compass Point Sessions''
</P>
<P>
   At last comes a twin-CD set focusing on some of the best early
'80s dance music of all. That would be the Jones' stylish sessions
with the Compass Point All-Stars led by the dynamic reggae rhythm
section of drummer Sly Dunbar and bassist Robbie Shakespeare,
including keyboardist Wally Badarou and guitarists Barry Reynolds
and Mickey ``Mao'' Chung. ``Private Life: The Compass Point
Sessions'' (Island) explores three albums: ``Warm Leatherette,''
``Nightclubbing'' and ``Living My Life,'' offering hits from each,
two previously unreleased tunes, four previously unheard versions
of hits and 16 numbers appearing on CD for the first time. The
stuff still holds up. 3{ Stars. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
SHIRLEY BROWN/``The Soul of a Woman''
</P>
<P>
   A mess of r&AMP;b and gospel tunes get the going over from Southern
soul diva Brown, owner of some of the biggest pipes since Ann
Peebles or Dorothy Love Coates. ``The Soul of a Woman'' (Malaco),
recorded in Mississippi, Alabama and Tennessee with the real guys
(guitarist Jimmy Johnson, bassist David Hood, drummer Roger Hawkins
and the Muscle Shoals Horns), is just that _ a glimpse inside the
heart and soul of a genuine dear. Best tracks here include the sly
Millie Jackson-esque ``I Caught You With Your Pants Down'' and the
rousing gospel of ``He Looked Beyond My Faults.'' 3 Stars. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
DAVE ALVIN/``Blackjack David''
</P>
<P>
   Alvin's band usually includes some of the finest roots musicians
on the scene. His latest album, ``Blackjack David'' (HighTone),
produced by country guitar mainstay Greg Leisz and named after the
traditional folk tune that opens the disc, is also Alvin's first
collection of mostly new material in some time. It's a doozy,
putting forward many of this brilliant songwriter's most evocative
songs _ ``Abilene,'' ``New Highway,'' ``The Way You Say Goodbye''
and ``From a Kitchen Table,'' among them. If you're a fan of
first-rate writing or just want to check up on some top-notch roots
music, this one's for you. 4 Stars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-98 1419EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980702.0109 </DOCNO>
