<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 14:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7778 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-CELLUCCI-ANALYSIS-     07-02 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-CELLUCCI-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEACHER STANDARDS PUT CELLUCCI CAMPAIGN TO THE TEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK PHILLIPS AND SCOT LEHIGH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ When the Board of Education finished voting Wednesday,
Acting Governor Paul Cellucci finally had the tougher
teacher-testing policy he wanted, but the victory came at a heavy
political price.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say Cellucci's zig-zagging on the pivotal issue has not
only cast doubt on his leadership abilities, but has also helped
undercut his standing as a strong favorite in the governor's race.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters, Cellucci shrugged off criticism that has
dogged him since he first acquiesced in the board's decision to
water down teacher-certification standards, then flip-flopped to
demand tougher requirements.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not concerned about political consequences,'' he said.
``I am concerned with doing the right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   But Cellucci's fumbling of the testing issue, coming after a
series of missteps on lesser matters, has helped reshape a
governor's race in which he was once a heavy favorite. Adding to
that perception is a new University of Massachusetts poll showing
that two of Cellucci's Democratic opponents have drawn almost even
with him in the public's estimation.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's controversy capped a month in which Cellucci has
repeatedly been caught off-guard or has seemed unwilling to address
some fundamental state policy issues. The going has gotten so rocky
that long-time friends increasingly doubt the abilities of his
inner circle of advisers.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the administration, some of the best and the brightest
officials bridle under an intellectual lockdown that has left the
year barren of important policy initiatives. Others fret that the
lack of action has caused much of Cellucci's cabinet to fade almost
to anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, one source says doubts have grown so pronounced that
even Argeo R. Cellucci, the acting governor's father, has privately
complained that his son's handlers ``are not letting Paul be
Paul.''
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci himself, other sources say, may be growing frustrated
and is ready to rely more on his own instincts than the advice of
chief of staff Virginia Buckingham and campaign manager Rob Gray,
who are pushing him to run a campaign of low-key conflict
avoidance.
</P>
<P>
   The critics say that the current strategy has made Cellucci,
despite the political knowledge that comes of years on Beacon Hill,
seem less a take-charge chief executive than a cautious caretaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paul's a little angry,'' said one GOP source. ``It's clear he
is going to use own instincts more.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray Howell, a Cellucci's political consultant, scoffed at the
idea that Buckingham and Gray are botching the acting governor's
re-election effort. Howell particularly tried to craft the flap
over the teacher-testing standards as a ``big win'' for the acting
governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the other candidates have been reduced to holding press
conferences and criticizing the governor, but Paul Cellucci dug in,
got the voters, and turned the board around,'' Howell said. ``While
everyone was on the sidelines booing, he got the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   But other more neutral political analysts say Cellucci has
squandered his months as acting governor instead of developing a
strong image with voters and that the teacher testing controversy
only compounded his problems.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Domke, a Republican consultant, said Cellucci's penchant
for avoiding risks has made him vulnerable because he has not
connected with the public in a way that has earned him a deeply
rooted respect or popularity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now he is viewed as just another politician who has to dodge
the incoming barbs,'' Domke said. ``In politics, the biggest risk
is not taking risks. Part of Bill Weld's popularity is he took
risks.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly Cellucci's handling of the whole teacher testing
fiasco suggests a candidate and an administration not quite ready
for prime time.
</P>
<P>
   Last January, establishing his election-year themes in his State
of the State speech, Cellucci firmly declared that he would stand
his ground against any attempt to water down educational standards.
</P>
<P>
   Saying he knew student failure rates would create pressure to
lower standards, Cellucci vowed: ``But I will stand firm. I will
not lower the standards. I will not let mediocrity be the standards
for our schools.''
</P>
<P>
   But when the Board of Education did just that on teacher
standards by voting to lower the passing grade prospective teachers
must achieve to be certified, Cellucci seemed to have forgotten his
January vow.
</P>
<P>
   Although he wouldn't have voted that way himself, Cellucci said,
he couldn't reverse the vote. ``The decision has been made,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   It was only after three days reflection that Cellucci decided he
would try to change the vote.
</P>
<P>
   And despite the acting governor's repeated promises to insist on
high educational standards, several board members said Wednesday he
made no attempt to lobby them before the board's vote to lower the
passing grade for prospective teachers. Nor, as he himself conceded
Wednesday, did the Acting Governor talk to Frank Haydu, the interim
commissioner of education.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the controversy broke, there was reason to doubt the
Rose Garden strategy of avoiding contentious issues and eschewing
big ideas in favor of low-key tours parcelling out grants on
regional tours.
</P>
<P>
   The same period has seen him duck questions about University of
Massachusetts President William Bulger, contradict himself on the
proposed tobacco settlement, and make a blatantly political attempt
to avoid taking a position on a ballot question to eliminate
turnpike tolls.
</P>
<P>
   But it's the controversy over teacher testing, which has
dominated headlines and newscasts for a week, that really
crystallized those doubts. The only good news, one Cellucci adviser
said, was that the episode had jolted a campaign and an
administration grown cautious and complacent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a wakeup call,'' this person said. ``Hey, we're
in a race here. We need to be more diligent and not get behind the
curve.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
