<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 14:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7786 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROFILE-KENNEDY-2ND &LR;  &UR;      07-02 1405
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROFILE-KENNEDY-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 (l and i coding)  
 DUBLIN: ... than hurt.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   But ``it didn't faze me,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   She smiles when asked if she is hard to work for.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know. I think I'm fairly demanding, probably. You have
to feel that when you're appointed to a job you have to do the
job.''
</P>
<P>
   She pauses for a moment, then adds, ``The reprimand part was
unfortunate.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
A natural politician
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Men are jealous of her, full stop,'' said Mary O'Rourke, the
Irish Cabinet minister for trade. ``Jean came here without a
reputation in politics, but she practiced the art of politics
better than her male predecessors.''
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, Adams is partial to her. The former IRA leader turned
politician has brought the Irish republican movement into the
political mainstream. He credits Kennedy Smith with assisting in
that process.
</P>
<P>
   ``She believes in dialogue, in creating the conditions that lead
to dialogue,'' Adams said.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy Smith says her ``open house'' policy was simply
following White House policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president has said the United States will help those who
take risks for peace, and I agree wholeheartedly with that
philosophy,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   She took risks herself. She backed the Adams visa long before
Clinton did. Attorney General Janet Reno and then Secretary of
State Warren Christopher were toeing the British line, that Adams
was an unreconstructed terrorist, that he needed to denounce
terrorism and distance himself from the IRA. Kennedy Smith accepted
that for Adams to do so would be political, if not literal,
suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy Smith's friends, among them the author Tim Pat Coogan
and the New York publisher Niall O'Dowd, who were both privy to
Sinn Fein strategy, told her that the IRA was considering a
cease-fire. But the IRA did not trust the British government, and
wanted the American government to broker the peace process. John
Hume, the leader of moderate nationalism in Northern Ireland, and
Albert Reynolds, then the Irish prime minister, told her they
thought letting Adams into the United States could dramatically
change the political climate and set in motion events that could
lead to a cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to prove that politics worked, worked better than
violence and produced better results,'' said Reynolds. ``Getting a
visa for Gerry Adams against all the opposition from London would
show the republican leadership and nationalists that politics and
the democratic system does work.''
</P>
<P>
   Ted Kennedy said his sister convinced him to back the visa for
Adams, and to lobby Clinton for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I listen to my big sister,'' Kennedy explained, only
half-jokingly.
</P>
<P>
   After Clinton let Adams in, the resulting howls from the British
Establishment convinced the IRA that it was a bigger deal than it
really was.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy Smith went even further in August 1994, when the IRA's
cease-fire was being held up because Sinn Fein wanted Joe Cahill,
the 78-year-old former IRA chief of staff, to brief American
supporters. Cahill had been convicted of killing a policeman in
1942, and the White House would have to intervene to let him into
the United States. Compounding the problem was the timing. Both
Washington and Dublin are virtually shut down during the last week
of August.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy Smith was on vacation in France when she learned about
the holdup. She tracked down Nancy Soderberg, then the National
Security Council director, who was on vacation in Madrid. A few
days later, she found Soderberg again, this time in Los Angeles,
and repeated her appeal. Sensing that Soderberg was unconvinced,
Kennedy Smith called Reynolds on a boat in the Mediterranean and
asked him to call Soderberg.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's 25 percent Irish. Tell her to use it,'' Kennedy Smith
told him.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy Smith didn't leave anything to chance. She disturbed one
more vacation, calling President Clinton on Martha's Vineyard.
</P>
<P>
   Cahill got in and the cease-fire was declared 24 hours later.
</P>
<P>
   Even now, when Soderberg gets an unexpected phone call in a
strange place, she half-thinks it's Jean Kennedy Smith. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Bonds of bereavement
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While such diplomatic persistence impressed many, it did little
to change the perception among Protestants in Northern Ireland that
the Kennedys in general, and Jean Kennedy Smith in particular, are
blatantly pro-nationalist. Still, the leaders of loyalist groups,
which in the past killed Catholics in an attempt to weaken support
for the IRA, are among those who regularly attended Kennedy Smith's
soirees.
</P>
<P>
   Among her fans is Billy Hutchinson, a leader of the Progressive
Unionist Party, the political wing of the Ulster Volunteer Force,
for which he served 15 years in prison for killing two Catholics.
Hutchinson said his party sees her as a nationalist, but admires
her for treating them with respect.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since the IRA and the main loyalist paramilitary groups
called their cease-fires in 1994, it has been the representatives
of the extremists who have been most willing to compromise. It is
their people, after all, who do the bulk of the killing, dying, and
prison time. In Kennedy Smith, they found someone who understood
both the weight of suffering and the promise of politics.
</P>
<P>
   Looking out over the Dublin Mountains in the distance, Jean
Kennedy Smith acknowledges that the assassinations of her brothers
have had a profound effect on her.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first came here, I went to Belfast for a reception. We
saw in the news that a woman's husband had been shot. I said I
wanted to stop by and see her. So we did. We just took a long walk,
the woman and I, and she told me the story of how it happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the men who killed her husband ran out of the house, her
two children ran out after them, screaming, `You bastards!' She was
so afraid that they'd shoot her kids, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was extemely brave, and I was very moved. She opened up to
me, because I think she saw me as someone who's been through it. I
think she felt that we had some bond there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was interesting to see how people came to their positions.
It's understandable, there was so much violence. I experienced that
in my own family. I think they appreciated the fact that I could
understand it.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
An Irish heritage
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The extended family is living here vicariously. Even those long
dead are everywhere, in photographs and paintings. Rose's photo is
on a radiator. Bobby and Jack are framed together on a side table.
Joseph Kennedy Sr. and three of his four sons, Jack, Bobby, and
Ted, are engraved into a decanter that rests, empty, on another
table.
</P>
<P>
   There is an oil portrait of Joe Sr. in the main foyer. A
portrait of Jack, looking pensive, stares across at his father, his
mother's portrait just beneath him. There is a Jamie Wyeth of the
ambassador hanging in one of the reception rooms. In the hush of an
afternoon, all of these Kennedy eyes are unnerving.
</P>
<P>
   Because they are Irish, the Kennedys are obsessed with history
and anniversaries. Kennedy Smith took up her Dublin post 30 years
to the day that she arrived in Ireland with her brother, Jack. She
carried with her a photograph of her standing with President
Clinton after he nominated her. Ted wrote on the back: ``For Jean,
who is going back in the springtime.''
</P>
<P>
   Before she returns to New York, she will end her official duties
Sunday as she began them, by going back to New Ross, in Wexford,
149 years after her great-grandfather Patrick Kennedy boarded a
ship there to escape the potato famine and begin a new life in
Boston. She will travel just a bit outside New Ross, to a place
called Dunganston, to the Kennedy homestead. She goes there, on
occasion, to smell the air, to wonder what would have happened if
her great-grandfather had not got on that boat.
</P>
<P>
   ``My great-grandfather's youngest brother never left,'' she
says. ``And his great-grandson, Pat Kennedy, is a farmer in
Wexford. I visit him and we talk. We always have a chuckle about
what would have happened if his great-grandfather had gone over,
and how life would have been so different.''
</P>
<P>
   Some have suggested Jean Kennedy Smith was driven by a desire to
complete some unfinished family business. She isn't so sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was part of the tide,'' she says, glancing at a photo of her
brother, the dead president. ``I really didn't think of it as a
Kennedy thing. I thought of it as a moment. A moment in history.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
