<HEADER>
A7790 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TITANIC-ARTIFACTS-ART     07-02 1096
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TITANIC-ARTIFACTS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DREDGING UP TITANIC'S MEMORIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ARNOLD  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Sometime early on the morning of April 15, 1912, a white
porcelain teacup trimmed with 22-carat gold followed the Titanic to
the ocean floor. It settled, right-side up, on a crushed,
building-sized boiler that had been stoked by laborers, joining for
eternity symbols of the rich and the working class in a union too
deep for tampering.
</P>
<P>
   Or so it seemed when the cup was photographed by the Woods Hole
Oceanographic Institution, which located the wreck in 1985 and,
honoring its sanctity, took away only pictures.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the 2 1/2-mile-deep wreck has been visited 132
times, 96 of them under the auspices of George Tulloch, a
Connecticut entrepreneur whose exhibit, ``Titanic _ The Artifact
Exhibition,'' opened July 1 in a tent opposite the World Trade
Center in downtown Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Tulloch and associates have corralled about 5,000 items from the
wreck. Critics, including a Titanic historian, call Tulloch a grave
robber who has cheapened the Titanic by disturbing it for profit.
Admirers call him a hero who has guaranteed the artifacts will be
around for centuries, silently screaming of the thoughtlessness
that led to humankind's most spectacular maritime folly.
</P>
<P>
   ``If, today, someone were to break off a piece of Plymouth Rock,
would the Museum of Fine Arts rush to display it?'' asked Don
Lynch, a Titanic historian and author who is vice president of the
Springfield-based Titanic Historical Society. ``What a shame that
Eastern Massachusetts, which has figured so prominently in our
nation's history, has so little regard for it by displaying these
artifacts.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Titanic historian takes the opposing camp's view.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been unethical not to salvage these artifacts,
and to have allowed the acidic sands to continue destroying them,''
said Charles Haas, a New Jersey teacher who has written three books
about the Titanic. ``Wait too long, and the pieces will be
destroyed. Tell me: Just when does history begin? When is it proper
to collect the evidence of a major human event?''
</P>
<P>
   The teacup, dramatically photographed by Dr. Robert D. Ballard
in ``The Discovery of the Titanic,'' is not in the exhibit. In
fact, its whereabouts today are in dispute. Critics suspect it was
knocked from its deep sea perch by all the robots plying the wreck
for the past nine years. To them, its disappearance represents
everything that is wrong with excavating a ship for profit.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Paul Louden Brown, a Titanic Historical Society officer who
lives in Kent, England, has accused Tulloch of ``looting it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For 80 years, it nestled undisturbed, testament to an event
that caught ordinary people in an extraordinary moment of time,''
Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Tulloch adamantly denies touching the cup, saying it remains
where it has always been.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what I care about? Making this exhibit so tasteful,
so devastatingly emotional that no one ever, ever ignores the kind
of warnings Captain (Edward J.) Smith ignored when he speeded into
that iceberg field,'' said Tulloch, who is 53.
</P>
<P>
   One thing is clear: It is not smooth sailing through the ethical
reefs of a disaster that killed more than 1,500 people at a site
where the US Coast Guard continues to drop a commemorative wreath
annually. Is ``Titanic _ The Artifact Exhibition,'' a legend to
life or an insult to the dead? When the exhibit opened in London in
1994, it was the first time artifacts from the sunken ship had ever
been displayed.
</P>
<P>
   The appropriateness of the display is an issue for James
Delgado, a maritime archeologist who has written extensively on the
pitfalls of salvaging shipwrecks for profit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most important is that the audience ask the question,'' said
Delgado, executive director of the Vancouver Maritime Museum.
``This exhibit may end up teaching you most about yourself.'' He
praised the careful conservation and archeological standards
maintained by Tulloch's crews.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston show (9 a.m.-6 p.m. Sun.-Thurs, 9 a.m.-8 p.m.
Fri.-Sat.) will be the fifth for an exhibit that has traveled
through London, Hamburg, St. Petersburg, Fla., and Memphis. The
show has been popular enough to force an extension of exhibition
hours and dates in those cities, curators said.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston show features 500 artifacts, including sheet music,
the ship's telegraph (the device that linked the bridge to the
engine room), and personal effects such as a man's suit and china,
to name a few.
</P>
<P>
   A string of victories in Admiralty Court has granted Tulloch's
RMS Titanic Inc. exclusive salvaging rights to the wreck. He
essentially has vowed not to sell artifacts, and envisions storing
the collection, to which he adds annually, in its own museum
someday.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I die it will be together,'' Tulloch said of the
collection during a break in exhibition construction the other day.
</P>
<P>
   But as remnants of the Titanic literally surface _ Tulloch hopes
to bring the bow up this summer _ vestiges of the disaster's
aftermath, captured in photographs such as the teacup, disappear
below. And this, said Louden Brown, cheapens the Titanic story.
</P>
<P>
   ``This ship is still within the memory of the five living
survivors,'' he said. ``Shall I go collect and display artifacts
from the TWA 800 disaster or the Challenger explosion? Would this
be right? Who would pay, other than the ghouls?''
</P>
<P>
   And he added: ``There's nothing historically relevant in the
Titanic exhibit. We see a smoking pipe. So what have we learned?
That Edwardians smoked?''
</P>
<P>
   To such criticism, Tulloch cites such memorials as the Holocaust
Museum in Washington, which charges admission to illustrate with
actual artifacts the horror and bravery of humans in distress. No
human remains have been confirmed in the Titanic wreckage;
salvagers surmise the dead drifted away from the ship.
</P>
<P>
   Haas, the schoolteacher, said an artifact does not have to be
unique to be historically important. For example, he said he
recently viewed in the exhibit a pair of eyeglasses, nail clippers,
a paperback book with a turned-down page, and pocket change.
</P>
<P>
   ``By themselves, they didn't mean much. But consider that they
were in the possession of Abe Lincoln when he was shot,'' Haas
said. ``That's how artifacts teach us about an event, and about
ourselves.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-98 1429EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980702.0118 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 14:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7794 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-2ND &LR;  &UR; TA     07-02 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 WEST TISBURY, Mass.: ... development rights.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Obtaining Spongberg, one of the country's most respected
horticulturalists, as its first director was a coup. He was asked
to recommend a director and surprised everyone by retiring from his
position as horticultural taxonomist at Harvard's Arnold Arboretum
to take the Vineyard job himself.
</P>
<P>
   The classic shingled caretaker's cottage near the road, once a
17th-century inn on the long trip from Vineyard Haven to Gay Head,
has been transformed into Spongberg's office with conference and
library space.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Visitors center
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At the far end of the property, which includes 20 acres of
gardens and 40 wooded acres, a new entrance with parking for 50
cars has been added, leading to a striking new visitors center
designed by Thompson &AMP; Rose Architects of Cambridge. With the help
of structural engineer Wayne King of Ipswich, it was built on a
shallow foundation using a structural design new to this country.
``They didn't want to hurt the roots of stewartia trees growing
nearby so they actually used a technique from Scandinavia where
frost is a problem,'' said Smith.
</P>
<P>
   The showcase building was affordable, he said, because ``this is
their next national prize winner. We're doing a lot more than
people thought we could at half the cost originally estimated by
one Martha's Vineyard builder.''
</P>
<P>
   The visitors center features a heavy timber construction system
with thick Douglas fir beams tapered like tree trunks. Many large
windows create an airy interior (it won't have to be heated in the
winter). You feel the outdoors when you're indoors.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby is a designated picnic area and another handsome building
containing the Vineyard's most elegant public restrooms. ``We're
very excited about it. They're the only public bathrooms on that
side of the island. Our client wanted to make beautiful bathrooms
as a gift to the people who come to the Vineyard,'' said Maryann
Thompson, who with her partner, Charles Rose, earned a Young
Architects Citation for design this year from the American
Institute of Architects for integrating a Florida building with its
landscape.
</P>
<P>
   The roofs of both buildings have a shedlike single pitch that
not only kept costs down, but directs rainwater to gutters that
extend 2 feet beyond the edge of each building to make waterfalls.
Each drains into a catch basin, which creates a small pool for a
garden of water-loving plants designed by Van Valkenburgh
Associates of Cambridge. Benches under the overhanging roofs allow
visitors to sit outside and enjoy the waterfalls when it rains.
</P>
<P>
   A large barn long used by barn owls is also being restored to
provide classroom and exhibition space. Vineyarder Bruce Weatherbee
is doing the construction.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Educational role
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Smith envisions an arboretum dedicated to science and education
that hosts symposiums and uses plants to introduce scientific
methodology to local elementary school students. (No weddings, he
said.)
</P>
<P>
   Docents will provide tours throughout the season. Smith also
commissioned a video of Hill leading a personal tour through the
collection, which she will now be able to do in perpetuity as she
takes her place in island lore as one of the Vineyard's defining
individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Touring the garden with Hill, whether in person or via video, is
a memorable experience. She'll point out each of the new azaleas
she named for her family members, immortalizing them, too, in a
way. Her husband, the late Julian Hill, a scientist who worked on
the research team that developed nylon for Du Pont, gave her a hard
time about this when she tried to name an azalea after him. ``He
said he didn't like azaleas. He said he wanted a white flower, a
big white flower. So I named my biggest white flower after him,''
she said, peering into a 15-inch white chalice on a large tree she
named Magnolia macrophylla cultivar Julian Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Any tour in Hill's trademark yellow golf cart includes a spin
down the 240-foot allee of Kousa dogwoods, through the European
hornbeam ``tunnel of love,'' and into the 385-foot-long fenced
enclosure her family nicknamed The Playpen because of all the time
she spent there. It contains many of her choicest azaleas,
including the North Tisbury series of flat ground-cover evergreen
azaleas, one of which is the aptly named Pink Pancake, grown from
seeds sent by a horticulturalist she met in Japan. ``I saw that
they had low azaleas growing around the temples, which we'd never
seen in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Change and continuity
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hill thrives on her garden's mix of change and continuity. The
passing seasons and her detailed computer records all provide a
framework for observing discoveries which, if you're growing trees
from seed, come slowly, but are no less thrilling for that.
</P>
<P>
   With lifetime rights to the converted barn that is her
summerhouse, she is planning for the future, and enjoying the
surprises that each day in her garden brings.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's my mother's pecan tree,'' she said, pointing to a
large specimen with long, peculiar catkins. ``She planted it in
1936 and this is the first time it's ever blossomed.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (The Polly Hill Arboretum is open 7 a.m. to 7 p.m. from Memorial
Day to Columbus Day, and from dawn to dusk the rest of the year.
Requested donation is $5. Call 508-693-9426 for details.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
