<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DANGER A SKIP AWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Skip Away ducked the famous one-two punch thrown by opposing
trainer Richard Mandella, the same punch that knocked out Cigar's
16-race winning streak, and went on to capture the $1 million
Hollywood Gold Cup last Sunday in stellar fashion.
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of the Breeders' Cup, Mandella had saddled
the winner of the previous six $1 million races in California. He
is noted for sending out entries from his powerful stable of
handicap runners, many of them talented horses bred in South
America. In 1996, Mandella stopped Cigar's record run, which had
tied that of Citation as the best in North America during the
modern era, in the Pacific Classic at Del Mar by sending out
speedball Siphon to set a sizzling pace and closer Dare and Go to
come along and pick up the pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Mandella tried the same thing Sunday, as Gentlemen (from
Argentina) stalked Skip Away's every step before tiring at the
eighth pole, even as closer Puerto Madero (from Chile) made a
fierce charge up the rail. Unlike Cigar, however, Skip Away (off at
2-5, $2.80 to win) had more than enough left to hold off Puerto
Madero and prevail by a length and three-quarters in the time of
2:00 for the mile and one-quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The victory was the seventh straight for Skip Away, five of
which have come this year. The $600,000 winner's purse raised the
big gray's career earnings to $8,906,360 in his hot pursuit of
Cigar's North American record of $9,999,815. Named champion
3-year-old in 1996 and handicap champion last year, Skip Away has a
career mark of 34-16-10-5, not bad for a $30,000 purchase as a
2-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   It was in Skip Away's favor that he was ridden by Jerry Bailey,
who also rode Cigar. Bailey was the victim in the ending of the
Cigar streak. He went after Siphon far too early and far too fast,
and Cigar had nothing left when Dare and Go, who was less than a
standout, offered his surprisingly strong rally. This time, Bailey
sat chilly and let Gentlemen and Gary Stevens come right to the
pacesetting Skip Away entering the far turn. They raced stride for
stride into the stretch and, because Bailey never unduly urged Skip
Away, he finished up well despite the menacing move by Puerto
Madero and Kent Desormeaux.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always said that if they want to run with him they are in
trouble,'' said Bailey. ``He'll put them away. I knew the setup
from the start. Gentlemen was supposed to soften him up and Puerto
Madero was supposed to come and get him. But he's too much horse.
He's a great horse; there's no quit in him.''
</P>
<P>
   Sonny Hine, who trains Skip Away for his wife, Carolyn, may
start him next in the $1 million Pacific Classic at Del Mar Aug.
15, where he could possibly face last year's 3-year-old champion
Silver Charm, as well as the Mandella duo. However, Skip Away has
had bothersome feet since running away during a gallop at Belmont
Park prior to the Gold Cup, which puts the Pacific Classic in
question.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Winning `Touch'
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Touch Gold, who won the Belmont Stakes and the Haskell
Invitational at Monmouth in 1997 before a persistent quarter crack
forced him to the sidelines after poor performances in the Pegasus
at Meadowlands and the Breeders' Cup, made a terrific 1998 debut
last Sunday, winning a 1-mile allowance race at Churchill Downs in
1:34, one tick off the track record.
</P>
<P>
   Off at 1-5 ($2.40 to win), the talented son of Deputy Minister
prevailed by nearly 3 lengths under a patently patient ride by  &UR; Pat
Day &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   ``He ran very fast and he got a lot out of it,'' said trainer
 &UR; Pat Byrne &LR; , who took over the conditioning of Touch Gold from
 &UR; David Hofmans &LR;  when he became private trainer for owner  &UR; Frank
Stronach  &LR; in December. ``He cooled out really well and we're happy
with that. The Whitney (at Saratoga Aug. 8) will be his next likely
start. If he has an unbeaten campaign, he has a great shot at Horse
of the Year.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Filly for the field?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There is a chance that Rockingham Park will attract a top grass
filly, Tresoriere, to Sunday's $75,000 Breeders' Cup Handicap,
which is run at a mile and one-16th.
</P>
<P>
   Tresoriere is trained by  &UR; Christophe Clement &LR; , who saddled
Statesmanship to victory in the $200,000 New Hampshire Sweeps June
20. She has been co-highweighted at 119 pounds, along with
stablemate Heaven's Command, among the 28 nominees. Tresoriere, a
daughter of Lyuphard, can really run. She took both the Grade III
Gallorette Handicap at Pimlico and the Moseley Handicap at Suffolk
last month and is 3 for 4 with a second on the year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
