<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980702.0121 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 14:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7802 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROFILE-KENNEDY-ART-B     07-02 1485
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROFILE-KENNEDY-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A KENNEDY LEAVES HER MARK ON IRELAND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)  
 (l and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBLIN _ Dead Kennedys, their images, their spirits, are
everywhere in this grand Georgian house that Jean Kennedy Smith has
called home for five years. They don't haunt the place as much as
inform it with a purpose.
</P>
<P>
   That purpose is served now, and so Jean Kennedy Smith, the
longest-serving American ambassador to Ireland, is going home.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-five years ago, she stood on these very grounds, in the
massive expanse they call the Phoenix Park, the shy sister of the
most powerful man in the world. She was standing here when John F.
Kennedy promised to return in the springtime. She was standing next
to her brother Jack when he looked around and wistfully suggested
he would like to live here as ambassador.
</P>
<P>
   But because of Dallas there couldn't be Dublin. It was left to
his little sister to return in the spring of 1993, to live in this
house as ambassador, to see through the unfinished business of
Ireland, which has always been, to one degree or another, the
unfinished business of the Kennedys.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, 70-year-old Jean Kennedy Smith will end one of the
most improbable, controversial, and ultimately successful
diplomatic careers in recent memory.
</P>
<P>
   Once a sleepy outpost for sleepy men, the US Embassy in
Ballsbridge, an ugly, circular granite building that looks like a
block of cheese, became a nerve center for White House foreign
policy on her watch. Britain's role as America's staunchest ally
became less important to a White House occupied by the first
president in a half-century whose world view was not shaped by
World War II. Under Bill Clinton, Washington abandoned its
hands-off policy in Northern Ireland, injecting itself into the
conflict, and treating Dublin's view of the problem as equally
valid as London's. Clinton's precedent-breaking foreign policy was
enthusiastically encouraged by his ambassador in Dublin.
</P>
<P>
   A diplomatic neophyte and a politician only by osmosis, Jean
Kennedy Smith eschewed protocol and went with her gut, pushing for
things that career diplomats considered too controversial _ among
them a visa for Gerry Adams, the leader of Sinn Fein, the Irish
Republican Army's political wing, so he could enter the United
States in 1994 while the IRA was still killing people. Her disdain
for protocol rubbed many traditionalists the wrong way.
</P>
<P>
   Neil Jordan, the filmmaker who is among the eclectic mix at her
frequent dinner parties, gave her a cameo appearance in his film
``Michael Collins.'' Some at the State Department rolled their
eyes, thinking such a stunt was beneath the dignity of a sitting
ambassador.
</P>
<P>
   When the Irish president, Mary McAleese, was getting flak for
breaking Catholic canon law by taking communion in an Anglican
church to promote ecumenism, Kennedy Smith showed some sisterly
solidarity by going out and doing the same. Again, the
traditionalists at Foggy Bottom shook their heads.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy Smith treated dissent from her staff as disloyalty. She
punished two career diplomats who questioned her judgment on the
Adams visa, a break with protocol for which she was reprimanded by
the State Department. Raymond Seitz, the former US ambassador to
Britain recently used his memoirs to slam her as shallow, naive,
and ``an ardent IRA apologist.''
</P>
<P>
   What may bother her critics most is that Jean Kennedy Smith got
results. She has left bruised egos and toes in her wake. But she
has played a prominent role in one of Bill Clinton's few foreign
policy success stories. She will leave her post having seen the
Northern Ireland political settlement overwhelmingly approved by
people throughout the island.
</P>
<P>
   As democratic politics gradually phase out terrorism in Ireland,
she has earned a mention in the history books for her own actions,
not those of her brothers. For someone who lived most of her life
in the shadow of powerful men, she has stepped out into the light
and, critics be damned, got the job done.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in her library, the soft light of a soft Irish day
filtering across a face that looks at this angle so much like her
brother Bobby, dead these 30 years, Jean Kennedy Smith folds her
arms across her chest. She is sliding her pumps on and off, smiling
that Cheshire cat smile, when asked about a tenure marked by both
diplomatic controversy and diplomatic triumph.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel I was very fortunate to be in the position to do
something positive, to make a contribution to change. It gave me
terrific satisfaction,'' she says. ``It wasn't any hardship for
me.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
From the Kennedy mold
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hardship, however, is no stranger to Jean Kennedy. Despite
having grown up rich and privileged, there was always a hint of
melancholy about her. Being on the bottom rung of a big, important
family can be a lonely place. She and Teddy were the youngest of
nine kids, she four years older than he.
</P>
<P>
   She has not had an easy life. Three of her four brothers died
young and violently. Her husband, Stephen Smith, who died in 1990,
was part of the Kennedy machine and was often on the road. She
raised four children. One of her daughters, Kym, married a Dublin
bartender a few years ago in what was a Dublin society event. The
marriage didn't last. One of her sons, William, was acquitted of
rape in a highly publicized 1991 trial that was hardly a
vindication of Kennedy family get-togethers.
</P>
<P>
   But through it all, there was a dogged determination about her,
an ability to ride out stormy waters. In that respect, she is often
compared to her sister-in-law, Ethel. It was Jean who fixed Bobby
up with Ethel, Jean who introduced Jackie to Jack, and Joan to Ted.
More than an aunt to most of her nieces and nephews, Jean is
literally the matchmaker who ensured their births.
</P>
<P>
   At her dinner parties, however, she breaks couples up, refusing
to seat them next to each other, or even at the same table.
Instead, she invites people of different backgrounds and political
persuasions then deliberately sits them next to or near each other.
She prides herself on prodding those with different viewpoints to
share and defend them.
</P>
<P>
   At a recent soiree, Liz Mansergh and Patricia Walsh sat across
from each other, debating the merits of the settlement in Northern
Ireland. Mansergh, whose husband, Martin, is the Irish government's
top Northern Ireland strategist, was understandably optimistic.
Walsh, a clinical psychologist, was more cynical, viewing the North
as a hopelessly violent and bigoted place.
</P>
<P>
   Both women, however, agreed on one thing: They love Jean Kennedy
Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she has an extraordinary talent for getting people of
different backgrounds together and getting them to talk,'' said
Mansergh.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh is an unabashed fan because of the Very Special Arts
program for the mentally disabled, which Kennedy Smith founded. It
is now in 55 countries, including Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   It is perhaps telling that women are among Kennedy Smith's
staunchest admirers, and men among her most vituperative critics.
</P>
<P>
   Seitz, US ambassador to Britain from 1991 to 1994, says she got
the job because it ``had always been a plaything for American
presidents who wanted to score a point or two with the
Irish-American electorate.''
</P>
<P>
   In his memoir, ``Over Here,'' Seitz was less than diplomatic:
</P>
<P>
   ``Jean Kennedy Smith, who distrusted her own staff and penalized
them for their dissent, became a promotion agent for Adams. Too
shallow to understand the past and too naive to anticipate the
future, she was an ardent IRA apologist.''
</P>
<P>
   Historically, Washington's ambassador to the Court of St. James
has been the most influential in the White House. But Seitz
increasingly found his counsel on Northern Ireland, a situation he
called ``an issue without a resolution,'' being ignored. Clinton,
who wanted to help break the cycle of violence and reap the
political benefits, was more receptive to his Dublin ambassador,
who told him that he could help change the political dynamic.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Seitz's influence was eclipsed by a woman who as an
11-year-old lived at 14 Prince's Gate, the palatial US ambassador's
house in London that Seitz so adores, by the daughter of one of his
predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   Seitz accused Kennedy Smith of ``clientitis,'' a serious offense
in diplomatic service marked by identifying more with the interests
of the country where you are stationed than the one for which you
work.
</P>
<P>
   Given that Seitz is an unabashed Anglophile who now lives in
England, many wrote his criticism off as sour grapes. Some friends
suggest Kennedy Smith was stung by his attack. But she professes
more bewilderment than hurt.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
