<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-GROUND-COVERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR GROUND COVERS, FORM FOLLOWS FUNCTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE HATCH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ajuga, pachysandra, and vinca are well-known ground covers, all
evergreen perennials. Cotoneaster, euonymus, and juniper also can
be ground covers, certain kinds being low-growing evergreen shrubs.
Day lilies, hostas, ornamental grasses, heaths and heathers _
myriad plants qualify as ground covers.
</P>
<P>
   So what makes one juniper a spreading welcome mat and another a
landscape specimen?
</P>
<P>
   Function and structure.
</P>
<P>
   Ground covers generally are planted to cover the ground in a
solid mass of foliage, reducing maintenance and creating attractive
textures and patterns. More specific functions include preventing
erosion on slopes, hiding the dying foliage of bulbs, providing
cover under ornamental trees and shrubs, and creating recreation
areas from rough playing fields to manicured putting greens.
</P>
<P>
   Plant structure, especially form, determines under what
circumstances a plant is appropriate as a ground cover.
</P>
<P>
   Metasequoias, or dawn redwoods, like things dampish, so mine had
to be moved from the front lawn to a depression. But since it
ultimately may reach 100 feet in height, it cannot be used as a
ground cover unless viewed from a substantial distance.
</P>
<P>
   Thyme, on the other hand, some kinds of which barely top an
inch, can be simply perfect in sunny spots on the ground or between
paving or among rocks, where I like it.
</P>
<P>
   If there's traffic, say from visiting children or resident
Newfoundland dogs, grass cannot be beat. There's a reason football
can't be played amid gaultheria or ivy. Nothing that can be trod
upon can withstand being trod upon the way grass does.
</P>
<P>
   Yet grass, while tough, requires a lot of maintenance.
Nutrition, disease, predation, soil compaction, a host of issues
affect grass. It must be mowed and watered, aerated if regularly
trampled, ``policed'' and reseeded if carnivorous quadrupeds
frequent it, and religiously sworn at.
</P>
<P>
   My strategy has been to carve garden beds from the lawns,
treating the remainder as grassy pathways (except for the back
lawn, which goes to the dogs, literally).
</P>
<P>
   I also have been removing lawn from around the trees and shrubs
so they do not have to compete with thirsty, hungry grass for
moisture and nutrients.
</P>
<P>
   Under a clump of birches, I have cut a small, round bed and
planted it with Ajuga reptans ``Burgundy Glow,'' which has bronze
leaves with purple and pink tones. But while some people contend
with ajuga running amok in the lawn and elsewhere, I have struggled
to grow it in the gravelly soil under the birches. In the heat of
July, the thin leaves of this shallow-rooted plant would turn
papery, and the plants died. Finally, I have seen the light and
begun replacing the bad earth with soil loaded with composted
manure.
</P>
<P>
   Poor soil also is responsible for my travails with Phlox
subulata ``Emerald Pink,'' which has bright green, needled leaves
and is smothered in pink flowers in spring. It is in a bed on a
small slope with a mugho pine, goldthread chamaecyparis, and ``Blue
Chip'' juniper. With a few heucheras thrown in _ and they make nice
ground covers, too _ this first attempt at replacing lawn is
supposed to be tied together by the phlox. Again, soil amendments
are the answer.
</P>
<P>
   And that gets to the point that there are no easy answers.
Ground covers may spread and even be invasive in cases, but you
cannot get away with failing to prepare beds. Nor can you fail to
weed and maintain ground covers. They may require less maintenance
than lawns, but not at first.
</P>
<P>
   A related early effort was planting Vinca minor under a nearby
crab apple. It would fill a woodland transition zone with the dark
luster of its evergreen leaves plus the gorgeous light blue flowers
of ``Bowles Variety.'' Of course, that choice is the clumper among
the varieties of vinca vines, so it has not spread as fast as I
thought it would, and I have been busy weeding my vinca these past
years, though less so recently as it finally is filling in.
</P>
<P>
   Sweet woodruff, Galium odorata (formerly Asperula odorata),
which is under the crab apple on the other side of the house, also
has required weeding. This is great stuff. It has small white
flowers in spring and delicate whorled leaves that smell like
new-mown hay when disturbed and often even when left alone. Each
year I put in 12 small plugs, weeded (tall grass still comes up
amid it), and added manure. Last year I began tearing it up by the
roots (a satisfying way of keeping plants in bounds). I buried a
plastic edging strip around it, and it keeps on coming, threatening
the more elegant gingers and ferns growing at its edge.
</P>
<P>
   Waiting for the woodruff to break free so they can duke it out
for the garden championship are several mints I planted in an
edging scheme. The mints were in pots sunk into the earth, but they
escaped into the mulch. I have torn clumps from the ground, laid
them aside, then shoved them rudely into bad soil in another bed,
and they have thrived. Also part of that edging scheme are some
lamiums, with white-splotched leaves. These are lovely, and I keep
a careful eye on them to protect them from their thuggish
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   All of these, by the way, take shade, which is often one of the
requirements of a ground cover.
</P>
<P>
   My latest efforts include Baltic ivy along the north side of a
wall I am building along the road. I envision it climbing over the
wall and being kept in bounds by the head gardener's diligence. (No
gardener ever has enough to do.) I also have loosed pachysandra
under the apple tree, where nothing but weeds grows anyway, and
under the red maple, where it can compete with a bamboo.
</P>
<P>
   Bamboo, now there is a ground cover. Some get 30 feet high, and
it can just tear across a property. Be careful with this guy.
Still, I have a scheme. I'd like to screen my swimming pool from my
neighbor's new shed, built close to the property line, and I'd like
to have it happen quickly. Bamboo grows fast, and it goes well with
water. So maybe I can plant just a little screen of it. Oh, I'll
have to sink some kind of containment into the ground to keep it
from escaping. And I'll need to improve the gravel that lies under
the landscape plastic around the pool. And I suppose I'll have to
weed for a few years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
