<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHE SOWED A FEW SEEDS AND PLANTED A LEGACY 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CAROL STOCKER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST TISBURY, Mass. _ A garden seldom outlives its creator. And
with a hot stock market spurring a vacation-home boom on Martha's
Vineyard, there was every chance that Polly Hill's renowned plant
collection on 60-acre Barnard's Inn Farm here would be cut up into
little pieces.
</P>
<P>
   But things worked out differently, and now the Polly Hill
Arboretum is open to the public.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1958, Hill has been growing and selecting new plant
varieties at her summer residence at 809 State Road. She continues
to do so today. Because of her perseverance in growing trees that
weren't supposed to survive this far north, the garden contains 73
``New England Champion Trees'' designated the largest examples of
their species in the six-state region. Now her collection of 1,700
unusual specimen trees and shrubs will be preserved under the
directorship of Arnold Arboretum curator emeritus Stephen
Spongberg.
</P>
<P>
   The daughter of a Philadelphia stockbroker, Hill began spending
summers at the old sheep farm as a teenager when her mother bought
it in 1927. She was 50 when she herself became its mistress and
took up gardening, planting the stone-wall grid of pastures with
seeds she acquired from around the world. From the start, she used
computers to keep detailed scientific records, a ``live file'' of
successes and a ``dead file'' of plant experiments that failed (of
equal interest to serious horticulturalists).
</P>
<P>
   Hill's goal was simple: to expand the list of plants growing on
Martha's Vineyard. The island seemed to her ``horticulturally
impoverished'' compared to her home state of Delaware.
</P>
<P>
   Her method was to grow everything from seed. Few people have the
patience to grow from seed a tree that may not bloom for 20 years.
Hill did, savoring the plant's struggling infancy as much as its
ornamental payoff at maturity.
</P>
<P>
   Her result was plants such as evergreen Southern magnolias and
camellias that had never been seen growing outdoors on Martha's
Vineyard before.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Natural selection
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How did she do it?
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't realize that most trees and shrubs they buy are
vegetatively propagated,'' explained Spongberg. ``Like Dolly the
sheep, they're identical clones.''
</P>
<P>
   Working without a greenhouse, Hill would start seedlings
outdoors. Most would die. But because they varied genetically and
were not clones, some were more suited for a northern climate and
would survive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The weather chose for me,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In this way over a long span of time, Hill was able to introduce
more than 80 new plant varieties, including a family of 22 North
Tisbury azaleas. She also helped prove that the zonal
characteristics of plants can be dramatically extended if
individuals are grown from seed. ``There are so many factors
besides zones. What we have here on the Vineyard is perfect
drainage and no pollution.''
</P>
<P>
   Her garden became a living catalog of what would grow on
Martha's Vineyard. But there's another reason islanders developed a
fond spot for Hill: In a community where privacy is increasingly
fiercely guarded, her garden had a veritable open-door policy to
lovers of horticulture.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to say, `Come in and behave.'''
</P>
<P>
   Two of the many who enjoyed the garden were artist Joan Smith
and her husband, Dr. David Smith, a low-profile summer resident
celebrated for his discovery of a vaccine that eliminated childhood
meningitis in the United States, where it killed or permanently
impaired 20,000 kids a year. A supporter of conservation causes,
Smith serves on the national board of the Environmental Defense
Fund and recently helped save Moshup Trail in Gay Head from
development.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to the island's conservation groups,'' he recalled,
``and I said, `There's a lot of liquid money around that will soon
close off your options.' And I challenged them to come up with a
list of priority properties to preserve. And they started with
Polly Hill's because it's strategic as well as horticultural. It
connects to other conservation land.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you don't spend much time with Polly Hill without falling
in love with her.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Magic garden
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``He was excited by my records,'' explained the doyenne of the
affinity that grew between her and Smith, to the great relief of
those who had long worried about the magic garden's unsecured
future.
</P>
<P>
   Erect and aristocratic, cheerful and friendly, Hill is a
handsome woman who looks as timeless in her cardigans and sun hats
as the island's stone walls. Her only obvious bow to advanced age
is that she prefers driving to walking long distances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting to know Polly Hill these last few years has been one
of the great joys of our lives,'' said Smith. ``The fact that she
was willing to start everything from seed at the age of 50 in this
era of instant gratification is a special treat. She's the
grandmother everyone wished they had. Bright. Intelligent. And
she's very well organized.''
</P>
<P>
   And so what started as a simple impetus to save open land
evolved into the much more sophisticated effort to preserve a
garden and create an institution.
</P>
<P>
   Other major contributors include the Hill family, horticultural
friends, and the state, which exchanged $300,000 for the land's
development rights.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
