<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRUTH, LIES AND THE LOTTERY
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   Lottery winnings can cause all sorts of vexing interpersonal
problems, as anyone who's been following the news lately must know.
So Dee Dee, our all-purpose advice columnist, is reaching out in
her usual caring way to readers with lottery-related questions.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dear Dee Dee: I would like to join the swelling ranks of those
laying claim to that disputed $21 million lottery ticket. I didn't
actually telephone my bet into Watertown Provisions on Feb. 5, but
I distinctly remember telepathically projecting the winning numbers
to the store's lottery machine during my regular Thursday afternoon
out-of-body experience. So obviously the prize is mine. Although I
wouldn't mind sharing it. How should I go about claiming it? _
Optimistic
</P>
<P>
   Dee Dee has always maintained that honesty is the best policy.
Just tell the truth. Dee Dee thinks that your story is as good as
any of the rest of the tales that have emerged thus far. She thinks
there's no way you can lose.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dear Dee Dee: Recently I was a guest on ``Jerry Springer,'' you
may have seen the show, ``Women Who Win Millions in the Lottery and
Throw it All Away on Some No Good Bum.'' I was one of the no good
bums, the third from the left. I am writing to protest the Springer
show's use of the phrase ``throw away.'' I earned every penny of
Darlene's winnings, and I have a note from my doctor to prove it.
Since the program aired my self-esteem has suffered and I find I
have lost the knack of preying on defenseless rich women. What can
I do? _ Disenfranchised
</P>
<P>
   Until recently you could have petitioned the National Endowment
for the Arts for a grant, but since the NEA is being forced to get
picky about what constitutes performance art, Dee Dee thinks that
you have no choice but to sue Darlene, Jerry Springer, and
everybody connected to the show for defamation of character, loss
of income, pain, suffering, and anything else you or your attorney
can think of. Good luck!
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dear Dee Dee: Since I won the Lottery I worry that no one will
ever love me for myself. Actually, no one ever loved me for myself
before I won, and even now, with $32 million, I have trouble
getting a date. So how can I be sure? _ Pining
</P>
<P>
   Sure of what? That you're a loser? Dee Dee thinks that's pretty
obvious. She advises you to give away all your winnings to
charities and to worthy individuals such as herself who unselfishly
devote their lives to helping others. Only then can you be certain
that money plays no part in your failure to find love.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dear Dee Dee: Several of my multiple personalities jointly hold
a winning lottery ticket and can't agree on which one of them
should claim the money. They argue among themselves continually,
day and night. I am getting no sleep, and neither are the rest of
my personalities. We are just about at the end of our ropes. Help!
_ Exhausted
</P>
<P>
   Try to persuade the winners to see a financial adviser who
specializes in multiple personality issues andwho will arrange for
them to incorporate themselves before they claim the money. Dee Dee
understands that there may be certain tax advantages to this plan.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dear Dee Dee: My ex-husband's wife has won $10 million in the
lottery. I can't help but feel that the money is rightfully mine,
since I was married to him for 20 years and she's had to put up
with him for only the last six months. How can I convince her that
in the court of karmic justice the money should go to me? _
Cheated, Again
</P>
<P>
   Dee Dee tends to agree that, karmically, most of the cash
probably should be yours, but as anyone who watches Judge Judy
knows, karma doesn't cut much ice in a traditional courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Diane White is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
