<HEADLINE>
FIRST SHIPMENT OF RADIOACTIVE WASTE TO ARRIVE IN BAY AREA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KEAY DAVIDSON  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Shipments of radioactive nuclear fuel rods are
scheduled to begin passing through the San Francisco area this
month, according to the Department of Energy.
</P>
<P>
   California Attorney General Dan Lungren declined Wednesday to
sue the federal government to stop or delay the shipments, angering
the state Coastal Commission, which asked the attorney general to
represent them in court.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Douglas, executive director of the commission, said he was
``really shocked ... frustrated and dismayed'' at Lungren's
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's an accident and the stuff spills and is exposed to
the environment, the consumer of fish poisoned (by the waste) is
going to avoid those fish knowing there's radioactive waste out
there,'' Douglas said.
</P>
<P>
   Staci Turner, a spokeswoman for Lungren, said Wednesday she
could not comment on the issue. She cited attorney-client privilege
between Lungren's office and the Coastal Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Lungren authorized the commission to sue on its own, but
commission members say they lack the money to hire a lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Commission Vice Chairwoman Sara Wan said that by declining to
sue, Lungren ``basically is taking away from the people of this
state the right to review or have a hearing about this issue. An
accident is possible. ... I'm not convinced that everything has
been done to maximize the safety.''
</P>
<P>
   Gray Davis, the Democratic gubernatorial candidate, criticized
Lungren, a Republican who is running for governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once again, Dan Lungren is putting his own personal ideology
in front of his duties as attorney general,'' Davis said in a
telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next 11 years, five shipments of radioactive fuel rods
are scheduled to be delivered through the Bay to the Concord Naval
Weapons Station. There, the shipments will be packed onto a freight
train and hauled through California, Nevada, Utah and Idaho. The
ultimate destination is a storage site at the Idaho National
Engineering and Environment Laboratory, a nuclear weapons
laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   The shipments are part of a national effort to retrieve
radioactive fuel rods from foreign reactors to prevent ``hot''
waste from being diverted for use in nuclear weapons or
radioactivity-dispersing chemical bombs.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Energy Department spokesman John Belluardo
confirmed that the first shipment will arrive sometime this month.
He declined to identify the name of the ship or its precise course
before its planned arrival at the Naval Weapons Station.
</P>
<P>
   The first shipment involves about 360 fuel rods from South
Korea. The radioactive material originated in North Korean nuclear
plants and the United States agreed to dispose the material under
an agreement aimed at preventing the communist-led nation from
developing weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
</TEXT>
