<P>
   FILM-SMOKE (Undated) The Native-American road picture, ``Smoke
Signals,'' which debuted locally as the ``mid-festival gala'' of
the recent Seattle International Film Festival and begins its
regular run today, is the closest thing we're likely to have this
summer to an American indie ``event'' picture.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (story will move in the ``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-CHERRY (Undated) Abbas Kiarostami's ``Taste of Cherry,''
which won the prestigious Palme d'Or at the 1997 Cannes Film
Festival, might be described as a fancy-free Iranian version of
Frank Capra's ``It's a Wonderful Life.''
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (story will move in the ``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-KINGDOM (Undated) ``The Kingdom II'' is contagiously
entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (story will move in the ``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-HANGING (Undated) Director and writer Thom Fitzgerald was
so hellbent on exorcising his painful coming of age demons _ he
left home at 18 and didn't return for 10 years after his mother
learned he was gay _ that he purposely chose to write the most
furious ``non-literal'' script imaginable about the experience. The
result is ``The Hanging Garden,'' which won prizes at the Toronto
Film Festival and took home a Genie (the Canadian equivalent of the
Oscar) for best screenplay.
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (story will move in the ``e'' category)
</P>
