<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-NOTES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US NEWS' FALLOWS: NO NEWS WAS BAD NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This past Monday, as he was informing his staff that he had been
fired after almost two years at the helm, U.S. News &AMP; World Report
editor James Fallows revealed the journalistic priorities that may
have gotten him in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the magazine made big news with its June 29 ``exclusive''
report on the Monica Lewinsky tapes. But in the message to his
staff, the outgoing editor lavished much praise on that issue's
``Retirement Guide,'' a 27-page primer on the virtues of the
401(k)and Roth IRA. The guide was vintage Fallows, more service
than scandal, more wonky than sexy. And maybe it explains why owner
Mort Zuckerman, in Fallows's words, wanted a ``change in
direction.'' (The magazine's editorial director Harold Evans
insisted it was his decision to fire Fallows.)
</P>
<P>
   As he turns over the reins to veteran news magazine manager
Stephen Smith, Fallows's legacy is likely to be a subject of heated
debate. Audited numbers at the end of 1997 show a total circulation
of 2.22 million with 57,300 newsstand sales, a slight rise in
single-copy sales and a slight drop in overall circulation from the
previous year. By comparison, Time is at 4.16 million circulation
and Newsweek is at 3.18 million.
</P>
<P>
   Fallows _ keenly aware of the charge that he softened the
magazine by eschewing hard news for navel gazing _ told the staff
that no one should define his dispute with Zuckerman as ``a `news'
versus `non-news' dichotomy.'' But he left little doubt about his
priorities when recounting the magazine's achievements: enterprise
work that ``puts familiar topics in an entirely different light'';
the ``Silver Bullets'' concept of offering solutions to the
nation's thorniest problems; and ``service journalism...worth the
same care, creativity, and standards as any other kind of story.''
</P>
<P>
   This is in keeping with the reputation Fallows has earned _
thanks to his book ``Breaking the News: How the Media Undermine
American Democracy'' _ as a critic of journalism-as-usual and a
believer in the profession as a tool for civic improvement. The New
York Times' Maureen Dowd recently dubbed him the ``Rector of
American Journalism.'' Whether that's fair or not, it is hard to
see how someone so disdainful of the Beltway press corps could
successfully run a Washington-based news magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the competition has opted for more
lifestyle-oriented coverage in recent years, U.S. News was often
furthest off the headlines. When Newsweek and Time splashed the
death of Frank Sinatra on the cover, U.S. News ran a story
explaining the drop in violent crime. When the big two played the
Arkansas schoolyard massacre on the cover, U.S. News went with an
uncompelling account of life aboard a U.S. submarine.
</P>
<P>
   Fallows's vision was apparent in such cover stories as ``16
Silver Bullets'' which offered potential solutions to problems
ranging from teenage pregnancy to land mine casualties. And a March
cover story, ``Don't Die Before You Read This,'' may have been the
ultimate in quirky service journalism. The piece _ an expose of
corruption in the funeral industry _ examined everything from the
markup in casket prices to morticians who bribe clergymen and
advised people on how to avoid being ripped off in their moment of
grief. It was fascinating reading, but was it too weird to work?
</P>
<P>
   This raises the eternal question for the perennial show horse in
a three-horse field. Is U.S. News wiser to march to a different
drummer or battle Time and Newsweek in the trenches?
</P>
<P>
   That's a matter that henceforth, will furrow the brow of Smith,
49, an alum of the Daily Hampshire Gazette and The Boston Globe.
For Smith, who has been editing the National Journal, getting the
top slot at U.S. News comes as professional vindication. Twice
before he has just missed the brass ring.
</P>
<P>
   Having risen quickly through the ranks at Time magazine, Smith
took a Newsweek job in 1986 at a point when Henry Muller was going
to beat him out for the Time managing editor's job. He was
dismissed by Newsweek in 1991 after a contentious stay that ended
when his rival, Maynard Parker, won the battle for leadership of
the magazine, leaving Smith with a reputation for less than
world-class people skills.
</P>
<P>
   He has since worked his way back, toiling for Knight-Ridder,
founding Civilization magazine and moving to the National Journal.
Smith is widely praised for strong editing skills and as a
seasoned, smart magazine professional. And his admirers say that
his work in the past decade has earned him a return ticket to the
big time.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``I don't think anyone envisions any kind of sharp change in
direction,'' says Smith of his new job. ``My hope is to make as
clear as possible the distinctions between U.S. News and the other
two news magazines...Time and Newsweek are fighting for the same
readers and to an extent, define each other. We get to choose the
ground we fight on while they're locked in World War II.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever Smith's vision, there's always the question of whether
he'll get to execute it. At U.S. News, where he has a three-year
contract, he becomes Zuckerman's seventh editor in 14 years. And
any honeymoon there may be tempered by Harold Evans' response last
November when asked about rumors that Fallows' days were numbered.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is not going to be a new editor at U.S. News &AMP; World
Report,'' he declared.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
