<HEADLINE>
`SMOKE SIGNALS' IS AN AMERICAN INDIE `EVENT' PICTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Native-American road picture, ``Smoke Signals,'' which
debuted locally as the ``mid-festival gala'' of the recent Seattle
International Film Festival and begins its regular run today, is
the closest thing we're likely to have this summer to an American
indie ``event'' picture.
</P>
<P>
   Not only does it have a strong local connection (it's the first
offering of the Seattle-based ShadowCatcher Entertainment and
adapted from stories by Seattle author Sherman Alexie), it also won
both the Audience Award and Filmmaker's Trophy for best dramatic
film at the last Sundance Film Festival.
</P>
<P>
   And it's laying claim to being the ``first full-length feature
film written, directed and co-produced by Native Americans,'' which
should guarantee it a high profile among critics, and a special
place (or at least an interesting footnote) in film history.
</P>
<P>
   Happily, all this hoopla and advance praise has turned out to be
more than just hype. The film is no earthshaker, but it's a funny,
charming, often poignant coming-of-age picture and all-around slice
of contemporary Indian life that just sparkles with authenticity.
</P>
<P>
   Based on Alexie's 1993 short story collection, ``The Lone Ranger
and Tonto Fistfight in Heaven,'' it's the story of two young Idaho
Indians: the athletic, charismatic and popular Victor Joseph (Adam
Beach) and his smaller, nerdy worshiper, Thomas Builds-the-Fire
(Evan Adams).
</P>
<P>
   The film opens with a prologue set on the Fourth of July, 1988,
when a celebration at the Coeur d'Alene Indian reservation gets out
of hand, a fire breaks out, and a series of events ensue that
forces Arnold (Gary Farmer), father of the then-12-year-old Victor,
to desert his family.
</P>
<P>
   Cut to 10 years later, and word reaches Victor and his mother
(Tantoo Cardinal) that Arnold has died in an Arizona trailer camp.
Victor feels obligated to bring back the ashes for burial, but,
with no money, the only way he can finance the trip is through his
ever-admiring pal Thomas, who insists on tagging along.
</P>
<P>
   From here, ``Smoke Signals'' segues into an enjoyable, if
familiar, mismatched-buddy road picture, with the two opposites
regularly attracting and repelling each another through a series of
picaresque experiences that leaves them, in the end, wiser and
better people.
</P>
<P>
   But it's extremely well done: cleverly scripted, almost
perfectly cast (Beach has the stuff of a major star), alternately
funny and touching, and thematically very effective, communicating
its serious message _ the plight of the American Indian _ with an
ingratiating, self-deprecating humor, rather than off-putting
anger.
</P>
<P>
   The only real flaw in the film is that the script has a certain
self-conscious tendency to relate every aspect of the characters'
lives to the ``Indian experience,'' which gradually gets tiresome
and often makes them come off less as living/breathing human beings
as literary devices designed to make a point.
</P>
<P>
   Smoke Signals. Directed by Chris Eyre. Written by Sherman
Alexie. Cast: Adam Beach, Evan Adams, Tom Skerritt, Tantoo
Cardinal, Gary Farmer. Miramax. 89 minutes. Rated PG-13 for mature
themes and language.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
