<SLUG> BC-FILM-CHERRY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CHERRY' IS AN IRANIAN VERSION OF ``IT'S A WONDERFUL LIFE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Abbas Kiarostami's ``Taste of Cherry,'' which won the
prestigious Palme d'Or at the 1997 Cannes Film Festival, might be
described as a fancy-free Iranian version of Frank Capra's ``It's a
Wonderful Life.''
</P>
<P>
   Its hero is an apparently well-off, middle-aged man named Badii
(Homayoun Ershadi), who, for reasons he never expresses, has
decided to kill himself and is driving around the dusty,
mountainous outskirts of Teheran in his Range Rover looking for
someone to help him.
</P>
<P>
   He's already dug a shallow grave, and he believes he's mustered
the courage to lie down in it and do the deed that night. But he
wants someone to come back in the morning to cover him up, or, if
he somehow fails to pull off the task successfully, to rescue him.
</P>
<P>
   He picks up a young Kurdish soldier in the Iranian Army, then an
Afghan seminary student, then an old Turkish taxidermist who
collects specimens for a natural history museum. The soldier flees
in terror when he explains what he wants, and the others are almost
as reluctant to get involved.
</P>
<P>
   The trio give him a succession of reasons why suicide is not a
good idea. Everything from Hamlet's fear of the unknown to the
religious stigma of breaking God's will to your basic humanistic
bias against squandering the sweet gift of life _ giving up ``the
taste of cherries.''
</P>
<P>
   A cynical reviewer might argue Capra told this same story a lot
more effectively and that the Palme d'Or is often politically
inspired, so the award might have less to do with cinematic
brilliance in this case than with the director's courage in dealing
with the taboo subject of suicide in a country still ruled by
strict Islamic law.
</P>
<P>
   But Kiarostami (``Through the Olive Trees'') definitely has his
own distinctive sensibility and world-view, which come across
nicely; his film has a kind of lyrical and poetic beauty at the
same time it's remarkably free of sentimentality and didacticism;
and it tells its tale with the minimalist effectiveness of a
first-rate short story.
</P>
<P>
   Taste of Cherry. Directed, written and edited by Abbas
Kiarostami. Cast: Homayoung Ershadi, Abdolhossein Bagheri, Afshin
Bakhtiari, Ali Moradi. Zeitgeist Films. 95 minutes. In Farsi with
English subtitles. Unrated.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
