<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-KINGDOM-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE KINGDOM II IS CONTAGIOUSLY ENTERTAINING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It isn't nearly as ghostly, creepy or compelling as part one but
``The Kingdom II'' retains a contagiously entertaining flair _
though it pushes the boundaries of good taste onto gaudy,
far-fetched, soap opera turf.
</P>
<P>
   Director Lars von Trier, who developed the series for Danish TV,
presented similar contrasts of good versus evil and sacrifice in
love in his last film, the moving, acclaimed ``Breaking The
Waves.''
</P>
<P>
   He, along with co-director Morten Arnfred, expand on those
themes here as well as pitting old world ignorance and superstition
against modern science.
</P>
<P>
   And they've instilled this 4-hour installment with the same dark
comedy and unflagging energy that helped attain cult status for
``The Kingdom.''
</P>
<P>
   The huge Copenhagen hospital known as The Kingdom was built atop
an ancient cloth bleaching ground and the ghosts of the laborers
who died in the pits haunt the hospital halls. Somewhere in the
bowels of the structure lurk Satanic forces and worshippers.
</P>
<P>
   It's up to a select group of the hospital staff and some psychic
and disabled patients to uncover who among them is the ``Grand
Duc'' to the devil himself.
</P>
<P>
   Is it Stig Helmer (Ernst-Hugo Jaregard), the Swedish consultant
who hates the Danish (``Danish scum,'' he spits), or could it be
his chief associate, Dr. Moesgaard (Holger Juul Hansen), the dim
bulb of the department? Whoever it is, it's up to Mrs. Drusse
(Kirsten Rolffes), an eternal patient who never seems to get
discharged, to rally the hospital's good spirits together to fight
the growing forces of evil.
</P>
<P>
   Part two as a whole is much lighter and more fantastical than
the original. ``The Kingdom II'' suffers from many of the same
problems as regular TV series and soap operas in that relatively
little happens over the four-hour time span. We're fooled into
thinking we've seen much more than we have. And once again, we're
left with a cliff-hanger of an ending which, according to von
Trier, will be resolved in the last episode of the trilogy.
</P>
<P>
   While part two is more ambitious _ it follows 11 stories instead
of the five or six that were tracked in the first series _ the
developments that occur are absurd and silly. The intriguing thing
about the initial show was its gothic creepiness and flight of
imagination and fancy. Here we see more, but that doesn't
necessarily make it better.
</P>
<P>
   Hopefully, the final saga will sway back to the gothic tone of
the original. The traipses into zombie-ism and New Age spirituality
that trip up ``The Kingdom II'' are banal and the dark, dark sense
of dread and unknown that oozed through part one were far more
spooky.
</P>
<P>
   The Kingdom II. Directed by Lars von Trier, Morten Arnfred.
Written by von Trier, Niels Vorsel. Cast: Ernst-Hugo Jaregard,
Kirsten Rolffes, Ghita Norby, Soren Pilmark. October Films. 286
minutes. Unrated with nudity, gore, scenes depicting Satanic
rituals. In Danish with English subtitles.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
