<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-SOTHEBYS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEHIND THE CURTAINS OF SOTHEBY'S 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINE TEMIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
SOTHEBY'S 
Bidding for Class 
By Robert Lacey 
Little, Brown, 354 pp., Illustrated, $27.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We're probably still safe in calling Sotheby's the world's most
famous auction house. Robert Lacey's wildly entertaining new book,
``Sotheby's _ Bidding for Class,'' demonstrates that it isn't the
oldest, as the firm has always claimed, nor, in some seasons, even
the biggest.
</P>
<P>
   Lacey's is the second book in a year to expose the Bond Street
auction house. Peter Watson's ``Sotheby's _ The Inside Story''
investigated the firm's habit of spiriting art out of its country
of origin without proper paperwork. Watson quoted an internal memo
_ ``Should we stop selling anything that might have been smuggled,
for PR reasons?'' _ that seems to sum up Sotheby's creative ethics.
</P>
<P>
   Watson's book is highly focused. Lacey's is broader, a complete
history of the business that began as a London bookseller's,
expanded into fine art, conquered New York, and then went global.
Lacey opens with the spectacular 1996 sale of the effects of
Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis, and quickly gets to the heart of the
matter _ what's under the auction house's gloss of refinement and
taste. ``The trick,'' he writes, ``is to persuade people who
already possess more than their fair share of worldly goods that
their happiness depends on acquiring even more.''
</P>
<P>
   This fiction is complemented by others. ``Founded in 1744,'' the
company's catalogs proclaim. Not so, counters Lacey. ``Started
trading under the name of Sotheby in 1778'' would be more accurate,
by which time the firm's great rival, Christie's, had been in
business for a dozen years. What's now called ``Sotheby's'' started
with one Samuel Baker, a freelance London book dealer who
bequeathed his business to his nephew John Sotheby. There hasn't
been a Sotheby in Sotheby's since the last of the line died in
1861, but no matter. Brand name recognition is the foundation of
the firm, whether it's their name or Van Gogh's. (Lacey offers an
amusing account of the failure of the Sotheby's cigarette, which
was supposed to bail the firm out of one of its periodic financial
crises.)
</P>
<P>
   The revolutions of 18th-century Europe meant that the treasures
of deposed nobles flooded London, making it the center of the
world's art trade. The collections of the great British country
houses were formed when then-new auction houses sold these spoils
of war to English dukes and earls. And when those aristocrats fell
on hard times, the auction houses helped them discreetly dispose of
their property, sending it still further west, as when Sotheby's
sold the duke of Devonshire's great library to the American
railroad tycoon H.E. Huntington in 1913 for $15.9 million in
today's money.
</P>
<P>
   What's even more fascinating than the mind-boggling prices that
culminate with Sotheby's 1987 sale of Van Gogh's ``Irises'' to
Australian entrepreneur Alan Bond for $49 million, money it turned
out he didn't have, is Lacey's analysis of how we got to that
point. For generations, auction houses peddled fair-to-middling
paintings, while dealers sold the stars. Consigning your great
Titian to an auction house wasn't considered nice. Nor was it nice
to turn up at an auction and bid in public. It took Sotheby's 1956
sale of Poussin's ``The Adoration of the Shepherds'' to break the
psychological barrier. The painting ended up in London's National
Gallery, its prestige intact. Collectors were suddenly eager to
unload their major masterpieces at auction, where bidding frenzies
might mean more money than they'd get from a closed-door deal with
a dealer.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the bizarre characters who populate Lacey's book, Peter
Wilson tops the heap. Scion of an aristocratic family fallen on
hard times, Wilson, in a half-century association with Sotheby's,
created the firm we know today. Under his direction, Sotheby's
pioneered the notion of art as excellent investment _ which Lacey
disputes _ and glamorized what was considered a slightly shady
business through black-tie auctions attended by celebrities.
</P>
<P>
   Lacey doesn't spoil his string of deliciously disgusting
anecdotes about greed with moralizing. Nor does he spend much time
on actual art. Only once, in describing the ``Irises,'' does he wax
rhapsodic over a painting. Mostly, he lets the facts and follies
speak for themselves, and they're quite enough. Consider Sotheby's
1993 sale of the title to the abandoned moon rover, which is stuck
up there in perpetuity. The winning bid was $68,000. ``It was a
conceptual thing,'' said the presiding auctioneer, ``because true
collecting is not about the actual possession of objects.'' Can a
sale of the emperor's new clothes be far behind?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-98 1441EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
