<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDNOTES-SCI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
_LIGHT IS SHED ON MORNING-AFTER PILL  
 _CHIROPRACTIC CARE GETS MIXED GRADE  
 _CANCER MORTALITY, RACE LINK MULLED  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOLORES KONG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
 
 Light is shed on morning-after pill
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The morning-after pill must be taken within 72 hours of
unprotected intercourse _ but a woman needs to go get a doctor's
prescription for the pill, making that time frame difficult to
meet.
</P>
<P>
   A prescription has long been thought necessary to prevent women
from using the emergency contraception inappropriately or unsafely.
</P>
<P>
   Now a study has found that such a pill, essentially a high-dose
birth control pill, can be safely made available to women without
their having to go to a doctor every time.
</P>
<P>
   ``This study suggests that women are able to self-administer
emergency contraception correctly, at the appropriate time, and
without adverse effects,'' write the researchers from Edinburgh in
the current New England Journal of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers gave one group of about 500 women a supply of
pills to take home, while another group of about 500 women had to
go to a doctor's office for the pill.
</P>
<P>
   The women who got the take-home supply were not more likely to
use the pills repeatedly, to forgo using other contraceptive
methods, nor to experience serious side effects than were those who
went to the doctor. Yet while 25 women in the doctor's office group
had an unintended pregnancy, only 18 among the take-home supply
group did. Those numbers, however, were too small to establish
statistical significance.
</P>
<P>
   In an accompanying editorial welcoming the study, Dr. Phillip
Stubblefield of Boston University Medical Center writes, ``If
emergency contraception were made available without a prescription,
it would be used more often and could be expected to reduce the
number of unwanted pregnancies.''
</P>
<P>
   The high-dose birth control pill is not approved in the United
States specifically as a morning-after pill, but US physicians are
authorized to write prescriptions for licensed drugs for
nonapproved uses. The pill is not the same as the controversial
abortion pill, RU-486, which has not been licensed to be marketed
in this country for any use.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Chiropractic care gets mixed grade
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Good and bad news for people who suffer from low back pain.
</P>
<P>
   The good news: A study finds that low back pain sufferers are
just as likely to get appropriate spinal manipulation from
chiropractors as patients with other health problems are to get
appropriate medical procedures from physicians.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news: Only 46 percent of the spinal manipulation _ or
``back cracking,'' as it is sometimes called _ met guidelines for
appropriateness, while 29 percent of the care was inappropriate.
For the rest, treatment was deemed uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   The study, considered the most thorough analysis yet of spinal
manipulation, is in the current Annals of Internal Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody needs to stop treating chiropractors as if they are
quacks. An appropriateness rate of roughly half is in the same
ballpark as the findings for certain medical procedures when
appropriateness measures were introduced a dozen years ago,'' said
Dr. Paul G. Shekelle, an author of the study. At the same time, he
added, ``clearly, a 29 percent inappropriateness rate is too high
and should be decreased.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Cancer mortality, race link mulled
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Statistics show that black men die at a higher rate from
prostate cancer than white men do, but they don't show why.
</P>
<P>
   Some researchers have theorized that black men have less access
to health care, and thus get diagnosed later, when the cancer is
more deadly. Others have suggested the cancer is biologically more
virulent in black men.
</P>
<P>
   A study in the current issue of the Journal of the National
Cancer Institute explores that question by looking at prostate
cancer survival rates for black and white men belonging to the same
HMO _ where access to care is theoretically equal.
</P>
<P>
   For comparison, the researchers from Stanford and the Kaiser
Permanente health maintenance organization looked at the survival
rate for black and white men who did not belong to the HMO.
</P>
<P>
   Of the more than 21,000 men, both HMO members and nonmembers,
the researchers found the prostate cancer death rate for black men
was more than 20 percent higher.
</P>
<P>
   ``These results argue strongly that racial differences in
prostate cancer survival are not due solely to inequalities in
access to health care,'' the researchers conclude. ``The findings
are most compatible with the hypothesis of increased tumor
virulence in black men.''
</P>
</TEXT>
