<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 14:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7833 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RETROSPECTIVE-JACOB-L     07-02 1693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RETROSPECTIVE-JACOB-LAWRENCE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACOB LAWRENCE: A LIFE IN ART  
 (WITH INTERVIEW-JACOB-LAWRENCE) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By REGINA HACKETT  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Tucked into the lower left corner of Jacob Lawrence's
1977 ``Street Scene'' is a small boy drawing a house on the
sidewalk. Even with a crowd streaming around him, his focus never
falters. With deep, dark eyes, he concentrates on his creation,
opening white windows on gray pavement and a world within the
world.
</P>
<P>
   This gouache (opaque watercolor) hangs at the entrance to
``Jacob Lawrence: Painting Life,'' a retrospective exhibit opening
today at the University of Washington's Henry Art Gallery.
</P>
<P>
   Although the show, organized by guest curator Beth Sellars,
spans more than 60 years with 200 paintings, drawings and prints,
its organization is only loosely chronological.
</P>
<P>
   Sellars thinks Lawrence's work bears directly on his life, that,
in essence, he paints an extended autobiography.
</P>
<P>
   The idea sounds good on paper and has a striking amount of truth
in it. Played out on the gallery walls, however, it becomes a
puzzling mannerism, with stray paintings from, say, the 1940s
popping up amid other works from a decade earlier, just because
they illustrate some point of biography.
</P>
<P>
   Retrospectives usually follow the artist's chronology, with
beginnings, middles and ends. If not, there has to be a compelling
visual reason. This show doesn't have one.
</P>
<P>
   That said, ``Painting Life'' is still terrific, even something
of a miracle. Given roughly six months to put it together, Sellars
managed to secure a significant number of key loans from across the
country and deliver a credible version of Lawrence's career.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the fact the Henry gave itself half a year
instead of the more common year and a half or two years to mount a
major show means there's no catalog. It also means the exhibit
won't travel _ a missed opportunity since there hasn't been a major
Lawrence retrospective since a 1986 Seattle Art Museum show that
traveled to five major venues around the country, breaking
attendance records.
</P>
<P>
   ``Painting Life'' opens in the first gallery with 30 paintings
from the ``Migration Series,'' completed in 1940, when Lawrence was
23. The full narrative cycle of 60 paintings charts the flow of
Southern blacks to the North, leaving Jim Crow oppressions in hopes
of better lives.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence was quickly tagged as a Social Realist, although like
every other movement that would come along in this century, he
didn't fit it.
</P>
<P>
   What the ``Migration Series'' actually represents is a young
artist making uncanny use of his technical limitations and mining
one of his essential gifts, the instinct for economy.
</P>
<P>
   Because he couldn't mix colors with any degree of accuracy, he
stuck to primary and secondary shades laid on straight from the
jar. And because he hadn't yet mastered the rendering of fluid
volumes, he reduced his figures to the starkest of shapes. With a
limited palette and simplified forms, his striking compositional
sense lifted his work into virtuoso accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   Sharing the gallery with ``Migration'' are a suite of paintings
he did earlier of Harlem street scenes. At 19, he painted the
magnificent ``Street Orator.''
</P>
<P>
   The only visible part of the painting's namesake is his striped
cuffed pants and shoes disappearing up a ladder in the foreground
as their owner ascends to his platform. The real subject is, as
ever for Lawrence, the audience. Pressed against the rungs of the
ladder and looking up, they have a German Expressionist intensity
without the usual angst, rancor or blight.
</P>
<P>
   Also from 1936 is ``Ice Man.'' Hung from a large hook on the
front of the rickety old cart is an ice tong, tenderly carved in
black and given its full sculptural dimension, the first of the
tools that will appear again and again in his work throughout his
lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the ``Migration Series,'' the great cycles of narrative
paintings done in his youth in the 1940s include ``Toussaint
L'Ouverture,'' inspired by the Haitian Revolution of 1795;
``Frederick Douglass,'' ``Harriet Tubman'' and ``John Brown.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Painting Life'' has half of ``Migration,'' and no ``Frederick
Douglass'' or ``Harriet Tubman'' from this period. ``Toussaint''
appears in print form, as 16 serigraphs from 1986 to 1998, as does
``John Brown,'' with 22 serigraphs from 1977.
</P>
<P>
   These narrative cycles remain the most famous of his career.
With their fierce scale shifts and glowing masses of high-toned
color popping out like fire bursts in variegated seas of brown,
they register on the nerve endings with a jolt.
</P>
<P>
   Gems from the 1940s in this show include ``The Apartment,'' a
clear statement of another lifelong theme, how people living in
dire poverty sometimes manage to find a grace note.
</P>
<P>
   The apartment in question is cramped and the woman walking
through it, coming home from work, is bent with trouble. Around
her, however, are the riotous blessings of inanimate objects.
Flowers woven into a throw rug are strewn at her feet, and a
Picasso-like crazy face made from liquid-light circles looms out
from a gold rug hung on the wall.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, Lawrence had become adept at mixing colors and
rendering fluid volumes. ``Diners'' from 1942 is undoubtedly a
dive, but the turquoise curtains hung on rods of gold and patterned
with creeping black vines are praise poems to the virtues of cheap
charm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rooftops'' from 1943 is a celebration of syncopated life of
color found in hand-painted signs, billboard advertising, church
spires and the pleasures of a vertical life in rundown high-rises,
with room for your body and maybe a potted plant.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence continued working on his Harlem series in the 1940s,
interpreted by service in the Coast Guard, where he became a
shipboard artist.
</P>
<P>
   The world continues to pitch and sway in Lawrence's Coast Guard
paintings, especially ``Cmbar Katian'' from 1944. He painted
soldiers from the back who were packed into a ship's hold on a
strong diagonal: green helmets, backpacks and red flares. In the
foreground, a railing breaks the diagonal flow. Under it, soldiers
break formation, the green cones of their covered heads lurching in
disarray.
</P>
<P>
   In 1949, he was hospitalized for nine months for depression. His
spirit muted, he nevertheless continued to draw with unfettered
fluency, making bodies that sag with the gravity of their illnesses
and objects that try to lift them up: weavings and quilts, saws and
planks, strings and fabrics flying.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1950s, he began a brilliant series relating to
performances and masked parties. Lawrence had begun to pick up some
criticism for being decorative, and these paintings are decorative
with a vengeance. In ``Concert'' from 1952, vines burst through
walls on the stage to curl into a grand piano, blooming everywhere
but around the pianist, whose pale dress looks like a prism of
fractured ice.
</P>
<P>
   The large, benign figures in ``Iyo'' from the Nigerian series of
1964 resemble Romare Bearden's in their heavy, misshapened faces,
hands and feet. Only Lawrence, however, would drape them in fabrics
full of luminous air and colored light.
</P>
<P>
   The 1960s also saw the advent of his ``Civil Rights'' series,
which continued into the 1970s with the famed ``Confrontation at
the Bridge,'' represented here in serigraph form. In the 1970s, he
began his ``Builder'' series, which continues to the present day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Painting Life'' has a choice selection of ``Builders,''
including ``No. 1'' from 1972. Nails are laid out in front of a
formidable carpenter like jewels before a king, silky and softly
shadowed piles of blue, grays and golds.
</P>
<P>
   The man himself is muscled for his tasks and serene like the
Buddha. His bounty attracts Mount Rainier. From a rear window, it
strains toward him in snow-peak splendor.
</P>
<P>
   Three of Lawrence's finest series have emerged in the last two
decades: ``Genesis'' from 1990, ``Hiroshima'' from 1983 and
``Supermarket'' from 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Eight Sermons of the Creation from the Book of Genesis''
are hung in ``Painting Life'' in print form, while ``Hiroshima''
and ``Supermarket'' are in gouache.
</P>
<P>
   ``Genesis'' traces the world's origins and ``Hiroshima'' its
end, playing across the spectrum from joy to horror.
</P>
<P>
   No one touching the theme of nuclear war has risen to the
standard Lawrence sets. The ground cracks and the hapless figures
on it are frozen in the act of becoming their shadows. As they
lament, they are baking down to their bones.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Genesis'' and ``Supermarket,'' Lawrence has all of the
fluid energy he developed in the 1940s, but in this later work his
polish and density, force and grace, work together to achieve
symphonic greatness.
</P>
<P>
   Included in the exhibition are two paintings by Gwen Knight,
Lawrence's wife of 57 years. Small bust portraits in oil on canvas,
one shows the artist herself, poised and self-protective, casting a
cool eye at the viewer. Lawrence, in contrast, more than fills his
picture frame. Done in golden brown tones, the patina of old
bronze, his face radiates warmth and open affection.
</P>
<P>
   Across the span of more than 60 years, Lawrence has treated the
human figure and the flow of human figures as they mistreat,
defend, comfort and challenge each other. Through purely visual
means, he has expanded our collective notions of own history and
honored our rarely honored heroes and heroines. While the size of
his work is usually modest, its scale is enormous.
</P>
<P>
   What Herman Melville wrote about the Mississippi River is true
of Lawrence's human dramas, that they are ``dashing and all-fusing
spirits'' uniting the streams of the ``most distant and opposite
zones'' and pouring themselves along, ``helter-skelter, in one
cosmopolitan and confident tide.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacob Lawrence: Painting Life. University of Washington's Henry
Art Gallery. Through Sept. 27. Admission: $5 general, $3.50
seniors, free for members, students, children under 14; free for
all Thursday nights, 5-8 p.m. Hours: Tuesdays-Sundays, 11 a.m.-5
p.m., till 8 p.m. Thursdays.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
