u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-USWOM-BAUER-BOS &LR;      07-02 1290
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-USWOM-BAUER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BETH BAUER`S FUTURE IS OPEN ENDED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KOHLER, Wis. _ Barbara McIntire has stood up to golf pressure
before, but this time it was rather awkward. The two-time US
Women's Amateur champion was asked about the Curtis Cup team she
will captain in August, in particular her youngest player.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually,'' said McIntire, addressing a group of reporters,
``I have never met Beth personally 'til seeing her right here on
the stage.''
</P>
<P>
   Seizing the opportunity, the moderator said, ``Barbara, this is
Beth. Beth, this is Barbara.''
</P>
<P>
   There was laughter and smiles, but the introduction was
symbolmatic because today, a teenage phenom steps up on a stage
that has seemingly been waiting for her. Golf world, meet Beth
Bauer. Beth Bauer, meet the golf world.
</P>
<P>
   She is 18 years old and in the fall she will be a freshman at
Duke University. Her stature in the golf world has grown rapidly,
from a great talent, to a dominant junior player, to a teenager who
arguably could step right into professional golf. That won't
happen, she says, because college is definitely in her plans, but
when they tee it up today in the 53d US Women's Open at Blackwolf
Run, Bauer will test her much talked about game against the world's
best. She seems prepared, which should not be a surprise because if
there's such a thing as grooming someone to play golf, we may be
looking at the female version of Tiger Woods.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ufdots &LR;
</P>
<P>
   John Bauer introduced his daughter to golf and it didn't take
long for him to realize there was something special. So like
hundreds of parents, John and Christine poured their energy and
financial resources into Beth's career. There was never a shortage
of events, from the American Junior Golf Association circuit, to
the PGA Junior Maxfli, to USGA competitions, with the tab running
as much as $20,000 per year.
</P>
<P>
   But it was seen as an investment in a professional golf career,
and always there have been dividends in the form of victories.
Twenty-five national wins, 16 of them being AJGA events, the major
league of junior golf. But no victory meant more, or came with such
eye-opening ease, as last summer's USGA Girls' Junior. At the
Legends Club of Tennessee, Bauer set 18- and 36-hole records with
qualifying rounds of 68 and 66 to win medalist honors by a whopping
seven shots.
</P>
<P>
   She then marched through match play, won the championship, and
accepted another trophy. Only this time, the victory felt somewhat
hollow. She had been trained for this, but there was something
missing. The golf had been easy, but the ceremony ... well, it was
impossible. Bauer cried, and those close to her knew why. Her
father deserved the spotlight, too, but he was sorely missed.
</P>
<P>
   John Bauer had died three years earlier at the age of 41. He had
taken Beth to the PGA Junior Championship when he collapsed. Rushed
to the hospital, he had only one request _ that his daughter go on
with the tournament. Her father's condition deteriorated quickly,
but Beth was never told how bad the situation was. She won the
championship, but three days later real life came crashing down on
her _ her father died as a result of something called Guillain
Barre syndrome, a neurological disorder.
</P>
<P>
   Life has gone on, so has the golf, but she rarely plays a golf
shot without remembering her father. ``I think about my dad and
always try to do my best.''
</P>
<P>
   Her best has been quite impressive and if recent form is any
indication, perhaps she is as good as advertised. Consider the
results of a spur decision. ``My coach at Duke called me about a
month ago and asked me play in these two amateur championships (the
Women's Southern Amateur and Women's North &AMP; South). Luckily I went
out and I really played well and won them both.''
</P>
<P>
   If there was any doubt about her selection to the Curtis Cup
team (the amateur women's version of the Ryder Cup), there was none
now. Bauer, so long a talked-about name in junior golf circles, was
now an elite name. And with the team selection came an exemption
into the US Women's Open, which may be too much, too soon, except
the world today isn't what it used to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being 18 or 19 today,'' said Nancy Lopez, ``isn't what being
18 or 19 was back then.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ufdots &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Sally Little can vouch for that. Today, Little will look at the
young teenager in her pairing, but she won't see something that
brings back memories. ``When I was 17, we never had that many
tournaments, just one a year,'' said Little. ``When I was 18, I
came over to play professionally to get experience. The women's
tour is where I trained.''
</P>
<P>
   The South African native was LPGA Tour Rookie of the Year in
1971, the year after Bauer was born. She is 46 now and winless
since the third of her major titles, the 1988 du Maurier Classic,
but like Bauer, Little is here for a reason. ``I'm not here for
nostalgia purposes,'' said Little, who was denied a US Women's Open
victory in a playoff loss to Jane Geddes in 1986. ``I feel as a
player I have not achieved my potential. I love competing.''
</P>
<P>
   And if that competition is a wide-eyed teenager with her own
personal coach and a machine-like swing that has been grooved by
years of training, so be it. ``To me it doesn't matter,'' said
Little. ``I've hit against (Joanne) Carner and (Beth) Daniel. When
I tee it up in a national open, I think I've got a tremendous
advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Bauer would not argue that point. ``The course is longer than
I'm used to. (In junior events) I'm usually hitting 5-iron or less
into the par-4s, but out here I'm hitting 3-woods. It's going to
test my short game and long irons.''
</P>
<P>
   When reminded that she had shot 76-70-72-72 to tie for 16th in
her only other appearance in a professional tournament _ the
Nabisco Dinah Shore in March _ Bauer tugged at the Titleist cap
that is pulled tightly on her head, the brim bent the way kids wear
them these days. That means nothing this week, she said. ``I would
like to make the cut. That would be my first goal.''
</P>
<P>
   The future goals are not so modest, of course, and there are
those who think Bauer is being polite, that she has the game to
compete right now. ``We may be seeing the best American woman
golfer of our time,'' said Rhonda Glenn of the USGA, who has
authored several books on women's golf. ``I can't think of anyone
who has done as much as her at her age.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ufdots &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Under a scorching sun, Bauer was at work Wednesday, listening to
her caddie and coach, Phil Krick, who knows what it is to compete.
Years ago, he was what they called a rabbit, one of those guys who
had to play in Monday qualifiers just to get into PGA Tour events.
He didn't fare well, but he learned a lot about being
tournament-tough. It's part of the package that he hopes to pass on
to Bauer.
</P>
<P>
   As Bauer played her practice round, an interested bystander
walked several yards behind. ``She's impressive, very impressive,''
said McIntire, who was finally getting a chance to see the
youngster play.
</P>
<P>
   On the 540-yard, par-5 16th, a typical Pete Dye creation that
has a tree on the leftside of the fairway 25 yards in front of the
green, Bauer's layup off a nice drive was pulled left. She looked
at Krick, who shook his head in in disapproval. His player would be
blocked out by the tree, and he pointed firmly to right side of the
fairway.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer reloaded and rifled a 3-wood down the middle, which cut
slightly and settled in perfect position for a wedge into the
green.
</P>
<P>
   Another lesson learned for the young lady who has been studying
for this test for most of her young life. Today, the curtain rises
on what many predict will be a bright golf future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
