<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980702.0137 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 14:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7837 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERVIEW-JACOB-LAWRE     07-02 1692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERVIEW-JACOB-LAWRENCE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT 80, LAWRENCE IS STILL SEARCHING FOR `SOMETHING ELSE'  
 (WITH RETROSPECTIVE-JACOB-LAWRENCE) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By REGINA HACKETT  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ By the time Jacob Lawrence got to Harlem, the party
was over. The flush days of Harlem's cultural renaissance had come
to an abrupt end with the 1929 stock market crash and the beginning
of the Great Depression.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Lawrence was in a position to judge his neighborhood's
sagging fortunes. In 1930, at age 13, he wasn't prepared to lead
anything close to the good life.
</P>
<P>
   Born in 1917 in Atlantic City, N.J., to a couple who had come
North in the general migration of blacks out of the South, he found
little he could count on in his early years.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he was 13, his father was long gone. He and younger
brother and sister had spent three years in foster care before
their mother could afford to send for them. She was a domestic with
an irregular income, barely able to hold her family together.
</P>
<P>
   In Harlem, he was shocked by the lack of open space, the crush
of humanity and the cramped verticality of the buildings. Because
he neither played sports or followed them, he wasn't a big hit with
his contemporaries. Nor was he especially drawn to school.
</P>
<P>
   What follows from such beginnings? Predictably, he became a high
school dropout, leaving to help his mother earn a living. His
sister died early from tuberculous, his brother from a drug
overdose.
</P>
<P>
   And yet his story is one of resounding successes, with triumphs
coming fast and early and sustaining themselves throughout a long
and productive life. To date, he has received 20 honorary
doctorates, membership in the American Academy of Arts and Letters,
the National Council of the Arts and the National Academy of
Design, as well as scores of significant citations, prizes and
foundation grants.
</P>
<P>
   Two retrospective exhibits featuring his work have toured the
country to record-breaking crowds (organized by the Whitney Museum
of American Art in 1974 and the Seattle Art Museum in 1986). Two
similarly popular touring exhibits, both in 1994, featured his
early work: one featuring series charting the careers of
anti-slavery activists Harriet Tubman and Frederick Douglass and
the other the ``Migration Series.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked about his radically changing fortunes as a youth,
Lawrence is quick to give credit where it belongs: to Harlem's
black community. He doesn't mean only Harlem's extraordinary
grouping of painters, musicians, poets and playwrights who
befriended him, but the ordinary people with whom he interacted
every day.
</P>
<P>
   His first Harlem break came right away. ``My mother wanted me to
be safe when I wasn't at school, so she enrolled me in an arts and
crafts program at Utopia House,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On the staff was painter Charles Alston, who immediately
recognized the young man's drawing talent. Alston provided him with
materials and some technical information, but let him build his
painted, cutout cardboard cities on his own.
</P>
<P>
   As a teenager, Lawrence continued to study with Alston, who
became director of the Harlem Art Workshop funded by the WPA Mural
Project for the Federal Art Project.
</P>
<P>
   Alston ran an intellectual salon. Through him, Lawrence met poet
Langston Hughes, painter Aaron Douglas, writers Ralph Ellison and
Claude McCay. Before Lawrence was out of his teens, McCay was
hailing him as a ``peerless delineator of the Harlem scene.''
</P>
<P>
   Another important mentor was sculptor Augusta Savage. When
Lawrence dropped out of high school to earn money, taking on a
series of mind-numbing menial jobs, Savage tried to get him
employment as a WPA artist. The first time she took him, he was too
young. The following year, she remembered and brought him back down
to sign up.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was the first person to give me the idea of being an
artist as a job,'' he said. ``I always wanted to be an artist, but
I assumed I'd have to work in laundry or something of that
nature.''
</P>
<P>
   The heady company he kept encouraged his intellectual interests,
and he spent many hours in the Harlem library, studying the history
of African Americans, research that would result in his first great
cycles of narrative paintings.
</P>
<P>
   He also accompanied various mentors on trips to downtown
galleries and the Metropolitan Museum of Art, eventually going by
himself on foot, 60 blocks south of his home territory. While still
a teenager, he had developed an appreciation of early Renaissance
art, the murals of Jose Orozco and the paintings of Arthur Dove,
John Marin and Kathe Kollwitz.
</P>
<P>
   The credit goes to Savage for introducing Lawrence to Gwen
Knight, a young painter from Barbados whom he married in 1941.
</P>
<P>
   That was a big year for Lawrence. Art dealer Edith Halpert
included his ``Migration'' series in a show in her Downtown
Gallery, where the Phillips Collection in Washington, D.C., and the
Museum of Modern Art immediately began vying to purchase it. When
neither would give way, the series was split, with 30 paintings
going to each institution. He was the first African American artist
to be represented by a major New York gallery and to have a solo
exhibit at the Museum of Modern Art.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel discovered (at that point),'' Lawrence said in
an interview this week. ``I'd already been discovered by my own
community. It had prepared me for success.''
</P>
<P>
   The community had also given him a lifetime of themes to ponder.
``I used to hang around a group of brothers who were cabinet
makers, the Bates brothers,'' he said. ``I'd watch them working
with their tools, never thinking they'd represent my content in the
future.''
</P>
<P>
   The energy and diversity of Harlem moved him as well. He
remembers taking a stroll and passing Marcus Garvey's messengers or
even the great man himself exhorting Harlem's citizens to return to
Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Vying with Garvey for atteniton were communists and labor
organizers, preachers of old and new faiths, musicians with their
hats out, sellers of trinkets and healing potions, jump ropers and
crap shooters, old people sitting on stoops and little kids darting
in and out.
</P>
<P>
   In 1932 he was baptized in the Abyssinian Baptist Church and
remembers the ringing sermons of the Rev. Adam Clayton Powell Sr.,
the model for his ``Genesis'' minister 50 years later. Lawrence was
particularly fond of Powell's ringing ``old bones'' sermon from the
Prophet Ezekiel: ``Son of Man, can these bones live?''
</P>
<P>
   Knight and Lawrence went to New Orleans for their honeymoon,
experiencing Jim Crow laws for the first time: the segregated
drinking fountains, dining and buses. ``We just did what everybody
else did,'' said Knight. ``We sat in the back of the bus and ate in
the restricted areas.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence nodded. ``But I don't think we felt real hatred in New
Orleans. It was too cosmopolitan a city for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Knight remembered waiting at a lunch counter for a seat and one
being empty at the end of the white section. ``A (white) man just
moved the sign over so the empty seat was in the black section. I
said thank you.''
</P>
<P>
   When Joseph Albers invited Lawrence to teach at Black Mountain
College in North Carolina, the school hired a separate compartment
on the train so that the Lawrences wouldn't have to endure the
inferior segregated sections. ``We just stayed in our room,'' said
Knight.
</P>
<P>
   And once at the college, they didn't dare leave it to go into
town. ``Nobody told us we couldn't leave, but nobody encouraged us
to either,'' said Lawrence.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the 1950s, Lawrence discovered that he enjoyed teaching,
thanks to a offer at the Pratt Institute in Brooklyn. After an
8-month trip to Nigeria, he was appointed an instructor at the New
School for Social Research.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence's mother died in 1968, after he had become a major
figure in the art world. ``She was proud, but she would have been
much happier if I'd had a job in the civil service,'' he said.
``For people of her generation, security was everything.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1971, he was offered a full professor, tenured faculty
position at the University of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never intended to stay more than 3 or 4 years,'' he said.
``But we established relationships and made commitments. It was a
gradual thing. I've always felt fortunate to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, he and his wife lived in a modest bungalow
within walking distance of the university.
</P>
<P>
   Classic New Yorkers, neither ever learned to drive. They now
live in a retirement complex on First Hill, which is nice without
being at all luxurious. They live modestly. Only this year could
their dealer Francine Seders persuade them to fly first class on
the longer flights.
</P>
<P>
   With little interest in the high life and a steady appreciation
of his own worth, Lawrence has been able to pace himself and
produce a great flowering in his later years.
</P>
<P>
   For his entire career, he has been odd man out from the art
mainstream. In the 1940s, he was considered a raw talent,
unschooled, even though he had been rigorously schooled by the
generation of Harlem artists who preceded him. In the 1950s and
1960s, he was considered decorative. As a figurate painter, he was
an odd man out in the New York art scene dominated by Abstract
Expressionism from the mid-'40s through the '50s. Nor was he any
closer to the movements that replaced it: Pop, Industrial Process,
Conceptualism and finally, in the '80s, Neo-Expressionism.
</P>
<P>
   Until the 1986 SAM retrospective revived his career, his name
didn't come up much in the art world.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, he has produced close to 1,100 works, estimated art
historican Peter Nesbett, director of the Jacob Lawrence Catalogue
Raisonne Project, an attempt to find and document all of his work.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence has continued to push the boundaries of what he can do,
retaining his edge as he increases his mastery, maybe because he
never allowed the spotlight to become essential.
</P>
<P>
   At 80, he still seeks to break new aesthetic ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``The search goes on for something else,'' he says. ``I don't
know what it is _ some other dimension I still hope to find.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
