<HEADLINE>
POPCORN IS JUST LETTING OFF STEAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Why does popcorn pop?
</P>
<P>
   _ J.N., Joshua, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: The pop occurs because of steam pressure that can't escape
the popcorn kernel any other way. Ideally, the unpopped kernel
contains approximately 13 percent moisture.
</P>
<P>
   Jolly Time, which began selling popcorn in 1914, answers your
question on its World Wide Web site at www.jollytime.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every kernel of popcorn is like a little steam engine,'' the
site says. Cracks in the kernel cause unpopped or partially popped
corn.
</P>
<P>
   Before the 1930s, popping problems prevented the product from
prospering, Jolly Time postulates. ``It was just too darn
unpredictable. Sometimes the kernels would pop ... and sometimes
they would just sit there and do nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can I write to Lea Thompson of ``Caroline in the City''
and buy a poster or other merchandise from the show?
</P>
<P>
   _ L.A.S., Hayward, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   A: Write to Thompson in care of the Gersh Agency, Box 5617,
Beverly Hills, Calif. 90210.
</P>
<P>
   No posters turn up, but the NBC Store in New York City sells
four different ``Caroline'' T-shirts and a baseball cap.
</P>
<P>
   These can be ordered by calling (800) 622-8760 or visiting the
World Wide Web page www.nbc.com/shop.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Did Victor Mature star in ``The Glory Brigade,'' a movie
about Greek soldiers during the Korean War? Also, where can I write
to him?
</P>
<P>
   _ G.O., Ridgefield Park, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   A: In the 1953 film, Mature played Lt. Sam Pryor, a
Greek-American who escorts troops from Greece on a reconnaissance
mission behind Communist lines.
</P>
<P>
   Fans can write to the 82-year-old actor and avid golfer at Box
706, Rancho Santa Fe, Calif. 92067.
</P>
<P>
   If the city sounds familiar, it's the community of 12,000 where
the Higher Source cult suicide took place in March 1997.
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
