<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-SEYMOUR-HERSH-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DIFFERENT TREATMENT FOR GULF WAR SYNDROME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 (Photo available through Wieck Photo Database)  
 By ED OFFLEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Investigative reporter Seymour Hersh for decades has
specialized in unearthing deeply buried government secrets and
recounting them in massive book-length treatments.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning with his 1969 expos &UR; gfacute &LR; e of the My Lai massacre
in Vietnam, in which a company of American soldiers gunned down
several hundred civilians, to his best seller last year, ``The Dark
Side of Camelot,'' which plumbed in depth the disturbing side of
John F. Kennedy's life, ranging from sexual misconduct to mafia
connections, Hersh has set a standard for thorough, in-depth
research.
</P>
<P>
   But in his latest project, an account of the mysterious Gulf War
Syndrome that has stricken more than 90,000 American veterans of
the Persian Gulf War, Hersh has taken a radically different tactic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Against All Enemies,'' (Library of Contemporary Thought, 103
pages, $8.95), is actually an in-depth magazine article formatted
into a soft-cover book format. Unlike his massive treatment of the
Kennedys, which required more than four years of full-time research
and spanned nearly 500 pages, Hersh wrote the 103-page Gulf War
project in four months. And speed did not necessarily translate
into loss of depth on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a tough, concise account of how the Pentagon,
military doctors, the Veterans Administration and White House
botched one of the biggest medical mysteries to emerge from combat
since the Agent Orange defoliant scandal from Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   In both cases, Hersh writes, there was not so much a deliberate
coverup of wrongdoing as a mindset to disbelieve an increasingly
credible avalanche of data.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning less than a year after the end of hostilities in the
Arabian desert in March 1991, a steadily increasing number of
veterans from the massive allied deployment began contracting a
baffling array of symptoms, including bone and joint aches, blurred
vision, night sweats and short-term memory loss. Until last year,
government experts dismissed the medical complaints as stemming
from stress, Hersh notes, a characterization insinuating the
veterans were imagining their symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter whether it (the source) is real or from
stress,'' Hersh said in a telephone interview this week. ``They are
sick.''
</P>
<P>
   Hersh was in Seattle Wednesday to discuss his Gulf War Syndrome
research at the University of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Hersh's book does not significantly break new ground in
revealing causes of the medical ailments, but it does succinctly
review how a growing number of activist veterans, concerned
congressmen and medical experts were able to overcome the
inattention and inertia of the Pentagon, White House and major news
media.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, he says, our increasing awareness of Gulf War
Syndrome and revelation of a host of potential health threats
(depleted uranium ammunition, Iraqi chemical and biological
stockpiles that survived the war, experimental drugs given soldiers
to protect them from the Iraqi materials) firmly repudiate the
televised smart-bomb image of Operation Desert Storm as a ``clean''
war.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got into this because of a father of one of the kids who
called me,'' Hersh said. ``I heard something I hadn't heard since
Vietnam: a radicalized father.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a parent myself and very sensitive
</P>
<P>
   to a parent talking about a son dying,'' he
</P>
<P>
   said.
</P>
<P>
   Hersh's book is the latest of a series of in-depth journalism
from the Library of Contemporary Thought, a publishing initiative
by the Ballantine Publishing Group that has been releasing similar
paperback treatments on a monthly basis.
</P>
<P>
   Hersh said the concept is needed because major magazines such as
The New Yorker no longer can accommodate full-length investigative
articles. Other works published under the series have included
``Team Rodent'' by Carl Hiaason, a critical examination of the Walt
Disney Co. empire in Florida, and ``News is a Verb'' by Pete
Hamill, a retrospective on
</P>
<P>
   his controversial and lengthy journalism career.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
