<SLUG> BC-ENTREPRENEUR-STUDIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDERSTANDING THE SPIRIT OF ENTREPRENEURSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHANA R. SCHOENBERGER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Alexander F. Kleiner 3d &UR;  &LR; is an entrepreneur through and through.
Last month, before fulfilling his dream of starting a company, he
earned an MBA &UR;  &LR; from the Massachusetts Institute of Technology's
Sloan School of Management. The following Monday, he founded
Frictionless Commerce Inc., an Internet shopping startup, with
three MIT Media Lab engineers.
</P>
<P>
   Kleiner, 30, credits a set of Sloan courses in ``New Venture and
Product Development,'' which trains students in the basic skills of
entrepreneurship, with helping him get Frictionless Commerce off
the ground. But he says it never would have been possible had he
not been passionate about his business idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always wanted to start my own company,'' says Kleiner,
the company's president. But taking classes helped turn that
passion into a reality. ``It's certainly easy to guide people who
have some predisposition'' toward entrepreneurship, he adds.
</P>
<P>
   Kleiner and other young company founders with MBAs shed new
light on the longstanding question of whether entrepreneurship can
be taught. &UR;  &LR; Critics of entrepreneurial studies programs argue that
entrepreneurship is an instinct or talent _ involving passion,
creativity, and drive _ that cannot be taught. Academicians at
Sloan, Harvard Business School, and Babson College, which have
entrepreneurship programs for MBA students, counter that a
masters-level curriculum that teaches specific business skills is
critical for success in the fiercely competitive startup market. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   But the young entrepreneurs themselves say both the talent and
the toolbox are needed: Instinctive entrepreneurial drive and
classroom-taught business skills can both be essential.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you can teach somebody to be an entrepreneur,''
says Deborah E. Frieze, a 28-year-old partner at the Boston-based
Internet consulting startup Zefer Corp. ``You just have to have an
incredible amount of passion, spirit, and drive.''
</P>
<P>
   Frieze, who received her MBA from Harvard Business School last
month, came to entrepreneurship by an unusual path. A longtime
skiing and boating enthusiast, the Newton, Mass. native graduated
from Amherst College and promptly headed to Colorado to be a ski
instructor, or ``ski bum for a year,'' as she puts it. While editor
of the ski magazine Snow Country, Frieze realized that she wanted
to work on both the business and news sides of publishing.
</P>
<P>
   A family history of entrepreneurship is among the key indicators
of entrepreneurial traits in business people, according to MIT
Entrepreneurship Center director Kenneth P. Morse. Frieze fits this
profile: her father started his own business.
</P>
<P>
   But it was at Harvard Business School that Frieze discovered a
long-dormant strain of entrepreneurship within herself. She
accepted a founding position with Zefer, where she runs the
company's content development for its Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Business school, Frieze says, taught her the nuts and bolts of
running a company, but it couldn't teach her to love the
entrepreneurial life. Her business partner agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The parts that can be taught are the parts that are common to
every business, such as the fundamentals of strategy and the
fundamentals of finance,'' says Anthony K. Tjan, Zefer's chief
executive officer and a Harvard Business classmate of Frieze. An
entrepreneurial spirit since childhood, Tjan, 28, credits Harvard
Business School with teaching him the skills he needed to run his
business.
</P>
<P>
   He and some friends entered and won the school's annual business
plan competition with their plan for Zefer, and he says his
professors acted as ``true advisers,'' helping him understand the
intricacies of a venture financing deal he secured with
Toronto-based Mosaic Venture Partners.
</P>
<P>
   Zefer, which is renovating office space on South Street in
Boston, has 12 fulltime employees and receives 10 to 15 resumes a
week from job-seekers. The firm has signed up two major clients and
projects revenue of ``several hundred thousand dollars this
quarter,'' Tjan says.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, would-be entrepreneurs, lured by stories like
Zefer's, have turned to business schools to teach them the
practicalities of starting a business. Of the 900 students in the
Harvard Business School Class of 1998, 90 percent took one elective
class in entrepreneurship; 25 percent took three classes. And 22
percent of the Class of 1997 took jobs with small companies,
according to the school. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   At Babson, a school known for its entrepreneurial studies, 30
percent of 1,600 undergraduates major in entrepreneurship, making
it the most popular major. And about 340 MBA students at the
Wellesley school enter the annual second-year business plan
competition, says entrepreneurship professor Julian E. Lange,
contest's faculty adviser.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Sloan MBA students also favor entrepreneurship; New Product
and Venture Development was the second most popular track for MBAs
in the 1997-98 academic year.
</P>
<P>
   In entrepreneurship classes, students learn how to run a startup
from conception to initial public offering, taking classes such as
Sloan's ``Entrepreneurial Marketing,'' ``Starting and Running a
High Tech Company,'' and ``The Nuts and Bolts of Business Plans.''
They also network with other students, often forming partnerships
which can blossom into businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people I've been developing this concept with are great,''
says Kleiner, of his partners. ``We've had dinner every week since
October.''
</P>
<P>
   In the debate over entrepreneurship education, professors say
they're tired of defending an educational field &UR;  &LR; which has
spawned &UR;  &LR; multiple successful companies.
</P>
<P>
   Morse, himself the founder of six companies, scoffs at the idea
that entrepreneurship is purely innate. ``That's like saying
someone has to be born a fighter pilot,'' he says. ``Would you put
somebody in a $16 million plane and say, `You look like Tom Cruise,
why don't you fly this plane?''' he notes, referring to the movie
``Top Gun.''
</P>
<P>
   But academics and students agree the fundamental drive which
impels every entrepreneur cannot be taught.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you walk into the class saying, `Teach me to be an
entrepreneur,' you're not going to get it,'' says Babson MBA
Michael A. Healey, 33, who founded PCBuild Upgrade Centers Inc., a
hardware servicing firm in Needham which will have $5 million in
sales this fiscal year. ``If you say, `I want to be an
entrepreneur, what am I missing?' you'll do better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
