<HEADLINE>
LEGIONS OF LEES LAND IN MASSACHUSETTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHANIE EBBERT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ There was Yon Lee and Wilson Lee, David Lee and Yolanda
Lee, Steven Lee and Dan Lee. There were short Lees and tall Lees,
boisterous and demure Lees, jittery Lees and self-assured Lees.
</P>
<P>
   Big enough to fill a banquet hall, the Lee family descended on
Boston's Chinatown this week for a reunion of roughly 350 members
from across the United States, Canada, and Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Though they do not all share a bloodline, they share the most
common surname in the world and a familial spirit that has linked
Lees _ in formal associations _ for 122 years.
</P>
<P>
   With an estimated 100 million Lees worldwide _ including 100,000
in the United States and 5,000 in Greater Boston _ it's quite a
family. The Lees are so numerous they own seven credit union
branches with $22 million in assets and buy buildings that serve as
cultural centers and meeting places in various cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``All Lees are not immediate relatives,'' said Yon Lee, the
English secretary of the Lee Family Association of New England.
``We follow the Confucius philosophy _ under the family tree, all
people of the same surname, at one time or another, came from the
same forefathers.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lees say they descended from the ancient philosopher Lao
Tzu, the founder of Taoism, who lived about 2,500 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The family reunion _ also called a convention, bringing together
``delegates'' from various cities _ is primarily social, but also
includes elections and meetings on fund-raising and launching more
credit unions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoever shares the last name of Lee can come _ besides Robert
E. Lee's descendants,'' jokes Steven Lee of San Francisco, the
group's grand national president.
</P>
<P>
   With only 10 delegates, compared to San Francisco's 40, Boston
won the rare opportunity to host this year's convention _ the last
of the millennium, since they're held every three years. Dynasty
restaurant owner Wilson Lee, who heads the New England chapter and
hopes to win election as grand national president at the
convention, excitedly bustled through the banquet, ushering people
to their seats.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in the back of a San Francisco store by two Lee brothers
in 1866, the Lee Family Association has sprouted 18 chapters since
then. The Lees have banded together for financial and moral support
and even to generate political power.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been here for 150 years and we're still second-class
citizens,'' said Steven Lee. ``The only way the Chinese can get
more into the mainstream is to get more into politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Their best-known relative is Bill Lann Lee, the assistant
attorney general for civil rights who was appointed by President
Clinton late last year.
</P>
<P>
   Financial assistance is one of the benefits of membership. ``It
helped me when I purchased a restaurant. I went there to borrow
money,'' said Steven Lee.
</P>
<P>
   But the association is best known as a friendly connection in an
unfamiliar place. What began as a support group providing food,
shelter and medical treatment for immigrant laborers facing
hostility and hardship has evolved into a networking group for
immigrant or non-immigrant Lees moving to new locales.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Lee, who met his cousin through the association, said his
nephew needed a hand when he came to Harvard University. Steven
Lee's son was at Harvard Medical School and, a few phone calls
later, the sons were linked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nowadays, a lot of people go to city government for help,''
said Al Lee, who noted the family association provides more
personal aid. ``All you need is to say the name of your village and
they'll know someone from the area.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Wire service material was used to prepare this repot.)
</P>
</TEXT>
