<SLUG> BC-ATTACK-TURKEY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POSTAL SERVICE WON'T DISPATCH WILD TURKEY TO NEW HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ELIZABETH BENJAMIN  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Neither rain nor snow ... nor a wild turkey will
keep the postman away.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the bird that has been attacking mail trucks and preventing
postal deliveries on a leafy residential street here will not be
dispatched to a new home.
</P>
<P>
   Under an arrangement worked about between the residents of
Loughlin Street and the U.S. Postal Service, homeowners agreed to
move their mailboxes to the curbside.
</P>
<P>
   This will allow the letter carrier to deliver mail without
having to get out of the mail truck and risking a turkey attack,
said Mary Madonna, spokeswoman for the Postal Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hoping that the turkey will get accustomed to the new
system, and that will be the end of it,'' Madonna said.
</P>
<P>
   The turkey, which lives in the woods around Loughlin Street,
began periodically assaulting the mail truck last winter, neighbors
said. Frightened that he would hurt the bird, the postman stopped
delivering mail. Residents had to pick up their letters at the post
office.
</P>
<P>
   The Postal Service offered to have the bird trapped, but
residents refused, saying they had grown to like it.
</P>
<P>
   The new arrangement is fine with turkey-loving residents, said
James Palmer, 76, of 5 Loughlin St.
</P>
<P>
   But the bird has kept a low profile recently. Loughlin Street
residents say they have received their mail without incident for
the past week.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Hollister, former wildlife biologist with the New York
Department of Environmental Conservation, said the bird might have
perceived the red, white and blue mail truck as a competitor. But
now that the mating season has ended, so has the bird's aggressive
behavior, he theorized.
</P>
<P>
   ``Birds have a tendency to get more belligerent during the
mating season,'' Hollister said. ``They start in early March and
continue until June or as long as there are receptive hens
around.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
