A7898 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAMILIES-ADVISORY-NYT     07-02 0538
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILIES-ADVISORY-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (ATTN: Managing editors, lifestyle editors) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service calls your attention to the
following families features.
</P>
<P>
   The stories are from The New York Times (NYT), The Boston Globe
(BOS), Cox News Service (COX), and Hearst Newspapers (HNS).
</P>
<P>
   Photos, where indicated, have been sent to NYT photo clients.
Graphics, where indicated, have been sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   For retransmission of these stories, call 212-556-1927.
</P>
<P>
   KIDS-PRIVACY-MEDIA-NYT (Undated) _ A look at the commercial Web
sites cited in the FTC's recent online privacy report as the most
intrusive into children's privacy.
</P>
<P>
   TEEN-JOBS-COX (Austin) _ More than 3 million teens nationwide
work summer jobs _ and this year, with the nation's lowest
unemployment rate in a generation, more teens may have a better
pick of the jobs they want and it already looks as if more teens
are working. But there's more to a summer job than just money, and
several experts say teens can walk away from a summer job with
valuable experience in addition to cash.
</P>
<P>
   TEACHERS-SQUEEZE-BOS (Undated) _ With the baby boomlet bulging
enrollments and teachers hired for the baby boom poised to retire,
the nation will find itself replacing 2 million of its 2.7 million
teachers over the next eight years. By Kate Zernike.
</P>
<P>
   TEACHERS-TESTING-BOS (Undated) _ How Japan and some other
countries are dealing with the teaching question more effectively
than the United States. By Kate Zernike.
</P>
<P>
   BLOND-BOYS-KAN (Kansas City) _ Guys bleaching their hair blond
is all the rage. By Katherine Dykstra.
</P>
<P>
   MENTAL CRUELTY-AZR (Phoenix) - We hear a lot about the physical
side of domestic abuse, but the mental cruelty - ranging from the
mean to the bizarre - leaves wounds and scars that often endure
much longer. By Ginger Scott.
</P>
<P>
   TV-FAMILY-TIES-NYT (Undated) _ Considering the general flood of
television shows, it's startling to realize that at the height of
its popularity in the 1980s, ``Family Ties'' ranked as one of the
most-watched shows not just of the moment but in the history of
television. Watching four episodes just released on videocassette
by Columbia House, one might wonder why but there is no doubt how
well a top sitcom can serve its era before passing on. By Peter M.
Nichols.
</P>
<P>
   KIDSBOOKS-AZR (Undated) _ June's kid books range from counting
red-eyed tree frogs to scary disaster stories to a scholarly
collection of biographical portraits of queens. One highlight is an
innovative series called ``We Both Read.'' It is designed to make
story time more interactive for beginning readers, with parents and
children taking turns reading each page. By Beverly Medlyn.
</P>
<P>
   KIDPORN-COX (Atlanta) _ Federal investigators say it was not
unusual for 25-year-old Stephen Parrish of Atlanta to spend six
hours a day in front of his computer, cruising the Internet. But
unlike most people who use the Internet for research or legitimate
entertainment, Parrish had a more sinister motive, searching for
child pornography and stalking young boys in teen chat rooms. By
Ron Martz.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
