<SLUG> BC-GINGRICH-ALAMO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GINGRICH TOUTS ALAMO AS SYMBOL OF FREEDOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAIME CASTILLO  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ House Speaker Newt Gingrich satisfied an old
historical itch Wednesday with a private tour of the Alamo as he
continued crisscrossing the nation, gauging reaction to a possible
presidential bid in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia Republican also attended a GOP fund-raising event
before going to Dallas to address the national convention of the
League of United Latin American Citizens.
</P>
<P>
   The former history professor described his first visit to the
storied Alamo, a Franciscan mission that became a symbol of Texas
independence, as remarkable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really about freedom,'' Gingrich beamed after emerging
from a 40-minute guided tour before the historic site opened to the
public. ``Just as freedom was the issue at the Alamo, it is an
issue around the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich, 55, said he was impressed by the number of Texans of
Hispanic descent who died during the famed battle of 1836 against
the forces of Mexican General Antonio Lopez de Santa Anna.
</P>
<P>
   Continuing the Hispanic-friendly theme, Gingrich said his speech
to the Hispanic convention would involve an inclusive theme aimed
at attracting more minorities to the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe every American of every background deserves a
better education,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich told reporters that Texas Gov. George W. Bush was a
``serious, honorable man'' who is ``definitely a contender'' for
the 2000 presidential nomination, if he chooses to run.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, a Republican and son of the former president, is expected
to easily win re-election this year in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   On his own presidential aspirations, Gingrich said he would not
make a decision until Labor Day 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
