<SLUG> BC-PR-STATEHOOD-$ADV04-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE UNLIKELY TO APPROVE PROCESS FOR PUERTO RICAN STATEHOOD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release over the July 4 weekend)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senate Republican leaders have this good news for
Michael Liberman: You won't have to toss out your inventory of
50-star flags any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   Liberman, president of Valley Forge Flag Company, Inc., in
Womelsdorf, Pa., the nation's largest retail flag maker, has been
fretting that moves in Congress to make Puerto Rico the 51st state
would leave him with a huge inventory of outdated Old Glorys.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't lobby for statehood from a flag manufacturing point of
view,'' said Liberman. ``It's no picnic.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the House voted in March for a plan for Puerto Rico to
hold a plebiscite on whether its 3.9 million residents wanted to
become a state or be totally independent or retain their present
commonwealth status, the measure appears dead in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The residents of Puerto Rico already are U.S. citizens and serve
in the U.S. military. They have a local government like most states
and get most federal services, like the U.S. Postal Office, but get
a smaller share of programs for the needy like Medicaid.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike residents of the 50 states, Puerto Ricans aren't
represented by voting members of Congress and they can't vote for
president. They also don't pay federal taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The last time Puerto Ricans voted on their future political
status, in 1993, they showed themselves ambivalent: 48 percent
favored the current commonwealth status, 46 percent wanted
statehood and 4 percent preferred total independence.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, some Puerto Ricans think Congress should act this
year because 1998 marks the 100th anniversary of the U.S.
annexation of Puerto Rico as part of the spoils from the
Spanish-American War.
</P>
<P>
   If a congressionally approved plebiscite were held anytime soon,
polls in Puerto Rico indicate the statehood option would likely get
the most votes. If a majority opted for statehood, the House-passed
bill would give Congress 10 years to decide whether to grant
statehood to Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   The issue's apparent death in the Senate stems from two factors.
</P>
<P>
   First, there are the ``cultural'' opponents of Puerto Rican
statehood led by Sen. Don Nickles, R-Okla., the assistant majority
leader.
</P>
<P>
   Nickles says he doesn't believe Puerto Rico should become a
state because ``there are very significant cultural differences,
language, traditions and culture'' between Puerto Rico and the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, who supports the plebiscite plan, disagrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``To use their culture to bar them from voting rights or
responsibilities in our country, if they so choose to seek them by
majority vote, is wrong,'' Clinton said earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Nickles also says he has ``strong reservations'' about the House
bill because it ``really seems tilted toward statehood.''
</P>
<P>
   At any rate, he adds, it's ``not going to be on the (Senate's)
calendar this year.''
</P>
<P>
   The second factor is that no one knows whether Democrats or
Republicans would occupy all or most of the two new Senate seats
and six new House seats that Puerto Rican statehood would bring to
Congress. Given this uncertainty, senators are reluctant to change
the political status quo.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Larry E. Craig, R-Idaho, No. 4 in the Senate Republican
leadership and a supporter of a plebiscite in Puerto Rico, says the
uncertainty is one reason the issue won't come up in the Senate
this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would it be Democrat or Republican?'' Craig said. ``Nobody
knows. Who can predict the politics of Puerto Rico 10 years down
the road?''
</P>
<P>
   About 70 percent of Puerto Rico's local senators and
representatives are Republicans and their legislature recently
approved such Republican agenda items as school tuition vouchers,
school prayer and income and capital gains tax cuts. On the other
hand, with the average wage in Puerto Rico at about $11,000 a year,
there's speculation that traditional Democratic programs might
appeal to many voters there.
</P>
<P>
   Others predict that the political party that Puerto Ricans
perceive as championing statehood could expect to cash in.
</P>
<P>
   Craig cites Alaska and Hawaii, which joined the union in 1959
and 1960 respectively, as examples of political unpredictability.
While many senators thought Alaska would be a Democratic state and
Hawaii would be Republican, the opposite has generally been the
case.
</P>
<P>
   The reluctance on the part of lawmakers is easy to understand,
Craig said. ``It's very simple, you count numbers.'' Puerto Rico,
with nearly 3.9 million residents, would be larger than 24 states,
which means it would have more House members than nearly half the
states.
</P>
<P>
   At least some Republicans think a GOP push for Puerto Rican
statehood would help erase any lingering anti-Hispanic blemish on
the party stemming from California Gov. Pete Wilson's energetic
campaigns against bilingual education, illegal immigration, state
benefits to illegal immigrants and affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   Xavier Romeu, the Washington lobbyist for Puerto Rico Gov. Pedro
Rossello, warned that words coming from the Senate about cultural
differences between Puerto Ricans and the rest of the United States
smack of racism and will not play well in the territory and among
American Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republican party can ill afford such anti-Hispanic
sentiment,'' Romeu said. ``It is a time bomb for Republicans
because if they fail to act, it will look like racism.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican Pollster Frank Luntz advised House Speaker Newt
Gingrich, R-Ga., who pushed for the House bill, that pressing for
Puerto Rican self-determination would be a good way to appeal to
Hispanic voters around the nation.
</P>
<P>
   But the razor-thin vote in the House in March, 209 to 208, was
too close to sweep the issue onto the Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bob Graham, D-Fla., a co-sponsor with Craig of the bill in
the Senate, said the centennial of Puerto Rico's acquisition by the
United States ``would be an ideal time'' for a referendum.
</P>
<P>
   However, Graham said Congress should not put statehood up as an
option if the lawmakers are not prepared to grant it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst thing we could do is set up a plebiscite and then
not respect their choice,'' Graham said. ``That would go to the
core of issues of dignity and respect that are so critical to U.S.
relations in the Western hemisphere. If people feel this is a
beauty contest and it doesn't carry any consequences, then they
should vote no.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
