<SLUG> BC-ASHCROFT-GOP-$ADV04-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP SEN. JOHN ASHCROFT AIMS FOR PRESIDENTIAL RUN IN 2000 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For weekend release)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Staunch conservative Sen. John Ashcroft is battling
to break out of political obscurity and become the Republican
Party's new version of Ronald Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   Like Reagan, Ashcroft, 56, is a former governor. And although he
lacks Reagan's Hollywood credentials, Ashcroft is a baritone with
the ``Singing Senators'' (which includes Senate Majority Leader
Trent Lott), writes his own gospel tunes and has performed on stage
with country music stars including Ray Stevens and the Oak Ridge
Boys.
</P>
<P>
   The presidential election is two years off, but Ashcroft,
Missouri's first-term junior senator, is already elbowing his way
into a crowded field of GOP 2000 possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush, seen as a moderate conservative, is
the early darling of the party establishment. Publishing magnate
Steve Forbes, commentator Patrick Buchanan and former Vice
President Dan Quayle all loom large as Ashcroft competitors for
support among the party's hard-core conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   But none of that is stopping the senator from trying to be the
nominee who bridges the gap between the party's often-contentious
hardline conservative wings _ social conservatives, who favor
school prayer and oppose legal abortion, and fiscal conservatives,
who want major tax cuts and minimal government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoever leads the Republican Party in 2000 (has to) motivate
both of those streams,'' Ashcroft said at a recent lunch with
reporters. ``If you can't, I don't think you'll win. But if you
have both energized, you'll succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   So far Ashcroft has succeeded in winning support from Paul
Weyrich, a leading conservative thinker who is president of the
Washington-based Free Congress Foundation. In an interview Weyrich
called Ashcroft ``non-threatening'' and said that by contrast,
``one reason brother Pat (Buchanan) couldn't get elected (in 1992
and 1996) was that, stylistically, he was threatening.'' Ashcroft,
with much the same message as Buchanan, ``is somebody who is
attractive and saleable,'' Weyrich added.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft, a former law professor at Southwest Missouri State
University, has a long record of public service back home. He was
state auditor and state attorney general as well as a two-term
governor before winning his U.S. Senate seat in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Anxious to prove his bridge-building credentials, he cites his
record in balancing eight budgets in a row. On his watch, Missouri
adopted a restrictive abortion law that the U.S. Supreme Court
upheld in a landmark 1989 decision.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft's aides trumpet his current role in ratcheting up the
tax cut in the Senate Republicans' proposed 1999 budget. It had
been pegged at $30 billion, but last month GOP Senate leaders,
under pressure from Ashcroft and others, doubled it.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft is a champion of killing the so-called marriage
penalty, which requires many married couples to pay higher taxes
together than if each were single. The issue, Ashcroft insists,
appeals to conservatives of every stripe within the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   His political consultant, Keith Appell, calls Ashcroft ``the
best man to reunite the economic and social conservatives, which is
the Reagan formula for victory. That's why he's viewed as the most
electable conservative.''
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft also has sharply criticized President Clinton on the
Monica Lewinsky matter, calling Clinton ``a president who views a
vulnerable woman from the perspective of a predator.'' At the same
time, he has criticized fellow Republicans for failing to go on the
offensive over allegations that Clinton had a sexual relationship
with the former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   An evangelical Christian, Ashcroft leads his office staff in
prayer each morning. The senator, who has the demeanor of a
thank-you-ma'am Boy Scout, wins praise from the Christian Coalition
and popular Christian broadcaster James C. Dobson for his
opposition to the National Endowment for the Arts and his efforts
to win federal funding for religiously oriented organizations that
run homeless shelters and drug and alcohol rehabilitation programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``John Ashcroft has turned the heads of a lot of social
conservatives in this country,'' says Randy Tate, a former House
member from Washington state and executive director of the
Christian Coalition, which does not endorse candidates. ``He has a
message that resonates with the grassroots.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Ashcroft is running uphill. His name recognition is
nowhere near that of his chief conservative rivals.
</P>
<P>
   And if he were to win the nomination, ``he's not the kind of
candidate who could move back to the center, where most voters
are,'' said Stephen Hess, a presidential scholar at the Brookings
Institution. ``It would give the Democrat a great advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   A similar view was expressed by Mark Miller, executive director
of the Republican Leadership Council, which seeks to offset the
grip of social conservatives on the party. ``Republicans who focus
on narrow litmus-test issues have lost in the past and are going to
keep losing,'' Miller said. ``We want the party to focus on issues
that unite all Republicans.'' But he added that ``if Ashcroft does
that, I think he'll find some success.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ashcroft's political action committee, Spirit of America, has $1
million in the bank and is likely to take in another million by the
end of the year, says its director, Jack Oliver. Since declaring
his interest in seeking the nomination last August, Ashcroft has
visited such key states as Iowa six times, including a visit this
weekend, and New Hampshire twice.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft said he will make up his mind about running in October
or November. He figures he would have to raise $20 million to mount
an effective campaign. His attractiveness to big conservative
contributors hovers as a question mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one thing to have good ideas,'' said Tate of the
Christian Coalition. ``But if no one hears you, it doesn't do any
good.''
</P>
<P>
   Slowly, the GOP faithful are beginning to take notice. In March,
Ashcroft placed fifth with 9 percent in a straw poll of Republican
leaders in Biloxi, Miss. Bush was first with 18 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In a CBS News poll of Republican voters in April, Ashcroft
received only 2 percent. Bush had 25 percent. But in May, Ashcroft
was No. 1 in a poll of Republican activists in South Carolina,
taking 32 percent of the vote to Bush's 15 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
