<P>
   SHARP-COLUMN-COX (Atlanta) _ One of the greatest challenges
facing any automaker today is bringing the right product to market.
Few would argue that Mercedes-Benz is doing an exceptional job: the
E-Class, sporty SLK and M-Class sport-utility vehicle are all
blessed with exceptional customer demand. Just how does a carmaker
make the right decision at the right time? Many rely on research
groups, previous sales data and managerial skills. By Linda Sharp.
</P>
<P>
   TESTDRIVE-COX (Atlanta) _ It's not going to happen, but wouldn't
it be nice if all pickups came with extended cabs and a third door?
Of course, there'll always be buyers for two-door, regular-cab
models, but it's amazing how much convenience and utility the extra
space and door add, particularly to a compact like the Chevrolet
S-10. By Russ DeVault.
</P>
<P>
   ABOUT-CARS-MAZDA (Undated) _ The Mazda Miata, sports roadster,
has turned out to be a breath of fresh air. Mazda has now sold more
than 450,000 Miatas worldwide, more than half in North America to
young people buying their one and only car and to nostalgic baby
boomers who have made it as the second or even third car in their
household fleet. By Michelle Krebs.
</P>
<P>
   CAR-SMART-MIATA (Undated) _ The first redesign of the Mazda
Miata sports car since it was introduced in 1989 has helped make
the Miata Club of America's annual gathering this week in the
Pocono Mountains of Pennsylvania a sell-out. By Michelle Krebs.
</P>
