<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-GERMANY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERMAN WILL IS SYMBOL OF ITS SOCCER PRESENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: A version of this feature was sent and held yesterday.
Please use this version.) 
 (JT)  
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Of all the World Cup quarterfinalists, the Germans have
looked, at times, the most inept. Indeed, at home, they have been
compared to the Russian space station MIR, staggering from mishap
to mishap but somehow staying aloft.
</P>
<P>
   Clumsy, strangely disorganized, the team has often looked like a
group of aging has-beens. Coach Berti Vogts has experimented with
so many players in midfield _ even dropping what looked like the
best of them, the 25-year-old Jens Jeremies _ that attempts to
discern his strategy have seemed futile.
</P>
<P>
   But soccer's supreme competition is much more than a test of
skill, as England's epic struggle with Argentina showed. When, as
now, the final rounds loom, the game moves beyond the control and
distribution of a ball to the realm of psychological confrontation.
Nations unwittingly bear their souls in what amounts to
life-and-death struggles for victory.
</P>
<P>
   This is an area in which the German team _ known simply at home
as the ``Mannschaft'' (The Team) _ has excelled, regularly coming
from behind, often in the last minutes, to reach a remarkable six
finals and nine semifinals in thirteen World Cup appearances. It
has won the trophy three times, a record surpassed only by Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the classic image of the German team comes from the 1982
World Cup semifinal against France. With his team trailing 3-1 to
France and minutes left to play, the great striker Karl-Heinz
Rummenigge came on as substitute and immediately removed his shin
guards.
</P>
<P>
   By disdainfully hurling away his protection, Rummenigge was
declaring that the real battle, unsoftened and unfettered, had
begun. France, with perhaps its greatest team ever, and one clearly
more skilled than the German, shuddered. Germany surged back to 3-3
and won the game on a penalty shootout.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone has his own conception of tactics,'' Jurgen
Klinsmann, the German captain, said here this week. ``For
ourselves, we try to concentrate on our power. That is to say, we
try to build the pressure, increase the pressure, until the
adversary finally cracks and is overwhelmed.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, ability counts, but so, too, does the sheer
strength of character and self-belief that alone can keep tide
after tide of attacks coming and turn near-certain defeat into
victory. It is this quality of the Germans that strikes fear into
opponents who, on paper, have superior players.
</P>
<P>
   Klinsmann, who has played more than 100 times for Germany, was
speaking after Germany had reached the quarterfinals here by
beating Mexico 2-1. It was a textbook German victory against a team
that often seemed more skilled. Two goals in the last 15 minutes,
by Klinsmann and fellow striker Oliver Bierhoff, literally
shattered the Mexicans, who had seemed headed for a surprise 1-0
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the tournament, Germany trailed Yugoslavia 2-0 with
20 minutes left and came back to tie the game 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   On the way to its first World Cup victory in 1954 in
Switzerland, Germany was thrashed 8-3 in an opening game against
Hungary but nonetheless qualified for the knockout rounds. In the
final, it faced Hungary again. Within minutes the Hungarians took a
2-0 lead and the match seemed over. But the Germans came back to
win, 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   The Germans are in the final eight yet again, playing Croatia on
Saturday. It seems, more than ever, that sheer force of character
has brought them this far. For this, by any estimate, is not a
great squad. Indeed, its midfield has often resembled nothing so
much as a great and gloomy void.
</P>
<P>
   What then keeps the ``Mannschaft'' going here, urged onward by
the 34-year-old Klinsmann and the 37-year-old sweeper Lothar
Matthaus? Where does this exceptional will to win find its roots?
</P>
<P>
   The expression of national pride has, of course, been a
difficult issue for Germans ever since World War II. In the soccer
team the nation clearly finds a uniquely powerful symbol for values
of strength, determination and cohesion that cannot readily be
displayed elsewhere. While every country takes pride in its soccer
team, not every country takes pride in the team's moral fiber and
will power above all else.
</P>
<P>
   But with so many players over 30, and so many evident problems
in the team, a fourth triumph still looks like a long shot, despite
the fine performances of striker Oliver Bierhoff, the best header
of the ball in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the team's repeated last-minute comebacks here,
left-back Christian Ziege said this week, ``It is time we won a
game safely, otherwise our fans will die of heart attacks.''
</P>
<P>
   Historically, however, the heart attacks have generally been
suffered by Germany's opponents. France, which will meet Germany in
the semifinal if the teams win against Italy and Croatia
respectively, still bears the scars of that 1982 game which seemed
to many French commentators to reflect an old French inferiority
complex with respect to its powerful neighbor. France has never won
the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   As the French sports columnist Roland Gransart commented
laconically this week of the German side, ``Defeat? Never heard of
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
