<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 16:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8029 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COX-CHINA-ASSESS     07-02 1459
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-CHINA-ASSESS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    (ANALYSIS: CLINTON'S VISIT BRINGS NEW OPENNESS IN CHINA, BUT FOR
HOW LONG?
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By MARCIA KUNSTEL and JOSEPH ALBRIGHT 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service (at)
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ For the first time, Chinese from village leaders to
Communist Party Central Committee staff talked openly this week to
Americans about what has been a taboo topic _ taking direct
elections beyond the very lowest grass roots level in China.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's new thinking or just new talking about thoughts
that have lain hidden in Chinese minds for years, Robert Pastor, a
foreign policy expert with the Carter Center in Atlanta, believes
the change his delegation of elections consultants saw this week
was a rapid response to President Clinton's trip to China.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Clinton visit will change America's relationships
with China in operative ways,'' said Pastor, whose delegation
happened to be visiting the country simultaneously with Clinton.
``We found that the visit seemed to break down some officials'
reluctance to talk about sensitive issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether the change will last is altogether another question.
</P>
<P>
   What did the most to break down old ways was the unprecedented
joint news conference on June 27, when Clinton and China's
President Jiang Zemin aired their differing views about democracy
and individual rights on live television.
</P>
<P>
   Live, uncensored television coverage of that event and of
Clinton's major speech on Monday, which also dug into sensitive
human rights issues, was the most important victory the White House
attained on the nine-day China tour that was ending here Friday.
Appearances on a later Shanghai radio call-in show and a television
interview added two mini-achievements.
</P>
<P>
   But these were victories that came at a price to the Clinton
administration. They also were victories whose repercussions could
continue rippling down a positive course or could catch in an
undertow disastrous for the administration's goals of engendering
democracy and freedom in China.
</P>
<P>
   In the short-term, a key feature of that polite but tense
confrontation between Jiang and Clinton was its ending. The two
leaders stepped out of the ring smiling.
</P>
<P>
   And the fact that President Jiang held a well-publicized,
friendly dinner to say goodbye to the Clintons the next day
reinforced the message that debate at least on some levels can be
tolerated.
</P>
<P>
   It was followed by the surprising openness found by Carter
Center consultants who have been wandering around the countryside
for two years trying to help village elections proceed like they do
in a seasoned democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Their experience was probably more than just a fluke.
</P>
<P>
   Journalists sampling the Chinese reaction have met the same
phenomenon as the Carter Center team _ a shy opening that is far
from universal yet still noticeable among average Chinese. This
week, many Chinese who were queried on streets, in the train
station or at the infamous Tiananmen Square were willing to talk
about democracy and individual rights. The number was much greater
than in early June around the ninth anniversary of the crushing of
the Tiananmen Square democracy movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where it leads or what it amounts to or what additional things
might happen as a result of that type of opening is something
that's not entirely clear to us,'' White House spokesman Mike
McCurry said late this week. ``Maybe it's not even clear to the
Chinese authorities themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, the administration gives this an optimistic spin.
``We hope it signals some reconsideration of the degree to which
this has been a very closed political culture,'' McCurry said.
``Having made a conscious decision to be that open, it sometimes
becomes hard to reverse decisions like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, over the past quarter century the Chinese have
found it quite easy to reverse such decisions, despite the high
cost. Just ask the students who mounted the Tiananmen Square
protests that lasted for weeks before the government decided to act
against them. Ask the families of the hundreds who were killed by
government troops.
</P>
<P>
   What will happen if tens of thousands of Chinese start demanding
those freedoms Clinton said they deserve?
</P>
<P>
   McCurry noted that Jiang Zemin and the leaders who permitted the
live telecast of Clinton's sometimes hard words made a decision
``fraught with great risk.''
</P>
<P>
   So far there has been no manifestation of high level, internal
party dissent over that decision, which led to millions of Chinese
people viewing Clinton's exceptional public criticism of China's
policies. None of the politburo's seven standing committee members
boycotted the state dinner for Clinton held just hours after the
remarkable joint news conference.
</P>
<P>
   But party dissension isn't normally evident until it is acted
upon through the removal of officials or change of policies or
order to send out tanks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand,'' McCurry went on, ``that it's incumbent on us
to maximize the reward for doing the right thing and minimize the
opportunities for those who would try to exploit what some might
call 'weakness' on the part of the Chinese leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   Later he added that administration officials ``obviously want to
try to help the good guys as much as we can'' in China.
</P>
<P>
   And giving that ``reward'' to ``the good guys'' was the price of
airing American views.
</P>
<P>
   The first cost was paid when Clinton received the formal state
welcome outside the Great Hall of the People on the western edge of
Tiananmen Square. Participating in the ceremony there, with
saluting canon positioned on the square at the same place the
students' tents met tank treads, will be rightly viewed by many
pro-democracy activists here and abroad as closing the books on the
Chinese regime's 1989 violent crackdown on nonviolent protest.
</P>
<P>
   To some extent, Clinton has already paid with his reputation _
mainly among idealists who refuse to accept realpoliticking as the
basis for American foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   The second price was Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   In the statement Clinton seemed to toss off during a roundtable
discussion in Shanghai on Tuesday, he offered up to the Chinese
leadership the single most valuable gift he could have given.
</P>
<P>
   He became the first U.S. president to utter the ``three no's''
policy _ no support for Taiwan's independence, no support of a
``two China'' policy or a ``one China, one Taiwan'' policy, and no
support for Taiwanese membership in international organizations
whose members are sovereign countries. This was the message the top
Chinese leadership said they wanted to hear from Clinton in the
days leading up to the summit.
</P>
<P>
   To Western ears the ``three no's'' don't sound like much,
considering that other leading U.S. officials including the
secretary of state have repeated that the formula is American
policy.
</P>
<P>
   But it means something vital to Taiwanese, especially those
increasingly popular opposition figures in the Democratic
Progressive Party who do support independence and feel their
adherence to democractic principles earns them the right to form
their own nation. They will run in legislative elections at the end
of the year, which will be followed in the year 2000 by
presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
   With the President himself for the first time ever enunciating
the ``three no's,'' it is a clear statement that those
pro-independence forces will not get U.S. support, even if they win
overwhelming support of their own people at the polls.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton statement looked a lot like a trade-off with the
Chinese leadership, the quid the U.S. gave for the Chinese quo of
granting Clinton unfettered access to the air waves and thus to the
Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
   The day after the Chinese finally granted him his second live
access to a mass television audience, reporters noted a curious
last-minute switch in the composition of the Chinese members of a
roundtable discussion. An Internet entrepreneur who had arrived at
the Shanghai Library with an invitation to participate in the
roundtable was replaced inexplicably with a Chinese expert on
U.S.-Chinese relations. Clinton's ``three no's'' came in response
to a comment from that added-starter panelist.
</P>
<P>
   Both of the ``rewards'' Clinton gave the Chinese were intangible
_ accepting a welcoming ceremony on Tiananmen Square and
eliminating the wiggle room in American policy on Taiwan. They're
only symbols, but they carry great importance to China's leaders,
to underground Chinese dissidents and to the Taiwanese.
</P>
<P>
   They were symbols traded for a potential _ the potential of more
openness and greater democracy in China _ that may or may not be
realized.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
