r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEALTH-POIROT-COLUMN-     07-02 0599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-POIROT-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DIFFERENCE IS DONATIONS, NOT DISTRIBUTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The solution is more organ donation, not wider distribution.
</P>
<P>
   Changing the rules to require nationwide allocation of organs
and tissues for transplant surgery won't save more lives, but
working together as communities to increase organ donation will.
</P>
<P>
   Department of Health and Human Services Secretary Donna Shalala
says that ``accidents of geography'' explain why certain cities
have less waiting time.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, these cities have shorter waiting times because
the level of organ donation is higher, and the high levels of
donation are no accident.
</P>
<P>
   LifeGift, the Fort Worth-based organization that oversees the
donation and recovery of organs and tissues for transplant centers
throughout North Texas, increased organ donation by 51 percent in
the 108 counties it serves during the past five years, more than
twice the national rate of increase.
</P>
<P>
   Too few organs are available for all the lifesaving transplant
surgery needed in the Fort Worth area, or anywhere else. Increasing
donation is the only way to solve the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Proposed changes would punish communities such as ours that are
doing a good job of increasing organ donation, and would reward
communities that are lagging.
</P>
<P>
   In May, LifeGift recovered more organs for donation than any
other organ-procurement organization in the country.
</P>
<P>
   LifeGift does a great job of inspiring this community to donate
organs and tissues. The group works with doctors, nurses,
chaplains, families, community organizations and the media to
increase our commitment to organ donation.
</P>
<P>
   LifeGift and the United Network for Organ Sharing (UNOS) are
spearheading efforts to keep the current regional organ allocation
system.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, while the Senate was debating a new regulation to
revise the nation's organ-transplantation system, members of Texans
for Transplants were meeting outside Cook Children's Medical
Center, rallying public support for rejecting the new plan,
scheduled for adoption in October.
</P>
<P>
   UNOS, the national organization responsible for organ
allocation, was meeting in Fort Worth to emphasize the need to keep
the current system, which requires all patients listed for
transplant to meet certain requirements, no matter where the
surgery is to be done.
</P>
<P>
   Status 1 patients _ those on life-support systems with a week or
less to live without transplant surgery _ have highest priority
nationwide. What changes in the allocations system would do, UNOS
says, is decrease the waiting time for Status 2 and 3 patients at
centers with long waiting lists.
</P>
<P>
   That all translates into a substantial increase in transplant
volume at large centers and reduced transplant volume in small to
midsize centers, where procurement organizations such as LifeGift
have done an extraordinary job of recruiting donors.
</P>
<P>
   It would help the large centers grow larger and increase their
success rate, because they could give more transplants to less-sick
patients, but ultimately it won't save more lives. The only thing
that will do that is more donations.
</P>
<P>
   While politicians were debating the issue in Washington, UNOS
members from across the country were clarifying their stand in Fort
Worth: The current system best meets the goals of utility, equity
and justice.
</P>
<P>
   (Carolyn Poirot writes on health issues for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
