<HEADLINE>
STRESSED-OUT WORKERS, MANAGERS ARE OFFERED GOOD SUGGESTIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TERESA MCUSIC 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Twenty million Americans stay at their jobs only to retain
health benefits. Yet research studies indicate that their work has
a good chance of making them sick.
</P>
<P>
   That is an interesting observation discussed in ``Toxic Work:
How to Overcome Stress, Overload, and Burnout and Revitalize Your
Career'' (The Penguin Group, 245 pages, $12.95, paperback).
</P>
<P>
   The book is one of several paperbacks now out discussing the
horrendous problem of stress in the work place.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: Loving your job is not an option, but an absolute
necessity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Expect more pressure, greater demands, and fewer people
employed on-site to do the work,'' writes ``Toxic Work'' author
Barbara Bailey Reinhold. ``That's why loving what you do has never
been more important _ if your work doesn't excite you, the
accelerated expectations will be unbearable.''
</P>
<P>
   Workplace stress is the single greatest health problem of
working adults, according to the president of the American
Institute of Stress.
</P>
<P>
   Heart attacks are most common on Monday mornings between 8-9
a.m., a statistic that led to the coining of the term ``Black
Monday Syndrome,'' Reinhold writes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The syndrome of toxic work overtakes you when what's happening
to you at work causes protracted bouts of distress, culminating in
emotional suffering or physical symptoms and heightened by the
perceived inability to stop the pain and move on to find or create
a more rewarding situation,'' she writes.
</P>
<P>
   Body signals from stress at the workplace that can lead to
greater health complications include fatigue, dizziness, headaches,
nausea, allergies, back pain, digestive tract problems and
recurrent colds, flu or infections.
</P>
<P>
   These are some of the problems Reinhold has observed in her
clients over the past 25 years as a counselor and teacher of career
planning. Reinhold is also the director of career development and
an adjunct professor of psychology at Smith College.
</P>
<P>
   Using numerous vignettes and studies to support her case of
stressful work and health complications, Reinhold helps readers
evaluate their own work situation through a quiz and discussion of
body signals.
</P>
<P>
   For those who find a connection between the two, Reinhold
provides a detox section, in which she offers numerous suggestions
to relieve the stress. Changing jobs is just one of the options.
</P>
<P>
   ``While you cannot control some events ..., you can control how
you react to those events,'' she writes. ``Two major things make
the difference: how you interpret what's happening at work, and
whether you are able to see life's upheavals and dissatisfactions
as catalysts rather than catastrophes.''
</P>
<P>
   Another book in paperback offers good suggestions for managers
in charge of all those stressed-out workers.
</P>
<P>
   It's called ``The Bad Attitude Survival Guide: Essential Tools
for Managers'' (Addison Wesley, 278 pages, $15) by management
consultant Harry E. Chambers.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many management books that outline a Utopian work
environment supported by numerous case studies of companies that
are doing things right, this book deals more directly with the
down-and-dirty realities of most workplaces.
</P>
<P>
   Chambers suggests that there is an epidemic of bad attitudes in
the American workplace, primarily the result of poor managers, who
are not properly trained to deal with the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot change someone else's attitude,'' he writes.
``Trying to change bad attitudes is a fruitless pursuit. Focus on
behavior _ it is something you can change.''
</P>
<P>
   Chambers uses case studies of individuals to illustrate common
workplace situations. He then offers numerous approaches that a
manager can take to effectively turn around that individual's
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   The book is full of useful observations on how to handle real
work world scenarios.
</P>
<P>
   (Teresa McUsic reviews business books for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
