<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-DENMARK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DANISH GOALKEEPER CONSIDERED THE BEST IN THE WORLD ... AND THE
LOUDEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (See also SOC-WORLDCUP-GERMANY, SOC-WORLDCUP-VECSEY)  
 (JT)  
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ As he stood in goal for Denmark's 4-1 dismantling of
Nigeria, Peter Schmeichel grabbed his head with his hands and
twisted it from side to side as if he were unscrewing a bottle cap.
Then he repeatedly flexed his jaws, limbering the muscles of his
mouth the way others stretch their hamstrings. He is considered the
best goalkeeper in the world, and also the loudest.
</P>
<P>
   He screams and yells at teammate and opponent alike, blistering
them with the same histrionic torrent that John McEnroe and Jimmy
Connors leveled at tennis umpires. The son of a classically-trained
musician, he is a boisterous conductor on the field, using his
mouth as a baton.
</P>
<P>
   He sees everyone in front of him, knowing where they are, or
should be, and he feels it is his job to direct the rhythm of a
game. In keeping the ball out of the net, he believes he must be as
selfish as a striker trying to send it into the net. And he has
even been known to grab fans who have invaded the pitch and edgily
toss them out of his workspace.
</P>
<P>
   Because of Schmeichel's steadfastness, tiny Denmark has grown
accustomed to high achievement in the face of low expectations. Few
are expecting the Danes to defeat Brazil in the World Cup
quarterfinals on Friday in Nantes, but with the 6-foot-4 Schmeichel
hulking in goal, Coach Bo Johansson feels that Denmark will at
least begin the game with the equivalent of a goal advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time we have a great victory it is often just because
Peter Schmeichel is so good,'' Johansson said.
</P>
<P>
   The reason that no one is dismissing Denmark has much to do with
the 1992 European championships. That summer, its players were on
the beach, celebrating a short break between seasons, when they
were summoned to replace Yugoslavia, which had been banned because
of sanctions relating to the Bosnian conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did the late replacements acquit themselves well,
Denmark became the champions of all of Europe. In the semifinals,
Schmeichel saved a penalty kick against Holland's Marco Van Basten,
who was the world's best scorer at the time. In the final,
Schmeichel turned the momentum in Denmark's favor with a
spectacular save on a shot by Germany's Juergen Klinsmann.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, he will have to contend with Brazil and Ronaldo, the
latest gunslinger challenging for a shootout. Brazil returned to
bogo jonito, the beautiful game, with a 4-1 second-round swamping
of Chile as Ronaldo delivered two goals. But the Danes, playing in
only their second World Cup, have nothing to lose, so they approach
Brazil with great equanimity. There are only five million people in
all of Denmark, while there appears to be at least that many in the
frenzied Brazilian press corps.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's fantastic for a small country like Denmark,''
Schmeichel said. ``We have a lot of confidence. If we lose, okay,
people expect that, but if we win, then it will be the sensation of
the century.''
</P>
<P>
   He is 34 now, and came to full-time professional soccer at the
relatively late age of 24. As a semi-pro, he supplemented his
soccer income with various jobs that today's millionaires might
find insulting. Schmeichel served as an apprentice carpet, fitter,
he sold advertising for a newspaper, he worked as a cleaner and he
ran a charity shop for the World Wildlife Fund.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, Schmeichel was signed by powerful Manchester United of
the English Premier League. The price paid for him was the
now-miserly sum of 750,000 pounds (slightly more than $1 million),
considering that Schmeichel has now bolstered the team to four
league championships. His style in goal is to stand up tall, cut
down the angles, and force the attacker to make the first move.
That way, Schmeichel insists, the opposing striker is left to do
the thinking, and perhaps, the self-doubting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's his entire aura, this big, blonde Viking flying out at
you,'' Alex Ferguson, Manchester United's manager, once said of
Schmeichel. ``It cuts an attacker's options down 10 times.''
</P>
<P>
   Unafraid to join in attack, Schmeichel once headed in a goal for
Manchester United during a European cup match. Some consider him to
be reckless, though, in his wandering, and opponents try to make
him pay by lifting long chip shots over his head. His screaming has
gotten him into trouble, also. Twice he has been accused of making
racial remarks at Ian Wright, a black striker, during matches
between Manchester United and Arsenal. He has denied making the
remarks, and no sanctions have been taken against him.
</P>
<P>
   Away from soccer, Schmeichel, a father of two, is quiet and
reflective. He plays the piano, everything from Billy Joel to
classical, and he keeps a studio in his home. A tune he composed
for the 1996 European championships, ``We Can Do It,'' did well on
the Danish charts. Friday, it will be his difficult job to prevent
the rhythm on the field from becoming strictly samba.
</P>
</TEXT>
