<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-NUCLEARDUMP-960(3Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESOLATE BUT BEAUTIFUL, SIERRA BLANCA IN LINE TO BECOME A NUCLEAR
DUMP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM MADIGAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SIERRA BLANCA, Texas _ In the fall of 1948, with his political
survival hanging by a thread, President Harry Truman nonetheless
found time for a campaign whistle-stop that would be worth a few
dozen votes at best.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps Truman, at the time in a fierce re-election battle
with Thomas Dewey, had something other than the Electoral College
in mind when his campaign train pulled into this tiny southwest
Texas hamlet 90 miles east of El Paso. Maybe he stopped instead to
restore his spirits amid the rocky desert peaks of the Quitman
Mountains, and the blooming yucca, and the elk and deer and jack
rabbits, and the sun- and wind-burned people who somehow managed to
scratch sustenance from the dry earth.
</P>
<P>
   Surviving photographs of Truman's 10-minute visit to Sierra
Blanca show a beaming president exchanging a robust handshake with
a locally renowned rodeo cowboy named Charley Norton, who rode to
the presidential train on his horse, Snake. Truman briefly
addressed the gathered crowd that day, and his wistfulness was
palpable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather go see the rodeo than do what I have to do,'' he
said. ``But I have to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Given that sentiment, one wonders what Truman might think about
developments in this desert enclave today. Just east of town, there
are plans for a massive underground facility to receive low-level
nuclear waste from other parts of Texas and two Northeastern
states. Already, every day since 1992, tons of New York City's
waste-water sludge have been dispersed across the desert just to
the west.
</P>
<P>
   To an outsider, at least, this seems an affront. On my own first
visit here a decade ago, the local sheriff, a leathery fellow named
Dick Love, took me in his pickup on a long tour of the back country
south of town. Against the blue backdrop of racing storm clouds,
great mountains blazed orange in the setting sun. We drove up a
craggy one-lane mountain road that ran precariously along a steep
cliff, and came to look down on the crude huts of a tiny Mexican
village just across the Rio Grande.
</P>
<P>
   It was a breathtaking moment, one I've often thought of in the
years since. I can appreciate Truman's wistfulness for a land that
seems taken from a border novel of Cormac McCarthy, a land so
reminiscent of the Big Bend or the Guadalupe Mountains, Texas
places now preserved and celebrated as national parks.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed nuclear waste disposal site has long been a matter
of fierce debate. Whether it or the New York City sludge operation
pose threats to human health depends on whom you talk to. In fact,
they probably don't. But celebrations they are not.
</P>
<P>
   ``IT'S BEEN AN OBSESSION'': The mountain called Sierra Blanca
looms on the horizon northwest of the village, humpbacked and
tan-colored in the desert sun, not white like its Spanish name
suggests. When Spanish explorers first encountered this chunk of
the Chihuahua Desert centuries ago, rainfall was more abundant and
the mountain was covered by white poppies. Or so explains a tall,
thin man named Billy Addington, who stands in the desert sun
outside the family business.
</P>
<P>
   Addington talks above the noise of successive semitrailers as
they lumber through town, waving at each passing pickup, for he has
lived in Sierra Blanca for almost all of his 42 years and knows
virtually every one of the 600 or so residents.
</P>
<P>
   The brown-brick family-owned store was built in 1929 by his
grandfather, Jose Guerra, a Lebanese immigrant who came first to
Mexico, then to Sierra Blanca in 1910. Guerra first sold his goods
from a small wagon hauled up and down the newly finished railroad
line. Eventually there was a Guerra store, a butane company, a
lumberyard and a 6,000-acre ranch in the foothills of the Eagle
Mountains near the Rio Grande.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could have been a multimillionaire,'' Addington says of his
ancestor. ``But he loved this town. He could have made a lot more
money in the city, but he loved this. He put his sweat and blood in
this town. What you see here he built ... and by God, I'm going to
defend it.''
</P>
<P>
   So last Nov. 1, Addington embarked on a 56-day hunger strike to
protest the nuclear dump site, ending his fast at, of all places,
the Terlingua Chili Cook-Off in nearby Big Bend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had an experience with a Porta Potti that I won't describe
to you,'' he says, smiling. ``You're supposed to eat rice and drink
broth when you go off one of those suckers.''
</P>
<P>
   But for the rest of the conversation, Addington is deadly
earnest, his eyes welling up in tears while speaking of a long
battle against the dump that he says cost him his wife and young
son.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said, `I see you more on TV than at home,''' Addington
says. ``She left in January of 1994. She said, `I love you, Billy,
and I'll always love you. But I want a life.' It's been an
obsession, a self-admitted obsession. I've got a lot of anger. A
little bit of knowledge is a dangerous thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Addington, the leader of the local opposition, scarcely surfaces
for air as he rants on. State and federal politicians have
conspired with huge utilities who need a cheaper place to dump
nuclear waste, he says. Each of the six other similar nuclear dump
sites built in the United States since the 1960s has leaked. This
is the state's most active area for earthquakes, further
heightening the risk of leakage, which could contaminate the ground
water. Because it is small and isolated, Sierra Blanca has no
political clout with which to defend itself.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
