<HEADER>
A8075 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JULY4-MOVIES-2TAKES-N     07-02 1108
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JULY4-MOVIES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT ALL SUMMER MOVIES ARE SILLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hollywood has never issued an official declaration. But the
Fourth of July weekend is the peak of the silly season in movies.
As fireworks detonate around the country, thousands of screens will
light up with fantasies of the world (or part of the world) saved
at the last minute from destruction by the savvy and courage of
comic-book heroes going up against catastrophic forces.
</P>
<P>
   In a movie climate where giant mutant lizards (``Godzilla''),
earth-shattering comets (``Deep Impact'') and zooming asteroids
(``Armageddon'') call the apocalyptic shots, is there any room left
for real people with human-size problems?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, some high-profile movies (``The Truman Show,'' ``Out of
Sight,'' ``Six Days, Seven Nights'' and, of course, the re-release
of ``Gone With the Wind'') aspire to be more than high-concept
blockbusters. But the place you're still mostly likely to find one
is your local art theater.
</P>
<P>
   This year there are plenty of worthy small films to choose from.
Here is a sampling, listed in the order of this critic's
preference.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``HENRY FOOL.'' In an astounding leap beyond the polished
whimsy of movies like ``Flirt,'' independent filmmaker Hal Hartley
has concocted a gripping all-American fable about art and
excrement, friendship and fame, genius and self-delusion, that
follows the rise of Simon Grim (James Urbaniak) from persecuted
milquetoasty garbage man to internationally acclaimed poet.
</P>
<P>
   Simon's raggedy mentor, Henry Fool (Thomas Jay Ryan), is an
equally unlikely literary type, an erudite borderline psychopath
who camps out in the basement of the New York home Simon shares
with his grotesquely dysfunctional family.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing subtle about ``Henry Fool,'' which while cannily
avoiding quoting from Simon's epic poem, suggests that great
literature is necessarily shocking and offensive to the status quo.
Parker Posey is memorably abrasive as Simon's slatternly sister
who, in a fit of pique, douses him with boiling water. A caveat: If
you have no tolerance for raw, patently unrealistic allegory,
``Henry Fool'' is not for you.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``VOYAGE TO THE BEGINNING OF THE WORLD.'' In his last major
film role, an obviously ailing Marcello Mastroianni plays an aged
movie director who is the alter ego of the octogenarian
Portuguese-French filmmaker Manoel de Oliveira. Touring rural
Portugal with three younger colleagues, the crotchety old director
revisits crumbling landmarks of his youth that stir up old
memories. Paying a surprise visit to the aged aunt of one of the
travelers, the group arrives in a village where time seems to have
stood still for the last two centuries.
</P>
<P>
   The movie (much of which was filmed from the back of a moving
car in which the camera observes the landscape left behind) feels
like the director's long austerely poignant goodbye to filmmaking
and to life itself. Warning: There is no action, no suspense, no
real story. The film is essentially a personal meditation.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``PICNIC AT HANGING ROCK.'' The success of Peter Weir's
``Truman Show'' has prompted the re-release of the director's eerie
unsolved mystery (made in 1975). Adapted from a novel by Joan
Lindsay, it is about some virginal Australian schoolgirls who
mysteriously disappear one afternoon while exploring an ominous
geological formation.
</P>
<P>
   Contrasting the rigid formality and repression of boarding
school life in 1900 with the rugged outdoors teeming with life, the
film conveys a hallucinatory vision of two colliding worlds, one
artificially sanitized, the other fiercely predatory.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine a more surreal and subtle ``Close Encounters of the
Third Kind'' as conceived by Sigmund Freud.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``THE SPANISH PRISONER.'' Almost as sleek as ``North by
Northwest,'' David Mamet's homage to Alfred Hitchcock by way of
Kafka finds Joe Ross (Campbell Scott), a loyal corporate employee
and inventor of something called ``the process,'' caught in a web
of chicanery fiendish enough to drive anyone to a raving paranoia.
The screenplay's self-consciously staccato ``Mametese'' deepens the
tension, as Joe, finding himself a murder suspect, attempts to flee
with the help of a resourceful secretary (Rebecca Pidgeon).
</P>
<P>
   Steve Martin is especially intriguing as a twinkling-eyed bon
vivant named Jimmy Dell who pulls some powerful strings. More than
just a suspenseful romp, ``The Spanish Prisoner,'' is a moral fable
of integrity and greed that imagines the world as a game of poker
rigged against all suckers who are foolish enough to believe
otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``THE OPPOSITE OF SEX.'' Some of the nastiest dialogue ever to
spice a Hollywood film spews from the mouth of Dedee (Christina
Ricci), the selfish teen-age vixen who narrates Don Roos' smart but
occasionally stumbling comedy of gay and straight (bad) manners.
Fleeing Louisiana to visit her gay older half brother, Bill (Martin
Donovan), in Indiana, Dedee seduces his handsome younger lover,
Matt (Ivan Sergei), and the pair elope to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   That's just the beginning of a sustained comic chase in which
Bill and his ex-lover's spinsterish sister, Lucia (Lisa Kudrow),
pursue the couple from West Hollywood to the Canadian woods, with
many complications (including an accidental homicide) along the
way.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``I WENT DOWN.'' Paddy Breathnach's quirky underworld comedy
follows two comically mismatched Irish hoods, Git (Peter McDonald)
and Bunny (Brendan Gleeson), who are forced by their petty mobster
of a boss (Tony Doyle) to travel to Cork to bring back another man
who owes him money. The trip becomes a bumbling comedy of errors in
which the reluctant kidnappers establish an unlikely bond of
friendship.
</P>
<P>
   If the Irish dialect is sometimes too thick to be intelligible,
the movie unfolds like an absorbing, idiomatically pungent string
of anecdotes (announced by chapter titles) related from a bar stool
in a seedy Irish pub.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``HIGH ART.'' Ally Sheedy is mesmerizing as Lucy, a prickly
heroin-sniffing photographer whose downstairs neighbor, Syd (Radha
Mitchell), a low-level editor for a photography magazine, coaxes
her out of her self-destructive stupor to create a cover essay for
the publication. Patricia Clarkson is equally compelling as Lucy's
arrogant, seriously drug-addicted German lover.
</P>
<P>
   The movie, directed by Lisa Cholodenko, raises uncomfortable
questions about self-exploitation in the pursuit of art and career
success but is marred by a melodramatic ending that feels tossed
off and unconvincing.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   _ ``BUFFALO '66.'' Wiry, wide-eyed and twitching in his
semi-autobiographical debut film, Vincent Gallo is Billy Brown, a
high-strung loser just sprung from prison where he spent five years
for a crime he didn't commit.
</P>
<P>
   Abducting a teen-ager named Layla (Christina Ricci) from her
dance class, he coerces her into pretending to be his adoring wife
when he visits his monstrous parents (Ben Gazzara and Anjelica
Huston) and tells them a phony story about how well he has been
doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buffalo '66'' has the raw spontaneity and abrasive texture of
a John Cassavetes film and a nerve-jangling central performance by
Gallo, who also directed, helped write the screenplay and composed
the music.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``THE LAST DAYS OF DISCO.'' The Studio 54-like club to which
the endlessly loquacious yuppies in Whit Stillman's third film
periodically repair is only a backdrop for the philosophically
wistful conversations of its WASPy would-be smart set.
</P>
<P>
   If the conversation isn't as stimulating as the
upper-class-conscious prattle in Stillman's first and best film,
``Metropolitan,'' ``The Last Days of Disco'' has the same
distinctive style and mood. Kate Beckinsale is the group's arrogant
mean-spirited social director and Chloe Sevigny her persecuted
roommate and co-worker in a publishing house. Chris Eigeman, a
Stillman regular, offers an amusing analysis of Disney's ``Lady and
the Tramp.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``MARIE BAIE DES ANGES.'' Vahina Giocante is a sullen,
sexually precocious teen-ager who stirs up the hormones of a group
of American sailors on the French Riviera near Nice.
</P>
<P>
   In this ominous meditation on the primal savagery of teen-age
sexual rites, the camera never stops moving as it observes an
assortment of wild youth diving and preying on one another in the
pearly waters of the ``Bay of Angels.'' Frederic Malgras is the
disaffected petty criminal who plays a brooding Romeo to Ms.
Giocante's Juliet. If this first feature film by Manuel Pradal has
trouble telling a story and keeping track of time, it still casts a
spell.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``THE LAND GIRLS.'' As a hundred World War II movies have
taught several generations of postwar filmgoers, the Americans and
British were never more high-minded and noble than when
collectively standing up against Nazism. David Leland's appealingly
rose-colored memory film recalls the contribution of the Women's
Land Army to the British war effort.
</P>
<P>
   A high-toned soap opera with a stiff upper lip, the movie
follows the lives of three young women (Catherine McCormack, Rachel
Weisz and Anna Friel) from divergent backgrounds who share cramped
quarters on the same Dorset farm and take turns having flings with
the owner's son.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``HAV PLENTY.'' Nodding gracefully to Woody Allen and Spike
Lee, Christopher Scott Cherot makes a promising feature film debut
with a sharply witty, lighter-than-air satire of buppie mating
rituals. Chertot directed, wrote the screenplay and stars as Lee
Plenty, a self-effacing down-on-his-luck writer who resists the
aggressive overtures of several women to remain loyal to his pal
and secret true love, Havilland Savage (Chenoa Maxwell). An
arrogant materialistic beauty with a heavy attitude, Havilland must
discover for herself that money isn't everything. The movie is
marred by a weak, tacked-on ending.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``KURT AND COURTNEY.'' Did Courtney Love have Kurt Cobain
killed for his fortune? Nick Broomfield, an intrepid British
filmmaker infatuated with sleaze doesn't really believe she did.
But the what-if premise becomes an excuse for Broomfield, a pushy,
tabloid answer to David Frost, to stick his nose into some of the
grimier corners of the leftover Seattle grunge scene.
</P>
<P>
   Among the unpleasant characters interviewed, Ms. Love's father,
Hank Harrison, may be the most appalling. Years after Ms. Love has
fled the nest, he is still waging a bitter power struggle with his
absent daughter, whom he trashes with malicious glee.
</P>
<P>
   As Broomfield showed in ``Heidi Fleiss: Hollywood Madam,'' he
has a talent for coaxing unsavory characters to come out from under
their rocks and spill the beans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-98 1633EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
