<HEADER>
A8082 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-NUCLEARDUMP-2nd     07-02 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-NUCLEARDUMP-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
SIERRA BLANCA, Texas: to defend itself. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``It grieves me deeply that for the love of money, they're
making us the nuclear and sewage sludge pay toilet of the United
States, and that's never going to stop,'' Addington says. ``That is
the future of Sierra Blanca if this happens _ national dump, a
graveyard for retired reactors, maybe even more sludge projects.''
</P>
<P>
   But Addington probably fights a losing battle. On July 7, after
months of contentious hearings, a two-judge administrative panel in
Austin is expected to recommend that an operating license be
granted for the low-level waste site five miles east of Sierra
Blanca on Interstate 10.
</P>
<P>
   And the truth is, more Hudspeth County and Sierra Blanca
residents probably favor the site and the badly needed jobs and tax
dollars it brings than oppose it. As evidence, proponents routinely
point to Addington's campaign this spring for Hudspeth County
Democratic chairman, which he turned into a nuclear dump site
referendum. On April 14, Addington was defeated, 340 votes to 245,
by a retired Hudspeth County resident named Tom Neely, who took no
position on the dump.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of like the Nixon speech,'' area rancher James
Schilling says one day in the lobby of the Sierra Motel. ``Remember
the Silent Majority? The funny thing is, the only people you'll get
to talk about it are the ones opposed. I just don't see any
problems with it. It has to go somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Reasons for the support are not hard to fathom in the
predominantly Hispanic village, where most residents have stronger
ancestral ties to towns like Chihuahua and Coyame in Mexico than
any place north. They scratch out livings on the ranches, or
working for the county or school district. Century-old adobe homes
are cracked and weather-beaten, most roads are unpaved, and most
schoolchildren meet federal poverty guidelines for free hot
lunches.
</P>
<P>
   But today, in the middle of town sits a new, oasislike park,
strikingly green and lush against the otherwise dusty desert
backdrop. The park, replete with shiny new playground equipment and
pristine tennis courts, was built in part with tax money already
received from the disposal site. There is a new local firetruck,
too, and plans to renovate the crumbling adobe courthouse. The
school district owns two new buses, a new floor in the high school
gym, new turf and lighting at the football field.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wouldn't have those types of projects without a new bond
issue, and we're taxed almost to the limit already,'' says Lewis
Rogers, the retiring superintendent of Sierra Blanca schools, with
an enrollment of 128 students in grades K-12. ``Those buses were
very much needed, and we're very thankful to get them. Now we can
send our kids out almost anywhere they need to go, and not worry
about getting them back.''
</P>
<P>
   Addington calls this economic blackmail.
</P>
<P>
   ``We love to be isolated,'' he says. ``But that isolation has
been our greatest hurt now, because the reality is that there are
only 1,607 registered voters in the county, and 3 million acres, a
place the size of Connecticut. That's why they're putting it here.
That's why they keep coming back here. They just won't give up.
They've come in with that economic blackmail.''
</P>
<P>
   THEY LOVED PATTON: An uninterrupted night's sleep does not come
easy in Sierra Blanca. Every few hours, trains rumble loudly
through the middle of town, trains like the one that brought Truman
to town, Amtrak trains speeding west toward California or east to
San Antonio, freight trains, trains pulling red rail cars carrying
New York City sludge.
</P>
<P>
   They are ubiquitous reminders that without the railroad, there
probably would be no Sierra Blanca.
</P>
<P>
   On May 10, 1869, they drove the golden spike at Promontory in
the Utah Territory, celebrating the completion of the nation's
first transcontinental railroad. ``But the need remained for a
southern route,'' reads the historical marker in Sierra Blanca.
</P>
<P>
   In 1869, Southern Pacific began building a line east from
California; two years later, the Texas and Pacific railroad built
westward from East Texas. The two lines neared each other in Sierra
Blanca, where railroad officials agreed the lines would ``approach,
meet and form one continuous line to the Pacific.''
</P>
<P>
   The railroad's strategic significance and the mounting border
menace of guerrilla Pancho Villa in the early 1900s led to the
deployment of U.S. Cavalry in Sierra Blanca, including a
30-year-old lieutenant named George Patton. One Patton biography
would later describe Sierra Blanca as ``a violent holdover from the
Old West, populated by cowboys and gunfighters of fearsome
reputation. ... The entire town consisted of approximately 50
people, 20 houses, a saloon and a hotel. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``The whiskey flowed copiously in the saloon, and on any given
Saturday night the local pistoleros and cowhands entertained
themselves by firing weapons at targets both real and imagined,''
writes Patton biographer Carlo D'Este. ``Patton's profanity, his
ability to shoot a pistol and his free-spending ways at the saloon,
where he delighted in buying beer for them, quickly made him a
popular figure with the rough-hewn Texans, who sensed a kindred
spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
