A8084 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GERMAN-BALLETS-2TAKES     07-02 1140
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMAN-BALLETS-2TAKES-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LINEAGE OF A LEGEND: TWO GERMAN TROUPES RETURN TO NEW YORK  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 5) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Wis.)   (af)  
 Kate Mattingly teaches ballet in Salzburg and writes about dance in
Europe for Dance Magazine and The Village Voice.  
 By KATE MATTINGLY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STUTTGART, Germany _ When John Cranko, the artistic director of
the Wurttemberg State Theater Ballet, took his company to New York
in 1969, he warned his dancers, ``Don't unpack your bags until
after the first-night reviews.'' But the critics raved and the
company returned to Germany triumphant.
</P>
<P>
   From then on it would be known as the Stuttgart Ballet, a named
bestowed by the dance critic Clive Barnes, and today ballet
companies everywhere aspire to its success.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Cranko died in 1973 _ only 45, he had a heart attack
on a plane returning from another New York tour _ he had created a
company that was to become a dynasty builder: former members now
direct troupes in Frankfurt, Vienna, Stuttgart, Hamburg and Leipzig
as well as at The Hague and Vancouver. Cranko, a South African,
danced and choreographed in London before taking over the
Wurttemberg in 1961.
</P>
<P>
   There, he developed a company with several dancers from the
Americas who stayed on to help shape the German ballet scene. These
include Reid Anderson, John Neumeier, Richard Cragun, William
Forsythe and Marcia Haydee, who was also Cranko's muse.
</P>
<P>
   Starting on Tuesday, Lincoln Center Festival '98 pays tribute to
this influential choreographer and father figure when two members
of the 1969 tour, Anderson and Neumeier, return to New York as
directors of the Stuttgart and Hamburg troupes, respectively.
Performances by their companies span 36 years of choreography _
from Cranko's signature full-length works ``Romeo and Juliet'' and
``Onegin'' to Neumeier's two United States premieres, ``All Our
Yesteryears'' and ``Bernstein Dances,'' which begin on July 14.
</P>
<P>
   New York, which hasn't seen the Stuttgart for almost 20 years
and the Hamburg for 13, is an appropriate venue for the reunion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The success of New York in 1969 was so very important because
suddenly everybody in Stuttgart realized what they had in this
company, and they were able to change things,'' Anderson said in an
interview in April, sitting at his desk overlooking Stuttgart's
Schlossgarten. Dressed stylishly in a black-and-white-checked suit,
Anderson, a Canadian who studied dance in London and joined the
Stuttgart at 18, now doubles as artistic director and general
manager, or Intendant, of the 64-member troupe.
</P>
<P>
   ``For instance, Stuttgart was the first company in Germany whose
corps went on pay parity with the corps in the opera,'' Anderson
said. Previously, the chorus had earned more than the corps de
ballet. ``We were the first company here to actually become a
ballet company, not an opera-ballet company,'' he added, referring
to dancers who must perform in opera as well as ballet productions.
</P>
<P>
   When the Stuttgart Ballet started courting him for the position,
Anderson told the search committee he had to have his own budget,
meaning control of $6.1 million. Germany's system of
government-subsidized culture takes care of many basic expenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way it works is I have a budget, but I don't have to pay
for the making of the sets,'' Anderson explained. ``I don't have to
pay for making costumes, to rent a theater, to pay for an
orchestra. I don't have to have a huge staff; I can avail myself of
the theater's staff. Those are all costs that North American
companies have to pay out of their budgets. Eighty percent of my
budget goes toward the cost of my dancers and my team here.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson learned about budgets first-hand when he served as
artistic director of Ballet British Columbia in Vancouver, from
1987 to 1989, and then of the National Ballet of Canada in Toronto,
from 1989 to 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming from Stuttgart, when I first went to Vancouver, I
didn't even know what marketing and development was,'' he said.
``We raised $8 million for new works in seven years. I was
extremely happy in Toronto. In 1989 it was a go-getter city, it was
thriving. Everybody was in the black, everybody was doing lunch.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, the Province of Ontario cut Anderson's budget by a
half-million dollars. ``It was like being eaten by piranha,'' he
said. At that point, he accepted Stuttgart's offer.
</P>
<P>
   Two years after Cranko's death, Ms. Haydee, a Brazilian, had
taken over as artistic director. When Anderson arrived in 1996, he
said he found much to be done: ``It was kind of calcified at the
top. I was the gray eminence who would float through the hallways.
I had to fire friends of mine. I had to say, `I'm sorry I don't
think so.' '' Anderson subsequently hired 21 new dancers.
</P>
<P>
   German opera houses offer a combination of artistic freedom and
financial security that produces working conditions much different
from those in North America. But when Stuttgart Ballet mounted a
two-week homage to John Cranko in October, Anderson said, the
extravaganza cost ``a whole pile of money I didn't have.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, a regional bank backed the festival, becoming one of
a growing number of corporate sponsors of the arts in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Stuttgart Ballet's performances this week are classic Cranko,
Anderson said: ``I haven't had time to build up an arsenal of rep
to go to New York and say this is what we do now.'' ``Romeo and
Juliet,'' created in 1958, put Cranko on the map. (Ms. Haydee, who
danced Juliet in the Stuttgart version, plays Lady Capulet in the
current production.) Walter Erich Schaefer, Stuttgart's intendant
from 1945 to 1972, didn't know that much about ballet, Anderson
said, adding, ``But he knew what he had in John, especially after
the huge success of `Romeo and Juliet.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson praises ``Onegin,'' first performed in New York in
1969, as a brilliant story ballet. ``John's credo,'' he said, ``was
you should be able to arrive as the lights go down and you should
be able to understand everything that's going on without reading a
program note.''
</P>
<P>
   Cranko's choreography uses a cinematic technique in which two
scenes are juxtaposed, one interacting against the other. Anderson
remembers the choreographer's saying: ``Wherever I look onstage, I
want to see a story. The audiences happen to be focusing on the
(italics)lead,(end italics) but I want to see what's happening to
the other people onstage as a reaction to the drama.''
</P>
<P>
   This emphasis on a dramatic story line distinguishes many
European companies from those in the United States. Both the
Stuttgart's and the Hamburg's dancers excel at blending emotion and
technique, as the narrative choreography by Cranko and Neumeier
demands, influenced, perhaps, by their years in England.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
