<SLUG> BC-MURRAY-COLUMN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: Confessions of a June
father-of-the-bride
 &HT;    Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ My youngest daughter was a June bride. I was a
June father-of-the-bride.
</P>
<P>
   This was my third and last stint as father of the bride. Through
it all, I have learned much, most of which came too late to do me
any good.
</P>
<P>
   If you're a father of daughters, maybe some of the following
will help you.
</P>
<P>
   A girl can't begin planning her wedding too soon. If she hasn't
picked out a wedding dress by age 3, she is behind schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Guys have little or no part to play in weddings. A cardboard
cutout could do the job.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is the wedding for the bride. The wedding is for the bride's
mother. The bride will have her wedding a generation later when it
comes time for her daughter to marry.
</P>
<P>
   There is no way in heaven's name you can prepare yourself for
what the flowers will cost. Ever wonder why fathers of the bride
cry at weddings?
</P>
<P>
   That's not to suggest that a wedding is about money. A wedding
is about love. A wedding is about how women love to spend money.
</P>
<P>
   Wedding cakes are priced by the slice. For what it cost, you'd
think it'd be the size of a slice of watermelon.
</P>
<P>
   There will be wedding cake left over. Eat to your heart's
content. Better that than eating your heart out thinking how much
it cost.
</P>
<P>
   But the top of the wedding cake is to be saved, frozen and then
eaten by the couple on their first anniversary. Not all fathers of
the bride know about that ritual. I didn't when my oldest daughter
married. By the time they told me, it was too late. Sorry about
that.
</P>
<P>
   When my second daughter married, I offered a cash option.
Anything less than what her older sister had spent, she could have
in cash. So it was that she ended up with both a nice wedding and a
nice nest egg. Better she than the florist.
</P>
<P>
   Very little is required of the father of the bride. Get a
haircut and show up. That's about it.
</P>
<P>
   Don't make suggestions. Keep your mouth shut. Keep to yourself.
Best that you lock yourself in your room. Let them shove you the
bills under the door, and you shove them the checks.
</P>
<P>
   If you hold the reception at your home, make the proper
arrangements ahead of time at the bank. The blood bank, that is.
Before it's over, you're going to be bled dry.
</P>
<P>
   You'll need to have the house painted. You'll need new shutters.
(Wait until you find out what shutters cost. Shudder would be a
better spelling.)
</P>
<P>
   You may even need a new driveway, walkway and patio. Awnings are
a nice touch.
</P>
<P>
   Before it was over, we even added an extra outside staircase
from which the bride could toss her bouquet. I only wish I'd caught
the bouquet. Maybe I could have gotten a partial refund from the
florist.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
</P>
<P>
   AWEW18A(at)prodigy.com; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108,
Lufkin, Texas, 75915.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
