<HEADER>
A8091 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-NUCLEARDUMP-3rd     07-02 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-NUCLEARDUMP-3rdTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
SIERRA BLANCA, Texas: a kindred spirit.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eighty-three years after Patton's departure, the Sierra Blanca
train depot has been converted into a museum, and Hudspeth County
historian Julia Jenkins directs visitors to a small painting of the
nondescript wood-frame house Patton called home. On another wall is
the newspaper chronicling Truman's visit.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins, who was born in Sierra Blanca more than 70 years ago,
says the site of Patton's home is now a vacant lot. She points out
the back door of the museum to the ranch land where the sludge
operation now exists, but tries to deflect questions about the
current nuclear controversy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of have to stay neutral,'' she says. ``It's supposed to
be harmless. That's my word, supposed. It's just because we're
poor, I guess. Poor and struggling.''
</P>
<P>
   THE TRENCH AND THE ELK: Joe Castro grew up in Fort Hancock,
another small town only 35 miles west. In the dust of a windy, gray
afternoon, he points at and names each visible mountain. The Eagle
Mountains loom to the south. Devil's Back Ridge is over there.
Yucca Mesa. Sand Mountain. The Quitmans.
</P>
<P>
   But Castro's job today has more to do with what might soon be
below the ground than what is above it. He is a state employee,
field office supervisor at the desert site nominated to receive
low-level nuclear waste from Texas, Maine and Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   Castro and officials of the Texas Low-Level Radioactive Waste
Disposal Authority have convincing answers for most questions
raised by critics. In the last 20 years, they say, improved
technology has all but eliminated the chance of nuclear waste
escaping into the earth. Inside a brown double-wide trailer at the
proposed dump site, 28 thick volumes of research used in the
license application process fill a bookcase.
</P>
<P>
   Near the trailer's front door stands a 55-gallon barrel with the
top cut away to show the gloves, syringes, tools and other smaller
items irradiated by medical uses that will be disposed of at the
site. Outside are huge plastic containers that hold irradiated
water from nuclear power plants, water that will be transformed
into solids by a special resin before being buried here.
</P>
<P>
   At the far end of the property is a huge gash in the earth, 40
feet deep, hundreds of yards long. If the facility is licensed,
trucks will back into similar trenches and off-load the nuclear
waste into concrete canisters strong enough, Castro says, to
withstand a massive earthquake without leaking.
</P>
<P>
   But the technical merits of the waste disposal site are only
part of the tour. Jack rabbits skitter by. Castro points out the
soaptree yucca. He plucks small yellow berries from a poisonous
desert plant called a silver nightshade.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are used to curdle cheese even though the plants are
poisonous,'' Castro says. ``I remember gathering them for my
grandma as a kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Deer are abundant here, Castro says. There are javelina,
coyotes, snakes and turtles, whose well-being has been accounted
for in government environmental studies.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a matter of fact,'' Castro says, ``we had an elk who used
to come and sit up here beneath a yucca and watch us work on the
trench. It was kind of fun.''
</P>
<P>
   When the facility is built, Castro says, a double fence will
surround the property, to repel both human and animal visitors.
</P>
<P>
   THE RAINBOW: Dick Love retired as Hudspeth County sheriff five
years ago, and when I finally track him down, he's in an El Paso
hospital for tests. There will be no guided mountain tour on my
second trip to Sierra Blanca.
</P>
<P>
   So I set out alone in a rental car, south from town on the
blacktop of Farm Road 1111. The pavement turned to gravel after a
few miles and cut a beige ribbon through a broad valley toward the
Eagle Mountains. Earlier in the day, a rare storm had dumped badly
needed rain on the parched earth, but now the clouds were opening.
On the horizon toward Mexico was a huge, vertical rainbow. The sun
finally emerged through the clouds to the west, and in an instant,
the mountains were the brilliant orange I remembered.
</P>
<P>
   Darkness closed in before I reached the border. The peaks were
blue silhouettes as I returned to town, dodging jack rabbits that
skipped across the headlights. I'd driven for an hour without
seeing another human soul. I felt fortunate to be back in one of
the prettiest parts of Texas. But as I drove, a question kept
nagging.
</P>
<P>
   What if the mountains could talk? And yucca? And elk? Would they
quietly accept a nuclear landfill next door? Maybe two trips in 10
years didn't entitle me to an opinion, but as the sun set over the
desert, I couldn't help but think that this was a terrible place
for a nuclear dump, a terrible place for a dump of any sort.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
