<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 16:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8086 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GERMAN-BALLETS-2NDTAK     07-02 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMAN-BALLETS-2NDTAKE-$ADV5-NYT </SLUG>
  
 STUTTGART, Germany: in England.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In America, where ballet has evolved alongside modern dance,
speed, abstract movement and virtuosity take precedence. Balanchine
and Cunningham reign supreme, and many critics tend to favor
pure-movement styles.
</P>
<P>
   The Cranko protege who first challenged Stuttgart Ballet's
dominance in Germany was Neumeier, who was born in Milwaukee. Like
Anderson, he trained at the Royal Ballet School in London. Unlike
Anderson, he became a choreographer as well as a director. ``It
never was my intention to be an expatriate, but the ball started to
roll,'' said Neumeier. ``I did some choreographies for an
experimental group in Stuttgart, and one of them became very
popular and it led to my being asked _ at a very young age _ to be
director of the Frankfurt Ballet.'' He accepted.
</P>
<P>
   Three years later, in 1973, the invitation to direct the Hamburg
Ballet extended Neumeier's stay in Germany. This year he celebrates
his 25th anniversary as head of the Hamburg company. During that
time, the ballet's space has expanded from what he describes as ``a
half an office and a half-day secretary'' to a nine-studio
building, Ballettzentrum Hamburg John Neumeier, housing both the
company and its school.
</P>
<P>
   Neumeier operates on a $7.2 million budget. ``We are also having
financial problems, but I am more able to take chances than, say,
at American Ballet Theater,'' he said. ``I know my dancers have
these contracts and they will have them next year. If I don't fire
them.''
</P>
<P>
   After three years with Hamburg Ballet, the choreographer found
``it was impossible'' to share his dancers with the opera: ``They
had to be used exclusively for the ballet company because we work
so much that it wouldn't really be possible for them to do it.
Aside from that, generally the work in opera is not really that
interesting or productive.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Cragun, the California-born director of Deutsche Oper
Ballet, which continues to serve both functions, confirms this from
Berlin: ``A healthy ballet company should have the resources of the
opera house, but independence from the opera.''
</P>
<P>
   In Berlin, since the wall came down in 1989, Cragun's company
has had to compete for resources with two other major opera houses
and their dance troupes, leaving him with an ``unforeseeable''
future. He says his budget is ``a quarter to a third'' that of
Stuttgart's or Hamburg's.
</P>
<P>
   In 1969, Schaefer, referring to the period that followed World
War II, wrote: ``Music and dance were still intelligible to all,
even in a world of hatred and resentment. The great hour arrived in
Germany for ballet, the nonlingual art.''
</P>
<P>
   Although its postwar prosperity is fading, dance continues to
hold a prominent position in the country's civic life. The German
public worships culture the way American audiences worship sports.
In Stuttgart, the ballet never advertises. ``We don't have to,''
Anderson said. ``Performances are always sold out. We don't even
have a marketing department.''
</P>
<P>
   In Hamburg, Neumeier has achieved celebrity status. The premiere
of his ``Bernstein Dances'' last month attracted front-page
coverage in The Hamburger Abendblatt. ``Wherever I would have ended
up _ China, New York or Hamburg _ I would have been a
choreographer,'' Neumeier said. ``But like a seed, a choreographer
grows slightly differently in whatever soil he's put in. So I guess
my soil _ German soil _ has been very fertile for me.''
</P>
<P>
   His ``Bernstein Dances,'' a ballet-revue choreographed to a
suite of Leonard Bernstein's compositions, coincides with the
festival's tribute to the prolific composer. The idea for the
ballet emerged in 1978, when Neumeier made a version of ``West Side
Story'' that Bernstein saw in Hamburg. ``He was very enthusiastic,
and we became friends,'' Neumeier said.
</P>
<P>
   For his 20th anniversary with the Hamburg company, Neumeier
created a ballet using Bernstein's ``Serenade'' and piano
compositions, called ``Anniversaries,'' that Bernstein wrote as
gifts for friends and lovers.
</P>
<P>
   When Harry Kraut, Bernstein's manager, saw this
``Bernstein-Serenade'' in 1993, he said to Neumeier: ``That was
wonderful. Could you imagine doing a whole evening of his works?
Maybe even using some his songs and shorter symphonic works?''
Neumeier describes ``Bernstein Dances'' as ``kind of biographical
because it does go through stages of a person's, an artist's,
life.''
</P>
<P>
   The choreographer thrives on complicated subjects. Previous
topics range from the Bible _ as in ``Joseph's Legend'' (1977) and
``St. Matthew's Passion'' (1981) _ to Bavaria, as in ``Illusions:
Like Swan Lake'' (1976), based on the life of King Ludwig. These
dramatic narratives recall Cranko's story-ballet genre, but
Neumeier also cites Sybil Shearer, Antony Tudor and Jerome Robbins
as choreographers he particularly admires.
</P>
<P>
   For ``Bernstein Dances,'' Neumeier asked Giorgio Armani to dress
the performers. Armani's 427 costumes include mini-skirts and
halter tops for the women and long-sleeved shirts and classic
Armani suits for the men. They give the production a sophisticated,
cosmopolitan look, and with its Italian, American and German
collaborators, ``Bernstein Dances'' becomes a sort of microcosm of
German ballet: a scene that is shaped today by a cast of
international artists.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-98 1636EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
