<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980702.0176 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 16:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8093 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-DISABLED-2TAKES-$A     07-02 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-DISABLED-2TAKES-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUST ONE MAN'S SOCIETY, BUT IT SPEAKS FOR MANY  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 5) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 Mary Johnson is editor of The Disability Rag's Ragged Edge
magazine, which covers the disability-rights movement.  
 By MARY JOHNSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Soon after ``If I Can't Do It'' begins, Walter Brock, the
filmmaker, faces the camera and addresses the viewer. Arthur
Campbell Jr., the subject of this documentary, ``thinks I should
tell my account of our first meeting right up front,'' says Brock.
</P>
<P>
   ``He says it's the way society really feels about disabled
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Brock says that Campbell had been described to him only as a
disability-rights activist. He wasn't prepared to meet a man with
severe cerebral palsy and barely intelligible speech. He describes
his response: ``What kind of life could this guy have? Maybe the
most merciful thing to do would be to put him out of his misery.''
</P>
<P>
   Ten years later, that response still shocks Brock. ``Where does
such prejudice come from?'' he asks himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three's Company'' it's not. But television viewers who assume
that this documentary profile of a disabled person could be of no
possible interest to them will miss a program that is ultimately
less about disabled people than about viewers' own feelings.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I Can't Do It,'' which has its premiere on the PBS series
``P.O.V.'' on Tuesday at 10 p.m., seems a stunningly appropriate
observance right after Independence Day. This portrait of a
cantankerous activist-come-lately offers a vision not often seen on
television.
</P>
<P>
   The film may appear to deal only indirectly with the question of
prejudice as Campbell recounts his childhood, his escape from home
through a hunger strike and his later association with the
activists who gave shape and meaning to his life. But in fact,
prejudice is its overarching subject.
</P>
<P>
   Disabled people ``have suffered unspeakable torment _ and death
_ at the hands of their relatives and others, simply because they
do not look or do things as so-called normal people thought they
should,'' Campbell said in an e-mail interview, adding that they
are ``still denied the most basic of civil and human rights.''
</P>
<P>
   But our nation is not accustomed to thinking about the idea of
``disability prejudice.'' Scenes of activists kept out of
restaurants or off buses because of a lack of access haven't yet
generated the visceral response that most of us now feel when we
recall the ``white only'' and ``colored'' restrooms of the Old
South. We haven't had our consciousnesses raised.
</P>
<P>
   Most of us stick to our old convictions about what it's like to
be disabled. Campbell and his fellow protesters struggle to shake
those convictions but get little more than occasional random news
coverage (when Gallaudet University students demanded a deaf
college president in 1988, for instance, and when President Bush
signed the Americans With Disabilities Act in 1990). The issues
that disability activists raise are merely isolated news incidents;
they don't seem to merit sustained coverage.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the civil rights, women's rights and gay rights
movements, generating public enthusiasm for still another movement
is difficult. Yet of all movements, this one has the greatest
potential to humanize society: witness the concept of ``universal
design'' in housing, public buildings and products to make them
easier for everyone to use; the idea that living at home is better
than going to a nursing home; the advent of talking books,
voice-activated computers, television captioning that lets everyone
follow the game in a noisy sports bar.
</P>
<P>
   Yet pundits grouse that disability rights just let malingerers
and malcontents claim victim status and soak the legal system.
</P>
<P>
   That grousing comes from prejudice.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell hopes viewers will pay attention to what Adapt
(American Disabled for Attendant Programs Today) protesters with
their diverse and severe disabilities say in the film. ``If they
can live in their own homes on their own, with support systems to
help them day to day, then why can't the other two and a half
million of their fellow disabled brothers and sisters _ those who
are rotting away both mentally and physically in the institutions
and nursing homes in this nation _ do the same?''
</P>
<P>
   We've been taught to ``believe that disability is unnatural and
unsightly,'' said Campbell, ``so when I see myself on film I
cringe, worrying about how others react to how I look and move.''
He attributes this feeling to the way he believes he was
``programmed'' to feel from the age of 5 or 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt that I was a burden, causing fights in my family,'' he
said. He felt that guilt well into his 40s, he says, calling it
``part of a disability mentality that most of us with disabilities
never grow out of.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People like myself couldn't, or weren't allowed to, move into
the community on their own; there were no funds to hire someone to
come in and get them out of bed, bathe them, do personal hygiene,
dress them, prepare meals,'' he said. He believes his work in the
1980s _ which resulted in Kentucky offering more in-home services,
predating Adapt's current focus _ is the most important thing he
has done. Yet calling himself ``a has-been,'' he has now abandoned
the activism that once defined his life.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``I was born to be a leader,'' he says in a voice-over while the
film shows him eluding the police at a demonstration. ``And the
truth is there ain't no way,'' he says, for a man with his CP
speech impediment to do that in today's society.
</P>
<P>
   His longing and frustration mirror the feelings of every
disability activist I've encountered. Ed Hooper, a disability
movement writer, once put it this way: ``Our words, no matter how
clearly we communicate them, no matter how many facts we marshal,
society hears as so much gibberish.''
</P>
<P>
   The sense of belonging that Campbell found in Adapt has been the
salvation of many of his peers, salvation literally from suicide.
This belief in the saving grace of community spurs most disability
activists today.
</P>
<P>
   The group Not Dead Yet, for instance, offers a nuanced argument
that the so-called right to die has a disproportionate impact on
people with disabilities. Many have internalized the belief, as
Campbell once did, that they are useless burdens better off dead.
</P>
<P>
   Given the nation's still-unraised consciousness, however, Not
Dead Yet's analysis is dismissed by opinion makers who see all
right-to-die opposition as coming from the extreme political right.
</P>
<P>
   Activists rarely rebut conservatives' charges that the Americans
With Disabilities Act is out of control or that access is costing
the nation billions (it is one of today's more cost-effective
concepts). They don't write opinion pieces explaining why the
Supreme Court makes decisions like its recent ones validating the
disabilities act.
</P>
<P>
   The movers and shakers in the film _ Bob Kafka, Mike Auberger,
Cass Irvin _ are not yet the media equivalents of Gloria Steinem or
Larry Kramer.
</P>
<P>
   They're usually not credited for the changes they effect, a
point poignantly driven home by a weeping Shel Trapp, an Adapt
organizer, who sees a McDonald's commercial using sign language and
realizes with a start that an earlier Adapt protest demand has
borne fruit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Adapt did that!'' he shouts to his wife in a scene roughly
halfway through the film. ``Adapt did that!'' Viewers will very
likely weep with Trapp. But then they should ask why Adapt has been
unsung for so long.
</P>
<P>
   Today Adapt is working to shift federal long-term-care financing
from nursing homes to in-home services, using the Americans With
Disabilities Act to force states to redirect federal money to keep
people free of nursing homes and pressing the Department of Justice
to do the same.
</P>
<P>
   An Adapt-engineered bill in the House of Representatives (House
Resolution 2020, called Mi Casa) would move this agenda along. But
Mi Casa isn't on the nation's radar screen. ``The average person
could be behind this _ if they knew about it,'' says Mike Oxford,
an Adapt organizer.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell was leery of Brock's documentary idea at first: ``Most
filmmakers want to make us either some sympathetic, poor little
character that no one could have mature and normal relations with,
or some kind of a monster who has to be kept away and watched for
the safety of society or themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Brock is too astute to do this. Nevertheless, viewers may insist
on seeing Campbell's life as either inspiring or tragic. As
Campbell said, ``It's the way society really feels about
disability.''
</P>
<P>
   For such viewers, the personal here will never be political.
They won't recognize what this film has to do with their own lives,
even though all of us encounter illness and disability as we age.
But a film like ``If I Can't Do It'' can help us begin to
understand a new paradigm for our own futures. To not let it do so
would be the real tragedy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
