<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 16:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8105 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KUSAMA-ART-2TAKES-$AD     07-02 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KUSAMA-ART-2TAKES-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 5) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Calif., Japan)  
 A '60s FREE SPIRIT WHOSE MAIN SUBJECT WAS HERSELF   (af)  
 Edward M. Gomez has written about and curated exhibitions of
Japanese modern art in Japan and the United States.  
 By EDWARD M. GOMEZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ How do you classify Yayoi Kusama? Art historians,
critics and even other artists have found it difficult to
categorize the work of the Japanese-born artist, whose career
flourished in New York during the 1960s but whose art is not
exactly Pop, or Minimalist, or psychedelic, or Abstract
Expressionist.
</P>
<P>
   But from today's late-post-modern vantage point, Ms. Kusama's
art shared affinities with or anticipated all of these tendencies
and others, too. They include performance art, body art,
``feminist'' art and art forms full of role-playing or mass-media
manipulation that anticipated those developed later by artists like
Cindy Sherman, Yasumasa Morimura and Jeff Koons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Love Forever: Yayoi Kusama, 1958-1968,'' an exhibition that
opens Thursday at the Museum of Modern Art, explores this
art-historical lineage and other themes in a survey of 70 of the
artist's seminal works from her formative years in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The show, which remains on view through Sept. 22, includes
paintings, drawings, photographs, collages, sculptures, an
experimental film, three environmental installations and slides of
performance pieces.
</P>
<P>
   As a symbolic homecoming for Ms. Kusama to a city she adores but
left in 1973, ``Love Forever'' comes at a time of increasing
interest in '60s-era pop culture and of a surge in the career of
this reclusive Japanese artist, who is now 69 years old and who,
since 1977, has voluntarily resided in a Tokyo psychiatric
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   For someone seemingly emblematic of the free-wheeling spirit of
the '60s, even in her heyday Ms. Kusama, was something of an
art-world outsider. Japan's art establishment ignored Ms. Kusama
for a long time, until her overseas accomplishments forced it to
give her greater recognition.
</P>
<P>
   After a 1989 mini-retrospective at the now-defunct Center for
International Contemporary Arts in Manhattan, organized by the
Japanese modern-art specialist Alexandra Munroe, thrust Ms. Kusama
back into the international limelight, the artist was chosen to
represent Japan at the 1993 Venice Biennale.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kusama's fame did not come easily. She worked at it. As this
new show makes clear, she routinely put herself at the center of
her art and made special efforts to draw the attention of the news
media to her more sensational activities.
</P>
<P>
   A Wall Street nude-in and a body-painting event in Central Park,
for example, were a major part of her artistic project. ``This
artist transformed her persona into the most important work in her
oeuvre,'' says Laura Hoptman, an assistant curator at the Modern
and one of the show's organizers. ``It knits together the
paintings, sculptures and performances. They're Kusama's alter
ego.''
</P>
<P>
   For a Japanese woman, Ms. Kusama was unusually bold from the
beginning. She was one of four children who grew up in a well-to-do
rural household. Her father was mostly absent, and her mother
derided Yayoi's interest in art and her individualistic ways. She
even smeared and tore up her daughter's drawings.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of this tumultuous home life and wartime stress,
during childhood Ms. Kusama developed psychological disorders that
ultimately required psychiatric care. Emerging from deep anxiety,
her art has always been of and about obsession.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to pursue art to cure my mental illness,'' Ms. Kusama
has often remarked.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Munroe has noted that Ms. Kusama's art is its maker's
attempt to beat the self-obliterating power of her malady, which
has been called obsessional neurosis. ``It appears that as Kusama
became more familiar with the formal symptoms of her illness and
its childhood sources, her art became to a greater and greater
extent the literal working-out of her disorders,'' Ms. Munroe
writes in the show's catalog.
</P>
<P>
   At 28, with a few shows already behind her, the young artist
left Japan for the United States, but only after she had first
written to Georgia O'Keeffe for help. ``It seems to me very odd
that you are so ambitious to show your paintings here, but I wish
the best for you,'' Ms. O'Keeffe replied rather frostily.
</P>
<P>
   After a stopover in Seattle for her first solo gallery show in
America, Ms. Kusama arrived in Manhattan in 1958, armed with some
2,000 of her watercolors and drawings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming from Japan after the end of the long war, I felt a
sense of freedom in New York,'' the artist recalled in an interview
by fax from Tokyo. ``I was amazed, above all, by the high status of
women in society, far higher than in Japan. I did not leave Japan,
I fled Japan. Labeled as a lunatic, I had been ostracized from art
circles.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kusama immediately set out to find venues for her new works,
which, as her first solo outing 18 months later showed, quickly
assimilated the large-canvas proportions and techniques of the New
York School. These were the first of Ms. Kusama's ``infinity net''
paintings, whose all-over, intricately wrought net pattern, like
the ubiquitous polka dots that became her other signature motif,
had appeared in her earliest drawings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nearly all-white and monochromatic, these first `infinity net'
paintings made a perfect bridge between Abstract Expressionism and
what would later become known as Minimalism,'' says Lynn Zelevansky
of the Los Angeles County Museum of Art, where ``Love Forever,''
which she curated with Ms. Hoptman, originated.
</P>
<P>
   In these works, hand labor is intensive, unlike the mechanical
processes of stenciling or silk-screening that the Pop artists
favored, and they exude an obsessive quality with their daunting
repetitiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``If my sculpture and performance are a positive, my visionary
and apocalyptic paintings, which I have produced in large
quantities, are a negative,'' Ms. Kusama says. ``They spring up
from the bottom of my negative soul to heal it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kusama went on to develop soft sculptures in which she
covered armchairs, tables, high-heeled shoes and, most famously, an
entire rowboat with bulbous, phallic protrusions. Painted silver or
bright colors with polka dots, these creations, which she often
presented in installation groupings, gave physical form to her
obsessional neurosis. Even today, they possess an eerie, erotic
allure. They have frequently been described as fetishistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Love Forever'' features many classics of this genre, which
presaged the pop sculptor Claes Oldenburg's switch from
papier-mache to soft materials, including ``Accumulation No. 1''
(1962) and ``Aggregation: One Thousand Boats Show'' (1964).
</P>
<P>
   ``Aggregation'' incorporated 999 posters of the rowboat
sculpture, covering the walls around it. Andy Warhol saw and
admired Ms. Kusama's showing of this full-scale environment at the
Gertrude Stein Gallery in 1963, before he produced his own ``Cow
Wallpaper.''
</P>
<P>
   A famous image from that time shows Ms. Kusama posing nude, her
backside to the camera, at the edge of her surreal boat. In fact,
she appears in nearly all the photographs of her work from the New
York era that ``Love Forever'' documents. ``She was and is not
separable from it,'' Ms. Zelevansky says. ``She animated the art.''
Ms. Zelevansky describes this role of Ms. Kusama's within or
alongside her artworks, where she was often seen, as her art's
distinctly ``performative'' aspect.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kusama befriended many other artists in New York, including
Barnett Newman, Donald Judd and Joseph Cornell, who adored her and
sent her collaged billets-doux from his Utopia Parkway retreat.
</P>
<P>
   In Europe, her intensely personal work shared certain
art-as-object, abstract characteristics with that of participants
in the German Zero and Dutch Nul groups with whom she exhibited.
But as ``Love Forever'' demonstrates and Ms. Hoptman emphasizes:
``Kusama always went her own way. She was never a joiner.''
</P>
<P>
   That individualism, her drive and her survival story have
endeared Ms. Kusama to younger artists who have discovered her rich
visual vocabulary and prescient treatment of now-timely themes.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a unique bridge between outsider art and fine art,''
says Jon Waldo, a New York painter and ceramics artist with folk
art and rock-and-roll roots. Others note the links between Ms.
Kusama's ``sex and food obsession'' works, like her mid-1960s
macaroni-encrusted shirts and handbags, and the current concern
about bulimia and anorexia.
</P>
<P>
   And many viewers have been moved by the alchemical aura of the
Japanese artist's creations, in which, like Eva Hesse or Louise
Bourgeois, she powerfully transforms the meaning and nature of her
materials.
</P>
<P>
   In her newest works, on view at the Robert Miller Gallery
through Aug. 7, Ms. Kusama has applied her infinity nets to Venus
de Milo statues. She has also made elegant updated ``accumulation''
works featuring clusters of plump phallic protuberances, Barbie
dolls and even kitchen utensils painted gold.
</P>
<P>
   Paradoxically, ``Kusama wasn't really right for the 60s,'' Ms.
Zelevansky says. ``But she had great antennae. She has always been
a very sophisticated artist, and in these pluralistic times, people
really are interested in and respond to her kind of idiosyncrasy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-98 1640EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980702.0180 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8108 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT &LR;      07-02 0609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`AMERICAN STORIES: THE AMERICAN DREAM': AMERICA'S ESSENCE IN
ANECDOTES 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Broadcast notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
(bl) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``American Stories: The American Dream,'' from the Discovery
Channel, is a discount version of ``People's Century,'' the 26-part
world-history lesson that started on PBS in April and promises to
carry on into the 20th century's twilight.
</P>
<P>
   Both productions offer resounding events as experienced by
people who were caught up in them: history from below. But the
Discovery Channel series, which arrives Saturday, concentrates on
the United States and does the job in a mere five hours.
</P>
<P>
   The merger of oral history and newsreels has a natural appeal
for the television producer; eyewitness drama comes more readily to
the camera than intellectual depth. At its most effective, the form
can be stirring; the pictures from the archives combined with the
accounts of how war and weather, reform and rebellion touched or
transformed the lives of individuals and families invite empathy.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, ``American Stories'' is not all that effective.
There are moving moments, but many scenes will seem familiar, even
derivative, to fans of more innovative historical excursions,
notably ``The American Experience.'' The writing keeps edging into
platitude (a line like ``His name was Franklin D. Roosevelt'' must
be aimed at children), and the history is thin.
</P>
<P>
   The idea here is to concentrate on 10 people who lived through
upheavals like the stock market crash, World War II, the Vietnam
War, the civil-rights movement and what has come to be known as the
Reagan era.
</P>
<P>
   In Saturday night's opening hour, we meet Oklahoma and Arkansas
farmers who lost everything to dust storms and Depression and
braved the hard trip to California in search of paradise; a scion
of the patrician Peabody clan, embodiment of the East Coast
establishment, who wound up as governor of Massachusetts; two Ford
automobile workers, one black, one white, who fought together in
union-organizing battles, and an offspring of Jewish immigrants who
went from the family delicatessen to prosperity via the City
College of New York.
</P>
<P>
   The mixture of success and failure, of grand hopes and bitter
disappointments gives force to the memories. The white Ford worker,
an immigrant from Malta, says, ``I thought I was in heaven here,''
but his black co-worker remembers the factory as ``a hell on
earth.'' The former student credits City College with turning
success ``from a possibility to a real probability,'' but the farm
woman whose family was uprooted says, ``You felt unnecessary.''
</P>
<P>
   The people are easy to identify with, and their recollections
seem honest. But even by undemanding television standards,
``American Stories'' delivers what viewers have already seen and
heard in superior documentaries, and some of the personal
interludes, like the Peabody romance, are just dull. The packaging
is efficient, but the narration, delivered by Peter Fonda, is
relentlessly conventional, in the spirit of a play-it-safe
junior-high textbook.
</P>
<P>
   ``These stories,'' he reports, ``take us to the heart and soul
of the American dream.'' It seems to me they take us mainly where
we have already been many times.
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   ``AMERICAN STORIES: THE AMERICAN DREAM''
</P>
<P>
   Discovery Channel, Saturday night at 6
</P>
<P>
   Peter Fonda, narrator; produced by Atlantic Productions for
Discovery Channel; Anthony Geffen, executive producer; Nancy
LeBrun, executive producer for Discovery Channel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
