   &UR; MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ROCK-POET-TEX (Undated) _ There's no questioning Jesse F.
Garcia's allegiance to the music of the Rolling Stones, Beatles,
Jimi Hendrix, the Who, the Grateful Dead and dozens more _ right up
to R.E.M. and Rage Against the Machine _ the minute one starts
reading ``Rock 'N' Roll Dreams,'' his slim, self-published first
volume of poetry. By Dave Ferman.
</P>
<P>
   60S-MUSIC GUY-TEX (Undated) _ Like a lot of people, Ricky the K
is stranded in the '60s. He's obsessed with classic '60s Top 40
radio. The difference is, he's making his obsession pay off by
creating his own station and selling subscriptions to listeners on
the Internet for a three-hours-a-day, five-nights-a-week dose of
mirth, music and vintage Winston cigarette ads. By John Austin.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-MCKENNITT-BOS (Undated) _ Loreena McKennitt, a Canadian
new age/world music singer, has finally gotten notice, in no small
part because of her manager, Loreena McKennitt. By Jim Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   LILITH-SECOND-KAN (Undated) _ An interview with Lilith Fair
founder Sarah McLachan. She talks about the second year: more
money, more following. at-risk readers, handout art. By Timothy
Finn.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GENERAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CRAMER-PROFILE-MEDIA-NYT (Undated) _ A profile of the ubiquitous
James Cramer of Street.com fame. By Lisa Napoli.
</P>
<P>
   NEESON-BROADWAY-NYT (New York) _ Liam Neeson talks about his
role as Oscar Wilde in the Broadway production ``The Judas Kiss.''
By Anita Gates.
</P>
<P>
   EXCLUSIVE-MCVEIGH-NYT (Undated) _ Previously undisclosed letters
written before the Oklahoma City bombing and subsequent FBI
interviews conducted afterward indicate that even though Timothy
McVeigh never confided any plans to his family, he could not hide
his feelings, so much so that his father and sister suspected right
after the 1995 blast that he had been responsible. But the McVeigh
family was divided on the issue of how Timothy McVeigh came to hate
the government so much that he would kill 168 men, women and
children. By Jo Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   MARV-ALBERT-NYT (New York) _ Marv Albert's life is one without
work. Nine months after pleading guilty to misdemeanor assault
three days into an embarrassing trial, he attends movies; reads
voraciously; plays tennis with Kenny, his oldest son, and his
brother, Steve; walks his new pugs, Lulu and Ruby, and plans a
future with his fiancee, Heather Faulkiner, from their duplex
apartment on Columbus Avenue. By Richard Sandomir.
</P>
<P>
   STANTON-RIGHTS (Undated) _ On a hot July day in 1848, a
frustrated upstate New York housewife named Elizabeth Cady Stanton
assembled a convention in a Seneca Falls church and made the
radical demand that women be allowed to vote. In that moment, she
changed not only American history but the expectations placed on
the next five generations of women in her own family. By Elisabeth
Bumiller.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVIES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-AFFLECK-PROFILE (Los Angeles) _ Last fall he roamed among
us almost unnoticed. Now he's starring in a blockbuster, dating
actress Gwyneth Paltrow, sporting an Oscar and posing shirtless for
the cover of GQ magazine. For Ben Affleck, it's been ``one weird
transition.'' Affleck stars in ``Armageddon,'' which opened
nationwide Wednesday. By Bruce Westbrook.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-AFFLECK-BOS (Los Angeles) _ Ben Affleck muses about
``Hollyweird'' and his new movie, ``Armageddon.'' By Jay Carr.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-DOWN-BOS (Undated) -- Newcomer Peter McDonald talks about
``I Went Down,'' his new buddy movie with a twist. By Patti
Hartigan.
</P>
<P>
   WILL-PATTON-FILM-NYT (Undated) _ For Will Patton, it's the end
of the world. Again. In the course of some 30 films, the actor has
endured post-apocalyptic mail carriers, squishy parasites from
outer space and the wrath of God, so this weekend's scourge _ an
asteroid the size of Texas, headed straight for Earth _ should be
no trouble. Patton is appearing in ``Armageddon,'' which stars
Bruce Willis and is the summer's second doomsday adventure movie.
By Justine Elias.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BOOKS  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-BRIDGET-KAN (Undated) _ Here's an ugly thought: What if
someone were to put Helen Fielding's new novel, ``Bridget Jones's
Diary,'' into a time capsule so as to preserve for women of the
distant future an image of what they might have been like if they
had lived today? By Anne Stephenson.
</P>
