<SLUG> BC-TALK-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TALK TO ME': BETTY AND VERONICA SEEK A GUY WHO'S NO JUGHEAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Betty and Veronica are the focal females of ``Talk to Me,'' but
the action is far from the teen-age angst of Archie Comics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Talk to Me'' may have been made in 1996, but it is very much
at home in 1998 because it revolves around telephone sex.
</P>
<P>
   In this amiable, modest romantic comedy, Betty and Veronica are
facing the dread age of 30, and the romantic lives of these New
Yorkers are not in the best of shape.
</P>
<P>
   Betty hasn't had sex in nine months. Veronica, or Ronnie as she
is known, is still dating Stuart even though they have broken up
because he said he wasn't ready for marriage.
</P>
<P>
   So one night Betty (Cheryl Clifford) succumbs to the temptation
to dial the ``900'' number of the Universe of Love (``Tired of
being judged before a person can get to know the real you?''), and
soon she finds herself smitten with the voice of a young man named
Arnold Dowling (Peter Welch).
</P>
<P>
   And not long after that, they are involved in a private
telephonic chat, shucking off clothes and acting out a fantasy
about a cleaning woman in a blue uniform, a white apron and high
heels and some sudsy water.
</P>
<P>
   But Arnold, it seems, has a problem, which his brother Michael
(Gary Navicoff), a psychiatrist, is trying to address. Arnold, an
architect, has been traumatized by a devastating office romance.
After a year, without warning, Maggie, Arnold's love, turned up one
day wearing another man's engagement ring.
</P>
<P>
   What he cannot stand, therefore, is a liar, and what he has not
yet discovered is that the woman he knows on the telephone only as
Miranda is actually Betty.
</P>
<P>
   Well, one day Betty will actually track down the reticent
Arnold, and they will have a date, which will lead to
complications. And in the meantime, Veronica (Elizabeth Landis),
will also decide to let her fingers do the trolling, which leads
her into the lair and limo of the suave Frederick (Ralph Romeo).
</P>
<P>
   George Esguerra, who produced and directed ``Talk to Me'' and
wrote the screenplay with Robert Foulkes, displays a nice
understanding of the scars of the dating game, the difficulties of
the mating game, the uses of guises and the elements of human
comedy. ``Talk to Me'' holds no special surprises and reaches no
heights of hilarity, but Betty and Arnold prove to be the sort of
decent people who deserve a happy ending.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   ``TALK TO ME''
</P>
<P>
   CAST: Cheryl Clifford (Betty Cole), Peter Welch (Arnold
Dowling), Elizabeth Landis (Veronica), Gary Navicoff (Michael) and
Ralph Romeo (Frederick). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Produced and directed by George Esguerra; written by Esguerra
and Robert Foulkes; director of photography, Randy Drummond; edited
by Tom McArdle; music by David McLary; released by Northern Arts
Entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   RUNNING TIME: 87 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   RATING: This film is not rated. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
