<BODY>
 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
Page 1, Friday, July 3. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (212-556-1927).
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   NIGERIA (United Nations) _ Nigeria's new military government
pledged today to release all remaining political prisoners,
Secretary General Kofi Annan said after meeting with the country's
President, Gen. Abdulsalam Abubakar. Annan said among those freed
would be Moshood K.O. Abiola, who apparently won a presidential
election in 1993, but was arrested for trying to take office after
Nigeria's military rulers annulled the vote. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-GAZPROM (Moscow) _ Russia's legendarily ineffectual tax
men stared down the nation's biggest and most powerful corporation
today, threatening to seize control of the firm _ and its
executives' dachas, yachts and other perks _ unless it coughed up
billions of rubles in back taxes and billions more every month
hereafter. To most everyone's amazement, the company, Gazprom, gave
in. By the end of a day filled with bluster and rumor, Gazprom had
agreed to start paying the government monthly taxes of about four
billion rubles, or some $645 million, and to turn over another 4.2
billion rubles in unpaid taxes by Monday. By Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-BLAIR (Belfast, Northern Ireland) _ Arsonists believed
to be members of a dissident Protestant group set fire to 10 Roman
Catholic churches in Northern Ireland early today and late
Wednesday night, setting off fears that wider sectarian violence
might return to in the British province. The police and officials
said the arson was probably the work of the Loyalist Volunteer
Force, a Protestant group opposed to the peace effort that has
produced cooperation between Protestants and Catholics in a new
provincial assembly. In an unusual move for a British Prime
Minister, Tony Blair flew to the province today to try to dispel
rising tension in this predominantly Protestant British province.
By James F. Clarity.
</P>
<P>
   DIANA-MUSEUM (Great Brington, England) _ If there were any
dissenters here who found it all a bit much _ the rush of cars on
once-quiet country roads; the $15 commemorative pillboxes; the
fresh expressions of grief that made it seem almost as if Diana,
the Princess of Wales, died last week instead of last August _ they
were mostly keeping quiet Thursday. ``I don't want to talk to you,
and I don't want to give my opinion,'' said one woman, answering
the door at her cottage not far from the gates of Althorp House,
Diana's childhood home. She did agree to sell a jar of homemade
honey, though, for $2.50. ``You should have seen the crowds
yesterday. One person was very rude.'' The crowds were bound, of
course, for Althorp, where Diana's brother, Earl Spencer, opened a
$5 million shrine (and a cafe and gift shop) to her memory on
Tuesday. By Sarah Lyall.
</P>
<P>
   SWISS-BANKS (Undated) _ The Swiss government said in a private
meeting that it has no intention of restoring any of the billions
of dollars in gold, cash and jewelry that the Nazis stole from
Holocaust victims and then sold to the Swiss government to raise
cash for war material, Alan G. Hevesi, the city controller, said
Thursday. Hevesi disclosed the remarks, made in a closed door
meeting of state and local government finance officers by the Swiss
ambassador, Jacques Reverdin, in announcing escalating sanctions
against Swiss banks, and ultimately all Swiss corporations, that
New York city and state will take unless restitution is made. By
David Cay Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MARINE-JET-CRASH (Washington) _ Failures by the Marine Corps and
the Air Force to disseminate crucial information cast ``substantial
doubt'' on whether the captain of a plane that hit a ski lift cable
in the Italian alps in February could be convicted in a
court-martial, a hearing officer found in a report released
Thursday. But the hearing officer said the captain should be tried
on the most serious possible charges in the accident that killed 20
people and caused a rift between Italy and the United States over
prosecution of the four-man crew. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   JULY4-RISKS (Washington) _ The hottest holiday argument this
weekend may be between partisans of wet or dry barbecue, or over
whether a day at the beach is worth half a day spent in traffic.
But there were Independence Days two centuries ago when the
consummate celebration of American nationalism decayed into bitter
disputes between rival political parties, exceeding even the
political passions that the early Republic displayed for the other
364 days of the year. At a lecture this week in the National
Archives, historian Len Travers of the Massachusetts Historical
Society described how the day became ensconced as a central rite of
the emerging republic. In those days, a fellow could be beaten for
wearing the wrong party's colors on his hat, and Boston routinely
threw two separate celebrations, each controlled by one of the two
contending political parties of the day. By John H. Cushman Jr.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CNN-NERVE-GAS (Undated) _ CNN retracted its story that the U.S.
military used deadly nerve gas during a Vietnam-era mission in Laos
to kill American defectors, apologizing for ``serious faults'' in
its reporting. A senior producer has resigned and the two main
producers of the report will be leaving CNN, sources said. The lead
reporter, Peter Arnett, has been reprimanded, a CNN source said. By
Felicity Barringer.
</P>
<P>
   FLA-FIRES (Ormond Beach, Fla.) _ At least 80 homes and other
buildings were burned overnight, 35,000 people were evacuated, and
the fires ravaging two counties were only expected to get bigger
Thursday. By Mireya Navarro. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CLIMBING-MT-MCKINLEY (Talkeetna, Alaska) _ The cemetery in this
risk-lover's domain should be enough to keep most people from
trying to stand atop the High One, as Athabaskan natives call Mount
McKinley. The climbers came from all over the world, drawn to the
highest point in North America, and they ended up with their names
on granite here _ 118 dead over the last 65 years. But there is no
sense of horror or defeat in the summer shadows. After nearly a
monthlong disappearance behind a cloak of mist and storms, the
mountain is out _ a hulk of luminous ice pressing the upper reaches
of the sky at 20,320 feet. So, even though three people have died
so far this climbing season, McKinley is more of a lure than ever
before. By Timothy Egan.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ The hot economy is showing definite
signs of cooling, but by only a few degrees. In June, the Labor
Department reported Thursday, unemployment edged up to 4.5 percent
and the pace of job creation slowed, dropping to 205,000 from more
than 300,000 in the two previous months. There were other signs of
moderation. Total hours worked dipped a bit, a clear indication
that the nation's gross domestic productthe output of goods and
services was growing much more slowly than last winter. The
moderation, however, follows a very torrid pace of the last six
months. By any historical standard, job creation remains robust and
unemployment very low indeed. Just one year ago, jobelessness stood
at 5 percent. And theres no sign in Thursday's report that the
economy was tipping into recessionas some bears have been saying.
By Sylvia Nasar.
</P>
