<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980702.0189 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 16:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8137 &Cx1f; ttf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  NEW&AMP;NOTEWORTHYTEXT7/12     07-02 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY TEXT 7/12
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anything Your Little Heart Desires: An American Family Story
</P>
<P>
   By Patricia Bosworth. Touchstone/Simon &AMP; Schuster, $15. The
daughter of Bartley C. Crum, the famous corporate lawyer of the
1940's and 50's and champion of leftist causes, tracks the dazzling
arc of her father's life, including his undoing by his personal and
political furies. Last year our reviewer, Richard Lingeman, called
this a ''multilayered act of discovery and reconciliation . . . in
which redemption comes from the truth of the telling.''
</P>
<P>
   Underworld
</P>
<P>
   By Don DeLillo. Scribner, $16. This sprawling wake for the cold
war explores how people rearranged their lives around the moral
void of Mutual Assured Destruction, with its attending terror and
absurdity. Selected by the editors of the Book Review as one of the
best books of 1997, the novel spans half a century, from its
opening in 1951 at one of baseball's legendary games to its
epilogue in central Asia. The characters - both fictional and
cultural heroes like Frank Sinatra and Lenny Bruce - are
psychological fallout victims. '' 'Underworld' surges with
magisterial confidence,'' Martin Amis said here last year. ''It
isn't every day, or even every decade, that one sees the ascension
of a great writer.''
</P>
<P>
   Resurrection: The Struggle for a New Russia
</P>
<P>
   By David Remnick. Vintage, $15. The author argues that the
Russian people have had their fill of Boris N. Yeltsin and the
oligarchs who gained power after his re-election in 1996. ''As a
gifted journalist, with an eye for the broad themes as well as the
telling details of a story, he provides us with an amplitude of
particulars'' about the miseries that have occurred during
Yeltsin's reign of deception and criminality, Abraham Brumberg
wrote here last year. The thesis of Petersburg, Crucible of
Cultural Revolution, by Katerina Clark (Harvard University,
$18.95), is that the city's idealistic artists and intellectuals
during the tumultuous years between 1913 and 1931 created an
atmosphere that made the Great Terror of the late 1930's possible.
This revisionist account is ''a major contribution to the cultural
history of this seminal period,'' Harlow Robinson said in the Book
Review in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The Blessing
</P>
<P>
   By Nancy Mitford. Carroll &AMP; Graf, $10.95. This spirited riff on
French-British relations on the highest social plane pits a
beautiful English wife and her charming French nobleman husband
against a diabolical villain: their young son. The result is a
''cunningly constructed, artfully written . . . farce of the most
civilized kind,'' Elizabeth Janeway wrote here in 1951.
</P>
<P>
   Imagining Robert. My Brother, Madness, and Survival: A Memoir
</P>
<P>
   By Jay Neugeboren. Owl/Holt, $14.95. A novelist describes his
younger brother's 30-year battle with mental illness, and his own
struggle to navigate the nightmarish system of mistreatment and
inattentive care that dooms many victims of schizophrenia and
manic-depressive disorder. This is a ''powerful story,'' Frederick
Busch said in these pages in 1997. In Out of the Shadows:
Confronting America's Mental Illness Crisis, by E. Fuller Torrey
(Wiley, $16.95), a psychiatrist reports that millions of Americans
are suffering from severe mental illness without treatment. ''The
crisis he delineates should stir any halfway sensitive human being
to anger,'' Daniel J. Kevles wrote here last year.
</P>
<P>
   The Underground Man
</P>
<P>
   By Mick Jackson. Penguin, $12.95. This first novel focuses on
one of Victorian England's most famous eccentrics, the real-life
fifth Duke of Portland, who built an elaborate network of tunnels
beneath his lands to allow him hidden access to all parts of his
realm. ''Jackson has produced a marvelous study of human foibles,''
Erik Burns said here in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Bear and His DaughTer: Stories
</P>
<P>
   By Robert Stone. Mariner/Houghton Mifflin, $12. The novelist's
first collection of short fiction is populated by men who feel most
alive when they are angry. In evoking a kind of grinding male
arrest, ''Stone turns the scraps and figments of style that we call
characters into real people,'' James Wood wrote here last year.
</P>
<P>
   Never Eat Your Heart Out
</P>
<P>
   By Judith Moore. North Point, $13. A California writer and
editor expresses her life story through the food she has prepared,
peppering her lively account with bite-sized essays on everything
from the history of the cranberry to the sex life of turkeys. Last
year our reviewer, Susan Cheever, called this a ''tart,
satisfying'' memoir.
</P>
<P>
   The Teachings of Don B.: Satires, Parodies, Fables, Illustrated
Stories, and Plays of Donald Barthelme
</P>
<P>
   Edited by Kim Herzinger. Vintage International, $15. Whether a
parody of Bret Easton Ellis or a shaggy dog story about a
4,000-pound Gouda cheese, the 63 pieces collected here bristle with
the author's delight in surprising the reader with his
genre-jumping acrobatics. The result is ''a small education in
laughter, melancholy and the English language,'' James Marcus wrote
here in 1992. A Dog's Head, by Jean Dutourd, translated by Robin
Chancellor (University of Chicago, $12), is a slender Barthelmesque
fantasy about a middle-class Frenchman born with the t te of a
spaniel. This satirical novel is ''sad-eyed, witty and often very
funny,'' C. J. Rolo wrote here in 1953.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Veale...end
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-98 1652EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
