<DOCNO> NYT19980702.0190 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 16:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8145 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RESORT-BOOK-REVIEW-NY     07-02 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RESORT-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE LAST RESORT': SCENES FROM A FALTERING MARRIAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: publication notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The basic ingredients of Alison Lurie's new novel ``The Last
Resort'' are the same as those she used in ``The War Between the
Tates,'' her classic 1974 portrait of a disintegrating marriage: an
eminent man, who is working on an important book; his once
worshipful helpmate of a wife; their two disappointing children;
the wife's best friend, who happens to be a bossy feminist, and a
bubble-headed young woman who has made herself the chief groupie of
the eminent man.
</P>
<P>
   The recipe used to put these ingredients together, however, has
undergone serious change, and not for the better. In renouncing her
gift for psychological insight and social detail, Ms. Lurie has
produced a thin, spindly novel, peopled not by flesh and blood
characters but by papery cartoons. Her wicked sense of humor, once
used to point up the absurdities of contemporary life, is now
employed solely at her characters' expense, just as her cool
omniscience has given way to a chilly, sardonic detachment.
</P>
<P>
   As ``The Last Resort'' opens, we are introduced to the Walkers:
Wilkie, a famous naturalist (``perhaps the most famous popular
naturalist of his generation'') who is working on a biography of a
tree called ``The Copper Beech,'' and his much younger wife, Jenny,
who has devoted her adult life to helping Wilkie with his books.
</P>
<P>
   Something has happened recently to upset the Walkers' pleasant
routine. The 70-year old Wilkie has become convinced that he is
suffering from colon cancer, and he has also begun to despair about
his career. He feels that he has become a mere popularizer of
serious environmental issues, a has-been who has inspired a host of
``posturing, sentimental amateur naturalists.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Jenny has no idea that Wilkie has decided to commit
suicide, she is concerned about his deepening depression and
proposes spending the winter in the vacation paradise of Key West.
</P>
<P>
   As things happen in novels like this, the change of scenery will
work all sorts of changes on the Walkers' life. Jenny takes a
part-time job for the first time in her life, becomes friends with
a feisty feminist named Lee Weiss and carries on flirtations with
both Lee and a self-dramatizing poet named Gerald Grass. As for
Wilkie, he meets an ardent fan named Barbie Mumpson, the plump,
unhappily married wife of a congressman, and he realizes that he
enjoys a devoted audience among Florida retirees.
</P>
<P>
   Will Wilkie be thwarted in his efforts to commit suicide or will
he think better of his plans to kill himself? Will his marriage to
Jenny break up? Will she become a feminist or take off with Lee or
Gerald? And what of Wilkie's book? Will it become the capstone of
his career or be abandoned as a sad, unfinished symbol of his
unraveling reputation?
</P>
<P>
   These questions are supposed to propel ``The Last Resort''
toward its conclusion, but the reader has an increasingly difficult
time caring what happens to any of Ms. Lurie's characters, who are
uniformly portrayed as dimwitted ninnies and jerks, unimaginative
stereotypes in the gender wars the author has been chronicling for
so many years. The men are male chauvinist pigs who want their
wives and girlfriends to wait on them night and day while the women
are either sniveling little creatures who hang on their husbands'
every word or noisy feminists, bitter and hostile toward men.
</P>
<P>
   In earlier novels like ``The War Between the Tates'' and
``Foreign Affairs,'' Ms. Lurie performed a delicate balancing act,
using her authorial omniscience to portray her characters'
tumultuous emotional lives from within, while at the same time
showing us the comical, self-deluding faces they present to the
world.
</P>
<P>
   This time, she has all but abandoned any effort to examine their
inner lives, and as a result they quickly devolve into brittle,
satiric pawns, pushed hither and thither like chess pieces by the
author's heavy hand.
</P>
<P>
   Wilkie emerges as a sour old coot, selfish, self-absorbed and
self-pitying. He's the sort of cutesy naturalist writer who sees
people as animals and plants. When he's thinking fondly of Jenny,
she seems like a ``transfigured human version of a salt marsh
mouse.'' When he's angry at her, she comes to resemble the common
garden shrew with a ``shrill little twittering voice.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that Ms. Lurie's own characterization of Jenny is
equally cliched. In fact, Jenny comes across in this novel as a
sadly submissive sap; though it's the 1990s, she has spent her life
behaving like a parody of a '50s sitcom housewife, worrying about
how much of Wilkie's life ``was wasted on inessentials'' and
echoing his every thought.
</P>
<P>
   As Gerald the poet observes: ``A real wife. I thought they
didn't make them anymore. Classically beautifully, well-educated,
intelligent, fantastic gourmet cook. And besides that, she keeps
their accounts, drives the car, answers Wilkie's letters and does
all his research. And whatever he believes, she just naturally goes
along.''
</P>
<P>
   The social matrix the Walkers inhabit feels similarly cursory in
tone. Gone is the Updikean detail that made the lives of the Tates
and other characters so palpable in earlier novels; gone is the
complicated network of relationships that anchored her earlier
characters' lives.
</P>
<P>
   Although Ms. Lurie's prose is fluent as ever, the reader learns
almost nothing about the Walkers' life in New England, and their
experience in Key West is defined almost completely in terms of
predictable encounters with new acquaintances and friends, all of
them tired types, from colorful homosexuals and anxious retirees to
boorish tourists and smarmy panderers to the tourist trade.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps this is why ``The Last Resort'' even feels flimsy as a
physical object. In retrospect, its small pages and large type seem
indicative of the attenuation of the story itself.
</P>
<P>
   Publication notes:
</P>
<P>
   THE LAST RESORT
</P>
<P>
   By Alison Lurie
</P>
<P>
   321 pages. Henry Holt &AMP; Co. $22.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
