even if there's no matching contribution. By Kenneth Hooker.
</P>
<P>
   YIP-COLUMN-HNS (Undated) _ Utility stocks have had a good run
lately. What's unusual about that is that they've done it in a
still-strong stock market. ``Utilities have been the
best-performing sector of the market for the last four weeks,''
said Hugh Johnson, chief investment officer at First Albany Corp.
in Albany, N.Y. By Pamela Yip.
</P>
<P>
   JOHN-DORFMAN (Boston) _ A couple of restaurant stocks look
attractively cheap to me right now. Commentary. By John Dorfman.
</P>
<P>
   SUSAN-ANTILLA-COLUMN (New York) _ Viagra isn't the only would-be
miracle that's surprising seniors with unexpected shocks these
days. Some elders are finding their financial portfolios suddenly
deflated after falling for a high interest-rate pitch with a
too-good-to-be-true promise of generous returns for little risk.
Commentary. By Susan Antilla.
</P>
<P>
   CAROLINE-BAUM (New York) _ The front end of the Treasury yield
curve has run as far as could in the face of strong economic news.
But give it a whiff of weak economic news, which is what it got
today, and a neutral Fed, and the possibilities are endless.
Commentary. By Caroline Baum.
</P>
