<P>
   &UR; FEATURES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   OPTIMISM-HEALTH-NYT _ People who look on the bright side have
reason to be optimistic. Evidence suggests that they have
healthier, longer lives than their gloom-and-doom counterparts. By
Susan Gilbert.  &UR; Moved 6-29. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AIDS-RELATED &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-AIDS-NYT (Geneva) _ The body's immune system can recover to
a large extent, even after it has been ravaged by severe AIDS,
according to evidence reported here on Wednesday by French
scientists at the 12th World AIDS Conference. By Lawrence K.
Altman.  &UR; Moved 7-1. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-EXPERIMENT-BOS (Geneva) _ If ethics committees approve,
researchers in Boston and Geneva will soon do the crucial AIDS
experiment: Stop all antiviral drugs in a group of patients who
began treatment soon after they became infected with the human
immunodeficiency virus (HIV). The aim is to see if these patients'
immune systems have revived enough to keep the AIDS virus under
permanent control, just as most people's do with the chickenpox,
Herpes simplex, or Epstein-Barr virus. By Richard A. Knox.  &UR; Moved
7-1. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-RESISTANT-BOS (Geneva) _ AIDS specialists had hoped it
wouldn't happen, but now, they say, they know that strains of HIV
that are immune to the most potent triple-drug treatments can be
passed from one person to another. By Richard A. Knox.  &UR; Moved
6-30. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-PREGNANT-BOS (Geneva) _ Opening a new front in the global
fight against AIDS, U.N. officials said Monday they would offer
30,000 pregnant women in developing nations access to a drug
regimen recently proven to cut their risk of transmitting the AIDS
virus to their babies. By Richard A. Knox.  &UR; Moved 6-29. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-UNPROTECTED-BOS (Geneva) _ A 50 percent increase of
high-risk sex among gay men in San Francisco has surprised and
puzzled AIDS experts there, because it has so far not shown up in
higher rates of human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) infection. By
Richard A. Knox.  &UR; Moved 6-29. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BLACKS-AIDS-NYT (Washington) _ Seventeen years after AIDS was
first recognized among gay white men in New York and San Francisco,
the disease in this country is becoming largely an epidemic among
black people, quietly devastating families and neighborhoods, yet
all but ignored by leading black institutions. By Sheryl Gay
Stolberg.  &UR; Moved 6-28. With photo. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DIET/NUTRITION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BRODY-HEALTH-NYT _ Picture a childhood without ice cream or the
occasional hot dog or burger at a birthday party or ball game.
Picture in their stead organic applesauce, peanut butter and soy
patties. The latter are the kinds of foods children should be fed
if they are to grow up lean and healthy, states the most
influential book on bringing up children, Dr. Benjamin Spock's
``Baby and Child Care'' (Pocket Books). By Jane E. Brody.  &UR; Moved
6-29. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EXERCISE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CIR-HEART-MONITORS-NYT _ Heart-rate monitors are an increasingly
popular tool and a part of a nationwide boom in fitness-equipment
sales, which reached $3 billion last year. In 1998 heart-rate
monitor sales in the United States will top $40 million, up 15
percent from 1997, says Corey Cornacchio, director of marketing at
Polar Electro, a company that claims 80 percent of the worldwide
market. By Alex Frankel.  &UR; Moved 7-1. With photo. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INSURANCE  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-HEALTH-ASSESS-NYT (Washington) _ They gritted their
teeth, but on Wednesday, with their health-care gurus lined up
shoulder to shoulder, House Republicans unveiled their plan to
patch up managed care with such measures as expanding a patient's
ability to choose a doctor and to receive emergency care. By
Lizette Alvarez.  &UR; Moved 6-26. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-POIROT-COLUMN-TEX _ The solution is more organ donation,
not wider distribution. Changing the rules to require nationwide
allocation of organs and tissues for transplant surgery won't save
more lives, but working together as communities to increase organ
donation will. y Carolyn Poirot.  &UR; Moved 7-2. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HEALTH-SENSE-BOS _ `Routinely' covered by insurance? Not
always. By Judy Foreman.  &UR; Moved 7-2. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MEDNOTES-SCI-BOS _ Light is shed on morning-after pill;
Chiropractic care gets mixed grade; Cancer mortality, race link
mulled. By Dolores Kong.  &UR; Moved 7-2. &LR;
</P>
