<HEADER>
A8227 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LIBERTARIANS03-COX     07-02 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIBERTARIANS03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CAN LIBERTARIANS CREATE A MASS MOVEMENT OF INDIVIDUALITY?
 &HT;    730&AMP;add
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Back in the 1980 political campaign, a lot of folks
figured the Libertarians had some ``nutty ideas,'' recalled Steve
Dasbach, the party's national chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Why, the Libertarians were talking about privatizing Social
Security to give individual Americans control over their retirement
accounts. They wanted to use vouchers and home schooling to give
parents more educational choices for their children. And they were
for abolishing the income tax and reducing the role of the federal
government.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as the Libertarians gather in the nation's capital for
their 1998 ``Road to Victory'' convention, those ``crazy'' notions
are being earnestly debated in Congress and across the country,
said Dasbach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Republicans and Democrats aren't adopting our ideas. They're
stealing them,'' lamented Charles Schoonover, who drew 2 percent of
the vote as a 1992 Libertarian congressional candidate in South
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Libertarians believe they are the emerging political
party for this era of an unregulatable Internet, a cynical
Generation X and a growing suspicion _ if not scorn _ for
government.
</P>
<P>
   There is no doubt that much of the Libertarian philosophy of
less government, lower taxes and more personal freedom has become
part of mainstream political thought in the past decade, agreed
Steven Hess, a political analyst with the Brookings Institution, a
liberal research center in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that doesn't mean they're about to become a 'third party,'
as opposed to a 'minor party','' Hess said. Instead, ``they're part
of a long, distinguished tradition of ideological minor parties''
whose ideas were absorbed by one or the other or both of the two
major parties, he said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, ``many ideas of the Socialists of Norman Thomas
were adopted during the New Deal period,'' said Hess.
</P>
<P>
   One of the challenges the Libertarians are confronting at their
national convention is how to convert their popular ideas into a
viable political force. About 750 activists, including delegates
from all 50 states, are attending the four-day meeting, which ends
Sunday. The party has about 28,000 dues-paying members nationwide
and is aiming for 100,000 by its presidential nominating convention
in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   However, many Libertarians are running for local and state
offices this fall, and much of the convention focuses on those
elections.
</P>
<P>
   The party must win the votes of people who agree with their
philosophy but who ``are hanging back, waiting to make sure we
really do have a chance to win,'' said Frank Longo, a computer
systems manager and Libertarian activist from Boca Raton, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``Poll after poll shows Americans are frustrated with the tired
old choices offered by Democrats and Republicans,'' said Dasbach, a
chemistry and math instructor at Lutheran College in Fort Wayne,
Ind. ``But it's not enough to want an alternative. We have to build
an alternative.''
</P>
<P>
   In places where they have candidates on the ballot, the
Libertarians do, indeed, offer an alternative philosophy _ one
based on the notions of maximizing personal freedom for individuals
and minimizing reliance on government.
</P>
<P>
   While they might agree with Republicans on tax cuts and school
choice, for instance, Libertarians differ by wanting to end the
federal war on drugs. Libertarians don't want the government
restrict gun ownership rights, or ban abortions, or probibit flag
burning, or censor the Internet. They favor campaign finance reform
and oppose farm subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's range of speakers illustrated the breadth of
Libertarian thought. Those scheduled to address the convention
include Atlanta talk radio host Neal Boortz; Amy and Dan Gifford,
producers of the videotape documentary ``Waco: The Rules of
Engagement;'' Roy Ennis, president of the civil rights group CORE;
Social scientist Charles Murray, and Walker Chandler, a Georgia
lawyer who represented himself in a landmark case in which the
Supreme Court struck down a state law requiring political
candidates to take drug tests.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Republican Party believed in the principles they say
they believe in, we would not be necessary,'' said Michael Cloud, a
Libertarian candidate for the U.S. Senate in Nevada. ``If the
Democratic Party lived the civil liberties they claim to live, we
would not be necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   But the major parties ``are all rhetoric'' in regards to
adopting Libertarian ideas, said Anthony Trauring, a Georgia
delegate from Decatur. ``Their performances show that they're just
lying.''
</P>
<P>
   In states such as Texas _ home of Ron Paul, the 1988 Libertarian
presidential candidate who is now a Republican member of the U.S.
House _ the party has candidates on ballots throughout the state.
However, ``ballot access'' is still a key issue in Florida, the
delegates said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easier to get on the ballot in Russia than in Florida,''
complained Richard Shepherd, a delegate from Juno Isles, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Convention delegates expressed disappointment in the lack of
change since the Republicans took over Congress in 1994. If House
Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., had been advising Rosa Parks, Cloud
said, the civil rights legend would have moved up from the back of
the bus at the rate of one row per year, while Gingrich kept making
the bus longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to add a word to the vocabulary of politicians _
'now','' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Helmut and Michelle Forren, a couple from Duluth, were among the
Georgia delegates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been Libertarians all our lives _ only we just realized
it a few years ago,'' said Helmut.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
