<HEADER>
A8228 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NORTHUP03-COX     07-02 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NORTHUP03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GINGRICH, FIGHTING TO KEEP MAJORITY, STUMPS IN KENTUCKY
 &HT;    430&AMP;add. Not for Atlanta.
 &HT;    By MARK SHERMAN
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ House Speaker Newt Gingrich visited this
Democratic-leaning city Thursday to boost a Republican colleague
whose re-election is critical to Gingrich's hold on his job.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich helped raise money for freshman Rep. Anne Northup, who
won her seat by the slim margin of 1,299 votes as President Clinton
carried the district in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a $700,000 campaign bank account, she expects a stiff
challenge from Chris Gorman, a conservative Democrat and former
state attorney general who has tried to tie Northup to Gingrich and
``extremist'' Republican policies.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have an 11-seat edge in the House, and Democrats
think Northup's seat is one they can recapture.
</P>
<P>
   On the last leg of a week-long campaign swing before returning
to Georgia for the Independence Day holiday, Gingrich continued to
mix an effort to expand Republican influence among minorities with
pointed political attacks on Democrats, their allies and
constituents.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich and Northup visited the summer camp and community
center of a predominantly black church that is seeking federal
funds to renovate an old building.
</P>
<P>
   Later, he spoke to more than 400 Northup contributors, including
United Parcel Service chairman Oz Nelson, whose Atlanta-based
company has a large facility in Louisville. The luncheon crowd paid
between $100 and $1,000 a person for sandwiches and chips.
</P>
<P>
   They heard Gingrich toss darts at some favorite targets:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  About Clinton's responsibility for an increase in drug use,
Gingrich said, ``If you have no moral authority, young people don't
believe you.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Trial lawyers are very dangerous, frankly, to the core
fabric of society,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``If we don't get the surplus out of Washington, Al Gore and
Teddy Kennedy will find a way to spend it.''
</P>
<P>
   At one point in his address, the speaker related an imaginary
conversation between two public housing residents concerning their
reaction to welfare reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear people think we should go to work. Have you thought
about going to work?'' Gingrich said.
</P>
<P>
   Then, shifting to the other person, he continued, ``No, it never
actually occurred to me. What do you think it would be like to go
to work? They say you get paid. You actually get money you can take
home and spend without a bureaucrat telling you what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Northup refused help from Gingrich in 1996, fearing the
unpopular speaker would hurt her bid. But Gingrich's poll numbers
have improved since then.
</P>
<P>
   And Northup said she plans to campaign on her ability to get
things done in a Republican-controlled Congress.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   In addition to campaigning with GOP candidates, Gingrich has
given generously from his ample campaign funds and hosted
fund-raisers for the Republican congressional committee, including
a Silicon Valley event with computer executives this week.
</P>
<P>
   His political action committee, the Monday Morning PAC, gave
$72,000 to GOP candidates in May alone, according to its most
recent report to the Federal Election Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich also has helped Republicans who don't have serious
opposition add to their campaign accounts so that they can
contribute to imperiled colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   One such fund-raiser that took place Wednesday in Texas
illustrated the delicate nature of trying to expand Republican
support while preserving the party's base at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   After addressing the convention of a Hispanic civil rights group
that has been at odds with the GOP-led Congress, Gingrich moved on
to a fund-raising reception and dinner for Rep. Joe Barton,
R-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Barton, who is expected to coast to re-election, was the leader
of a failed effort in May to keep legal immigrants from receiving
food stamps. Hispanics fiercely opposed the move and criticized
Gingrich as well for not stopping it.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
