u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STARR-GRANDJURY-$ADV0     07-02 1114
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARR-GRANDJURY-$ADV04-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARR MAY BRING LEWINSKY BEFORE GRAND JURY IN VIRGINIA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For weekend release)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For nearly six months, Independent Counsel Kenneth
Starr has marshaled more than 50 witnesses before a grand jury
here.
</P>
<P>
   But he also has another, lesser-known panel across the Potomac
River in Alexandria, Va., which he set up at the same time that he
created the one in the District of Columbia. And it is there, in
Virginia, where some legal experts predict he will bring charges in
the Monica Lewinsky case.
</P>
<P>
   These experts point to Starr's recent leasing of 5,800 square
feet of office space in Alexandria _ across the street from the
federal courthouse where the second grand jury meets _ as evidence
that he is planning to move his investigation across the river.
</P>
<P>
   The space nearly equals the area that Starr's operation uses in
Washington. He has not given any details on how the new space will
be used.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts say he may want to bring charges against Lewinsky
there simply because prosecutors win more often in Northern
Virginia than they do in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, defendants in federal court are twice as likely to be
acquitted by a jury in Washington than in Northern Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Turley, a law professor at George Washington University
who has defended clients in both jurisdictions, says juries and
judges in Northern Virginia tend to be more conservative than in
the District of Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   The Northern Virginia district ``has long been the favored court
room for prosecutors,'' Turley says.
</P>
<P>
   He and other experts cite additional factors drawing prosecutors
to Virginia: faster trials, juries that tend to follow the letter
of the law and judges that usually rule in favor of prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Virginia is possibly the worst jurisdiction that Ms. Lewinsky
could face in a case of this kind,'' Turley says.
</P>
<P>
   John Q. Barrett, a law professor at St. John's University in New
York City, says the 11 counties and cities that make up the
Northern Virginia district have a population that tends to be tough
on defendants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at what's in that area: the Pentagon, retired military
personnel and a number of government security agencies,'' says
Barrett, a former associate independent counsel. ``The people who
work there and their families hold law and order in the highest
regard.''
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Lewinsky, the former White House intern who
denied under oath that she had an affair with President Clinton,
that attitude could lead a grand jury to take any perjury charges
against her more seriously than a jury in Washington, Turley says.
</P>
<P>
   A perjury conviction in federal court carries a mandatory
sentence of 8 to 12 months in prison unless the prosecutor asks for
leniency.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Starr has the evidence, they'll look at the law and say,
`Regardless of the circumstances, what she did was illegal and,
therefore, she's guilty,''' he says. He adds that Washington juries
have a reputation for looking at the events surrounding the case
and then deciding whether the law should apply.
</P>
<P>
   Washington jurors also have a reputation for distrusting the
motives of government prosecutors, particularly in high-profile
cases, according to Peter Kostopulos, a former federal prosecutor
who has tried cases in both Washington and Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   ``During trials, minority jurors, which usually make up the
majority in Washington juries, tend to be more susceptible to
arguments that the government is trying to railroad a defendant
into jail,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   This attitude, Kostopulos says, means Washington juries tend to
be more sympathetic to defendants than Virginia juries.
</P>
<P>
   Kostopulos cites the case against Washington Mayor Marion Barry
in 1990. Despite being videotaped in a hotel room smoking crack
with a woman he thought was a prostitute, Barry was convicted only
on a misdemeanor possession charge and served six months in prison.
He later won back the mayor's office.
</P>
<P>
   Although having two grand juries investigating the same case is
unusual, Starr is within his rights if he brings charges against
Lewinsky in Virginia rather than Washington, some experts say.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett says that if Lewinsky lied about her relationship with
Clinton, she probably lied about it in both Virginia and
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Both Lewinsky and Linda Tripp, the woman who secretly
tape-recorded their conversations about the alleged presidential
affair, worked at the Pentagon in Virginia. And a number of the
recordings between the two apparently took place in that area.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, when the FBI and attorneys for the independent counsel
confronted Lewinsky about the allegations, they did it at the
Pentagon City shopping mall.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett says a Starr indictment in Alexandria would be ``very
difficult to challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Nathaniel Speights, a lawyer for Lewinsky, says
attorneys for the independent counsel have assured him that the
Alexandria grand jury is only being used for the investigation into
the Pentagon's release of confidential information about Tripp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time the (office of the independent counsel) has been
confronted with the issue, we have been assured that there will not
be any type of illegal, unconstitutional forum shopping,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While he may be safe legally, Starr can be sure that any attempt
to move the case to Virginia would be challenged politically.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton supporters would be expected to point out that
Washington's population is 66 percent black, while the Alexandria
jurisdiction is 81 percent white. So any decision by Starr to move
his investigation to Virginia would expose him to accusations that
he doesn't trust a black jury.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be a public relations disaster,'' says Robert F.
Drinan, a law professor at Georgetown University specializing in
civil rights and race relations.
</P>
<P>
   Although the main players in this case are all white, several
key supporting actors are African American, including Clinton
friend Vernon Jordan and White House Secretary Betty Currie, both
of whom have been questioned about the help they provided Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Washington voters also heavily supported Clinton in his 1996
re-election _ the president received 85 percent of the vote _ while
half the voters in the Alexandria jurisdiction backed Clinton. In
addition, in an April Gallup Poll, more than 90 percent of African
Americans _ compared with 60 percent of whites _ said they believed
investigations into the allegations involving Clinton should ``stop
now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
