</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-VIDEO-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY VIDEO SHELVES EMPTY FASTER  
 NEW VIDEO RELEASES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The old question of why you often can't find what you want in a
video store has taken on interesting ramifications because of new
ways that movie studios are doing business with video stores.
</P>
<P>
   Studios used to sell videos to stores for a set price up front,
with retailers keeping all revenues from rental transactions. Now
studios frequently offer big chains like Blockbuster a price break
on new releases in return for a share of each rental transaction.
And though they also offer small, independent stores such
revenue-sharing plans, the arrangements aren't as favorable as they
are for the chains, which do a higher volume of business.
</P>
<P>
   The upshot, smaller retailers and distributors say, is that big
stores use the price breaks to stock more copies of big hits,
gradually squeezing out wider inventories of older and specialized
films sought by many movie buffs. At the same time, the small
retailers say, they have to use more of their money to buy the big
hits, leaving them with fewer resources to buy other titles of
interest to a particular local clientele.
</P>
<P>
   Increased supplies of big hits certainly please the movie renter
who pounds up to the counter on a Friday night _ only to learn that
all 40 copies of ``Scream 2,'' say, are out for the weekend. But,
in the view of many independent video dealers, the stocking of more
cassettes of a few movies conditions the customer to want and
expect nothing else.
</P>
<P>
   And worse, they say, it discourages customers from browsing for
alternative choices, an activity that small stores count on for a
large part of their income.
</P>
<P>
   ``Studios are pushing video stores away from carrying broad
selections,'' said Russ Ward, owner of Video City U.S.A., an
independent store in Glendale Heights, Ill., about 20 miles west of
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   But studios say they are simply giving customers what they want.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't take a mathematician to figure out what's going
on,'' said Steve Feldstein, vice president of corporate
communications at Fox Home Video.. ``We put together a program to
satisfy consumer demand for new titles.''
</P>
<P>
   And though Karen Raskopf, Blockbuster's vice president for
corporate communications, acknowledged that the company was
acquiring deeper supplies of the latest hits, she strongly disputed
the contention that the policies discouraged range and choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're driven by what the consumer wants,'' Ms. Raskopf said.
``In most cases, what they're talking about is new releases.''
</P>
<P>
   She said that this year Blockbuster has increased the numbers of
its copies of new titles by 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's not just big box office,'' she said. ``I'm also
talking about B titles.'' Blockbuster, she said, has also doubled
the number of smaller and lesser-known movies on its new-release
wall.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, she said, the chain is working to fit inventories
to the demographics of individual areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's a kids' store, we add that to the mix,'' she said.
`'Same thing with classics or foreign films. We buy on a
store-by-store basis to make sure we have the mix right.''
</P>
<P>
   But, said Ward, the independent store owner, that's the kind of
thing the neighborhood store does best.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blockbuster and other chains have a hard time with this
because they're like McDonald's,'' he said. ``The old video store
is run by people who are part of the community and understand what
it wants.''
</P>
<P>
   Ward made his case against the new arrangements in a recent
article in Video Business magazine, and elaborated in an interview.
Consumers want to see hits, he said, but how many are there in any
one week?
</P>
<P>
   ``Take the first week of July,'' he said. ``There's `Palmetto.'
Ever hear of that one?'' Reviews were mixed, and theater stays
short for Volker Schlondorff's convoluted and overly steamy film
noir, starring Elisabeth Shue and Woody Harrelson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good Will Hunting'' will also be available next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a great title,'' Ward said. ``But that's what you've
got for the week. If people want to rent only what's new, are they
only going to rent `Good Will Hunting'?''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   NEW VIDEO RELEASES
</P>
<P>
   Good Will Hunting
</P>
<P>
   Pushing a janitor's broom at the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology, young Will Hunting (Matt Damon, left) pauses to doodle
a few equations on a hallway blackboard, thereby establishing
himself as a mathematical prodigy. But Will is frightened of his
gifts and is hiding out amid a circle of working-class friends, one
of them portrayed by Ben Affleck, who wrote the screenplay with
Damon for Gus Van Sant's film. Psychiatrists get nowhere with Will
until the case goes to Sean McGuire (Robin Williams), a middle-aged
counselor with many of the same problems. Together, the two make a
bumpy go of it in a film, Janet Maslin wrote in The New York Times,
directed with ``style, shrewdness and clarity.'' 1997. Miramax.
$107.37. Laser disk, $49.99. 126 minutes. Closed captioned. R.
Release date: Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Boxer
</P>
<P>
   Once a firebrand for the Irish Republican Army, boxer Danny
Flynn (Daniel Day-Lewis) withstood 14 years in prison without
betraying his comrades. Released in Belfast, he tries to build a
life free of extremes and starts a gym that encourages a healthier
brand of competition between Catholics and Protestants. But old
hatreds boil when he renews a romance with a woman (Emily Watson)
who is now the wife of an imprisoned IRA member, and the gym is
burned down by a terrorist faction that is trying to prolong
strife. Director Jim Sheridan has collaborated with Day-Lewis
before on this subject (``In the Name of the Father''), but ``this
more reflective and mature film sees a bigger picture'' (Maslin).
1997. Universal. $107.37. Laser disk, $34.98. 113 minutes. Closed
captioned. R. Release date: Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Long Way Home
</P>
<P>
   For many Holocaust survivors the suffering was far from over
after they left the camps. In Mark Jonathan Harris' documentary,
life becomes a debilitating trek toward an often harsh fate in a
world that wants to avoid them. ``We were hated because we returned
from the dead,'' one refugee says. Some stumble across the Alps
with babies in their arms, hoping to reach a new state in Palestine
that itself hardly awaited them with open arms. ``Along the way,
Harris creates an intense empathy'' (Maslin). 1997. BWE. $24.95.
120 minutes. No rating.
</P>
<P>
   Mouth to Mouth
</P>
<P>
   Phone sex is an overworked film subject, but Manuel Gomez
Pereira's film gives it another try. A would-be actor, Victor
(Javier Bardem), finds that the finer points of sex on the line can
be more involved than his chosen profession. Elaborate
complications emanate from Victor's desire to connect with Ms.
Right and his telephone romps with a woman whose husband, it turns
out, is also his client. But it all gets too tangled in a film that
``sorely needs the antic talents of Pedro Almodovar'' (Maslin).
1997. Miramax. $103.91. Laser disk, $39.99. 97 minutes. Closed
captioned. Spanish with English subtitles. R.
</P>
<P>
   Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release at one time or appeared on television.
</P>
<P>
   TRUE PRINCE: VLADIMIR MALAKHOV. Tony Papa and Leigh Badgeley's
prize-winning documentary examines the life and development of the
ballet dancer, who recently appeared at City Center with the modern
dancer David Parsons. Highlighted are selections from ``Giselle,''
``Romeo and Juliet'' and ``Manon,'' performed with the National
Ballet of Canada, and a modern solo created for Malakhov by Renato
Zanella. 1996. Alegrias Productions. $29.95. 48 minutes.
Information: (212) 874-5772.
</P>
<P>
   ANTIGONE. A Greek production, set in Thebes, stars Irene Papas
in Sophocles' tragedy about a woman who is sentenced to death and
buried alive in a cave for defying the king. 1962. Hen's Tooth.
$24.95. 86 minutes. Greek with English subtitles. Information:
(219) 471-4332.
</P>
<P>
   ELIA KAZAN: A DIRECTOR'S JOURNEY. Paying close attention to
Kazan's testimony before the House Committee on Un-American
Activities, Richard Schickel's film documents the career of the man
who directed such films as ``On the Waterfront,'' ``East of Eden''
and ``Baby Doll'' and, on both Broadway and the screen, directed
``A Streetcar Named Desire.'' 1995. First Run Features. $29.95. 75
minutes. No rating.
</P>
<P>
   MISFIT PATROL. Conrad Brooks, who appeared in all the films of
Ed Wood, stars in Anthony Cardoza's film about two of the Los
Angeles Police Department's finest and dumbest. 1998. Tapeworm.
$94.95. 101 minutes. No rating.
</P>
