<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 17:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8272 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SMITH-ART-REVIEW-2TAK     07-02 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMITH-ART-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TONY SMITH ART REVIEW: A FLUID RESONANCE IN THE GEOMETRIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MICHAEL KIMMELMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The best way to approach the new Tony Smith
retrospective at the Modern is from the north. Then you can stop at
the Doris C. Freedman Plaza at 60th Street and Fifth Avenue and
check out ``Cigarette,'' one of his best big, all-black steel
sculptures from the 1960s. It's a virtual primer on how Smith's
works work, when they do.
</P>
<P>
   They work partly by causing you to look carefully, as Smith did,
at the way geometric forms can be combined into abstract shapes
that seem to shift as you move around them.
</P>
<P>
   Smith was forever tinkering with cardboard and plaster models
shaped as tetrahedrons and octahedrons, mixing them, twisting and
turning them around, sort of like Rubik's Cubes, to find forms that
seemed to him sculpturally resonant. It's why his work, even though
it's often monumental like ``Cigarette,'' can seem provisional, as
if what you see were only a step in a process _ which is in fact
the case. Change, the idea that the same forms can keep mutating in
provocative ways, is Smith's constant.
</P>
<P>
   So ``Cigarette'' from one vantage point can look simply like a
gateway to Central Park. From a different angle, it can seem like
the legs of a kneeling figure, and from yet another it becomes what
its title says. Or really it looks like a crushed cigarette, bent
in places: a joke on Smith's part, maybe, but not a joke in the
cheerful spirit of, say, Claes Oldenburg's pillowy cigarette
sculptures. The humor in Smith's art was always black.
</P>
<P>
   I've stressed at the start what might be called the contingency
of Smith's forms because contingency gives a fair idea of his
general situation in postwar American art. Although he once made
the cover of Time, he is one of those figures who have become
famous for being hard to place: he's the other Smith in modern
American sculpture, not David.
</P>
<P>
   Born in 1912 (he died in 1980), he belongs chronologically with
the first generation of Abstract Expressionists, and he considered
himself nearest to them psychologically and otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   But he began to make sculpture only later in life, in the 1960s,
after having been an architect and a painter, and at a moment when
a generation of Minimalists, like Donald Judd and Carl Andre,
partly reacting against Abstract Expressionist angst and
improvisation, came to prominence making work that looked very much
like Smith's austere sculptures.
</P>
<P>
   His case is a good example of what happens when we listen to
what an artist says as opposed just to looking at what he does. Roy
Lichtenstein once joked:
</P>
<P>
   ``All abstract artists try to tell you that what they do comes
from nature and I'm always trying to tell you that what I do is
completely abstract. We're both saying something we want to be
true.''
</P>
<P>
   The situation is more complicated with Smith, because we partly
miss the soul of his art if we neglect what he believed about it.
But Lichtenstein's point is not altogether irrelevant: Smith
straddles movements less opposed than the history books say.
</P>
<P>
   A virtue of the Modern's intelligent, not-too-large
retrospective is that it brings together the three aspects of his
career _ architecture, painting and sculpture _ so that we can see,
for example, how Smith's approach to form had as much to do with
Frank Lloyd Wright, Le Corbusier and Mies van der Rohe as with
Barnett Newman and Clyfford Still, and more to do with Newman and
Still than with Judd.
</P>
<P>
   One of the familiar stories about Smith, one he liked to tell,
is that as a tubercular child he was kept apart from his brothers
and sisters in a small prefabricated house that his father built
for him in the family's backyard in New Jersey. Smith lived there
for several years in a kind of spartan isolation. The only
significant object in the house was a black stove. ``If one spends
a long time in a room with only one object,'' Smith said, ``that
object becomes a little god.''
</P>
<P>
   He recalled, years later, having traveled with his parents
before he got sick to the Panama-Pacific International Exposition
in San Francisco, where he saw Pueblo houses. Alone in his small
house, he passed the time by making Pueblo models out of
papier-mache and medicine boxes.
</P>
<P>
   Who knows whether Smith really remembered seeing the exhibition
as a 3-year-old or just thought he had in retrospect. In either
case the story is as good as true if he believed it. And it shows
us what he regarded as important: that prefabricated structures
were not vacant industrial forms but potential Proustian
madeleines; that a solitary black metal object, even a stove, could
have a spiritual aura. And that evocative shapes could be concocted
out of modular units.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Smith worked for his family's toolmaking company,
learning to use a lathe and drill press, before studying, briefly,
at the New Bauhaus in Chicago. Then he landed a job working for
Wright, his hero, on Wright's Usonian houses.
</P>
<P>
   All this explains several impressions left by the show. The
first is how closely his sculptures relate to his houses, which are
a minor revelation; functionality aside, they seem artfully attuned
to space as a fluid sculptural form. His Scoppettone House in
Irvington-on-Hudson, N.Y., for example, with its mix of wood and
brick, looks virtually like a live-in version of one of his later
sculptures like ``Memphis.''
</P>
<P>
   And among his other projects it's especially a pity that his
airy, eccentric, modular proposal for a church on pillars, with
clerestory windows to be painted by Jackson Pollock, never got
built.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   His paintings relate to both his architecture and sculpture.
Robert Storr, the show's organizer, stresses drawings and paintings
that involve repeating shapes and shapes that Smith varied only
slightly from one work to another to make what can appear to be
sequential images. He used amoebas, figure-eights and circles in
different configurations, and also linear forms: blocks of color
that bring to mind abstractions by Newman, Ellsworth Kelly or Ken
Noland _ but that can, more specifically, look like architectural
or sculptural fragments, colored close-ups of his own angular
constructions.
</P>
<P>
   You may notice a casualness to the way he actually put down
paint. When it's not good, Smith's work suggests a certain
anonymous and chilly indifference. His sculptures can look
industrially produced. This is partly our mistaken assumption that
all hard-edged forms are inherently cold while squishy forms are
always expressive. But I also get the impression that Smith's heart
was often more in the ideas behind the art than in the finished
products. He brought an architect's mentality to everything: he
planned what he often let others complete.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, photographs can't tell us how large his
sculptures are unless other things are in the picture for
comparison's sake, because everything he did looks innately huge.
He conveyed the fact that monumentality wasn't necessarily about
size. This was one of his contributions to modern art. That said,
some of his sculptures do register completely only at full scale.
</P>
<P>
   ``Moondog'' now towers over a corner of the Modern's garden as
an awesome beast that also becomes a sheltering presence once you
get under it. Like all of Smith's best work, it doesn't look the
same from any two angles or as the passing sun strikes different
facets of it.
</P>
<P>
   The effect is the same with ``Moses,'' another big sculpture in
the garden: from one side, it seems open in the middle until you
realize that the opening is a jutting volume catching the light in
such a way that the form dissolves.
</P>
<P>
   Storr describes Smith in the show's catalog as having strived
for ``a new art of a grandeur proportionate to the unfulfilled
greatness of America, and the equal of anything produced by the
most developed civilizations of the past, virtually all of which
used architecture, painting and sculpture to celebrate their gods.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem Smith repeatedly confronted,'' Storr adds, ``was
how to do the same in a modern, secular society, and his
experiments in all mediums reflected that improbable but devout
aim.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the lavish phrases, one detects a respectful reservation
about Smith in the words ``improbable but devout,'' which seems
right. Smith's work ultimately is imperfect, incomplete, great
sometimes, not always.
</P>
<P>
   But if we tend to neglect one aspect of it, it's not the
grandeur. It's the more human side, which is often harder to
recognize.
</P>
<P>
   I'm talking about his anthropomorphic allusions, sardonic and
otherwise, in self-referential works like ``The Elevens Are Up'':
two big black monoliths referring to the enlarged tendons on the
neck of a heavy drinker, which Smith was.
</P>
<P>
   I also mean that Smith spent a lifetime trying to endow geometry
with feeling, to distill emotion from indifferent forms.
</P>
<P>
   There was a sense of wonderment to the way he kept on
discovering new shapes in these forms. To the end of his working
life he remained that boy poring over little cardboard and
papier-mache models.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony Smith: Architect, Painter, Sculptor,'' remains on view at
the Museum of Modern Art, 11 W. 53rd St., through Sept. 22. Five of
Smith's sculptures, including ``Cigarette,'' are installed around
midtown Manhattan. The installations were organized by the museum
in collaboration with the Public Art Fund; a map is available at
the museum.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
