<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8277 &Cx1f; tad-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RURAL-HEALTH-$ADV04-C     07-02 1241
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RURAL-HEALTH-$ADV04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RURAL HOSPITALS STRUGGLING TO SURVIVE
 &HT;    For release Saturday, July 4.
 &HT;    By REBECCA CARR
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTICELLO, Ga. _ When Sara Deleza's heart stopped 10 months
ago, she was rushed to Jasper County Memorial Hospital, where the
local doctor brought her back to life, stabilized her and sent her
on her way to a major medical center to await a heart transplant.
</P>
<P>
   As Deleza, a 64-year-old former nurse, recovers from heart
surgery this week, she has more than once thought back to that
Sunday afternoon, realizing how she was saved by ``the little
doctor who was sent to me like an angel'' at the tiny 17-bed
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it hadn't been there, I wouldn't be here,'' said Deleza,
speaking through a friend at a hospital at the University of
Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   Deleza was among the most dramatic of the hospital's 2,600
emergency calls last year. More often, patients arrive at the
low-slung brick building with snake bites, allergic reactions or
broken bones. But her survival illustrates how important a hospital
can be to the people living in a rural community.
</P>
<P>
   In Jasper County, that role is in danger.
</P>
<P>
   Across the country, hospitals in rural communities are finding
it increasingly difficult to stay in business, and Jasper County
Memorial is no exception.
</P>
<P>
   The hospital has been in trouble for the last decade, but it has
never seen days like these. Faced with a budget shortfall of about
$300,000 this year, it also has a $500,000 debt after a renovating
its adjacent 55-bed nursing home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Small hospitals are feeling a real pinch,'' said Dr. Corbitt
Kelly, who grew up here and is now one of two doctors who treat the
county's 10,000 residents. ``Now I see that we might not make it,
and that is tough because of what this hospital means to the
people.''
</P>
<P>
   To hear Rep. Charlie Norwood tell it, the culprit here is
managed care. Health maintenance companies are siphoning patients
from local communities such as Monticello and forcing them to visit
associated doctors in Atlanta and other urban centers, he said. At
the Georgia Republican's insistence, a congressional task force is
drafting legislation aimed at regulating managed care companies and
providing more rights for patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rural hospitals have always been the first line of defense for
health care,'' Norwood said. ``It doesn't do anyone any good to
have state-of-the-art cardiac treatment centers in Atlanta or Macon
if a patient has a heart attack in Monticello.''
</P>
<P>
   But competition from managed care is only part of the problem.
Rural hospitals are being hit even harder on two other fronts. The
federal and state governments are cutting back on Medicare and
Medicaid reimbursements as a result of the Balanced Budget Act of
1997, and a rising number of uninsured patients are seeking care.
</P>
<P>
   For example, 60 percent of Jasper Memorial's patients are
Medicare or Medicaid patients, and an additional 10 percent are
uninsured and can't pay their bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you how hard it is to keep it going,'' said Tim
Jordan, president of the Monticello Bank and member of the hospital
authority's board. Jordan admits that the hospital's financial
condition is so poor that he probably could not sell the loan that
his bank granted the hospital for its nursing home renovations.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the hospital went under, I think it would be hard to
replace the jobs, but it would also be a big void. I mean, you have
to provide education for your children, but you also have to
provide health care for your community,'' Jordan said. ``On the
other hand, how do you attract new business when you don't have
something as basic as a hospital?''
</P>
<P>
   The managed care market is growing rapidly, and its impact has
been felt by rural health providers. Managed care and other health
networks are now the dominant health-care providers in America,
with about 160 million people, or 60 percent of the population,
enrolled.
</P>
<P>
   But most of that growth has been in urban areas, with just about
3 percent of enrollees living in a rural community. Therefore, HMO
officials say, the reasons behind Norwood's regulatory push are
suspect.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds like Congress is just looking for another culprit,''
said Kevin Curtin, executive director of the Georgia Association of
HMOs, which represents 12 health maintenance organizations. ``It's
a little hard to be a culprit when you're not even there.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem in many cases, Curtin said, is that regional
hospitals demand exclusive contracts for large geographic areas of
the state, leaving rural hospitals out in the cold. ``That makes
the rural patients drive past their local hospitals,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Joe Parker, president of the Georgia Hospital Association,
said it is not a regional-vs.-rural issue. He said regional
hospitals supported a recent state law that benefited rural
health-care providers.
</P>
<P>
   Rural hospitals play a critical role in assuring access to basic
health care to underserved populations, he said. Rural communities
have a higher infant mortality rate, a higher adolescent pregnancy
rate and a higher number of people living below poverty, he pointed
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are concerned about the state of rural hospitals,'' Parker
said. ``When you lose a hospital, you lose a physician. When you
lose a physician, you lose businesses in rural communities.''
</P>
<P>
   The answer, said Parker, is for the community to come together
and save hospitals like Jasper Memorial.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Without rural hospitals, patients such as Deleza would not
survive a trip to a hospital in Atlanta or even the 30 miles to the
closest regional hospital, doctors and health-care experts say.
</P>
<P>
   What is happening in Jasper County, Ga., is happening throughout
the country. The most recent tally by the Office of Inspector
General at the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services shows
that only 10 of the nation's 5,134 rural hospitals closed in 1996,
but health-care experts say that hundreds more are drowning in red
ink.
</P>
<P>
   To the people of Monticello, losing the hospital is akin to
losing a family member. It is as much a part of the community's
fabric as the high school's Hurricanes sports teams, fried chicken
at the Tillman House, or the annual Fourth of July fireworks show.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an anchor in this community,'' said Martha Mock, an
English professor and interior designer who grew up here. ``In a
large city, the first thing they ask you, is do you have insurance?
Here, (Dr.) Corbitt Kelly says how can I help you?''
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Saturday night, the emergency room doctor saw a
25-year-old man who couldn't move his neck because he had banged it
against a wall a Metallica concert the night before. There was a
23-year-old woman who had cut her finger opening a can of cat food.
But there were more serious cases, such as an 85-year-old man who
couldn't articulate what was wrong with him. Tests at the hospital
showed his discomfort came from a urinary tract infection.
</P>
<P>
   For hospital personnel, patients like these are a reason to go
on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your heart is here,'' said Norma Mattison, the lab technician
who diagnosed the elderly man's trouble. ``It's like a church here.
You want to help everyone who comes in the door and most often, you
know their name.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
