<DOCNO> NYT19980702.0212 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8279 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      07-02 1303
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTIQUES: GREEN FEES (SO TO SPEAK) FOR GOLFERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio, N.J., N.Y.)   (bl)  
 By WENDY MOONAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In his 1968 book ``The Truth About Golf, and Other Lies''
(Doubleday), Buddy Hackett describes a round of golf with Jimmy
Durante: ``Jimmy's first round was a total disaster. As he came to
the 18th hole, his partner, who had long since lost count,
estimated Jimmy's score was over 200. After holing out for 12, the
Schnoz turned to his companion and asked, `What should I give the
caddie?' Without smiling, the friend answered, `Your clubs!'''
</P>
<P>
   Buddy Hackett was retelling a joke, but nowadays it might be the
caddie who has the last laugh. A set of old golf clubs can be
extremely valuable.
</P>
<P>
   Some 25 million Americans play golf, and 5,000 collect antique
clubs, balls, trophies, medals, ceramics, trinkets and books,
according to Morton Olman, the 82-year-old owner of the Old Golf
Shop in Pleasant Plain, Ohio, a Cincinnati suburb, and a recognized
authority on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Mutch, the curator of Golf House, the U.S. Golf Association
Museum and Library in Far Hills, N.J., which has 50,000 items,
said, ``People get as hooked on collecting as on the game itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Golf memorabilia have become a big business. Christie's,
Sotheby's, Phillips and Bonham's all conduct auctions of
memorabilia. The next one, on Tuesday, is a Christie's sale in
Glasgow, Scotland, of property from the Royal Perth Golfing Society
and the Royal Burgess Golfing Society of Edinburgh.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perth was founded in 1824 and was granted royal patronage in
1833, even before St. Andrews,'' said Christie's golf specialist,
Edward Monagle. ``So the sale gives us real insight into one of the
earliest golfing societies.''
</P>
<P>
   Sotheby's ``Golf, Cricket, Boxing and Other Traditional Sports''
sale will be held in London next Friday; the Phillips golf sale is
scheduled for July 14 in Chester, England, and Bonhams' first sale
devoted to golf will held be Aug. 8 in Manchester, England.
</P>
<P>
   There are websites for collectors, too. One site,
www.golfmuseum.com, lists the collection of the Philadelphia
Private Golf Museum, which Christie's is trying to sell privately
for $2.8 million. It includes 17 of the earliest feather golf
balls, gutta percha (a form of rubber) balls from the 1850's,
medals, trophies, tankards and a bronze sculpture of a golfer.
</P>
<P>
   Golf antiques fall into two categories: serious (expensive) and
nonserious (under $500). Titus Kendall, a private dealer in London
who helped assemble the Valderrama Golf Museum in Sottogrande,
Spain, for its owner, Jaime Ortiz-Patino, said, ``You can't mix
trinkets with serious history.''
</P>
<P>
   Kendall attended the Pacific Book Auction Galleries' sale of
golf books in San Francisco last month. It featured the collection
of Joseph Murdoch, a renowned bibliographer of golf books, which
went for $743,750. ``We bought a seventh of the sale,'' he said.
``It included the third edition, from 1793, of the first printed
book on golf, called `The Goff,' a prose poem by Thomas Mathison.
It sold for $80,500.'' The buyer was Richard Donovan, a dealer in
rare golf books in Endicott, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   George Fox, a vice president of the Galleries, said: ``When you
pay $250 to play a round at Pebble Beach, spending $1,000 on a book
is not a big deal. No other sport has books like golf books.
Baseball books don't go for $10,000 apiece.''
</P>
<P>
   Kendall, who spent years assembling the Valderrama collection,
noted that a ``really early, rare and interesting'' golf club can
cost $200,000, a feather ball, between $20,000 and $40,000, and a
gutta percha ball, $17,000. ``Before 1900, golf was rarefied,'' he
said. ``Until 1850, it was a terribly expensive game played by rich
people in England or Scotland.''
</P>
<P>
   There were enthusiasts from the beginning. Kendall has found
early 17th-century Dutch tiles depicting golfers in blue and white
and a famille vert Chinese porcelain bowl of 1797 with golfers on
it. How did the Chinese know what golfers looked like? ``They
copied the letterhead of the Honorable Company of Golfers,''
Kendall explained.
</P>
<P>
   In H.B. Martin's 1966 book ``50 Years of American Golf,'' he
quotes David R. Forgan's widely circulated tribute to the game.
Golf, Forgan wrote, ``is a contest, a duel or a melee calling for
courage, skill, strategy and self-control. It is a test of temper,
a trial of honor, a revealer of character.''
</P>
<P>
   So is collecting at these prices. Mutch, the curator, advises
people to consider only items in mint condition, with solid
provenance, rarity and some history. ``The golf collecting market
does not lend itself to retail stores,'' he said. ``There's no
one-stop shopping. It's a networking thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Olman warned that clubs and balls are sometimes dated
incorrectly in catalogs. The earliest clubs had shafts that were
not too tapered, he said. He advises people to examine feather
balls, the earliest balls, made of leather stuffed tightly with
goose feathers. ``If they have holes in them, someone tried to
mount them and they aren't good,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He values rarity. He said he bought a machine, circa 1850, at
Phillips' golf sale last November in New York that made
crosshatching marks on golf balls. The bidding started at $5,000
but ended at $64,000, when Olman got it. Olman is attracted to a
signed watercolor by J. Michael Brown titled ``Carnoustie, 1891,''
in the Christie's sale on Tuesday. The painting, of a Scottish golf
course where the British Open is scheduled be played in 1999, is
expected to sell for $17,000 to $24,000.
</P>
<P>
   At a Sotheby's auction at St. Andrews in 1995, Olman paid
$92,000 for two Brown paintings. On July 10, Sotheby's is
auctioning a red golf-club captain's coat from 1938 with the Gothic
initials DGC on the brass buttons. Sotheby's golf specialist,
Edward Playfair, explained that golfers from the earliest days were
asked to wear red jackets when they played on common land to alert
people to the danger of ``missiles flying through the air.''
</P>
<P>
   He is also selling a red golf ball from 1855 (estimate: 1,500 to
2,500 pounds, or $2,500 to $4,166). Beginning in the 1850s, red
balls were produced for players who wanted to play in the snow.
Martin's history notes that golfers used red balls to play golf in
the snow in Yonkers, N.Y., as early as 1887.
</P>
<P>
   Evidently few New York dealers specialize in golf antiques, but
several galleries carry a few pieces. Pamela Walker, a private
dealer in Manhattan and Southampton, sells golf cuff links, ties,
watches and drinks paraphernalia. She recently sold four charming
glass stirrers for drinks depicting dogs playing golf, for $65.
</P>
<P>
   Deco Deluxe (993 Lexington Ave., at 71st Street, Manhattan) has
a few items, mostly from the 1930s. ``Golf stuff goes for a
fortune,'' said the owner, Sandi Berman, ``because golf is a rich
man's sport and things were made of good quality to appeal to
people with money.'' She has a pair of silver-plated golf ball salt
and pepper shakers from England for $220, an International Silver
golf bag pencil cup for $485, a metal golf bag lighter for $275 and
an etched glass martini shaker depicting a stooped (possibly
looped) golfer for $275.
</P>
<P>
   Couper Lord, a private dealer in Southampton, N. Y., is a
walking encyclopedia of the history of his two local clubs:
Shinnecock Hills, America's oldest incorporated golf club (1892),
and the National Golf Links of America (1908). Lord sells old
photographs of some of the great players, vintage books, ceramics
from various golf clubs, plaques and medals.
</P>
<P>
   But he won't sell his best piece: an antique wooden whirligig
golfer in his backyard. It's a piece of true folk art, and when the
ocean breeze is stiff, this golfer has a swing as wild as Jimmy
Durante's.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
