<DOCNO> NYT19980702.0213 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8297 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT &LR;      07-02 1473
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE SILVER SCREEN  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAMES STERNGOLD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _
</P>
<P>
   &UR; From Hoops To Heartaches &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ It is often said in Hollywood that young directors
and writers should start with a subject they know well, so why is
Kevin Rodney Sullivan making his debut as a feature film director
with a movie about a woman's search for love in seemingly the wrong
place?
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan, a onetime child actor who has written screenplays and
directed television movies, has directed ``How Stella Got Her
Groove Back,'' a film based on Terry McMillan's popular novel and
due in theaters on Aug. 14. The movie, about a 40-year-old career
woman and single mother who falls in love with a Jamaican man 20
years her junior, stars Angela Bassett as Stella and Whoopi
Goldberg as her good friend Delilah. It is being distributed by
20th Century Fox.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan, who has been eager to direct a feature film, said the
choice of this ``woman's movie'' was not as unusual as it might
sound. First, the last movie based on one of Ms. McMillan's novels,
``Waiting to Exhale,'' was also directed by a man, Forest Whitaker.
More important, Sullivan said, ``How Stella Got Her Groove Back''
is about love, and that is something men can understand.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Sullivan, 39, whose last television film was ``The Soul
of the Game,'' for HBO, about basketball, fathers and sons, said
directing ``Stella'' had, in some respects, been an odd experience.
There were plenty of times, he said, that he and Ron Bass, one of
the screenwriters, felt a little lonely, since the film focuses on
a woman, her best friend and her sisters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ron and I were the only men in the room a lot of times,''
Sullivan said. ``It made us friends real quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan spent years as an actor, appearing in ``Star Trek II:
The Wrath of Khan,'' and in the television series ``Happy Days.''
He then wrote for the television series ``Fame'' and directed
television movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a lie to say there was no difference making a
movie like this,'' he said, referring to ``Stella.'' ``But I know
what it is like to be into and to fall in love with the most
inappropriate person. It didn't feel like I was going on an
expedition into unknown territory.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, he said, there were plenty of times that he and
Bass had to defer to what the actresses said a woman would feel or
not feel at a certain moment.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan, who is black, said that he felt that the movie was
first and foremost a love story, but that he was concerned it might
be perceived as a ``black film'' and thus marketed to a limited
audience. He expressed some frustration with the fact that even
though there are many ethnic movies, so-called black movies still
frequently had to struggle for the marketing muscle to attract a
broader audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``The film business is a little slow in getting around to what
the world is thinking,'' he said. ``The world is not Anglo-Saxon.
The paying audience wants diversity, and they appreciate good
stories no matter what the cultural background. Films like this, I
think, say the barrier should come down a little quicker.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Weird Is Cool &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The bigger the entertainment conglomerates get, the more they
rely on supposed formulas for making successful movies. And few
formulas are embraced more than the one that says that when the
weather turns hot, a blockbuster needs lots of special effects, a
marketing tie-in with a taco and a strong dose of death and mayhem.
Just like in, say, ``Dr. Dolittle.'' Huh?
</P>
<P>
   Expectations were shattered when ``Dr. Dolittle,'' an oddball
children's film from 20th Century Fox starring the protean Eddie
Murphy, battered its rivals and brought in an astounding $29
million on its opening last weekend. Jaws dropped around Hollywood
because, put simply, the film, about a strange doctor who can talk
to animals, does not fit the formulas. Worse, critics were
generally hostile. Richard Corliss, of Time, was typical in calling
it a ``slow, vacant farce.'' (Janet Maslin of The New York Times,
however, called it ``the sunniest family film so far this
season.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``It turns out kids don't read reviews,'' said Betty Thomas, the
movie's outspoken director. ``I guess that's good.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Thomas, 49, was gloating happily about the success of ``Dr.
Dolittle,'' but even she admitted that she had no idea the film
would open so big.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was confused by the initial reaction,'' she said. ``But it's
funny. Doesn't anyone remember how to have fun anymore?''
</P>
<P>
   But as improbable as the movie's immense success is the fact
that a director like Ms. Thomas made it. Not surprisingly, she said
she initially scoffed at the project. The movie is based on the
sweet children's stories of Hugh Lofting and follows by several
decades a treacly, musical version of the movie that starred Rex
Harrison.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like cute,'' said Ms. Thomas, which is not hard to
believe, given that her last movie was ``Private Parts,'' about the
sex-obsessed shock jock Howard Stern. ``I'm not a fan of cute. I'm
into funny. My kind of funny.''
</P>
<P>
   She said her first reaction was swift.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Get serious,''' Ms. Thomas recalled. ``Then they said
Eddie Murphy was going to do it. That's when I said: `That's
interesting. That's unusual. That's not what people expect.' I like
to come out of left field, so that appealed. Eddie was the
reason.''
</P>
<P>
   With Murphy's edgy brand of comedy, the movie was given a
slightly irreverent tone, with many anatomical jokes. That
contributed, Ms. Thomas said, to the real message behind the movie,
which worked hard to make more than just a romp with a silly man
who thinks he can talk to animals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really think that the movie's about the artists in the world
and how we have to accept them as they are,'' Ms. Thomas said.
``Parents are too busy saying to their kids, you have to get good
grades, you have to get into the right schools, you have to do
everything right. I felt we had to get across that weird people are
where it's at!''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Boom Town &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood's stock in trade is illusion, of course, principally
about itself. But one of its greatest illusions is less well known
_ the fact that the movie studios, as businesses, have never been
that significant a presence in the Los Angeles economy. That is,
until recently.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Economic Development Corp. recently issued a
report on the film industry in large part to counter some old myths
and to underscore the remarkable arc of growth in this booming
industry.
</P>
<P>
   The movie studios were once dwarfed as employers by other
industries, like aerospace, particularly in cities like Burbank
that had a reputation of being dominated by the studios. But the
recession of the early 1990's hit the aerospace companies hard, and
the subsequent boom in all facets of entertainment has made the
studios, for the first time, huge businesses with payrolls to match
the impact of the movies on the public consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   According to the report, 96,000 jobs were added to the movie
industry between 1990 and 1997. Another 6,000 jobs have been added
this year, which the report said made it something of a slow one.
The economic development corporation estimates that total
movie-related employment in Los Angeles County is now 500,000.
</P>
<P>
   Even those figures understate the impact of the industry on the
local economy, however. According to the report, these are not
ordinary jobs; they pay significantly more than other kinds of
jobs, on average. By one estimate, these jobs pay $53,000 a year on
average.
</P>
<P>
   The Motion Picture Producers Association said earlier this year
that the industry generated $25.6 billion in economic activity in
Los Angeles County in 1996, the latest year for which there are
figures, compared with $15 billion in 1992. And the report
estimated that between now and 2001, demand for films will grow 7
percent a year.
</P>
<P>
   But one of the more interesting pieces of information about the
structure of the movie industry concerned who employs all these
people. According to the report, the studios themselves actually
account for a tiny fraction of the jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Figures supplied by the U.S. Department of Commerce showed that
a whopping 78 percent of jobs came from companies with one to four
employees. Another 8.6 percent of the jobs were at companies with
five to nine employees. Less than 1 percent of the jobs came from
employers with 1,000 or more employees.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the vast majority of the overall employment in
the movie industry does not come from the most visible entities,
the studios, but from tiny companies. And most of those provide
specific services, including everything from costume design to
computerized special effects, often on a per job basis.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-98 1743EDT &QL; 
