<HEADER>
A8302 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MACBETH-THEATER-REVIE     07-02 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MACBETH-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MACBETH': WHEN HIGHJINKS OUTWEIGH SHAKESPEARE'S WORDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It must be the fashion this year for theater
productions to begin before the audiences arrive. Turn up half an
hour early for ``Cabaret,'' for instance, and there are the
decadent Kit Kat Girls, slithering and stretching onstage,
establishing the Weimar atmosphere for the show to come.
</P>
<P>
   Arrive a little early for the International WOW Theater
Company's production of ``Macbeth,'' and there are various cast
members with swords, witch's brooms and other props, moving about
and interacting in clearly choreographed ways. Periodically one of
the jump-suited actors identified in the program as the Machinists
comes to the center and speaks into a walkie-talkie in a loud voice
of intense fear. This is expert mood establishment.
</P>
<P>
   This ``Macbeth,'' performed at the Washington Square Methodist
Church in Greenwich Village, is a daring blend of styles that works
more often than not.
</P>
<P>
   The witches (Amo Gulinello, Jy Murphy and Robert Saietta) remove
their wigs and black robes, don straw hats and turn into vaudeville
song-and-dance men. Banquo's ghost is covered with enough blood to
have come from a scene in ``Reservoir Dogs.''
</P>
<P>
   The musical accompaniment includes ``Any Way You Want It,'' some
romantic 1920s instrumentals and the orchestral crescendo from the
Beatles' ``Day in the Life.'' (Surrounding the ``ravell'd sleave of
care'' speech with theme music from the television series ``Three's
Company'' and a loud laugh track, however, was a bad idea.)
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the best parts of the evening are nonverbal, which is
an odd thing for Shakespeare. If the cast members could put as much
originality and conviction into their lines as they invest in their
behavior, this would be an outstanding production. To be fair, all
young interpreters of Shakespeare are at a disadvantage in an era
when audiences can rent a Kenneth Branagh interpretation at the
corner video store, but much more attention should have been paid
to making these Elizabethan words the actors' own.
</P>
<P>
   The story of a husband-and-wife team who kill the husband's
rivals to gain power, then love the perks but hate the guilt, is
certainly as meaningful today as when it was written, and the
actors have hold of its universality.
</P>
<P>
   Aya Ogawa makes a forceful, seductive Lady Macbeth, although the
sleepwalking scene is one of her least effective.
</P>
<P>
   Josh Fox, who directed the production with Ron Russell, turns in
an uneven performance as Macbeth, somewhat unconvincing in his
moments of guilt and fear but charming and engaging when his
character is high on his own new-found power.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Frace is appropriately confident as Duncan but plays
Macduff with a deliberate quietness that works only now and then.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, there are many praise-worthy aspects to the
production, including Fox's evocatively dark sound and lighting,
and the set, by Fox and Caitlin Connolly, which makes good use of
the church's interior.
</P>
<P>
   After Friday night's and Saturday afternoon's performances,
``Macbeth'' continues, on Friday evenings only, through July 31.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   ``MACBETH''
</P>
<P>
   By William Shakespeare; production concept and direction by Josh
Fox and Ron Russell; sound and lighting by Fox; costumes by Jody
Waserman; set Fox and Caitlin Connolly; production manager, Alison
McGonigal. Presented by the International WOW Theater Company. At
Washington Square Memorial Church, 135 West Fourth St., Greenwich
Village, Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   CAST: Josh Fox (Macbeth), Jeffrey Frace (Duncan and Macduff),
Amo Gulinello (Witch and Ross), Jy Murphy (Witch, Banquo and
Porter), Aya Ogawa (Lady Macbeth) and Robert Saietta (Witch and
Malcolm).  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
