<HEADER>
A8306 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-US-MEXICO-HNS &LR;      07-02 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-MEXICO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S., MEXICAN ATTORNEYS GENERAL SEEK TO PATCH DIFFERENCES OVER DRUG
STING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN MacCORMACK  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROWNSVILLE, Texas _ The attorneys general of Mexico and the
United States, seeking to patch soured relations over a sweeping
American money-laundering investigation, signed a three-page letter
Thursday pledging cooperation and greater openness in the
international drug war.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation, codenamed Operation Casablanca, was
triumphantly revealed in May by U.S. authorities, but Mexican
officials quickly condemned the brashness of the operation and
threatened to pursue criminal charges against American agents who
operated in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from 12 Mexican banks were among those arrested in the
probe.
</P>
<P>
   The letter signed Thursday by Attorney General Janet Reno and
her Mexican counterpart, Jorge Madrazo Cuellar, includes a
provision to give advance notice of any ``major or otherwise
sensitive cross-border activity of our federal law enforcement
agencies.''
</P>
<P>
   It also includes various other pledges of bilateral
understanding, training and cooperation, but it does not address
Mexico's stated intent to seek extradition and prosecution of the
U.S. agents.
</P>
<P>
   Reno took no questions after the ceremony, and Madrazo paused
only briefly to speak to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   But in a news release, he vowed to prosecute anyone who broke
Mexican law.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is important to clearly state that this agreement in no way
impedes the Attorney General of the (Mexican) Republic in
continuing on-going investigation to determine if agents,
informants or witnesses cooperating with the government of the
United States committed any crimes in the national territory (of
Mexico) in connection with Operation Casablanca,'' Madrazo's
statement said.
</P>
<P>
   He also vowed to continue his investigation of the Mexican banks
and bankers who were the targets of Operation Casablanca.
</P>
<P>
   The three-year Treasury Department probe broke in early May with
the indictment of 26 Mexican bank officials, as well as more than
120 other individuals.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials said the elaborately orchestrated operation would
result in the seizure of more than $150 million in illicit funds.
</P>
<P>
   Seventeen of the Mexican bankers were arrested in a sting
operation in Mesquite, Nev., after they were invited to attend the
grand opening of ``The Casablanca,'' a gambling casino, allegedly
financed with the proceeds of the money-laundering operation.
</P>
<P>
   The charges allege that 12 of Mexico's 19 largest banks were
involved with laundering money from drug operations.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican national pride quickly turned Operation Casablanca from
a crime-fighting triumph into an American trampling of national
sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   President Ernesto Zedillo issued harsh criticism of the
investigation, saying: ``It is inadmissible because it is a
violation of our sovereignty; it is inadmissible because it
tramples on our laws; and it is inadmissible because it violates
international law and weakens our bilateral cooperation.''
</P>
<P>
   Mexican officials also filed a formal complaint and said they
would attempt to extradite and prosecute the U.S. agents they said
had violated Mexican law.
</P>
<P>
   Later, however, Mexican officials acknowledged they had been
informed two years ago of the investigation, but said they had had
no detailed briefings on its scope.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton quickly attempted to mend fences by calling
Zedillo and acknowledging that the United States should have
informed Mexican authorities of undercover operations on Mexican
soil.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's letter of understanding, addressed to both
presidents, closed on a note of hopeful optimism that historically
has rarely been realized by these two uneasy neighbors, who share
an intractable drug problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``The law enforcement relationship between our two countries is
important to each of us and to the citizens of both our
countries,'' the letter says.
</P>
<P>
   ``With these renewed understandings, we are confident that we
will enhance our cooperation and further our accomplishments
against the criminal organizations that threaten the security and
well-being of our countries.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
