<HEADER>
A8310 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ART-NOTES-NYT &LR;      07-02 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE ART WORLD  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; A De Kooning Depicts Kennedy &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Willem de Kooning's painting ``Reclining Man'' has been in the
Hirshhorn Museum and Sculpture Garden in Washington since Joseph
Hirshhorn, the museum's founder, acquired it in 1964. But though
signed by the artist, the painting was undated.
</P>
<P>
   Now museum officials say the work was finished in 1963 and the
artist, who died in 1997, modeled the face of the figure on
President John F. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about the identity of the face in the painting arose
five years ago when ``Reclining Man'' was part of an exhibition for
artist's 90th birthday. At that time, several Hirshhorn officials
commented to Judith Zilczer, the museum's paintings curator, that
the man's face uncannily resembled Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   But, Ms. Zilczer said, ``nothing in our records had indicated
that the face was of our late president.''
</P>
<P>
   In researching the issue, the curator could not consult de
Kooning, who had suffered from Alzheimer's disease for years. So
she spoke to Susan Brockman, the artist who was de Kooning's
companion at the time Kennedy was assassinated on Nov. 22, 1963.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Zilczer recalled that Ms. Brockman said ``Reclining Man''
was the artist's portrayal of Kennedy. The curator also said Ms.
Brockman remembered that on the day of the assassination and for
the next four days, de Kooning, like many Americans, was glued to
the television set.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill was utterly involved. He was very moved, Ms. Zilczer
quoted her as saying.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Zilczer added that Ms. Brockman said de Kooning's paintings
were always loosely based on something he had seen.
</P>
<P>
   Others confirmed the artist's preoccupation with Kennedy at that
time.
</P>
<P>
   In their diaries, de Kooning's close friends and neighbors Ibram
and Ernestine Lassaw recalled watching television with him on Nov.
23. And another friend, the photographer Hans Namuth, took a series
of 35-millimeter color transparencies of the painting, which he
dated 1963. The barren landscape and bare trees visible through the
artist's studio windows in two of the transparencies indicate that
the time of year was late fall or early winter, Ms. Zilczer said.
</P>
<P>
   There was another tie between de Kooning and Kennedy. The
artist's estranged wife, Elaine de Kooning, with whom he still had
contact, had been working for nearly a year on a portrait of the
President for the Truman Library, and her East Hampton studio was
filled with sketches of Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have revised the date and the title'' of the work, Ms.
Zilczer said. ``It now is dated 1963, and we have added `John F.
Kennedy' in parentheses after `Reclining Man.'''
</P>
<P>
   The painting is unusual because de Kooning is best known for
expressionist images of women and rarely painted men or portraits
of recognizable individuals. When the work first entered the
Hirshhorn collection, it was thought to have been painted in 1964
because that was when Hirshhorn bought it, and he had an agreement
with de Kooning for right of first refusal on works as the artist
painted them in return for subsidizing some construction costs for
the artist's new Long Island studio.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why she thought the artist never identified his subject,
Ms. Zilczer said: ``I have a hunch this was his personal response
to a national tragedy, and he didn't want to exploit the subject.
Nor, I suspect, did he want to steal Elaine's thunder.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pompidou in New York &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum in New York has formed a
temporary partnership with the Georges Pompidou Center in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Although most of the Pompidou Center's galleries are closed for
renovation until 2000, the institution has agreed to team up with
the Guggenheim to present two major exhibitions, one at the
Guggenheim's Fifth Avenue headquarters and the other at its SoHo
branch. Both shows will open in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a one-time unprecedented opportunity where we could
structure shows using anything we wanted from both museums,'' said
Lisa Dennison, the Guggenheim's deputy director and chief curator.
``Even though the Pompidou Center is a public institution and we
are a private one, we're both quite similar. We're both about 40
years old, we both have radical buildings, and we discovered our
collections perfectly complement one another.''
</P>
<P>
   The uptown exhibition will be called ``Rendezvous: Masterpieces
From Centre Georges Pompidou and the Guggenheim Museums'' and will
fill the entire building. Using more than 350 paintings, sculptures
and drawings by about 150 artists, the show will chart the history
of modern art from the turn of the century until 1970. Among the
artists whose works will be on view are Picasso, Matisse, Ernst,
Dubuffet, Klein and Beuys.
</P>
<P>
   In many cases, one institution owns the study for a final
painting in the other. For example, Kandinsky's painting and oil
studies for ``Landscape With Tower'' (1908) and ``In the Black
Square'' (1923) will be shown together.
</P>
<P>
   The show in SoHo, ``Premises: Invested Spaces in Visual Arts,
Architecture and Design From France, 1958-1998,'' will concentrate
on more contemporary works and will explore the relationship
between the artist and the architect.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the expected names like Jean Dubuffet, Christian
Boltanski, Le Corbusier and Jean Nouvel, the show will also include
younger artists and architects, many not well known in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A Warhol for Israel &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In honor of the 50th anniversary of the Israel Museum in
Jerusalem, an international group of donors has given the
institution Warhol's ``10 Portraits of Jews in the 20th Century''
from 1980. The piece consists of silk-screen portraits of Sarah
Bernhardt, Louis Brandeis, Martin Buber, Albert Einstein, Sigmund
Freud, George Gershwin, Franz Kafka, the Marx Brothers, Golda Meir
and Gertrude Stein.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
