<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8318 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-02 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOWARD A NEW AMERICA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: Due to holiday peg, moving on the a.m. cycle.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Saturday is the Fourth of July, a holiday celebrated with the
traditional American pastimes: family reunions, cookouts, and
fireworks. But it is also a time for somber reflection. And a time,
perhaps, for giving back.
</P>
<P>
   What better day than Independence Day to acknowledge the
terrible injustices committed by our ancestors? To face history,
and ourselves, and to recognize that one man or woman's
``independence'' inevitably entails the enslavement or degradation
of a fellow human being.
</P>
<P>
   Cast your mind back 222 years. Imagine the plight of the hated
Tory, or Loyalist _ ordinary citizens of Boston, like yourselves.
These were the Bruce Lindseys and Sidney Blumenthals of their time,
men who put loyalty to their sovereign ahead of narrow personal
concerns. While Sam Adams and his petit-bourgeois pals brayed about
customs regulations and ``taxation without representation,''
Loyalists stood by king and country. You're such a fan of
representative government? I give you Jesse Helms, the late Sonny
Bono, and congressional hopeful Marjorie Clapprood. They were worth
fighting a war over?
</P>
<P>
   What fate befell the Tories? They paid the ultimate price. Most
were forced to move to Canada, home of Alex Trebek, socialized
television, and the ever-plunging dollar. Their ancestors now eke
out a living in towns like Shelburne, Nova Scotia, which had more
Harvard graduates in the '80s than Cambridge. The 1780s, that is.
It is time to make amends.
</P>
<P>
   Or what of the bedraggled Hessian mercenaries, objects of
universal derision in our history books? Sons of a great,
peace-loving nation, plucked from peaceful husbandry behind the
plow to fight an unpopular war in a foreign land. Poorly clothed
and fed, dodging bullets fired by grog-sodden cowards from behind
hedgerows. How do you think they felt?
</P>
<P>
   Do I have something concrete in mind? Yes. It's not enough to
apologize for our shortcomings, as our president recently did
before the slavemasters of Beijing. (World Cup soccer balls
stitched by Chinese prison labor? Talk about bad timing for that
little revelation ...) It is time for redress. I propose nothing
short of returning the original 13 colonies to their rightful
owners, the resurgent House of Windsor and ``Cool Britannia.''
</P>
<P>
   I don't know about you, but I'm prepared to bow and scrape
before the incipient King William. People magazine reports he's
endowed with his mother's ``sapphire eyes,'' and has the initials
W.O.W. (William of Wales) monogrammed on his racing Speedos. WOW
indeed! And if it's constitutional government you want, they've got
a mediagenic prime minister who seems every bit as alert as our own
guy, but doesn't fool around. Plus Britain has real tabloid
newspapers, the Spice Girls, and a terrific national anthem to
boot.
</P>
<P>
   But why stop there? Would you like to know how we acquired all
those flat states lined up along the Mississippi River? Tom
Jefferson stole them, that's how. That's right. Tiresome Tom,
champion of much-bruited ``Jeffersonian'' ideals, took advantage of
a country in chaos to negotiate the Louisiana Purchase from
war-torn France. Louisiana Swindle is more like it. How about
Texas? Land-hungry cattle barons trumped up the Battle of the Alamo
_ the Tonkin Gulf incident of its time _ and look whose armies are
marching down to the Rio Grande.
</P>
<P>
   Is this a past we can be proud of? Give it back, I say.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Alaska, too. If Boris wants it back, we'll surrender it to
him. We'll see how the Alaskan Wildlife Refuge fares at the hands
of the Russian Environmental Protection Agency. (Hint: Russia
doesn't have an Environmental Protection Agency.) California? What
Rupert Murdoch and the Japanese don't own goes back to Mexico. Then
we won't have to listen to Pat Buchanan yapping about a ``border
wall'' during Campaign 2000.
</P>
<P>
   So what do we keep? We're keeping a patch of the original Boston
_ the North End _ at least until the end of today. I need a place
to watch the Italy-France World Cup quarterfinal match, and I want
to enjoy it on American soil. After that, who knows? Maybe Tony
Blair will let us keep Rhode Island.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Alex Beam's e-mail address is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
