<HEADER>
A8333 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOCCIONI-ART-REVIEW-N     07-02 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOCCIONI-ART-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART REVIEW: ON A TRIP BACK TO FUTURISM, WOMEN AND SETTINGS MERGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By GRACE GLUECK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the brief life span of the Italian Futurist
movement, the short-lived Umberto Boccioni (1882-1916) was a
blazing comet. With Filippo Tommaso Marinetti (1876-1944), the poet
and critic who founded Futurism, Boccioni was a fiery theoretician
of the movement, drafting two Futurist manifestoes in 1910 and 1912
that exalted the force and energy of contemporary life.
</P>
<P>
   They called for an art that glorified speed, violence and the
machine age, one that above all reflected the dynamism of an
engine-driven civilization.
</P>
<P>
   A painter with ideas, Boccioni was also the group's outstanding
sculptor. ``Boccioni and Women,'' a small show of his work from
1905 to 1916, at the Metropolitan Museum of Art, makes no pretense
of giving a major account of his work. But while focusing on the
easy theme of women, it conveys the important shifts in his style
between those years. The material in the show _ drawings, prints,
one oil and one sculpture _ is from a bequest by Lydia Winston
Malbin, a dedicated Futurist collector and archivist, who died in
1989.
</P>
<P>
   Right off, it can be seen that in his portrayals of women,
Boccioni was no Picasso or de Kooning. The women in his work were a
means of exploring artistic strategies, rather than his own psyche,
and his mother, sisters and neighbors as well as Ines, his
significant other, were put to decorous use as models. A 1907
etching, ``The Artist's Mother Crocheting,'' shows Boccioni as a
strong but traditional draftsman, portraying his mother in a
genteel domestic scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maria Saachi Reading,'' another etching from 1907, is also a
realistic but far more ambitious rendering of an old woman bent
raptly over a page, her rugged features, hair and clothing drawn
with a bold freedom of line and shading that evokes past masters
like Rembrandt and Durer. Still, there is an almost photographic
approach to this close-up study that puts it squarely in the 20th
century.
</P>
<P>
   But by the time he met Marinetti, in 1909, and became a member
of the Futurist circle, Boccioni was ready for a radical change of
style. His 1909 drawing, ``Woman Leaning on a Chair (the Artist's
Sister),'' already hints at the distortions, the play of angular
lines and planes adopted by the Futurists from Cubism, that he
would pursue with increasing intensity.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, in the drawing ``Analytical Study of a Woman's
Head Against Buildings'' (1911-1912), Boccioni is fully occupied
with the Futurist notion that to the mind's eye there is a constant
interplay between object and environment. In this drawing, the
blocky architecture of his mother's deliberately distorted head
segues into a helter-skelter arrangement of Cubistically broken and
dislocated building facades.
</P>
<P>
   In 1913, he translated his mother's head into a sculpture, his
first, and the most powerful work in the show. A bronze
appropriately called ``Antigraceful,'' it is a mass of intriguing
contradictions, melding soft fleshy facial contours with angles and
planes that create a surface as broken as a mountain terrain. The
many expressions of the face range from cheerful to menacing,
depending on how you look at it.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, carrying out the notion in his earlier drawing of
merging objects with their environment, the head bears the solid
form of a building amid its topknots of hair. A facescape of
imposing imagination, it was possibly influenced by the Cubism of
Picasso and Braque, and certainly by the Italian Impressionist
sculptor Medardo Rosso (1858-1928), whose flowing movement and
spareness of detail appealed to the Futurists.
</P>
<P>
   Boccioni returned to painting after a stint in the Army, where
he served, with other Futurists, on the Italian front in World War
I. The forward thrust of Futurism was all but over, and his new
style was much closer to Cezanne's. His ``Head of the Artist's
Mother,'' a pen-and-ink drawing of 1915, is Cezannesque in its
stripped-down forms; the almost featureless visage, all bulges and
hollows, is the skin and bones of a face but not much more.
Recalled to military service in 1916, Boccioni was fatally injured
in a fall from a horse.
</P>
<P>
   Although the idea of Boccioni's women is a rather lightweight
premise, this small, compact show, organized by Sabine Rewald of
the Met's department of 20th-century art, whets the appetite for a
full-scale Boccioni retrospective. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Boccioni and Women'' remains at the Metropolitan Museum of
Art, Fifth Avenue at 82nd Street, through Oct. 18.
</P>
</TEXT>
