<HEADER>
A8335 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-LOVETT-TEX     07-02 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-LOVETT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH `THE OPPOSITE OF SEX,' LYLE LOVETT CONTINUES HIS DRIFT TOWARD
FILM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two Texans are having breakfast with screenwriter-director Don
Roos when Roos asks them to explain the difference between Dallas
and Fort Worth. One of the Texans is Lyle Lovett, so it seems best
to defer to him.
</P>
<P>
   Lovett, having just polished off a plate of huevos rancheros,
gives the standard line: Fort Worth is old cattle culture, Dallas
is new money. But then, Lovett waxes nostalgic:
</P>
<P>
   ``Growing up, wanting to be a cowboy, which is the way things
are when you're a kid in Texas, Fort Worth was a mythical place,''
the lanky singer-actor says. ``The cattle drives and all that. So I
remember coming to Dallas and getting to go to Fort Worth for the
first time when I was 10 years old. I just thought it was a big
deal, wow. Flew in an airplane for the first time, to Love Field,
on my 10th birthday. ... Getting to go to Cowtown and getting to
drive around the Stockyards was a very big deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth is more cosmopolitan these days, but then, so is
Lovett. Still, he remains as synonymous with Texas as ... well, as
Fort Worth. He even looks Texan in Roos' new movie, ``The Opposite
of Sex,'' although it's set in Indiana, Canada and California
(where it was filmed). In the movie, Lovett plays Carl, a
gentle-natured sheriff who favors boots and Wranglers. Although the
part wasn't written specifically for Lovett, Roos acknowledges that
Carl has a certain Lyle-ness about him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bet he has a few of your albums,'' Roos says to Lovett. ``I
needed somebody substantial _ kind of like rugged, decent, American
to play this part ...''
</P>
<P>
   ``... And he couldn't find anybody, so he let me do it,'' Lovett
interjects.
</P>
<P>
   For Lovett, interruptions such as this are rare. He is
unfailingly polite, with quick, crooked smiles and compassionate
eyes that put those around him at ease. Still a singer first, he's
becoming more and more linked to movies, whether through songs
(he's on the soundtrack to ``Hope Floats'') or appearances (a cameo
in ``Fear and Loathing in Las Vegas,'' a role in Robert Altman's
upcoming ``Cookie's Fortune''). Since appearing in Altman's ``The
Player,'' his stature as an actor has been growing.
</P>
<P>
   Although he doesn't have many scenes in ``Sex,'' the movie gives
Lovett his biggest role yet. Roos' decidedly politically incorrect
comedy centers on a trashy blonde named Dedee (Christina Ricci),
who moves in with her gay half-brother, seduces his lover,
convinces the lover that they should get married because she's
pregnant, and runs away with the lover and some valuables.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually everyone in the movie pursues her, although Carl is
more interested in the romantic pursuit of a sexually repressed
schoolteacher (''Friends''' Lisa Kudrow).
</P>
<P>
   Roos, who also wrote ``Single White Female'' and ``Boys on the
Side,'' is taking his first directing turn on ``The Opposite of
Sex.'' He says that Lovett didn't even have to read for the role.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lyle came down for a meeting, and I thought he was auditioning
us, because I was a first-time director,'' Roos says. ``So (I was)
like, `OK, OK, everyone, he's coming, he's coming! All right, we'll
be cool!'''
</P>
<P>
   Lovett has spent much of this year working on a new CD, which is
due in September (a fall tour will follow, with a Fort Worth-Dallas
date likely). The album is a collection of 21 songs written by
Texas singer-songwriters, including four by the late Townes Van
Zandt, a Fort Worth native.
</P>
<P>
   ``Townes was like a spirit in life, and he was so insightful,''
says Lovett, who sang at Van Zandt's funeral. ``He talked about his
songs being `sky songs.' They would come out of the sky and just go
into his arm and into his guitar. He was a mysterious guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Lovett's not-quite-country, not-quite-pop music is hard
to categorize, it isn't as prevalent on the radio as George Strait
or Garth Brooks. But he credits Dallas' KERA/90.1 FM and Poor
David's Pub for early career support, and he has frequently used
Fort Worth's Caravan of Dreams as a rehearsal venue before touring.
Some singers might be bitter about the lack of airplay; Lovett
prefers to be grateful for the support he does get.
</P>
<P>
   He also prefers not to be bitter about something else.
</P>
<P>
   ``This sounds like a Julia question,'' Roos says after listening
to an apologetic preface. ``I've been (touring) with him now long
enough to know.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it's a question about Lovett's short-lived marriage to
actress Julia Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the questions that can get you in trouble, it's the
answers,'' Lovett says, adding that he and Roberts are still good
friends, despite what supermarket tabloids would have you believe.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would actually be very easy for tabloids to get things
right a lot of the time, and they'll concoct a story that, even if
it's innocuous, it's inaccurate,'' says Lovett, who was a
journalism student at Texas A&AMP;M University. But ``you can't dismiss
it as something that only a small part of the public is interested
in, because they make a lot of money for what they do. And that's
what gives them credibility.''
</P>
<P>
   The tabloids probably wouldn't look twice at Lovett's home life
now. When he's not working, he lives next door to his parents, in
his grandparents' house on a farm outside of Houston. He remains
close to his family, and visits with them as much as time allows.
</P>
<P>
   As to whether he'll break out of supporting movie roles and take
a lead part, Lovett says that's not his ambition, but he'll take
the right role if it comes along.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know,'' he says. ``It's great film school to be in a
movie and to work with smart and talented people and who are the
best at what they do. It's really great. How that will settle out
later on _ who knows?''
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is a film critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Call him at (817) 390-7872, or e-mail
robp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
