<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8337 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HAMMERSHOI-ART-REVIEW     07-02 1022
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAMMERSHOI-ART-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART REVIEW: A DANE WHO TURNED COPENHAGEN AND NATURE INTO STILL
LIFES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By HOLLAND COTTER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Maybe it's just an accident of scheduling, or a sign
of cultural downtime at the end of a decade of intense and
challenging art. But Manhattan's high-profile museums are offering
a confluence of deeply conservative fare this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Wyeth holds center stage at the Whitney Museum of
American Art, Pierre Bonnard at the Museum of Modern Art. At the
Metropolitan Museum, Edward Burne-Jones follows hard on the heels
of two 18th-century French academics. The lineup has many agreeable
features, but a kind of self-protective reverie is the defining
mode: nostalgia hanging like a perfume in the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vilhelm Hammershoi (1864-1916): Danish Painter of Solitude and
Light'' at the Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum sustains this trend.
Hammershoi was born in Copenhagen, worked and died there, and made
it his primary subject. And his art seems to be pervaded by the
hunkered-down atmosphere of that northern European city in
mid-winter.
</P>
<P>
   In that season, daylight lasts only a few hours and has a
muffled radiance. Natural light _ slanting through a window,
gleaming from polished furniture or from a gilded picture frame _
takes on a kind of precious, metaphorical weight. The domestic
interior becomes a refuge and a universe, protective,
claustrophobic, self-contained.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Hammershoi's paintings are of such interiors,
specifically the Copenhagen apartment he shared with his wife, Ida.
One can guess at a glance that the couple had no children: this is
an adult domain, furnished with self-conscious austerity,
immaculately clean, blanketed (or so it seems) in silence.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Hammershoi was a shut-in. He was an artist of
considerable renown in his day, and much of his art is that of a
public man. The show _ organized by Anne-Birgitte Fonsmark and
Mikael Wivel of the Ordrupgaard museum in Copenhagen, Henri
Loyrette of the Musee d'Orsay in Paris and Robert Rosenblum of the
Guggeheim _ includes several of his paintings of the exteriors of
Copenhagen buildings, as well as depictions of the surrounding
countryside where he vacationed and of European cities that he
regularly visited.
</P>
<P>
   Landscapes are, in fact, among the earliest paintings in the
show, and the most luxuriant and lyrical. In a near-abstract image
of a farmhouse, for example, the whitewashed wall, the dark
thatched roof and a green hedge are rendered as horizontal layers,
like folds of soft cloth. And a painting of a line of trees
dividing a band of lake water from a big patch of rain-soaked sky
has the ornamental elegance of a fabric pattern.
</P>
<P>
   There are no figures in these scenes. Nor do any appear in the
city paintings, in which Copenhagen's facades suggest architectural
renderings, entirely about measurement and line. The Baroque front
of the Asiatic Company is as flat as a cutout; the Old
Christiansborg Palace, filtered through sea mist, is plain and
blank, like a design for a mausoleum.
</P>
<P>
   In Hammershoi's hands, as in Morandi's and Mondrian's, the world
becomes a still life: a narrow assortment of set components that
can be endlessly rearranged but that harbor no disquieting
surprises. This is particularly true of his paintings of interiors,
by far his most original works, where the human figure is permitted
to play a carefully controlled role.
</P>
<P>
   The figure depicted is usually Ida, seen in the apartment at 30
Standgade where they lived for several years. The walls of the
rooms are painted a dove gray (which the Guggenheim installation
echoes); doors, wainscoting and windows are white. The furniture is
sparse but fine: a dining room table with a crisp, creased white
cloth, a ponderous cabinet sofa, a sideboard carrying a ceramic
tureen with a floral pattern.
</P>
<P>
   But even though the rooms are clutter-free, they feel smothered
and static, in part because nothing is happening in them. Ida is
there in a plain black dress and bathed in wan, indirect sunlight.
(Hammershoi's love of Vermeer is often noted by scholars.) But
whether reading or standing still, she is viewed impersonally, as
if she were a prop, an extra piece of furniture.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to get a sense of how the artist related to her. This
is true even of a double portrait from 1898 in which she and
Hammershoi appear together. Ida sits at the table, looking toward
the viewer, but down and away. Her hand, with its glinting gold
wedding ring, rests in front of her; her expression is mute. But
here her dress is amazing: it is colored a gorgeous, inscrutably
complex moss green and molded, through a network of tiny brush
strokes, to the shape of her breasts.
</P>
<P>
   The result is literally, physically, a loving image. Yet the
artist himself, sitting across the table from her, barely seems to
be in the picture at all. He is a silhouette over to the right,
faced away, so one cannot tell where his gaze actually falls. Is he
staring at his wife in reticent admiration? Or at something on the
table?
</P>
<P>
   The few other bust-length portraits of Ida are equally striking.
In one back view, she wears a velvety blouse whose puckers and
pleats and stress lines are sensually suggestive. In a later, Van
Eyckian picture, her expression is slightly frazzled and skeptical
as she absent-mindedly dips a spoon in a white porcelain cup. She's
facing front here and for once doing something homey and specific,
but she still seems just as boxed in as she does in the rooms whose
doors, moldings and framed pictures form a relentless, exhausting
geometry.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few years of his life, before he died of cancer at
51, Hammershoi turned to different subjects, including the female
nude. There's an early example in the show, a grisaille figure with
a voluptuous body and a demure child's face. And while the standing
figures from the end of his career are larger, they look, with one
exception, unresolved and awkward, as if the painter wanted an
effect of monumental intimacy but wasn't quite sure how to achieve
it.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   To some extent, the real intimacy of Hammershoi's work lies less
in what he painted than in how he painted. His grayed-down colors
may not look like colors, but they are, and they have a kind of
secretive, confiding presence. They range from silvery
Whistleresque beiges to faint roses, saffrons and blues that
whisper just below the surface. And the surfaces themselves are
texturally alive, energy fields of visual incident created through
short, restless, caressing strokes.
</P>
<P>
   This touch gives Hammershoi's paintings a distinctive pulse,
though it is the slow, energy-conserving pulse of a cold-weather
metabolism, very different from the excited, urbane beat of French
modernism. Hammershoi, who visited Paris, was familiar with
Impressionism and Symbolism, but dismissed their bright palettes
and antinaturalist styles with angry derision (so did Burne-Jones),
much as his wife deplored the cosmetic extravagances of Parisian
belles.
</P>
<P>
   So he kept to his narrow groove, and looked backward rather than
forward, to the 17th-century Dutch and the early Italians, to
19th-century Danish forebears like Christen Kobke and the romantic
German painter Caspar David Friedrich. And he looked inward rather
than outward, which is what gives him a claim on our attention.
</P>
<P>
   The show's catalog compares him to Edward Hopper, which is
plausible, though Andrew Wyeth isn't far away. Is there any real
difference between Hammershoi's ``Dust Motes Dancing in the
Sunbeams'' (1900) and one of Wyeth's Maine farmhouse interiors
washed with winter light? Both images traffic in a melancholy sense
of the ephemeral, a naturalism of nostalgia, emotions easy to feel
and easy to feel good about feeling.
</P>
<P>
   But Hammershoi's paintings come across not as illustrations of
emotions, but as embodiments of the real, weird thing, the
components of a personal fantasy, a softly hallucinatory fiction,
the pictorial equivalent of the desire to shut the door and draw
the curtain against the clamor of the new and the different, all
the generative disharmonies of life out there. One could say the
same of Burne-Jones, Bonnard and even Wyeth. And why these artists
have landed together in our midst just now may be a question worth
pondering.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vilhelm Hammershoi (1864-1916): Danish Painter of Solitude and
Light'' remains at the Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum, 1071 Fifth
Ave., at 89th Street, through Sept. 7. Financing was provided by
the Danish Ministry of Culture and Novo Nordisk.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
