<DOCNO> NYT19980702.0230 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 17:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8342 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JUMBO-FUNERAL-HNS &LR;      07-02 1190
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUMBO-FUNERAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKER, 82, HAS LAST LAUGH AT FUNERAL WITH TEXAS-SHAPED
TOMBSTONE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See optional trims) 
 
By ALLAN TURNER 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Jumbo Atwell never stopped laughing.
</P>
<P>
   And even now, in his own way, Ben Dodson Atwell, a former
longtime state representative from Dallas and chairman of the House
tax committee, is getting the last laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Atwell was buried Thursday in the state cemetery beneath a
tombstone of his own design _ a pink granite, Texas-shaped marker
bearing his name and the inscription ``Lawyer-Legislator. Author of
tax bill.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Atwell's remedy to an oversight of which he often
complained _ the dearth of monuments honoring tax men.
</P>
<P>
   Atwell, a robust man who stood 6-foot-3 and at his peak weighed
300 pounds, died Monday in Austin at age 82.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will say this,'' his daughter, Sandi Purdy of Dallas,
observed, ``he lived his way, and he never missed an opportunity to
have a good time. He absolutely was one of the ones who enjoyed
life to its fullest and never missed a beat.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He was,'' added Bay City state Rep. Tom Uher, ``the oldest
teen-ager.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Atwell, a Hutchins native who chaired the crucial
House Revenue and Taxation Committee for 12 years, was eulogized as
a man of ``courage, leadership and humor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Most members of the Legislature would scurry away from a tax
bill like mice in front of a flock of cats,'' said former state
Sen. Carl Parker of Port Arthur. ``Jumbo had the courage to carry
these bills at a time when the state badly needed the revenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wouldn't have the level of education, law enforcement or
social services we have if it weren't for him. He made the world a
better place for having lived in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Atwell's funeral, which began with recorded Willie Nelson tunes,
was a blend of solemnity and humor.
</P>
<P>
   His body, attired in a boldly patterned orange, black and white
shirt, lay in a mahogany coffin draped with a Texas flag. Nearby
was a stand holding a ceramic bust of the lawmaker, which, in turn
was topped with a fuzzy cowboy hat with rattlesnake skin band,
complete with rattles. Dangling from the statue's neck was an
oversized, red, white and blue necktie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to correct an error that's been appearing in the
obituaries,'' Parker told those gathered at Austin's Weed Corley
Fish Funeral Home. ``Jumbo wasn't 82 years old, he was 164. He just
did it quicker than most.''
</P>
<P>
   Among Atwell's other key achievements in the House _ where he
served more than two decades beginning in 1951 _ was his promotion
of a bill authorizing Dallas and Tarrant counties to create the
Dallas-Fort Worth International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   But the state's serious business aside, Atwell's former
colleagues this week recalled him for his bonhomie, describing him
as a larger-than-life figure in an era when serving the state was _
in former House Speaker Gib Lewis' words _ ``fun.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a man who prided himself on being a `character,''' said
Bob Slagle, former state Democratic Party chairman, who knew Atwell
in the 1960s. ``He had a wonderful time. He wasn't going to be
bored. He liked to tell jokes, be loud and have something to drink.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was kind of a fun guy, a roguish type of cat.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Atwell himself often allowed that he ``voted with the
conservatives and partied with the liberals.''
</P>
<P>
   Purdy, Atwell's daughter, recalled the time her father lampooned
the House of Representatives' strict coat-and-tie dress code by
arriving for a session attired in a plaid sport coat with a
5-foot-long red, white and blue necktie.
</P>
<P>
   Others remembered Atwell's outlandish Cadillac, the hood of
which was shadowed fender to fender by an enormous set of steer
horns.
</P>
<P>
   Though at one point deemed the ``dean'' of the Dallas County
delegation, Atwell rarely lived in his district, preferring the
livelier environs of the capital city, his daughter said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me one time that he never wanted to live in Dallas,''
she said. ``Said he never wanted to be cold again. He loved South
Texas, especially Austin.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Jumbo was a party fellow, but he was dependable and honest,''
said former Harris County state Sen. Chet Brooks. ``If he said he'd
vote with you, he'd be there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People knew he could turn off the frivolity, the
devil-may-care attitude and be very serious when focusing on the
issues he was working on,'' added Uher, who served on Atwell's tax
committee.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks recalled a Republican juggernaut of the early '60s that
ousted the entire Dallas delegation with the exception of Atwell.
Shortly afterward, Atwell received a bristling telegram from an
irate Republican physician.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a searing telegram,'' Brooks said. ``The guy did
everything wrong in making a political contact. He said he was a
Republican leader in Dallas who hadn't voted for him last time and
wouldn't support him next time. Meanwhile, he said Jumbo should
vote this, this and this.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked him, `Jumbo, how are you going to answer this?'
</P>
<P>
   ``Jumbo said, `That's simple. I sent him a telegram: Screw you.
Nasty letter to follow.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Jumbo had a great sense of humor.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Brooks remembered that Atwell lived in a building jocularly
called the ``Playboy Club,'' that was half apartment, half bar. The
veteran Harris County legislator still recalls a party at the
Playboy that featured the remarkably well-preserved Miss Wool of
1938.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was still a looker,'' Brooks said. ``Jumbo loved beauty.
He loved people.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Atwell's former colleagues agreed that he was a product of his
time and place, a creature of a freewheeling, old boys' legislative
culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had the pleasure to serve in state government when it was
fun,'' said Lewis, who was among Atwell's pallbearers. ``You could
curse, say what you wanted, without having the press haunt you for
life.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I called it `The Big Top,''' recalled Mississippi author
Willie Morris, who then edited the Texas Observer, a liberal
political journal.
</P>
<P>
   Morris vividly recalled a free-for-all on the House floor during
debate of a sales tax bill authored by Atwell and former state Rep.
Charlie Wilson, who later went on to become a longtime U.S.
congressman.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were wrestling in the aisles,'' Morris said. ``Some of
the secretaries were, too. Back then, secretaries sat next to the
legislators. The barbershop quartet, made up of four legislators _
it was like the orchestra on the Titanic _ they got up to sing
songs to quell the riot. I remember someone pulled the PA system
out.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Former Texas Observer publisher Ronnie Dugger characterized the
Legislature of those years as ``wild and wooly like the Wild West.
(It was) a wild, disreputable scene.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Those were simpler times,'' Brooks observed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now the stress is impossible. I don't think Jumbo would have
wanted to stay in it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
