<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, July 3, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   The holiday weekend will begin sunny and warm with comfortable
humidity over the Northeast and Middle Atlantic states. Gentle
winds will allow sea breezes to develop, keeping the coast
noticeably cooler than the interior. Meanwhile, a very weak
disturbance will encourage afternoon puffy clouds over parts of New
England.
</P>
<P>
   The boundary separating this pleasant air mass from sultry air
over the South will provide the focus for batches of showers and
thunderstorms from the Southeast Coast to the middle Mississippi
Valley. Most of the storms will develop along and on the humid side
of the front. Most of Florida will remain parched, though a shower
is possible across the south. Wildfires will continue to ravage
northern parts of the state. Meanwhile, tropical downpours will
spiral into the western Gulf states as a disturbance presses
westward.
</P>
<P>
   A potent cold front will slice through the upper Middle West.
Ahead of the front, hot, sticky air will erupt with showers and
thunderstorms. Supercell thunderstorms capable of producing
isolated tornadoes are possible from Nebraska to Illinois, though
high wind gusts and hail will be the primary threat.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, a jet stream disturbance will cause pockets of
showers and isolated thunder across the interior Northwest. Fog
will persist much of the day at the coast. Thunder will develop
over the Rockies Friday afternoon, as the mountain peaks provide an
elevated source of heat for rising air currents. The Southwest will
be sunny and seasonably hot, while coastal fog yields to afternoon
sun in California.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Alaskan Heat Low
</P>
<P>
   A heat low induced showers and thunderstorms across parts of
interior Alaska early Thursday. A heat low is a pocket of weak,
shallow low pressure that forms when the density of low-level air
decreases in response to high temperatures. This week, readings
soared toward 90 degrees over interior Alaska, leading to an island
of very warm, light air whose barometric pressure was lower than
the surrounding sea of cooler air. Air converging around the low
rose into the atmosphere, setting the stage for thunderstorms. A
flash-flood watch was posted for a region northwest of Fairbanks.
</P>
</TEXT>
