<HEADER>
A8381 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLIMBING-MT.MCKINLEY-     07-02 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLIMBING-MT.MCKINLEY-ART-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVENTURERS DESCEND ON MOUNT MCKINLEY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(lh) 
 By TIMOTHY EGAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALKEETNA, Alaska _ The cemetery in this risk-lover's domain
should be enough to keep most people from trying to stand atop the
High One, or Denali, as Athabascan Indians call Mount McKinley. The
climbers came from all over the world, drawn to the highest peak in
North America, and they ended up with their names on granite here _
118 dead over the last 65 years.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no sense of horror or defeat in the summer shadows.
After nearly a monthlong disappearance behind a cloak of mist and
storms, the mountain is out _ a hulk of rock and luminous ice
pressing the upper reaches of the Alaskan sky at 20,320 feet.
</P>
<P>
   So, even though three people have died so far this climbing
season, McKinley is more of a lure than ever before. Just outside
the cemetery in this village in south-central Alaska, about 50
miles southeast of Mount McKinley, bush planes fly away with fresh
loads of climbers setting out to begin a three-week haul from base
camp at 7,000 feet to the top of one of the world's most demanding
mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Until a few years ago, McKinley, the heart of Denali National
Park and Preserve, was a comparatively lonely place. Its reputation
for foul weather _ even in the summer, the upper slopes can be
gripped in wind-chill temperatures that are well below zero _ deep
crevasses in the glacial ice, and a need for slow-moving,
military-like ascents kept all but the most obsessive away.
</P>
<P>
   But since the mid-1980s, the number of climbers have doubled.
And this year, McKinley is likely to set a record, with more than
1,300 people trying to reach the summit. It was always a trophy
mountain. But it is even more so now, when there is a worldwide
fascination with mountaineering.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, a 12-year-old boy became the youngest person to
climb the mountain. The boy, Kim Yong Sik, a South Korean who was
with a party that included his father, made the summit by the
popular West Buttress route.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear trouble when I hear something like that,'' said Daryl
R. Miller, the chief climbing ranger at the park. Miller is in
charge of rescue operations; he keeps track of all climbing
accidents, and he has climbed McKinley numerous times over the last
15 years as a volunteer, a guide and a ranger.
</P>
<P>
   More than anything, Miller worries that some people will lose
respect for Mount McKinley. ``This mountain does not
discriminate,'' he said. ``If you look at all the accidents _ and
that's what I do for a living _ you see that the common factor is
weather, not experience level.''
</P>
<P>
   He scanned a list of fatalities from the last seven years. Under
the heading of cause, several reasons came up repeatedly: cold,
wind, frostbite, avalanche, dehydration, hypothermia.
</P>
<P>
   A board inside the ranger headquarters here keeps track of all
the attempts to reach the summit. On average, 50 percent of all
climbers make the top. This year, the success rate is only 35
percent.
</P>
<P>
   One of the deaths this year was an experienced member of a
rescue team; another was a mountaineering guide from Washington
state. A British military team with years of experience nearly lost
all their members in a fall; they were plucked by helicopter about
1,400 feet from the summit.
</P>
<P>
   The National Park Service does not screen people for experience
or common sense. Climbers pay $150, register 60 days in advance,
then are left on their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't play God,'' Miller said. ``We just have to hope
people understand what the risks are.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But as Miller shakes his head while wondering what the news of a
12-year-old climbing the tallest mountain in North America will
mean, climbers all around him at the ranger station chatter away in
the international language of challenge. There are teams of
mountaineers from Japan, Russia, France _ all of them raccoon-eyed
from spending weeks in the intense ultraviolet light of McKinley's
high glacier slopes.
</P>
<P>
   And there are people who say the mountain has become too
crowded, with too many people on a lark. ``I'm not going up there
anymore _ there are too many intellectuals,'' said Adrian Nature,
who just returned from nearly a month on McKinley.
</P>
<P>
   Nature, a resident of Salt Lake City, has been on McKinley 14
times, he said, but now he seems disgusted by the new popularity of
high-alpine mountaineering.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's that Jon Krakauer book,'' Nature said, referring ``Into
Thin Air,'' Krakauer's best-selling book about the disastrous 1996
climbing season on Mount Everest. ``There are so many people up
there now, it's disgusting. People don't take the time to learn
what this mountain is all about. They don't know what this mountain
can dish out.''
</P>
<P>
   Like other veteran climbers, Nature complained about the
``traffic jam'' of people _ literally hundreds of climbers in the
higher base camps above 14,000 feet _ snaking their way to the top.
Still, he may change his mind and return again next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why?'' he said. ``Because I love it. Because it is Denali, and
there is no other place like it in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The best of the early McKinley adventurers felt the same way.
Don Sheldon, perhaps the most famous bush pilot in Alaskan history,
opened numerous routes on McKinley and plucked many a frostbitten
climber from the mountain's icy flanks.
</P>
<P>
   After all the derring do, all the whiteouts, the slips and
falls, the uncertain steps into dark clouds, Sheldon died, in 1975,
of something that can strike people who seldom leave their couches
except to pick up the television remote _ cancer. He is buried in
the cemetery here, his ice ax embedded in stone. On the grave are
these words: ``He wagered with the wind and won.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-98 1818EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
