<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8388 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JACOB'S-DANCE-REVIEW-     07-02 0576
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACOB'S-DANCE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACOB'S PILLOW DANCE REVIEW: CREATIVE ENTERPRISE AMID BERKSHIRES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)   (bl)  
 By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Performances by the Paul Taylor Dance Company and Donald
Byrd/The Group are the formal attractions this weekend at the
Jacob's Pillow Dance Festival in Becket, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   But informal dance sprouts, it seems, in every lawn, hill and
grove, ranging from spontaneous eruptions like solitary pirouette
practice in a parking lot to free organized events like lectures,
exhibitions, book signings, self-guided walking tours and even a
hands-on interactive computer installation.
</P>
<P>
   And one of the most popular of such events is the ``Inside/Out''
series of staged performances, on Fridays and Saturdays at 7 p.m.,
on a rustic outdoor stage with a lush view of Berkshire greenery.
(Bring the mosquito repellent, though.) The festival closes Aug.
29.
</P>
<P>
   Some ``Inside/Out'' artists are recognized New York
choreographers and dancers. Others are new but promising, and
several are presenting work they have developed during Pillow
residencies. In the first category is Hernando Cortez, whose Cortez
and Company will present dances performed last month in Manhattan
at Dance Theater Workshop. (David Grenke's new Thingsezisee'm
Dance/Theater group performs Saturday.)
</P>
<P>
   What can Pillow audiences expect Friday night? Cortez, a former
Paul Taylor dancer who is now with Mikhail Baryshnikov's White Oak
Dance Project, is a compelling dancer and a choreographer who is
willing to wear his heart unpretentiously on his sleeve. He knows
how to put movement together clearly and fluidly in dance that
makes his performers look good. Several of the dances on this
program suggest, however, that his ideas have not kept pace with
his development as a choreographer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dark Wood,'' performed to music by David Darling, offers a
chance to savor Cortez's precisely balanced mix of muscularity and
fine-scaled physical articulation, of abandon and inward-focused
containment.
</P>
<P>
   Cortez juxtaposes a quiet, wondering individuality with the
heedless rush of the crowd in ``Bittersweet Symphony,'' set to a
pounding score by the Verve. In a group of robotic aerobic
exercisers, one woman separates to pick up and gently deposit tiny
toy birds with several others following suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dark Lover'' and ``Whisper at a Thousand,'' quartets danced to
music by Beethoven and Philip Glass respectively, address death in
unusually serene ways, with dancers settling briefly into poses and
groupings suggestive of Victorian tombstone sculptures. ``Shining
Path,'' set to music by John Adams, was an elegiac dance for an
Adam and an Eve dressed in costumes that looked like stylish
swimsuits.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Blind Love/Cruel Beauty'' and ``She Referred to `The
Evening' as if It Were a Person,'' dances set to music by Handel
and Leslie Stuck respectively, look as if they have been included
only to suggest Cortez's range of choreographic styles.
</P>
<P>
   The program by the Paul Taylor dancers, appearing at the Ted
Shawn Theater on Friday night at 8, Saturday at 2 and 8:30 p.m. and
Sunday at 2 p.m., will include Taylor's juicy new tango piece,
``Piazzolla Caldera.'' Byrd's group, appearing at the Doris Duke
Studio Theater on Friday night at 8:15 and Saturday and Sunday at 5
p.m., will perform his new ``Jazz Train,'' set to scores by Max
Roach, Vernon Reid and Geri Allen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-98 1824EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980702.0239 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8393 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-PARK-DANCE-REVIEW-     07-02 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PARK-DANCE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DANCE REVIEW: DEFEATING OUTDOOR PITFALLS WITH AN AFTERNOON FROLIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It is a risky proposi4ion to present dance outdoors
in an urban setting. The program must be strong enough to survive
the depredations of jets, boomboxes, weather shifts and audience
inattention. As q result, mere accessibility often overrules
artistic taste and quality.
</P>
<P>
   That was not the case, however, with ``Dancing With Myself!,''
presented by the Bryant Park Restoration Corporation in a
late-afternoon performance Wednesday on the lawn of Bryant Park.
</P>
<P>
   The program wAs short, running its course in just under an hour.
The seven choreographers, chosen by Peter Diggins, represented
ballet and modern and Broadway dance. The seven new solos, which
ranged from the mildly entertaining to the intriguing, were strong
and simple enough to capture the attention of passers-by and draw
them in. And the roster of performers offered a chance to catch up
with some new and familiar dancers who are seldom seen these days
in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl Yeager, a former principal at American Ballet Theater,
opened the program in Peter Pucci's ``Betweef the Voices,'' danced
to a sort of breathy yodeling by Sweet Honey in the Rock. Most of
the solos were preceded by brief comments from their
choreographers. Pucci talked of his intent to create a piece for
Ms. Yeager that bridged her ballet world and his world of modern
dance.
</P>
<P>
   There were no revelations about either form or about his
ballerina in ``Between the Voices.'' But Pucci's intent was clear
in the choreography, a matter of flick and ooze, with promenades in
arabesque balanced by long, easy breathing and slow subsidings into
the ground. And Ms. Yeager delicately embodied Pucci's balance of
dreaminess and joy.
</P>
<P>
   Like a clap of thunder after distant summer music, Mia Michaels'
``I Am'' spilled Jason Parsons onto the stage and let him loose to
revel in continual shifts between satanic energy and exhaustion,
moving to music by Tori Amos. Parsons is a strikingly committed
performer. Tall and sinuous, dressed in black briefs under a
rose-colored sarong with painted, curled-back lips and glittering
eyes, he looked like a refugee from an exceedingly decadent rock
group.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Pucci and Michaels solos, Christopher Wheeldon's
``Agnus Dei'' was most of all a showcase for the soloist, in this
case young Jared Angle of the New York City Ballet. The gentle flow
of the piece gave Angle a chance to display his attenuated ballet
body line and youthful solemnity. But the choreography did not make
it clear why Wheeldon had chosen the very specific score, the Agnus
Dei from Poulenc's Gloria.
</P>
<P>
   Kirk Peterson's ``Something Like a Tango,'' performed to music
by Gary Chang, was created for the recent International Ballet
Competition in Jackson, Miss. The jazzy, spiky choreography
doubtless served its purpose of jolting weary competition judges.
</P>
<P>
   But the dance offered a frustratingly narrow glimpse of Melissa
Wishinski, a much-talked-about young dancer who trained under
Peterson at the Hartford Ballet and was making her New York debut
here. A bronze medalist in Jackson, Ms. Wishinski is a confident
performer with a youthful sweetness and glow, and a dancer who
clearly promises much in terms of classical technique.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Shriver, a Broadway choreographer and performer, brought
that larger-than-life perspective to bear on ``The Living Room,''
performed by David Elder to a song by Randy Newman. Ms. Shriver
never moved beyond the obvious in this ``empty chair'' solo about
loss and grieving. Elder, also a Broadway performer, is a
beautifully supple mover, but his repertory of facial expressions
was small and over-used, and he looked as if he might break into
song at any moment.
</P>
<P>
   Melanie Person, a former member of Dance Theater of Harlem, has
just begun to choreograph, but she already knows the value of
simplicity, usually a hard-won attribute. Ms. Person's ``River
Goddess,'' danced to traditional Afro-Cuban music performed live,
was a loving, knowing valentine to Virginia Johnson, the longtime
ballerina of the Harlem ballet troupe. But Ms. Person also gave Ms.
Johnson substance enough for her to inhabit the dance.
</P>
<P>
   ``River Goddess'' offered a clearsighted exposition of Ms.
Johnson's special blend of fragility and power. Dressed in an
exquisitely exotic costume by Pamela Allen, Ms. Johnson was part
temple dancer, part sensuous temptress of Middle Eastern street
bazaars, suggesting, too, an antic spirit rising from and riding a
timeless river. The musicians were Don Babatunde Eaton, Gwen
Laster, Anna Ofori and Bernard Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   Margo Sappington closed the program with a bit of exuberant
trash called ``Valentina . . . Unplugged,'' set to music by
Santana. The pleasure of the solo was to see the way Valentina
Kozlova made the most of the dance.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in a purple lace body stocking with a purple scarf
accenting her bottom, Ms. Kozlova waved a fan of peacock feathers
and flirted teasingly with the audience in dance that consisted of
ladylike vamping in struts and poses, with fouettes thrown in for
incongruous good measure. Christian Holder designed the costume.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dancing With Myself!'' was part of the ``New Work, New York''
series in the summer festival of free music, dance and film in
Bryant Park. The dance programming continues with performances on
July 15 by Neta Pulvermacher and her company, and on Sept. 16 by
Sarah Skaggs, who will teach the audience her dance moves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
