<SLUG> BC-CRAWFORD-CONCERT-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POP REVIEW: MICHAEL CRAWFORD BECOMES THE PHANTOM OF RADIO CITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Many singers have recorded ``The Music of the
Night,'' that big greasy slice of ham and melted Swiss cheese from
``The Phantom of the Opera,'' in which the title character,
sounding like a lascivious hypnotist, feverishly coaxes his
reluctant dream lover to let her ``darker side give in.''
</P>
<P>
   But in imbuing this hunk of seductive bombast with creepy-crawly
melodrama, no one can touch Michael Crawford, who performed it on
Broadway more than 3,000 times.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Music of the Night'' is Crawford's million-dollar calling
card, the vehicle through which he made the almost unprecedented
leap from contemporary Broadway leading man to bona fide pop star.
</P>
<P>
   And at Radio City Music Hall, where he appeared with a 40-piece
orchestra and chorus on Tuesday and Wednesday evenings, Crawford
milked his signature song for all it was worth, portentously
intoning the opening bars offstage at the beginning of the show,
then performing a complete rendition later on
</P>
<P>
   Crawford's theatrically supercharged approach to ``The Music of
the Night,'' is similar to the way he treats most of his material,
which runs toward large-scale sentimental ballads. Beginning in a
hushed tension-filled whisper that verges on a hiss, he
methodically unfurls his reedy Irish-sounding tenor until it
becomes the braying sob of an overgrown child pleading for another
piece of candy.
</P>
<P>
   Although Crawford's voice is too quirky for opera, he flaunts
many operatic mannerisms, from broad gesticulation to enunciation
so exaggeratedly precise it treats lyrics like phonics lessons
inspired by pseudo-sacred texts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Music of the Night'' is really more than a song in
Crawford's highly polished show, which is touring 32 cities. It
supplies the running theme in his flowery between-numbers patter,
in which he gasses on effusively about the power of music to unite
people in laughter and in tears, and delivers rose-colored personal
reminiscences.
</P>
<P>
   After opening Wednesday's show with a ferociously over-the-top
rendition of ``Gethsemane,'' from ``Jesus Christ Superstar,''
Crawford momentarily quieted down to offer a tear-stained page from
his personal scrapbook, commemorating his beloved Irish nanny who
died at the age of 99 with a sweetly crooned version of ``I'll Take
You Home Again, Kathleen.''
</P>
<P>
   But he wasn't quiet for long. ``Before the Parade Passes By,''
``Being Alive'' and two numbers from a recent inspirational album,
``On Eagle's Wings'' (Atlantic) found Crawford back on his pulpit.
``Gethsemane'' was finally surpassed in intensity at the end of the
show with a rendition of ``Papa Can You Hear Me?'' (from the movie
``Yentl''), directed heavenward, that was so fervent that it made
Barbra Streisand's version sound demure.
</P>
<P>
   Was ``An Evening With Michael Crawford In Concert'' as
unabashedly corny as pop concert can get? Yes. But for all the
singer's florid gestures, the show had enough heart to make you end
up liking this former choirboy turned maestro of flamboyant
sentiment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-98 1829EDT &QL; 
