u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CREDIT-NYT &LR;      07-02 0399
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TREASURIES RALLY AMID SIGNS OF ECONOMIC SLOWDOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ROBERT HURTADO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Treasury prices rallied in an abbreviated pre-holiday
session Thursday, as the dollar gathered strength in currency
trading and the government's latest report on employment suggested
the economy was slowing.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the 30-year bond rose 14/32, to 107 19/32. The
bond's yield, which moves in the opposite direction from its price,
fell to 5.60 percent from 5.62 percent Wednesday. Last Friday, the
yield was 5.63 percent. The market closed at 2 p.m. Thursday and
will be closed Friday in observance of Independence Day.
</P>
<P>
   Gains came early as the dollar rallied against the yen on
investors' skepticism over Japan's latest plan to fix its ailing
banks. A strong dollar makes dollar-denominated investments like
Treasury securities more attractive to foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
   Bond prices were also bolstered by the June employment report,
which showed that the pace of job creation slowed in the month.
``This report provided some bullish support for the market because
it revealed significantly lower wage pressures than the market was
expecting,'' said Anthony Chan, managing director and chief
economist for Banc One Investment Advisors Corp. in Columbus, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts have said that if signals of an economic slowdown
continue, the market may even begin to price in the possibility of
a cut in interest rates by the Federal Reserve.
</P>
<P>
   But minutes of the May 19 meeting of Fed policy-makers, which
were released Thursday, show that the Fed remained concerned about
a flare-up in inflation. The decision to hold rates steady at the
May meeting came over the objections of two Fed policy-makers.
</P>
<P>
   The May meeting minutes ``tell us that it will take many more
economic reports to convince policy-makers that current economic
growth is no longer a threat to our long-term inflation outlook,''
Chan said. `` Recent trends show this may very well occur in the
near-term future.''
</P>
<P>
   Next week investors have little hard data to scrutinize with the
report on June producer prices on Friday being the most important
report. And although the report does not incorporate the effects of
import prices, say economists, it should still mimic the benign
price environment echoed in much of the data recently released.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
