<P>
   BRAVES-METS _ Since the beginning of the season, the Mets
consistently have made moves in an effort to challenge Atlanta for
National League supremacy. And many think, beginning Friday night
with the first of a three-game series, that New York is ready to
make its move. (Rosenberg, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). ETA: 8
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   MCGWIRE _ Mark McGwire is coming to Cincinnati this weekend for
a three-game series with the Reds. ``He is baseball's Paul
Bunyan,'' Hal McCoy writes. ``Instead of an ax he swings a
Louisville Slugger and splinters more furniture than a long
distance mover.'' (McCoy Dayton Daily News). ETA: 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   WOMENS-OPEN _ KOHLER, Wis. _ Coverage, first round of U.S.
Women's Open. (Sheeley, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). ETA: 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   WOMENS-NOTES _ KOHLER, Wis. _ U.S. Women's Open notebook.
(Sheeley, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). ETA: 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   WOMENS-COLUMN _ Column from first round. (Stoda, Palm Beach
Post) ETA: 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR-TEAMS _ DAYTONA BEACH, FLA. _ In this age of money _
millions are at stake _ some wonder if team racing is good for the
sport. Cale Yarborough, former driver and single-car owner, said
the edge multi-car team owners have from testing, swapping
information and sharing technology ``. . . ain't fair.'' But there
are other concerns: Has NASCAR reached the stage where drivers
would cheat on the final five laps to let teammates win? Some
drivers wonder. (Levine, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). ETA: 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ALYDAR _ Alydar, the most valuable stud in history, had to be
put down in 1990 after suffering a mysterious broken leg. Now the
groom guarding him that night is on trial for perjury in Houston as
part of an investigation of an alleged insurance scam involving
Calumet Farms of Kentucky and First City Bank Corp. of Texas. A
feature on the Alydar trial in Houston. (Thatcher, Austin American
Statesman). ETA: 10 p.m.
</P>
