<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8413 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNN-NERVE-GAS-BOS &LR;      07-02 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNN-NERVE-GAS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CNN RETRACTS NERVE GAS STORY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Less than a month after reporting the dramatic news that the
United States had used deadly sarin nerve gas during a secret 1970
mission in Laos to kill American defectors, CNN Thursday apologized
and retracted the story.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is insufficient evidence that sarin or any other deadly
gas was used,'' said CNN News Group chairman Tom Johnson in a
statement that aired at noon. ``Furthermore, CNN cannot confirm
that American defectors were targeted.'' While apologizing to
viewers, Johnson said CNN ``owes a special apology to the personnel
involved in Operation Tailwind.''
</P>
<P>
   CNN's retraction was based on the findings of a 54-page report
filed by noted media attorney Floyd Abrams, who was commissioned by
the network to conduct an independent investigation of the nerve
gas allegations.
</P>
<P>
   That June 7 story, which was reported by CNN producer April
Oliver and international correspondent Peter Arnett, marked the
debut of a CNN ``NewsStand'' prime time program that is a joint
collaboration between CNN and corporate partner Time magazine.
Although Time did not use its own reporters, it did publish a
version of the ``NewsStand'' story in its June 15 issue.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of CNN's admission, a network source said that
``NewsStand'' senior executive producer Pamela Hill has resigned,
Oliver and senior producer Jack Smith will be leaving the network,
and Arnett has been reprimanded. The Associated Press reported that
Oliver said she was fired and was standing by the accuracy of her
reporting.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  In Thursday's statement, Johnson also apologized to ``our
colleagues at Time'' and asserted that ``CNN alone bears
responsibility for both the television reports and for the printed
article in the June 15 issue of Time.'' Nevertheless, Time managing
editor Walter Isaacson Thursday issued his own apology and
retraction, saying Time's and CNN's investigation ``concluded that
the facts simply do not support the allegations that were made.''
</P>
<P>
   Sources at CNN and Time said plans were afoot to tighten the
reporting procedures on ``NewsStand'' but that there was no thought
of ending the partnership. ``We'll be a lot more careful,'' said
CNN spokesman Steve Haworth, adding that ``a very strong
relationship persists'' between Time and CNN.
</P>
<P>
   The ``NewsStand'' program _ cohosted by CNN's Bernard Shaw and
Jeff Greenfield _ is part of new CNN/US president Richard Kaplan's
plan to build ratings for the network's prime time programming. And
the stunning June 7 nerve gas story _ essentially indicting the US
government for war crimes _ made an instant impact.
</P>
<P>
   The day after the story, Secretary of Defense William Cohen
responded that the use of nerve gas in 1970 ``would ... have
violated our own policy at the time,'' and announced a Pentagon
investigation into the allegations. (Thursday, a Department of
Defense spokesman said that probe would continue and was expected
to conclude in a few days.)
</P>
<P>
   But nagging questions about the ``NewsStand'' story also began
to surface quickly. Former Defense Secretary Melvin Laird and
General William Westmoreland expressed doubts that the United
States would have used chemical weapons in Vietnam. Numerous news
media outlets produced stories questioning CNN's findings. And one
of the cable network's military advisers, retired Air Force Major
General Perry Smith, resigned in disagreement with the story.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, CNN stood by its reporting, running a June 14
``NewsStand'' piece affirming its original story. And in an
interview with The Boston Globe, Greenfield expressed his belief
that the nerve gas piece was ``awfully solidly sourced.''
</P>
<P>
   But after Thursday's retraction, analysts wondered whether a
network with a reputation for solid journalism had done serious
damage to its credibility and overreached in an effort to launch a
flashy prime time news magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you can make a mistake of this magnitude and not
suffer the consequences,'' said Bill Kovach, curator of the Nieman
Foundation at Harvard University. ``At what point is it going to be
possible for journalists to resist the pressure ... to compete for
revenue dollars rather than focus on quality?''
</P>
<P>
   Said Marvin Kalb, director of Harvard's Shorenstein Center on
the Press, Politics, and Public Policy: ``I cannot help but believe
that the marriage (between CNN and Time) is not going to last very
long.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
