<DOCNO> NYT19980702.0251 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8419 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIDS-MAIN03-COX     07-02 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-MAIN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Proposed vaccine could treat HIV-positive people by tricking
immune system
 &HT;    By Lillian Lee Kim
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Geneva _ One of the co-discoverers of the AIDS virus, Dr. Robert
Gallo, is preparing to launch a vaccine study that he said could
lead to a new way to treat HIV-positive people by manipulating
their immune systems.
</P>
<P>
   Gallo won't be using an HIV vaccine, but instead a vaccine that
will suppress substances in the blood that prevent healthy,
uninfected immune system cells from proliferating.
</P>
<P>
   The idea for the vaccine stems from new knowledge about how the
virus attacks human immune cells and how the body responds _ or
doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   Gallo, who heads the Institute of Human Virology at the
University of Maryland in Baltimore, spoke Thursday at the 12th
World AIDS Conference about new possibilities for preventing HIV
from invading cells and turning them into miniature munitions
factories that churn out more viruses.
</P>
<P>
   Much of AIDS treatment research focuses on using drugs to stop
the replication of HIV once it has already attacked and entered
cells.
</P>
<P>
   But Gallo said he believes it may be possible to halt the virus
at an earlier stage by blocking it from entering cells in the first
place, or by augmenting the immune system, which the experimental
vaccine is intended to do.
</P>
<P>
   He plans to start testing the vaccine this fall in Baltimore. It
has already been tried among 50 adults in Africa, with good
results.
</P>
<P>
   Melanie Thompson, lead researcher for the AIDS Research
Consortium of Atlanta, called Gallo's talk encouraging, although
she said it probably will be a few years before widely applicable
therapies can be derived from the concepts.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think one of the hopeful things, although it's not
immediately hopeful, is that there will be new targets for
therapy,'' Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
   One approach involves naturally occuring molecules called
beta-chemokines, which are credited with preventing HIV infection
in some hemophiliacs.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers have learned that HIV enters cells through the same
keyhole that chemokines use, called chemokine receptors. If an
over-abundance of chemokines are present in the blood, they lock
out HIV.
</P>
<P>
   A specific gene mutation may also confer immunity to HIV by
decreasing or eliminating the number of chemokine receptors in host
cells. A fraction of people of Caucasian ancestry possess one or
two copies of this mutant gene. Two copies provide total immunity;
one copy permits infection but slows the disease.
</P>
<P>
   ''HIV needs the chemokine receptor to enter the cell,'' Gallo
said. ''If you're born without the receptor, you're uninfectable.''
</P>
<P>
   Another possible treatment option is based on the gp41 protein
on HIV's outer coat. This protein fuses with human host cells.
</P>
<P>
   The drug manufacturer Roche is testing a substance, T-20, that
stops this fusion. In preliminary studies it has reduced virus
levels in the blood, Gallo said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, researchers said Thursday a weakened virus that many
consider the best hope for an AIDS vaccine may actually cause the
disease it was meant to prevent, citing tests on adult monkeys.
</P>
<P>
   The approach _ what scientists call a live, attenuated vaccine _
initially protects monkeys from getting infected with the simian
version of HIV. However, the new work shows that over time, the
weakened virus can mutate into a lethal form that causes the
disease it was meant to prevent.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers infected nine monkeys with a live attenunated
vaccine. Five years later, six had developed AIDS, five were dead
and none were immunologically normal, s &QC; aid Dr. Ruth Ruprecht of
Harvard University, who called the results ''sobering.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
