<SLUG> BC-BLACKARTS-MAIN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    National Black Arts Festival: Familiar faces, features make
encore appearances in midst of newcomers
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JULY 5: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA--Five days before the start of the National Black Arts
Festival and, one could say, the returns are already in. Legendary
vocalist Abbey Lincoln is returning for the biennial event. Actress
Phyllis Stickney is back. And so is poet-author Sonia Sanchez, the
Big Dance and the Black Rock Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   While two-time Pulitzer Prize winner August Wilson's staging of
``Jitney'' and the first American performance of musician-composer
Yusef Lateef's ``African-American Suite'' top the sizable number of
impressive new attractions, much of the programming for the fifth
NBAF is already quite familiar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, there are a number of people at this festival who have
participated in past festivals,'' says NBAF artistic director
Dwight Andrews. ``We've brought back some major artists whom, very
frankly, I wanted to see. I mean, (for instance) Maya Angelou. I
wasn't able to see her the last time because I was curating a
program at the same time of her appearance. There were a number of
major artists that I missed.
</P>
<P>
   ``But let me say this,'' he continues, ``some voices can be
heard more than once. These are not one-hit wonders. ...''
</P>
<P>
   In all fairness, this familiarity should be qualified. A
performance or program familiar to the NBAF is still hardly a
commonplace experience for your average reader, moviegoer or
theater patron.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, Sonia Sanchez is back and Maya Angelou will be there,
and so on,'' remarks New York author and cultural critic Nelson
George, a featured guest at past festivals. ``But where else can
anyone who pays the ticket price go see a Maya Angelou or Sonia
Sanchez and possibly run into August Wilson on the way to their
show? And talk to him? That's still an experience unlike any that
immediately comes to my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe in empty birthday parties,'' continues
Andrews, making reference to the festival's 10-year anniversary.
``I think this is very representative of where we are, and the
culture is in 1998. We could have done some 10-year retrospective,
but the culture is at too critical a juncture to start looking
back. We need to start thinking and responding to our art in new
ways.''
</P>
<P>
   The local arts community seems to agree. Here's what some had to
say about the NBAF offerings as a whole, and what they don't want
to miss. Use it as your guide:
</P>
<P>
   -- Must see in performance/theatre: Alliance Theatre artistic
director Kenny Leon recommends ``Jitney'' on July 12, 14-19 at the
Alliance.
</P>
<P>
   -- Must see in film/visual arts: Anne Hubbell, executive
director of Atlanta's Image Film &AMP; Video Center, recommends ``Night
of the Black Independents'' on Friday-Saturday at the Goethe
Institut Atlanta and ``Homage'' on July 13-17 at the High Museum of
Art's Walter Hill Auditorium. ``And the Paul Robeson tribute (July
17 at the Renaissance Atlanta Hotel ballroom and July 17-18 at the
High's Rich Auditorium) is important in the film community and
culturally because a lot of people don't quite understand the wide
influence he had.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Must see music: Mark Shimmel, chief operating officer of
LaFace Records, recommends ``World Drums for Peace'' on July 14 at
Variety Playhouse and the Black Rock Coalition's ``A Max &AMP; Abbey
Conversion in a Jungle Style'' on July 17 at Variety Playhouse.
</P>
<P>
   -- Must see literature: G. Ewa Ealy, assistant manager of the
Shrine of the Black Madonna Bookstore, recommends ``An Evening With
Maya Angelou'' on July 16 at Symphony Hall and fiction readings
with John Edgar Wideman and Marita Golden on July 15 at Georgia
Tech's Ferst Center for the Arts. She also suggests creative
nonfiction readings with bell hooks and Nathan McCall on July 16 at
the Ferst Center.
</P>
<P>
   -- Must see dance: Ken Bartlett, executive director of Dancers
Collective, recommends
</P>
<P>
   ``Diverse Duets'' on July 13 at the Rialto Center for the
Performing Arts and Urban Bush Women on July 15 at the Rialto.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
