<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACKARTS-PLAYWRIGHT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wilson brings issues center stage: Playwright to continue summit
on black theater
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JULY 5: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Dan Hulbert
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA--August Wilson, who is coming to the National Black Arts
Festival here both as a distinguished playwright (``Jitney'') and
the fiery, controversial organizer of a black theater summit, is
not above taking advice on how to improve his plays.
</P>
<P>
   Especially when the pointers come from a character in his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``One character comes to me and says, `Hey man, nobody gonna
know this is your play!''' says Wilson by phone from his Seattle
office, describing how he recently revised ``Jitney,'' a 1979 tale
about the first taxi cab company to serve his black community of
Pittsburgh. ``I say, `Why is that?' He says, `There ain't no
monologues in this play.' And I looked and saw he was right, so I
went back and put some in.''
</P>
<P>
   The winner of two Pulitzer Prizes (``Fences,'' ``The Piano
Lesson'') is inviting a few laughs at his own expense. Yes, his
characters can indeed wax loquacious, to say the least, with
monologues that cover multiple pages. And powerful soliloquies they
are: plain-spoken but poetic testimonies of love, yearning, terror,
suffering, hilarious mischief and mysterious dream visions. They're
delivered by an expanding gallery of African-American characters in
Wilson's projected cycle of 10 dramas, one for each decade of the
20th century.
</P>
<P>
   The revised ``Jitney,'' opening July 12 at the Rialto Center for
the Performing Arts, is the seventh of those plays, representing
the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   From writer to public firebrand
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most explosive of all of Wilson's speeches was one
that he delivered himself, not in a play but on the public stage of
racial and cultural politics.
</P>
<P>
   In a keynote manifesto before the Theatre Communications Group
two summers ago, Wilson accused Rrous standard of quality, even if
the grants usually go through white-run theaters. At one point last
year the two theater men actually took their heated argument to a
live debate on a New York stage.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson's next move was to call a National Black Theatre Summit
in March at Dartmouth College, to discuss with other major theater
figures practical strategies for bolstering black-run theaters. The
playwright's fire-in-the-gut had not cooled. Among his statements
was a denunciation of a ``Saturday Night Live'' sketch, with guest
star Samuel L. Jackson, that he called ``mean and slanderous to
black Americans. There should have been 100,000 ... black people
surrounding NBC headquarters the next morning.''
</P>
<P>
   National Black Theatre Summit II, the follow-up event at the
NBAF this year, will consist of closed-door meetings and symposia
at the Renaissance Hotel in Atlanta. It will culminate July 15 in a
public forum at the Alliance Theatre, scene of so many outstanding
productions of Wilson's plays (``Joe Turner's Come and Gone.'')
</P>
<P>
   One of the visiting dignitaries will be director Douglas Turner
Ward (``A Soldier's Play''). The fact that the Negro Ensemble
Company, which he founded over 30 years ago, had to suspend
operations a few years ago because of $750,000 in debts dramatizes
the intense plight of many black theaters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're moving past the talking phase; we're going to solicit
ideas on what to do and devise a plan,'' says Wilson, a compelling
speaker whose appearance is a must even for those who aren't
galvanized by the summit issues. ``We're looking at how to set up
an organization with memberships for the 50,000 black performing
artists in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Play complements his public agenda
</P>
<P>
   Wilson concluded his Dartmouth summit saying, ``If the condition
of black theater art is dependent on the benevolence of white
America, it has lost its self-determination.''
</P>
<P>
   That sense of empowerment will be on display in ``Jitney.''
Growing up on The Hill, the oldest black community of Pittsburgh,
Wilson was struck by the exploits of some unlicensed cabbies or
jitney drivers, who started with a vacant storefront and a pay
phone and built a thriving, colorful business.
</P>
<P>
   ``The white cabs wouldn't pick up blacks in those days, so this
was a service that was created from scratch and changed peoples'
lives,'' Wilson says. A key relationship in the play is between a
driver and a son who has just been released from prison after
serving a murder sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jitney'' was the first of Wilson's plays, produced in
Pittsburgh and St. Paul, Minn., but is still the least-known, his
only work not to play New York. The playwright hopes that his
recent revisions will lead to a second life for the 19-year-old
play, which is scheduled for a fall production in Boston that will
help determine its Broadway prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't always value the way black people really talk, the
way I do now,'' Wilson says, by way of explaining why he thinks the
new script is stronger and more t
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
