<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8437 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-TEENS-COX     07-02 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-TEENS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Teens from a rainbow of backgrounds learn to share pride and
pain while gaining a world of insight
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JULY 4: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Banner Elk, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   What are some stereotypes?'' the Rev. Jimmy Harper asks 42
teenagers sitting around his feet in the dining hall of Hoston
Presbyterian Camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``People tend to think all Mexicans ride around in the backs of
trucks,'' a Hispanic boy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without knowing about your religion, people assume you worship
the devil or are in a cult or something,'' said a Baha'i boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a friend who has really short hair. A lot of people
think she's a lesbian,'' said a white girl.
</P>
<P>
   The discussion winds its way through hatred and prejudice,
personal and communal hurt and anger, and ends with talk about
spiritual values, love, tolerance and respect for other people.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's those things that make us good, decent human beings,''
Harper said.
</P>
<P>
   The teens applaud.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to Anytown, a weeklong camp run each year by the Atlanta
office of the National Conference for Community and Justice,
formerly the National Conference of Christians and Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Its purpose is to bring together high school students of various
religions, races and cultures to get to know one another as
friends.
</P>
<P>
   This mountain setting near North Carolina's ski slopes is one of
about 40 locations across the country where Anytowns are held each
summer. Harper, 57, an ordained Southern Baptist minister married
to a Jewish woman, is the conference's regional director.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 session is the 10th sponsored by the Atlanta office.
Students who came as ``delegates,'' or campers, are back as
counselors and advisers.
</P>
<P>
   James Mills, 25, the camp's co-director, was there in 1989. ``It
rained every single day. It was a good three-quarters of a mile
from the cabins to the meeting area,'' he said. ``And we had a
great time.''
</P>
<P>
   Mills has missed only one session of the camp, which has rented
space at various locations over the years.
</P>
<P>
   A math teacher at DeKalb County(Ga.)'s Indian Creek Elementary
School, where more than half the student body is international,
Mills said he uses his Anytown experience ``every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Counselor Genevieve Colquitt, 18, was a delegate in 1996, when
she was a student at Pebblebrook High School in Mableton, Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I realized about other people is that although we are
different and go through different experiences and have different
backgrounds, basically we are the same. We have the same pain, no
matter where we're from,'' she said. ``I got a lot of skeletons out
of my closet.''
</P>
<P>
   Adviser Amy Ward, 22, a student at the University of Tennessee
in Knoxville, attended an Anytown in Memphis.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was growing up, I was mostly surrounded by white
people,'' said Ward, who is white.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think of myself as prejudiced, but when I got into
that group, I noticed stereotypes I had, whether they affected my
direct actions or not,'' she said. ``The opportunity to spend time
with people of different backgrounds was so incredible to me. I
learned so much.''
</P>
<P>
   At the university, she has gotten involved in political
movements to promote civil rights and justice.
</P>
<P>
   Through Anytown, she said, she realized ``just how few people of
color and women are in positions of power. I'm working to change
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Barin Sultani, 15, came to Anytown as a camper. This
year, she is Anytown's first counselor intern. Born in Afghanistan,
she is a student at DeKalb County's Druid Hills High School.
</P>
<P>
   As a Muslim, she said, she has had to clear up misconceptions
about Muslim women. Meanwhile, she has learned about other
religions and cultures.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what Anytown is all about,'' she said. ``Correcting
wrongs.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
