<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980702.0258 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8438 &Cx1f; tad-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-CONNEMARA-COX     07-02 1204
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-CONNEMARA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Connemara recalls Sandburg, the goats
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JULY 5: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Flat Rock, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Tapestry the goat is not a kid anymore. The flop-eared Nubian
whose mottled coat inspired her name is a yearling now _ much to
the delight of the youngsters who remember her from their last
visit to the goat farm at Connemara, the Carl Sandburg Home.
</P>
<P>
   ``They couldn't wait to see if any of the babies they saw last
summer would still be here,'' says their dad, Don Buckley of
Knoxville.
</P>
<P>
   The goats have always been a big attraction.
</P>
<P>
   Sandburg's wife, Lilian Steichen Sandburg (called Paula), found
the white-columned home built in 1838 by former Secretary of the
Confederate Treasury Christopher Memminger. Pleased with the gentle
climate and ample pasture, she declared Connemara (named by second
owner Ellison Smyth to honor his Irish ancestry) just right for a
family of seven _ and a growing herd of goats.
</P>
<P>
   So the Sandburg clan _ including three grown daughters, two
grandchildren and the goats _ moved from Michigan in 1945 and
settled quietly into the 240-acre mountainside farm with little
fuss from townspeople.
</P>
<P>
   Today, folks from far and wide take notice. Connemara, a
National Historic Site, is by far Flat Rock's most-visited
attraction, welcoming more than 100,000 visitors a year. About half
that number tour the house, while others simply enjoy the grounds,
including the goat barns, and walk along the five miles of trails
on the property.
</P>
<P>
   Home to the people's poet until his death in 1967, Connemara was
a haven where the author could compose without worldly
distractions. He drew inspiration from the pastoral surroundings
and strength from the mountains, and was able to rejuvenate after
his frequent lecture tours.
</P>
<P>
   But at least in agricultural circles, Connemara was best-known
for Paula's prize-winning goats. In fact, many who bought the
farm's highly regarded goat milk and cheese were surprised to learn
that the woman who bred champion goats was married to one of
America's most beloved poets.
</P>
<P>
   Even now, visitors of all ages are as captivated by the resident
goats as they are by the big white house with Sandburg's library of
more than 10,000 books, stacks of yellowed newspapers and
correspondence lying where he left it.
</P>
<P>
   Visiting the estate, it's easy to imagine the place described by
Sandburg's granddaughter, Paula Steichen, who lived at the farm
with her mother, Helga, the youngest Sandburg daughter, and brother
John Carl until she was 10, in her 1969 book ``My Connemara''
(Eastern Acorn Press, $3.95):
</P>
<P>
   ``This wilderness of Connemara, this wild, sweet way of
Connemara, would come back to me always after leaving _ in the
scent of wild blackberries, the nickering of a colt watching its
mother being led away to plow, the feel of wet morning grass on
bare feet, and the moving of a herd at milking time up the pasture
lane. ... ''
</P>
<P>
   Connemara has been a National Historic Site since 1968, when the
family sold the property and donated the house's contents to the
National Park Service.
</P>
<P>
   Touring the home with a park ranger guide 30 years later, one
gets the feeling that the family is simply away for the day and
will return as soon as we intruders leave. Beds are neatly made,
dishes washed and the dining table set. Rolled-up copies of the
Sunday New York Times lie next to Sandburg's place at the table.
Scraps of paper mark favorite passages in Sandburg's books. Life
magazines are strewn about, waiting to be read, then stacked with
others in orange crates. Sandburg's guitar lies ready for the
troubadour to pluck its strings and warble some traditional ditty
like ``Eating Goober Peas'' in his gravely voice.
</P>
<P>
   Sandburg's cluttered workroom on the third floor, which he
called ``the dizzy corner,'' is in the sort of disarray that only
the person who rendered it that way could sift through.
</P>
<P>
   While the clapboard house is large and comfortable, it is rather
plainly outfitted with solid, reliable furnishings. Black and white
photographs _ notably one of Carl and Lilian in 1923 _ taken by her
brother Edward Steichen grace the walls. Sandburg's collection of
carved walking sticks is amassed in the living room.
</P>
<P>
   After parking in the lot off Little River Road, visitors to the
historic site first see the house in the distance on the side of
Little Glassy Mountain, a lake in the foreground and grassy fields
in between. It's a .3 mile walk via a footbridge over the lake and
up a steep grade to reach the house, but once glimpsed, the
gleaming white structure lures you to its doors. (Strategically
placed benches along the trail provide welcome stopping places as
you ascend 100 feet _ the equivalent of a 10-story building. A
shuttle van is available for guests with disabilities or those not
fit enough to make the trek.)
</P>
<P>
   Plan to spend at least half a day at Connemara. Very little of
the estate is off-limits, although no swimming or fishing in the
lakes is allowed. If you still have the energy after the hike to
the house, take the .8 mile trail around Little Glassy Mountain _
or the .4 mile trail over Little Glassy. It's 1.2 miles along the
Memminger Path to Big Glassy Mountain, from which gorgeous vistas
unfold: lakes and ponds, rolling pastures, dense forests and the
Blue Ridge Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   On weekdays during the summer, the Vagabond Players from Flat
Rock Playhouse present performances such as dramatic adaptations of
``Rootabaga Stories'' at the amphitheater in the meadow in front of
the house.
</P>
<P>
   At the barn complex, rangers give programs about the goats and
offer goat cheese-making demonstrations. Although feeding the goats
is verboten and parents are warned to keep an eye on small
children, gentle petting is fine _ the goats seem to enjoy and
expect it.
</P>
<P>
   The 18 goats are descendents of the original herd of
white-on-brown Toggenburgs, white Saanans and multicolored Nubians.
The herd numbered more than 200 head in 1952, when 50 to 80 does
were milked twice a day. The top doe of all time was Jennifer II,
who produced 5,750 pounds of milk in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   House tours begin every 30 minutes in the visitor center on the
main floor, where tickets are sold. While you wait, you can watch
films about Sandburg and the home. Especially worthwhile is the
10-minute video of excerpts from an Edward R. Murrow documentary,
which features Sandburg reading from ``The People, Yes'' and
crooning the moody ``September Song.''
</P>
<P>
   Browsing the bookstore shelves, I was amused to find several
books about goats alongside volumes of Sandburg's poetry and his
acclaimed Lincoln biography. Carl and Paula Sandburg probably
would've liked that.
</P>
<P>
   -- Information: Open daily except Christmas. No admission
charged, but house tours are $3 for adults (free for children under
12). Take I-85 north to U.S. 25 in Greenville, S.C., then north on
U.S. 25 to Flat Rock and turn left on Little River Road between the
Flat Rock Playhouse and the post office. The parking lot is .10
mile on the left. 828-693-4178.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
