<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8439 &Cx1f; tad-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-FLATROCK-COX     07-02 1051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-FLATROCK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Escape summer in the city at Flat Rock
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JULY 5: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Flat Rock, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   It's 8 o'clock on a Friday night and it seems that every car on
U.S. 25 is heading for the Flat Rock Playhouse _ a red barn of a
building that sits on the same granite outcropping where the
Cherokees held tribal gatherings centuries ago.
</P>
<P>
   When the thousands of cars that descend on the ``flat rock''
that gave the town its name depart two or three hours later, they
leave the town as whisper-quiet as it was before they arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Designated the State Theatre of North Carolina, the summer
theater draws 50,000 visitors annually to Flat Rock (population
2,000) between May and October for a nine-play mix of
Broadway-style comedies, classics and musicals. ``The Affections of
May'' is on the boards now, with the musical ``The Will Rogers
Follies'' coming up July 15-Aug. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Big-city production values and a professional acting company
belie the rustic setting and the shorts-and-sandals ambience. Which
is exactly what makes the playhouse so appealing.
</P>
<P>
   But the theater and nearby Carl Sandburg Home aren't the only
reasons to visit the area called ``the Little Charleston of the
Mountains'' since the mid-1800s when wealthy plantation owners,
seeking a respite from the oppressive, coastal heat built large
summer estates where they could relax and unwind.
</P>
<P>
   Flatlanders return to this day for the same reasons, finding
low-key lakeside resorts and cozy old inns to loll for at least a
night or two in the cool, green mountain calm.
</P>
<P>
   For all its charms, Flat Rock is not a typical mountain resort
village. A small sign on the outskirts of town heralds your arrival
in Historic Flat Rock, but you could drive right through and be
halfway to Hendersonville four miles north before you realize
you've passed it by.
</P>
<P>
   Although the entire district is included in the National
Register of Historic Places, there is no quaint main street with
shops, antiques emporiums and restaurants like you'll find in
Hendersonville.
</P>
<P>
   Heading north into Flat Rock along U.S. 25, past green,
undulating mountain ridges and spry orange day lilies waving from
the roadside, the private Kenmure Golf Course and its gated
community of upscale homes hint of the posh life of year-round
residents. There are summer homes tucked all over these hills, but
you don't see many along the main drag.
</P>
<P>
   Near the intersection of Blue Ridge Road (site of the only
traffic light) are a handful of businesses. Dean's Deli and Market
(look for the Exxon sign and boxes of red geraniums along the
porch) is a good spot for a quick breakfast, lunch or snack
(homemade biscuits, pastries, cakes, pies, soups, salads and such).
</P>
<P>
   The Wrinkled Egg is a former general store that sells gifts and
homemade breads baked in a wood-fired oven and assembles ``care
packages'' for parents to send to their kids at area camps. Next
door is the Secret Garden, filled with (and surrounded by) plants
and everything to delight the green thumb. The redbrick Singleton
Center houses a collection of artist studios and galleries. Up the
road is the Book Exchange and the Hand in Hand Gallery.
</P>
<P>
   Farther north is the turnoff for the Carl Sandburg Home and the
St. John in the Wilderness Episcopal Church. The latter was built
in 1833 as a chapel on the grounds of Mountain Lodge, the home of
the Charles Barings, the first of many Lowcountry families to
settle in Flat Rock. In 1836, the Barings deeded the yellow brick
church to the Episcopal Diocese of Western North Carolina, and
services have been held here ever since. The church and graveyard
are open 9 a.m.-4 p.m. daily for self-guided tours (828-693-9783).
</P>
<P>
   There are no restaurants in Flat Rock, but the Highland Lake Inn
and the 1852 Woodfield Inn dining rooms are open to nonguests _ and
both worth a visit.
</P>
<P>
   Pecan-encrusted trout and batter-fried lobster tails and an
outstanding dessert of lemon sorbet and fresh fruit in a praline
basket hit the spot at Woodfield. The next night at Highland Lake's
Old Dining Room, the trout lover among us again ordered the fish,
this time stuffed with crab meat and goat cheese, and proclaimed it
another winner. The marinated and grilled shrimp and scallops
accompanied by garden-fresh vegetables grown on site were also
tasty _ as were desserts of bourbon pecan pie and creme brulee.
</P>
<P>
   Both the recently renovated Woodfield (with panoramic views from
its sweeping verandas) and Highland Lake (with tennis, swimming
pool, stocked fishing lake, mountain bikes, organic gardens and a
small working farm) would have been fine places to spend the night.
</P>
<P>
   But we were quite content at the Mill House Lodge, where dozens
of indolent Canada geese paddle alongside canoers in the lake and
waddle about on the shore as anglers while away the afternoon. The
Mill House is not fancy but clean, comfortable and homey with a
variety of accommodations including rooms in the 1830 gristmill and
the one-bedroom suite we booked in the Jordan Lodge next to the
swimming pool stocked with fun inflatables. There is no restaurant
on site, but kitchenettes are available and the outdoor grills are
much-used _ as are the porch chairs.
</P>
<P>
   Once you've caught a play and checked out local sights, there's
not much left to do but take it easy. Works for the geese.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   -- Staying over: Mill House Lodge, $69-$120, 1-800-736-6073;
Highland Lake Inn, $79-up (rooms, cottages and cabins),
1-800-762-1376; Woodfield Inn, $89-$149, 1-800-533-6016.
</P>
<P>
   -- Flat Rock Playhouse schedule: ``The Affections of May,''
Tuesday-Saturday; ``The Will Rogers Follies,'' July 15-19, July
21-26 and July 29-Aug. 2; ``Perfect Wedding,'' Aug. 5-9 and Aug.
11-15; ``Annie Get Your Gun,'' Aug. 19-23, Aug. 25-30, Sept. 1-6;
``To Kill a Mockingbird,'' Sept. 9-13, 18-20; and ``Swingtime
Canteen'' Sept. 30-Oct. 4, Oct. 7-11 and Oct. 14-18. Evening
performances at 8:15; matinees 2:15 p.m. Musicals $23, plays $20.
828-693-0731. Web site: www.flatrockplayhouse.org
</P>
<P>
   -- Information: 1-800-828-4244 (Henderson County Travel and
Tourism).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
