<HEADER>
A8441 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-RESORT-COX     07-02 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-RESORT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Colorful crowd convenes in `Last Resort'
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JULY 5: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Carolyn Nizzi Warmbold
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's been a decade since Alison Lurie's last novel, ``The Truth
About Lorin Jones,'' and 14 years since her delightful ``Foreign
Affairs,'' which won the Pulitzer Prize. Her 1994 short stories in
``Women and Ghosts'' were mere appetizers for readers who hungered
for another novel.
</P>
<P>
   Lurie has cooked up an entree worth the wait. ``The Last
Resort'' is a comic novel of manners that, although lacking the
bite of ``Foreign Affairs,'' is a gourmet summer read.
</P>
<P>
   Jenny Walker, 46, has been wife, secretary and research
assistant to naturalist author Wilkie Walker, 25 years her elder.
Their two grown children are horrified by her Victorian attitude,
but Jenny revels in her auxiliary position, at least until Wilkie
inexplicably freezes her out. Hoping to rejuvenate his interest in
life, she suggests they spend the winter in Key West, Fla., the
Last Resort.
</P>
<P>
   The lush locale holds irony for Wilkie, who is secretly
convinced he is dying of cancer. He plans his suicide to look like
an accident, but it does not turn out to be easy to drown oneself,
particularly in a novel peopled by characters who are as colorful
as bougainvillea.
</P>
<P>
   There are the locals: Lee Weiss, a lesbian who gave up a
counseling career to run a lodge for women; Molly, an
unpretentious, arthritic widow who once drew covers for The New
Yorker; and Jocko, an HIV-infected landscaper. And there are the
visitors: Poet Gerald Grass, who, having discarded a wife and
yuppie girlfriends, hopes to seduce Jenny; Jocko's plant-loving
Mumsie; and his airhead cousin, Barbie Mumpson of Tulsa, Okla.
</P>
<P>
   Readers may remember Barbie from the end of ``Foreign Affairs,''
when she visits Virginia ``Vinnie'' Miner in London. Barbie is the
daughter of Chuck Mumpson, Vinnie's unlikely, loudmouthed lover
from Oklahoma who died of a heart attack. In the interim, Barbie
has maintained her love for animals, her accent and a penchant for
apologizing for her stupidity.
</P>
<P>
   But she has lost a touch of her joie de vivre. Dominating mother
Myra has pushed Barbie into marrying freshman congressman Wild Bob
Hickock. He has been sowing his wild oats with a showgirl, despite
Barbie's attempts to reignite his libido with silver lace camisoles
from Neiman Marcus. Myra, with a Victorianism more ironic than
Jenny's, suggests that Barbie stay married and tell herself she
``was doing it for Oklahoma.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, there has been little that's novel in the
American novel, but this book strolls seldom-trod literary ground
when Jenny is attracted to Lee, and their love flourishes among the
flowers. Think about it: How often do contemporary mainstream
novels have lesbian protagonists? Gay women, when they appear at
all, are most often secondary characters (Patricia Cornwell's Lucy)
or peripheral (Anne Rivers Siddons' couple in ``Up Island''). Lurie
places Jenny and Lee's love front and center, in counterpoint to
Wilkie's rabid homophobia and moves Barbie's heterosexual dilemma
to the edges.
</P>
<P>
   Lurie, aptly compared to Jane Austen by Joyce Carol Oates,
craftily steers the plot away from soap opera or farce down lush
paths of irony. Key West might be a 20th-century version of Bath,
offering the same rejuvenation and discovery of self. But in our
time, Anne Elliott is swept away not by Captain Wentworth, but by
another woman. Austen, were she writing today, would find it droll
indeed.
</P>
<P>
   The Last Resort. By Alison Lurie. Henry Holt. $22. 321 pages.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict:
</P>
<P>
   Another ironic novel of manners from a contemporary Jane Austen.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
