<HEADER>
A8442 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-LMAY04-COX     07-02 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-LMAY04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN:Graceful grasses perfect ornament for summer lawn
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JULY 4: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Lee May
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the air feels like camel's breath and ozone alerts alert
everyone but politicians and policy-makers, when it's hotter than
fire on the Fourth of July and hydrangeas keel over in a heated
faint while roses refuse to bud, the grasses keep on keeping on.
</P>
<P>
   Burn them, dry them, fry them, and still they're as lush as they
want to be.
</P>
<P>
   If I were building a climatically smart garden, ornamental
grasses would be all over it. As it is, my nod to xeriscaping
amounts to less and less watering in an effort to train my plants
to tolerate drought _ and a few patches of perennial grasses here
and there. Most grow in full sunlight, but some do just fine in
light shade.
</P>
<P>
   Flowering time usually starts in late summer and goes into fall,
but this year I've already noticed blooms on one clump of Japanese
silver grass. Must be El Nino.
</P>
<P>
   My oldest patch _ maiden grass _ was started in a pot and moved
from Washington to Atlanta in 1989. I put it in the ground that
year and have divided it several times. Nevertheless, it is a hefty
4 feet high and wide. During hot, dry spells, I water it about once
every couple of weeks, and it never falters.
</P>
<P>
   Graceful (sometimes called the queen of ornamental grasses),
this clump with long green leaves, a narrow white stripe down the
center, waves in the slightest breeze, cheerfully, majestically. In
winter, after its blooms have turned fluffy and its leaves have
gone beige, it is still beautiful, elegant with age.
</P>
<P>
   Far less elegant, but chipper, is the festuca, less than a foot
tall with silver-blue leaves and little flower spikes growing well
above the clump. While the festuca does not wave, it speaks
eloquently through its contrast with the nearby brick wall.
</P>
<P>
   Then, there's the aptly named Japanese blood grass, whose leaves
bleed red into green, giving life to space around a granite stone
and evoking vistas of marsh grasses as it ripples in window boxes.
</P>
<P>
   One, whose name I don't know, grows like wild and crazy hair
matted and flying helter-skelter. Call it Cousin It. For more than
a year I haven't known whether this grass is dead or alive. But
even if it has gone on, it is too charming to let go.
</P>
<P>
   Not much to look at, not much to feel, the sweet grass is a
fragrant delight, recalling so many baskets I've known, works of
art and craft, created by artisans around the Southeast. I've
bought them on the streets of Charleston, at mountain fairs,
sniffed them so much I feared I'd suck the smell right out of them.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, sweet sweet grass. Crush it and it's like vanilla mixed with
almond and freshly cut lawn.
</P>
<P>
   My clump came from the U.S. Botanic Garden several years ago. I
put it in a pot, and it comes back each year (defying the rules,
supposedly. Annual lemon grass returns, too).
</P>
<P>
   Gradually, the sweet grass has filled its 12-inch pot, and soon,
maybe this fall, I will take it from the container and put it in
the ground, despite warnings that it is invasive.
</P>
<P>
   Invasive. There's the rub many cite when talking about growing
any ornamental grass. True, some are serious spreaders. But, if I'm
choosing among invasive plants, grasses would be one I'd keep.
</P>
<P>
   And sweet grass? Invade me. Take over my garden. Grow like
kudzu. Grow like dwarf bamboo. Like English ivy. What a lovely
invasion this could be.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: leemay(at)bellsouth.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
