<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8443 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-FREEDOM-COX     07-02 2111
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-FREEDOM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Legislators, courts refine definition of freedom of worship
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JULY 4: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In recent years, the Million Man March organized by the Nation
of Islam's Minister Louis Farrakhan and the Promise Keepers' Stand
in the Gap rally of Christian men put religion symbolically in the
center of the nation's capital. But while massive rallies have
drawn public attention, actions in the legislative halls and
courtrooms have been changing and refining the definition of what
freedom of religion, as expressed in the First Amendment to the
Constitution, really means. Here's a snapshot of recent and pending
legislation and court cases affecting religious liberty:
</P>
<P>
   Religious Freedom Amendment
</P>
<P>
   On June 4, a majority of the U.S. House of Representatives voted
in favor of a constitutional amendment introduced by Rep. Ernest
Istook (R-Okla.) to permit school prayer _ but the tally fell short
of the two-thirds majority required. As the legislation went down
in the House, Istook's fellow Oklahoma Republican, Sen. James M.
Inhofe, introduced the same amendment in the Senate. It says in
part, ``The people's right to pray and to recognize their religious
beliefs, heritage or traditions on public property, including
schools, shall not be infringed.'' It specified that no one could
be compelled to join in prayer or other religious activities.
</P>
<P>
   Many mainline groups oppose the legislation. Southern Baptists
supported the Istook amendment after persuading the sponsor to
amend it until they were satisfied it ensured equal access to all
religions.
</P>
<P>
   The amendment, says Stephen Kao of the conservative Rutherford
Institute, is ``a laudable attempt to remedy some problems. We did
feel, however, that it was not the best language that could have
been offered.''
</P>
<P>
   Religious Liberty Protection Act
</P>
<P>
   The unlikely sponsoring team of Ted Kennedy (D-Mass.) and Orrin
Hatch (R-Utah) in the Senate and Charles T. Canady (R-Fla.) and
Jerrold Nadler (D-N.Y.) in the House of Representatives hopes this
legislation will make it more difficult for governments to
interfere with religion.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, introduced in June, requires the government to
accommodate religious practices unless they conflict with a
``compelling interest'' of the public, such as health or safety.
</P>
<P>
   It is the most recent link in a chain of legislation and Supreme
Court decisions going back to 1990:
</P>
<P>
   -- Deciding 6-3 in a case known as the Employment Division vs.
Smith, the U.S. Supreme Court ruled that the state of Oregon could
deny unemployment benefits to American Indian men, including Albert
L. Smith, fired from their jobs for the sacramental use of the drug
peyote. The decision came despite briefs on Smith's behalf from an
incredible range of religious organizations. The majority opinion
said no special consideration must be given to religion as long as
a law is generally applicable.
</P>
<P>
   -- In an attempt to gain back ground lost in the Smith decision,
a broad coalition of religious groups and an overwhelming
bipartisan majority of Congress worked together and passed the
Religious Freedom Restoration Act in 1993. The law said that
government ``shall not substantially burden a person's exercise of
religion'' without a compelling interest.
</P>
<P>
   -- A year ago, the U.S. Supreme Court struck down the Religious
Freedom Restoration Act, saying Congress overstepped its authority
in interpreting the First Amendment to the Constitution. The ruling
came in Boerne vs. Flores, a zoning dispute in the small town of
Boerne, Texas, where a Catholic church wanted to expand its
facilities in the city's historic district. Attorneys for St. Peter
the Apostle Catholic Church and Archbishop Patrick Flores claimed
that the Religious Freedom Restoration Act exempted it from the
requirements of the district.
</P>
<P>
   ``The argument of Bishop Flores was quite simply that churches
have First Amendment ... guarantees that mandate that they be
treated differently than bowling alleys and used car lots,'' said
Richard Land, president of the Ethics and Religious Liberty
Commission of the Southern Baptist Convention. ``In effect, in the
Boerne decision, the Supreme Court said, 'No, you don't.'''
</P>
<P>
   The new Religious Liberty Protection Act is narrower in its
focus than its predecessor. Its authors have attempted to focus on
three areas they believe Congress can regulate under the
Constitution: commerce, federal funding and land use. The bill
prohibits state or local governments from undue interference with
any religious program receiving federal financial assistance or
affecting interstate commerce and specifically addresses the area
of land-use regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Some areas will not be covered. ``It is possible, but not
absolutely certain, that home schooling won't be protected,'' said
Marc Stern, lawyer for the American Jewish Congress. ``And views
about autopsies are going to be hard to fit in.''
</P>
<P>
   The new bill has the support of more than 80 religious groups
and civil rights organizations, from the American Civil Liberties
Union to the Christian Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   The Freedom From Religious Persecution Act / International
Religious Freedom Act
</P>
<P>
   In May, the House of Representatives overwhelmingly passed a
bill to impose sanctions on foreign governments determined to be
engaging in religious persecution.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the opposition of many business lobbyists and the
Clinton administration, the House approved the Freedom From
Religious Persecution Act, sponsored by Rep. Frank Wolf (R-Va.),
co-sponsor of the bill with Rep. Christopher Smith (R-N.J.).
</P>
<P>
   A Senate bill sponsored by Sens. Don Nickles (R-Okla.) and
Joseph Lieberman (D-Conn.) allows the administration more
flexibility. The International Religious Freedom Act would require
the president to take action against countries determined to be
violating people's religious rights but does not invoke automatic
sanctions. It would establish a bipartisan commission to monitor
religious freedom and create a new ambassadorship-at-large for
religious liberty.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate is holding hearings on the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver Thomas, special counsel to the National Council of
Churches, said he supported some aspects of the House bill but
favors the Senate approach. In some cases, he said, automatic
sanctions might aggravate the situation of persecuted peoples.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think sanctions ought to be a matte of thoughtful, last
resort rather than a first resort,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Land of the Southern Baptist Convention testified at Senate
hearings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want the strongest bill that can be passed out of this
Congress and sent to the president,'' he said. ``We are not
demanding that other countries follow the First Amendment liberty
standards of the United States, as much as we believe they would
all benefit from doing so. What we are interested in is that all
the nations of the world live up to the United Nations Declaration
on Human Rights, which guarantees freedom of conscience. ... They
do not have the right to imprison people and to torture people and
to rape people and to crucify people and to enslave people because
of their religious faith _ and all those things are going on in
various parts of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Religious Liberty and
</P>
<P>
   Charitable Donations Act
</P>
<P>
   On June 19, President Clinton signed legislation overwhelmingly
passed by both houses of Congress to protect contributions to
charitable and religious organizations made by people who later
file for bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, known as the ``tithing bill,'' adds language to
the federal bankruptcy code ensuring that institutions cannot be
forced to give the contributions of a bankrupt donor to creditors.
It protects tithes and other contributions up to 15 percent of the
debtor's annual income.
</P>
<P>
   The bill was co-written by Rep. Ron Packard (R-Calif.) and Sen.
Charles Grassley (R-Iowa) in response to a case in which a
bankruptcy trustee demanded that the Crystal Evangelical Free
Church of Minneapolis return $13,450 donated by a couple the year
before they filed for bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   The act also gives debtors the right to tithe and make
charitable donations after declaring under Chapter 13 bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas of the National Council of Churches praised the new law.
In some cases, he said, churches had even been required to pay
penalties and interest on money they were given by people who later
went bankrupt.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can go out and squander your life savings on booze and
cigarettes and we don't set those transactions aside,'' he said.
``But give $1,000 to your local church and the church has to give
it back after they've already paid it to the preacher.''
</P>
<P>
   School Vouchers
</P>
<P>
   In a case that may make its way to the U.S. Supreme Court, the
Supreme Court of Wisconsin on June 10 said that public education
funds can be used for vouchers to religious schools.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling marks the first time a court of that level has upheld
the use of tax money for tuition at a religious primary or
secondary school.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the court overruled a lower court striking down
Gov. Tommy Thompson's plan to expand the Milwaukee Parental Choice
Program from 1,500 poor children in 23 nonreligious private schools
to 15,000 in either secular or parochial schools.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1990, Wisconsin has allowed some poor children to attend
private schools at state expense.
</P>
<P>
   If a government is providing school vouchers, parents should be
able to use them at religious schools, maintains Land of the
Southern Baptist Convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to empower more and more Americans to make the same
choice that President and Mrs. Clinton made,'' he said. ``They felt
it was best for their daughter to go to a Quaker school instead of
the public schools in Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   But Barry Lynn, an ordained minister in the United Church of
Christ and executive director of Americans United for Separation of
Church and State, said the Wisconsin ruling _ if it stands _ will
mean that ``all taxpayers will, in effect, be subsidizing the
religious education of some children. When you start taking money
from taxpayers' pockets and putting it in the collection plates of
religious schools, I think that is a major religious freedom
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas of the National Council of Churches characterized the
Wisconsin case as a ``gateway decision'' and a ``huge, huge
development.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, chairman of the local school board in his home town of
Maryville, Tenn., opposes school vouchers but acknowledges that a
well-drafted voucher plan can ``pass constitutional muster.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wisconsin decision, he said, is a signal that voucher
opponents can no longer rely on the courts to overturn voucher
plans but must fight the battle at the legislative level.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have to convince our legislators not that
vouchers are unconstitutional, but that they're bad public
policy,'' he said. ``We're going to have to win the debate on the
strength of the merits of our arguments.''
</P>
<P>
   Clergy Confidentiality
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago jailers in Oregon secretly taped a conversation
between a prisoner, Conan Wayne Hale, and a priest. An Oregon judge
denied the Catholic Church's request to destroy the tape, but a
prosecutor eventually agreed not to use it at Hale's murder trial.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, in the case of People vs. Burnidge, the Illinois
Supreme Court ruled that information in a sexual assault case
disclosed by the defendant to a Lutheran minister could be excluded
from evidence. The minister, the Rev. John E. Golisch, is also a
clinical psychologist. Under Illinois law, a psychologist is
required to report abuse and neglect, but a minister is not.
</P>
<P>
   And just this spring, a judge in Pierce County, Wash., ruled
that a minister must divulge the confidences of Scott Anthony
Martin, who was accused of killing his own 3-month-old son. The
minister, the Rev. Rich Hamlin, pastor of the Evangelical Reformed
Church, is appealing.
</P>
<P>
   The lower court based its decision on the reasoning that
Hamlin's church has no formal rite of confession, such as that of
the Roman Catholic Church.
</P>
<P>
   Stern of the American Jewish Congress says he sees a trend of
questioning the relationship between clergy and their parishioners.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last couple of years, there have been more important
priest-penitent privilege cases than in the 20 years I've been
here,'' he said. ``There's a greater willingness on the part of
government officials to press the envelope.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
