<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-BRAZIL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAZIL HAS RESPECT FOR DENMARK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Brazil should know what to expect when it meets Denmark Friday
night, and not just because the Danes conducted a lesson in soccer
tactics in a 4-1 victory over Nigeria in the second round of the
World Cup finals.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, Denmark took a 4-0 victory over Brazil in Copenhagen in
a tournament commemorating the 100th anniversary of the Dansk
Boldspil Union. The leader of the Danes was Michael Laudrup, who
made his first World Cup appearance at Mexico '86 and will make his
last international appearance during this tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Laudrup might not be essential for Denmark's success _ he
boycotted the team in a dispute with former coach Richard
Moeller-Nielsen when the Danes won the 1992 European Championships
_ but there are few more respected leaders in the game. Laudrup has
played in Holland, Italy, Japan, and Spain, where he is revered by
supporters of both Barcelona and Real Madrid.
</P>
<P>
   And he would have another extremely willing taker, if it were
possible, in Brazil coach Mario Zagallo, especially after Brazil's
first-round loss to Norway.
</P>
<P>
   Zagallo has tried 11 players as midfield choreographer since
1994. None have interpreted the role the way Laudrup has. Only
Juninho, who failed to recover from a broken leg for the World Cup,
seemed able to transform Brazil's 4-4-2 into an attacking 4-3-1-2
at the right time. Leonardo has the responsibility now, but Zagallo
has not been satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   ``Denmark has strong players, Michael Laudrup above all,''
Zagallo said earlier this week at training camp in Lesigny. ``In
Brazil, they think Denmark could be another Norway. However,
Denmark does not just kick the ball high. Denmark knows how to play
the short-passing game; they are much better technically.''
</P>
<P>
   Brazil has regained its confidence after a 4-1 victory over
Chile in which Dunga reasserted his leadership role and Ronaldo
scored twice. But Denmark will be a difficult opponent, with
Laudrup's younger brother, Brian, and young players such as Thomas
Helveg and Martin Jorgensen, who have been performing in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   The Danes have had their greatest success when perceived as
underdogs. The Danish Dynamite team at Mexico '86 bombed out after
first-round wins over Uruguay (6-1) and Germany (2-0). They were
last-minute replacements for Yugoslavia and won Euro '92 in Sweden,
and they have little pressure in this World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   They prepared for the Nigeria game by water skiing, relaxing on
the beach, and hanging out at the marina in Saint-Cyr-sur-Mer. They
then surprised the Nigerians by scoring twice in the first 12
minutes in one of the most dominating performances of the
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the first to be surprised for how we were able to play
against Nigeria,'' Laudrup said after the game. ``Usually, after
having scored a goal we close down in defense, but this time we
were able to command the whole field.''
</P>
<P>
   The Laudrup family has scored two of Denmark's seven goals. They
are the symbols of the Danes, sons of Finn Laudrup, a top player in
the country before players such as Allen Simonsen began making
their mark in the top professional leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Denmark might have a reputation for solidity and stoicism, but
this team is ``unpredictable,'' according to its Swedish coach, Bo
Johansson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We respect Brazil but only to a certain point,'' Johansson
said. ``If we would play with too much respect, we would not have
the possibility of winning.''
</P>
<P>
   The Brazilians, meanwhile, have their own problems.
</P>
<P>
   The absence of Romario has limited their attack, and replacement
Bebeto is being booed by the thousands of Brazilians who attend
games and practices here. A poll conducted by Folha de Sao Paulo
newspaper revealed 85 percent of respondents favored Bebeto's
replacement. Clearly, they would prefer the younger, more dynamic
Denilson.
</P>
<P>
   Zagallo, though, is staying with Bebeto.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zagallo is like the politicians,'' Bebeto told L'Equipe, the
French sports daily. ``He doesn't need to read the polls to lead.
He knows what to do and the best way to do it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
