<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8444 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-JAKES-COX     07-02 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-JAKES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    T.D. Jakes is a preacher who reaches across cultural lines
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JULY 4: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By John Blake
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before he became known as a bishop, T.D. Jakes had another
tittle, Bible Boy.
</P>
<P>
   People in Jakes' hometown of Charleston, W.Va., gave him the
nickname because Jakes always carried a Bible to high school and
preached to imaginary congregations.
</P>
<P>
   But there was a reason Jakes held his Bible so closely. He was
looking for answers. Only 16 at the time, Jakes was watching his
father slowly die of kidney disease at home. He had to shave, feed
and clean his father virtually every day for six years until Ernest
Jakes died in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found out the things that hurt us the most can become the
fuel and catalyst to propel us toward our destiny,'' Jakes said.
``Pain can make us bitter or better. I wanted to be made better.''
</P>
<P>
   Jakes, 41, no longer preaches to imaginary congregations. He is
expected to preach to at least 40,000 people at the Georgia Dome
Friday and Saturday for his ``Woman, Thou Art Loosed!'' conference.
The event coincides with the publication of Jakes' latest book,
``The Lady, Her Lover and Her Lord'' (G.P. Putnam's Sons, $19.95).
</P>
<P>
   Jakes has become the Oprah Winfrey of popular preachers. He is
black but easily reaches across racial, political and class lines.
His sermons combine fiery traditional black preaching, therapeutic
principles and earthy realism. And Jakes, like Winfrey, is not
afraid to talk about his personal struggles. (He recently waged a
public campaign to shed 100 pounds.)
</P>
<P>
   The formula has made Jakes one of the most popular preachers in
America. His television show, ``Get Ready with T.D. Jakes,'' airs
three times a week on Black Entertainment Television and the
Trinity Broadcasting Network. Jakes has written nine books which
have landed on the national Christian best-seller's list, including
``Woman, Thou Art Loosed!'' (G.P. Putnam's Sons, $19.95), which
sold 1.25 million copies.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Franklin, president of the Interdenominational
Theological Center in Atlanta, recalled watching Jakes preach one
broadcast from a prison courtyard, where he deftly explored how men
are damaged by childhood sexual abuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was riveted to the television screen,'' Franklin said. ``He
did it with great sensitivity and care. If someone can do this kind
of therapeutic work in a religious context, I want to affirm it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jakes instinctively goes after people the traditional church
ignores. His books and sermons have focused on the problems of and
been written for convicts, women and troubled youths, and have
dealt with the pressures ministers and their spouses face.
</P>
<P>
   Lorycq Mosley, a 36-year-old Atlanta woman who plans on
attending this week's conference, said Jakes is a man of
compassion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love that man,'' said Mosley. ``God has given him an
anointing to liberate women and men from past hurts and abuse. I
believe he delivers people in those areas that no one talks about,
but he does.''
</P>
<P>
   Jakes said his sensitivity comes from a difficult childhood. His
father's death had a dramatic impact on his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``To lose him right in the middle of my adolescence was
devastating,'' he said in a recent phone interview. ``It caused me
to take my life more seriously than other people my age.''
</P>
<P>
   A year after his father's death, Jakes said God came to him in a
dream and called him to preach. Jakes started preaching on street
corners until he found his first congregation, a storefront church.
It had 10 members. Today his church in Dallas, The Potter's House,
is one of the fastest-growing mega-churches in the country. It has
gained 14,000 members in the last 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   Jakes' notoriety has grown along with his church. People as
diverse as NFL star Deion Sanders and Texas Gov. George Bush have
endorsed his ministry. Yet Jakes has been careful not to be too
narrowly defined.
</P>
<P>
   He refuses to reveal his political affiliation and didn't
participate in the Million Man March in Washington in 1995 because
of theological differences with Nation of Islam Minster Louis
Farrakhan. And he consistently points out his church is multiracial
and nondenominational.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to be in a box and speak to one people,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Jakes' family life today is good, he still must deal
with the pain that is part of living. He and his wife, Serita, have
five children. But recently, Jakes' mother, Odith, fell ill with a
brain tumor.
</P>
<P>
   Jakes said his faith sometimes falters when he visits his mother
in the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel like Bishop Jakes when I'm in the hospital room
with her,'' he said. ``I feel like her baby boy, Tommy.''
</P>
<P>
   He's received death threats from hate groups because of the
multiracial makeup of his church. Despite that kind of hassle,
Jakes has no plans to slow down his preaching schedule.
</P>
<P>
   He still talks like Bible Boy, a smalltown kid who found comfort
and his calling in the Bible's ancient promises.
</P>
<P>
   ``God has blessed me beyond my imagination,'' he said. ``I had
an insatiable thirst for the word of God. Those wells that I dug
became cisterns of living water that other people came to drink.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
