<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-RIVALS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANCE, ITALY, OLD RIVALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAINT-DENIS, France _ Nobody wants to play this match. Not this
early. Not in the quarterfinals. ``I'm very disappointed that we
have to play against France,'' Italian midfielder Enrico Chiesa
says. ``It's the final before the event.''
</P>
<P>
   The Germans, who get the winner if they beat the Croats Saturday
might dispute that. But there's no doubt that someone will be going
home from the Stade de France Friday night earlier than they'd
planned.
</P>
<P>
   The French, who needed a ``golden goal'' in overtime against
Paraguay to get here, were hoping at least to make it to the
semifinals, which they managed the last two times they qualified
for the tournament. ``I have only one wish,'' says playmaker
Zinedine Zidane, back in the lineup after sitting out two matches
for his expulsion against Saudi Arabia. ``That the adventure
continue.''
</P>
<P>
   The Italians, who lost the last Cup on penalty kicks, will
consider it a failure if they can't at least get a rematch with the
Brazilians here a week from Sunday. ``I truly believe that the team
which wins this match will make it to the final,'' says keeper
Gianluca Pagliuca.
</P>
<P>
   So these old neighbors, these old blue-shirted rivals _ the
Bleus and the Azzurri _ are prepared to go 120 minutes and beyond
if they have to. ``Only one thing matters to the Italians and
that's winning, no matter how,'' says French captain Didier
Deschamps, who plays for Juventus in Italy's Serie A.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Azzurri (17-6-7) have dominated a rivalry that goes
back to 1910, the Bleus are 3-0-1 with three shutouts in their last
four meetings, including the ``perfect game'' they threw at Italy
in the second round in 1986. And France will be playing in its
national stadium before 80,000 people _ most of whom will be
wearing red, white, and blue. ``France is favored,'' concedes
Italian defender Moreno Torricelli, ``but I think we'll win.''
</P>
<P>
   The French have only allowed one goal (a penalty by Denmark) in
four matches, but they haven't faced a team of Italy's quality or a
striker like Christian Vieri, who's scored five goals in the
tournament, including the killer finish that beat Norway and got
the Azzurri here.
</P>
<P>
   The French, who rely on a grudging defense and an opportunistic
midfield to beat people, have nobody like Vieri, and it worries
them. But at least they'll have Zidane, who watched in torment from
the bench as his mates sweated blood to beat the Paraguayans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very hard, terrible even,'' says Zidane, who was 14 the
last time France played in the Cup and feared that this one might
end without him. ``The longer the match went on, the longer I
suffered. Now, this match is the most important of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Italians can shut down Zidane, they think they'll win,
especially since attackers Christophe Dugarry and Thierry Henry and
midfielder Emmanuel Petit are all gimpy. Neither Zidane nor most of
his mates are any mystery to the Azzurri _ seven French players,
including most of their stars, play for Italian clubs, where their
teammates call them `galeti' (little roosters). ``They hold no
secrets for us,'' says Italian coach Cesare Maldini.
</P>
<P>
   Nor do the Italians for the French. They know the Vieris and
Baggios and DiBiagios by heart and they know the ``kings of 1-0''
will play them the same way they play everybody else _ with a
classic counterattacking style that waits for a mistake and pounces
on it. ``All they want is one master stroke for a goal,'' says
Zidane. ``And then, it's `I'm closing the box.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Italians did that against the Norwegians, who'd beaten the
Brazilians with two late goals. The French, who know something
about countering themselves, are prepared to play that way, too. It
will be, predicts defender Laurent Blanc, ``un grand rendez-vous.''
They'd just rather have had it next weekend.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
