<SLUG> BC-SPOT-BUDGET-BOS </SLUG>
  
 For Release FRIDAY AMs, July 3, 1998  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following stories for use by
NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta  &LR; at the
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of graphics
or photos please call 212 556-4204 or -1927.
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HONGKONG-CLINTON (Hong Kong) _ President Clinton to emphasize
the need for direct elections and full democracy, something the
territory never had in 156 years of British rule. By Indira A.R.
Lakshmanan. 1300 words.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-CLINTON (Yucun, China) -- President travels to the
tranquil Li River, a tiny farming and fishing village of some 500
peole tucked amid the storybook limestone hills of Guilin. By Brian
McGrory. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   IRELAND-CHURCHES (Belfast) -- Ten Catholic churches are set on
fire, presumably by Protestant extremists bent on wrecking the new
peace in Northern Ireland. By Kevin Cullen. 700 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON (w) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FRANK-PARTNER (Washington) -- US Rep. Barney Frank says his long
relationship with partner Herb Moses helped him grow emotionally
and become a more responsible public servant. By Bob Hohler. 900
words. (w and a coding)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-TESTS (Geneva) -- A proposal to have 300
physician-volunteers take an AIDS vaccine made from a live but
weakened form of the HIV virus triggers a heated debate. By Richard
A. Knox. 900 words. (a and i coding)
</P>
<P>
   CNN-NERVEGAS (Undated) -- Less than a month after reporting that
the United States had used nerve gas during a secret 1970 mission
in Laos to kill American defectors, CNN retracts the story. By Mark
Jurkowitz. 800 words. (a and e coding)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-PLAN (Undated) -- Bowing to international pressure, Japan
to implement a ``total plan'' to close insolvent banks and protect
depositors by putting up as much as $30 trillion yen. By Kimberly
Blanton. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   WINDOWS98-PROBLEMS (Undated) -- Windows 98 experiences some
problems. Compaq and Toshiba have posted warnings on their Web
sites telling users not to install W98 on certain PCs they make. By
Hiawatha Bray. 500 words.
</P>
<P>
   BANKBOS-CARRASCO (Boston) -- BankBoston chief says the bank has
disciplined some 20 employees, firing several, in the wake of the
Carrasco scandal. He calls the episode painful and embarrassing and
insists again that Carrasco acted alone. By Steven Fainaru. 800
words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (s) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SOC-WORLDCUP-FRANCE (Saint-Denis, France) -- The French have
never won the Cup, haven't even reached the final. If they can at
least get past the Italians and Germans and get a date with
champion Brazil, Les Bleus will have made history. By John Powers.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   SOC-WORLDCUP-RIVALS (Saint-Denis, France) _ These old
blue-shirted rivals are prepared to go 120 minutes and beyond if
they have to. By John Powers.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   SOC-WORLDCUP-BRAZIL (Undated) -- Brazil should know what to
expect when it meets Denmark. By Frank Dell'Apa.
</P>
<P>
   TEN-WIMBLEDON (London) -- The question from the media member was
asked not once, but twice, of Jana Notovna, whether her 6-4, 6-4
win over defending Wimbledon champion Martina Hingis was her finest
singles outing ever. By Jim Greenidge.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN (London) -- The New Wave got washed away,
beached, and Jana and Nathalie, seeded 3 and 16, find themselves in
one of the least expected finals ever. By Bud Collins.
</P>
<P>
   BBA-EXPOS-REDSOX (Boston) _ By Gordon Edes.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   BBA-RYAN-COLUMN (Boston) _ By Bob Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   GLF-WOM-OPEN (Kohler, Wis.) -- By Jim McCabe.
</P>
<P>
   GLF-GHO (Cromwell, Conn.) -- By Joe Concannon.
</P>
