<HEADER>
A8465 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-FRANCE-B     07-02 1190
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-FRANCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR FRANCE, WINNING IS A NOBLE CAUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAINT-DENIS, France _ ``So, then, who will win the match between
France and Italie?'', an elegant grandmere asked a foreigner over
her lunchtime rabbit at the Cafe des Federations in Lyon the other
day. ``France,'' she was told. ``Really?'' she replied, in
semi-disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   It has been so long since the French soccer team won a big match
that the very idea raises Gallic eyebrows. What the people are used
to is failure. Noble, even stylish failure, but failure.
</P>
<P>
   Beating the Italians in Friday's World Cup quarterfinals in the
Stade de France will be a challenge. Winning the Cup here a week
from Sunday, with president Jacques Chirac watching from the
stands, would be ``un reve'' _ a dream.
</P>
<P>
   What the French are accustomed to from their Bleus (from their
blue jerseys) in the World Cup is ``un cauchemar'' _ a nightmare.
The loss to Germany on penalty kicks in the 1982 semifinals after
leading, 3-1, in overtime. The loss to Germany in the 1986
semifinals after beating Brazil and Italy. Failing to qualify for
the 1990 tournament. Failing to qualify again last time by losing
to the Israelis after they'd already popped the champagne at
halftime, then losing again to the Bulgarians in the final seconds.
</P>
<P>
   So even though the French are playing at home on a free pass
with an easy draw in familiar stadia packed with their own fans
(the organizing committee, headed by former star Michel Platini,
made sure of that), everyone from Normandy to Languedoc is crossing
his fingers.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, all the advantages that come with home cookin' have
just jacked up the pressure and the anxiety on the hosts. ``France
is the team to beat,'' Italian goalkeeper Gianluca Pagliuca
proclaimed. ``If they can't win this time, I don't believe they'll
ever win it.''
</P>
<P>
   The French have never won the Cup, haven't even reached the
final. If they can at least get past the Italians and Germans and
get a date with champion Brazil, Les Bleus will have made history.
``To enter into football legend,'' says midfielder Youri Djorkaeff,
``we must qualify for the final.''
</P>
<P>
   That would make up for the shock of 1982, which still makes
Frenchmen grind their teeth. Even after German keeper Harald
Schumacher had leveled Patrick Battiston with a flying elbow to the
face and gone unpunished _ regarded as one of the greatest
injustices in Cup history _ the French managed to get the match
into overtime and (incroyable!) go up by two goals.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, the Germans managed to draw even and won in a shootout
that left Les Bleus weeping on the field and their countrymen in
shock. The disappointment and the bitterness endures. When
L'Equipe, the French sporting daily, sent a writer across the
border last month to do a retrospective, Karl-Heinz Forster, who
played for the Germans that day, greeted him with: ``So, how's
Monsieur Battiston doing?''
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, the French came to Mexico with a better team
and the Germans took them out cold, 2-0. No elbows, no shootouts.
ADIOS MUCHACHOS, a headline said back home.
</P>
<P>
   So if their countrymen express surprise that Les Bleus are
favored in a big one, it's that history has taught them to expect
the worst. Even though the French have been playing soccer since
1872 (Jules Rimet and Henri Delaunay actually concocted the World
Cup), they've achieved relatively little, even on the Continent.
They've won one European title (in 1984, as hosts) and their clubs
lost six Champions Cup finals before Olympique Marseille won in
1993. Their best players (captain Didier Deschamps, Zinedine
Zidane, Djorkaeff, Lilian Thuram) play for Italian clubs.
</P>
<P>
   Soccer has never inspired the fever here that it has in Italy,
in Germany, in England, in Spain. The French had to build the
80,000-seat Stade de France because they didn't have a stadium big
enough to stage the final. Platini, exasperated by the lack of
cooperation from the government, from corporations, from unions
during the buildup to the tournament, threw up his hands. ``France
hasn't really understood the importance of the World Cup,'' he
sighed.
</P>
<P>
   The Coupe du Monde falls somewhere behind wine, cheese, amour,
smoking, and the Tour de France among national passions.
Three-quarters of women polled said that they could care less about
the Cup _ but that it would be a pity if Les Bleus didn't win it.
So despite the insouciance, there is an undeniable burden on the
national team. ``There has been a huge amount of pressure on us
right from the start of the World Cup,'' coach Aime Jacquet
acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   Beating South Africa, 3-0, and Saudi Arabia, 4-0, only jacked up
expectations. When the French edged the Danes to win their group _
and got unknown Paraguay instead of feared Nigeria in the second
round (``YOU SAID PARAGUAY?'' a headline wondered) _ ``le reve''
began in earnest. ``Even I am beginning to dream,'' acknowledged
Chirac, who's been taping the matches on his VCR.
</P>
<P>
   But the Paraguay match was a purgatory. With playmaker Zidane
sitting out the match because he'd taken a stupid red card against
the Saudis, Les Bleus struggled. They ended up locked in a
scoreless draw (``They looked paralyzed,'' Italian coach Cesare
Maldini observed) that went into overtime, where defender Laurent
Blanc won it with a golden goal.
</P>
<P>
   LA DELIVRANCE, L'Equipe proclaimed, saying that a loss to the
Paraguayans would have been ``une immense catastrophe.'' In the
locker room, the French players embraced in joy and relief. ``We
had tears in our eyes,'' said Djorkaeff. ``Nobody could speak.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mondiale, keeper Fabien Barthez said, has been an emotional
roller coaster for Les Bleus. After a dozen years off the world
stage, nobody knew what to expect from them, especially after a
blah 1-0 victory over Finland in a tuneup days before the
tournament. Trying to win the Cup with this team, playing this way,
a French columnist mused, was like trying to climb Everest in
espadrilles.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the blowout of the South Africans amid a howling
Mistral in the opener in Marseille, with 60,000 fans singing `La
Marseillaise'. ``The public, like the wind, swept us along,'' said
midfielder Emmanuel Petit. Then came the advancement, then La
Delivrance.
</P>
<P>
   And now? ``Everybody's expecting to see us in the final against
Brazil,'' says Deschamps. ``But don't forget, there are other
matches to be won.''
</P>
<P>
   Italie, everyone agrees, will be ``un match dur.'' Even though
France hasn't lost to the neighbors since 1978. Even though the
Italians have struggled here, too. Even though Djorkaeff has
declared: ``This World Cup belongs to us.''
</P>
<P>
   The French may have dreamed it up, but the Cup has always been
that for them _ a dream _ and they expect to suffer mightily for
it. Beating the Italians here merely gets them the Germans, whom
the French haven't defeated in Cup play in 40 years. That's why the
elegant grandmeres raise their eyebrows when you tell them France
will win a big one. So, how's Monsieur Battiston doing?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
