reports that Harvard tests with a similar virus on monkeys caused
disease and death. By RUTH SoRELLE.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   US-MEXICO (Brownsville, Texas) _ The attorneys general of the
United States and Mexico meet along the border to sign letters to
Presidents Bill Clinton and Ernesto Zedillo calling for closer
consultation and cooperation in drug and money-laundering
investigations that involve both nations. By JOHN MacCORMACK.
(Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   BURNED-BOY (Spendora, Texas) _ Robert Middleton, the 8-year-old
boy who was doused with gasoline and burned over 99 percent of his
body, has told investigators that the teen-ager he had named as his
attacker was not the guilty one. He said a 15-year-old boy doused
him with gasoline and set him ablaze, but that he was afraid of him
and gave the other name out of fear. By PAUL McKAY and STEVE
OLAFSON.
</P>
<P>
   OYSTERS-RECALL (Galveston, Texas) _ The number of people who
have become ill from eating raw Galveston Bay oysters is up to 245
now, making this the worst outbreak of Vibrio parahaemolyticus in
U.S. history. Last year, some 200 cases were reported in Washington
state. By CINDY HORSWELL.
</P>
<P>
   ALYDAR-CONVICTION (Houston) _ A former groom is convicted of
lying to a grand jury investigating the 1990 death of the famed
race horse Alydar, raising the possibility that more indictments
will spring from a bank fraud case. By DEBORAH TEDFORD.
</P>
<P>
   JUMBO-FUNERAL (Austin, Texas) _ Ben Dodson Atwell, a former
state representative from Dallas and chairman of the House tax
committee, is buried in the state cemetery beneath a tombstone of
his own design _ a pink granite, Texas-shaped marker bearing his
name and the inscription ``Lawyer-Legislator. Author of tax bill.''
Atwell died Monday in Austin at age 82. By ALLAN TURNER. (Already
filed)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
