<HEADLINE>
ANNAN SAYS NIGERIA WILL FREE POLITICAL PRISONERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ps) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan said Thursday
that Nigeria's new military government pledged to release all
remaining political prisoners, among them Moshood K.O. Abiola, who
was jailed after apparently winning the presidential election in
1993.
</P>
<P>
   Annan made the announcement at a news conference in Abuja, the
Nigerian capital, after meeting with the country's president, Gen.
Abdulsalam Abubakar.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm leaving Nigeria with the stage set for the release of all
political detainees,'' Annan said. ``The government will make an
announcement at the appropriate time.''
</P>
<P>
   No official government announcement followed Annan's remarks
Thursday. But in London, Wura Abiola, one of Abiola's daughters,
said that she believed his release was imminent.
</P>
<P>
   Abiola agreed to drop his claim to the presidency based on the
1993 vote, which the government annulled, Annan said Thursday
before leaving Abuja for Ghana. Abiola apparently has made no
promises about future elections, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found him more realistic than some of us outside,'' said
Annan, who met Abiola on Tuesday. ``Chief Abiola realizes that a
lot has changed.'' Annan said that Nigerians appeared to want new,
democratic elections.
</P>
<P>
   A vote had been scheduled for Aug. 1, but only one name was on
the ballot, Gen. Sani Abacha, the former military ruler, who died
suddenly on June 8. Abubakar has said that he would turn over power
to an elected civilian government by Oct. 1, in keeping with the
timetable set by Abacha. The government has not announced whether
the August election date is firm and whether it would allow genuine
opposition candidates to run.
</P>
<P>
   In London, Ms. Abiola, a management consultant, said that her
father would need time to get back in touch with his family and
with politics, and take time to reflect on his future political
career. Abiola had been denied reading material in prison and was
kept as isolated as possible from even his relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Abiola had four wives and four sets of children. All have united
in campaigning for his release. One of his wives, Kudirat Abiola,
was gunned down execution-style while working to have her husband
released.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Abiola said that family members have taken note of reports
that Abiola has renounced his presidential claim, but want to hear
the decision from him, and they want him to be given some breathing
space to decide what to do next.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to be very happy to see my father and start to
rebuild on a personal level all those dimensions in my father's
life and our lives,'' she said. ``We have to see that we get more
than a promise, that we actually get him home and can see him and
talk to him. Nothing will substitute for hearing his words and
understanding where he is coming from.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He has to get in touch with all the relevant Nigerian
parties,'' she said. ``Only after that can he make a decision. The
Nigerian people will start to express what they desire out of my
father in the month after his release. It's only after he weighs
the different demands, after he understands the different
implications, that he can then re-evaluate his position. Hopefully
the people will give him time to take stock.''
</P>
<P>
   Abiola, a wealthy businessman from southern Nigeria who is a
Yoruba and a Muslim, could still face difficulties if he decided to
run in a new election because the all-powerful military is
dominated by northerners.
</P>
<P>
   But some moderates in the military establishment have apparently
come to realize that Abiola cannot be sidelined indefinitely and
will have to be brought into the political process at some point if
Nigeria is to move toward a more democratic system.
</P>
<P>
   Southern Nigerians have borne much of the military government's
repression. In 1995, a group of nine southern environmental
activists, including the playwright Ken Saro-Wiwa, were executed
for opposing development of their region. Nigeria, Africa's richest
and potentially most powerful country, already under some
international sanctions for annulling the 1993 vote, was suspended
from the Commonwealth because of the executions.
</P>
<P>
   The secretary-general of the Commonwealth, Emeka Anyaoku, a
Nigerian based in London, said Thursday that he expected Abubakar
to outline a democratic program for Nigeria that will allow the
country to be readmitted.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, State Department spokesman James Rubin welcomed
the news about prisoner releases and said that a high-level
American delegation would be going to Nigeria this weekend for
meetings with Abubakar.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a week, Nigerians have suspected that talks may
have been going on with Abiola. Annan's visit may have provided the
opportunity to make a public breakthrough in his case, diplomats
said.
</P>
<P>
   The government of Abubakar has already freed 26 other political
prisoners, including Gen. Olusegun Obasanjo, a former military
ruler who turned over government to civilians in the 1970s. In
1995, he was imprisoned by Abacha for campaigning again for
civilian government. Human rights groups estimate that Nigeria is
still holding between 150 and 250 political prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   Some Nigerians have suggested that Abiola may be encouraged by
followers to reinstate his claim to the presidency after being
freed. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
