<SLUG> BC-DISASTERFILMS-GOTHAM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Neither monsters nor meteors can bring Big Apple to its knees
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JULY 5: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   New York, New York, it's a wonderful town.
</P>
<P>
   The filming's up, and the buildings are down.
</P>
<P>
   Finito. Wiped out like some out-of-town pedestrian caught in the
cross hairs of a careening Checker Cab.
</P>
<P>
   And to think it happened right before our eyes. In
``Armageddon,'' the latest summer blockbuster, meteor-spawned
mayhem includes everything from caved-in subway tunnels to a
decapitated Chrysler Building.
</P>
<P>
   All this, just when the city had managed to put itself back
together again after ``Godzilla's'' late May rampage. Even then,
Gothamites were still knocking the water from their ears, courtesy
of ``Deep Impact's'' April tidal wave.
</P>
<P>
   You get the point. Fast food tie-ins and way-too-loud Surround
Sound still count, but it seems the top item for this summer's
biggest movies is a soon-to-be-obliterated New York City setting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you get a taste for it, it's a very hard thing not to
do,'' admitted ``Godzilla'' co-writer and producer Dean Devlin.
``It's quite addictive.''
</P>
<P>
   What Devlin considers a sort of backhanded compliment to New
York _ disaster films work best when destroying instantly
recognizable, incredibly powerful cities, after all _ isn't an
entirely new phenomenon. His own ``Independence Day'' took out New
York two years ago. And ``King Kong'' attacked the Empire State
Building way back in 1933.
</P>
<P>
   But this is a prolonged pummeling of the sort that's got some
New Yorkers _ hold onto your hats _ almost at a loss for words.
</P>
<P>
   Almost.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was like `a-w-w-W-W-W'!'' ``Godzilla'' actor and Queens
native Hank Azaria recalled about seeing his lumbering co-star
flatten Madison Square Garden and other local landmarks. ``I love
this city, and they made it look so real that it actually was
disturbing to me.''
</P>
<P>
   You want disturbing? The art deco-style Chrysler Building has
gone from the ``Godzilla'' frying pan directly into the
``Armageddon'' fire, getting destroyed on-screen twice within a
mere six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't compliment me, but it doesn't make me nervous
either,'' said Sol Bissu, who works at Chrysler Camera in the
needle-nosed skyscraper. ``It's true almost anything can happen in
New York. But not that.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, New York's tabloid Daily News was nervous enough when
``Godzilla'' was released to report on how the city would handle an
attack by a 200-foot lizard. Call in King Kong, joked the emergency
management director, sounding almost like he was enjoying this.
</P>
<P>
   Well, why not? Moviemaking in New York is up about 35 percent
from five years ago. Meanwhile, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's office
suggests that all those celluloid monsters and meteors aren't
attacking New York so much as reinforcing its image as a vibrant
mecca for all sorts of overachievers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's only natural that filmmakers would choose to set and film
their movies in the most famous, exciting and diverse city in the
world,'' said deputy press secretary Dwight Williams. ``No matter
what the disaster, it gives us great exposure.''
</P>
<P>
   Azaria, for one, doesn't sound entirely convinced.
</P>
<P>
   ``I imagine,'' he sighed, ``some people will cheer at New York
being so rampaged.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
