<TEXT>
<P>
   (pr) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Friday, July 3. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (212-556-1927).
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-ECON (Tokyo) _ The government announces a long-awaited
plan to clear away the nation's pile of bad debt in hopes of
bolstering global confidence in Japan and setting its economy on
track for growth. By Sheryl WuDunn.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-REPUBS (Washington) _ Even before President Clinton's
return from China, many prominent Republicans concede that the trip
has been a political success that could deprive their party of a
potent election-year issue. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   FLA-FIRES (Ormond Beach, Fla.) _ At least 80 homes and other
buildings were burned overnight, 35,000 people were evacuated, and
the fires ravaging two counties were only expected to get bigger
Thursday. By Mireya Navarro.
</P>
<P>
   CNN-NERVE-GAS (Undated) _ CNN retracts its story that the U.S.
military used deadly nerve gas during a Vietnam-era mission in Laos
to kill American defectors, apologizing for ``serious faults'' in
its reporting. By Felicity Barringer.
</P>
<P>
   CLIMBING-MT-MCKINLEY (Talkeetna, Alaska) _ The cemetery in this
risk-lover's domain should be enough to keep most people from
trying to stand atop the High One, as Athabaskan natives call Mount
McKinley. The climbers come from all over the world, drawn to the
highest point in North America, and they end up with their names on
granite here _ 118 dead over the last 65 years. But there is no
sense of horror or defeat in the summer shadows. After nearly a
monthlong disappearance behind a cloak of mist and storms, the
mountain is out. So, even though three people have died so far this
climbing season, McKinley is more of a lure than ever. By Timothy
Egan. With photo. (MOVED)
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-BLAIR (Belfast, Northern Ireland) _ Arsonists believed
to be members of a dissident Protestant group set fire to 10 Roman
Catholic churches in Northern Ireland, setting off fears that wider
sectarian violence might return to in the British province. By
James F. Clarity. (MOVED)
</P>
<P>
   NIGERIA (United Nations) _ Nigeria's new military government
pledges to release all remaining political prisoners,
Secretary-General Kofi Annan says after after meeting with the
country's president, Gen. Abdulsalam Abubakar. By Barbara
Crossette. (MOVED)
</P>
<P>
   Reefers:
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ The hot economy is showing definite
signs of cooling, but by only a few degrees. By Sylvia Nasar.
</P>
<P>
   MARINE-JET-CRASH (Washington) _ Failures by the Marine Corps and
the Air Force to disseminate crucial information cast ``substantial
doubt'' on whether the captain of a plane that hit a ski lift cable
in the Italian alps in February could be convicted in a
court-martial, a hearing officer finds in a report. By Matthew L.
Wald.
</P>
