<HEADER>
A8481 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLAFIRES-HISTORY03-CO     07-02 0480
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLAFIRES-HISTORY03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FIRES ARE FLORIDA'S WORST, BUT NOT NATION'S
 &HT;    By SAMAR ABULHASSAN
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The wildfires raging in Florida may be the worst in
the state's history, emergency fire officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the worst episode of fires in a drought situation
we've ever seen,'' said Barbara Doran, spokeswoman for the Florida
State Emergency Operations Center. ``The record-breaking
temperatures, the dry weather and high winds have led to a very
serious disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   The blazes that continue to spread through Florida have consumed
more than 280,000 acres since June 1, according to Jack Conner, an
information officer for the U.S. Forest Service. Only half as much
acreage is destroyed statewide in an average full year.
</P>
<P>
   Florida has had more than 1,900 separate wildfires since the end
of May, and at least 96 homes and 57 other buildings have been
burned.
</P>
<P>
   Only one event in Florida's wildfire history even compares,
Conner said. On May 17, 1985, in an event that became known as
``Black Friday,'' about 100,000 acres were charred, 143 homes were
destroyed and more than than 400 buildings were damaged.
</P>
<P>
   But this year's fires have lasted much longer than any previous
year's and are much more widespread, officials said. Nearly every
county in the state has reported an outbreak.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the National Interagency Fire Center (NIFC), which
tracks wildfires and publishes the monthly fire threat for the
entire United States, said Thursday that while the total loss of
acreage in the Florida fires so far is not unusually high, the fact
that tens of thousands of people are being evacuated and property
is being damaged increases the severity of the event.
</P>
<P>
   In Southern California, where seasonal wildfires regularly
consume expensive homes in one of the nation's largest media
markets, the disasters regularly become a national spectacle.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, in 1969 one rash of fires in Idaho took 219,000
acres and another incident in Nevada burned 150,000 acres. But
there was little or no property loss in those incidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``When there isn't property or lives at stake, you almost stand
back and watch, `` said Lorraine Buck, spokeswoman for the Boise,
Idaho-based NIFC. ``There are people's homes burning, so there's
national sympathy.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Florida fires dominate the network newscasts, at least
15 major blazes are continuing to spread at scattered sites
elsewhere, including Texas, Colorado, New Mexico, Arizona and
Alaska. There are nearly 4,300 firefighters battling fires
nationwide, according to the NIFC.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, the NIFC tracked more than 33,000 wildfires in
the United States through June 29. Nearly 742,000 acres have been
burned.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
