<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8486 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRELAND-CHURCHES-BOS &LR;      07-02 0613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-CHURCHES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAIR CONDEMNS ATTACKS ON 10 CATHOLIC CHURCHES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST _ British Prime Minister Tony Blair came to Northern
Ireland Thursday to condemn arson attacks on 10 Catholic churches
and to seek a compromise over a disputed parade that is expected to
cause trouble Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Police believe that acts of arson across Northern Ireland early
Thursday were a coordinated effort by Protestant extremists. Three
of the churches were destroyed. Police suspect the the Loyalist
Volunteer Force, a Protestant paramilitary group, but in a
statement the group denied involvement.
</P>
<P>
   As he surveyed the damage at St. James Church near Aldergrove
Airport on his arrival, Blair condemned the attacks and tried to
comfort one of the parish priests, the Rev. John Burns.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the past,'' Blair told reporters, indicating the
rubble. As he was departing, he said he was leaving the past for
``the future,'' his first visit to the Northern Ireland Assembly
after its inaugural sitting on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Blair was at Castle Buildings at Stormont, where last April he
presided over his most important achievement as prime minister _
the signing of the Good Friday political settlement in Northern
Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   But Blair's hastily arranged visit suggests he fears the
progress marked by the agreement is threatened by increasing
tension over Sunday's expected confrontation between Protestants
and Catholics in Portadown, 30 miles southwest of Belfast.
</P>
<P>
   Even President Clinton is involved in the behind-the-scenes
efforts to avert violence there. In an interview, John Hume, the
moderate Catholic nationalist leader, said Clinton had called him
from China ``asking if there was anything he could do.'' White
House officials confirmed that Clinton has been telephoning various
people in Northern Ireland, pleading for compromise.
</P>
<P>
   The Parades Commission that was created by Blair's
administration to arbitrate the thorny issue of Protestant parades
passing through Catholic neighborhoods has barred the Orange Order
from marching down the Catholic Garvaghy Road on Sunday. Catholic
nationalists consider the parade offensive.
</P>
<P>
   The Orangemen, named for William of Orange, an Ulster Protestant
hero, have vowed to defy that ban and say they will gather en masse
until they are allowed to follow the same route they have trod each
year since 1807. There have been standoffs the last three years and
widespread rioting the last two after residents were beaten off the
Garvaghy Road by police so that Orangemen could march.
</P>
<P>
   Even before Blair arrived, there was a flurry of
behind-the-scenes mediation going on, as the two new leaders of the
Assembly, First Minister David Trimble and his deputy, Seamus
Mallon, brought in leading clergymen and Orangemen in an attempt to
work out a compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Blair used the opportunity to congratulate Trimble and Mallon
and to pose with them for photographers. While Blair told reporters
he was not here to negotiate the parade ban, Downing Street
officials had earlier said the prime minister would only go to
Northern Ireland if he thought there was a chance of resolving the
looming confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   But on the Garvaghy Road, residents complained they were being
left out of the loop. Breandan Mac Cionnaith, the leader of the
residents' group, said no one had involved them in the secret
talks. Irish government officials talked to Mac Cionnaith Wednesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Trimble had accompanied Catholic and Protestant
churchmen to St. James, where he called the arson attacks ``an
appalling act.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
