<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 19:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8501 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COX-CHINA-CLINTON-MAI     07-02 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-CHINA-CLINTON-MAIN-03 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    CLINTON SET TO MEET HONG KONG DEMOCRATIC LEADERS
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: This story will be updated around 10:30 p.m. EDT following
Clinton speech. 
 &HT;    By MARCIA KUNSTEL and JOSEPH ALBRIGHT 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service (at)
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ President Clinton's low-key meetings on Friday with
Hong Kong opposition legislators will be his only chance to hear
critics of the ruling Chinese communist party regime during his
nine-day trip to China.
</P>
<P>
   Preparing to fly home late Friday for a Fourth of July greeting
at Andrews Air Force Base outside Washington at dawn on Saturday,
Clinton spoke about how Hong Kong's still limited democracy can
inspire the long-term future for the rest of China.
</P>
<P>
   In a dinner toast a few hours after arriving here Thursday
night, Clinton said the future ``will be difficult, but most of it
will be very good'' if China is able to ``stay on the right side of
history.'' He referred to his remarks last fall when he told
President Jiang Zemin that defending China's 1989 crackdown on
democracy advocates put him on the wrong side of history.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was exchanging toasts with Tung Chee-hwa, the
Beijing-appointed chief executive of Hong Kong who immediately
abolished the elected legislature last summer, when Britain turned
its one-time colony back to Chinese control after more than 150
years of British rule.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Clinton was scheduled to meet privately with the
leader of Hong Kong's Democratic Party, Martin Lee, and other
democratic activists who are working for multi-party democracy in
the only bit of China where any high-level democratic elections are
permitted.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, a fiery lawyer, told journalists: ``I was impressed by the
president's joint press conference with Jiang Zemin and believe the
fact that it was televised live in China was a significant
development for the Chinese people.''
</P>
<P>
   Even here, only one third of the Legislative Council members are
elected now. The rest are appointed by pro-Beijing professional and
social groups.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's talks with members of what in Hong Kong is a tolerated
opposition fall short of qualifying as a meeting with dissidents.
The White House vacillated in the days before Clinton left on his
China tour about whether the president would have face-to-face
talks with any dissidents who face arrest or labor camp terms for
speaking out against Communist Party rule.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, Clinton met neither with political dissidents
nor with leaders of China's burgeoning underground churches.
</P>
<P>
   His ostensible objective was to insulate dissidents living in
China from being harassed in the future. However, clearly another
part of the calculation was trying to spare his Chinese official
hosts from the negative publicity that would attend such a meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The White House even tried to downplay the meetings with Lee and
others in Hong Kong's elected opposition, refusing to allow
American or Chinese television to film any part of the sessions.
</P>
<P>
   Especially in Hong Kong, Clinton could have met some of the most
effective human rights monitors keeping track of what is happening
to dissidents on the mainland.
</P>
<P>
   Lu Si Qing, for example, runs a shoestring operation called
International Centre of Human Rights and Democratic Movements in
China, which reports frequently to journalists by fax or cellphone
about Chinese dissidents who are arrested or simply disappear.
</P>
<P>
   It was Lu's organization that put out news of several dissidents
detained in the days before Clinton arrived in China, detentions
which prompted angry White House reactions.
</P>
<P>
   Lu escaped from detention on the mainland and gained asylum in
Hong Kong while Britain still was in control. His organization is
considered subversive by Chinese authorities, but the observance of
free speech and free press here in Hong Kong has kept him from
arrest.
</P>
<P>
   ``For people not very famous, the police can do many things,''
he said in a recent interview. ``For the very famous, the Western
countries help them. For the thousands who nobody knows their
names, how can the Western nations care about them?''
</P>
<P>
   A high profile meeting with Clinton would provide at least some
shield of protection for activists like Lu.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's arrival in Hong Kong came one day after the special
autonomous region celebrated the first anniversary of the handover
back to China.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese officials opened the new Chek Lap Kok International
Airport in conjunction with the anniversary on Wednesday, and Air
Force One was the first plane with passengers to land at the
airport Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   The presidential party was greeted with lion-costumed dancers,
drums and gongs.
</P>
<P>
   Hours before Clinton's arrival, a group of about 20
anti-American demonstrators staged a protest in front of the U.S.
consulate to denounce Washington's security pact with Japan, which
allows U.S. forces to use Japanese logistical support in case of
regional crises.
</P>
<P>
   One demonstrator held up a cartoon caricature of Clinton in the
shape of a turtle, something considered an obnoxious insult in
China.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
