<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AZR-BUDGET-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News service for Friday, July 3. If you have
any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
CANYON (Undated) - In an unusual twist, nine major environmental
groups are pushing to have more, not less, development near the
main entrance to Grand Canyon National Park. In a statement
released Thursday, the environmentalists are backing plans by
Canyon Forest Village, a Scottsdale partnership, to build more
hotels and stores than proposed by the U.S. Forest Service. It is a
unique situation, they contend, prompted by unique circumstances:
Preservation of a global treasure and Arizona's namesake national
park. The Canyon's delicate ecosystem is threatened, they say, by a
compromise development plan they expect to be pushed by the U.S.
Forest Service. By STEVE YOZWIAK. Story will move in the ``A''
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
RAINBOW (Springerville, Ariz.) - A frenetic beat rose from dozens
of pounding drums as a milling, tie-dyed crowd of Rainbow warriors
danced and sang, wildly proclaiming their message of freedom,
harmony and togetherness. It's a strange and unlikely scene on this
isolated Alpine meadow deep in the Ponderosa pines where more than
17,000 men, women and children, plus thousands of wandering dogs,
have come for the 27th annual Rainbow Family of Living Light
National Gathering. By BOB GOLFEN. Story will move in the ``A''
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
PLAYBOY (Phoenix) - Jail inmates can ogle again. The federal
appeals court in San Francisco rules that Maricopa County Sheriff
Joe Arpaio, the self-styled ``world's toughest sheriff,'' can't ban
magazines showing frontal nudity from the county jail. The reason:
The ban could be used against ``National Geographic'' and classic
art works as well as ``Playboy'' and ``Hustler.''  &QL; 
 &QL; 
BUMPED (Phoenix) _ Wanna earn some extra money on your summer
vacation? All you have to do is pack plenty of snacks and
magazines, get to the airport early and volunteer to be bumped from
your flight. If the airline needs your seat, you'll get a free
ticket or voucher, often worth more than you paid for the
ticket.All for a little flexibility and patience. It's shaping up
as a great summer to get bumped from your plane. By DAWN
GILBERTSON. Story will move in the ``A'' and ``F'' categories. &QL; 
 &QL; 
SAGUARO-CELL PHONE (Undated) Cellular phone providers are getting
more creative in hiding towers in everyday objects. The latest in
the Phoenix area is a faux saguaro, the first in the state. There
is a growing movement to hide cell-phone towers, even as their
numbers multiply. By KERRY FEHR-SNYDER. Story will move in the
``F'' category. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
