u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HONKONG-CLINTON-BOS &LR;      07-02 1319
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONKONG-CLINTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TO TALK DEMOCRACY IN HONG KONG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ A year ago, when China dissolved Hong Kong's elected
legislature, ousted politicians borrowed a phrase from General
Douglas MacArthur, defiantly vowing from the balcony of the
colonial legislature: ``We shall return.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursdaythey did, thanks to a healthy victory in recent
elections, the first under Chinese rule here. But even with 60
percent of the May 24 popular vote, democrats won only a third of
the seats under a new electoral system that favors pro-Beijing
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, with the help of the Hong Kong people, you have elected
us,'' declared a jubilant Democratic Party chairman Martin Lee,
promising to work for a better economy. But to those who say
livelihood issues matter more than political freedoms, Lee added in
Chinese: ``People should never think that democracy, prosperity,
and the economy are separate. They are not mutually exclusive; they
are mutually beneficial.''
</P>
<P>
   In meetings with Lee and other political and business leaders
Friday and over dinner with Chief Executive Tung Chee-hwa Thursday
night, President Clinton was expected to discuss the prospects for
speeding the pace of democracy in Hong Kong. Arriving at Hong
Kong's brand-new $20 billion airport Thursday, Clinton caps his
nine-day China trip in the territory ranked the world's freest
economy _ a far cry from the communist mainland that regained
control of Hong Kong last year, and where Clinton just spent a
week.
</P>
<P>
   Yet while economic freedoms are not new to Hong Kong, democracy
did not exist for a century and a half of British rule. The
overwhelming vote in May for the democracy camp, however, seems to
show that Hong Kong people want more than economic liberty. For its
part, if China were to allow people here to set their own pace for
democracy, it would prove Beijing's sincerity in upholding ``one
country, two systems,'' and its greater openness to outside ideas.
</P>
<P>
   It would also be a powerful encouragement to Taiwan that
reunification with China and democratic freedoms could go hand in
hand.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, China and the Beijing-allied government here show
no signs of budging on the timetable for elections and gradual
democratization agreed upon with Britain under the 1990 Basic Law,
Hong Kong's mini-constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Suen, secretary for constitutional affairs, recently
compared democracy to red wine, saying it needed time to mature and
that Hong Kong was not ready.
</P>
<P>
   Christine Loh, chairwoman of the Citizens Party and one of the
politicians Clinton will meet Friday, said she found Suen's
comments insulting.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way that Hong Kong people are any less ready for
democracy than many countries that already have it,'' said Loh, who
won one of 20 directly elected seats in the new 60-person
legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Basic Law, the number of directly elected seats will
increase in the next elections in two years from 20 to 24, and the
number of seats chosen by a pro-Beijing ``election committee'' will
fall from 10 to six. The number of ``functional constituency''
seats, elected by members of special interest and professional
groups, would remain at 30.
</P>
<P>
   By 2004 all election committee seats would be eliminated, and
the legislature would be evenly divided between directly elected
representatives and those chosen for special-interest seats. In
2007 it would be possible to eliminate the special-interest seats,
but any change would require approval of the chief executive and a
two-thirds vote in the legislature.
</P>
<P>
   ``In short, if Beijing doesn't want it, it'll never happen. So
don't assume we'll have full democracy by 2007,'' Democratic Party
leader Lee said in an interview. Lee is expected to have a
15-minute talk with the president Friday. The discussion will be
private, perhaps to avoid rubbing China's nose in Clinton's meeting
with its most famous nemesis in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   Emily Lau, founder of the Frontier political group, who will
also meet Clinton, will point out that she won more than 100,000
votes _ but will be seated alongside lawmakers chosen by as few as
30 people from special interest groups.
</P>
<P>
   Any change to speed direct elections for lawmakers and the chief
executive, however, would require a constitutional convention and
the approval of China's National People's Congress to amend Hong
Kong's Basic Law _ something Lau admits is unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing holding us back is China's intransigence and the
selfishness of some businesspeople here who want positions to be
given to them on a plate,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But Lau and Lee may be underestimating many of their colleagues
in the pro-China camp. Allen Lee, chairman of the pro-business
Liberal Party, said his party members would support fully direct
elections in 2007.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, the biggest pro-Beijing party, the Democratic Alliance
for the Betterment of Hong Kong, will support direct elections by
2007, said Tsang Yok-sing, its chairman. ``And if there's a
consensus among Hong Kong people that we should speed it up, the
DAB will support that.''
</P>
<P>
   But others, such as David Chu, a lawmaker chosen by the
Beijing-vetted election committee, oppose speeding the process.
``Democracy takes time to develop. Look at America _ how many years
after the establishment of your country were women able to vote?''
Chu asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hong Kong is running quite well, so there's no reason to make
dramatic changes, even if it's good for us...We're running like a
Rolex watch _ or maybe a Timex watch,'' he allowed with a laugh,
referring to the poor economy.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the slow pace for direct elections is rooted in Chinese
as well as British fears that Hong Kong could become a base for
undermining the mainland, explained David Dodwell, co-author of
``The Hong Kong Advantage.'' Hong Kong has a long history as a
haven for opponents of mainland regimes _ dating back to Sun
Yat-sen's movement to overthrow the last emperor 100 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mainland is still anxious...that Hong Kong not act as a
catalyst for political destabilization on the mainland,'' Dodwell
said. ``It will take time before they realize that higher levels of
free speech don't necessarily challenge their authority. Clinton's
being in China is a drip on a stone, and democratization in Hong
Kong is another.''
</P>
<P>
   Albert Cheng, host of the popular radio call-in show ``Teacup in
a Tempest,'' said that while Hong Kong may not have a democratic
government, it does have ``a democratic community. We are stil able
to talk and do whatever we want. People criticize openly the local
government...Nonetheless, we need one-man, one-vote for the Chief
Executive and one-man, one-vote for the Legislature. That's the
only way you could qualify Hong Kong as a democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   At an official dinner Thursday night, Chief Executive Tung
Chee-hwa assured Clinton that Hong Kong will ``gradually evolve our
political structure, with universal suffrage our ultimate
objective.'' But he cautioned that progress would follow ``the
timetable laid down by the Basic Law and what is in the best
interest of the people of Hong Kong.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton exchanged warm toasts with Tung and was treated to a
gala reception by colorfully costumed lion dancers at the new
airport. But his arrival was not without drama. A case of 50
bullets was found floating in the harbor near a building where he
is expected to speak Friday. And later, if he needed any proof that
free speech remains intact, a dozen people burned an American flag
to protest the Washington's supposedly weak stand on human rights.
</P>
<P>
   But the freedoms go only so far; a law passed after the handover
bans the desecration of Hong Kong's or China's flag.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Editorial Assistant Liz Lau contributed to this report from
Hong Kong.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
