</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAGUARO-CELL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAUX CACTUS IS LATEST TWIST FOR CELL-PHONE TOWERS 
</HEADLINE>
  PHONE-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KERRY FEHR-SNYDER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) - Atop a hill overlooking the Carefree Highway north
of Phoenix is a three-armed saguaro cactus.
</P>
<P>
   Monolithic and unusually straight, it stands out from other
saguaros that are neither as tall nor green. And for good reason.
Mother Nature had no hand in crafting this one.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it's the work of wireless phone company US West and a
Tucson, Ariz., company that has made a variety of faux features,
including the artificial rocks for a posh Phoenician resort in
Phoenix and the FAO Schwarz Trojan horse at Caesar's Palace in Las
Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike those cosmetic features, Larson's latest man-made project
is a actually a sheath over a monopole, commonly known as a
cellular phone tower.
</P>
<P>
   ``We asked ourselves, `How do you create an icon or something
that allows Air Touch or US West to build out their system?' In
this case, a saguaro made a lot of sense,'' said Harold Schifman,
president of The Larson Co., which is owned by DMB, a real
investment firm based in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Cellular phone providers are getting more creative in hiding
towers in everyday objects. The Larson Co. has hidden monopoles in
pine trees, palm trees, church steeples, even in artificial bricks
on the side of buildings, such as America West Arena and a
Scottsdale coffee house.
</P>
<P>
   But this is the first saguaro that doubles as a cellular tower
as far as anyone can tell.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the first one we've done,'' said Rex Engebretson,
regional real estate manager for US West.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was concern that we do something of a stealth nature
because the site is unique in terms of elevation,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The faux saguaro sits on state land overlooking the freeway. US
West needed about 65 feet to get a two-mile radius coverage area.
The elevation of the site meant the cactus could be about 30 feet
and still cover the required area.
</P>
<P>
   The need to hide towers is driven by growth in their numbers.
</P>
<P>
   More than 55,600 antenna sites dot the country, about half
what's needed to build out each carrier's system, according to the
Cellular Telephone Industry Association in Washington, D.C. The
trade group does not break down the sites by state or county.
</P>
<P>
   CTIA spokesman Tim Ayers said he had not heard of any stealth
saguaros anywhere else in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's cool,'' he said. ``I've heard of pine trees and palm
trees, though.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone, it seems, wants the convenience of using a cellular
phone. Few like the ugly towers required to make that technically
possible.
</P>
<P>
   The Larson Co. came up with the concept of a faux saguaro about
two years ago, Vice President Scott Krezner said. It began working
on prototypes soon afterward. Construction took about two months.
</P>
<P>
   The stealth saguaro is about 30 feet tall and 20 inches in
diameter. It's made of fiberglass, which is transparent to radio
waves. It cost $30,000 to $40,000 to build, Krezner said.
</P>
<P>
   That's considerably more than an unobstructed monopole.
</P>
<P>
   But US West's Engebretson said the cost was necessary to
complete the buildout of the company's network in the Phoenix area.
US West has about 180 sites in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the stealthlike nature, the faux saguaro is surrounded
by two big metal boxes. One provides power and the other is a meter
for electricity usage.
</P>
<P>
   The tree also sits on a slab of cement and has three large black
cables running from its base.
</P>
<P>
   ``The antennaes have to be on a stable platform,'' Engebretson
explained.
</P>
<P>
   Federal law prohibits local governments from denying
applications by wireless service providers to build towers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can do anything but say no,'' the CTIA's Ayers said.
``They can say here not there, yellow not green.''
</P>
<P>
   Most wireless providers willingly comply with local governments'
stipulations, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Companies want to come in as customer friendly,'' he said.
``They're not coming in to make enemies.'' &QL; 
Kerry Fehr-Snyder can be reached at kerry.fehr(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
