</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-CLINTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SEES IDYLLIC SIDE OF CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   YUCUN, China _ He towered a foot over virtually every villager.
The hamlet's only store did its accounting with an abacus. And one
of the village elders, 88 year-old Qu Zhenxin, said she never heard
of this man, this president, but was certainly pleased to welcome
him to town.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said he wanted to show America the many faces
of China. Thursday, he fled the shimmering skyscrapers of Shanghai
for the tranquil Li River, where he arrived by boat to this tiny
farming and fishing village of some 500 people tucked amid the
storybook limestone hills of Guilin.
</P>
<P>
   They have no telephones here, no power equipment, no overt will
to be anything different than precisely what they are. The
villagers who met Clinton on the sun-baked dirt of their
schoolhouse playground carried with them a sense of China's rural
history and an innate sense of pride. They stood in the doorways of
their ancient houses beckoning this oversized American to join them
for a piece of fresh fruit and a photo opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like this,'' Clinton said. ``You learn a lot about the
country from places like this. There is a larger percentage of
Chinese people in places like this than in the big cities, which is
hard to imagine when you think of how many people live in places
like Beijing and Shanghai.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly every resident of the village, accessible by an hour's
boat ride up the Li River or a two-mile walk across a dirt path to
the nearest road, has the family name of Zhao, and most are
obviously related to each other in ties that outstrip memory. A
member of one family said the house has been in his family name for
500 years.
</P>
<P>
   Accompanied by an entourage that seemed to dwarf the village
itself, Clinton walked up a crooked stone and dirt path into the
village of clustered brick houses with terra cotta roofs set in the
shadows of soaring rock formations.
</P>
<P>
   The houses have hard stone floors, spare furnishings, and photos
of Mao or Chinese military officials of the past hanging on the
walls. Their ceilings typically soared 20 feet or more, and the
upstairs loft areas were reached by ladders. While most residents
proudly pointed at their cable television hookups, there were no
telephones in the village.
</P>
<P>
   At the first house, Clinton sat awkwardly inside with his wife
and daughter against a wall as the extended Zhao family stood
staring at them in silence. One offered them fruit from a bowl
filled with bananas and grapes and what they said were green plums,
but the guests declined. Finally, Clinton asked who were the people
in the the photographs on the wall. More Zhaos, he was told.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many households live here?'' Hillary Clinton asked. Three,
she was told, all Zhao brothers and their families. As she talked,
a young boy came over and stood in front of Chelsea, and they
smiled at each other. When the Clintons got up to leave, the entire
family stood and applauded.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton soon arrived at what is known as the biogas facility, a
place where the villagers take all their human waste, put it
together in a large pot and bake it to what one local called ``a
nice brew.'' Once cooked, the waste emits a gas that the villagers
use to power their stoves and lights in a low cost fuel source that
seemed to provide the president with a unique sense of delight.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are lots of rural places all over the world that should
be doing this with biogas,'' Clinton said, walking away from the
facility. ``This is one of the things that almost any village could
be doing. It's very important.''
</P>
<P>
   In nearby Guilin, Clinton Thursday urged China to learn from the
United States' mistakes and not harm the environment for the sake
of economic growth. He pledged US support to clean up the rivers,
air and land in China, which has five of the most polluted cities
in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let us, Chinese and Americans, preserve what we have inherited
from the past and, in doing so, preserve the future we are working
so hard to build for our children,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Praising Guilin's environmental leaders during a roundtable
discussion, Clinton said it is not too late for all of China to
reverse environmental trends that have put the country on track to
overtake the United States as the number one emitter of greenhouse
gases within 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   When Clinton arrived at the town's one tiny store, he
immediately began telling the shopkeeper about his own grandfather,
who ran a store in Arkansas. Within a few minutes, Clinton was
standing inside posing by a glass case with the entire family.
Everyone was smiling. Afterward, Clinton saw their version of a
cash register. ``Look at this,'' he called out. ``An abacus for the
store, for counting.'' He pushed some of the beads around and said,
``This one still works pretty well.''
</P>
<P>
   Back in the schoolyard, he shook hands along a ropeline with the
remaining townspeople as if he were running for mayor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if every American could see what I've seen they would
be impressed, and I think they would want to work with China to
fulfill it's potential and the potential of its people,'' Clinton
said. ``They would want every Chinese life to have the chance to
flower.''
</P>
</TEXT>
