<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-VACCINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VACCINE MADE TO PREVENT AIDS BRINGS DISEASE, DEATH, RESEARCHER
SAYS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RUTH SoRELLE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ The hope for a vaccine made of a live, weakened form of
the AIDS virus dimmed Thursday when a Harvard researcher reported
tests with a similar virus caused disease and death in monkeys.
</P>
<P>
   Six of nine rhesus monkeys inoculated with the weakened form of
the simian immunodeficiency virus as infants have developed the
equivalent of full-blown AIDS since being vaccinated five years
ago, Dr. Ruth Ruprecht, associate professor at Harvard University
Medical School, said at the 12th World AIDS Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Five of the monkeys have died and the others have early forms of
SIV infection but have not yet progressed to full-blown AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Four of 15 adult monkeys inoculated with the weakened virus show
increasing levels of SIV in the blood, and one has died of
infection and AIDS, Ruprecht said.
</P>
<P>
   Still another is showing serious immune system disorder and the
other two have indications of changes in their immune systems.
</P>
<P>
   The virus was weakened, partially by deletion of two important
genes, Ruprecht said. That should have made it less likely to cause
disease and reduced its ability to reproduce.
</P>
<P>
   But the virus continued to reproduce itself in the adults and
infants, she said. The size of the gene deletions got bigger and
bigger, and ``by the end of three to five years, we had a different
beast.''
</P>
<P>
   Using a weakened form of a virus is an accepted practice in
medicine. The oral Sabin polio vaccine was a weakened form of the
poliovirus. Infants who received it developed strong protection
against polio, and they often passed the weakened virus on to
others.
</P>
<P>
   In some rare instances, however, children acquired polio from
the weakened virus. That's the disaster Ruprecht wants to avoid.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, answering a call from the International
Association of Physicians in AIDS Care, more than 300 doctors who
treat AIDS volunteered to test a weakened virus vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   If such a vaccine could be made safe, it would offer the best
hope for an effective vaccine to prevent infection with the human
immunodeficiency virus. Some physicians thought the vaccine cause
was being ignored.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Charles Farthing, a Los Angeles physician who issued the
call, said he would have expected the newborn monkeys in the
experiment to become infected by the weakened virus because they
have immature immune systems.
</P>
<P>
   Even while arguing it is impossible to determine the safety of
an HIV vaccine by testing it in monkeys, Farthing said he would
take the vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I firmly believe we should do the experiment. The worst thing
that would happen is that I would have to take anti-retroviral
therapy that I give to my patients.''
</P>
<P>
   He said if patients in the safety study of the vaccine became
ill, they could go on the three-drug cocktail, which should help
keep the virus at bay.
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. Bernard Hirschel, a leader of the conference and
professor at the University of Geneva, said that after hearing
Ruprecht's data, ``I have my doubts.''
</P>
<P>
   Hirschel was one of the vaccine volunteers, but now has second
thoughts because of safety issues.
</P>
<P>
   He said the maker of the vaccine being proposed for human
studies has a virus that it is even more weakened than that used by
Ruprecht.
</P>
<P>
   There is a point of diminishing returns, he said. With too much
attenuation, the vaccine will not cause the immune response needed
for protection. If it is not strong enough, the person gets the
disease instead of the protection, Hirschel said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I doubt it is possible to make a vaccine that is both
attenuated and effective,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hirschel said if he were convinced it was safe, he would have no
problem with a few volunteer physicians testing the vaccine. ``But
if it is a barrel over Niagara Falls, I don't think many people are
going to want to go,'' Hirschel said.
</P>
<P>
   Ruprecht said she does not think the idea of the attenuated
virus is dead. She wants to look at other ways to weaken HIV or SIV
to prevent it from reproducing easily.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Robert Gallo, co-founder of HIV and director of the
Institute of Virology at the University of Maryland, said he agrees
with Ruprecht's concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``A retrovirus (such as the vaccine) is forever,'' Gallo said,
pointing out that all retroviruses cause disease, although it takes
30 years for some.
</P>
<P>
   In an earlier statement, Gallo warned against putting all
research money into a vaccine because the need for treatment
continues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if we had effective vaccines today, we would still have
30 million people infected,'' he said. ``We can't put all our eggs
in the preventive vaccine basket.''
</P>
<P>
   Gallo cited new targets in the life cycle of the virus as
promising avenues of preventing HIV from entering a cell.
Chemokines, proteins that fight cellular invaders, can compete with
HIV for the doorways or receptors to cells. That might be a viable
way of fighting HIV infection, he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
