<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-TESTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAILURE OF AIDS VACCINE TEST IN MONKEYS SPURS DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ Amid signs that the search for an AIDS vaccine is
finally getting the attention it deserves, some scientists Thursday
criticized the safety of one vaccine type that proponents say
should be tested in humans soon.
</P>
<P>
   Monkeys injected with an experimental vaccine, which contains a
live but weakened version of the simian AIDS virus, have sickened
and died of immune-system damage in recent experiments conducted by
a Harvard Medical School scientist.
</P>
<P>
   The new information immediately touched off a sharp debate about
the risks of a human version of the live-virus vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly our data raise a red flag'' about the safety of such
``attenuated'' viruses as AIDS vaccines, even when scientists try
to disable them by removing several genes, Ruth Ruprecht of
Dana-Farber Cancer Institute told colleagues at the 12th World AIDS
Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Charles Farthing, a Los Angeles physician who last year
organized 300 doctors willing to be guinea pigs in a test of a
live-virus AIDS vaccine, said Ruprecht's monkey data did not
necessarily imply danger to human volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   Live attenuated vaccines have a long and illustrious history.
It's the way the world eliminated the ancient scourge of smallpox,
and a live-virus version furnished the prototype polio vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   Other types of HIV vaccine are being studied, such as those
based on pieces of the virus's coat or genetically engineered
canary pox viruses containing HIV genes. But scientists have no
idea yet whether those models will either be safe or protect
against HIV infection.
</P>
<P>
   Interest in a live-virus AIDS vaccine stems in part from tests
on a simian version developed by Ronald Desrosiers of the New
England Regional Primate Center in Southborough, Mass. That vaccine
protected macaque monkeys against infection by the simian
immunodeficiency virus (SIV), a close cousin of HIV.
</P>
<P>
   Desrosiers's experiment convinced many AIDS researchers that a
live attenuated virus would make the best vaccine, if it could be
proven safe.
</P>
<P>
   Also lending impetus to the idea was an intriguing report from
Australia that a handful of people infected through blood
transfusions with a genetically deficient form of HIV have remained
well for 14 years, as has the blood donor. It would be ideal if a
vaccine could mimic this ``natural experiment,'' many reasoned.
</P>
<P>
   But Ruprecht reported Thursday that four out of 15 rhesus
monkeys vaccinated with a supposedly disabled SIV have had rising
levels of the virus in their blood _ the opposite of what
vaccination is supposed to do. One monkey has died of simian AIDS,
another is in early stages of the disease, and two more show signs
of immune system damage.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston researcher found in 1995 that the same vaccine caused
what she terms a ``fast-forward'' version of AIDS in infant
monkeys. Of nine young animals, six developed AIDS, five of the six
died, and the other three are in earlier stages of the disease.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, even a weakened SIV vaccine can mutate into
disease-causing forms, Ruprecht said. Unlike polio and other
viruses, SIV and HIV insert themselves into the genes of their
host's cells. Other viruses introduced through vaccines ``are no
longer around to cause trouble'' after they stimulate a lasting
immune reaction, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ruprecht's findings were clearly a setback for proponents of
human tests of live attenuated HIV vaccines.
</P>
<P>
   Farthing, who leads the physician group pushing for human tests,
said Ruprecht's findings are ``concerning'' but not directly
relevant to the proposed tests of a human version of the monkey
vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   He said the HIV used in a human test would lack four or more
genes, while the monkey virus Ruprecht tested was missing three
genes.
</P>
<P>
   Ruprecht's finding immediately undermined some support for a
live attenuated vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of this week's conference, which has attracted more
than 12,000 AIDS researchers to Geneva from all over the globe,
indicated Thursday he would withdraw as a volunteer for the trial
of a live attenuated HIV vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have my doubts now,'' said Dr. Bernard Hirschel of Geneva's
University Hospital, who had signed up with Farthing's group. ``At
first I thought it was a good idea because there has been an
exaggeration of the dangers of live attenuated vaccines. But if you
listen to Ruth Ruprecht, you get a new perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   During a sharp exchange Thursday, Dr. Robert Gallo of the
University of Maryland criticized Farthing for assuming a vaccine
based on live HIV would be safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would take years beyond your lifetime'' to be able to
conclude that such a vaccine would be safe, Gallo told Farthing,
``and it would take a lot of people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
