r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BULLS-SKILES-AZR &LR;      07-02 0556
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BULLS-SKILES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SKILES' KIND OF TOWN?  
 SUNS ASSISTANT COACH WILL TALK TO CHICAGO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The Chicago Bulls have asked the Suns for permission
to talk with assistant coach Scott Skiles about the Bulls' head
coaching position, league and Suns sources said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Skiles, contacted Wednesday in Indiana, declined to comment
about the Bulls or other teams that have contacted him this summer,
and he said he's not in any hurry.
</P>
<P>
   ``This summer, next summer, I'm not tied up into a time (to
become a head coach) or anything,'' he said. ``I'm just going
through it like everyone else does.''
</P>
<P>
   His agent, Keith Glass, would neither confirm nor deny that
Skiles has been contacted by the Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Put this in boldface with quotes _ No comment,'' Glass said.
</P>
<P>
   Suns officials also declined to comment. General Manager Bryan
Colangelo would only say that the club told Skiles when he was
hired that it would not stand in the way of his getting a head
coaching job if the opportunity arises.
</P>
<P>
   A Bulls spokeswoman said Wednesday that Chicago General Manager
Jerry Krause will not comment on prospective coaches.
</P>
<P>
   But sources said Skiles is among five or six candidates the
Bulls plan to contact or have contacted about the job. Others
rumored to be under consideration are Iowa State's Tim Floyd and
Kansas' Roy Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Skiles, along with Indiana's Rick Carlisle and Cleveland's
Sidney Lowe, is considered one of the up-and-coming head coaching
prospects among NBA assistants.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Jackson, who guided Chicago to six NBA championships in the
1990s, has announced that he will not return as Bulls coach.
</P>
<P>
   Because of Jackson's departure, the Bulls job could be the most
desirable in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Or the next coach could face a complete rebuilding job.
</P>
<P>
   League Most Valuable Player Michael Jordan is contemplating
whether to return, retire or play for another team.
</P>
<P>
   With Jordan back, the Bulls will be a contender.
</P>
<P>
   Perennial All-Star Scottie Pippen is a free agent who has
indicated that he probably will not be back. Dennis Rodman also is
a free agent, along with center Luc Longley and three-point
specialist Steve Kerr.
</P>
<P>
   If all return, the Bulls likely will be the team to beat again.
If they all leave, the Bulls will be in a rebuilding mode.
</P>
<P>
   But the Bulls aren't the only club interested in Skiles.
</P>
<P>
   Glass confirmed that the Los Angeles Clippers and Denver Nuggets
have inquired about the Phoenix assistant, who spent 10 years in
the NBA as a point guard and still holds the league record for
assists in a single game (30). He joined the Suns last season and
was Coach Danny Ainge's lead assistant.
</P>
<P>
   But Skiles, 34, was considered a hot property in coaching
circles even before that.
</P>
<P>
   Before joining the Suns, he served as head coach of PAOK, a
Greek professional club. He took over that team during midseason
with the club foundering and led it to the European Cup playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been contacted directly and indirectly by some teams,''
Glass said. ``They expressed interest in various forms. I'm just
excited for him. People know what he's about.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll be a great coach in the league. If it doesn't happen
this year, it will happen next year.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
