<HEADLINE>
FAILURE OF AIDS VACCINE TEST IN MONKEYS SPURS DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ Amid signs that the search for an AIDS vaccine is
finally getting the attention it deserves, some scientists Thursday
criticized the safety of one vaccine type that proponents say
should be tested in humans soon.
</P>
<P>
   Monkeys injected with an experimental vaccine, which contains a
live but weakened version of the simian AIDS virus, have sickened
and died of immune-system damage in recent experiments conducted by
a Harvard Medical School scientist.
</P>
<P>
   The new information immediately touched off a sharp debate about
the risks of a human version of the live-virus vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly our data raise a red flag'' about the safety of such
``attenuated'' viruses as AIDS vaccines, even when scientists try
to disable them by removing several genes, Ruth Ruprecht of
Dana-Farber Cancer Institute told colleagues at the 12th World AIDS
Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Charles Farthing, a Los Angeles physician who last year
organized 300 doctors willing to be guinea pigs in a test of a
live-virus AIDS vaccine, said Ruprecht's monkey data did not
necessarily imply danger to human volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   Live attenuated vaccines have a long and illustrious history.
It's the way the world eliminated the ancient scourge of smallpox,
and a live-virus version furnished the prototype polio vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   Other types of HIV vaccine are being studied, such as those
based on pieces of the virus's coat or genetically engineered
