</P>
<P>
   Ruprecht's findings were clearly a setback for proponents of
human tests of live attenuated HIV vaccines.
</P>
<P>
   Farthing, who leads the physician group pushing for human tests,
said Ruprecht's findings are ``concerning'' but not directly
relevant to the proposed tests of a human version of the monkey
vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   He said the HIV used in a human test would lack four or more
genes, while the monkey virus Ruprecht tested was missing three
genes.
</P>
<P>
   Ruprecht's finding immediately undermined some support for a
live attenuated vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of this week's conference, which has attracted more
than 12,000 AIDS researchers to Geneva from all over the globe,
indicated Thursday he would withdraw as a volunteer for the trial
of a live attenuated HIV vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have my doubts now,'' said Dr. Bernard Hirschel of Geneva's
University Hospital, who had signed up with Farthing's group. ``At
first I thought it was a good idea because there has been an
exaggeration of the dangers of live attenuated vaccines. But if you
listen to Ruth Ruprecht, you get a new perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   During a sharp exchange Thursday, Dr. Robert Gallo of the
University of Maryland criticized Farthing for assuming a vaccine
based on live HIV would be safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would take years beyond your lifetime'' to be able to
conclude that such a vaccine would be safe, Gallo told Farthing,
``and it would take a lot of people.''
</P>
