<SLUG> BC-LOTTERY-DISPUTE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WIDOW WITH CLAIM TO $21   MILLION LOTTERY TICKET TESTIFIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM F. DOHERTY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ During eight gruelling hours on the witness stand
Thursday, widow Paraskeve Kantges insisted she never canceled a
winning $21 million lottery bet, as a Watertown variety store owner
claims.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never _ I am certain,'' Kantges said under questioning by her
attorney, James Merberg.
</P>
<P>
   Kantges, testifying before a state Lottery Commission hearing in
Brantree, said she telephoned the winning Mass Millions bet to
Coolidge Provisions Feb 5. But store owner Nick Havan claims she
called back later and canceled the bet, so he kept the winning
ticket for himself.
</P>
<P>
   Former Massachusetts Lottery executive director Samuel M.
DePhillippo ruled in favor of Kangtes, but Havan appealed. Retired
Superior Court Judge Robert
</P>
<P>
   Steadman is hearing evidence and will make a recommendation to
the full
</P>
<P>
   lottery commission.
</P>
<P>
   Since the hearing began Monday, Havan's witnesses have testified
that Kantges, a frequent lottery player, is obstreperous and fickle
about her bets. One witness, James G. McGoldrick Jr., testified
that Kantges told him she didn't win the $21 million jackpot.
</P>
<P>
   On the stand Thursday, Kantges refuted that testimony. ``I was
not going to talk to him or anyone else about my personal affairs _
especially about money,'' she testified.
</P>
<P>
   Kantges identified records showing she has played the same
number, based on her birth date, for years. She also reiterated her
side of the story _ that she called in 96 lottery bets to Havan
about 4 p.m. the day of the drawing, but got only 95 tickets the
next morning, with the winning ticket missing.
</P>
<P>
   Kantges said she called Coolidge Provisions on Feb. 6 and told
clerk Hrach ``Richie'' Abrahamian that she won the jackpot. ``He
said, `You didn't have it,' and hung up the phone. I thought he was
playing a joke,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   After taking a cab to the store, Kantges testified, Abrahamian
tossed a batch of 95 tickets at her. When she realized the winning
ticket was gone, she confronted Havan.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `I gave the ticket to Richie. He must have ... given
it to someone else.''' Kantges said. ``I felt like the legs had
been cut out from under me.''
</P>
<P>
   Kantges admitted she had run up a $3,000 tab for lottery tickets
at another Watertown store and had quit making payments after
reducing the amount to $2,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
