<SLUG> BC-BUMPED-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLIERS LIKELY TO GET BUMPED MORE OFTEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAWN GILBERTSON  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) - Wanna earn some extra money on your summer vacation?
</P>
<P>
   No lawn mowing or lemonade stands involved.
</P>
<P>
   All you have to do is pack plenty of snacks and magazines, get
to the airport early and volunteer to be bumped from your flight.
</P>
<P>
   If the airline needs your seat, you'll get a free ticket or
voucher, often worth more than you paid for the ticket. America
West Airlines, for example, was offering $500 passes last week for
an overbooked Phoenix-to-San Francisco flight that goes for as low
as $150 round-trip with advance purchase. Ditto on a recent
Albuquerque-to-Phoenix flight that goes for as low as $78
round-trip.
</P>
<P>
   It's not cash, but it could take care of that trip home for the
holidays or an upcoming business trip. All for a little flexibility
and patience.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines ask for volunteers when a flight is overbooked, and
that happens frequently in the peak summer travel period as throngs
of vacationers join business travelers in the skies.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the season,'' said Tom Parsons, a travel bargain guru
who publishes ``Best Fares,'' a magazine and Web site
(www.bestfares.com) focusing on travel deals. ``Most of the major
airlines are going to be bumping.''
</P>
<P>
   Parsons thinks there could be a bumper crop of bumping this
summer because airlines are filling a record number of seats as the
travel boom continues.
</P>
<P>
   Bonnie Harry, owner of Travel Etc. in Tempe, Ariz., has seen it.
She flew to San Diego and back recently on two overpacked flights.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were buying them off going, and they were buying them off
coming,'' she said with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   A host of factors can lead to an overbooked flight. First,
history can prove the airline wrong. Carriers, hoping to fly a
flight as full as possible, typically sell more seats than
available based on previous no-show levels. Sometimes, those
no-shows show up.
</P>
<P>
   Add in weather woes, mechanical problems and canceled flights _
on your airline or another with a lot of service in the area _ and
you're looking at a classic imbalance of supply and demand.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, a little more than 1 million passengers volunteered
to be bumped by one of the 10 major U.S. airlines, according to the
U.S. Department of Transportation. An additional 54,000 were
involuntarily bumped. The figures are out of a total of 503 million
passengers boarded.
</P>
<P>
   Tempe-based America West was tops in volunteer bumping, with 31
per 10,000 passengers. Southwest used the fewest volunteers (12.9
per 10,000) but it involuntarily bumped more (2.16 per 10,000) than
everyone but Alaska Airlines. America West forced 1.98 passengers
per 10,000 from their seats.
</P>
<P>
   America West's prolific bumping is great news for Phoenix
travelers, since it is the busiest carrier at Sky Harbor
International with 206 daily departures.
</P>
<P>
   Walk through the airline's concourses in Terminal 4, and you're
bound to see this message scroll across the electronic message
board at each gate: ``This flight may be overbooked. Please ask
about our Silverliner passes.''
</P>
<P>
   It caught Kelli Henson's attention this week.
</P>
<P>
   Henson and her boyfriend, Tom Hill, both from Houston, were on
their way to Orange County for a Tall Clubs International
Convention. (He's 6-foot-4; she's 5-foot-10). Their 10:24 a.m.
connecting flight out of Phoenix was oversold, and the gate agent
was offering $400 vouchers to potential volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We figured that's good for another trip later in the year,''
Hill said.
</P>
<P>
   They weren't in in a big hurry _ ``as long as we're there for
happy hour,'' Henson said with a laugh _ so they put their names on
the volunteer list.
</P>
<P>
   So did Carole Haworth, an Amway distributor on her way home from
a business trip to Detroit. She figured the voucher, which was
worth twice what she paid for the entire trip, could be used for a
future business trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``The expenses for travel are out of my pocket,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, America West didn't need any volunteers on
that flight, and the three boarded the plane as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   Frequent fliers tend to be the most savvy bumpees, said Harry,
who's also president of the Arizona chapter of the American Society
of Travel Agents.
</P>
<P>
   They pick flights they know are frequently overbooked to
increase their chances for free travel. At the gate, they ask for
two $200 vouchers instead of one $400 voucher so they can go on two
trips, even if it means adding a little extra money to go to say,
Chicago. With a $400 voucher, at least on America West, you only
get one trip, regardless of the fare. If the flight costs $238, for
example, you wouldn't get the balance.
</P>
<P>
   Those in the know also know not to jump at the airline's first
offer, unless they think it's the best deal out there and is plenty
for an upcoming trip. Airlines often up the ante if they're not
getting enough volunteers. On a recent Phoenix-to-St. Louis flight
on America West, for example, the gate agent started at $300 per
passenger and upped it to $400 about five minutes later, one
passenger said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It goes to auction,'' Harry said. ``It's absolutely amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   The compensation varies, and is again based on supply and
demand.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they can't get their seven people off the plane for this
price, they will up it,'' Harry said.
</P>
<P>
   America West offers a maximum of $600, according to spokeswoman
Patty Nowack. Southwest starts at $100 over the face value of the
ticket and goes up from there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do what we need to get the flight off and accommodate those
people we couldn't get on board the plane,'' spokeswoman Linda
Rutherford said.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, when a flight looks very overbooked, the airlines
look for volunteers in advance.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, US Airways called Harry's agency and offered a
family of five $500 a piece in vouchers to give up their seats on a
flight to the East Coast. They had paid less than $400 for the
tickets. They jumped at it, and used the vouchers for a Christmas
trip they otherwise wouldn't have been able to afford.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're talking $2,500,'' Harry said, and all they gave up was
one day of their two-week vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Just this week, America West called one of Harry's clients to
see if she would give up her seat on a Las Vegas-to-Flagstaff
flight in exchange for a seat in first-class on a later flight. She
passed.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there are negatives to getting bumped. Your luggage
goes ahead of you, for example. And there's no guarantee your
self-imposed delay won't be longer than planned. Although the
airline guarantees you a seat on one of its later flights or a
competitor's flight, there's no guarantee that plane will leave on
time.
</P>
<P>
   A Phoenix business traveler who accepted America West's $500
voucher to get off his San Francisco flight last week ended up
spending the entire morning at Sky Harbor because the flight they
put him on was delayed.
</P>
<P>
   It comes down to your schedule and penchant for travel.
</P>
<P>
   Parsons volunteers to get bumped every chance he gets. Last week
he gave up his first-class seat on a 7 a.m. Delta Air Lines flight
from San Francisco to Dallas. In return, he received a free
first-class round-trip ticket _ not a voucher _ and a seat on the
noon flight.
</P>
<P>
   The noon flight also was overbooked, but he passed on being
bumped from that flight because the next non-stop flight (which he
prefers) was about 12 hours later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel like sitting around until midnight,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The deal has paid off. Parsons is flying free to New York today
for an interview on ``Good Morning America.'' The fare for such a
last-minute trip in first-class: $2,026.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, it's a godsend,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tips for getting bumped
</P>
<P>
   - Try to find out in advance whether the flight is overbooked.
Your travel agent can check the seating situation in the computer,
or you can call the airline. If the travel agent says there are no
seats left to be assigned or the airline says the seats are under
``airport control,'' it's a good sign the flight is overbooked.
</P>
<P>
   - Arrive at the airport approximately 90 minutes before
departure time. It pays to be at the gate even before the flight
opens so you can be first in line. Sometimes airlines need just one
volunteer to give up a seat.
</P>
<P>
   - Ask if the flight is oversold and whether volunteers will be
needed. Ask what the compensation will be. If it sounds good, sign
up.
</P>
<P>
   - Ask the agent what flight on which you will be guaranteed a
seat. If you can't be guaranteed a seat on the next flight out, ask
the agent to protect you under Rule 240 (they know what it is) with
a guaranteed seat on another carrier's flight.
</P>
<P>
   - Carry the airline's flight schedule so you know your options.
</P>
<P>
   - If you are bumped and have more than a two-hour wait, ask for
all the extras: a free long-distance call (or five-minute calling
card), a meal ticket, free admission to the airport club and free
drink and headset coupons for the flight. Be courteous. &QL; 
Source: ``Best Fares'' magazine Web site, www.bestfares.com &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Dawn Gilbertson may be reached at dawn.gilbertson(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
