<HEADER>
A8547 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-GAZPROM-775&AMP;AD     07-02 1133
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-GAZPROM-775&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN TAX COLLECTORS WIN SHOWDOWN WITH BIG OIL COMPANY 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By MICHAEL WINES    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russia's legendarily ineffectual tax men stared down
the nation's biggest and most powerful corporation Thursday,
threatening to seize control of the company _ and its executives'
dachas, yachts and other perks _ unless it paid billions of dollars
in back taxes.
</P>
<P>
   To most everyone's amazement, the company, Gazprom, gave in. By
the end of a day filled with bluster and rumor, Gazprom had agreed
to turn over 4.2 billion rubles ($675 million) in unpaid taxes by
Monday, and to start paying the government about 4 billion rubles a
month.
</P>
<P>
   Experts were left wondering whether President Boris Yeltsin had
grown a backbone in dealing with the oligarchs who control the
Russian economy _ or whether he had staged a deft act of political
theater.
</P>
<P>
   For the agreement, announced Thursday evening, does not merely
force Gazprom, the world's largest petroleum company and Russia's
biggest tax delinquent, to make good on its back taxes. It also
would require the government to pay Gazprom billions of rubles for
oil and gas that government agencies and state companies purchase
but never pay for.
</P>
<P>
   By many estimates, the two payments would amount to a wash. And
if that is true, the government's raid Thursday is unlikely to have
much impact on Russia's budget deficit, the core of its economic
woes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was certainly a see-saw day as far as Gazprom's fortunes
are concerned,'' said Stephen O'Sullivan, an oil expert and
co-director of research for the United Financial Group in Moscow.
``But if this is all that happened, it doesn't seem to justify the
farce that took place.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the government's crackdown offers great symbolic
benefits. For one, it signals that politically influential
companies will no longer escape the taxes they have ignored since
Russia ended Communist rule.
</P>
<P>
   The action is also likely to impress the International Monetary
Fund, which is negotiating a multibillion-dollar loan that Russia
is seeking. The IMF has demanded that Russia improve its tax system
as a condition for further loans.
</P>
<P>
   There is a downside: if the government genuinely has decided to
get tough on Gazprom, the company may have to get tough on its
non-paying customers. Gazprom is owed 100 billion rubles ($11.6
billion), and its customers are so strapped that more than half the
debts are settled through barter. Dunning them could send a
political and economic shudder through the entire nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many businesses which operate completely
unprofitably,'' said James Henderson, an oil and gas analyst for
MFK Renaissance, a Moscow investment firm. ``They survive because
Gazprom doesn't turn off their power. The simplest method to deal
with them is to turn off the light.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's events bore the mark of the tough-minded new director
of the state tax service, Boris Fyodorov.
</P>
<P>
   If Fyodorov's revenue men were seeking a symbolic target, they
could hardly have chosen a better one. Gazprom _ the name is short
for Gas Industry _ is ubiquitous in Russia, and in business and
politics the $25 billion company is a force of nature.
</P>
<P>
   From a 34-story skyscraper surrounded by gardens and tennis
courts, its leaders direct a workforce of 370,000, control a third
of the world's known gas reserves and supply 25 percent of Western
Europe's natural gas.
</P>
<P>
   The company bought one-third of a major Russian television
network, NTV, in 1996 and wielded its investment unashamedly to
promote Yeltsin's successful run for a second term as president. By
Russian standards, that is not surprising: the government owns 40
percent of Gazprom; five of its 11 directors are government
appointees.
</P>
<P>
   Nor was it surprising that Yeltsin chose a former head of
Gazprom, Victor Chernomyrdin, as prime minister after his
re-election. During Chernomyrdin's tenure, Gazprom struck a deal to
pay about 2.5 billion rubles of its monthly 4-billion ruble tax
bill, with additional payments pegged to the company's ability to
collect the money owed it.
</P>
<P>
   But things clearly have changed since Sergei Kiriyenko, himself
a reformer, replaced Chernomyrdin this spring and hired Fyodorov as
chief tax collector.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, the rationale for the raid was that the company had
paid only a billion rubles of its June tax bill.
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday's events seemed more intended to generate a wave of
publicity _ and at that, they succeeded. Word began circulating
Wednesday that the government planned drastic action against the
company. How drastic became clear Thursday, when the state tax
service released a list of assets it pledged to seize.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Besides ``ruble and currency accounts of debtors,'' the list
included ``planes, yachts, boats, cabins, swimming pools, sports
facilities, countryside residences, reception mansions and other
luxury goods owned by Gazprom.''
</P>
<P>
   Interviewed Thursday night on his own NTV, Gazprom president Rem
Vyakhirev angrily called the crackdown ``a real circus
performance.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We heard that Moscow was making moves against Gazprom, that
the police were sent to our offices, money demanded and so on,'' he
said. ``Today in our reception rooms in Bogorodskoye, they arrived
in force: 5 plainclothesmen and 20 guys in masks, like Chechens who
came down from the mountains.''
</P>
<P>
   While the threat to curtail executives' luxuries grabbed
headlines, the tax office's real weapon lay in the legal document
that entrusts the government with 40 percent of Gazprom's shares.
Citing a clause that makes tax payments a condition of the trust,
Kiriyenko said the government would dissolve the agreement and take
control of the Gazprom board if the company did not come to terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody must pay taxes,'' he said. ``The government will not
allow blackmail.''
</P>
<P>
   A few hours later Deputy Prime Minister Boris Nemtsov said the
threat had been withdrawn. ``Despite the quite stormy nature of the
discussions, an agreement has been reached,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it remains unclear exactly what that agreement entails.
Gazprom claims that it owes the government 12 billion rubles ($2.6
billion) in taxes, but that the government owes it 13 billion
rubles in unpaid bills.
</P>
<P>
   A Finance Ministry official said Thursday night that the
government had not totaled its debts to Gazprom. A government
statement Thursday indicated that the two sides will convene a
committee to sort the matter out.
</P>
<P>
   Gazprom's director, Viyakhirev, greeted the specter of more
negotiations with tax collectors with unalloyed sarcasm: ``We're
planning to clear several offices so that they can settle there on
a permanent basis.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
