<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEY WASHED AWAY THE NEW WAVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The brassy Sass Class _ the brood with a 'tude _ was
supposed to take over Wimbledon, push the aged ladies in their
wheelchairs off the upper staircases at Centre Court and fight
among themselves to see who would be the adolescent queen, just in
case 17-year-old Martina Hingis couldn't handle it anymore. Where
are they now that those pensioners Jana Novotna and Nathalie
Tauziat have reclaimed the oldest tournament for, shall we say, the
maturest women?
</P>
<P>
   The New Wave got washed away, beached, and Saturday here are
Jana and Nathalie, seeded 3 and 16, in one of the least expected
finals ever, not exactly sending ``wish you were here'' postcards
to the kiddies they left behind.
</P>
<P>
   Among them, Anna Kournikova fell down short of the starting gate
and is nursing a sore thumb. The Williams Sisters, Venus and
Serena, guaranteeing that one of them would win, pulled up lame
with sore illusions. Mirjana Lucic and Patty Schnyder lost their
way in the second-round maze. And Hingis was mugged, 6-4, 6-4, the
crown toppling from her wise young head as Novotna fired a sizzling
serve, the last shot of an afternoon of chilling breezes and grimy
clouds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Munchkins, go home!'' was the theme as Tauziat and Novotna,
lurching toward October birthdays _ a 31st for Nathalie, 30th for
Jana _ made it the ``Old Faces of '98 Revue.''
</P>
<P>
   Jana lit up the frowning sky with a sublimely aggressive
performance on the worn and fading carpet of grass, a tour de force
that ranks with the finest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come on, Jana!'' resounded the shouts from across the dusky
green playroom, as though one voice representing the 13,120 Centre
Court witnesses. She had their eyes popping with soaring backhand
overheads, slithering slices that seemed hissing snakes at the
queen's feet, and volleying that made you think she could pluck
shooting stars.
</P>
<P>
   The witnesses felt for her. They knew she'd made a choky,
charitable donation of the championship to Steffi Graf five finals
ago, and hadn't been able to hold a 2-0 third-set lead against
Hingis in last year's title bout. Her clock was running, though not
as fast as she.
</P>
<P>
   Few have played as spectacularly in the game's prime showroom.
Novotna had to because plucky little Hingis countered fiercely,
feeling very possessive about her crown, won as the greenest champ
of the century.
</P>
<P>
   You could have named your price with any London bookmaker if you
were hallucinating about Tauziat going all the way. Never better
than a quarterfinalist in 42 previous major starts, she looked
worse than her age at the beginning of a 1-6, 7-6 (7-1), 6-3 surge
past Natasha Zvereva _ just like Novotna. Old bones. Creaky starts.
Flat tires on the wheelchairs.
</P>
<P>
   Tauziat was once a child herself, the women's champion of no
less than the mammoth Central African Republic at 14 _ ``well, only
a few people played.'' She grew up there, the daughter of a French
plumbing supplies salesman.
</P>
<P>
   As the longest shot of all female finalists here, Nathalie was
flirting with some history: the lone Frenchwoman since Francoise
Durr in 1970 to make the semis, and with a chance to be the first
Gallic finalist since _ whew! _ the incomparable Suzanne Lenglen,
champ of 1925.
</P>
<P>
   Wimbledon, the house that the magnetic Lenglen built, could be
Tauziat's. Until she came along in 1919, never to be beaten, the
original ground with 4,500 seats was big enough. The English mobbed
the joint to see her, inspiring construction of the ``new''
(present) layout in 1922.
</P>
<P>
   Durr, an onlooker left over from 1970, and hoping to be
surpassed by her friend, Tauziat, groaned, ``How can she get out of
this grave?'' as Nathalie lost the first set faster than you can
say Billie Jean Moffitt King, the woman who beat Francoise that
day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was embarrassed,'' says Tauziat. ``I was out there with my
big chance of my life and letting me _ everybody _ down. I said to
myself, `Don't let this happen. Fight.''' Lashing out angrily, she
launched an attack. Serving and volleying she caught up and brought
down Zvereva.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back from the dead,'' Durr wept happily.
</P>
<P>
   After beating Graf and Monica Seles, No. 22 Zvereva appeared a
Cinderella in progress, poised to be the only unseeded finalist in
the female annals. Tauziat turned her into a pumpkin. ``I am so
happy,'' smiles she, who came to town with a 13-11 record. ``Not on
the moon yet ... but almost.''
</P>
<P>
   Novotna looked like the moon had fallen on her at the 6-minute
mark. She lost the first 9 points, the first three games, and was
in a crater at 0-40 in the fourth game. Shedding four break points,
Jana was on a moonshot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' Novotna says, ``there are many wonderful new players,
but experience is very important.'' This is her apparently lucky
13th Wimbledon. No doubt the Children's Crusade will regroup, but
there is something to say for age and experience. It is Novotna.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
