</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CHINA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON URGES CHINA TO FOLLOW HONG KONG'S LEAD 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Story will update around 10:45 p.m., CDT) 
 
By CRAGG HINES 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ President Clinton, the first U.S. head of state to
visit this former British colony, called Thursday for the
territory's democracy to be a beacon to the rest of China.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Mike McCurry said Clinton raised the
touchy issue in a meeting with Tung Chee-hwa, the leader imposed on
Hong Kong after the territory was handed over to China a year ago
this week.
</P>
<P>
   To press the issue of political freedom, Clinton planned to meet
Friday with the leading anti-Beijing democrat in the Hong Kong
legislature, who has called on the United States to press China
more on human and political rights.
</P>
<P>
   McCurry called democracy ``an element of (Hong Kong's) future
and its past which is so vital'' and ``provides kind of an
inspiration for what could be the long-term future for the rest of
the People's Republic of China.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton did not mention political reform in remarks at a dinner
hosted by Tung.
</P>
<P>
   Tung told the dinner that Hong Kong ``will gradually evolve our
political structure, with universal suffrage our ultimate
objective.'' But he offered no assessment on when or whether
multi-party democracy might spread to the remainder of China.
</P>
<P>
   Tung stressed that the ``one country, two systems'' policy that
allows limited democracy in Hong Kong was ``working and working
well.''
</P>
<P>
   In his speech Friday to community leaders at the Hong Kong
Convention Center, Clinton planned to sum up his nine-day trip to
China with remarks that also looked more broadly at the question of
Asian stability in the 21st century. It was topical not only
because of Hong Kong's role as a financial center but also because
the city, once considered fiscally unshakable, has been roiled by
the Asian financial crisis and is technically in recession.
</P>
<P>
   Tung said Hong Kong's economy has been ``severely damaged by
this turmoil.'' But survival as a financial center is ensured, he
said, because of spirit, tradition, prudent management, sound
banking and a ``huge foreign exchange reserve.''
</P>
<P>
   Tung called for the United States to continue its leadership
position in combating the Asian crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe me, there is no one in America who is not eagerly
awaiting the resumption of real growth and stability in the Asian
economy, and we are prepared to do whatever we can to support it,''
Clinton responded before exchanging toasts with Tung at the dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``This present financial crisis, too, will pass if we work
together with discipline and vision to lift the fortunes of our
neighbors,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton arrived the day following the first anniversary of Hong
Kong's reversion to Chinese rule, after more than a 150 years as
Britain's principal toehold in East Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Since reverting to Chinese rule, Hong Kong has been governed as
a ``special administrative region'' under the ``one China, two
systems'' policy.
</P>
<P>
   But Hong Kong is not without its anti-Beijing dissidents, and
Clinton planned a 20-minute private meeting Friday with Martin Lee,
head of the local Democratic Party. Lee, a longtime member of the
old colonial legislature, was recently returned to the Legislative
Council in the first election after the hand-over.
</P>
<P>
   Only one-third of the council is elected by all Hong Kong
voters, with the remainder coming from professions and other
political groupings. Under the ``basic law,'' as the new Hong Kong
constitution is called, that proportion would increase to half by
2008, but Lee has called for the entire body and the chief
executive to face popular election much more quickly.
</P>
<P>
   A White House official said that although the Clinton
administration supports the timetable in the basic law, it would
not object to a quicker move to a fully democratic government in
Hong Kong. McCurry said Clinton intended to raise the prospect with
Tung.
</P>
<P>
   Following an afternoon news conference and a ride on one of the
famous Hong Kong Harbor ferries, Clinton was to depart for
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The relatively smooth hand-over is one reason the White House
has felt comfortable in continuing its eager engagement with
China's leaders. Had Beijing decided to crack the whip in the
former colony, U.S. opposition to Clinton's quest for a ``strategic
partnership'' with China would have been even more intense.
</P>
<P>
   Air Force One, Clinton's blue and white 747, touched down at
Chek Lap Kok, Hong Kong's new international airport, after a
65-minute flight from Guilin, where the president had spent the day
admiring the famous limestone mountains from a boat on the Li River
and consulting with Chinese environmental advocates.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was the first visiting foreign leader to use the new
streamlined airport, which opens next week. It replaces Kai Tak,
the in-town field known for its harrowing landing approach between
high-rise apartment buildings. Chinese President Jiang Zemin
dedicated the airport earlier Thursday and then took off for
Beijing from the new field.
</P>
<P>
   Before the hand-over, American presidents avoided Hong Kong, a
convenient Asian refueling spot and beguiling rest stop, because of
its colonial status and touchy geopolitical ramifications. Some
vice presidents and secretaries of state were less circumspect and
would dip into the city's luxurious hotels and restaurants for a
breather in the midst of a grueling Asian fly-around.
</P>
<P>
   A University of Hong Kong poll timed for the anniversary found
Hong Kong residents less confident of the future than they were a
year ago. In the survey, 48.6 percent of respondents said their
confidence had dropped since the hand-over, compared to 18.8
percent who held that view just after the British governor departed
last July.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
