<DOCNO> NYT19980702.0309 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8551 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIANA-MUSEUM-ART-650&AMP;     07-02 1095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIANA-MUSEUM-ART-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONCE-QUIET BRITISH COUNTRY ROADS INUNDATED BY WOMEN IN SEARCH OF
DIANA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(jt) 
 By SARAH LYALL    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREAT BRINGTON, England _ If there were any dissenters here who
found it all a bit much _ the rush of cars on once-quiet country
roads, the $15 commemorative pillboxes, the fresh expressions of
grief that made it seem almost as if Diana, the Princess of Wales,
died last week instead of last August _ they were mostly keeping
quiet Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to talk to you, and I don't want to give my
opinion,'' said one woman, answering the door at her cottage not
far from the gates of Althorp, Diana's childhood home. She did
agree to sell a jar of homemade honey, though, for $2.50. ``You
should have seen the crowds yesterday. One person was very rude.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowds were bound, of course, for Althorp, where Diana's
brother, Earl Spencer, opened a $5 million shrine (and a cafe and
gift shop) to her memory on Tuesday. Until the end of August,
members of the public who have paid $16 apiece and ordered their
tickets in advance will be allowed to tour the earl's new Diana
museum, which rehearses in vivid, sobering detail the now-familiar
stages of her brief life. (If you haven't bought a ticket already,
too bad: they're already sold out for the summer.)
</P>
<P>
   There is an exhibit devoted to Diana's childhood, with grainy
black-and-white home movies of Diana at a tea party, Diana on a
swing, Diana on her tricycle. There is an exhibit that shows her as
the devoted mother of two sons, one the heir to the throne of
England. Her larger-than-life wedding dress, all poofy silk and
satin frills, is on display here, as are a selection of other
outfits. There is also a Christmas card from Prince Charles, a toy
rabbit with an ear missing, and some of the books of condolence
signed by members of the public when she died. And, at an outdoor
clearing, pilgrims can sit quietly and look out across the lake at
the small island that holds Diana's grave.
</P>
<P>
   People who saw the exhibit Thursday pronounced it moving and
surprisingly untacky. ``It's very tasteful and very esthetic,''
said Steven Phillips, an importer and exporter of English and
American collectibles from Dallas, who said he was shifting his
professional attention away from his previous interest _
discontinued, or ``retired,'' Beanie Babies _ into Diana
memorabilia.
</P>
<P>
   Most people seemed to approve of the earl and all his works. But
here in what has become the epicenter of the Diana grief industry,
there were tiny hints of discord. One couple said they were shocked
to see that the hundreds of bouquets and notes left on Tuesday by
the first crowd of visitors had apparently been dumped in a bin
that looked uncomfortably like a huge trash receptacle.
</P>
<P>
   And Lindy Jamieson said she was shocked, period. ``I'm
embarrassed to be here,'' said Ms. Jamieson, a secretary who had
come, she said, only because a friend had begged for her company
and given her a free ticket. ``I know Earl Spencer keeps saying,
`Fancy making money out of her death,' but of course he's done it
to make money.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a serious gender divide seemed to be developing in
and around the Althorp parking lot, a muddy field with space for
hundreds of cars and the early gathering point for visitors. By far
the biggest number of the visitors were women, old and young, in
groups of two, three and four. The relatively few men accompanying
them seemed to be drastically less fervent about the whole thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I only came to prevent a big fight,'' said Brent Abbott, a
U.S. Air Force production superintendent stationed in Germany, who
pronounced the post-Diana phenomenon ``a woman thing'' that was
experienced not by him but by his wife, Belinda.
</P>
<P>
   How could he explain it? ``I guess because she's such a strong
woman and women look up to her,'' he said, looking guiltily at Mrs.
Abbott, who through sheer force of will had herded not just her
husband but their two children out of their base in Germany and
brought them all the way to Althorp. ``Is that a good guess?''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Outside the post office, Wilf Daniels, a 68-year-old resident of
Chelmsford, tried to account for his own presence in the heart of
Diana country. ``My wife's more ... '' he began. ``When you think
of it, really, women followed Diana when she was alive, and most
men are much more interested in their own wives than in other
women. What I want to know is why all these roads around here are
blocked.''
</P>
<P>
   Simon Walton, a service engineer from West Yorkshire, was
carrying a $120 Althorp trinket box bought by his wife, Samantha.
Mrs. Walton, he said, cried when she saw Diana's grave, but he most
certainly did not. ``Look, I was the chauffeur,'' he said. ``I came
to see the house and grounds. They had a lovely staircase made of
oak.''
</P>
<P>
   If many men were having a hard time dealing with all these
feelings, how was Great Brington itself coping? It was hard to
tell. Many of the residents of the village, once a farming
community that is now inhabited mostly by professionals, were at
work. Others treated reporters like so many spawns of the Devil,
rushing into their houses and pulling their curtains across the
windows.
</P>
<P>
   But Martin Whiley, the village postmaster, who has emerged as a
cheery neighborhood spokesman and who is enjoying a rich trade in
special-edition Diana stamps and Princess of Wales postcards, said
that Great Brington had moved past its earlier fears about the
Diana-seeking crowds.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, with several roads around the village now closed,
most people were parking in the designated Althorp parking lot
rather than on Great Brington's streets, he said. Nobody seemed to
be wandering around looking for a public bathroom, perhaps the
village's greatest fear (it doesn't have public bathrooms). And _
softened, perhaps, by Earl Spencer's gracious one-time-only gesture
in waiving the Althorp entrance fee for hundreds of his neighbors
last week _ the residents generally feel positive toward him,
Whiley said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the earl owns about 30 percent of Great Brington,
including the post office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people feel strongly about Diana, and some don't really
care,'' said Whiley, who counts himself among those that do feel
strongly. ``But there it is. We're here, and we have to put up with
it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
