<HEADER>
A8553 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLACKEYE-COX     07-02 0327
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACKEYE-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Journalists' judgement jeopardize credibility of profession
</P>
<P>
   By Lyle V. Harrisc. 1998 Cox News Service ATLANTA -- From the
Monica Lewinsky investigation to CNN's report on Tailwind, 1998 has
been a year of high profile apologies, corrections, and retractions
for the working press. Here are just a few of them:
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 27: The Dallas Morning News is forced to retract a story
based on accounts from a Washington lawyer suggesting that a Secret
Service agent had seen the president and Monica Lewinsky in a
``compromising situation'' inside the White House. The source later
claimed information for the report was inaccurate.
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 9: The Wall Street Journal published a story on its website
and in its early print editions claiming that White House steward
Bayani Nelvis told the grand jury he observed Lewinsky and the
president and Lewinsky in a study outside the Oval Office. After
Nelvis' lawyer attacked the story, the Journal ran a correction
explaining that he had made the statement to Secret Service agents.
</P>
<P>
   May 11: The New Republic Magazine fires associate editor Stephen
Glass for making up major parts of a story about a 15-year-old
computer hacker. Glass also acknowledges ``embellishements'' in
other stories he had written for the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   June 20: Boston Globe columnist Patrcia Smith apologizes to
readers after admitting that she had frabicated characters and
quotes in her work. She is forced to resign, and return an award
for distinguished writing from the American Society of Newspaper
Editors.
</P>
<P>
   June 28: The Cincinnati Enquirer issues a front page apology,
and agrees to pay Chiquita Brands International $10 million for a
series of stories on the company's s business practices. Lead
reporter Mike Gallagher is fired for allegedly stealing voice mail
tapes and failing to disclose that fact to his editors.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
