<DOCNO> NYT19980702.0311 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8555 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IVORY-COX     07-02 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVORY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Media reaction to CNN's retraction mixed By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Reaction within the media to CNN's Tailwind
retraction is double-edged: CNN did the right thing, after a
terrible mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a case of bad journalism followed by responsible
action,'' says Paul McMasters, first amendment ombudsman at the
Freedom Forum Media Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``(But) there's a heightened concern all around relating to
questions of media credibility,'' he adds. ``The message has been
received loud and clear that the public wants to be told when the
media messes up. I believe confession is not only good for the
soul, but good for credibility.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The press should do more of this: when they make mistakes, own
up to them,'' says Tom Rosensteil, director of the Project for
Excellence in Journalism. ``I think it establishes something about
the character of an organization. The way it deals with screwups
says as much about its character as its triumphs.''
</P>
<P>
   But some say that CNN's quick action in retracting the story
shouldn't diminish the enormity of the mistake and the problems
that led to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows a failure from the top down of the organization _ a
failure of reporting, editing, producing and oversight,'' says
Robert Lichter, director of Center for Media and Public Affairs in
Washington. ``It's more troubling than a columnist making something
up. This was a major story that they put resources behind and
intended to make their mark with. It turned out to be a black
mark.''
</P>
<P>
   The environment in which the Tailwind story was born makes it
more troubling than the string of other recent media
transgressions, some media observers say. The story debuted on the
first installment of ``NewsStand,'' a TV newsmagazine designed to
boost CNN's prime time ratings by combining the forces of Time
Warner's CNN and such Time Warner magazines as Time, Fortune and
Entertainment Weekly .
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of us have commented for years about what the
competitive forces have done to create an environment where these
kinds of mistakes are made,'' says Michael Kramer, editorial
director of Steven Brill's Content, a new magazine about the media.
``In this case, you could say it's one of the downsides of synergy.
They wanted to make a big splash. There was a sense of
breathlessness to it (CNN's Tailwind story) that's partially driven
to make this kind of splash and boost ratings.''
</P>
<P>
   ``CNN is on a campaign with Rick Kaplan (the CNN president who
spearheaded 'NewStand') to increase ratings,'' says Marvin Kalb,
director of the Shorenstein Press Center at Harvard University.
``Kaplan is an extremely able producer, but this is going to be a
setback. Rick and other producers work in a climate of such
ferocious competition and bottom-line imperatives that it is not
public service now that is the highest requirement.''
</P>
<P>
   But that competition can't be used as an excuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``The competition is intense, but that does not give the green
light to shortchange accuracy or integrity,'' says Bernard Kalb,
former network correspondent who hosts CNN's ``Reliable Sources,''
a weekly show that examines media issues, including those that
involve CNN. ``No matter how bloodthirsty the competition is, you
cannot surrender the integrity of the reporting.''
</P>
<P>
   Most observers see CNN's quick resolution to the Tailwind
story's controversy as good for the network in the short term. But
the longterm affects are still unknown.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is people forget all the good reporting you've
done when you have a terrible mess like this _ it's going to take
CNN a long time to recover the credibility it justly built up in
the past,'' says McMasters. ``Long term, if CNN upholds the
standards of the past, they can put it behind them. NBC's
'Dateline' (and its discredited truck explosion report) survived
and thrived, and CNN can do the same.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The effects on CNN will be minimal,'' counters Kramer. ``They
would be far greater if the story were continuing over time and
(CNN was) seen as recalitrant in addressing it. It's clear that
anytime you come out and admit an error you're in better shape in
the long run than if you sweep it under the rug.''
</P>
<P>
   But the real effect, some say, has to be internal.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (people at CNN) are some terrifically talented people and
I suspect they will learn from this,'' says Rosensteil. ``If it
causes people at the top to be clearer about what values are
important, that can be valuable. If it causes them to lose
confidence and move into institutional housecleaning, people become
frightened about what they should and shouldn't do.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there was an atmosphere where there was a premium put on
getting the story than on getting it right, they better look deep
inside themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
