u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PLAYERS-COX     07-02 0422
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLAYERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The survivors of the ``Valley of Death''
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA
</P>
<P>
   W. Thomas (Tom) Johnson
</P>
<P>
   Title: Chairman and CEO, CNN Newsgroup
</P>
<P>
   Role: As the controversy grew and it appeared CNN might have
erred, Johnson, the ultimate head of CNN, appointed attorney Floyd
Abrams to conduct an independent investigation and report back to
him. Johnson issued the retraction and apology in his name.
</P>
<P>
   Status: Unchanged
</P>
<P>
   Richard N. Kaplan
</P>
<P>
   Title: President, CNN-U.S., the domestic network.
</P>
<P>
   Role: Brought to CNN in August 1997 to revitalize the network
and improve ratings, Kaplan brought a somewhat controversial
reputation from ABC News. ``NewsStand,'' the show that aired the
Tailwind story, has been Kaplan's project.
</P>
<P>
   Status: Unchanged
</P>
<P>
   Peter Arnett
</P>
<P>
   Title: International correspondent.
</P>
<P>
   Role: Arnett, who made his name reporting from Baghdad during
the Persian Gulf War, was the on-camera reporter for ``Valley of
Death.'' It appears that most of the research that has been
questioned was done by producer April Oliver. Exactly what Arnett's
contribution was to the report, besides providing a recognizable
voice and face, is unclear. Arnett has not commented publicly.
</P>
<P>
   Status: Officially reprimanded, but will remain at CNN.
</P>
<P>
   April Oliver
</P>
<P>
   Title: Producer
</P>
<P>
   Role: Oliver did a lot of the research and interviews for the
story. She can be seen, partially off-camera, in the original
report.
</P>
<P>
   Status: Oliver has left CNN; the network will not comment
further. She reportedly has been fired.
</P>
<P>
   Pam Hill
</P>
<P>
   Title: Senior executive producer of ``NewsStand: CNN &AMP; Time.''
</P>
<P>
   Role: ``Valley of Death'' aired on Hill's watch. She has been a
key player at CNN since joining in 1989, and has headed the
network's investigative unit.
</P>
<P>
   Status: Resigned.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Smith
</P>
<P>
   Title: Senior producer of ``NewsStand: CNN &AMP; Time.''
</P>
<P>
   Role: No. 2 executive at the newsmagazine that aired the story.
</P>
<P>
   Status: Smith has left CNN; the network will not comment
further.
</P>
<P>
   Floyd Abrams
</P>
<P>
   Role: A noted First Amendment attorney, who has worked for CNN
and defended the New York Times in the Pentagon Papers case. He
conducted the independent investigation for CNN. Among his
findings: ``The CNN broadcast was not fair. Information that was
inconsistent with the underlying conclusions reached by CNN was
ignored or minimized.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
