A8560 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABOUT-CARS-CADILLAC-A     07-02 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABOUT-CARS-CADILLAC-ART-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS AMERICAN AS TAIL FINS AND BURNING RUBBER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo will be sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 5) 
(af) 
 By LEONARD M. APCAR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After decades in which Cadillac represented the epitome of
American luxury cars, plans to sell its first truck this fall, a
sport utility vehicle akin to the Chevrolet Tahoe and GMC Yukon.
Cadillac dealers are overjoyed. At last they will have something
for a hot part of the market.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the other sizzling part of the market is the luxury
segment, though you might not be able to tell by hanging out in a
Cadillac showroom. Sales of luxury cars rose last year more than
sales of sport utilities, mini-vans and pickup trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of Cadillac DeVille, though, were scarcely up from a year
earlier. It seems few people under 60 aspire to own one.
</P>
<P>
   What has happened to this American icon underscores a marketing
adage: Great brands don't die; they kill themselves.
</P>
<P>
   When foreign competitors began to redefine luxury cars by
melding performance with the ride and handling of a sport sedan,
Cadillac dawdled. Then, after a few self-inflicted wounds _ the
chintzy Cimarron and the pricey Allante _ younger buyers avoided
Cadillac altogether.
</P>
<P>
   It has been 20 years since Cadillac had a record sales year.
Back then, Lexus didn't exist and Mercedes-Benz and BMW were mere
blips. Lincoln, long the No. 2, added a luxury truck last year, the
Navigator, and is now outselling the General Motors nameplate.
</P>
<P>
   Cadillac has offered both a restyled Seville and the smaller,
German-made Catera to lure sedan buyers from the foreigners. It has
even put a bigger engine in a DeVille, firmed the ride even more,
and crowned it the Concours. None of these have dramatically
revived the brand.
</P>
<P>
   Cadillac's DeVille, a four-door, six-passenger, front-drive
cruiser is heir to the memorable beasts of a generation ago. The
problem with it is not that it handles or rides like the boats of
yore. It mercifully does not. The successful Northstar 4.6-liter V8
engine achieves its 300 foot-pounds of torque at surprisingly low
speeds. Here are 275 horses with 0 to 60 acceleration in less than
eight seconds. That is comparable to a BMW 740iL and a Jaguar XJ8,
which make the nearly $40,000 Cadillac look like a bargain.
</P>
<P>
   (GM has suspended production of the DeVille because of the auto
workers' strike.)
</P>
<P>
   But don't get the idea that you can toss this brute around. The
problem is that DeVille styling comes straight from Boston Whaler.
The bulging sides and swollen rear provide one of the biggest
trunks on the road, but also an oafish look that is painfully blind
to luxury styling today.
</P>
<P>
   At just over two tons, the DeVille could stand some treadmill
time. The Lincoln Town Car, which is longer and wider, weighs less
than a DeVille. The Cadillac's girth also makes you think the big
car is going to be difficult to control.
</P>
<P>
   Inside there is so much empty space between the driver and the
door that when you first get behind the wheel you are certain you
will sway with every turn. But the improved suspension and handling
allowed a lot less bucking and swaying than I had expected.
</P>
<P>
   The interior, however, is dated. It is quiet, and the generous
seats are sculptured and comfortable for four people, roomy enough
for two more. Armrests sport cup holders and storage bins. Air bags
in the dash and the front doors tag all the essential bases.
</P>
<P>
   But imaginative touches are few. A fake veneer crosses the dash
and doors. A computer gives data about fuel economy, mileage, even
engine oil life. Leather upholstery, heated seats and lumbar
support are expensive extras.
</P>
<P>
   A separate temperature control for the front passenger is a
cheap plastic knob. Yet DeVille ranks with the Japanese and
Mercedes in many J.D. Power &AMP; Associates customer satisfaction
listings.
</P>
<P>
   About five years ago, Cadillac updated the DeVille's boaty ride
and handling by giving them a firmer, more precise feel. This is
always a tricky balance: the softer and quieter the ride, the
mushier the handling. And the more precise the steering, the
rougher the ride. The body was made more rigid and the suspension
firmed up.
</P>
<P>
   What was offered in 1994 was a good compromise for a big
American car, but the design was a dud. The rear wheels were partly
hidden, the sides were bulky, and the car lacked panache.
</P>
<P>
   Back at the drawing boards, Cadillac stylists opened up the
rear-wheel wells and moved the wheels out a hair to make the 1997
car look less chubby. The 1998 retains that design. A major
restyling, probably a leaner, European look, is a year or so away.
</P>
<P>
   Cadillac recently got a new, 40-something boss. He told the
styling department to design a 1990s version of the celebrated 1959
Cadillac, the one with big fins and huge V8 power. The stylists are
still at work. That is a good sign. Maybe this time they will come
up with something boomers want to buy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
