u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     07-02 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: STAR SYSTEM IS DECLINING IN THE NBA 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By HARVEY ARATON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New Jersey philanthropist who envisions the Nets becoming
part of Newark's downtown revival apparently did his homework in
basketball economics. Ray Chambers, who helped broker the deal that
will very likely transfer the team to two real estate developers,
called around the sport's power circles and raised the question
that most owners haven't satisfactorily answered themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Of at least two sources, Chambers asked, among other things, why
Finn Wentworth and Stanley Gale of Florham Park, N.J., should plunk
down $150 million for control of the Nets and then face contract
negotiations with Keith Van Horn, Jayson Williams and Kerry Kittles
that would ultimately cost them more than the franchise is worth.
He was told that under the present system, the Nets will wind up
paying Van Horn a $100 million-plus jackpot that would probably
preclude them from keeping the other two players.
</P>
<P>
   Same story as in Minnesota, where ownership can afford Stephon
Marbury or Tom Gugliotta or possibly neither after shelling out
$126 million at boardroom gunpoint last summer for Kevin Garnett.
This entertaining young team is almost certain to die in its
infancy as a result.
</P>
<P>
   ``The days of having three stars are gone,'' one well-connected
agent said recently. ``It's two stars and then managing well enough
to surround them with the right role players.''
</P>
<P>
   This works out if those stars are Michael Jordan and Scottie
Pippen, John Stockton and Karl Malone. Most of the time, it looks
more like Chris Webber and Juwan Howard, teams that function more
like insipid monarchs.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan notwithstanding, the concept of the National
Basketball Association as a quality team sport is the reason to
root for David Stern and the owners in the latest round of labor
chess. Hope for them to somehow lower the ceiling on these $20
million-a-year stars, and not because the commissioner has virtue
on his side, but because the odds of building and maintaining a
cohesive team of diverse skill have become too high.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line that the players had better read is that the
product not only costs too much for the paying fan, it also too
often stinks.
</P>
<P>
   The old-school union thinking, espoused long ago by the late
Larry Fleisher, is that only the superstars, with their rising
salaries, can set the table for everyone else. Not in this market,
though. Now a couple of players, often leveraging only their
potential, gorge themselves and leave behind only minimum-salary
scraps and bones. At last count, there were 150 players making the
minimum. It is almost comical when the union claims it is fighting
for basketball's ``middle class'' at the same time it refuses to
discuss a system that would restore a modicum of sanity to the
top-tier salary.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Ewing is the association's president, and that helps
explain it. For 10 years, Ewing thought collective bargaining meant
him, David Falk and someone from the Knicks. Three summers ago,
Falk the agent informed Ewing and Jordan that the union was about
to cut a deal that would imperil the superstar windfall. Ewing
became an instant activist, and he helped save a system that
produced a cool $66 million for him last summer.
</P>
<P>
   When Ewing demonstrates sympathy for less fortunate teammates, I
will take him more seriously as the representative of all players.
Meanwhile, reporters seeking a few complimentary parting words on
Charles Oakley last week were hung up on. I ran into Ewing at a
dinner in Washington last Friday, asked about Oakley and was
promptly shooed away. Six days after the trade, Ewing finally
addressed the subject, but only at his own news conference to
unveil a painting. What a piece of work.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing complained that no other industry limits salaries, which
is news to postal workers, but there is nothing to prevent him and
Jordan from selling themselves as prime-time programming to CBS,
Disney or Fox. If the $20 million-a-year basketball star makes
dollars and sense, you can bet Uncle Rupert or some other
television network will pay it.
</P>
<P>
   Basketball has always been a star and ego-driven sport, but the
NBA marketeers went too far in exploiting this theme while
expanding and diluting their league, and now the system has
degenerated too much for the players to stop believing in the
parables spun in their behalf. They don't recognize the cyclical
nature of entertainment and sports. Reebok didn't fire Shaquille
O'Neal this week because he doesn't make free throws. People are
tiring of the rap and the hype.
</P>
<P>
   Two stars in basketball is no better a review than it is in the
movies.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-98 1946EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
