<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8563 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EARN-ABSENTS-ART-$ADV     07-02 1296
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARN-ABSENTS-ART-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PLAN FOR UNPLANNED ABSENCES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Mss., N.J., Ill.)  (ART ADV: Graphic on percent of employees absent for various
reasons is being sent to NYT graphics clients. Non-subscribers can
make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 5) 
(bl) 
 By SUSAN J. WELLS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gary Lehl takes pride in his attendance record at work: not a
single unscheduled day off in 6 of his 12 years as a maintenance
mechanic for Continental Airlines at Hobby Airport in Houston. But
it was the phone call he received back in January that really made
his effort seem worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   The call was from Continental chief executive Gordon Bethune and
president Gregory Brenneman. And the news was that the company was
giving Lehl a $40,000 Ford Explorer _ the Eddie Bauer Limited
Edition model _ to reward him for his devotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't hardly believe it, but I knew it sounded like
them,'' Lehl recalled.
</P>
<P>
   He was one of eight winners drawn in Continental's twice-a-year
raffle for employees, at the manager level and below, who have not
missed a day of work during a six-month period.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great incentive,'' said Lehl, 49. ``It creates
excitement among all of us, and people really strive to come to
work and achieve.''
</P>
<P>
   Attendance programs on the scale of Continental's remain
uncommon, but they are among the many tools that companies are
devising in the seemingly endless battle against costly unplanned
absences.
</P>
<P>
   Since Continental, which has 40,000 employees, began its
perfect-attendance program in 1996, it has given away 30 sport
utility vehicles valued, together, at $1.2 million, including sales
tax, title and license fees and gift taxes, all of which the
airline pays for the lucky winners. The payoff is clear, according
to company spokesperson Julie Gardner. The absence rate has been
reduced ``tremendously,'' she said, though she declined to give
specific figures.
</P>
<P>
   Some employers are also improving attendance by becoming more
realistic about the demands on their workers, according to Paul
Gibson, an executive editor at CCH Inc., a publishing and research
firm in Riverwoods, Ill., that surveys employers on absenteeism.
</P>
<P>
   Companies are starting to accept that their employees miss work,
Gibson said, ``not just because of sickness, but because of the
employee's need for personal time to handle everyday life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The absence rate is going down,'' he added, ``as companies
increasingly become savvy to and aware of the results that can be
had by giving employees more control over their time.''
</P>
<P>
   That can represent a big shift in corporate thinking and in
policies addressing time off, Gibson said.
</P>
<P>
   While some employees abuse traditional sick-leave policies, he
said, most don't. Instead, many employees end up with many unused
sick days at the end of the year. And so companies are turning away
from traditional sick-leave policies and toward more flexible
alternatives, like time-off banks that let employees use their days
off as needed for illness, personal days and vacation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Traditional sick-leave policies are just out of step with the
times,'' Gibson said. Last year, when CCH surveyed 451 U.S.
companies employing a total of 750,000 workers, only 9 percent of
the 130 employers who had improved their control of absenteeism
attributed the change to effective traditional sick-leave programs.
</P>
<P>
   The new strategies appear to be working. According to the CCH
survey, unscheduled absences as a percentage of paid productive
time were 2.32 percent last year, down from 2.77 percent the
previous year. The 1997 rate was the lowest since the survey was
first conducted in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, which polled human resources professionals in eight
industries, found that the annual per-employee cost of absences had
also declined, to $572 in 1997 from $603 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Government data confirm the trend. The average annual absence
rate among all American full-time wage and salary workers was 3.9
percent in 1997, according to the Bureau of Labor Statistics, down
from 5.1 percent in 1989, the first year such data were collected.
The government defines absences as instances when full-time workers
put in fewer than 35 hours during a week because of illness,
injury, child-care problems, family or personal obligations, civic
or military duty, or maternity or paternity leave.
</P>
<P>
   Fear of punishment certainly figures in the improved attendance
rates, and many employers say they see a strengthening work ethic,
Gibson said. But he puts greater stock in the new employer
strategies.
</P>
<P>
   A case in point is Fannie Mae, the government-chartered mortgage
finance company, based in Washington. Two months ago, it expanded
its already extensive benefits package after studying why existing
benefits were underused by its 3,700 workers.
</P>
<P>
   Among the innovations is a phase-back-to-work option that allows
new parents to return gradually after childbirth or an adoption
leave. The plan lets new parents work three days a week for four
months after either 12 weeks of paid maternity leave or four weeks
of paid paternity leave.
</P>
<P>
   Fannie Mae also increased its time-off allowances for
bereavement and for caring for sick children. It added 10 paid
hours of volunteer leave per month _ time, for example, that
parents can use to help at their children's schools. And it created
a reimbursement program that allows employees to use an on-site
day-care center in emergencies or to get in-home assistance when a
regular care provider is not available.
</P>
<P>
   ``We asked ourselves if we as employer were saying to employees,
`There are many reasons why you may need to be absent or away from
work,''' said Fannie Mae vice chairman Jamie Gorelick. ``It's a
more mature approach to the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``The need is recognized up front,'' she added, rather than
being ignored until the worker calls in to say he or she will not
be coming in that day.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, not all businesses see it that way. ``On any given
day, supervisors or directors at most companies really don't know
who's working and who's not,'' said Edward Muldoon, vice president
of disability management services at Prudential Insurance Co. in
Newark, N.J. ``Much less do they track it and attach a cost to
it.''
</P>
<P>
   That lack of knowledge has helped generate a cottage industry of
consultants who help employers minimize the costs of unscheduled
absences. For instance, Prudential, working with Work/Family
Directions, a benefits consulting firm based in Boston, has
developed a set of training materials intended to get employees
back to work promptly.
</P>
<P>
   Prudential's absence-and-productivity program teaches managers
ways to discover the real reasons for absences, to make sure the
missing worker's job gets done and to handle chronic absentees. The
kit even includes a pen and a set of 12 greeting cards _ with
sentiments like ``We miss you,'' ``Get well soon,'' and
``Congratulations'' _ that supervisors can send to absent
employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message of this is, `We do feel your absence here, and we
want you back soon,''' said Marybeth McKeown, manager of client
support at Prudential. ``We do everything but write out the card
for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Prudential has supplied hundreds of kits to clients in the last
year and also uses them in its own operations.
</P>
<P>
   The popularity of such a program is easy to understand. If
employees aren't working, productivity suffers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Productivity is all-important in today's competitive
environment,'' said Gibson of CCH. ``Companies are asking employees
to give 110 percent, but the difference we're seeing now is that
they're also starting to ask them how they can help them achieve
that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-98 1947EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980702.0316 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8564 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-PLAN-BOS &LR;      07-02 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-PLAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPAN SAYS PLAN WILL EASE BANKING CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON   
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Giving in to international pressure, Japanese leaders Thursday
announced a comprehensive plan to resolve a banking crisis that has
threatened to drag the United States economy into Asia's financial
woes.
</P>
<P>
   The mountain of bad loans that has piling up in Japanese banks
for years has reached more than $550 billion _ twice the size of
the US's bailout of Texas savings and loan institutions a decade
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Although details of Japan's plan were unsurprising, approval
came two weeks ahead of schedule and was viewed as tacit
acknowledgement that efforts to rescue the financial system are the
government's highest priority. The Japanese plan, which is modeled
on the US bailout plan, will be submitted to the Diet for approval
after national elections July 12.
</P>
<P>
   US Treasury Department officials, who went to Tokyo last month
to pressure the Japanese government to shut teetering banks and
restore public confidence in the financial system, were encouraged
by the detailed measures laid out in a policy statement.
</P>
<P>
   But despite Japan's new bailout plan, there is widespread
concern among government officials and economists the country will
be slow to impose on the taxpayers and businesses the painful and
costly measures required to overhaul rapidly deteriorating
financial system.
</P>
<P>
   ``The recognition that the problems in the large banks have to
be addressed, that selective and targeted use of public money is
necessary, and the importance of selling off bad assets rapidly ...
_ all are potentially constructive,'' a senior Treasury official
said Thursday in reaction to Japan's announcement. ``But what is
important for the crucial goal of market confidence is
implementation through timetables and concrete actions.''
</P>
<P>
   The world is watching Japan closely. The future of Southeast
Asian countries already in political and economic turmoil hinges on
how quickly Japan can deal with its crisis and keep the yen from
sliding further. Economists fear that as Japan sinks further into
recession because banks are unable to lend, it could place a drag
on a thriving US economy or tip it into recession.
</P>
<P>
   Financial markets seemed unimpressed by the plan. The US dollar
rose to 140.99 yen in New York trading, Thursdayup from 138.07 late
Wednesday. Japan's 225-stock Nikkei index moved up 0.66 percent,
closing at 16,471.58.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've announced things before,'' Edward J. Kane, a banking
professor at Boston College, said about Japan's plan. ``There's an
incentive for politicians to understate the problem to the voters
because the taxpayers get angry about having to pay these bills,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The depth of Japan's problems is unknown. Nor is it known how
many of Japan's 19 primary banks are in trouble. Some are
estimating the bad loans are as high as $1 trillion. Prime Minister
Ryutaro Hashimoto has been criticized for failing to face up to
problems left after a speculative ``bubble'' in real estate and
stock prices popped in the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Finance Minister Hikaru Matsunaga announced the plan
immediately after it was approved Thursday by a special government
task force set up last month. ``It is of utmost importance that we
restore confidence in our banking system,'' Matsunaga said.
</P>
<P>
   A senior official of Japan's Ministry of Finance who briefed
reporters said he expects the pace of mergers in the financial
sector to accelerate.
</P>
<P>
   He also said if the 30 trillion yen ($213 billion) earmarked
earlier this year to stabilize the industry was not enough, further
steps would be taken. ``When you go above 30 trillion yen and some
measures need to be taken, there are various measures, ways to
resort to public resources.''
</P>
<P>
   The crisis has infected some of the biggest banks, according to
former US regulators advising Japan. The Long Term Credit Bank of
Japan Inc., which has been on shaky ground, said this week it would
merge with Sumitomo Trust &AMP; Banking Co. in a private sector
solution that would create the country's second-biggest bank, with
$310 billion in assets.
</P>
<P>
   The government's plan would create what is known as a ``bridge
bank'' to provide a temporary home for troubled institutions and
their borrowers. The term is borrowed from government-run
organizations set up by US regulators to oversee Texas banks.
</P>
<P>
   According to the plan, government accountants will comb the
books of financial institutions to pinpoint those in the worst
condition. Troubled banks would be transferred to bridge banks and
run by a newly created holding company known as the Heisei
Financial Revitalization Corp.
</P>
<P>
   There is as much concern about protecting Japan's relatively
healthy banks as there is about dispensing with the bad ones. A
primary goal of the bridge bank is to keep credit flowing to
healthy bank customers as the government takes over insolvent
banks.
</P>
<P>
   As was done when Texas and New England institutions failed,
assets backing the bad loans _ whether real estate or the
collateral from failed businesses _ would be sold to help recoup
the cost to taxpayers of keeping the troubled financial system
afloat.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Wire service reports were used to prepare this article.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
