<SLUG> BC-CHINA-RIVER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT REITERATES ECOLOGY PLEA DURING TRIP ALONG LI RIVER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GUILIN, China _ Admiring the sharp peaks along the Li River,
President Clinton and his family took a water cruise Thursday after
urging China to cut pollution through the use of clean energy.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, before heading to Hong Kong, the final stop on his
nine-day journey, spoke to community leaders at a local park where
he called on China to adopt clean energy sources.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without any loss of economic opportunity we can conserve
energy much more than we do; we can use clean, as opposed to dirty,
energy sources much more than we do; we can adopt new technologies
to make the energy we have go further much more than we do,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   He called on China to avoid the path taken by the United States
and Europe, which resulted in ``more and more pollution to get more
and more growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Later joined by first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton and daughter
Chelsea, the president boarded a cruise boat called Panorama for a
three-hour tour down the picturesque Li River. Looking at the
spectacular tree-covered peaks, Clinton said, ``It's great.''
</P>
<P>
   The president also toured the Yucun Village where he visited
with a store owner, recounting how his grandfather owned a grocery
store in Hope, Ark. Clinton toyed with an abacus used by the
shopkeeper instead of a cash register, telling reporters that ``it
still works.''
</P>
<P>
   The unique landscape here has been the subject of Chinese
paintings and poetry for 2,000 years. A flood last week kept the
president's trip in doubt but the water receded and scores of
Chinese army soldiers cleaned up debris along the banks before the
Clintons' arrival.
</P>
<P>
   This rural region of China also is a step back into time. Rice
paddies hoed by hand line the highway. Water buffalo grazed at
will. Women washed clothes on rocks at the water's edge. Men in
bamboo skiffs fished for food. A young girl practiced tai-chi. A
thriving shopping market lined the cruise's end.
</P>
<P>
   The area, long popular with Chinese, is increasingly becoming a
tourist destination with international flights now from Hong Kong
and Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since Chinese civilization first began to express itself
thousands of years ago, its poems and paintings have sung of the
beauty of the land, the air, the water. No place in China is more
evocative of the beauty of your country than Guilin,'' Clinton said
before his river tour.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
