<HEADER>
A8568 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCMANUS-GREAT-DADS-NY     07-02 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCMANUS-GREAT-DADS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TURN THE HEARTS OF THE FATHERS TO THEIR CHILDREN' 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Mike McManus is a syndicated columnist whose ``Ethics &AMP;
Religion'' appears in almost 100 newspapers)
</P>
<P>
   (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at (800) 444-0267 or (816) 822-8448, or
fax her at (816) 822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By MIKE McMANUS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   GLENARDEN, Md. -- The last verse of the Old Testament envisions
a day when the Lord ``will turn the hearts of fathers to their
children and the hearts of children to their fathers.''
</P>
<P>
   Using that yardstick, America's fathers are far off course. Four
of ten children -- 28 million out of 70 million kids -- do not live
in homes with their biological fathers. Never in history has there
been such an abandonment of children by their fathers.
</P>
<P>
   Those kids are six times as likely as those from intact homes to
be in poverty or commit suicide and 2-3 times as likely to drop out
of school, become pregnant or delinquent as teenagers.
</P>
<P>
   Another 25 to 50 percent of fathers are emotionally absent from
their children. ``The average dad spends 37 seconds with a child a
day. Kids spend six hours a day watching TV. Where are they getting
their values?'' Deacon Lawrence Lee asked a gathering of 119
African-American dads gathered for a ``Great Dads'' seminar the day
before Father's Day at First Baptist Church of Glenarden, Md.
</P>
<P>
   Great Dads is a new national group holding seminars across the
country to teach an ``Action Plan for Being a Great Dad.'' It was
founded by Robert Hamrin, 51, an economist who quit a presidential
campaign in 1983 to work as a consultant so he could spend more
time with his kids, a son who is now 21, and twin daughters, now
aged 17.
</P>
<P>
   Hamrin is the author of ``Straight From a Dad's Heart,'' an
inspiring book that can be ordered for $13 from Great Dads, PO Box
7537, Fairfax Station, VA 22039.
</P>
<P>
   His seminar teaches ``The Six Basics of Being a Great Dad'':
</P>
<P>
   1. Provide Unconditional Love and Affection: Thousands of teens
were asked what single question they would like their parents to
answer. Fifty percent said, ``Do you love me?'' One way to show
that love is to see the uniqueness of each child, and to read them
such Scriptures as Psalm 139: ``I am fearfully and wonderfully
made.'' Hamrin also tells his kids each evening as they go to bed,
``I love you.''
</P>
<P>
   Another key step is to build up each child. For every criticism,
dads ought to give ten compliments -- the opposite of what most
dads do.
</P>
<P>
   2. Spend T-I-M-E. Men pour themselves into their careers, not
kids. Richard Halverson, former U.S. Senate Chaplain, confessed he
should have spent more time with his kids when they were young. His
5-year-old girl once asked, ``Daddy, how come you are hardly ever
home with us?'' Hamrin heard that question when his son was 2, and
he determined never to have that regret.
</P>
<P>
   Love is spelled T-I-M-E. Block out time, say two to four hours
on a weekend, or keep a list of mini-adventures, one or two-day
excursions: to an historical site, a national park or trail, a zoo.
Spend one-on-one time with each child. Take a daughter out on a
``date'' such as a restaurant meal just with her. Or ask your
child, ``How would you like to spend 90 minutes together today?''
</P>
<P>
   3. Communicate Constantly and Creatively: Teens do want to talk
to parents, but when asked who they turn to for help when in
stress, dads ranked 48th on the list. ``If you listen when they are
little, they'll be talking when the subjects are important,'' says
Hamrin. ``If you don't listen now, you may never know when the
truly important things aren't being shared with you.''
</P>
<P>
   4. Partner with Mom: The most important gift parents can give
children is a healthy and vibrant marriage. Tell your kids that
divorce will never be considered. Dads should let moms choose what
is to be done together on a weekly evening out. Parents should
present a united front to children on all matters.
</P>
<P>
   5. Instill Basic Moral and Spiritual Values. ``Write down three
things you are willing to do to contribute to your child's
spiritual development,'' said Deacon Lee. ``It is important for
your child to know that you had to make a journey of faith what God
brought you through.''
</P>
<P>
   6. Establish My Fathering Legacy. ``If you want greatness in
life, do not look for fame, fortune or promotions, but spend a lot
of time with your children, who will live after us,'' says Hamrin.
``Blessed is the man who fears the Lord, who finds delight in his
commands. His children will be great in the land.'' (Psalm 112:1-2)
</P>
<P>
   I was so moved by the day that on Father's Day I penned a
two-page letter to each of my three grown sons, asking forgiveness
for my own failures as a dad, praising them for their achievements
that make me proud, and to underscore how much I love them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-98 1950EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980702.0319 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8569 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-NYT &LR;      07-02 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOVOTNA DOMINATES HINGES TO REACH WIMBLEDON FINAL  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBIN FINN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ Jana Novotna sank to her knees on the cold
grass and pumped her fist with vengeful ferocity. Only the
29-year-old woman who has just taught a lesson to the same
teen-ager who robbed her of her chance to win Wimbledon last year
would comprehend the emotion.
</P>
<P>
   Call it revenge, retribution, or a simple rematch, but Thursday
Novotna made the most of her semifinal assignment against the
top-ranked Martina Hingis and reached her third Wimbledon final
with an aggressive, athletic 6-4, 6-4 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Even more satisfying, Novotna had left the usually smiley Swiss
17-year-old slamming down her racquet in disgust after being beaten
by an oldster in her second consecutive Grand Slam. At the French
Open, it was the resurgent Monica Seles who pounded Hingis into
unwilling submission. Here it was Novotna, who has made a habit of
tearful exits at her favorite Slam tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Last year a triumphant 16-year-old Hingis became Wimbledon's
youngest champion since 1887 by winning the 1997 title at Novotna's
expense. But, after Hingis won three of the four Grand Slam titles
last year, even she acknowledges that her near-invincibility in
1997 has deserted her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I'm not the player I was last year,'' Hingis said.
</P>
<P>
   In Saturday's finale, the third-seeded Novotna will face a
first-time Slam finalist in the 16th-seeded Nathalie Tauziat, at 30
a decidedly undecorated veteran on the cusp of becoming a has-been
even in her native France. Tauziat is a late-blooming net-rusher
like Novotna, and Thursday she celebrated her victory with similar
body language. She collapsed flat on her back on the Center Court
grass after she became the first Frenchwoman to reach a Wimbledon
final since the Suzanne Lenglen won this tournament in 1925.
</P>
<P>
   Tauziat's first Grand Slam finale was achieved at the expense of
another member of tennis' hard-to-kill geriatric generation,
27-year-old Natasha Zvereva, who wilted in the final set of a 1-6,
7-6 (7-1), 6-3 defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, I'm not on the moon already, but almost,'' Tauziat
said.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, it is a long way up for Tauziat, who was thinking
about quitting the tour after a decade of lackluster results. It
took Tauziat 43 Grand Slam campaigns just to reach a semifinal,
more than any other player on the WTA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   She was elated that her belated breakthrough happened here on
the lawns that best reflect her predilection for serve-and-volley
tactics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what I'm going to do if I win the final,'' she
said, ``but I'm very happy that it's in Wimbledon.''
</P>
<P>
   The confrontation between Novotna and Tauziat, whose career
rivalry is deadlocked at 4-4, will present the oldest pair of
Wimbledon finalists since the 31-year-old Virginia Wade won her
historic home turf title by defeating 32-year-old Betty Stove of
the Netherlands in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   This will be Novotna's fourth career Grand Slam final and her
third at Wimbledon. After her first, and most memorable title-round
defeat here in 1993, she cried on the shoulder of the Duchess of
Kent after fumbling away a 4-1 third-set lead against Steffi Graf.
She again received royal condolences after last year's loss to
Hingis.
</P>
<P>
   According to Novotna, the Duchess reminded her last year that
the third time might work like a charm, and so far, she has been on
target.
</P>
<P>
   Though Novotna came into Thursday's semifinal dragging a 2-6
record against Hingis, she not only ignored her four consecutive
losses to the clever counterpuncher but also finessed her way out
of a 0-3, 0-40 opening-set deficit. It was Hingis' turn to be
bedeviled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was like up 3-0, 40-0, and after that, it just changed, like
this,'' Hingis said with an angry snap of her fingernails, ``and
everything just stuck in the net, and nothing would go over
anymore, and she was great at the net.
</P>
<P>
   ``She puts on a lot of pressure because she closes at net very
well,'' Hingis said. ``I hit some great shots, which against other
players would have been a point, but she always got it back somehow
with the slice.''
</P>
<P>
   Pestered by Novotna's continual backhand slicing and flustered
by her unapologetic monopoly of the net, Hingis spewed out 24
unforced errors and countless more forced mistakes. Half of her
volleys wound up in the net or soaring beyond bounds, and her
normally rapacious returns converted just three of the 10 break
chances Novotna allowed her. And on Hingis' service games,
Novotna's studious regrouping after every point had the youngster
impatiently stomping on the baseline.
</P>
<P>
   Hingis won the first 9 points of the match, but when Novotna
decided to pour on the pressure, Hingis had no answer to it. By the
time Novotna had broken her to take a 1-0 edge in the second set,
Hingis had lost seven of the last eight games. Ultimately, the
Swiss teen put Novotna in position to serve for the match by
dropping her serve with a backhand volley blooper to trail, 4-5.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to come in, I tried to stay back. I didn't know what
to do,'' said Hingis. ``I just wasn't patient enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Hingis, who had drawn criticism with her offhand remarks about
the seven-time champion Graf being past her prime, had some kind
words Thursday for her elders. ``She's not the youngest player on
the tour anymore, but sometimes it seems like the older the
better,'' Hingis said, ``and if you see Tauziat on the other side
in the finals, it's amazing. I hope it's going to be that way with
me, also: the older, the smarter, the cleverer, the better.''
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday belonged to Novotna. After beating her doubles
partner in singles, she teamed right back up with Hingis and
reached the semifinals of the women's doubles event, where they are
the top-seeded team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm one year older than last year, but I feel so much younger,
really,'' Novotna said. ``I said to myself today, `I may be older,
but I'm still all over the court.'''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-98 1950EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
