<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FED-REPORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTES SHOW FED IS STILL WORRIED ABOUT INFLATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (See related story, ECON-REPORT) 
(JT) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Despite signs that the economy might be slowing,
the Federal Reserve remained concerned at its May meeting about a
potential outbreak of inflation. Two of the 12 members on the Fed's
policy-making committee voted against the panel's decision then to
hold interest rates steady.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes of the May 19 meeting, released Thursday, suggested that
there was considerable unease within the policy-making group, the
Federal Open Market Committee, about waiting any longer for an
economic slowdown that always seemed to be just around the corner
but never quite materialized. For some members, the minutes said,
the decision not to raise rates ``was a close call.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the committee voted to hold the federal funds target
rate, the primary short-term rate controlled by the Fed, steady at
5.5 percent, it decided then to maintain its formal policy ``bias''
toward a tighter monetary policy, the minutes said, a signal that
it continues to lean toward raising rates in the absence of a clear
slowdown.
</P>
<P>
   The two members who bucked Alan Greenspan, the chairman, and
voted for an immediate interest rate increase were Jerry Jordan,
the president of the Federal Reserve Bank of Cleveland, and William
Poole, the president of the Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis, who
was attending only his second meeting of the committee.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan had also voted to raise rates at the Fed's March 31
meeting, where he was the lone dissenter. One of the features of
Greenspan's tenure as Fed chairman has been to encourage consensus
on interest-rate decisions, and it has been more than four years
since as many as two members broke with the majority on a vote. It
is particularly unusual that a relatively new member like Poole,
who took office on March 23, would dissent.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the Fed again decided to keep interest rates on
hold after a two-day meeting. The decision came in the wake of
further evidence that Asia's financial crisis is helping to slow
growth to noninflationary levels. Those reports were reinforced
Thursday by the news that the unemployment rate edged up in June to
4.5 percent from 4.3 percent the previous month.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes of this week's meeting will be released on Aug. 20, two
days after the Fed's next policy-setting session.
</P>
<P>
   The minutes of the May 19 meeting provided only a dry and
sketchy account of the day's debate.
</P>
<P>
   But the minutes gave a summary of the reasoning of Poole and
Jordan in dissenting from the decision to keep policy on hold. Both
men are monetarists who believe that clues to the likelihood of a
resurgence of inflation can be discerned in the growth of the money
supply. Although rapid money supply growth was discredited as a
predictor of inflation during the mid-1980s because of sweeping
changes to the nation's financial structure, it has lately shown
signs of becoming a reliable early warning signal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Poole dissented because he believed that the sustained
increase in money growth in recent quarters and associated
accommodative conditions in the credit markets pointed to rising
inflation,'' the minutes said.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, the minutes said, was concerned that the rapid growth in
the money supply was fueling speculative excesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``In his view, these high growth rates were fueling
unsustainably rapid increases of real estate and other asset
prices, and reports of `too much cash chasing too few deals' were
becoming more frequent,'' the minutes said. Ultimately, Jordan
said, the Fed faced ``a choice between smaller increases in
interest rates sooner versus larger increases later.''
</P>
<P>
   The members of the committee who voted to keep rates unchanged
cited a variety of reasons for not moving, according to the
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   They said they believed that companies would want to run down
the surprisingly large inventories of supplies and goods they had
built up in the first quarter, resulting in reduced demand. And
they expressed concern that Asia's economic condition continued to
deteriorate, likely leading to further downturns in demand for
American goods.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite the failure of domestic demand to moderate in line
with their earlier expectations, the members were persuaded that
appreciable slowing in the growth of economic activity was a likely
prospect over the course of coming quarters even though its exact
timing and extent was unknown,'' the minutes said.
</P>
<P>
   Reinforcing their decision not to raise rates, the minutes said,
was concern that any increase could have ``outsized effects'' on
Asian financial markets, potentially leading to ``substantial
adverse repercussions on U.S. financial markets and, over time, on
the U.S. economy,'' the minutes said.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the committee added, however, ``that market
considerations could not be allowed to jeopardize the effective
conduct of a U.S. monetary policy aimed at an optimal performance
of the U.S. economy,'' the minutes said. ``Indeed, such a
performance would best serve the interests of troubled financial
markets and economies abroad.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
