<SLUG> BC-ALGERIA-U.N.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALGERIA TO ADMIT U.N. FACT-FINDERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Algeria, which has for months resisted outside
efforts to investigate the violence that has killed tens of
thousands of Algerians since 1992, has agreed to admit a high-level
international political mission, the United Nations announced
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The mission, which the United Nations describes as ``a panel of
eminent persons,'' is expected to leave soon for a fact-finding
trip, after which it is to report to Secretary-General Kofi Annan
on a series of massacres, some of which human-rights groups
attribute to Islamic extremists and some to military death squads.
</P>
<P>
   The team will be led by former President Mario Soares of
Portugal. He will be accompanied by Donald McHenry, a former U.S.
representative at the United Nations; Inder Kumar Gujral, former
prime minister of India; Abdel Karim Kabariti, former prime
minister of Jordan; Simone Veil, a former French Cabinet minister,
and Amos Wako, attorney general of Kenya.
</P>
<P>
   The officials will be buttressed by a contingent of U.N.
technical experts.
</P>
<P>
   Algeria has suffered six years of violence and massacres of
civilians since an election in 1992 was canceled when Islamic
radicals pulled into the lead in what was to have been a two-stage
vote.
</P>
<P>
   Requests by Mary Robinson, the U.N. high commissioner for human
rights, to investigate the abuses have been rebuffed by the
Algerians. This time, however, the government has promised to
cooperate with the new team.
</P>
<P>
   The Group of Eight industrial nations urged Algeria last month
to allow a U.N. mission to study the violence. On Thursday the
secretary-general's spokesman announced that Algeria had agreed
without conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government of Algeria has assured the secretary-general
that it will insure free and complete access to all sources of
information necessary for the panel to exercise its functions in
order to have a clear vision and a precise perception of the
reality of the situation in all its dimensions in Algeria today,''
the announcement said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-98 1958EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980702.0325 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8591 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHICKEN-SOUP-PUBLISHE     07-02 1189
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHICKEN-SOUP-PUBLISHER-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT STORIES OF INSPIRATION BRING SUCCESS TO SMALL PUBLISHER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)  (duplication warning: also sent with `L' code) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(bl) 
 By DOREEN CARVAJAL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEERFIELD BEACH, Fla. _ Far from the center of New York's
literary hub, in a flat-topped industrial building fringed by
Florida palms and flaming pink hibiscus, is a publisher that
produces steamy books in a bouillon of chicken soup flavors.
</P>
<P>
   There is little about the publisher, Health Communications, that
is conventional except that it ladles up best sellers: three
currently on the New York Times paperback best-seller lists last
weekend, including ``Chicken Soup for the Teenage Soul,'' the 17th
book in its warm, shivery and carefully formatted Chicken Soup
series of simplistic and homespun inspirational parables of love,
kindness and triumph.
</P>
<P>
   The company rarely pays author advances, loathes advertising,
binds its own books, offers a company Bikram yoga room and made one
critical business decision based on the teary emotional response of
its co-founder and president, Peter Vegso.
</P>
<P>
   Vegso recalls being so overcome by the original manuscript of
``Chicken Soup for the Soul'' that he could not continue reading.
That did not prevent him, though, from making a calculating
business judgment that has resulted in the sale of 30 million
copies of assorted Chicken Soup titles and ambitious plans to pour
out 75 versions catering to souls from country music fans to
Muslims to orthodontists.
</P>
<P>
   It is the kind of rare, consistent success with a title that
makes other large trade publishers misty for more practical
reasons. ``There's absolutely nothing that comes close to it in all
of the rest of publishing,'' said Laurence Kirshbaum, the chairman
of Time Warner Trade Publishing, which includes Warner Books.
``They are the dream not only of small publishers, but large
publishers.''
</P>
<P>
   The roots of Health Communications are hardly literary and Vegso
is the first to concede that ``when we started in the publishing
business, we didn't know how to do it.'' So he and his partner,
Gary Seidler, did not know it was heretical to offer authors no
advances or that it was highly unusual for a publisher to own its
own a printing press _ let alone for its executives to don blue
jean and operate it.
</P>
<P>
   In 1977, the two men headed south for Florida from their native
Canada in a Volkswagen Beetle. They had a $10,000 grant to sustain
them, along with their skills as a marketing director and a press
officer for the Addiction Resource Foundation in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   They had come to the United States to capitalize on the growth
in drug and alcohol treatment programs by starting a newspaper
aimed at the recovery movement. Eventually they bought their own
printing press to publish pamphlets and books, discovering many of
their authors through conferences that they organized for
counselors and therapists.
</P>
<P>
   But in the years that followed, the company experienced a scary
cycle of rising and falling and rising revenues that could be a
fitting parable for a Chicken Soup for the Publisher's Soul.
</P>
<P>
   Sales plunged in the early 1990s with reductions in government
spending and health-care insurance subsidies for addiction recovery
programs, according to Vegso. Suddenly there was a glut on the
market of therapy-related books as larger trade publishers entered
the field and Health Communications scrambled to keep pace by
pumping chapter-length ideas into full-scale books.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a free for all,'' recalled Vegso. ``We just published
it to death.'' When its revenues, which had reached $17 million in
1990, dropped by 50 percent in 1991 to about $8.5 million and 50
percent more the following year, Health Communications laid off
employees, scaled back its schedule of conferences, and
concentrated on its backlist of steady selling perennial books.
</P>
<P>
   It was during this lull in the company's fortunes in 1992 that
Vegso and Seidler encountered two would-be authors and professional
motivational speakers, Mark Victor Hansen and Jack Canfield. With a
rich history of rejection, Hansen and Canfield had come to the
annual convention of the American Booksellers Association in
Southern California carrying the ``Chicken Soup for the Soul''
manuscripts, dozens of uplifting tales they had written themselves
and compiled from other sources, stuffed in their backpacks.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-three trade publishers had already dismissed the
manuscript, recalled Hansen, who said that essentially the various
editors believed that short stories did not sell.
</P>
<P>
   These were quirky upbeat tales offering lessons in love and
kindness: a rider thanking a cranky New York cabbie for a ``superb
ride'' in hopes that one compliment will multiply in niceness to 20
more fares; a hugging judge who revels in an embrace with a nursing
home patient who smiles for the first time in 23 years; a woman who
is certain that the heart of a mute stroke victim is beating out
the words, ``I love you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We said these aren't short stories,'' said Hansen, 50, who
lives in Newport Beach, Calif. ``These are visceral stories that
touch the soul. They didn't buy it.''
</P>
<P>
   Health Communications did. ``I didn't know I was the 34th
publisher and I really didn't care,'' Vegso said. ``I said, `Sure,
let's do it.' I was in the airport reading it and I was in tears. I
had to stop because I thought people would think there was
something wrong with a grown man crying in the airport.''
</P>
<P>
   It took more than a year for the first Chicken Soup to claw its
way onto The New York Times best-seller list. Health Communications
benefited from the fact that the authors were professional speakers
and tireless promoters, who developed their own intensive marketing
system, which included the fundamental daily rule of seeking ``five
media hits,'' or interviews, with small radio stations, newspapers
and regional television shows.
</P>
<P>
   The authors also sought unconventional outlets for their books,
from bakeries and nail salons to motivational seminars and pet food
stores. They asked dozens of their friends to buy 100 books each to
sell to their friends. They persuaded Celestial Seasonings to print
sample stories on its tea boxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call it bypass marketing,'' said Hansen, the co-author of
the series. ``Health Communications is the publisher and the
distributor and we're going to do all the promoting and marketing.
As you know, a book usually has 30 days on the market before they
pull it off the shelf.''
</P>
<P>
   And for their long list of sequel books, the two authors created
a focus group of readers and friends, Hansen said, who literally
grade stories for ``goosebumpy'' buttery emotions on a scale of 1
to 10.
</P>
<P>
   These critical lessons of self-promotion are factors that Health
Communications weighs when it picks its authors, who typically are
professional speakers with established forums to promote their own
books.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   It published two unlikely paperback best sellers this year, ``A
Child Called `It''' and its sequel, ``The Lost Boy,'' which are
based on the grim childhood memories of Dave Pelzer, a professional
speaker from California with a keen sense of humor who, as he puts
it, can talk in a disarming way that ``makes child abuse funny.''
</P>
<P>
   His first book _ written in a simple child's voice, but without
the lyricism of Frank McCourt's childhood chronicle ``Angela's
Ashes'' _ is a relentless description of his abuse at his late
mother's hand. Pelzer accuses her of every level of torture from
beatings to knife wounds.
</P>
<P>
   The book was first published in 1993 and initially did not sell
that well, according to Pelzer, who decided to invest his own money
in promotion by hiring several regional public relations firms and
increasing his speaking engagements, which finally culminated in a
breakthrough appearance in 1997 on ``The Montel Williams Show''
that increased sales dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   Pelzer said that he was initially referred to Health
Communications by one of the Chicken Soup authors. ``They were
small and privately owned and I'm thinking that with a bigger house
I might get more money, but I might get lost in the shuffle,'' he
said. ``One of the things that impressed me is that Peter sent me a
letter welcoming me to the family.''
</P>
<P>
   And eventually, Pelzer would truly make it a family, becoming
engaged to his editor from Health Communications.
</P>
<P>
   The success of Chicken Soup and Pelzer's two titles has
obviously made a difference in Health Communication's fortunes,
increasing its revenue to $85 million last year, according to
Vegso. And like any small publisher, he is well aware that at any
time one of his larger rivals in distant New York might try to
snatch away one of his successful authors.
</P>
<P>
   Already there are a host of imitators of the Chicken Soup series
by rival publishers and knock-offs from Health Communications
itself (``Taste-Berry Tales: Stories to Lift the Spirit, Fill the
Heart and Feed the Soul,'' or ``Puppies for Sale and Other
Inspirational Tales.'')
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Vegso's partner, Seidler, decided to withdraw from
full-time work at the company to act as a consultant to Health
Communications, but Vegso said he remained content to stay at the
company, dividing his time between books and his horse breeding
farm in nearby Ocala.
</P>
<P>
   Leaning back in his office chair, he toyed with a hand-crocheted
chicken given to him by a reader while talking about why he enjoys
his job so much. His reasons are the sweet essence of Chicken Soup
parables. ``I like the fact that we help a lot of people,'' he
said. ``People will come up and say that you've saved my life.
That's nice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
