<SLUG> BC-WINDS-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE WINDS OF GOD': POWERFUL _ AND PERHAPS COURAGEOUS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes at end of review.) 
(lh) 
 By D.J.R. BRUCKNER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In Masayuki Imai's play ``The Winds of God,'' two
comedians in modern Tokyo recover memories they were unaware they
had lost, and with them a chapter of history often avoided in Japan
as simply too bitter to dwell on. Wiped out in a motorcycle
accident on a Tokyo street, they find themselves reincarnated as
airmen training to be kamikaze pilots in the final days of World
War II. Other pilots in the squadron all treat them like old
friends, and gradually the two realize that the men they now
inhabit must have been former selves who died on suicide missions
to destroy American ships.
</P>
<P>
   Imai, a popular film and television star in Japan, wrote the
play in English. In the production at the Judith Anderson Theater,
he and six other Japanese actors, all making their New York debuts,
exchange jokes, insults and confidences so easily they leave the
impression that smart American street talk is their native tongue.
This is all the more striking since tone and inflection reveal many
unspoken meanings in a work that is more subtle and complex than it
seems.
</P>
<P>
   The comedians are very funny, in part because they are not very
good at their trade. Their plunge into a past they had only vaguely
heard of gradually becomes a painful enlightenment as they discover
not only the harshness, fanaticism and cruelty of the old
militaristic society but also its discipline and patriotism. The
period's unselfish dedication makes the rich, self-satisfied
individualism of half a century later seem tawdry.
</P>
<P>
   Although there is laughter almost to the last lines, this cast,
directed by Imai, lets one feel the intense emotional and spiritual
struggles of each pilot in the squad, a group of strong
personalities marked by the idealism, hopes and fears of youth.
</P>
<P>
   There are passages that descend into melodrama, a military
training scene that is nothing but noise, and the last episode
seems a peculiarly awkward conclusion to an elegant exploration of
the unaccountable influence of history on the individual. But on
the whole, ``The Winds of God'' (virtually a translation of
kamikaze) is a powerful play, perhaps a courageous one. It
effectively pulverizes an assumption we all too readily make: that
we can easily comprehend the past and fairly judge our forebears.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE WINDS OF GOD'
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Masayuki Imai; production consultant,
Frank Corsaro; producer, Kimie Usui; production manager, Kazuko
Yamamoto; associate producer, Fumiko Inoue; stage manager and set
designer, Toshiyuki Tashiro; lighting, Minoru Hiroi; sound,
Tadanori Hirata; production assistants, Yuko Yunokawa, Mayumi
Suzuki and Michika Yokosawa. Presented by Elle Company. At the
Judith Anderson Theater.
</P>
<P>
   With: Masayuki Imai (Aniki and Lieutenant Commander Kishida),
Mashahiro Matsumoto (Kinta and Lieutenant Fukumoto), Atsushi
Yoshida (Squadron Commander Yamada), Masanobu Yada (Lieutenant
Commander Terakawa), Rome Kanda (Lieutenant Matsushima), E. Ozaki
(Lieutenant Yamamoto) and A. Takada (Nurse).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
