<HEADER>
A8597 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-PEPSI400-POSTPONE     07-02 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-PEPSI400-POSTPONED-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TERRY BLOUNT  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ NASCAR officials were expecting to make
history this week, and they did. But postponing the Pepsi 400 is
not what they had in mind.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Winston Cup event scheduled for Saturday night, which was
going to be the first NASCAR race televised by a major network in
prime time, was postponed Thursday because of the raging wildfires
that have engulfed a large portion of northeast Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The event has been rescheduled for the evening of Oct. 17, with
qualifying Oct. 15-16.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the fires intensified, we felt the right thing to do was
postpone the race and focus all our efforts on helping the
community fight this situation,'' said John Graham, president of
the Daytona International Speedway. ``The emergency people we would
have had at the track this week will be at the fires now. This is a
most difficult situation. The community is our primary focus.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the area around the speedway is under a mandatory
evacuation. Interstate 95, which is a main road for spectators
coming to the speedway, was closed in both directions at Daytona
Beach. It would have been nearly impossible to get cars in and out
of the facility.
</P>
<P>
   Wildfires south and west of Daytona Beach have caused a smoky
haze over the 2.5-mile racetrack, which would have made a dangerous
situation for the drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Qualifying was scheduled for Thursday night and tonight before
the first-ever Winston Cup night race at DIS. It was expected to be
a milestone event for NASCAR because of CBS' live coverage, but the
first prime-time broadcast might have to wait a year.
</P>
<P>
   CBS officials will make a decision next week about whether they
will carry the race in October. Two things are working against CBS
opting to cover the race _ the entertainment division already may
have sold advertising for original programming on that date, and
the World Series begins that night on Fox.
</P>
<P>
   It is possible the race will be shown on cable network TNN, but
that would be a far cry from the original plans with CBS.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all are very frustrated,'' CBS commentator Ralph Sheheen
said. ``We had this date circled on our calendars. There was a real
buzz about this race.''
</P>
<P>
   The $5 million lighting project at the speedway, which was done
over the past year and completed last month, is believed to be the
largest ever for a sports arena. It required 1,835 lamps around the
tri-oval to generate as much light as the high beams of 87,000
passenger cars.
</P>
<P>
   Musco Lighting, which installed the lights, said the lighting
was equivalent to the standard residential lights of 24,285 city
blocks on a road stretching from Daytona Beach to Musco's
headquarters in Muscatine, Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody had ever tried to put this much light on something this
big,'' Musco president Joe Crookham said.
</P>
<P>
   Having to postpone the event is a huge disappointment for race
officials, especially since the race was a sellout for the first
time. All 143,000 grandstand seats had been sold, and at least
30,000 more spectators were expected in the infield.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have maintained all along that we would not do anything
that might compromise public safety,'' DIS media director John
Story said. ``After talking about it throughout the night
(Wednesday), we decided the responsible thing to do was to postpone
the event.
</P>
<P>
   ``This possibility has been in the back of our minds since the
wildfire problem began, but we were confident we could get the race
in.''
</P>
<P>
   Previous Pepsi 400 races were run during the day on July 4 in
scorching heat, which kept some fans from attending. But the chance
to see a Winston Cup race under the lights in cooler conditions
obviously was appealing to the expected crowd of more than 175,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those fans need to hold on to their tickets because they will
be honored in October,'' Story said. ``The same is true for the
tickets for the qualifying nights.''
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of fans already had arrived and parked their
recreational vehicles in the infield, but they packed up and headed
out when they heard the news Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was down there earlier, and a lady from Pennsylvania heard
me talking to some drivers,'' Story said. ``She walked up to me and
said she was sorry she had come so far, but she knew we were doing
the right thing. That seems to be how most people feel.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the drivers arrived Wednesday but learned less than 24
hours later they would be heading home for the Fourth of July
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sad to see this happen,'' said John Andretti, who won the
event last year. ``But it was obvious that things with the fires
got so much worse the last two days that there was no way they
could carry on with the race.''
</P>
<P>
   By moving the event to Oct. 17, it means Winston Cup teams will
have to race on 16 consecutive weekends, starting with the
Pennsylvania 500 at Pocono on July 26.
</P>
<P>
   The Pepsi 400 gains some added pressure for the drivers in the
points chase for the championship since it will be closer to the
season-ending NAPA 500 at Atlanta on Nov. 8.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
