<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWISS-BANKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TO IMPOSE SANCTIONS ON SWISS BANKS SEPT. 1 IF NO ACCORD
REACHED 
</HEADLINE>
  (Also moving in `a' category) 
(JT) 
 By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Officials of the City and State of New York said
Thursday that they would begin imposing sanctions on Swiss banks on
Sept. 1, hoping that the two-month ``cooling off period'' would
persuade Swiss bank officials and lawyers for Holocaust survivors
and heirs to reach a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Barring Swiss banks from bidding on overnight deposits, which
average more than $2 billion just for the city, would be the first
step, followed in stages by barring other business, canceling
existing contracts and selling all stocks in Swiss companies.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department said sanctions, last used to bring pressure
to end apartheid in South Africa, were ``unjustified, unwarranted
and counterproductive'' to reaching a quick settlement of the
claims of Holocaust survivors, whose average age is 81.
</P>
<P>
   Sanctions could undermine New York's position as the financial
capital of the global economy by raising doubts about how open
American financial markets are, Under Secretary of State Stuart
Eizenstat said in an interview. He also said that he had urged the
Swiss government to ``not overreact'' to the sanctions and
retaliate with actions that could make a settlement more difficult
to achieve.
</P>
<P>
   Two Swiss banks, UBS and Credit Suisse, offered $600 million
last month to settle claims.
</P>
<P>
   Mel Weiss, one of the lawyers for the survivors, heirs and
charities representing heirless assets, proposed settling the case
for $1.5 billion, provided the Swiss government and the Swiss
National Bank joined in a ``global settlement.''
</P>
<P>
   The talks collapsed after Weiss made his proposal last month.
The sanctions were announced by the city comptroller, Alan Hevesi,
and the state Comptroller, H. Carl McCall, a day after a meeting in
which they said that the Swiss consul general in New York, Jacques
Reverdin, told a panel of state and local government finance
officials that the Swiss government would never contribute to a
restitution fund.
</P>
<P>
   Hevesi said Reverdin's statements revealed a change from the
posture the Swiss government had taken in private talks, which he
said was to signal it would ease a ``global settlement'' to resolve
all claims. These, he said, would include those against the Swiss
government and its Central Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Hevesi said the Swiss government's position amounted to
``denying moral responsibility'' for buying stolen assets,
including gold removed from the teeth of Nazi death-camp victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``No punishment is being asked, no penalty,'' Hevesi said. ``It
is restitution we seek.''
</P>
<P>
   Hevesi pointed to a May 25 report by a panel created by the
Swiss government, known as the Bergier Commission, which concluded
that by 1942 Swiss government officials knew the gold the Nazis
sold to them was looted from Jews, a practice that was so obvious
that it could be discerned by careful readers of Swiss newspapers.
He said the report should have spurred the Swiss government to
``prepare its people'' to support a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Reverdin said that the Swiss government had been unwavering in
its position that all claims concerning assets that the Nazis stole
from Jews and then sold to the Swiss National Bank were resolved by
a 1946 agreement reached in Washington and signed by the World War
II Allies.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a settled matter and there is no reason to reopen
it,'' Reverdin said.
</P>
<P>
   Eizenstat said the Swiss government had never changed its
position that it would support any settlement that the two banks
might reach, but that it was not a party to the talks and was not
obligated to pay.
</P>
<P>
   Swiss banks were paid about $31 million in investment fees by
the city in the last year, more than 10 percent of the $285 million
that the city spent on investment management, advice and broker
commissions, Steve Newman, the first deputy city comptroller,
estimated.
</P>
<P>
   McCall's office could not immediately supply comparable figures.
</P>
<P>
   If all 800 state and local government finance officers were to
terminate short-term investment dealings with Swiss banks, the
annual fees would quickly total more than the $900 million
difference between the banks' offer and Weiss' proposal.
</P>
<P>
   The sanctions plan calls for the city and state to begin
sanctions on Sept. 1 by barring overnight investments with Swiss
banks, new letters of credit agreements and taking part in
underwriting new state and city debt.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 15, if no settlement is reached, Hevesi and McCall will
recommend excluding Swiss companies like Scudder Kemper Investments
and SBC Warburg Dillon Read &AMP; Co. from searches for new pension
fund investment managers and barring existing managers from doing
business through Swiss companies.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 1 the two officials would recommend canceling existing
investment management contracts, like a CS First Boston contract to
manage $740 million for the city pension fund. They would also ask
the Legislature and City Council to pass laws barring Swiss
companies from selling goods and services to the state and city.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, on July 1, 1999, they would seek to have the $106
billion state pension fund and the $82 billion city pension fund
begin divesting their holdings in Swiss companies. The city owns
$735 million in stock in Swiss companies, including $136.7 million
in the Swiss banks, Hevesi said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
