<HEADER>
A8602 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMISH-DRUGS-600&AMP;ADD-N     07-02 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMISH-DRUGS-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 AMISH ARRAIGNED IN DRUG-DISTRIBUTION SCHEME 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ At a glance, they looked little different from
any other defendant indicted on illegal drug charges. Standing
before Judge Jay Waldman at their arraignment in U.S. District
Court Thursday morning, the two men with the same name looked
frightened, anxious, perhaps even a little embarrassed.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Abner King Stoltzfus, 23, and Abner Stoltzfus, 24, who
are not related, are anomalies in the federal criminal justice
system. Authorities here say they are the first two members of
Pennsylvania's Amish community to be arrested for involvement with
cocaine and methamphetamine.
</P>
<P>
   Along with eight members and associates of a motorcycle gang
known as the Pagans, the Stoltzfuses were indicted after a
five-year investigation in Lancaster County, and they now face
charges that could bring them a mandatory minimum of 10 years in
prison. Nine of the defendants, including the Amish men, pleaded
not guilty; a 10th defendant, Natalie King, is to be arraigned next
week.
</P>
<P>
   As Waldman explained the procedure to each of the Stoltzfuses,
seven of their relatives and close friends, all dressed in typical
Amish wear, sat silently in the third row of the courtroom, hiding
their somber faces from courtroom artists in accordance with their
belief that it is a sin of vanity to have your likeness reproduced.
</P>
<P>
   For generations, the Amish have lived lives different yet not
entirely apart from mainstream America. In their eastern
Pennsylvania communities of Gap, Intercourse, Paradise and other
small towns, they work as farmers, craftsmen and small-business
owners who have raised families under the strictures of their
church and the quaint ways of a bygone era: They eschew such basic
conveniences as electricity and travel in horse-drawn buggies.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, they have been poster people for all that America
cherishes: strong family values, accountability, responsibility, a
deep faith in God.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent years, suburban sprawl westward from Philadelphia
has invaded their turf. Though it has brought new jobs at a time
when fewer Amish are tending to farms that are generations old, it
has also brought them wider exposure to commercial America and the
fast-paced enticements of modern life, which includes, as the
Stoltzfuses' case may demonstrate, some of its unsavory elements.
</P>
<P>
   Were it only alcohol involved in charges against them, the
levels of surprise and bewilderment among the Amish might not have
been so high. Typically, Amish teen-agers are permitted several
years of discovery outside the traditions of family and church to
help them decide whether they want to re-enter their church and
community for the rest of their lives. Often during that period,
known as timeout, the youth join groups that meet in social
settings the Amish call hoedowns, where tabooed activities like
drinking, smoking and driving cars are common.
</P>
<P>
   ``Times are a-changing,'' Robert Ham, who has been the police
chief for 28 years in Strasburg, a Lancaster County town of 3,000,
said in an interview earlier this week. ``Their young folks get out
into the world. They believe in sowing their wild oats while
they're young.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was not until recently that Amish elders had any notion
that some of their young might be involved with illegal drugs. Ham
said he was not surprised, inasmuch as many Amish young men, like
the Stoltzfuses, residents of Gap who earn money as roofers, find
work outside their communities, where temptations loom closer.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're no different than anybody else,'' Ham said. ``They're
looking for the bigger and better high.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For now, it is unclear what the Stoltzfuses might have been
looking for, if anything. The government contends that they joined
with Pagans and others in a scheme to distribute cocaine and
methamphetamine over a five-year period through last July. Lawyers
for the Amish men declined Thursday to discuss the case, which is
scheduled for trial with all 10 defendants in October.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, the possible involvement of the Stoltzfuses made
it apparent to many within the Amish community, as well as to
outsiders, that their venerated way of life may stand apart in
superficial fashion only.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the physical appearance, alone, of Abner King Stoltzfus
in court seemed to suggest a tension between the Amish world and
beyond: He wore the traditional black pants and suspenders of an
Amish elder but a shirt that was bright blue, rather than white,
and expensive white sneakers, rather than nondescript black shoes.
Also, his hair was cut stylishly short, with sharply-angled
sideburns. Most Amish men wear their hair much longer and in no
discernible style.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many people have an idealistic view of the Amish and treat
us as if we are wonderful people,'' said a 44-year-old Amish woman
named Rebecca, who manages an office in Strasburg and asked that
her last name not be used. ``I love the Amish people, but we have
our faults and our problems. It's not good for us to be looked upon
as morally great. We aren't perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Dominguez, the assistant U.S. attorney who is prosecuting
the case, cautioned against broad-brushing all Amish because of the
possible actions of a few. ``The Amish have a well-deserved
reputation as hard-working, decent people,'' Dominguez said. ``This
indictment does not change that.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hope Leferber, a lawyer for one of the Pagans, Douglas
Hersh, 29, predicted that the trial might at least prove Rebecca's
view correct, blurring the lines of distinction between public
perceptions of Pagans as rough-hewn thugs and of Amish as rustic
gentlemen.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're making the Amish out to be pristine, untarnished young
men, corrupted by the evil Pagans,'' she said. ``The truth be
known, these kids are the same as any other kids who surrender to
the temptations of youth. They weren't corrupted. At best, they
were willing participants.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
