u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-INVESTIGATION     07-02 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-INVESTIGATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIPP WRAPS UP SECOND DAY OF TESTIMONY IN CLINTON INVESTIGATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Pentagon worker Linda Tripp appeared again Thursday
before a federal grand jury investigating an alleged presidential
affair and cover-up as supporters tried to counter the perception
that she betrayed Monica Lewinsky as part of a book deal,
</P>
<P>
   While Tripp, whose tapes of her telephone conversations with
Lewinsky prompted the inquiry, spent almost 6 1/2 hours with grand
jurors, her supporters tried to portray Tripp as unwittingly caught
up in the events at the heart of the inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   As she left the U.S. District Courthouse, Tripp ignored
questions about the effort to recast her image. Asked how she was
feeling after two days of closed-door questioning by the grand jury
and independent counsel Kenneth Starr's deputies, Tripp responded:
``Well.''
</P>
<P>
   Escorted by uniformed federal police, Tripp, her attorneys and a
spokesman swept past reporters and out of the building to a minivan
for the short ride to her the lawyers' office, then to her suburban
Maryland home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Linda is actually very encouraged by the quality and content
of the questions presented by the grand jurors and the
prosecutors,'' said Joe Murtha, one of her lawyers. ``If there is
any truth to the adage that an honest person's pillow is peace of
mind, I assure you that Mrs. Tripp will sleep very well tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to characterize her testimony, Murtha said it is ``so
comprehensive'' that discussing any of it ``wouldn't serve any
purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   Murtha said Tripp will be returning to the grand jury but
Starr's office has not indicated when.
</P>
<P>
   Tripp's testimony comes in the fifth month of Starr's
investigation into whether the president or his associates tried to
cover up his alleged sexual encounters at the White House with
Lewinsky or Kathleen Willey.
</P>
<P>
   Tripp, 48, a former White House secretary who was transferred to
the Pentagon, became friends there with Lewinsky, 24. Like Tripp,
Lewinsky had been transferred to the Pentagon from a job at the
White House, a full-time, paying position she was given after her
internship ended in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Tripp, a holdover from the Bush administration, had been
appalled by the behavior and relaxed dress around the Clinton White
House. In 1996, Tripp contacted New York publicist Luciana Goldberg
about a book deal, but it never developed. The working title was
``Behind Closed Doors: What I Saw at the Clinton White House.''
</P>
<P>
   In October 1997, Tripp again contacted Goldberg after Clinton's
lawyer, Robert Bennett, called Tripp a liar for comments she made
in Newsweek magazine about a November 1993 encounter between
Clinton and Willey near the Oval Office. Willey has testified that
the president groped her.
</P>
<P>
   When Tripp talked to Goldberg about Bennett's remark and the
tales Lewinsky was telling, Goldberg suggested taping telephone
conversations with the former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   During the next several weeks, Tripp compiled 20 hours of
conversations in which Lewinsky reportedly says she and the
president had an 18-month affair. The tapes have been turned over
to Starr and the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   When it became apparent that they might have to testify in the
Paula Jones sexual harassment lawsuit against Clinton, Lewinsky
told Tripp that Clinton urged her to lie about their relationship,
according to published reports about the tapes' contents.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the Jones lawsuit, Clinton and Lewinsky denied the
affair under oath. Clinton has said publicly he never asked anyone
to lie.
</P>
<P>
   The tapes, Tripp's defenders say, include her warning to
Lewinsky that she planned to respond truthfully when questioned by
Jones' lawyers. In one conversation, Tripp reportedly urges
Lewinsky to tell the truth and encourages her to caution the
president not to lie when questioned by Jones' lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Citing e-mail messages Tripp sent to Lewinsky in late 1997, one
unnamed source quoted by The Associated Press said that Tripp tried
to end her friendship with Lewinsky last fall, about three months
before the investigation began. Those e-mail messages, the unnamed
source told AP, indicate that she tried several times to get
Lewinsky to stop calling and visiting to discuss Clinton and their
alleged affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please give me a break; I can't take this,'' Tripp wrote in an
e-mail letter to Lewinsky on Oct. 27, 1997, the source told AP. On
Nov. 24, another e-mail to Lewinsky from Tripp said: ``The
information alone is a heavy burden, one I did not ask for.'' Tripp
spokesman Philip Coughter confirmed the content of the messages,
which have been turned over to Starr.
</P>
<P>
   The effort to burnish Tripp's image is designed to counter the
findings of recent polls, which show the public holding unfavorable
views of the career government worker.
</P>
<P>
   A CNN-Time poll released Thursday shows 52 percent of Americans
have an unfavorable view of Tripp while 12 percent view her
favorably. The rest do not recognize her name.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the survey of 1,024 adults conducted June
30-July 1, found that Tripp's image was not as tarnished as
Lewinsky's. Sixty-nine percent of those polled had an unfavorable
opinion of the former intern; 12 percent viewed her favorably.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
