<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8610 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-CLINTON-ART-2TA     07-02 1010
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-CLINTON-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON, IN HONG KONG, ADDRESSES ASIAN ECONOMIC WOES 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: CHINA-CLINTON, CHINA-REPUBS, CHINA-NOTEBOOK) 
(ART ADV: Graphic on Clinton's China trip is being sent to NYT
graphics clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(bl) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ President Clinton arrived in Hong Kong, the heart of
free-market China, Thursday evening and pledged that the United
States would do its part to lift Asia out of its economic quagmire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want you to know that the United States considers Hong Kong
vital to the future,'' said Clinton at a banquet hosted by the
chief executive of Hong Kong, Tung Chee-hwa. ``This present
financial crisis, too, will pass, if we work together with
discipline and vision to lift the fortunes of our neighbors.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's visit to Hong Kong, the first by a sitting U.S.
president, came one day after the former British colony marked the
first anniversary of its return to China. And it gives him the
opportunity to assess one of the grander experiments in modern
political history: China's pledge to let Hong Kong remain a
capitalist enclave in the world's last communist empire.
</P>
<P>
   These days, economics are overshadowing politics here. Hong Kong
is suffering badly from the Asian financial contagion, and Clinton
will make the Asian economy the centerpiece of a major speech
Friday, in which he is expected to offer a more detailed analysis
of the region's economic problems.
</P>
<P>
   ''Hong Kong is a world symbol of trade, enterprise, freedom, and
global interdependence,'' said Clinton, who looked weary despite
having relaxed earlier in the day on a two-hour boat trip on the Li
River near Guilin, in south China. He used the visit to Guilin to
discuss China's dire environmental problems.
</P>
<P>
   After flying here he praised Hong Kong and China for being
anchors of stability in a region-wide economic storm _ a reference
to the fact that neither government has devalued its currency,
despite the continued weakness of the Japanese yen and a wave of
tit-for-tat devaluations across the region.
</P>
<P>
   Tung, a shipping magnate appointed by Beijing shortly before the
handover, welcomed the president's show of support, saying that
``what started as a regional crisis has taken on a global
importance.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton met privately with Tung for 20 minutes before the
banquet, during which they discussed the economy, according to
White House spokesman Mike McCurry. But he said Clinton also
pressed Tung to accelerate the introduction of democracy to Hong
Kong by allowing voters to elect a larger percentage of legislators
directly.
</P>
<P>
   Tung, who long lived in the West, is not known as a champion of
democracy. In his remarks at the banquet, he pointedly reminded
Clinton that Hong Kong was a Chinese city. ``The fact is, we are
Chinese and were brought up in Chinese tradition and values,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Clinton will be able to sample the new Hong Kong _ with
a hectic series of meetings and appearances that will bring him in
contact with newly-elected politicians, both friendly and hostile
to Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   James Steinberg, the deputy assistant to the president for
national security affairs, said the Clinton administration wanted
to demonstrate that the United States ``continues to be active and
involved and concerned about preserving Hong Kong's autonomy and
strengthening democracy there.''
</P>
<P>
   But the White House has landed in a minor tempest over a meeting
with Hong Kong's most prominent pro-democracy leader, Martin Lee.
Clinton is scheduled to meet alone with Lee on Friday, a move
likely to displease Beijing. But the White House has barred press
coverage of the meeting, except for a photographer, and will issue
no public statements afterward, upsetting Lee and his supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Steinberg said the restrictions were ``normal practice'' when
Clinton meets with opposition leaders. Lee's aides said the White
House was seeking to assuage the Chinese, and had originally balked
at a one-on-one meeting, even though Lee has met Clinton before in
the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   If true, the White House may have ended up irking both sides.
Lee said he found the decision ``very odd, because it seems to me
that President Clinton's whole visit to China has been televised.
Why does he stop with me?''
</P>
<P>
   After that meeting, Clinton will sit down with a group of Hong
Kong leaders, including Lee and three other popularly-elected
legislators. Among them will be Tsang Yok-sing, a former high
school principal and avowed Marxist who heads the main pro-Beijing
party in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   The president will also meet with senior civil servants, and the
head of Hong Kong's government-owned broadcasting outlet, Radio
Television Hong Kong, Cheung Man-yee. RTHK has been harshly
criticized by pro-Beijing people here for undermining the local
government and being disloyal to the mainland.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was among the first passengers to land at Hong Kong's
new $20 billion airport _ touching down 10 hours after Chinese
President Jiang Zemin dedicated the vast complex _ and became its
first departing passenger.
</P>
<P>
   Like some Hong Kong residents, though, Clinton expressed
nostalgia for the old airport, Kai Tak, which was famous for the
rooftop-skimming approaches made by planes as they landed. Clinton,
who sat in the cockpit of a plane as it landed at Kai Tak on a
visit to Hong Kong more than a decade ago, said, ``It was one of
the most exciting and uncertain experiences of my life-time.''
</P>
<P>
   Before flying to Hong Kong Thursday night, Clinton spoke on the
environmental hazards confronting China.
</P>
<P>
   With the spectacular limestone peaks of the southern city of
Guilin as a backdrop, Clinton said that 5 of the world's 10 most
polluted cities are in China and virtually every body of water in
the country is tainted with human and industrial waste. But, he
said, China did not have to sacrifice its environment to continue
to build its economy.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   He urged China to build more energy-efficient cars, homes and
factories. The alternative, he said, was further environmental
degradation and ultimately, slower economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   The president, addressing a small, carefully-screened audience
at a park in Guilin, one of China's most popular tourist
destinations, said that not long ago U.S. cities were choked with
smog and many of its urban waterways were seriously polluted.
</P>
<P>
   ``China's extraordinary growth has put the same kind of pressure
on your environment, and the costs of growth are rising right along
with your prosperity,'' the president said. ``You know better than
I that polluted air and water are threatening your remarkable
progress. Smog has caused entire Chinese cities to disappear from
satellite photographs. And respiratory illness is China's No. 1
health problem.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that China can take immediate steps to slow the
environmental damage. ``We can use clean, as opposed to dirty,
energy sources much more than we do; and we can adopt new
technologies to make the energy we have go further much more than
we do.''
</P>
<P>
   China and other developing countries have resisted wealthy
nations' demands to reduce emissions of gases that contribute to
global warming, complaining that the developed countries were
trying to retard the Third World's growth.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton said that China did not have to follow the path of
Europe and the United States, where growth has been fueled by
cheap, dirty and inefficient sources of energy.
</P>
<P>
   To help China address its environmental problems, Clinton
announced a $50 million Export-Import Bank loan to pay for clean
energy projects, a contract to develop methane gas from coal fields
and U.S. assistance in promoting renewable energy sources.
</P>
<P>
   Beijing and Washington this week signed an agreement to develop
an air-quality monitoring network for China's major cities. China
will buy American-made monitoring equipment, while the United
States will provide technical aid and training to operate the
system.
</P>
<P>
   Later Thursday, Clinton, first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton and
their daughter, Chelsea, took a two-hour Li River boat ride among
the steep peaks of the Guilin region. Occasionally splattered by
rain, they passed tangerine orchards and rice fields before
arriving at the village of Yangshuo. They then boarded their
motorcade and departed for the airport and Hong Kong.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
