<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mosquitoes, other pests carry disease, CDC warning
 &HT;    By M.A.J. McKenna
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- When you go outside this weekend, be sure to stop for
bug spray.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past two years, 286 people _ three of them in Georgia _
have contracted serious cases of encephalitis from mosquito bites,
the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Eight bite victims died in 1996 and 1997 from three types of
encephalitis, a dangerous swelling of the brain, carried by
mosquitoes. The first 1998 death, Harry Marsocci, 44, of West
Warwick, R.I., who died June 21, has just been reported, the CDC
added. No deaths were in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   In its weekly national roundup of diseases, the CDC said 19
states including Georgia have reported a serious problem with
arboviruses, disease organisms carried by mosquitoes or ticks and
transmitted to humans in a multi-step cycle that includes birds and
other animals. The viruses cause 150 to 3,000 cases per year of
three unusual and potentially fatal diseases: La Crosse
encephalitis, St. Louis encephalitis and eastern equine
encephalitis, which caused the three Georgia cases in 1997 and
killed the Rhode Island man.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the human cases, 23 states including Georgia have
recorded arbovirus infection in animals _ chiefly horses and emus,
a flightless bird farmed for meat _ that can potentially be passed
to humans by mosquitoes. Georgia saw 16 cases of eastern equine
encephalitis in horses in 1996 and 1997, the CDC said.
</P>
<P>
   Because arbovirus infection can have such serious results,
health professionals should consider it as a possible diagnosis
when treating cases of fever, muscle aches and nausea, meningitis
or encephalitis from mosquito-prone areas, the CDC said. And
residents in such areas should take particular precautions,
including wearing long sleeves and long pants outdoors after dark,
using insect repellent and properly screening doors and windows
against bugs.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
