<SLUG> BC-CNN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CNN issues a retraction and apology for Operation Tailwind's
story
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Three executives have left CNN after an independent
investigation found the cable news network's report of alleged U.S.
use of nerve gas was ``journalistic overkill.''
</P>
<P>
   CNN Newsgroup CEO Tom Johnson rectracted the story and
apologized to viewers and the military personnel involved in
Operation Tailwind, a 1970 mission into Laos.
</P>
<P>
   ``The story shouldn't have been on,'' said attorney Floyd
Abrams, who was hired by Johnson to investigate after people
involved challenged the report.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone from top to bottom bears a level of responsibility,''
Abrams said.
</P>
<P>
   ``CNN's system of journalistic checks and balances, which has
served us exceptionally well in the past, failed in this case,''
Johnson said in a statement Thursday that was read repeatedly on
CNN and posted on its web page.
</P>
<P>
   April Oliver, the producer of the report that aired June 7 on
``NewsStand: CNN &AMP; Time,'' reportedly was fired Thursday. Pam Hill,
senior executive producer of the newsmagazine, resigned, and Jack
Smith, senior producer, left the network under unclear
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Arnett, the on-air reporter of the story, was reprimanded,
although it was not clear how much of a contribution he had made to
the story.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Greenfield, co-anchor of ``CNN &AMP; Time,'' said the 10 p.m.
Sunday show will air a ``full and lengthy presentation of the fact
that we screwed up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We said we're going to hold ourselves to the same standard
that we hold everyone else,'' Greenfield said Thursday. ``That's
going to happen. There will be no attempt to spin, no attempt to be
defensive or political about this.'' Assistant Secertary of Defense
Kenneth Bacon said Thursday the Pentagon was ``gratified that CNN
retracted a report that we believe was not accurate.''
</P>
<P>
   Time magazine, which ran a print version of the story written by
Oliver and Arnett, also apologized Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
