<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Web sites offer fast updates, insight, photos
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- The Internet offers a variety of news and dramatic
pictures on video documenting the fires burning out of control in
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Web sites covering the fires are showing thoughtful
restraint, offering news and emergency information first and saving
the dramatic pictures for farther down on their sites.
</P>
<P>
   The local Web sites covering the fires also are making extensive
use of streaming video to chronicle the disaster, making expert use
of a technology that wasn't in wide use a year or even six months
ago.
</P>
<P>
   For example, The Daytona Beach News-Journal
(http://www.n-jcenter.com) has extensive coverage of the fires on a
simple, picture-free start page that includes breaking news
coverage and emergency information. The news package runs under the
title ``Central Florida in Flames'' and includes evacuation
information, a photo tour and editorials.
</P>
<P>
   The Orlando Sentinel (http://www.orlandosentinel.com) also has
news and information in a special section visitors can link to from
the front page. The Sentinel offers dramatic pictures of the
devastation and offers emergency phone numbers and volunteer and
donation addresses and phone numbers. The Sentinel makes use of
graphics and QuickTime video to explain how firefighters battle the
flames and record astonishing photos of the fires. The Sentinel is
continually updating its Web site with breaking news and
information.
</P>
<P>
   Florida's Volusia County also has a Web site devoted to wildfire
updates at http://www.volusia.org/firenews.htm. The site offers
information and a special visitor's section. ``We're happy you're
here, and we hope you enjoy your stay,'' begins the tips page
asking visitors to obey certain fire safety and prevention rules.
The site also has a map of the stricken areas and lists of road
closings.
</P>
<P>
   For road closure updates and county-by-county trouble spots in
Central Florida, check out Inside Central Florida
(http://insidecentralflorida.com), a Cox Interactive Media site in
partnership with several local radio stations.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government has many sites devoted to the science and
management of the fires. But the most fascinating is the National
Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration
(http://www.noaa.gov/floridafires.html). It offers a scientific
explanation of the abnormal weather patterns and climate conditions
that led up to the fires' outbreak. Visitors can look at
statistical information and satellite photographs of the fires.
</P>
<P>
   On a national level, CNN (http://www.cnn.com) makes extensive
use of VXtreme streaming video to bring astonishingly clear fire
footage to computer desktops. The resolution is clear even on 28.8k
bps modems.
</P>
<P>
   The use of streaming video technology to tell the story of this
natural disaster is a giant step forward in Web site development
and technology, and most sites use it to good advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
