</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLARACE-COx </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Flames outpace race
 &HT;    By Tom McCollister
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH -- The lights of Daytona International Speedway
won't shine on the July 4 Pepsi 400 as planned this weekend. Race
officials postponed Saturday's historic event early Thursday
morning because wildfires continue to plague Daytona Beach and
surrounding areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Conditions being the way they are now, we don't think there's
room for the race and the fire,'' NASCAR President Bill France Jr.
said. ``And the fire is winning.''
</P>
<P>
   The race has been rescheduled for the night of Saturday, Oct.
17, three weeks before the season-ending NAPA 500 race south of
Atlanta. All Pepsi 400 tickets will be honored at that time, but
there will be no refunds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Postponing this race is the right thing to do,'' Speedway
President John Graham said. ``Our manpower, facilities and
resources will remain completely devoted to our community until
this crisis is over. The fires have not directly affected the
480-acre Speedway facility.''
</P>
<P>
   The postponement was announced an hour before the gates were to
open, turning the speedway into a ghost town. Hundreds of fans in a
wide variety of vehicles who had lined up for infield vantage
points turned and left.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too dangerous for everybody,'' said racing fan Mark Smith
of Dalton, Ga. ``We're breathing soot and everything else right
now. There are ashes falling out here. Just imagine what it's doing
at the race track.''
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR drivers and teams, scheduled to qualify Thursday night,
headed back to their race shops.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some ways, it's like a 'snow day' at school, where you sit
there and wonder what the heck you are going to do,'' said Jeremy
Mayfield, driver of the No. 12 Mobil 1 Ford. ``It's not that neat
feeling, though, because I'd be wanting to go outside and play when
I was a kid. If I have a weekend off now, I think about racing
somewhere. I'd love to be racing at Daytona Saturday night, but I
bet everybody else would be, too.''
</P>
<P>
   All 143,000 grandstand seats were sold out for the race, billed
as the largest night sports event ever. The Pepsi 400 would have
been the first night NASCAR race at Daytona International Speedway
and the first motor sports event televised by a network during
prime time.
</P>
<P>
   Officials were forced to postpone the race after wind-driven
wildfires roared to life Wednesday afternoon and evening just north
of the speedway, forcing thousands of people in Ormond Beach and
Daytona Beach to evacuate.
</P>
<P>
   Daytona Beach and Volusia County authorities also closed roads
because of fires. A ride from the Orlando airport to the speedway,
which usually takes less than an hour, took more than three hours
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are all very frustrated,'' said Ralph Sheheen, chief auto
racing reporter for CBS, which was to televise the race. ``We all
had this date circled on our calendars. There was a real buzz among
fans, teams and CBS.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The October weekend was the logical choice,'' said Mike
Helton, NASCAR's vice president for competition. ``There's two
opportunities left in the '98 season, two weeks from now, and the
next is Oct. 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt like, with the level that the fire elevated itself
last night, with that intensity and level of damage it jumped to
last night, trying to get to two weeks from now was not as logical
as Oct. 17.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the first time a NASCAR event has been postponed because
of fire. But NASCAR has had two other memorable postponements _ a
1993 snow storm in Atlanta postponed a race at Hampton, and sand
storms in Phoenix two years ago postponed that race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Needless to say, we would prefer to be running the race,''
France said. ``And I know everybody in town would prefer for us to
be running the race. But nobody is thinking that what's going on
out there (fire) is a better deal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``(This is what happens) when Mother Nature or an act of God
gets into the playing picture,'' Helton said. ``We're an outdoor
sport and depend on the environment outside. It's the price we pay
sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, NASCAR had announced that the race was still on.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the course we were on through (Wednesday),'' Helton
said. ``But during the night, it simply took a very sharp turn and
a very quick movement to the negative side. And that changed our
whole philosophy.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
