<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980702.0346 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8629 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARG-COX     07-02 1448
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARG-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    King of the road
 &HT;    By Jim Auchmutey
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- In 20 years of photographing the Great American Road,
John Margolies has come to expect the things he loves to vanish. He
returns to a town and, more often than not, the tepee motel or
wiener-shaped hot dog stand that once beckoned his camera have gone
on to that big four-lane in the sky. So imagine his delight when he
arrives in Atlanta, six years after his last visit, and sees the
same sign on the same wall at Biggar's Antiques in Chamblee. The
green tin disk advertises Tom Thumb miniature golf, a chain of
putteries that was all the rage in 1930.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen a sign like that,'' says Margolies, who did an
entire book on miniature golf. ``I deserve that sign.''
</P>
<P>
   Alex Biggar, the billy goat-bearded man behind the counter,
agrees that it's a nice sign. His price: $850.
</P>
<P>
   Margolies winces; now he remembers why he didn't buy it six
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   If a 68-year-old piece of scrap metal is selling for hundreds of
dollars, Margolies has no one to blame but himself. More than
perhaps anyone, he's responsible for the fact that people have come
to value the eccentricities of the American roadside even as they
disappear in the era of interstates and franchise standardization.
</P>
<P>
   Since the mid-'70s, Margolies has driven a hundred thousand
miles throughout the lower 48 and snapped a hundred thousand photos
of motels, storefronts, gas stations, fast-food joints and the
like. He's tapped his personal archive for nine picture books that
are as bittersweet as they are quirky and entertaining.
Preservation magazine called him ``a cartographer with the heart of
a poet and the eye of an artist.''
</P>
<P>
   Just now, he has the stomach of a hungry traveler. Margolies has
flown in from New York, where he lives in an Upper West Side
apartment, to promote his latest volume, ``Fun Along the Road''
(Bulfinch Press, $29.95), an ode to old-time tourist attractions
like Florida's Gatorland Zoo and South Carolina's South of the
Border. It's lunchtime, and the man wants some real Southern
barbecue. ``We don't have hickory in Manhattan,'' he deadpans.
</P>
<P>
   So we pile into a Chevy Cavalier _ Margolies prefers to make his
trips in a roomy Cadillac _ and light out for Atlanta along the
Avenue Formerly Known as Stewart. Metropolitan Avenue (as the city
recently renamed it) is also U.S. 19-41, a main tourist route to
Florida before the interstates were built. This is the way
Margolies likes to approach a city, on its bypassed arteries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't photographed much in Atlanta because the prosperous
places tear things down,'' he says. ``I'm more interested in the
forgotten places, the bad side of town.''
</P>
<P>
   As we drive, his eyes dart back and forth, and he points out the
rusting archaeology of the avenue: the site of an old tourist court
(``I've got their postcard''), the converted buildings that once
housed gas stations (``That was a Texaco''), the renovated
apartments that used to be the Alamo Plaza, part of America's first
motel chain (``Terrible! They've ruined the mission facade''). It's
easy to imagine that the man in the passenger seat isn't a paunchy
58-year-old with a hairline headed for Canada, but a boy taking in
the roadside for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   That's how it started for Margolies. Growing up in
pre-interstate Connecticut, he enjoyed the family's vacation drives
to the beach as much as the beach. After studying art history and
communications at the University of Pennsylvania, he took an
editing position with Architectural Record magazine.
</P>
<P>
   It was the 1960s, the waning days of modern architecture, and
Margolies found himself more interested in the roadside memories of
his childhood than the glass boxes he was writing about. He quit
the Record and made a name for himself as curator of a
controversial 1970 exhibition on Morris Lapidus, the architect of
Miami Beach's most gloriously tacky hotels. In 1976, he hit the
road to document the simpler (but often just as tacky) buildings
that Americans had erected to seduce motorists during the first
decades of the automobile.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to dismiss what I do as kitsch, but I think it's
important,'' Margolies says. ``I've made a visual record of the way
free enterprise has manifested itself on the sides of the road and
Main Street.'' Besides, he likes his teapot gas stations and
swirl-topped ice cream stands better than the buildings that were
done in good taste. ``They're less pretentious, more honest, easier
to dance to.''
</P>
<P>
   Margolies would take frequent trips of 30 to 60 days, funded in
part by grants from the Guggenheim Foundation, the National
Endowment for the Arts and patrons such as architect Philip Johnson
(who wanted to see slide shows when he returned). The vision never
varied: Margolies took color slides designed to show structures as
timeless icons. No people, no cars, no rain _ just a building
against a blue sky, God's own postcard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I missed half the Super Bowl one year waiting for the clouds
to break over Mammy's Cupboard,'' he says, referring to a Natchez,
Miss., cafe tucked inside a two-story servant's enormous skirts.
</P>
<P>
   He's eaten a mountain of bad food. Drunk so much coffee and
gobbled so many aspirin that he developed an ulcer. Slept on enough
mashed potato mattresses to know that he doesn't want to stay in
the mom and pop motels he loves to photograph.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the old two-story Holiday Inns,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Last time he was in Atlanta, Margolies spent an afternoon
shooting portraits of the Big Chicken in Marietta. Perhaps this
time he would like to see our latest larger-than-life entree, the
65-foot salmon at the Atlanta Fish Market.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a fine fish,'' he says, admiring the finned wonder on
Pharr Road in Buckhead. So why isn't he reaching for his camera?
``It isn't as good as the Big Fish in Minnesota. I'd like it better
if it were painted some unnatural color. It's too tasteful for
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Margolies doesn't devote much time to driving around America
these days. Most of the things that attracted his eye have either
vanished or already been added to his collection of images. He
finds it more fruitful to explore flea markets and antiques shops _
which is why, after a stop for a barbecue sandwich, we're cruising
down Antique Row in Chamblee headed back to Biggar's. It has
something he wants.
</P>
<P>
   Saying that Biggar's is cluttered is like saying that the
Smithsonian has some stuff. Located in a former Methodist church,
the rambling shop has replaced the sanctuary and Sunday school
rooms with floor-to-ceiling furniture and advertising memorabilia.
The outside walls are covered with roadside signs such as the rusty
pig from Macon's old Pig 'n' Whistle restaurant. The Tom Thumb
miniature golf sign is hanging outside the vestibule. Margolies
would like it for an exhibition he's curating next year on American
tourism at the National Building Museum in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can't you come down on the price?'' he asks Biggar.
</P>
<P>
   The shopkeeper laughs. ``This person rides around taking
pictures of other people's hard work and makes a lot of money, and
he can't afford to buy a sign?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't make a lot of money,'' Margolies says.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't look sick to me,'' Biggar replies.
</P>
<P>
   None of his books has sold more than 30,000 copies, so maybe
Margolies can't drop $850 for every sign he takes a liking to. He
passes. Instead, he spends $66 on vintage road maps and travel
brochures that might end up in the Washington show.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the car, Margolies can't get over the rejection. ``He
annoys me with that sign,'' he mutters. There's a third visit
later, still to no avail.
</P>
<P>
   But that's only part of it: Margolies is also annoyed that some
people seem to think his life's work has consisted of being paid to
take a perpetual vacation.
</P>
<P>
   ``They tell me that it must be so much fun, what I do. Well,
it's work. Hard, lonely work. When I'm on the road, almost always
by myself, I don't do the things people on vacation do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw the Grand Canyon for all of 30 seconds and took three or
four pictures. I spent hours at Flintstone Bedrock City and took
six or eight rolls. When I was driving through Colorado and saw the
turnoff for the Great Sand Dunes National Monument, I didn't take
my foot off the accelerator. That wasn't what I came to see. I was
focused.''
</P>
<P>
   There's a big, beautiful country out there beyond the roadside.
Maybe, one day, the King of the Road will see it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometime,'' he says, wistfully, ``I would like to go back and
see the sand dunes.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
