<SLUG> BC-keyword-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE VETERANS HELD WITHOUT BOND IN BIOLOGICAL WEAPONS CASE IN
TEXAS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Pa.) 
 
By JAMES PINKERTON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROWNSVILLE, Texas _ Three Texas military veterans were jailed
without bond Thursday after federal prosecutors accused them of
threatening to use biological weapons against the directors of the
IRS and FBI, among other federal agents.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Magistrate John Black, although conceding the evidence
presented by the government was ``sparse,'' ruled the threat was
serious enough to warrant the men's continued detention. He also
left sealed the government's affidavit and search warrants in the
case.
</P>
<P>
   After the hearing, federal marshals chained Jack Abbott Grebe
Jr., 43, Oliver Dean Emigh, 63, and Johnnie Wise, 72, and led them
from the courthouse to the Cameron County Jail. They are charged
with conspiracy to use weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
   During the brief detention hearing, prosecutors called no
witnesses to support their contention the men posed a danger to the
community, nor did they say whether the men actually possessed any
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday afternoon, federal and local authorities arrested
the suspects at Wise's dilapidated trailer in Olmito, a small
community just north of Brownsville in south Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Hazardous materials disposal teams removed several containers of
chemicals found behind Wise's home, but Felix Recio, a federal
public defender who is representing Emigh, told the court that they
did not contain dangerous substances.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Rick Lara told the court the men sent a
threatening electronic message over the Internet on June 26 to
federal officials and to local and state government offices. He
said along with composing the e-mail threat, the men discussed
delivery systems for the weapon.
</P>
<P>
   Lara named Emigh as the author of the e-mail, but would not say
exactly what the threats said.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth television station KXAS reported Thursday night that
threatening e-mail sent to President Clinton also may have been
traced to the suspects.
</P>
<P>
   Court-appointed attorneys representing the three complained they
had no way to determine the roles their clients allegedly played in
the conspiracy. All three men were honorably discharged from
various branches of the military and have no prior criminal
records.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is sealed, your honor. Our hands are tied,'' Recio
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't even own a gun, much less a weapon of mass
destruction,'' said Wise's lawyer, Keith Uhles. He added that his
client is a Navy veteran who was honorably discharged after serving
in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   After the hearing, Uhles said he had no idea of the seriousness
of the threats allegedly made by his client and his two
co-defendants. ``I don't know what they have. They won't even show
us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A number of friends and relatives of the men attended Thursday's
hearing, including Wise's longtime friend Fred Foote.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds like a bunch of BS,'' said Foote, a La Feria
resident who said he has known Wise for 26 years and characterized
him ``as a really nice person.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's well-read on nearly everything. If you want to make
Scotch whiskey, he'll say `here's what the ingredients are,'''
Foote said of his friend. ``But he knows as much about bombs as you
and I do.''
</P>
<P>
   Grebe's lawyer, Dan Herink, told the court his client is a
Pennsylvania native and a single parent who raised daughters by
himself and had no prior criminal record. Herink asked the court if
the federal criminal justice system had reached the point where a
person could be jailed by the government for saying something, but
then the government was not required to tell the defendant's lawyer
what it was he allegedly said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last time I checked, we had a right to free speech in this
country,'' Herink said.
</P>
<P>
   While defense attorneys argued unsuccessfully to unseal the
documents, Recio did succeed in convincing the judge to impose a
gag order in the case, citing intense media interest.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
