u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-ECON-1     07-02 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-ECON-1,000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPAN ANNOUNCES PLAN TO DEAL WITH BANKS' BAD DEBTS AND SPUR
ECONOMIC CONFIDENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ps/mk) 
 By SHERYL WuDUNN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ The government announced a long-awaited plan Thursday to
clear away the nation's pile of bad debt in hopes of bolstering
global confidence in Japan and setting its economy, the world's
second largest, on track for growth.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Total Plan,'' which still needs to be approved by
Parliament, amounts to a program for dealing with $550 billion in
uncollectable loans held by Japan's largest banks. The plan's
centerpiece is a mechanism to allow banks to fail without provoking
chaos in the financial system.
</P>
<P>
   The government would shut insolvent institutions and turn over
their clients to government-run ``bridge banks'' to maintain a
supply of credit. It would also accelerate sales of depressed real
estate held as collateral for bad loans. Shaky companies would
close down, thousands of people could be put out of work and
bankers could be prosecuted for malfeasance.
</P>
<P>
   Hikaru Matsunaga, the finance minister, announced that the
government was embracing the plan shortly after it was approved
Thursday by a task force. Markets reacted cautiously to the
announcement, which had been widely anticipated, while foreign
governments urged that it be followed up with strong measures to
put it into effect.
</P>
<P>
   There has been growing apprehension that the Japanese banking
crisis may threaten economies in the West and the long boom on Wall
Street. And President Clinton and other American officials have
been stepping up the pressure lately on the Japanese. In
Washington, U.S. Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin said in a
statement that the plan contains ``potentially significant steps,''
but he stressed that ``what is important is for the Japanese
authorities to move quickly to translate this approach into
concrete actions.''
</P>
<P>
   Finance Ministry officials said the government would submit
implementing legislation to Parliament at a special session in late
July. Parliamentary approval is expected.
</P>
<P>
   In Tokyo, analysts warned that because the plan would bring
about a great deal of pain, Japan's leaders face enormous obstacles
in carrying it out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a great deal of will to clean the bad debt out
of the private sector, and I think the politicians are committed to
that, but I'm not sure the politicians are willing to restructure
the financial sector and restructure the economy,'' said John
Neuffer, a political analyst at Mitsui Marine Research Institute in
Tokyo. ``They are wonderful when it comes to passing around the
pork, but much less willing to pass around the pain.''
</P>
<P>
   The benchmark Nikkei index of 225 stocks, which has soared over
the last seven days on expectations of the plan and in anticipation
of tax cuts, rose again Thursday, though it lost some of its gains
in the afternoon as details of the plan were reported. The Nikkei
finished up 108.69 points, or sixth-tenths of a percent, at
16,471.58. Currency markets also showed hesitancy, weakening the
yen to 140.34 to the dollar from 139.17 in early London trading,
just as Japan's finance minister, Hikaru Matsunaga, was outlining
the plan.
</P>
<P>
   An outline of the plan, which is expected to be approved by
Parliament in late July or early August, was unveiled by Matsunaga
and other government and regulatory officials. They insisted that
Japan would move toward a market-based economy and pull away from
the convoy system in which all the banks support one another and
move ahead only as quickly as the slowest bank. Masaharu Hino, head
of the new Financial Supervision Agency, suggested that the
government would allow more banks to fail. He said the agency would
take ``strict measures'' after it inspected the nation's 19 largest
banks over the next few months.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will recover confidence in the Japanese financial system by
severing ties with the past convoy administration and shifting to
an administration of severe policing, based on clear rules,'' Hino
said. ``That is the main road toward the rebirth of the financial
system.''
</P>
<P>
   The restructuring is needed because Japanese banks, especially
the big banks, carry far more bad debt than their American
counterparts. Bad loans as a percentage of equity run from 90
percent at Sanwa Bank to 371 percent at Nippon Credit Bank, while
the average for the 22 largest banks in the United States at the
height of the savings-and-loan crisis was 58 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Officials used the English words ``Total Plan'' to describe the
restructuring proposal, perhaps because they sound bolder and more
innovative than the equivalent Japanese terms. The effort appears
to be modeled on the U.S. efforts to clean up the savings-and-loan
crisis of the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   The plan's centerpiece is a mechanism to allow banks to fail
without provoking chaos in the financial system. Using a two-stage
``bridge bank,'' the plan will first put collapsed banks under
government administration, protecting credit-worthy borrowers left
in the lurch by the failed bank, while a merger partner is sought.
Then the collapsed bank either will be acquired or will be
nationalized with public money, sending the bad debts to an agency
established to collect bad loans.
</P>
<P>
   The advantage of the bridge bank approach is that it insures
that corporate customers of a failed bank will continue to have
access to loans, reducing the shock of a bank failure. The
disadvantage is that it raises questions about whether Japan, which
has overcapacity in its financial system, is truly willing to let
banks fail and whether the bridge bank system is simply one more
way of allowing insolvent institutions to founder a bit longer.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, public money will be drawn from the $213 billion
bailout fund set up in March at Deposit Insurance Corp., which will
set up the bridge banks as subsidiaries of a new holding company.
The corporation will then try to transfer the business to a healthy
bank within two years, though that could be extended to five years.
The total cost of the bailout is by no means clear.
</P>
<P>
   One sticky point is how the distinction between good and bad
borrowers will be made and whether bad borrowers will be rescued
along with the good ones. Naturally, any client of a failed bank
will insist that it is a good borrower and should continue to
receive loans.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Japan is designing a mechanism that appears similar to the
former Resolution Trust Corp. in the United States, which disposed
of bad debts during the savings and loan crisis in the 1980s. In
Japan, the Financial Supervisory Agency, which last month split off
about 400 people from the Finance Ministry to inspect the banks,
will be given wide authority to direct the process.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the blueprint, however, say the Total Plan does not
address some of the fundamental rigidities of the economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a Total Plan at all,'' said Chiaki Nishiyama, an
economist at the Hoover Institution at Stanford University, who is
now in Tokyo. ``It's a very deceiving term.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if the plan successfully purges the banks of their bad
loans, a broad restructuring and deregulation of industry is still
necessary to bring about a strong economic revival. One difference
between the American experience and Japan's situation is that the
United States embarked on the painful reworking of the
savings-and-loans industry just as the economy was picking up. In
contrast, Japan is beginning its plan as it sinks into a recession,
and it already is spending $120 billion in fiscal expansion to
bolster economic output.
</P>
<P>
   ``They might get a mild recovery out of this, but it will not be
impressive,'' said Peter Morgan, chief economist at HSBC Securities
Japan. ``If there's a promise of a deregulatory effort, they can
use fiscal expansion as a down payment. But a fiscal down payment
by itself, without restructuring, is a waste.''
</P>
<P>
   Some economists, however, are a little bit more hopeful.
Resolving the bad debt is the first step toward improving the
economy, they say.
</P>
<P>
   ``First we have to solve the confidence crisis, and solving the
bad loans is a starting point,'' said Heizo Takenaka, an economics
professor at Keio University. Then, he added, Japan can ``promote a
deregulated, more transparent open-market system.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
