<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8641 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GM-STRIKE-ART-700&AMP;ADD     07-02 1258
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GM-STRIKE-ART-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORTAGE OF POPULAR MODELS WORRIES GM DEALERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(JT) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYLVANIA, Ohio _ Ask David White Jr., a Chevrolet dealer here,
how long he can last during the current General Motors strikes
without running out of vehicles, and his initial response is full
of confidence: two months, because he has about 220 new cars and
trucks in stock and typically sells 110 a month.
</P>
<P>
   But ask about supplies of specific models, and the confidence
fades to dismay. There are lots of slow-selling Lumina and Prism
sedans, plenty of Astro full-size vans and enough tiny Metro
economy cars for at least six months of sales. By contrast, he
expects to sell the last of his high-profit Tahoe and Suburban
sport utility vehicles and S-10 pickups this weekend, with no
prospect of further deliveries until early August even if the
strikes end quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at your hot products, you're at zero,'' said White,
holding out the thumb and forefinger of each hand to form little
zeros for emphasis.
</P>
<P>
   A shortage of popular models at dealerships now lies at the
heart of the troubles facing GM, the world's largest auto maker.
Showdowns with the United Automobile Workers are always costly for
auto makers, but GM came into the current strikes with extremely
low inventories of its most profitable vehicles, and the strikes
are obviously making it worse.
</P>
<P>
   So as customers head to showrooms this weekend for the
traditionally busy Fourth of July auto sales, they are likely to
find the most popular GM models in short supply, with few
combinations of color and options available. Discounts are
evaporating, pushing up the prices that car buyers actually pay.
And dealers for Ford, Chrysler and foreign auto makers are trying
to woo GM customers by offering wider selections, but seldom at
lower prices. Even used car prices are climbing, as dealers flock
to auctions, desperate to buy late-model cars to keep their lots
from looking empty.
</P>
<P>
   Because of a price war this spring, GM had been offering $500 to
$1,000 discount coupons on even its most popular models but allowed
these to expire on Tuesday night. Chrysler officials have already
indicated that their similar coupons will expire on Monday, and
Ford is likely to terminate its coupon program on Tuesday. Auction
prices for used 1996, 1997 and 1998 cars have already risen by
hundreds of dollars, with the few used 1998 models on the market
now selling for close to the original sticker price even though
they have a few thousand miles on them.
</P>
<P>
   The strikes at two GM auto parts factories in Flint, Mich., have
forced GM to close 26 of its 29 North American assembly plants, so
customers who want to order a precise combination of paint color
and options from the factory face months of delay _ or must
compromise and pick from dealers' dwindling selections.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you see is what you get,'' said Jim Yark, an Oldsmobile
dealer in nearby Toledo, as he surveyed the 78 new cars and light
trucks on his lot _ less than a third of his usual supply, and only
enough for another three weeks of sales, he calculated.
</P>
<P>
   Many GM dealers also have franchises for other auto makers, and
are using their Ford, Dodge and other dealerships to woo customers
unable to find the right GM car or truck. The Burdick Cos., a chain
of 18 dealerships in central New York state, including a Buick
dealership, has culled from state auto registration records a list
of all nearby owners of GM full-size sport utility vehicles and
pickup trucks and plans to mail them brochures offering big Dodge
Durango sport utility vehicles and Dodge Ram pickup trucks instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our strategy is to hit at the weakness,'' said Louis Bregou,
the group's director of operations, while acknowledging that the
aggressive strategy could produce a shortage later this summer of
the popular Dodge light trucks. ``We could be out of Durangos and
Ram trucks by Labor Day.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The strikes come at a time of record sales for GM which
announced June results by model Thursday: sales of each of its
full-size sport utility vehicle models were the highest ever in
June, and its overall light truck sales have set industry records
for the last four consecutive months. The record sales have helped
GM clear out 1998 models before the 1999 models are introduced,
which traditionally happens in late September, but GM has been too
successful for its own good. Now the auto maker finds itself
running out of popular models even as the economy is booming,
unemployment is low and people are buying lots of light trucks.
</P>
<P>
   With experience gained from more than a dozen other GM strikes
over the last five years, Wall Street analysts thought they could
estimate with confidence the company's losses from work stoppages
and put the damage to GM's after-tax earnings in the second quarter
at up to $1 billion. But GM said on Tuesday that its actual losses
were $1.18 billion, nearly 20 percent higher than Wall Street's
highest estimates, mainly because sales of light trucks had dropped
especially fast.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald L. Zarrella, GM's group vice president for marketing,
tried to reassure Wall Street and vehicle shoppers on Wednesday
that GM dealers still had ample inventories. GM has canceled
low-profit sales to car rental companies and other fleets, and its
dealerships' remaining inventories of cars and light trucks are
equal to 70 days of retail sales, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But such figures mask wide differences in the availability of
particular models, as well as big gaps among dealerships. Small
cars, on which GM loses money, are still plentiful, but full-size
sport utility vehicles, on which GM makes up to $10,000 apiece, are
extremely scarce. At the same time, some dealerships that started
the summer with unusually large inventories are less worried than
dealerships that tried to match up orders and sales more closely
and now find themselves with little to sell.
</P>
<P>
   In normal times, dealers sell scarce models to one another at
close to invoice prices. But this informal system has broken down
now, with dealers nationwide saying in interviews this week that
they are hoarding their remaining vehicles and generally selling
only to retail customers who pay close to the full sticker price.
</P>
<P>
   The uneven distribution of vehicles poses a problem for GM
because customer loyalty to dealerships has been its greatest
strength. More than any other domestic or foreign auto maker, GM
relies on sales to previous owners of GM vehicles, a legacy of the
days in the 1960s and '70s when GM controlled half the market. Very
few owners of foreign cars, or even owners of other domestic
brands, tend to switch to GM, which is one reason why its market
share has been slowly diminishing for a quarter of a century. But
now some of those loyal GM customers are coming into dealerships
that offer an increasingly limited selection.
</P>
<P>
   Drive up and down Central Avenue in nearby Toledo, the main
street for auto dealerships, and at first glance nothing is wrong.
But on closer inspection, some of the dealerships are suffering.
Yark Oldsmobile has even resorted to one of the oldest tricks in
the dealer business: parking its remaining cars and trucks with
wider spaces between them, so as to reduce the amount of empty
asphalt visible from the road.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
