<SLUG> BC-CHINA-SASSER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-SENATOR'S STAR RISES AS U.S. ENVOY TO CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Tenn.)  (See also: CHINA-CLINTON, CHINA-REPUBS, CHINA-NOTEBOOK) 
(bl) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Apart from Bill Clinton, who has clearly been having a
ball, possibly no one has taken greater satisfaction in the
presidential visit to China than the U.S. ambassador to Beijing,
Jim Sasser.
</P>
<P>
   The new warmth in U.S.-Chinese relations is in part a personal
victory for Sasser, 61, who came to China in early 1996 as a very
political appointee after the 1994 loss of his seat as a Democratic
senator from Tennessee, and at a time when China and the United
States were all but hostile.
</P>
<P>
   Big nations don't dance unless the geopolitical stars are
correctly aligned, but by all accounts Sasser personified the U.S.
effort to create friendlier ties despite the deep differences over
issues like human rights. His Southern style _ polite, charming and
attentive _ was an evident hit with President Jiang Zemin, who also
valued his closeness to his old Tennessee colleague, Vice President
Al Gore, in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Reached on Wednesday in Shanghai, where he was accompanying the
president, Sasser tried not to boast about the public relations
coups for the president here.
</P>
<P>
   It was up to his wife, Mary, to reveal their elation. ``Wow!''
she had said as she answered the phone. ``It's just going great!''
</P>
<P>
   Sasser is widely rumored to be leaving his post later this year
to help Gore _ ``social and political friends'' is how Sasser
describes the long relationship _ run for president.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Sasser was coy, saying, ``The normal term is about
three years, and I've been here two and a half.'' He added that he
hopes to usher Chinese Prime Minister Zhu Rongji to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   When Sasser first arrived in Beijing, he was criticized by some
as a non-expert and relations between the two countries were
plummeting. Shortly after he had taken up his post, the Chinese
fired off missiles near Taiwan and the United States sent aircraft
carriers to the region.
</P>
<P>
   That hint of conflict proved to be a catalyst for both countries
to seek a better way of communicating.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very much the right man for the time,'' said William
McCahill, the deputy chief of mission here and a professional
diplomat. ``Nobody else here can pick up the phone to the White
House.''
</P>
<P>
   After Jiang's visit to the United States last fall, which the
Chinese saw as a huge success, Sasser immediately pressed the White
House to move up Clinton's reciprocal trip from the originally
scheduled time next fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the prickliness of this relationship, I felt that to
wait a whole year was risky,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Today, though some privately concede that the achievements of
this summit meeting have been more atmospheric than substantive,
senior foreign policy officials say they are glad the president
followed Sasser's instincts.
</P>
<P>
   One senior administration official also said that Sasser's easy
personal ties with Jiang and other top leaders here over the last
two years have been a great asset, although the basic outlines of
policy have been firmly drawn in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Sasser is clearly proud of his relations with the Chinese
president, noting that he and his wife have been invited twice for
personal dinners with Jiang and his wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the training I had as a senator was just perfect for
this job in many ways,'' Sasser said, citing his skills gained as a
conciliator and his familiarity with the U.S. political system.
</P>
<P>
   In his successful 1994 campaign to unseat Sasser, Republican
Bill Frist charged that Sasser would be ``the official water boy to
Bill Clinton.'' Now, Sasser and Clinton, in their determination to
build friendlier ties with China, are sometimes criticized as
spending too much time carrying water for China, trying to minimize
the differences on human rights and other issues.
</P>
<P>
   Sasser asks the critics in return _ he isn't the sort to openly
bristle _ ``What is the alternative to a policy of dialogue and
engagement?'' The number one priority, he said, has to be working
out a security arrangement so that the two countries ``don't get on
a collision course militarily.'' He said he in no way minimizes the
disputes that remain.
</P>
<P>
   David Lampton, the director of China studies at the Johns
Hopkins School of Advanced International Studies, said that Sasser
has been ``remarkably successful.'' He added _ meaning this as a
compliment _ that ``his real strength has been to serve as China's
ambassador to Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting more legislators to visit China and see its changes and
diversity has been a prime State Department goal; close to 100
members of congressman have visited in the last year. This not only
better acquaints them with China, but also shows their Chinese
hosts that concerns like human rights and religious tolerance are
genuinely felt on the U.S. side.
</P>
<P>
   The exchange has made for amusing moments, Sasser recalled, as
at a luncheon when one member of Congress asked a Chinese deputy
foreign minister _ like all senior officials here a Communist _ if
he had accepted Jesus Christ as his personal savior. ``I haven't,''
the startled official replied.
</P>
<P>
   A personal high point, Sasser said, was when he was told last
fall that the Chinese were releasing Wei Jingsheng, the prominent
dissident who had spent most of the last 20 years in jail, to exile
in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese insisted on secrecy, so for Wei's release, and later
that of the student leader Wang Dan, the ambassador sneaked into a
building in the back of the Beijing airport to interview them
before they boarded their planes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are high moments, when you see those guys get on an
airplane for the United States, after spending so many years in
prison,'' he recalled.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
