<SLUG> BC-CHINA-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON IN CHINA: SCRIPTED EVENTS, IMMORTALITY AND SOUVENIRS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: CHINA-CLINTON, CHINA-REPUBS, CHINA-SASSER) 
(bl) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ As President Clinton traveled through China, his
permanent campaign rolled on.
</P>
<P>
   In Shanghai on Wednesday, for example, the president spoke at a
Chamber of Commerce breakfast, chatted with students at a
cybercafe, shmoozed with traders on the floor of the Shanghai Stock
Exchange, hyped home ownership to residents of a new apartment
complex and sat for an interview with Chinese state television.
Pretty much like any other day on the road in America.
</P>
<P>
   Like all presidential events at home, these were heavily
scripted. At the Internet cafe on Huai Hai Road, Clinton asked a
student, Hu Danqing, to call up the home page (www.whitehouse.gov)
for the White House. Surprise! Up popped pictures of the president
in China and the words, ``Welcome Home Mr. President.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spent lunch with a group of carefully selected young
entrepreneurs. The president was in full earnest-listener mode,
hearing descriptions of the frustrations of start-up businesses,
which sounded very much the same as the problems that independent
business people encounter at home.
</P>
<P>
   At the Jin Hui Gardens complex, Clinton told residents that he
had bought his first home in Little Rock after driving by the house
with his girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then I said to my girlfriend, `I bought that house you
like, now you'll have to marry me,''' the president said. ``And she
did.''
</P>
<P>
   The girlfriend has since been promoted to first lady.
</P>
<P>
   And, yes, the president did work a rope line after his remarks.
Just like back home.
</P>
<P>
   First Lady Misses Real Life  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton broke away from the president on several
occasions during their trip to attend events of her own _ a
conversation with Chinese women at a Beijing hotel, a visit to the
Beijing University women's legal services center, a tour of a
Shanghai hospital and a speech at a Shanghai girls' school.
</P>
<P>
   She received universally favorable coverage, but she still
couldn't resist a dig at the press for its past sins back home.
</P>
<P>
   During a round-table discussion in Shanghai on Tuesday, she was
asked whether the constant scrutiny bothered her or limited her
personal life.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady took a home-run swing at the questioner's
softball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I often refer to my life before the White House as when I was
a real person,'' Mrs. Clinton said, ``because when you are in a
position like this, people, particularly all of these people with
their pencils and their cameras, try to record everything you do
and then they try to put meaning into it _ whether you intend
meaning or not. So it is a very unusual experience to be in this
kind of position with this much attention for things that you have
no real conscious awareness or purpose for.''
</P>
<P>
   Intimations of Immortality  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said he had waited 20 years to see the famous
excavation of terra-cotta warriors at Xian, the first stop in his
nine-day odyssey to the land of the emperors.
</P>
<P>
   The president, the first lady and daughter Chelsea were granted
the rare privilege of being allowed to descend to the floor of the
huge pit where 1,087 of Emperor Qin Shihuang's warriors stand rank
on rank.
</P>
<P>
   At the urging of curators, Clinton donned white gloves and
placed a warrior head atop the body of one of the warriors.
</P>
<P>
   The president said the sight of the warriors, which took more
than a decade to build and were buried with the emperor to guard
him after his death, humbled him.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I kept thinking how interesting it was that this
emperor thought so much about his death,'' Clinton said a bit
wistfully. ``In our culture, we don't think about it. Or we try not
to. But we also don't imagine as he did that we could preserve
whatever earthly power we have after death.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. presidents, of course, do not build pyramids or huge
mausoleums to preserve their memories and power after death. They
build libraries. Clinton has already selected a site for his in
Little Rock, along the banks of the gentle Arkansas River.
</P>
<P>
   Going Souvenir Hunting  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After their tour of the archaeological exhibits at Xian,
Clinton's party invaded the gift shop, where Clinton and Chelsea
engaged in some hard bargaining. They got a replica of a warrior
head, priced at $225, for $45.
</P>
<P>
   Erskine Bowles, the taciturn White House chief of staff, was
obviously moved by the warriors. He bought a full-size reproduction
for $1,100 and ordered it packed and shipped home to Charlotte,
N.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife will either like it or she's going to kill me,''
Bowles said.
</P>
<P>
   The Classic and the Kitsch  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Beijing, the president and his senior aides stayed at the
Diaoyutai guest compound, a collection of villas of various ages
and styles surrounding fishing lagoons built by the Jin Emperor
Zhang Zong in the 12th century. The complex is an oasis of greenery
and calm in the heart of the gritty bustle of Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   The American party marveled at the architecture and the decor of
the various buildings that housed them. Some are built and
decorated in traditional and tasteful Chinese style. Others can
only be described as embodying the design principles of the High
Stalin Era.
</P>
<P>
   The dining room of the villa housing Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright was a garish combination of Epcot Center
faux-Chinese and ``Saturday Night Fever,'' with pulsing lights and
green neon on the ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   A new gymnasium for high Communist Party functionaries and
distinguished visitors includes a motorized rock-climbing wall.
</P>
<P>
   A small group of reporters lodged near the president promptly
dubbed the compound ``Camp Commie.'' Americans who stayed at the
compound said the Chinese staff was large and very, very attentive.
</P>
<P>
   They Also Serve
</P>
<P>
   It has been more than a week since President Clinton's flying
circus descended on China, and while eternal China will certainly
recover from the effects of the 1,000-member entourage, it is not
at all clear when, if ever, the staff of the U.S. Embassy in
Beijing will.
</P>
<P>
   Every worker in the embassy and many of their family members
were pressed into service as chauffeurs, translators, security
guards, tour guides, baggage handlers and shepherds of the huge
traveling party. They summoned cars for shopping expeditions, made
restaurant reservations and worked around the clock to insure that
no need went unmet.
</P>
<P>
   Embassy officials, in the last of the menial tasks assigned to
them, ran the final roundup of reporters as they boarded 10 buses
at the Shangri-La Hotel to take them to the airport Monday night
for the trip to Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
   One exhausted and exasperated middle-level diplomat said with a
sigh as he herded the last stragglers onto a bus, ``I went to
college for this?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
