<HEADER>
A8659 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BELLSOUTH03-COX     07-02 0326
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELLSOUTH03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Union objects to BellSouth's deal
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Officials of the union confronting BellSouth at the
bargaining table object to BellSouth's $50 million contract with
three temporary employment agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the company's stance that the contract has no relevance
to the union, the Communications Workers of America apparently sees
the agreement as a potential issue in its high-stakes bargaining
with BellSouth. Those sessions are intended to produce contracts
for six company units before current contracts expire Aug. 8.
</P>
<P>
   The current contracts do not provide for hiring the temporary
workers, said Noah Savant, an officer in the Communications Workers
of America for District 3, which covers the BellSouth territory.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth spokesman Kevin Doyle said the company has long hired
temporary workers from a multitude of agencies and the union has
not raised a significant objection to that practice. BellSouth's
agreement with the three agencies _ Kelly, Norrell, and Blair
Temporaries and Staffing _ is meant to save money on the occasions
when the company must fill vacancies created by sickness or
vacation in office and administrative work, he said.
</P>
<P>
   News of the deal _ released Wednesday by Blair _ comes at a
somewhat sensitive moment. BellSouth negotiators have been talking
to the Communications Workers of America, which represents 47,000
of BellSouth's 86,191 employees. Among the issues on the table is
the CWA concern about what it says is a BellSouth tendency to shift
jobs to outside contractors. BellSouth insists the agreement with
the temporary agencies is simply not an example of outsourcing.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are people who come in for a few days, we cut them a
check and they go home,'' Doyle said. ``They don't wipe out a
company position.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
