<DOCNO> NYT19980702.0356 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 20:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8661 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNNMORE-COX     07-02 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNNMORE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CNN roiled by biggest blunder in resignations
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- CNN's Bobbie Battista called Thursday ``a tough day
for everyone at CNN,'' and CNN-U.S. President Richard Kaplan called
it ``totally devastating.''
</P>
<P>
   It was that and much more.
</P>
<P>
   The news network took the strongest hit to its credibility in
its 18-year history Thursday _ a completely self-inflicted one _ as
it issued a retraction and apology for its story alleging that U.S.
military forces had used nerve gas on a mission in Laos in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day, CNN ran a statement from its chairman, Tom
Johnson, that the report ``cannot be supported,'' acknowledging
``serious faults'' in the reporting, and apologizing to viewers and
the military personnel involved.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's statement, and the independent report it was based on,
carefully did not call the report incorrect, emphasizing instead
that the evidence did not support the charge.
</P>
<P>
   Although no procedural changes have been announced, Kaplan said
Thursday CNN is studying creating a new office of journalistic
standards to review such programs before they become problems.
</P>
<P>
   The fallout Thursday included the departure, under differing
circumstances, of three producers involved; a reprimand for
international correspondent Peter Arnett; and CNN's own
self-examination of its flaws, hour after hour. ``NewsStand'' will
air a further report on what happened and why at 10 p.m. Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson also made a quieter apology, by phone Wednesday night,
to Maj. Gen. Perry Smith, CNN's military adviser who had resigned
in protest over the report and helped fan the controversy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like the word vindication, but I'm very pleased that
CNN has published a strong retraction,'' Smith said Thursday from
his home in Augusta.
</P>
<P>
   But other Vietnam veterans did use the word. ``It's a
vindication,'' said Stanley Olchovik, who was an Army Special
Forces major in Vietnam. ``I hope it puts enough pressure on the
media to be responsible.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost immediately after the report, called ``Valley of Death,''
aired June 7 on the premiere of the newsmagazine ``NewsStand: CNN &AMP;
Time,'' serious questions were raised about its accuracy by
personnel involved in the mission, called Operation Tailwind.
Although CNN reported some of the controversy on air, behind the
scenes the doubts were spiraling.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson received phone calls from former Secretary of State
Henry Kissinger and former CIA Director Richard Helms, Kaplan said,
both of whom told Johnson that the story ``didn't smell right,'' in
Kaplan's words. Kaplan spoke with Gen. Colin Powell, who told him
the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were casting more than doubt on it,'' Kaplan said.
</P>
<P>
   CNN, which had taken the position in the early days that it
stood by its story, stopped saying anything at all publicly. Rumors
swirled in the newsroom.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Johnson had CNN's general counsel, David Kohler, call
Floyd Abrams, a noted First Amendment attorney who had defended CNN
in the past, and ask him to investigate the Operation Tailwind
story. Abrams reviewed outtakes of the interviews and producers'
notes, talked to CNN personnel involved, and even hired an
investigative firm to track down people with knowledge of Tailwind.
(CNN paid for the report.) Gen. Smith e-mailed Abrams pages and
pages of his own research and contacts.
</P>
<P>
   What Abrams found was what Johnson and others had privately come
to fear, that most of the criticism was on target. He said that CNN
ignored or downplayed several key figures in Tailwind _ such as the
two pilots who dropped the gas and a medic who treated victims _
who said that tear gas was used rather than nerve gas. He also
found that selective editing of witnesses in the on-air version
made them appear to support the nerve gas allegation more than
their full statements, in context, supported it.
</P>
<P>
   But Abrams does not say the story was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of material they had gathered strongly pointed toward
the possibility that this gas had been used,'' he said Thursday in
a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said CNN's system of checks and balances failed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We placed a great deal of faith in some of the most respected
and experienced journalists in America,'' CNN President Kaplan
said. ``In this case it was not well-placed.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Valley of Death'' producer, April Oliver, had prepared a
150-page ``briefing book'' for the producers of ``NewsStand.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a bullish recitation of the sourcing,'' Abrams said.
``There was not sufficient attention paid to the sources who said
no. The impact of that was to provide a false comfort level.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The briefing book itself is flawed, and therefore the vetting
was flawed,'' said Kaplan, referring to the network's review
process.
</P>
<P>
   Abrams delivered his report to Johnson on Wednesday, and the
decisions about who would go and what would be said were hammered
out at meetings at CNN Center Thursday. Producer Oliver was fired,
she acknowledged to the Associated Press, as was Jack Smith, senior
producer of ``NewsStand: CNN &AMP; Time.'' Senior Executive Producer
Pam Hill, a nine-year CNN veteran, resigned.
</P>
<P>
   The retraction and apology went under the TelePrompTer for
anchor Natalie Allen to read shortly after noon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to handle this with dignity, but it's not pretty to
watch yourself pummeled in the press,'' Oliver told the AP.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although this was a good-faith effort, it was an error that
happened on my watch,'' Hill said in a statement. ``I have resigned
to clear the air.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll get through this,'' Kaplan said. `` 'NewsStand' will go
on and CNN will go on and everyone will be more vigilant. It points
up parts of our operation that need reform.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly there's a whole lot of people who should have looked
at this a lot harder, and I'm one of them,'' said Jeff Greenfield,
who anchored the ``NewsStand'' program.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like what Robert F. Kennedy said about Vietnam,''
Greenfield said. ``There's enough blame to go around.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
