<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-INFORUM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coca-Cola's quest for Inforum breaks down
 &HT;    By Sallye Salter
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- The Coca-Cola Co.'s attempts to buy the Inforum
office building have collapsed for the second time in the past
year, renewing uncertainty over downtown leaders' efforts to spark
redevelopment around Centennial Olympic Park.
</P>
<P>
   The deal fell through because Coca-Cola ``could not reach a
satisfactory solution with all existing tenants,'' said Coca-Cola
spokesman Mark Preisinger.
</P>
<P>
   The 720,000-square-foot building, which occupies the block
between Spring Street and Techwood Drive at Baker Street, is about
60 percent occupied, with the Georgia Lottery as the largest
tenant. Plans called for Coca-Cola to install 3,000 to 4,000
employees in the building, which would have brought it to full
occupancy and made it the company's second-largest location after
its North Avenue headquarters building.
</P>
<P>
   The company had never revealed how much it was going to pay for
the Inforum, but it was priced as low as $30 million prior to the
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola notified Equitable Cos., the New York-based insurance
giant that owns the building, on Thursday that the company ``has
decided not to acquire the Inforum property,'' Preisinger said.
</P>
<P>
   Equitable could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Coca-Cola remains ``very committed to downtown
Atlanta in general and the Centennial Olympic Park area in
particular,'' Preisinger said. ``We are currently considering our
other options.''
</P>
<P>
   Preisinger declined to identify other locations Coca-Cola might
consider.
</P>
<P>
   However, Coca-Cola, which has considered additional office
development off and on for several years, owns vacant land
diagonally across Techwood from the Inforum. The soft drink giant
staged its Olympic City festival there during the 1996 Games but
has not disclosed any future plans for the cleared site.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola also owns undeveloped land at its North Avenue
headquarters complex and leases large blocks of space in Midtown
office buildings.
</P>
<P>
   The six-story Inforum, which housed the headquarters of the
Atlanta Committee for the Olympic Games, was built nine years ago
for $150 million as a technology mart, part of architect-developer
John C. Portman Jr.'s trade mart complex.
</P>
<P>
   However, Portman, facing financial collapse in 1990, was forced
to turn the building over to Equitable. After the building failed
to attract enough technology tenants, Equitable opted to convert it
to office space in 1991. It has been up for sale for several years.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
