A8664 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEATH-PENALTY-KAN &LR;      07-02 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEATH-PENALTY-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMENDMENT SPELLS END OF DEATH PENALTY IN KANSAS, SOME PROSECUTORS
SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY RIZZO  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: Is capital punishment dead in Kansas?
</P>
<P>
   Some prosecutors think an amendment to the state's 4-year-old
death penalty law will make it more difficult to get a death
sentence. The amendment went into effect Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It almost really means we don't have a death penalty
anymore,'' said Jim Clark, executive director of the Kansas County
and District Attorneys Association.
</P>
<P>
   Although death penalty opponents don't foresee such a dramatic
effect, they are happy with any change that could limit use of the
death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are those of us who oppose the death penalty, period,''
said Tim Emert, chairman of the Kansas Senate's judiciary
committee.
</P>
<P>
   The change requires a jury contemplating a death sentence to
first consider whether ``a term of imprisonment is sufficient to
defend and protect the people's safety.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the mandated prison term in such a case is life with no
chance of parole for 40 years, the new wording will apply in nearly
every case.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to make it much more difficult,'' said Johnson
County District Attorney Paul Morrison.
</P>
<P>
   The bill started as a proposal to expand the death penalty by
adding the premeditated killing of a child younger than 14 as one
of the crimes that qualified for capital punishment.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Mike Farmer, a Wichita Republican who opposes the death
penalty, added a proposed procedural change that would give a judge
the option of finding, before the case even went to trial, that a
prison term would sufficiently protect the public.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Carla Stovall led a contingent of district
attorneys in strongly opposing that measure. Emert said he also had
concerns about giving judges that kind of discretion.
</P>
<P>
   The result was that both the expansion and procedural change
were killed. But the wording about protecting the public through
imprisonment was added to the factors that jurors can use to vote
against a death sentence. The wording was tacked onto a bill that
was passed with several other measures.
</P>
<P>
   Wyandotte County District Attorney Nick Tomasic, one of the
prosecutors who fought the procedural change, said the Legislature
needs to decide whether it wants capital punishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just another attempt to water down the death penalty,''
Tomasic said.
</P>
<P>
   Stovall said she opposed the change and thinks it doesn't take
into consideration the safety of corrections officers, other
inmates or the possibility of escape.
</P>
<P>
   She said a defendant's eligibility for the death penalty
shouldn't be judged on whether he will be a future threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he did to the victim should be the consideration on
whether or not he deserves the death penalty,'' Stovall said.
</P>
<P>
   In Kansas, jurors deliberating a death penalty case must balance
a list of mitigating circumstances against a set of aggravating
circumstances in deciding whether a death sentence is appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   An example of a mitigating circumstance is no significant
history of prior criminal activity. Aggravating circumstances
include previous murder convictions.
</P>
<P>
   The new amendment adds a mitigating circumstance. It will give
most defendants an automatic mitigating factor before any other
factors are even considered, Morrison said.
</P>
<P>
   The change is welcome for attorneys who must defend people
facing a possible death sentence, but the effect won't be known
until it is actually argued to a jury, said Ron Wurtz, who heads
the state's death penalty defense unit.
</P>
<P>
   Wurtz thinks the new law puts in writing a question that most
jurors would consider anyway in a capital case.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes it an up-front issue,'' Wurtz said. ``I think it just
puts some honesty in the process. I think it will probably make for
a fairer trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Stovall agreed that most defense attorneys would argue to the
jury that their client would not be a threat if locked up in
prison. She said she hoped the measure would not hurt capital
prosecutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm confident jurors will be able to weigh all of the factors
and still make good decisions,'' Stovall said.
</P>
<P>
   Emert said he did not consider the change a ``major detour'' to
death penalty prosecutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have so few to start with,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Since Kansas reinstated capital punishment in 1994 after a
22-year hiatus, two men have been convicted of capital murder and
sentenced to death. No executions have been carried out.
</P>
<P>
   A number of others charged with capital murder have pleaded
guilty or no contest in exchange for life prison sentences.
</P>
<P>
   To be charged with capital murder in Kansas, a defendant must
commit a premeditated killing in which at least one of seven
factors is involved. Those include a killing in connection with a
sex crime, killing more than one person or killing a police
officer.
</P>
<P>
   If the defendant is found guilty, a jury then deliberates the
penalty. The jurors are instructed to determine whether the
aggravating factors outweigh the mitigating factors.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri, which has a much broader capital murder law that can
apply to any case of premeditated murder, has not had any major
changes in its law in the last several years, according to a
spokesman for the Missouri attorney general's office.
</P>
<P>
   Like Kansas, jurors in Missouri weigh aggravating and mitigating
factors in reaching their decision. Capital murder was reinstated
in Missouri 20 years ago; 32 executions have been carried out since
1989.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-98 2042EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
