</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-FIRES-GRIDLOCK-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN WAKE OF FIRES: CLOSED HIGHWAYS, DETOURS AND DASHED PLANS 
</HEADLINE>
  (With FLA-FIRES) 
(lh) 
 By DOUGLAS FRANTZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Larry and Marcia Johnson shook the sand
from their beach towels, scowled at the floating ash turning the
sky gray and pondered their ruined Fourth of July weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``This race was a pretty big thing, the first night race at
Daytona,'' said Johnson, who had driven here from Ashville, N.Y.,
with his wife to attend the Pepsi 400 on Saturday night at Daytona
International Speedway. ``And now the race is postponed, and we're
going to have to go up the middle of the state to get home.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a day of cancellations, vast detours and dashed plans in
places normally jammed for the Fourth of July holiday.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of wildfires have closed highways here, including a
heavily traveled 140-mile stretch of Interstate 95 from
Jacksonville in the north to Titusville on the mid-peninsula coast.
The fires have also forced the evacuation of thousands of people in
Daytona Beach and the surrounding area, and cast a pall of smoke
over thousands of acres.
</P>
<P>
   The emergency procedures delivered a double whammy to the tens
of thousands of race fans who had already arrived in Daytona Beach
for a historic weekend. For the first time, a NASCAR race was to be
held at night, under new lights, at the famous speedway. It was
also to be the first prime-time television broadcast of a NASCAR
race.
</P>
<P>
   Early Thursday morning, officials at the speedway postponed the
race until Oct. 17. In light of the fires, they cited safety
concerns and traffic problems that would have been created by the
race, which was expected to attract thousands of fans for the
qualifying runs Thursday and Friday and a sellout crowd of 200,000
on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   But those fans quickly heard even more bad news: the closing of
the broad section of I-95, the main north-south highway that runs
the length of the Florida east coast. On an average day, 61,000
vehicles use that section of the Interstate. State transportation
officials said traffic for the Fourth of July weekend, the busiest
travel time of the year, was normally three to four times heavier.
</P>
<P>
   The section was closed at 10 p.m. Wednesday as wildfires along
the Interstate created so much smoke that visibility was reduced to
dangerous levels, state transportation and highway patrol officials
said. They were uncertain when it would be reopened.
</P>
<P>
   Drivers heading north were being routed along state roads, and
many found themselves behind long lines of tractor-trailer rigs.
Drivers going south to beaches and resorts for the three-day
weekend were dispatched west from Jacksonville on a 180-mile detour
along Interstate 10, Interstate 75 and Florida's Turnpike.
</P>
<P>
   By late Thursday afternoon, transportation officials said
traffic was running smoothly on the roads and highways being used
in place of I-95.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic was also smooth along Interstate 4 from Daytona Beach to
Orlando, where officials said the major theme parks were not
affected by the fires or smoke.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Despite temperatures approaching 100 degrees in Daytona Beach,
the beach was nearly deserted Thursday afternoon. Managers and
clerks at ocean-front hotels said they were getting many
cancellations from race fans and beachgoers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normally, you couldn't get a parking spot on the beach,'' said
Bill Baker, who rents golf carts and four-wheelers for cruising the
beach at K.D. Cycles.
</P>
<P>
   After hearing on the radio that the race was postponed, the
Johnsons spent part of the afternoon lounging on beach towels
beside their car, which had several NASCAR decals on the windows
and a racing flag flying from a window. They said they would wait
until Thursday night to begin the drive home.
</P>
<P>
   But some fans were in no hurry to leave. In a parking area for
recreational vehicles near the speedway, Mary and Chocks Treleven
from Tallahassee, Fla., had set up camp with several friends
alongside their campers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to party until the beer's gone,'' Mrs. Treleven
said. ``We're upset about the race getting postponed, but I think
they made the right choice. I'm just in no hurry to get home.''
</P>
</TEXT>
