<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUNKEN-BOATERS-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WATER PATROL WILL BE OUT FOR THE HOLIDAY TO AVERT DRUNKEN BOATERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY L. THOMAS  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE OF THE OZARKS, Mo. _ Missouri Water Patrol officers quietly
anchored their boats at Mile Marker 19 just before midnight
Saturday on the lake's main channel near Osage Beach.
</P>
<P>
   By 2 a.m., they had randomly stopped 41 boats during a routine
sobriety checkpoint. Eight boat operators were arrested for being
drunk _ nearly one for every five ``pulled over.''
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, a typical Kansas City Police Department sobriety
checkpoint on the roads will net arrests in only one of 20 cars
stopped.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably 85 percent of the people we deal with on Friday night
or Saturday have been drinking,'' said Patrolman J. Pragman, who
was involved in the Osage Beach checkpoint.
</P>
<P>
   As the Independence Day holiday kicks off, hundreds of boaters
will be heading for area lakes _ but some won't be going home. In
Missouri and elsewhere, authorities are finding that more people
than ever are dying in boating accidents involving alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   So while vacationers are loading up their crafts and their
coolers, Water Patrol officers are gearing up for a crackdown on
drunken boaters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be out in full force, looking for violations,'' said
Pragman. ``...By Friday afternoon, it'll be organized chaos.''
</P>
<P>
   The Water Patrol said that on a typical weekend, the Lake of the
Ozarks will see 20,000 boats on the water. On holiday weekends that
number will at least double.
</P>
<P>
   ``Typically, the Fourth of July is the busiest boating weekend
of the year,'' said Cpl. Mark Richerson, a Water Patrol spokesman.
``We're hoping for no drownings and no fatalities, but to be quite
honest, if we see that, we'll be very fortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   Missouri had 25 boating fatalities in 1997, Richerson said. He
said that through June 21 this year, there had been 119 accidents
on Missouri waterways, resulting in 11 deaths. Most involved
alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   The Water Patrol is trying to combat the problem by getting
drunks off the water. Last Friday through Sunday, officers made 19
BWI, or ``boating while intoxicated,'' arrests on Lake of the
Ozarks alone.
</P>
<P>
   The arrests have steadily increased, from 95 in 1993 to 331 in
1997. So far this year, Water Patrol officers have arrested 142
drunken boaters statewide. Through roughly the same time frame last
year, they had made only 76 arrests.
</P>
<P>
   Pragman's colleagues say he is one of the more aggressive
officers when it comes to nabbing drunken boaters. Perhaps that's
because in just three years Pragman has seen first-hand the tragic
consequences of drinking and boating.
</P>
<P>
   In April 1997, he helped investigate a crash that killed two
Kansas City firefighters and a Lee's Summit motorcycle officer. The
men were on a fishing trip when their 20-foot Regal Runabout
crashed into a 5-foot-high walkway made of reinforced galvanized
steel. The boat skidded nearly 80 feet before stopping on a wall,
authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Tests determined all three were legally drunk.
</P>
<P>
   The following month, on Memorial Day weekend, Pragman
investigated an accident in which one boat ran over another. The
man in the boat that was hit fell into the water. His body wasn't
found for seven days. Both drivers were intoxicated.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other driver drove away from the scene,'' Pragman said,
shaking his head. ``When we found him, he said he thought he had
hit a log.''
</P>
<P>
   Authorities say the reasons for the increase in BWI arrests may
be heightened enforcement, or just more drunks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're either getting better at it, or there's more and more of
them out there, or both,'' Richerson said. ``For one thing, we've
got more officers now than we ever had. But more importantly, we
have improved detection techniques. A lot of our people are
carrying PBTs, portable breath testing machines.''
</P>
<P>
   There also is more awareness about drunken boating.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are getting tired of not being able to take their
families to the lakes because of the drunk boat operators,''
Richerson said. ``Take Memorial Day weekend. We had 43 intoxicated
operators on Lake of the Ozarks alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Drinking in boats is allowed, Pragman said, as long as the
driver isn't drunk. He added, however, that ``the others in the
boat can be drunk, and they usually are.'' -More-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
