<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NICHOLS-MERGER-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
J.C. NICHOLS STOCKHOLDERS APPROVE MERGER WITH HIGHWOODS
PROPERTIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JULIUS A. KARASH and CHARLES R.T. CRUMPLEY  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ J.C. Nichols Co. shareholders on Wednesday
approved a merger between the Nichols Co. and a North Carolina
firm, a move that ends local control over the company that shaped
much of Kansas City's landscape.
</P>
<P>
   The merger with Highwoods Properties Inc. was approved by
holders of 3.5 million Nichols shares, about 76 percent of the
total. The merger required approval by holders of two-thirds of the
stock of Nichols.
</P>
<P>
   The merger is valued at $544 million, including $231 million in
Nichols Co. debt that Highwoods will assume. It is scheduled to be
completed by July 15.
</P>
<P>
   Highwoods is a real estate investment trust based in Raleigh,
N.C. With its partnerships and subsidiaries, Highwoods develops,
manages, leases and acquires real estate, mostly suburban office
and industrial properties.
</P>
<P>
   The J.C. Nichols Co. is best known for its development and
ownership of the Country Club Plaza shopping center.
</P>
<P>
   Jesse Clyde Nichols, founder of the Nichols Co., envisioned the
Plaza when he climbed a hill overlooking the sludgy Brush Creek
Valley in 1912. His company began developing the Plaza 10 years
later. With its fountains, walkways and Spanish architecture, it is
Kansas City's best known chunk of real estate.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald P. Gibson, Highwoods' president and chief executive
officer, on Wednesday described the Plaza as a ``crown jewel.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a rare opportunity to become associated with such a high
quality piece of property,'' Gibson said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the Plaza, the Nichols Co. has developed neighborhoods,
shopping centers and office buildings around the Kansas City area.
Nichols developments include the cities of Fairway, Westwood,
Mission Hills, Mission Woods, Prairie Village, the Country Club
District residential neighborhood and much of the Brookside area.
</P>
<P>
   Nichols' developments are known for tree-lined streets and
generous doses of artistic amenities, including statues imported
from Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The Nichols Co. also has significant holdings in Des Moines,
Iowa. However, it failed in its effort to create a Plaza-like
development in St. Petersburg, Fla., several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from Highwoods and Nichols said the Nichols Co. will
retain its name. Barrett Brady, president and chief executive
officer of the Nichols Co., will become a senior vice president of
Highwoods and will be Highwoods' top regional officer in Kansas
City.
</P>
<P>
   Approval of the merger with Highwoods came at a special meeting
of Nichols shareholders Wednesday morning at the Ritz-Carlton,
Kansas City. About 200 people attended.
</P>
<P>
   The merger agreement was praised by officials from Nichols and
Highwoods but drew criticism from some Nichols shareholders, one of
whom has waged a legal battle against the merger.
</P>
<P>
   That legal battle met a setback Wednesday afternoon when Jackson
County Circuit Judge William F. Mauer denied a request that the
court issue a temporary restraining order to prevent the merger's
completion.
</P>
<P>
   John Flake of Prairie Village, a Nichols shareholder, made the
request. Flake filed a class-action lawsuit in opposition to the
merger, on behalf of himself and other Nichols shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Mauer also did not grant Flake's request that the court hold a
hearing to consider a preliminary injunction to stop the merger.
</P>
<P>
   Mauer's decision said ``insufficient facts'' had been presented
to show that Flake and the other plaintiffs would suffer
irreparable harm if the merger went ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Flake said he didn't know whether he would appeal Mauer's
ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Nichols shareholders will receive cash, Highwoods stock or a
combination of both. Based on Wednesday's closing price of
Highwoods stock, the value to be received by Nichols shareholders
is $65 a share. The final exchange ratio for the stock part of the
transaction will be determined on the closing date.
</P>
<P>
   The Highwoods merger also was challenged by Blackacre Capital
Management of New York. Blackacre owns 14 percent of Nichols'
shares and made a $70-a-share cash offer for Nichols, subject to
certain conditions.
</P>
<P>
   - MORE -
</P>
</TEXT>
