<SLUG> BC-CARS-COLLECTING-1,000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAR COLLECTING: ON THE ROAD WITH AN E-TYPE JAG 
</HEADLINE>
  (Duplication warning: Also moved in `a' category) 
(mk) 
 By VINCENT DE PAUL O'BRIEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Suppose you fulfill your fantasy and actually buy a classic car,
say a 1969 E-Type Jaguar roadster. What in the world would you do
with it?
</P>
<P>
   What if you cast prudence and all reason aside, hint at
adventure to a dear photographer friend and drive it cross-country
_ some 10,000 miles in 39 days? Cover 21 states, eight national
parks and four big cities. And while you're at it, endure five
breakdowns (the car's, not your own). After all, it is a '60s Jag,
a finicky breed of cat that many Americans love to look at, whether
it is tearing down the road or sitting on the shoulder waiting for
a tow truck.
</P>
<P>
   I had expected breakdowns when I set out last summer from Long
Island, with an itinerary that included stops in Seattle, San
Francisco, Los Angeles and Las Vegas, Nev. But there were two
fascinating developments I had not anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   The first was the car's reception, or more accurately its lack
of one, between the coasts. It has always turned heads, thousands
of them, in New York, and was enthusiastically received in San
Francisco and Los Angeles. But in the 3,000 miles in between it
didn't cause much of a stir. In Buhl, Idaho, conversations were
more likely to center on the price of potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   The second was altitude sickness _ not mine, the car's. Out
West, everyone knows about the horrible effects of altitude on the
fuel and air mixture in older cars, which have no computers to
steady performance and only a limited range of adjustments. But I
didn't know that, and the ascent to the northeast entrance of
Yellowstone from Montana, the snaking Bear Tooth Pass (elevation
10,947 feet), was our first indication that we wouldn't hear the
engine run evenly again till we were at sea level in California. I
replaced the spark plugs four times during mountainous passages and
cleaned the carbon off the plugs' tips about every other day.
</P>
<P>
   Until I began to prepare for the trip, the car was just the way
it was made 29 years ago. To increase the low odds of a successful
journey, a guru of classic Jags, Mark Thornton of Sayville, N.Y.,
replaced the antiquated points and condenser with a relatively
new-to-the-market electronic ignition that fit in the same space.
He also added a computerized gizmo called a multiple spark
discharge box, which provides a significantly stronger jolt of
juice to the spark plugs, followed microseconds later with smaller
jolts _ the effect being virtually complete fuel combustion. In
essence, more oomph. The spark plug wires and the coil were
upgraded commensurately, the figuring being that the ignition
system posed the greatest risk.
</P>
<P>
   When I left last June, Thornton was restoring a 1961 Jaguar Mark
II sedan for his wife. He suggested that I pack a spare alternator
and, gesturing toward his wife's car, added, ``I wouldn't even take
that car cross-country after I'm done with it.''
</P>
<P>
   After that less-than-ringing commentary on my plans, I loaded
the trunk with spares, but no alternator, since mine had been
rebuilt the year before. The alternator was the third thing to
fail.
</P>
<P>
   The first was the little sensor in the radiator that tells the
cooling fans to turn on. It quit on a steep grade at the beginning
of the Teton Pass just past Jackson, Wyo., and was the only failure
I was actually prepared for. The fans in my car are wired two ways,
one that worked off the sensor, like all other E-types, and one
that overrode it though a switch on the dashboard. If you change
the connections on a few wires, presto, the fans work. But you have
to remember to turn them on manually, and I will not recount here
the number of times I forgot.
</P>
<P>
   The trip was grand, with stops at the Badlands, Mount Rushmore,
Crazy Horse Mountain and Little Big Horn. Then came the altitude
sickness, starting at Yellowstone.
</P>
<P>
   The scariest trouble came after leaving Crater Lake National
Park in Oregon, when I heard a snapping noise behind me. Poking
around on the side of the road, I found that two of the 72 spokes
in the left rear wire wheel had broken. Further poking revealed a
broken cotter pin in the wheel bearing. Without that pin, a nut
slowly loosens and the wheel comes off, which is what was in the
process of happening. The stress from the loose wheel had snapped
the spokes. Using the spare wheel and a borrowed nail bent to work
like a cotter pin, we were back on the road; I found a replacement
the next day.
</P>
<P>
   The alternator started squeaking near Crescent City in Northern
California, though the voltmeter on the dashboard indicated that it
was still putting out enough current to keep the car going. When
the squeak became a screech 80 miles later in Eureka, a phone call
to an alternator rebuilder another 120 miles away in Ukiah
persuaded me to push on, based on his guess that he could fix it.
He couldn't.
</P>
<P>
   The next hope was in San Francisco, 120 miles to the south. The
alternator, by then howling for a warm spot in the junk yard sun,
made it. But if you've never traveled in the dark and the fog on
Highway 101, a succession of hairpin turns, you might not want to
add to your agitation by wondering whether you could manage it
without handy accessories like headlights.
</P>
<P>
   Several San Francisco shops actually had the correct rebuilt
alternator, and one was near the 49-mile scenic trail that many
tourists follow to see the city. So we picked up the new
alternator, I installed it in the street, and we spent the rest of
the day driving the trail.
</P>
<P>
   On the way down the coast we stopped in San Luis Obispo at XK's
Unlimited, a renowned rebuilder of classic Jaguars. While I ogled
their collection they retuned my carburetors for sea level,
straightening out the mess I had made of them along the way.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The lengthiest delay began when one of the rear shock absorbers
collapsed with startling suddenness not far from Zion National Park
in southern Utah, falling into the rear brake rotor and making an
awful metal-on-metal racket.
</P>
<P>
   There are four rear shocks on many Jags, not the traditional
two, and they are twinned, two on each side. After getting a tow 30
miles to Kanab, where the broken pieces were pulled out, we decided
that nothing would stop us from seeing the wonders of Grand Canyon
and Bryce Canyon National Parks, so we pressed on. It was great for
us, but too much to ask of the working twin, which sagged until the
car listed badly to port. It took two unscheduled days and nights
in Panguitch, Utah, before XK's Unlimited could ship replacements
to St. George, Utah, and a delivery service could get them the
remaining 90 miles. I installed them and headed East.
</P>
<P>
   But not before one last crisis. The down-pipe portion of the
exhaust system, which started the trip with an innocent little
leak, fractured on Interstate 70 on the way to Denver. After
fastening a clamp to the broken pipe, and electrical wire to the
clamp to tie it close to its original position, we roared over the
Rockies, sounding like a pack of Harley-Davidsons. The next day,
the local Midas dealer fabricated a new pipe.
</P>
<P>
   Some Jaguar aficionados say I've set a record for trip distance
in this country in a classic E-Type, but they offer no hard
evidence. I've decided to ignore the lack of documentation and
claim a world record.
</P>
<P>
   Will I ever do something like this again? The sights were
magnificent, so of course. But next time I'll start by flying to
Denver and renting a younger car.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
