<HEADER>
A8672 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN--ROBERTSON-HNS &LR;      07-02 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN--ROBERTSON-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   Slugfest looming &QL; 
on Centre Court
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
WIMBLEDON, England _ For a change, the form chart held. That four
male seeds made the Wimbledon semifinals is odd enough _ they tell
us it happens less than 50 percent of the time in Grand Slam
tournaments _ but the truth is the best four seeds did so as well,
convening for today's semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   At the outset, Pete Sampras, Richard Krajicek, Goran Ivanisevic
and Tim Henman were really the only blokes who had solid chances to
wind up standing tall Sunday. None has had a particularly smashing
season, but grass-court tennis is ever a challenge unique unto
itself.
</P>
<P>
   Note the unexpected, yet hardly unfathomable, women's final:
Jana Novotna vs. Nathalie Tauziat. They are two wizened,
battled-hardened veterans of the turf wars who have put their years
of experience on the capricious lawns to excellent use.
</P>
<P>
   And as with the remaining pair of women, the aforementioned four
grasp the nuances of grass and have the proper smash-mouth games to
put their educations to good use. It's a two-part equation, the
solution of which escapes most.
</P>
<P>
   Marcelo Rios is No. 2 in the world behind Sampras, but he should
have faked an injury or illness and stayed home. The Chilean churl
and Wimbledon are never going to be amigos. Rios' first-round
defeat wasn't a shocker in the least. Nor was the one suffered by
the French Open champion, Carlos Moya, in the second. He told us
after his win at Roland Garros he had no chance here.
</P>
<P>
   Weak fall by the wayside
</P>
<P>
   OK, Petr Korda, the Czech ace (bandage), might be a bona fide
contender if he were ever healthy, but he won't be. You ever see
this guy's body? It's a bunch of fragile sticks held together with
baling wire. Korda has been known to pull muscles and strain
ligaments while sipping coffee.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Rusedski's mental health is his obstacle. He, perhaps more
so than Henman, should be England's great hope, but the bogus Brit,
a Canadian by birth, is a mess, as the recent run of his fed-up,
fleeing coaches will attest.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Philippoussis, Australia's Greek-god would-be Sampras
clone, can't seem to get his handsome head right, either, although
slamming headfirst into Pete as he did in the quarters made for an
additional complication.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras often plays elsewhere as though his mind is on
non-tennis matters, but Wimbledon is one temple he dares not
desecrate. He laps the field on his best Centre Court days, and on
his worst he's still where the smart money belongs.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to believe he was a first-round loser the first two
times he visited and a second-round pigeon the third year. But
since, he has soared with the eagles, suffering a mere two defeats
in 44 matches, leaving him positioned to equal Bjorn Borg's Open
Era record of five titles.
</P>
<P>
   But one of the two thugs to mug him is certain to be waiting in
the final. Krajicek ('96 quarterfinals) and Ivanisevic ('92
semifinals) will wallop aces at each other today in the preliminary
to Sampras-Henman, the latter being perhaps the most anticipated
match on Centre Court since Virginia Wade's victorious Wimbledon
centennial final of 1977.
</P>
<P>
   Henman, a baby-faced boomer of 23 whose slight frame belies the
G-force behind his serve, has given the English something about
which to cheer in a week when they badly need cheering up. Like
Sampras, he chases a bit of history of his own as the lone native
son in a quarter of a century to reach the Wimbledon semis.
</P>
<P>
   Henman has rare opportunity
</P>
<P>
   Should he beat Sampras, then go the distance, he would become
the first Brit in 62 years _ since the late Fred Perry completed
his three-peat in 1936 _ to hold the cup aloft Sunday afternoon.
Which might be almost enough to put England's mind at ease over the
end of its World Cup bid, lost on a penalty shootout against
Argentina on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   But asking Henman to handle Sampras on Pete's home court, the
staunch loyalties of the spectators notwithstanding, might be a tad
unfair. The tide of emotion will carry Henman only so far, and the
burden of expectations could create a damaging counter-drag. If
Sampras is on, Henman goes off quickly.
</P>
<P>
   But Krajicek and Ivanisevic, the Dutchman and the Croat who are
tax-saving neighbors in Monte Carlo, should stage quite the
donnybrook. Although Ivanisevic spots Krajicek an inch and 10
pounds, Goran's lefthandedness is the equalizer.
</P>
<P>
   The twice Wimbledon runner-up, to Andre Agassi in '92 and
Sampras in '94, has beaten the '96 champion in eight consecutive
matches, but the three most recent ones have gone three sets with
Ivanisevic winning tiebreakers in the third. Six of their past 11
sets have required tiebreaks.
</P>
<P>
   It all makes for a long and, by definition, brutish afternoon of
elemental grass-court tennis. Only the strong have survived to
fight again. The meek never shall inherit this well-worn patch of
sodded earth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
