<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPIDERMAN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Spiderman caught in a web
 &HT;    By Monika Gonzalez
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. -- Spiderman _ a burglar detectives say
scaled high-rise condominiums to slip through unlocked balcony
doors _ is sitting in a Broward County jail cell doing something
else spiders do.
</P>
<P>
   Waiting.
</P>
<P>
   Derrick Gregory James has not been charged with burglary, but
police said he was caught in the act.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives said they expect charges will be filed against James
within the next two weeks. Tuesday, they charged a suspected
accomplice, Derrick Davis, 28, of Miami Lakes, with 32 counts of
forgery, grand theft and passing on a forged document, the Florida
Department of Law Enforcement reported.
</P>
<P>
   James, a former paratrooper from Miami-Dade County, was already
wanted on an unrelated warrant issued in April 1997 _ long before
many of the burglaries. He is being held on violation of sentencing
rules, stemming from an earlier conviction.
</P>
<P>
   James was supposed to be serving out a house-arrest sentence for
grand theft, and probation officials said he wasn't staying home as
required. James was allowed to leave home only for work. Department
records show he was unemployed.
</P>
<P>
   Police suspect Spiderman in more than 100 burglaries from
Brevard County to Miami _ thefts totaling $6 million in cash,
jewelry, credit cards and computer equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Jupiter and Boca Raton police are among about 45 law enforcement
agencies that consider James a suspect in high-rise burglary cases.
</P>
<P>
   Because James is being held without bail until a
probation-violation hearing, detectives say they have more time to
research and prepare cases for filing with a statewide prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   A task force led by the FDLE had been working to determine his
identity for about a year, an FDLE spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've always referred to him as Spiderman,'' said Jupiter Sgt.
Tom Flannery.
</P>
<P>
   For the past six months, Jupiter detectives have reviewed
unsolved burglary cases dating back at least three years to see how
many may be linked to the elusive Spiderman.
</P>
<P>
   James surfaced as a suspect months ago based on clues and
information discovered by several Miami-Dade County police
agencies, police in Miami-Dade and Palm Beach counties said.
</P>
<P>
   A network of detectives staked out several locations, including
Bristol Tower, a 30-story building on Brickell Avenue in Miami,
police sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Then Spiderman walked into their web.
</P>
<P>
   Police said they saw his tall, muscular frame walk into Bristol
Tower _ but then they lost him. Later, they spotted the burglar
carrying, among other things, jewelry labeled with a burglary
victim's name.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
