<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 20:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8679 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-AIDS-IMMUNE-600&AMP;A     07-02 1308
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-AIDS-IMMUNE-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAILED TESTS ON MONKEYS FRUSTRATE HOPES FOR HUMAN AIDS VACCINE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By LAWRENCE K. ALTMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ Hopes for a vaccine against AIDS were set back at the
12th World AIDS Conference here Thursday when researchers reported
that a vaccine made from a weakened simian virus and injected into
monkeys has caused the disease it was designed to prevent.
</P>
<P>
   The vaccine was made by deleting genes from a version of the
simian virus. Many experts had looked to this SIV vaccine as the
best model for developing a human counterpart, because it seemed to
provide the strongest evidence of protection against an AIDS-like
virus.
</P>
<P>
   The new findings leave researchers little ahead of where they
were when the disease was identified a decade ago, two leading
American AIDS experts said here. They are Dr. Anthony Fauci, head
of the National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases in
Bethesda, Md., and Dr. Robert Gallo, a co-discoverer of the human
immunodeficiency virus, who works at the Institute of Human
Virology in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Fauci said the new findings show that he and other federal
officials were correct in urging caution in testing vaccines made
from artificially weakened, or attenuated, AIDS virus. More than
300 doctors in the United States and elsewhere have pleaded with
the U.S. Food and Drug Administration to let them become human
guinea pigs for a similar experimental vaccine made from a weakened
HIV. Therion Biologics Corp. of Cambridge, Mass., is trying to
develop such a human AIDS vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   The leader of the group of doctors, Charles Farthing, an AIDS
specialist in Los Angeles, said that he would still volunteer to
test an attenuated AIDS vaccine, despite Thursday's news. Farthing
repeated his plea in a talk at the meeting Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The report came from Dr. Ruth Ruprecht, a scientist at the Dana
Farber Cancer Institute in Boston. She said that the weakened SIV
injected into monkeys mutated to cause simian AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993 Dr. Ruprecht began her experiments by injecting nine
newborn monkeys with the weakened SIV vaccine developed by Dr.
Ronald Desrosiers of the New England Primate Center in Southboro,
Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Although she had reported earlier that some of these monkeys
became ill, Thursday she said, ``we have some rather sobering
news'' that all newborn monkeys given the vaccine are ill or dead.
Of the nine newborn monkeys injected with the weakened SIV, six
have developed simian AIDS and five of them have died. The
remaining three monkeys are ill or have immunological abnormalities
related to simian AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts had said that an AIDS vaccine given to newborns
would not work because their immune systems were immature. But
Thursday Dr. Ruprecht had similar news about tests on adult
monkeys.
</P>
<P>
   Of 15 vaccinated adult monkeys, four have had the virus return
after it initially disappeared. Of the four, one is dead of simian
AIDS, one has early-stage disease and two have developed
immunological abnormalities.
</P>
<P>
   All the newborn and adult monkeys developed simian AIDS from the
initial injection with SIV and not from a second injection designed
to test its effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we saw with the infants was a fast-forward version of
what can happen to vaccinated adults,'' Dr. Ruprecht said. ``It's
not going to lead to a safe vaccine.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has called for development of an AIDS vaccine
in nine years. But many health officials and others are calling for
the administration to provide more money to meet his challenge,
saying that a vaccine is needed as the major weapon to stop the
AIDS epidemic.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Many vaccines are made by weakening a live virus. Others are
made by killing a virus. Some newer vaccines are made from tiny
portions of a virus, using genetic engineering techniques.
</P>
<P>
   HIV is notorious for its ability to mutate, and the possibility
has led many experts to shun making a live attenuated vaccine. They
have said that a variety of approaches will be needed to develop an
AIDS vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes two types of vaccines are needed to protect. For
example, both the killed Salk vaccine and weakened live Sabin
vaccine have brought polio to the verge of eradication.
</P>
<P>
   Last month the FDA authorized the first full-scale test of an
AIDS vaccine, one genetically engineered by Vaxgen of South San
Francisco. The vaccine is made from a fragment of the outer shell
of the AIDS virus. Scientists are divided about the degree of
protection it will afford.
</P>
<P>
   The research that led to Thursday's report on a live attenuated
AIDS vaccine began in 1992 when Desrosiers reported that his team
in Massachusetts had prepared an experimental vaccine by deleting a
gene known as nef from SIV. Desrosiers reported that he had given
the nef-deleted SIV to six monkeys that did not develop simian AIDS
even after injection of SIV containing all its genes.
</P>
<P>
   Interest in the nef gene got another boost in 1992 when Jennifer
Learmont, a Red Cross official in Sydney, Australia, reported that
five people who had developed HIV from contaminated blood
transfusions did not seem to be developing AIDS. More startling was
that the blood donor also had been infected for many years without
developing AIDS. The strain carried by the donor was naturally
missing the nef gene.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Learmont said here Thursday that the Australian patients
still had not developed AIDS 14 years after becoming infected
although the number of CD4 immune cells in their blood was
beginning to decline, a possible sign that the infection was
progressing.
</P>
<P>
   The unusual cluster has led Australian researchers to try to
develop an AIDS vaccine derived from the nef-deleted virus from the
patients.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Ruprecht said she originally shared Farthing's optimism
about the prospects of a live attenuated AIDS virus because so many
other human vaccines were based on the concept.
</P>
<P>
   She said that in 1993 she began her experiments on newborn
monkeys after obtaining the virus from Desrosiers. The experiments
were patterned after those that showed that a human vaccine could
provide about 95 percent protection against the liver infection,
hepatitis B, if given shortly after birth.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Ruprecht said that other scientists, including Desrosiers,
have found that monkeys injected with genetically weakened SIV have
become ill or died.
</P>
<P>
   The simian findings shed new light on the nef gene, which
scientists thought was responsible for the virulence of the virus.
Dr. Ruprecht said in an interview that her research has taught that
deletion of the nef gene is not safe for a vaccine because it can
still produce disease.
</P>
<P>
   That shows that other genes must be involved. Like Desrosiers,
Dr. Ruprecht is studying other HIV genes to determine if any could
be deleted singly or in combination to develop a different
attenuated vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   Farthing said that earlier this year the FDA had given the green
light for further research to develop a live attenuated HIV
vaccine. But he said it would be two or more years before human
trials of such a vaccine could begin.
</P>
<P>
   The initial tests of a vaccine or other drug are designed to
test safety, not effectiveness. The history of vaccine development
is replete with examples of scientists who have been the first
human guinea pig.
</P>
<P>
   In earlier interviews, Desrosiers has said that he was unwilling
to test his HIV vaccine on himself.
</P>
<P>
   But Farthing, who is not involved in the vaccine's development,
said Thursday: ``The only way to find out if it works is to test it
in humans. SIV is not HIV and monkeys are not humans.''
</P>
<P>
   If the vaccine proved unsafe and he developed HIV, Farthing said
he would take the newer combination of drugs that controls HIV in
many people. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
