A8675 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NICHOLS-MERGER-2NDTAK     07-02 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NICHOLS-MERGER-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ to certain conditions.
</P>
<P>
   No one from the Blackacre group presented themselves at
Wednesday's special meeting of Nichols shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too bad that shareholders left value on the table, a
minimum of $8 to $10 (per share),'' Ronald Kravit, a Blackacre
principal, said in a telephone interview after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Price Sloan, Nichols' general counsel, countered that the Morgan
Stanley investment banking firm issued an opinion stating that the
Highwoods transaction was fair to all Nichols shareholders from a
financial standpoint.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Sloan said Institutional Shareholder Services, the leading
advisory firm to institutional shareholders, considered both the
Highwoods and Blackacre proposal and then recommended that Nichols
shareholders vote for the Highwoods merger.
</P>
<P>
   Flake said he attended Wednesday's meeting but did not speak out
when the floor was opened for questions because he thought it
``wouldn't have made any difference.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very disappointed in how it went,'' Flake said. ``I had
hoped it wouldn't pass, but I was afraid it was going to, because
of all the time and money the officers had spent trying to get
everybody to vote in favor of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gibson, Highwoods' president and chief executive officer, said
Highwoods was attracted by the Nichols Co.'s talents and assets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look to the people first,'' Gibson said. ``People who are
credible in the community and have significant market share.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the Nichols name will be kept because of its great
recognition value.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson said Highwoods and Nichols will develop a strategic plan
``that will feature a very aggressive posture toward developing
retail, office and industrial properties in this community.''
</P>
<P>
   Highwoods is committed to all current Nichols Co. plans for
development and redevelopment, including plans to redevelop the
Plaza, Gibson said.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding his own company, Gibson said Highwoods has grown
through mergers and acquisitions. He said the 25-year-old company
has never defaulted on a loan or had to give a property back to a
lender.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Smart, a longtime Nichols shareholder who is the chairman
of the Perkins Smart and Boyd Inc. investment firm in Fairway, said
Wednesday's vote came as ``a very big surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   Smart said many believed the merger would not get the two-thirds
affirmative vote that it required, especially since a fairly
sizable contingent of shareholders voiced disapproval about what
they considered a low offering price for the stock.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, shareholders seemed to be weary, Smart said.
Different stockholders have feuded with different managers on and
off for more than 3 1/2 years. Even dissatisfied stockholders
apparently preferred accepting the Highwoods deal with its
allegedly lower price instead of continuing a fight for a year or
two, Smart said.
</P>
<P>
   Barney A. Karbank, a Nichols shareholder and chairman of the
B.A. Karbank &AMP; Co. real estate firm, said it was ``unfortunate that
a company as important to the Kansas City area and its economy is
losing local ownership and control.''
</P>
<P>
   But Brady said the vote represented a ``great day for the
Nichols Co.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The financial muscle and expertise of Highwoods, coupled with
the local knowledge and local team that's in place here, will bode
well for the J.C. Nichols Co. and the community,'' Brady said.
</P>
<P>
   Kay Callison, a Nichols board member and daughter of Nichols Co.
chairman emeritus Miller Nichols, said she was pleased by the high
level of shareholder support for the Highwoods deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very comfortable with Highwoods,'' said Callison, who was
designated as a Highwoods board member Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The votes of participants in Nichols' employee stock ownership
plan were crucial because the merger required the approval of
holders of at least two-thirds of Nichols stock.
</P>
<P>
   Audy Waldrop, a Nichols employee stock ownership plan
participant who attended Wednesday's meeting, said he supported the
Highwoods merger.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us this is like a retirement account,'' said Waldrop, who
formerly did maintenance work at Nichols apartments. ``I can take
the cash and roll it over into something that's more lucrative and
I will have more personal control over.''
</P>
</TEXT>
