<SLUG> BC-ATWORK-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHANGES TO `JOB' BRING MORE TEMPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: My job could be at risk. So could yours.
</P>
<P>
   Before we run around in a millennium panic, though, let's define
terms, starting with the word ``job.''
</P>
<P>
   About 10 percent of U.S. workers _ maybe up to 20 percent,
according to the Society for Human Resource Management _ already
understand the new definition. They are members of the contingency
work force, which includes temporary, leased, free-lance and
on-call workers, independent contractors and consultants.
</P>
<P>
   They are workers ``who have little or no attachment to the
company at which they work. Whether they work, when they work and
how much they work depend on the company's need for them. They have
neither an explicit nor implicit contract for continuing
employment.''
</P>
<P>
   Those are the words of Helen Axel and Stanley Nolen, business
researchers and authors of (italics begin here) Managing Contingent
Workers: How to Reap the Benefits and Reduce the Risks(italics end
here).
</P>
<P>
   And throughout the U.S. business world, employers are reaping
and reducing.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T, for example, began to eliminate many regular payroll jobs
seven years ago. But instead of just saying bye-bye to employees,
the company channeled many of them to its internal staffing
service, Resource Link. There, the downsized employees jumped into
a pool of workers to do AT&AMP;T ``jobs'' on an as-needed, or
contingency, basis.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, AT&AMP;T filled the Resource Link pool with workers
whose jobs were eliminated or at risk. Today, half of the pool is
occupied by workers who choose the option because of the
flexibility and cross-training opportunities they believe
contingency work provides.
</P>
<P>
   True, the AT&AMP;T experience is enhanced because the company
continued to provide employee benefits to Resource Link workers.
That's a comfort many contingency workers don't have.
</P>
<P>
   But the phenomenal national growth in temporary staffing _ the
number of professional temps has quadrupled since 1991, according
to the National Association of Temporary and Staffing Services _ is
prompting industry changes.
</P>
<P>
   Organizations such as Working Today are promoting portable
benefits and group insurance purchase prices for independent
contractors so they have the same safety nets as traditional
employees.
</P>
<P>
   All this talk about the new face of the work force I thought had
hit home the other day when I read a posting on our office bulletin
board. Someone had found a report on the labornet.org Web site
about a May 30 appearance in Ann Arbor, Mich., by the chairman of
our parent company. It concerned a symposium on ``The Information
Revolution in Midstream.''
</P>
<P>
   It turns out the story, originated by an alternative weekly
paper in Detroit, was inaccurate. It wrongly attributed to Tony
Ridder, chairman of Knight Ridder, the comments that ``jobs will be
irrelevant in the future'' and workers of the future will be
independent contractors working on a free-lance basis.
</P>
<P>
   The remarks were made by another panelist, Graham Whitehead, a
British Telecom vice president. Last I checked, British Telecom
doesn't own us.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, such predictions about the future work force are
widespread. It (itals here)could(end itals) have been any CEO. So
watch this space. I'm not exactly sure when the ``future'' is, but
I'm trying to find out whether free-lance columnists charge by the
inch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
