<DOCNO> NYT19980702.0370 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 20:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8678 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAMSTOWN-CASINO-KAN &LR;      07-02 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAMSTOWN-CASINO-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAM'S TOWN PAYMENTS TO LOCAL AGENCIES WON'T STOP WHEN CASINO
CLOSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK ALM  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ As Sam's Town executives announced the
casino's imminent closing Tuesday morning, hundreds of area postal
carriers were delivering the riverboat's latest promotional offer
to players _ a two-for-one buffet dinner deal.
</P>
<P>
   Those bargain coupons were part of a new direct-mail advertising
initiative launched this week by Mark Aiello, marketing manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``Be sure to look out for more discounts and special offers I'll
be sending your way, because this coupon is just the beginning!''
he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, it was the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark Aiello had no idea this was happening until Monday
morning,'' said Rob Stillwell, spokesman for Las Vegas-based Boyd
Gaming Corp.
</P>
<P>
   After nearly three years of red ink, the gaming company said
Tuesday that it was pulling the plug and selling its troubled
Kansas City property to competitor Harrah's Entertainment Inc. The
casino will close within 60 days, costing 646 workers their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   It may jeopardize gambling tax revenue that Kansas City collects
at Sam's Town, although scheduled payments of hundreds of thousands
of dollars to area agencies, including scholarship funds, will
continue for seven years. A loan program for minority- and
women-owned businesses, however, will die with the casino.
</P>
<P>
   With a local gaming industry turnover rate that approaches 50
percent a year, those Sam's Town employees aren't likely to be out
of work for long.
</P>
<P>
   Both Harrah's North Kansas City Casino &AMP; Hotel and Station
Casino Kansas City are the hosts of job fairs this week so Sam's
Town employees can learn about company benefits and submit
applications.
</P>
<P>
   Together, Boyd Gaming and Harrah's operate more than two dozen
casinos in other states, and the companies said they would make
relocation offers to some Sam's Town workers.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Sanfilippo, president of Harrah's riverboat division,
said Wednesday that firm job offers were being made to some Sam's
Town workers on Tuesday within an hour of Boyd's announcement.
</P>
<P>
   By late afternoon Wednesday, Station Casino General Manager John
Finamore said 60 Sam's Town workers were already on Station's
payroll.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have offers out to a number of others and they're still
streaming in,'' he said. ``We're very, very happy with the quality
and quantity of employees we're seeing.''
</P>
<P>
   Finamore said the bulk of those hired were table game dealers,
slot machine attendants, and food and beverage workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a few walk-ins,'' Argosy General Manager Larry
Kinser said Wednesday. ``We're pretty well fully staffed, but we
are looking for a few specific jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Station's job fair, at the casino, continues today and Friday
from 10 a.m. to 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Stillwell said Sam's Town players club members would be allowed
to redeem their earned points for cash and merchandise until the
casino closes _ which is expected to be a matter of weeks as key
employees depart for new jobs.
</P>
<P>
   But the loss of casino jobs and marketing freebies aren't the
only consequences in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Since it opened in September 1995, Sam's Town has paid $41
million in direct gaming taxes to the city and state, plus millions
more in sales and income taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Most if not all of those gaming tax dollars are expected to be
recovered as Sam's players increase their visits to other casinos
in Kansas City, North Kansas City and Riverside.
</P>
<P>
   The question for Kansas City is how much of the estimated $2
million in annual gaming taxes the city budget ultimately will
lose. A spokesman for the mayor's office said Wednesday that the
issue was under intense review.
</P>
<P>
   Most casino revenue is funneled into the city's capital
improvements program for street repair, public parks and the like.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Boyd Gaming will continue _ for seven years _ making
annual payments totaling $350,000 to various public and private
agencies in the area to fund a city scholarship program, riverfront
park development, tourism marketing, and research on the causes and
treatment of compulsive gambling.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told me yesterday, face to face, they are going to honor
those commitments,'' Kansas City Port Authority lawyer Phil
Kuznetsky said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The city's college scholarship program got under way in recent
weeks after nearly three years of planning while the fund has
accumulated.
</P>
<P>
   Boyd and Station each pay $50,000 a year to the Kansas City
Council's Opportunities Scholarship Fund to aid financially needy
students ages 17 to 25.
</P>
<P>
   The Greater Kansas City Community Foundation and Affiliated
Trusts administers the program and will select the first recipients
later this summer, said Earnest Rouse, of the city manager's
office.
</P>
<P>
   Students can renew their annual stipends, which are expected to
average $1,000 a year, as long as they remain in college.
</P>
<P>
   Internally, Boyd also has managed a minority- and women-owned
business loan program and community outreach grant fund that, over
three years, has received $350,000. Those programs will cease with
the casino's closing, Stillwell said.
</P>
<P>
   Harrah's has made no decision yet on what the company will do
with Boyd's 254-foot-long Judy's Prize riverboat and 31-acre tract
that includes a 1,300-car parking garage and an 80,000-square-foot
retail and office structure. Unlike the larger of Harrah's two area
casinos, Judy's Prize is a motorized vessel fully certified to
navigate the river.
</P>
<P>
   The 1,600-passenger riverboat could come in handy later this
year if Missouri voters reject a proposed ``boats in moats'' ballot
measure to retroactively legalize noncruising riverboats moored off
river in man-made ponds and lagoons.
</P>
<P>
   Games of chance at Sam's Town and three of the four other Kansas
City gambling operations are threatened with closing if voters do
not approve the measure. Under a 1997 Missouri Supreme Court
decision, those games, including slot machines, are only legal
aboard vessels moored directly in the river's flow.
</P>
<P>
   Sanfilippo insisted Wednesday that the purchase of Sam's Town
was unrelated to the boats-in-moats issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not looked at it that way at all,'' he said. ``We're
confident that the outcome in November will be positive for us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
