<HEADER>
A8682 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DRUNKEN-BOATERS-2NDTA     07-02 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUNKEN-BOATERS-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE OF THE OZARKS, Mo. _ they usually are.''
</P>
<P>
   Officers must have probable cause, such as no registration decal
or improper lights, to stop a boat. If an officer smells the odor
of intoxicants or notices that the driver is wobbling, has
bloodshot eyes or slurred speech, he will perform a field sobriety
test.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't really do any kind of balance tests out here,''
Pragman said, ``so we do alphabet tests, have them count backward,
that kind of thing.''
</P>
<P>
   In Missouri, where the blood alcohol level limit is .10 _ the
same as with cars _ the first two offenses are misdemeanors. The
third offense is a Class D felony, with a maximum penalty of five
years in jail and/or $5,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   A BWI conviction, however, does not affect licenses, because a
person doesn't need a license to operate a boat.
</P>
<P>
   In Kansas, lakes are patroled by Fish and Game officers. The
legal limit for intoxication is .08, the same as for motorists.
First offenses are misdemeanors, but habitual violators can be
charged with felonies by the courts.
</P>
<P>
   Boaters also are subjected to the elements _ the sun, the wind,
the vibration of the boat and the glare on the water, Richerson
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They actually call it boater's hypnosis,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   Richerson said studies have shown that four hours of exposure to
the ``boater's hypnosis'' elements can have the same effects on
people as intoxication.
</P>
<P>
   Another concern is the changing face of boating.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing both ends of the spectrum,'' Richerson said.
``Some boats are getting bigger and more powerful, but we're also
seeing an increased number of personal water craft, which are
smaller.''
</P>
<P>
   Some boats, he said, can hit speeds up to 100 mph. Even the
small water craft can go up to 60 mph or more.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're also seeing the bigger offshore boats which have a lot
of speed, but less maneuverability, then we're seeing bigger
cruisers and houseboats which have less speed and less
maneuverability,'' Richerson noted. ``And we still have the bass
boats and the runabouts, too. There's just congestion in general.''
</P>
<P>
   However, authorities don't think that a $24 million bridge that
opened in May and connects Lake Ozark to Shawnee Bend will worsen
the congestion.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who have established places on the lake have just been
driving longer to get to them,'' said Water Patrol Sgt. Hans
Huenink. ``It cuts your drive time down from two hours to 30
minutes, so this just makes it more convenient.''
</P>
<P>
   Authorities also said that the infamous ``Party Cove'' _ an area
where boats gather and complaints of noise, public nudity and sex
are common _ does not contribute to the increase in BWIs as much as
its name suggests.
</P>
<P>
   ``They remain stationary in there for the most part,'' Huenink
said, ``so we don't get to them.''
</P>
<P>
   As he cruised the lake earlier this week in his 28-foot
Challenger, Pragman pulled alongside a group of young men on a
craft called the ``Party Barge.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything OK?'' he asked. They assured him that things were
great.
</P>
<P>
   Pragman nodded and headed back across the lake, slowing when the
boat slammed into a wave created by a passing cruiser.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is nothing,'' he said. ``This weekend, there'll be so
many people out here, the waves will be nonstop. And that's when
our work really begins.''
</P>
</TEXT>
