<SLUG> BC-CNN-NERVE-GAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CNN RETRACTS REPORT THAT MILITARY USED LETHAL NERVE GAS IN LAOS IN
1970 
</HEADLINE>
  (ps) 
 By ROBIN POGREBIN AND FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Presented with an independent investigation concluding that it
stretched the available evidence beyond the breaking point, the
Cable News Network on Thursday retracted its report that the U.S.
military had used lethal nerve gas in a secret 1970 mission in Laos
intended to eliminate American defectors.
</P>
<P>
   The broadcast, which was accompanied by the fanfare of advance
publicity common in the growing community of broadcast news
magazines, was shown on June 7 as the feature presentation on the
first broadcast of the news magazine show ``CNN Newstand Time,'' a
joint venture with Time magazine that was being hailed within the
Time-Warner empire as the fruit of productive synergy between the
company's disparate news gathering operations.
</P>
<P>
   The apology amounted to a devastating admission that the report
had falsely cast the United States government, and in particular
its military and intelligence arms, as brazenly using and
concealing the use of sarin nerve gas, one of the most forbidden
weapons in the modern arsenal that is banned by numerous
international treaties.
</P>
<P>
   A day after the piece was broadcast, a slightly modified version
of the account of a mission that was code-named Operation Tailwind
was published in Time. Journalists at Time and CNN said Thursday
that the story was broadcast and published despite memos and
complaints raised by journalists within both organizations who
received a last-minute chance to examine the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Saying that CNN alone was responsible for the erroneous report,
Tom Johnson, chairman of the CNN News Group, issued a statement
Thursday saying, ``We acknowledge serious faults in the use of
sources who provided Newsstand with the original reports and
therefore retract the Tailwind story.
</P>
<P>
   ``We apologize to our viewers and to our colleagues at Time for
this mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Time Magazine's managing editor, Walter Isaacson, also issued a
retraction and an apology for the story, which appeared under the
bylines of a producer, April Oliver, and Peter Arnett, a
Pulitzer-Prize winning journalist whose visibility across a 30-year
career had made him perhaps the network's most prominent
correspondent.
</P>
<P>
   A senior executive with the network confirmed Thursday that
Arnett had been reprimanded for his work on the story. Ms. Oliver
and her colleague Jack Smith, the two producers who had led the
eight-month reporting effort, declined a suggestion that they
resign and were fired. Pamela Hill, the noted documentary producer
who as the executive producer of CNN Newstand Time, made the basic
decision to broadcast the report, also submitted her resignation.
</P>
<P>
   But beyond the firings, resignations and recriminations within
Time-Warner, the report, conducted by Floyd Abrams, the noted
constitutional attorney, offered a microscopic examination of how
the basic fabric of journalism can unravel.
</P>
<P>
   His report showed no venality, willful deception or illegality,
but a more subtle process of distortion that began when conclusions
outstripped the available evidence, continued when sources were
encouraged to believe that unseen evidence proved their own
suspicions to be true and was compounded by interviews laced with
hypothetical questions and ambiguous answers. Ultimately, the
report concluded, the journalists refused to give more than a
glancing nod to a series of denials by witnesses that sarin gas
could have been used.
</P>
<P>
   ``The CNN journalists involved in this project believed in every
word they wrote,'' according to the Abrams report. ``If anything,
the serious flaws in the broadcast that we identify in this report
may stem from the depths of those beliefs and the degree to which
the journalists discounted contrary information they received
precisely because they were so firmly persuaded that what they were
broadcasting was true.''
</P>
<P>
   But even as her work was being repudiated and she was being
fired by her employer, Ms. Oliver, the producer of the piece,
refused to back away from her conclusions. ``I feel that this
report was solid,'' said Ms. Oliver, 36, ``that I made every step
any journalist would take to insure its accuracy and that I had the
full backing of management all the way up to the top.''
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call with reporters, Abrams said he enlisted
former intelligence officers from the investigative firm of Jules
Kroll to try to confirm the account independently through their own
military, intelligence and diplomatic sources.
</P>
<P>
   His report included devastating details of overreaching. For one
thing, the journalists' most-cited source, retired Admiral Thomas
Moorer, who was chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff from mid-1970
to mid-1974, is 87, lives in an assisted-care retirement home in
Maryland, and is no longer relied on by CNN's military
correspondents. And many of the answers he gave were to
hypothetical questions.
</P>
</TEXT>
