<HEADLINE>
USB DEVICES ARE COOL, THAT IS, IF YOU CAN FIND ONE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you bought a personal computer in the past 12-18 months,
chances are that machine has at least one Universal Serial Bus
port, which is a new and, in theory, better way of connecting
devices to the system.
</P>
<P>
   The big question, as is always the case with new technology, is:
``Why should I care?''
</P>
<P>
   Since the dawn of the IBM PC, users have gotten along just fine
with two basic ways of hooking things up _ the serial and parallel
ports. The problem with both of these port standards is that they
are dumb and slow.
</P>
<P>
   The Universal Serial Bus, or USB, is supposed to fix that. It's
very fast, able to transmit data at speeds up to 12 megabits per
second. And it's relatively smart _ you can plug in a USB device
while a computer is on and it will be recognized instantly.
</P>
<P>
   Windows 98, released June 25, has built-in support for USB. And
the OSR2 version of Windows 95 can support USB with a software
add-on that's either on many new PCs or is available as a download
from Microsoft's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   So if USB has been around for almost a year and a half, and
Windows has been able to support it for almost that long, why isn't
the Universal Serial Bus ... well, universal?
</P>
<P>
   There are two issues here.
</P>
<P>
   First, USB support in Windows 95 was a bit rough around the
edges. While it works, it's not as smooth as it should be. Windows
98 fixes that problem, because USB support is not an add-on; it's
built into the operating system.
</P>
<P>
   Second, the companies that make devices that would plug into a
USB port are playing a chicken-or-egg game. They don't want to
start pumping out USB devices until they see more public
acceptance. But public acceptance won't come until consumers see
plenty of USB devices that fill their needs.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Intel Corp. in its early promotion of USB used to
cite Iomega's Zip drive as the perfect device to benefit from the
port's abilities. There's just one problem: Iomega executives say
they have no plans to introduce a USB version of the Zip until
early next year.
</P>
<P>
   I've been playing with some new USB devices on a computer, and I
have to admit that the technology is pretty cool. Yes, you can plug
a USB component into your computer while the machine is running
and, yes, Windows will install the drivers for it automagically.
</P>
<P>
   But there's a catch.
</P>
<P>
   Just because you have the drivers installed for a device doesn't
mean it will work. A driver is a small software program that acts
as go-between for the computer and the device. You usually need a
more sophisticated software package to coax the device into
operation.
</P>
<P>
   Some USB peripherals are simple enough that you can indeed
plug-and-go.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's new Natural Keyboard Elite _ a more compact version
of its popular ergonomic keyboard _ comes with both a PS/2 and USB
plug. When you use the latter, Windows finds the drivers, installs
them and you're ready to type.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft also has a USB version of its Intellimouse, which has
a wheel _ situated between the left and right buttons _ that is
designed for scrolling through documents. Plug it in, and you can
immediately begin mousing. However, the wheel won't work until you
install a control panel that activates it and other additional
features.
</P>
<P>
   USB is being highly touted for use with scanners and digital
cameras. One of the features of Windows 98 is a built-in
image-receiving and -editing program called Imaging for Windows,
which was developed by Kodak.
</P>
<P>
   I tried Storm Technologies' new PageScan USB. Plug it in, and
you can immediately begin using it with the built-in software. But
Imaging for Windows is rudimentary _ if you want to do more, you'll
have to install the suite of software that comes with the Page- &QL; 
Scan.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the USB aspect works fine, but the supporting software
still gives you fits.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Intel's Create &AMP; Share Camera Pack for USB requires
a full suite of software to operate, even though Windows also loads
quite a few drivers when the camera is first plugged in. The camera
uses this software to grab still images and record video with
sound. Without the package, the hardware is useless.
</P>
<P>
   Although I had no problems with the USB aspect, my entire system
froze during the first reboot after installing all that software.
Only after downloading an update to the software did it work
flawlessly. So much for plug-and-play.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Dwight Silverman can receive electronic mail via the Internet.
Address your comments and questions to
dwight.silverman(at)chron.com, or call (713) 220-2000 and enter
access code 1001. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
