u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTER-HELPLINE-HNS     07-02 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-HELPLINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S MORE THAN ONE WAY TO FIX PROBLEM WITH PROCOMM FOR DOS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: You may have missed when you swung at the problem in your
June 26 Help Line answer concerning the user with the Procomm for
DOS problem. Procomm Plus for DOS will not run on a Pentium
200-megahertz or faster machine. Datastorm has a fix for the
problem at support.qdeck.com/files/fd2up0001.exe.html. This takes
you to a description page of the fix and a link to download the fix
itself. The page says to use the fix only for 200-megahertz Pentium
systems, but in its user group Quarterdeck says it works on
anything 200 megahertz and faster. Another fix is a utility called
MoSlo which will slow your computer to under 200 megahertz so
Procomm works without the patch. You can set it so when you run
Procomm, your system slows, then speeds back up when you exit. The
utility can also slow your system for older, speed-dependent games.
You can get a free copy at www.hpaa.com or spend $20 for the deluxe
version.
</P>
<P>
   A: Thanks for the information. However, I'll stick with my
suggestion that he move to a Windows-based version of Procomm. It
has more features, is easier and doesn't require crippling the
processor.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have read and saved your June 5 Help Line regarding the
naming of a Web site. I have created a brochure in Publisher 98 and
am in the process of converting it to HTML.
</P>
<P>
   Now my confusion. The company at which I work has an America
Online address and we have five mail boxes. When we build our Web
site and must give it a name, we had hopes of naming the site with
our company's name _ ourcompany.com. Your column suggests that the
only option open to us, namewise, is members.aol.com/ourcompany.
This name is cumbersome, to say the least, and not easily
remembered. If we use this service, is this the only option open to
us for a naming of the site? That leads to a second question
regarding the name: How do others (companies located worldwide)
access our Web site? In other words, what do they type in to read
about the services we offer? If they were to type in the
``search/find'' area some words, for example, ``technology
licensing chemical engineering,'' would we be one of the
suggestions listed?
</P>
<P>
   A: The America Online feature I described was its free Web
hosting service, available to all subscribers. However, if you are
a business and are willing to pay for more, you can get your own
Internet domain name and have it hosted by AOL. Do a keyword
PRIMEHOST to find out more.
</P>
<P>
   As far as others finding your Web site, you can start the
marketing process by adding it to search engines, such as Yahoo!,
Lycos, AltaVista and Hotbot. Each has a page that lets you enter
information about your site, though when it is posted varies. In
some cases, it may not get posted at all _ for example, Yahoo! can
be very selective about what is included in its indices.
</P>
<P>
   In other cases, the search engines themselves have automated
software robots that scour the Web in search of pages to add to
their databases. Of course, your page must be linked to another
page to be found.
</P>
<P>
   There are several sites on the Web that will take a Web site
listing submission and automate its transmission to multiple search
engines, usually for a fee. You can also download software that
will do it from your computer, such as at www.submissions.com. Some
Web site developers will also do this for you as part of their fee.
</P>
<P>
   You can place certain words on your home page that will cause it
to be pulled in a Web search. If you think potential customers will
use the words ``technology licensing chemical engineering,'' then
add them to the page. You can also add keywords that appear only in
your main page's source code to attract searches.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Got a question about your computer? Dwight Silverman can receive
electronic mail via the Internet. Address your comments and
questions to dwight.silverman(at)chron.com, or call (713) 220-2000
and enter access code 1001. &UR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
