<HEADLINE>
JOBS REPORT FOR JUNE SHOWS GROWTH IS MODERATING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Two graphics are being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(mk) 
 By SYLVIA NASAR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The hot U.S. economy is showing signs of cooling, but by only a
few degrees. In June, the Labor Department reported Thursday,
unemployment edged up to 4.5 percent, and job growth slowed.
</P>
<P>
   There were other signs of moderation. Total hours worked were
virtually flat in June, a clear indication that the nation's output
of goods and services is growing much more slowly than in recent
quarters. And hourly pay rose by a mere penny, suggesting that wage
inflation, while higher than a year ago, was not accelerating.
</P>
<P>
   The slowdown, however, is from an exceptionally torrid pace.
Payrolls grew by 205,000 last month, compared with more than
300,000 in each of the two previous months.
</P>
<P>
   By any historic standard, job creation remains robust and
unemployment is very low indeed. As recently as a year ago,
joblessness stood at 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming after such phenomenal numbers, the June number looks
weaker,'' said Jeffrey Frankel, a member of the Council for
Economic Advisers. ``But on some objective scale, its very
positive.''
</P>
<P>
   The drag on the job market and the economy mostly reflects a
production slowdown in manufacturing as well as a temporary decline
in government jobs. Manufacturing payrolls, which have been flat to
down for months, fell by 29,000 in June, after dropping by 22,000
in May. The culprits: a superabundance of inventories, the initial
effects of the strike against General Motors and other labor
strife, and deepening economic woes in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   But elsewhere hiring was robust. The giant service sector, from
consulting firms and investment banks to hotel chains and shopping
malls, continued to scoop up workers, as did the temporary-help
industry, usually a harbinger of future job creation. Indeed, as
Katherine Abraham, commissioner of the Bureau of Labor Statistics,
noted, hiring by the private sector matched the average pace for
the past 12 months _ an exceptionally good stretch for job growth.
</P>
<P>
   Investors took the report in stride. They nudged bond prices
higher but pushed stock prices down modestly. Investors have been
fretting that continued strength in the labor market would prompt
the Federal Reserve to slow the economy by raising rates. Despite
the slowdown, investors and traders are aware that employers are
still creating jobs at a much faster pace than the Federal Reserve
is comfortable with or that would prevent the unemployment rate
from falling further.
</P>
<P>
   ``Job growth is slowing to a more comfortable pace, but it's
still not within Alan Greenspan's preferred range,'' said M. Carey
Leahey, chief U.S. economist at High Frequency Economics, a
consulting firm. The Fed chairman's comfort zone, as he pointedly
hinted in testimony last October, is closer to 100,000 than
200,000.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Labor Department officials cautioned against reading too
much into the increase in unemployment. June is the month in which
millions of students in search of summer jobs temporarily join the
labor force, an influx that often results in weird gyrations in
employment and unemployment as measured in the department's survey
of households. Last June, for example, the unemployment rate also
ticked up two-tenths of 1 percent, without signaling an upward
trend in joblessness.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   And business executives do not see much slackening in the demand
for workers, young or old. ``I dont see any weakness in the labor
market,'' said Mitchell Fromstein, chief executive of Manpower Inc.
Manpower's survey of employers' hiring plans for July through
September shows further expansion. The National Federation of
Independent Business, meanwhile, reported in its June survey that a
record 31 percent of small companies have job openings that they
are unable to fill.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly a third of June's decline in manufacturing jobs reflected
the initial effects of the General Motors strike, which has now
idled more than 160,000 workers. The jobs report survey was taken
the week of June 12, when 3,000 GM workers were on strike and
another 6,000 others had been furloughed. If the strike lasts
through mid-July, as many expect, the July employment report will
be sharply affected.
</P>
<P>
   The deepening crisis in Asia, which has strengthened the dollar
and battered demand, also hurt factory employment last month in
several industries that sell to Asian customers or compete with
Asian rivals. Payrolls were down by 1,000 in heavy machinery, 6,000
in apparel and 4,000 in electronic components, where there was also
a strike. The weakness could well continue; in a separate report,
the Commerce Department said that factory orders fell a sharp 1.6
percent in May after rising seven-tenths of 1 percent in April.
</P>
<P>
   The decline in government payrolls, especially at the state and
local level, in June was probably temporary. To be sure, the
federal civil service has been shrinking for years and will no
doubt continue. But a transit strike in Philadephia accounted for a
dip in state jobs. And June is the month that hundreds of thousands
of teachers go on summer break; the timing always changes a bit
from year to year, so attempts to make seasonal adjustments in the
data are rarely perfect.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wouldn't want to read too much into that decline,'' said
Tom Nardone, an economist at the Bureau of Labor Statistics.
``Outside of manufacturing and government, things look pretty good.
Things are growing.''
</P>
<P>
   Builders added 20,000 more carpenters, bricklayers and the like;
they likely would have added more if it hadn't been for heavy rains
in the Midwest last month. And the services juggernaut _ data
processing, consulting, engineering, health care, health supply,
temporary help, retail, finance, insurance, real estate, trucking,
wholesale trade, utilities _ added 215,000 net payroll jobs.
</P>
<P>
   How much the economy will slow is a matter of great debate among
forecasters. So far, consumers and businesses are continuing to
spend freely while industry is putting the brakes on production.
The question is whether the production cutbacks will continue long
enough to bring job creation to a crawl and to rein in spending, or
whether spending will stay strong enough to eventually revive
production.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the issue,'' said William Dudley, chief economist at
Goldman Sachs. ``Nobody knows for sure. It depends on how long the
production weakness lasts.'' One damper that seems to be correcting
itself faster than expected is the inventory pile up; Thursday's
Department of Commerce report showed that manufacturers'
inventories hardly grew in May.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
