s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-SMART-CORVETTE-AR     07-02 1096
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-SMART-CORVETTE-ART-$ADV05-725&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORVETTE: NOW THAT'S AMERICAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo will be sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 5)  
 (af)  
 By MICHELLE KREBS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   No modern car on the American road is more red-white-and-blue
blooded than the Chevrolet Corvette.
</P>
<P>
   Introduced as a 1953 model, it was America's first true,
mass-produced sports car. It was America's answer, as well, to the
pint-size roadsters that were being imported from Europe or shipped
home by GIs stationed there after World War II who had discovered
their lithe, open-air charms.
</P>
<P>
   And the Corvette remains the only American sports car to stand
the test of time. A million-plus Corvettes have been built in more
than four decades, more than any other sports car ever.
</P>
<P>
   Redesigned for the 1997 model year, only the fifth major remake
of the car, the Corvette remains an instantly recognizable American
icon worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   The black Corvette convertible, new for 1998, had just landed in
my driveway for a test drive when the school bus arrived. From
inside my house, I could hear the cheers and howls of the
neighborhood boys as they flocked around the car.
</P>
<P>
   No matter that the most recent redesign stole some styling cues
from foreign sports cars, including the much-higher-priced,
Japanese-made Acura NSX. These boys knew this was a Corvette, and
they knew what it stood for.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pop the hood,'' they commanded, and they set to discussing the
Corvette's huge 5.7-liter V8, which delivers 345 horsepower and a
maximum of 350 foot-pounds of torque. ``Take us for a ride,'' they
begged, as they helped me drop the easy-to-operate manual top.
</P>
<P>
   I, too, was anxious for my first drive in the Corvette
convertible. I had already driven the coupe, which has removable
roof panels; it was the first of the new Vettes redesigned for the
1997 model year to reach the market. The convertible followed, and
a hardtop coupe is scheduled to be rolled out in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of my test drive was ideal. Summer had arrived
seemingly overnight. With the sun blazing down on us, I headed east
with a friend across the northern suburbs of Detroit, aiming to
find an open-air restaurant on the St. Clair River for a Friday
night dinner.
</P>
<P>
   My friend was temporarily cured of his notion that Americans are
sensory deprived because they gaze into computer screens all day,
touch mostly plastic and insulate themselves in their cars, homes
and offices.
</P>
<P>
   The Corvette convertible provides enough sensory sensation to
last a long while. Detouring from the rush-hour madness onto a
winding, unpaved road, we inhaled the fragrance of the flowering
plants, felt the rush of the breeze and reveled in the powerful
rumble under the hood.
</P>
<P>
   The Corvette's rigid body structure emitted not a single shake
over the gravel surface, a significant accomplishment for a
convertible, and particularly for a Corvette convertible. Despite
the open top and fiberglass one feels surprisingly safe and snug
inside the Corvette.
</P>
<P>
   The car's sturdy structure also greatly enhances the ride, which
is extraordinarily comfortable for a sports car. We could easily
have gone on for miles after our evening-long drive.
</P>
<P>
   The Corvette behaves like an obedient soldier, hugging corners
and curves without deviation unless commanded to do so and steering
as directed with rifle-sharp precision.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the feeling one gets in some sports cars, one doesn't
feel cramped. In fact, the Corvette's interior space has been
expanded by mounting the transmission _ either the standard
four-speed automatic or the optional six-speed manual _ in the
rear.
</P>
<P>
   Back on a paved surface, we wound out the Corvette's powerful
engine _ somewhat. The only safe place to truly experience the
Corvette's raw power is on a race course or test track, which I had
done earlier. Raw power has long been a hallmark of the Corvette.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the safe and secure feeling is the Corvette's optional
active-handling system, available for the first time on 1998 models
for an extra $500.
</P>
<P>
   The car's stability enhancement system prevents the back end
from fishtailing and spinning the car wildly out of control by
selectively applying individual brakes to set the car back on
course. In contrast to other stability-enhancement systems on
Mercedes-Benz, BMW and Cadillac cars, the Corvette system allows
the driver to turn it on and off.
</P>
<P>
   Such innovation is nothing new for Corvette, which has a
reputation for cutting-edge technology, including the use of
fiberglass and plastic. Many of its ideas have become commonplace
in more mainstream cars.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The newest Corvette also adds another element missing from many
sports cars: practicality. Chevrolet designers and engineers have
eliminated the annoyances that made living day-to-day with the
Corvette difficult. For instance, climbing in and out of the car,
once difficult to do gracefully, is no big deal now.
</P>
<P>
   The roomy trunk, large enough for luggage or a couple of golf
bags, is a significant improvement, too. With traction control and
active handling, the Corvette could easily serve as a year-round,
everyday car instead of a weekend cruiser.
</P>
<P>
   So what is there to complain about? Not much. The back of the
passenger seat rattled a bit, but most sports cars are far from
perfect _ the little flaws add to a car's character. Indeed, sports
cars like the Acura NSX are criticized for being too perfect.
</P>
<P>
   Relatively speaking, the Corvette represents the good old
American tradition of value as well. Base prices start at $38,560
with destination fees; the convertible opens at $44,990, and the
fully loaded, topless test model topped out at just over $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   That's a lot of money but a bargain compared with the price of
the only other true American sports car, the Dodge Viper, which
starts at $65,000 and is far less practical than the Corvette.
</P>
<P>
   Many Americans must agree. Even before the strikes by the United
Automobile Workers began a month ago, the assembly plant in Bowling
Green, Ky., could barely keep up with demand. The plant is now
closed because of the strikes.
</P>
<P>
   The newest Corvette is the best Corvette ever and the best
American sports car on the market. It represents the greatest of
American virtues: power, strength, endurance and value.
</P>
<P>
   And, without a top, it offers the feeling of good, old American
freedom.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
