<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLAGONE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Residents scramble to save belongings amid evacuations
 &HT;    By Mike Williams
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORMOND BEACH, Fla. _ Like happy Florida retirees, Vonnie Brown
Evanoff and her husband, Bob, rode their bicycles to a neighborhood
meeting Wednesday night, hoping to learn what to do if the
wildfires that have plagued their area got too close.
</P>
<P>
   They never made it to the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``People came swarming out of there telling us there was a
mandatory evacuation and we better get out,'' said Mrs. Evanoff, a
longtime Atlanta resident who moved to the upscale Breakaway Trails
subdivision here seven months ago. ``We only had a half hour to
throw some clothes in the car and go.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple joined nearly 30,000 other residents of Flagler,
Volusia and Brevard counties along Florida's Atlantic coast driven
from their homes as brisk west winds fanned the fires late
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The winds continued Thursday, and few residents were allowed
back into their neighborhoods. Many went to stay with family or
friends, checked into local motels or went to shelters opened at
area schools and churches.
</P>
<P>
   The Evanoffs were allowed back into their development to check
on their home Thursday morning, but within minutes were ordered out
again as nearby flames flared anew.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I got out was my mother's cedar chest, my jewelry, some
papers and some of Bob's collector guns,'' she said. ``I had to
have that cedar chest. It has my mother and father's name inscribed
on the inside.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple also gathered a few photographs, but had to leave
many behind, including some of Mrs. Evanoff's first husband, who
died several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   They spent much of Thursday afternoon standing in a church
parking lot a half-mile from the entrance to their neighborhood,
watching as helicopters swooped low over two ponds, filling giant
buckets hanging on slings. The airships then swooped away to the
line of pine trees where dense smoke choked the air, dropping the
water and then heading back to the ponds for more.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really scares you watching that,'' Mrs. Evanoff said. ``But
you don't want to risk your life for anything material. It doesn't
look too good right now. If it jumps that road, we're gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Two miles away, Joseph Ramsey pulled up to a grocery store
parking lot, his Chevy van loaded with clothes and other personal
belongings.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years ago, Ramsey bought a secluded piece of Florida
paradise, purchasing an old wood-frame home in the midst of a
gorgeous stand of water oaks. A posh neighborhood grew up around
him over the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``We almost lost the place in the fires of 1985,'' he said.
``Flames came within a few feet of the house. This time we're
ready.''
</P>
<P>
   He and his wife, Althea, packed their belongings, but waited out
the fires Wednesday night, not wanting to load four dogs_three of
them Great Danes_and six cats and go searching for a shelter or a
motel that would accommodate the animals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put a sprinkler on the roof and stayed up all night,'' he
said. ``Today the fire is still two or three miles from our house,
but the wind is blowing it in our direction. If this wind keeps up,
there's a good chance it could make it to us tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   The Evanoffs spent Wednesday night in a motel, and didn't sleep
much either.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob had the radio things in his ears all night,'' Mrs. Evanoff
said. ``We turned off the TV about 1 a.m., but couldn't really
sleep. It was just fitful sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Evanoff, 51, called her children in Atlanta to tell them
she was OK.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I didn't think to tell them to call my three sisters,''
she said. ``When we got to the house this morning, there was
frantic message from one of my sisters, telling me, 'Call me
immediately when you get this message.'''
</P>
<P>
   The couple weren't sure how long they would have to stay out of
their home, but with fires burning on both the north and south
sides of their development, it could be days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now I just wish I was in Atlanta,'' Mrs. Evanoff said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
