<HEADER>
A8697 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLANOTES-COX     07-02 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLANOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tourist spots feel the heat
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARASOTA
</P>
<P>
   Wanted: some fire over here: While fires ravage much of the
state, burning homes and closing highways, officials at Myakka
River State Park in Sarasota can only sigh wistfully and wish they
had a little of that.
</P>
<P>
   Park officials are working to restore some habitats _ dry
prairies and pine flatwoods _ that existed before human
intervention. When those habitats are restored, park officials hope
to attract native species such as the crested caracara, the
burrowing owl and the gopher tortoise.
</P>
<P>
   But those habitats depend for their health and stability on
regular fires, park biologist Belinda Perry said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fire in Florida comes naturally during the lightning season,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Without it, grasslands turn to woods, different species take up
residence, and the natural ecosystem is altered, she said.
</P>
<P>
   But because of the statewide ban on burning, park officials have
not been allowed to set the fires they normally would have set. And
when nature has cooperated and lightning has ignited fires in the
park, officials, contrary to their desires, have had to put them
out.
</P>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL
</P>
<P>
   Space station threatened: NASA engineers grew increasingly
concerned Thursday about the effects of wildfires on the ``clean
rooms'' where modules of the new international space station are
waiting to be launched into orbit.
</P>
<P>
   Wildfires raged about 10 miles away from the Kennedy Space
Center, where visibility was reduced to 1 1/2 miles because of the
thick smoke and falling ash, said Bruce Buckingham, NASA spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   So far, filters and air handlers protecting the clean rooms have
managed to cope with the airborne debris, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing is burning on the base yet, but there is concern
because we have 100,000 acres here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The space center is part of a national wildlife refuge full of
pine forests, scrub bushes and marshland and hundreds of species of
wildlife. But most of the base is separated from the mainland fires
by the Indian River.
</P>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH
</P>
<P>
   Go away sunshine: Tourism officials in Daytona Beach usually
pray for cloudless, sunny days around the time of the NASCAR race.
But not this year.
</P>
<P>
   And the one year they don't want sunshine, guess what they're
getting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had three bright, beautiful days and there's no rain
predicted until Monday, which normally would be ideal for us _ but
not with this fire,'' said Blaine Lansberry, marketing vice
president for Oceans 11 Resorts, which operates five hotels in
Daytona.
</P>
<P>
   Lansberry advised tourists to postpone their visits to the
Daytona area until next week.
</P>
<P>
   She said the Oceans 11 hotels _ the Bahama House, Acapulco Inn,
Trans Island Inn, Beachcomer Inn and, in Ormond Beach, Casa del Mar
_ were booked solid this weekend, 90 percent with racing fans. Even
though the race has been canceled, many still are occupying their
rooms, since I-95, the main route out of Daytona, has been
closedbecause of the fires.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Lansberry said, ``This is a huge disappointment.''
</P>
<P>
   ORMAND BEACH
</P>
<P>
   Smoke on the water: The specter of wildfires was no reason for
some tourists to cancel vacations.
</P>
<P>
   While flames drove residents from their homes not far away,
beachgoers ignored smoky, sunless skies and ashes that washed up on
shore to play in the sand or look for seashells.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to overlook it, otherwise you would have to pack and
go home,'' said Victor Adkison of Tyler, Texas, who built a sand
castle with his 9-year-old son on Ormond Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still down here,'' Adkison said. ``It can't always be
perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   MIMS
</P>
<P>
   Lawn ornaments threatened: Real pets take precedence over fake
ones sometimes, even when the fake ones took years to make.
</P>
<P>
   At Whirligig World near Mims, a place that sells colorful lawn
ornaments, Norman Carter gazed forlornly at his wooden turtles,
raccoons and Mickey Mouses. Their legs and arms whirled comically
in the breeze as though the creatures wanted to flee the fires en
masse.
</P>
<P>
   Carter spent years making these things. Now they seem doomed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've packed as many as we can, but we don't have room for all
of them,'' he said. ``We packed important things like our pets,
important papers and money. We're just keeping our eyes open and
hoping it doesn't get any closer.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
