<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FREEMAN-TRIAL-730&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JURY REACHES MIXED VERDICT ON FRAUD TRIAL OF FREEMEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BILLINGS, Mont. _ A federal jury on Thursday convicted the
leadership of the anti-government Freemen movement of a series of
charges, largely financial fraud, but was unable to reach verdicts
on several other counts including the conspiracy charge that is at
the core of the case.
</P>
<P>
   Judge John Coughenour of U.S. District Court here refused to
declare a mistrial on the 11 deadlocked counts of the 41-count
indictment and ordered the jury to return to the courthouse on
Tuesday to resume deliberation of the undecided counts. The jury
also found three of the defendants not guilty on two charges each.
</P>
<P>
   Capping four days of deliberations, the jury also convicted
LeRoy Schweitzer, portrayed by prosecutors as the mastermind of the
group, Daniel Peterson, the group's treasurer, and Richard Clark of
two counts of threatening to kill Montana's chief federal judge,
Jack Shanstrom.
</P>
<P>
   Schweitzer was convicted on 21 counts involving phony financial
instruments. The jury found Peterson guilty on four fraud-related
counts, Russell Landers on three, Dale Jacobi and Rodney Skurdal on
two each, and Clark on one.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors charge that the Freemen wrote 3,432 ``checks,'' with
a total face value of $15.5 billion, using the number of a Norwest
Bank account that never contained more than $116.
</P>
<P>
   With 92 witnesses and five weeks of testimony, the trial offered
glimpses into the Freemen's secretive world of financial fraud and
violence. A radical anti-government group with racist elements, the
Freemen caught the nation's attention in the spring of 1996 during
an 81-day FBI siege of their ranch compound in Jordan, Mont.
</P>
<P>
   Unbowed after two years in jail, nine of the defendants
boycotted the trial, refusing even to talk to their lawyers, and
seven of them have spent the last two weeks in a prison hospital in
Springfield, Mo., following two hunger strikes.
</P>
<P>
   John McGuire, the only defendant to testify at the trial, argued
that the federal court had no jurisdiction over him and that he had
not committed any crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for other defendants argued that their clients sincerely
believed that the phony checks printed by Freemen on home computers
were genuine. They charged that the FBI falsely encouraged the
Freemen when an undercover agent told them he cashed their checks
and used the money to buy a copier, computer and radio system for
the compound.
</P>
<P>
   The two women defendants, Agnes Stanton and Cherlyn Petersen,
attended the trial. Their lawyers used what one lawyer called the
``gofer defense,'' alleging that they were merely following their
husbands' instructions.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the prosecution testimony tried to prove that the
Freemen's central activity in Jordan was to try to pass bogus
financial instruments as real.
</P>
<P>
   Printed from a home computer, these ``checks'' carried
impressive sounding names: ``documentary draft,'' ``lien draft,''
``comptroller warrant, ``certified money order,'' and ``certified
banker's check.''
</P>
<P>
   These ``checks'' went out to 1,004 recipients in about half the
states of the nation, investigators said. The problem was so severe
that the U.S. Comptroller of the Currency issued four worldwide
alerts to the financial community from October 1994 until the FBI
placed the Freemen compound under siege in March 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``Worthless junk'' was how Judge Coughenour described the
checks. He warned defense lawyers not to portray the checks as
genuine, adding they could say only that the defendants believed
them to be genuine.
</P>
<P>
   Even though less than 1 percent of their checks were honored,
the Freemen managed to accumulate a small fortune; $144,000 in
cash, plus a small hoard of money orders and gold and silver coins.
</P>
<P>
   Stored in a small wooden box, the cash and coins were smuggled
out of the compound in the early days of the siege, testified Ebert
Stanton, a former Freeman, whose parents, Agnes and William, were
on trial here.
</P>
<P>
   Despite fears that the trial would draw crowds of right-wingers,
fewer than a dozen supporters appeared here during the trial. In
late May, several men came here from the Pacific Northwest in
response to an Internet appeal for militia members to ``intercede''
in the trial.
</P>
<P>
   One Freeman supporter, Jacob Miller of Florida, was expelled
from the courtroom for studying the jury with binoculars, and one
death threat against the judge was reported.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   An FBI firearms examiner testified that the Freemen's arsenal in
Jordan held 23 handguns, 67 rifles, 10 shotguns and more than
40,000 rounds of ammunition, including 182 rounds of armor-piercing
bullets.
</P>
<P>
   A series of witnesses testified that they threatened to kidnap,
put on trial and execute a host of local officials. Witnesses said
the Freemen also offered $1 million bounties for the capture or
death of the lead FBI investigator and a federal judge who had
issued a foreclosure order against a farm owned by two of the
defendants.
</P>
<P>
   Tommie Canady, the lead FBI agent in the case, testified that
fear of provoking bloodshed prevented the bureau from arresting the
Freemen when they shifted operations from Roundup, Mont., to Jordan
in September 1995. In addition, the FBI seems to have used the
Freemen as bait to amass intelligence information on the militia
movement during a yearlong surveillance.
</P>
<P>
   The delay not only caused hundreds of thousands of dollars in
fraud losses to businesses victimized by Freemen checks but also
caused deep resentment among the Freemen's rural neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   In the June 2 Republican primaries, voters in Garfield and
Musselshell Counties rejected their sheriffs, men who had become
associated with the go-slow policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our hands were tied to working with the FBI,'' said Charles
Phipps, the Garfield County sheriff who plans to run as a write-in
candidate in November. ``We could have gone out, got in a gun
fight, shot somebody, then be in lawsuits for the rest of our
lives. People didn't understand that.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
