<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-HERSHISER-SIDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VERBAL ABUSE IN '93 CLASH NOT FROM OREL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Sidebar to Hershiser story) 
By ERIC NOLAND  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In one of the many ironic twists of Dodgers-Giants
lore, Orel Hershiser emerged as the No. 1 villain in the Bay Area
at a time when he was trying to quell a blaze of emotions.
</P>
<P>
   A simple case of mistaken identity.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the 1993 season, San Francisco and the Atlanta
Braves were deadlocked in a fight for the NL West title, but the
also-ran Dodgers, in their season finale, routed the Giants 12-1 at
Dodger Stadium to knock them out of the race.
</P>
<P>
   Later, San Francisco third baseman Matt Williams singled out
Hershiser as a player who had been taunting the Giants unmercifully
from the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   But Hershiser says he had climbed to the top step of the dugout
precisely to silence the magpies on his team. The Giants saw him,
heard the voice of Dodgers rookie Jerry Brooks behind him, and
fused the two.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fred (Claire) and Tommy (Lasorda) gave a huge pep talk before
the game about how many times the Giants knocked the Dodgers out of
the playoff race, and how this series has always been huge. But
you've got the 40-man roster up, not just the regular 25 guys, so
all of these kids are just on fire,'' Hershiser said this week.
``They're ragging (verbally abusing the Giants).
</P>
<P>
   ``You had to let it go a little bit because Tommy inspired it
all. ... But during a (Giants) pitching change, guys started
yelling from the field to our dugout, from our dugout to the field.
And I just stood up on the top step in front of our guys, as if to
say, `I don't want anymore.' I looked over my shoulder and gave our
guys dirty glares. And Matt and Robby T. (Thompson) and a bunch of
the guys on the infield thought I was the one doing the yelling.''
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser later called Williams to sort out the entire affair.
The two later were locker mates in Cleveland and laugh over the
story today.
</P>
<P>
   But passions aren't always cooled as readily among Giants
faithful.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, said Hershiser, ``all of a sudden I'm the worst
person ever to wear a Dodger uniform. The fans remember it. There
are fans out there who will go to their grave thinking I was the
jerk.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-98 2114EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980702.0386 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8712 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEN-MEDIA-COLUMN-LADN     07-02 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-MEDIA-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIKE-ROSCOPIC MEDDLER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Man, how wise can it be to put a mike in the hands of a Mike
Weisman?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Joe Torre doesn't agree, but the folks in charge of Fox
baseball aren't about to cut the juice.
</P>
<P>
   This season, it's been the modus operandi of producer Weisman to
find another nontraditional way to tweak the Fox Saturday
game-of-the-week telecast with wireless microphones and/or
hand-held cameras.
</P>
<P>
   For example, for Saturday's Dodgers-Giants broadcast from 3Com
Park, Weisman sought and received permission from Orel Hershiser to
put a mike on the pitcher in the San Francisco dugout and get his
commentary (to be taped and used judiciously). That would have been
another Weisman broadcast first _ no one outside of a manager or
coach has ever worn audio equipment during a real game. But
Thursday afternoon, before leaving for the Bay Area from his home
in Brentwood, Weisman was informed he couldn't do it because it
needed approval from the MLBPA.
</P>
<P>
   ``So we'll do it another time,'' said Weisman, who wants to hook
Tom Lasorda up with a mike in the stands for some live, impromptu
fillibustering.
</P>
<P>
   For Weisman, a nonoral Orel is a small bump in the road.
</P>
<P>
   Assigned by Fox baseball coordinating producer John Filipelli to
oversee one of the four regional Saturday telecasts with the Thom
Brenneman-Bob Brenly broadcast team and director Jim Lynch, Weisman
has turned these World Series hors d'oeuvres into midseason treats.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the Good Lord wanted to create a baseball producer, he
started with Michael Weisman,'' said Filipelli, who Weisman hired
as the lead baseball producer at NBC some 15 years ago and has
returned the favor.
</P>
<P>
   Back as a hands-on producer, Weisman's baseball broadcasts are
part ``Late Night with David Letterman,'' part ``Pop-up Video.''
Yet they're 100 percent Weisman, who once had the media-created
nickname ``Mad Mike'' when he did particularly innovative things
for NBC Sports as its boy-wonder executive producer during the
1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always loved the way Letterman broke down the wall
between the TV camera and the audience,'' said Weisman. ``Doing
games for Fox, I've been able to live out some sports TV
fantasies.''
</P>
<P>
   Such as:
</P>
<P>
   _During a Chicago Cubs-Atlanta Braves game, Weisman sent
cameraman David Benzer from his normal dugout spot in the fourth
inning and had him go onto Weyland Avenue, beyond the left-field
wall.
</P>
<P>
   Weisman's thinking: We've seen all kinds of TV pictures of a
ball hit out of the park and onto that street. Why not have a live
camera capture the flight of the ball as it comes right into the TV
viewers' laps?
</P>
<P>
   With a glove on his left hand, the camera on his right shoulder
and a wireless mike so he could talk on the air to Brenneman and
Brenly, the burly Benzer went out there and waited.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't get a chance to catch a ball with his glove (or lens),
but Benzer ended up talking to a father and son who were playing
stickball against the outside of the Wrigley Field wall.
</P>
<P>
   _During a recent Dodgers-Rockies game at Dodger Stadium, Weisman
put a mike on Roger Owens, the famed peanut vendor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no interest in mikeing (then manager) Bill Russell,''
said Weisman, ``frankly because baseball is slow enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Without telling Owens when he'd be on camera, Weisman used him
as an escape hatch for some levity during an otherwise one-sided
game. Weisman's reward was some priceless live footage of Owens
bantering with the customers (even though much didn't make it on
the air).
</P>
<P>
   _During a Rangers-Giants telecast last week, Weisman put a
microphone on one of the 3Com Park ``ball dudes,'' the 70-something
gentlemen who sit in uniform down the left- and right-field lines
to retrieve foul balls. The result was something like Letterman
doing a live remote with Larry ``Bud'' Mellman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is some of this stuff sophomoric? Yes,'' said Weisman. ``Are
we doing it to amuse ourselves in the truck? Yes. Do the people at
home enjoy it? I'm not sure, but my rationale has always been to at
least try, make it fresh. With this crew (Breneman and Brenly), we
can do almost anything we want.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not as if Weisman doesn't know when to shut up. The irony
is that the guy who won 15 Emmy Awards in 11 years from '78 to '89
with NBC as either producer or executive producer on the '88 Summer
Olympics, eight World Series, seven Super Bowls and numerous
Wimbledon and French Open tennis tournaments was also the one who
came up with the ``silent minute'' during the pregame show of Super
Bowl XX.
</P>
<P>
   And it's not as if Fox doesn't keep an eye on him, either. It
was the Yankees-Red Sox game last year that Weisman was producing
when miked manager Torre's expletive was inexplicably aired after a
key Paul O'Neill home run. Although the blunder occurred because
the audio man rewound the tape about three seconds too far, Weisman
took full responsibility. He issued an apology on air, then
personally apologized to the irate Torre, who had to be persuaded
by Weisman to wear the mike in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   The New York media actually backed Weisman for the mistake since
he apologized to Torre (who wouldn't accept it) and for Fox's
attempt at add a little life to some otherwise stagnant midseason
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``More times than not, I think that no one blames you as long as
you're trying,'' said Weisman. ``I'm glad more producers haven't
caught on to that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sports TV can be such a copycat business. The material is
often the same, but it's in how you present it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-98 2115EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980702.0387 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 21:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8713 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOREIGN100-AZR &LR;      07-02 1320
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN100-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOP 100 FILMS: FOREIGN FLAVOR TASTES BEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD NILSEN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: UPDATED VERSION OF FOREIGN. with LIST100) I used to
tell people my top-10 list had 40 movies on it. It's a common
problem. We all like to make lists, but there's never enough room.
</P>
<P>
   So when the American Film Institute recently decided to list the
hundred greatest films, they restricted it to American films _ or
at least they say they did. Somehow, a few English films made the
list. But no foreign language films did.
</P>
<P>
   And that leaves us a whole universe of movies not eligible,
including some of the best ever made.
</P>
<P>
   So, this week, in response, we are providing the list of 100
best foreign films.
</P>
<P>
   Most of these films are established classics, and if you worry
that the list has too many of the ``usual suspects,'' I hope I have
included enough eccentric personal choices to give everyone
something to talk about. That, after all, is the purpose of such a
list.
</P>
<P>
   The movies on this list were chosen for several reasons. Some
are among the greatest artistic creations of our civilization.
Others are on the list because of their enormous influence on other
filmmakers. Still others are just such fun to watch.
</P>
<P>
   Which reminds me, if you think all foreign films are dreary and
boring, you haven't been watching the right ones. Admittedly,
French or German films are more likely to investigate the outer
reaches of alienation and philosophy than Hollywood films, but you
will never find better battle scenes than in Akira Kurosawa's
``Ran.'' You will be hard pressed to find more suspense than in the
last half-hour of Georges-Henri Clouzot's ``Diabolique.'' And if
it's blowing things up you are after, check out Clouzot's ``Wages
of Fear,'' in which Yves Montand and a bunch of toughs drive a
truck full of nitroglycerine 300 miles over unpaved South American
roads.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, I don't want to gloss over the difference between American
and foreign films.
</P>
<P>
   I have always made the distinction between what I call
``Hollywood films'' and ``real movies.''
</P>
<P>
   The real movie is about being human, about relationships,
character, moral issues, and historical and philosophical meaning.
Hollywood movies are about blowing things up.
</P>
<P>
   Now, there are foreign-made Hollywood movies by my definition,
and Hollywood-made real movies: One thinks of spaghetti Westerns on
one hand, and of Francis Ford Coppola's ``The Conversation'' or
John Ford's ``The Searchers'' on the other.
</P>
<P>
   At least one film manages to play both sides of the field: AFI's
No. 1 film, ``Citizen Kane'' manages like nothing else I know, to
join seamlessly the slick Hollywood side with the depth and
character development of a ``real movie.''
</P>
<P>
   As critic Pauline Kael has said, it is one of the few great
movies that is also great fun.
</P>
<P>
   But by and large, foreign filmmakers play out their creativity
in a larger world, with more possibilities and fewer hidebound
conventions.
</P>
<P>
   After all, Hollywood ``earned'' its reputation as the
manufacturer of the shallow happy ending.
</P>
<P>
   My list of the 100-best foreign films is a very personal list,
drawn from a lifetime of watching movies. I expect you have your
own films to nominate. But these are the ones I came up with.
</P>
<P>
   First on my list is ``Children of Paradise,'' which is more like
a full-length novel than any other film I know. It has a rich cast
of characters and follows them over many years. And as in
``Brothers Karamazov,'' each character also embodies a different
philosophy. It is a very full movie.
</P>
<P>
   Set in the Paris of the 1840s, it tells the tale of Baptiste
Debureau and the theatrical world in which he lived. It is also
about love, art and social class.
</P>
<P>
   If ``Kane'' manages to mix high and low successfully, so does
``Children of'' ``Paradise,'' in its own way. It has something of
the sweep of ``Gone With the Wind,'' the passion of ``From Here to
Eternity'' and the wit of ``Ninotchka''.
</P>
<P>
   And it is a film you can grow with rather than out of. When I
was fresh out of college, I identified with the idealistic
Baptiste; after a few marriages, I took the practical Frederick
Lemaitre's attitude toward relationships; nowadays, I uncomfortably
find myself more in the cynical Pierre-Francois Lacenaire.
</P>
<P>
   Jean Renoir's ``Rules of the Game'' might just as well claim the
top spot. No other film is as deft at showing the disjunction
between what our impulses are and what society demands of us.
</P>
<P>
   Cocteau's ``Orphee'' is also a great deal of fun, playing with
all the tricks of cinema to create visual magic. What you see is
likely to remain in your memory forever.
</P>
<P>
   Fellini's ``8{'' begins with the same kind of magic, a dream
sequence that you can't get out of your mind, but it continues on
to be about a film director that doesn't know what to do next.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seven Samurai'' is a pure action film, the model for the
Western, ``The'' ``Magnificent Seven,'' but much, much better. You
actually care about these characters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Potemkin'' is one of those seminal films that invent the
language of cinema. What is all the more astonishing is that this
Soviet propaganda film actually plays down the more sensational
aspects of the affair. If it had been truer to history, it would
have felt more simply propagandistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Passion of Joan of Arc'' is not the most consistently good
film. It has stretches of languors, but when the camera is on the
face of Maria Falconetti, in the only film she ever made, the
intensity is literally unbearable. It is the face of human
suffering.
</P>
<P>
   Kurosawa's ``Ran'' is a Japanese retelling of Shakespeare's
``King Lear,'' and shows the director at the absolute peak of his
powers, with the best battle sequences ever filmed.
</P>
<P>
   Marlene Dietrich sings ``Falling in Love Again'' in ``The Blue
Angel,'' which makes ``Cabaret'' look like ``Gidget Goes to the
Weimar Republic.'' Steamy, smoky, atmospheric, its director, Josef
von Sternberg _ an American _ never did anything so good again.
</P>
<P>
   It takes a serious commitment of time and attention to sit
through Andre Tarkovsky's ``Andrei Rublev,'' but you will know you
have experienced something worth your effort, as the director takes
us through a brutal vision of life and the place in it for both art
and faith.
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, almost any of the next 25 or 30 could legitimately
make it to the top 10, but I'll stand with the ones I have chosen.
</P>
<P>
   Some, like ``Jules and Jim'' or ``Amarcord'' are pure pleasure
to watch. Others, such as ``Rashomon'' or ``Wild Strawberries''
have at their core a moral vision. And still others, such as ``The
Cabinet of Dr. Caligari'' and ``Metropolis'' are simply visionary.
</P>
<P>
   You will find intensity, passion, intellect, visuals, acting and
directing the equal or better of anything from Hollywood. What you
will not find are giant lizards and serial car wrecks.
</P>
<P>
   A few, such as ``Henry V'' and ``The Mahabharata'' are
unabashedly theatrical, using their staginess as a style.
</P>
<P>
   There are few British films on my list: AFI threw me a curve and
included several on its list. So, ``Third Man, Dr. Strangelove''
and ``Lawrence of Arabia'' are not here, although they would have
been.
</P>
<P>
   You will discover that a handful of directors made the majority
of these films. I cannot apologize for that. I made the list
without considering authorship. As it turns out, Ingmar Bergman
shows up a dozen times; Kurosawa, 10. Francois Truffaut and
Federico Fellini follow up with seven and five films.
</P>
<P>
   Does this mean Bergman is the greatest director? No. He has made
many great films, but he is more prone to self-parody than any
other important director and when he is bad _ as in the miserable
Elliot Gould film, ``The Touch,'' he comes close to rivaling Ed
Wood.
</P>
<P>
   In art, there is no best. There is only overwhelming. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
