<SLUG> BC-FREEMEN-TRIAL-730&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JURY REACHES MIXED VERDICT ON FRAUD TRIAL OF FREEMEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BILLINGS, Mont. _ A federal jury on Thursday convicted the
leadership of the anti-government Freemen movement of a series of
charges, largely financial fraud, but was unable to reach verdicts
on several other counts including the conspiracy charge that is at
the core of the case.
</P>
<P>
   Judge John Coughenour of U.S. District Court here refused to
declare a mistrial on the 11 deadlocked counts of the 41-count
indictment and ordered the jury to return to the courthouse on
Tuesday to resume deliberation of the undecided counts. The jury
also found three of the defendants not guilty on two charges each.
</P>
<P>
   Capping four days of deliberations, the jury also convicted
LeRoy Schweitzer, portrayed by prosecutors as the mastermind of the
group, Daniel Peterson, the group's treasurer, and Richard Clark of
two counts of threatening to kill Montana's chief federal judge,
Jack Shanstrom.
</P>
<P>
   Schweitzer was convicted on 21 counts involving phony financial
instruments. The jury found Peterson guilty on four fraud-related
counts, Russell Landers on three, Dale Jacobi and Rodney Skurdal on
two each, and Clark on one.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors charge that the Freemen wrote 3,432 ``checks,'' with
a total face value of $15.5 billion, using the number of a Norwest
Bank account that never contained more than $116.
</P>
<P>
   With 92 witnesses and five weeks of testimony, the trial offered
glimpses into the Freemen's secretive world of financial fraud and
violence. A radical anti-government group with racist elements, the
Freemen caught the nation's attention in the spring of 1996 during
an 81-day FBI siege of their ranch compound in Jordan, Mont.
</P>
<P>
   Unbowed after two years in jail, nine of the defendants
boycotted the trial, refusing even to talk to their lawyers, and
seven of them have spent the last two weeks in a prison hospital in
Springfield, Mo., following two hunger strikes.
</P>
<P>
   John McGuire, the only defendant to testify at the trial, argued
that the federal court had no jurisdiction over him and that he had
not committed any crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for other defendants argued that their clients sincerely
believed that the phony checks printed by Freemen on home computers
were genuine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
