<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-NOTEBOOK03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chipper literally blasts out of slump
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG _ While Andres Galarraga nurses his bruised left
wrist, his bruised left tricep and his bruised back courtesy of
Tampa Bay's pitching staff, the Braves' clean-up hitter may be
pleased to know that someone has returned to hit in the No. 3 slot
ahead of his.
</P>
<P>
   After a two-week slump, Chipper Jones has come around this week.
Staggered by a 5-for-41 slide dating back to June 17th, Jones hit
just .122 over an 11-game period and saw his season average dip to
a year-low .300.
</P>
<P>
   But recovered fully now from the flu, Jones may have turned a
corner against Tampa Bay. Surely, it's an expansion pitching staff
but Roberto Hernandez and Rolando Arrojo are not expansion fodder
and he homered off both of them. He finished the series at 6-for-14
with six RBI, three homers and a triple.
</P>
<P>
   Before the series, Jones had gone nine games without an
extra-base hit. Wednesday night with his parents and extended
family members in the crowd, he beat the Devil Rays with a
ninth-innning two-run homer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed to come in here and win three games,'' he said.
``After we struggled in the last few weeks, we've had some injuries
and haven't been able to keep everybody in the lineup at the same
time. This is a big deal for me but I'll take the three wins ahead
of my breaking out of a slump any day.''
</P>
<P>
   Finishing
</P>
<P>
   Greg Maddux being Greg Maddux, there was not much
self-appreciation in the fact that he threw a complete game for the
fifth time in seven starts. Just like there was not much
significance attatched to his 16th straight road victory. Or his
major-league leading ERA dropping further to 1.54. But with six
complete games already, Maddux has a clear shot at his career-best
(10 in both 1994 and 1995). And given that just one in 16 NL starts
results in a complete game this season, the achievement is
noteworthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``That says I got to the ninth inning with a low pitch count,''
said Maddux. ``And that's all it says.''
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz home early
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday starter John Smoltz returned home ahead of the team
Thursday to seek treatment for an aching back that has flared up in
the past few days. Though Smoltz has been prone to back pain in the
past, the right-hander may this time receive a cortisone injection,
now that he has at least a week and probably more before his next
start. Smoltz said the back pain was a response to
over-compensation for his right elbow.
</P>
<P>
   Survey says . . .
</P>
<P>
   For those scoring at home, Tampa Bay's first baseman was
3-for-12 this series with a double and no RBIs. The Braves first
baseman was 3-for-10 with two home runs and three RBIs, which sums
up the first head-to-head meeting between Fred McGriff and Andres
Galarraga. Devil Rays followers are waiting for McGriff to
reappear. After a sensational April (.349 with six homers and 23
RBI), McGriff homered twice in the past two months with just 18
RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
