<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    On Deck: New York Mets
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When: Today at 7:40 p.m., Saturday at 7:10 p.m., Sunday at 1:10
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Where: Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   TV/radio: TBS and 750-AM will broadcast all three games.
</P>
<P>
   Probable starting pitchers: Tonight, LHP Tom Glavine (11-3,
2.71; 9-4, 3.41 lifetime vs. Mets) vs.
</P>
<P>
   Series history: This is the first meeting between the two clubs
this season. The Mets lead the all-time series 201-194.
</P>
<P>
   Past Meetings: New York has won two of the last three season
series and went 7-5 against the Braves last year, splitting six
games at Turner Stadium in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Quickly: Now 85 games into the season, the Braves finally face
the Mets for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   On the DL: 1B Matt Franco (fractured toe), C Todd Hundley (right
elbow surgery), P Jason Isringhausen (right elbow surgery), P Al
Leiter (torn left knee tendon), P Hector Mercado (left elbow
surgery), 3B Craig Paquette (sprained left ankle), P Armando
Reynoso (sprained right elbow), C Tim Spehr (broken left wrist) and
P Paul Wilson (right shoulder strain).
</P>
<P>
   Who's hot: CF Brian McRae has hit four home runs in nine games
and has reached base 16 times in his last 29 plate appearances
(.551). 2B Carlos Baerga is hitting .324 in his last 35 games with
four homers, eight doubles and 19 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   Who's not: Since joining the Mets on May 22, C Mike Piazza is
hitting .192 (5-for-26) with runners in scoring position. The
left-handed Bohanon has been harder on righties (.198) than lefties
(.265).
</P>
