</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-SIDEBAR03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Galarraga as a target has Braves concerned
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG _ Andres Galarraga was a little better prepared
this time, outfitted with a new re-enforced guard for his left
elbow to go with the heavily padded glove on his left hand.
</P>
<P>
   Didn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   The Tampa Bay Devil Rays hit him anyway. For the third time in
three games _ for the third time in nine plate appearances _
Galarraga was hit by a pitch. Thursday, Rolando Arrojo plunked him
in the back in the sixth inning with a man on base.
</P>
<P>
   The incident did not lead to trouble, but it suggested it. By
the time Greg Maddux drilled the Devil Rays' Rich Butler in the
beltline in the seventh, the mood shifted. And when Tampa Bay
reliever Scott Eldred threw a change-up behind Eddie Perez's back,
this one was one more buzz-ball away from a confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know they want to throw in on me, but I don't know,''
Galarraga said. ``Sometimes I don't know if it's on purpose or
not.''
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay's Larry Rothschild said he thought that Maddux threw
at Butler purposefully, a curious sentiment from a manager whose
team leads the majors in hit batsmen (50). Maddux, by comparison,
has hit 12 batters in his last 670 innings, just two this season.
And while Butler would not debate Maddux's intent, he was grateful
for his pin-point control.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it was intentional, thank God he didn't throw at my head,''
Butler said, ``because he would have hit me right in the eyeball.''
</P>
<P>
   ``(Maddux) hit him on purpose,'' said Rothschild, who left the
dugout to debate the point with plate umpire John Shulock. ``And if
he did, he should have been thrown out of the game. My feeling was,
he was hit on purpose. They'll never say it; he'll never say it.
(But) it happens in baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Braves afterward were seething, although not for the
record. But the punishment Galaraga has absorbed _ not only here
but in 12 plunkings this year _ has the club disturbed.
</P>
<P>
   Galarraga is the majors' active career leader, hit 124 times. He
has broken his left wrist, as well as fingers and bones in both
hands, as a result. He freely admits that some of it results
because he leans into the strike zone. But opposing pitchers
apparently are willing to go far beyond the inside corner. A free
trot to first, after all, is better than a home run.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it happens is when we hit a home run,'' said Galarraga,
who opened this series with a two-homer game Tuesday. ``It never
happens when I strike out two or three times.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It scares me,'' manager Bobby Cox said. ``We got to get him
some more protection on his hands and arms. You lose him, you're in
deep trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   The Perez pitch was debatable; Aldred sent a change-up past
Perez's backside to the backstop. But there was little doubt that
Maddux was addressing the abuse the Braves feel that Galarraga
withstood these three games, even if the pitch to Butler slipped.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I hung on to it too long,'' Maddux said. ``If it slips,
you miss the other way. I wanted to bury it in, and a little too
far in.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
