<HEADER>
A8722 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAVES03-MAIN-COX     07-02 0457
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAVES03-MAIN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Maddux 'awesome' in 6-0 win
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG _ To face Greg Maddux during this extraordinary
stretch of his career is like visiting an anesthetist. Two and a
half hours later, you come to, knowing something happened but
you're not exactly sure what.
</P>
<P>
   Case in point: the Tampa Bay Devil Rays, who for five innings
Thursday afternoon were in twin headlocks with Maddux. Then so
quickly, it was 6-0, it was over and Maddux had not only his major
league-high fourth shutout (his third in six starts) and his sixth
complete game. He became the game's first 12-game winner at 12-2,
took his 10th straight decision and made a lie of the fact that for
much of the afternoon, he and Tampa Bay's Rolando Arrojo were
dueling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stopped being surprised three years ago,'' said Braves
manager Bobby Cox. ``He's just awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   The afternoon had its tartness, after Arrojo hit Andres
Galarraga with a pitch in the sixth (the third straight game the
D-Rays plunked the Big Cat). Maddux waited an inning before
drilling Tampa Bay outfielder Rich Butler and Eddie Perez was later
made to dance around Scott Aldred's change-up that flew behind his
back.
</P>
<P>
   But by then, the Braves had begun to hit home runs regularly _
Keith Lockhart with a solo shot in the sixth, Chipper Jones with a
solo shot in the eighth and then Lockhart again with two on in the
ninth.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves won their fifth straight, tying their second-longest
streak of the season. The club returned home to open a weekend
series with the Mets, which concludes the first half of the
schedule, finally getting a glimpse of the team that has tailed
them in the NL East.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly feel a little bit better about ourselves now,''
said Jones, recalling five deflating losses to Boston and the New
York Yankees last month. ``We've strung a few wins together, we're
swinging the bats pretty well every night with a different guy
coming up with some big hits and some big home runs.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart became the third Brave in three games (with Galarraga
and Jones) to produce a two-homer game, thought the last one, off
Jim Mecir, was a surprise. Particularly after Mecir jumped out to a
0-2 count.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just trying to hit a sacrifice fly,'' said Lockhart, who
had one previous two-HR game in his career. ``And then I'm 0-2 and
I'm just trying to make contact.''
</P>
<P>
   Just like Maddux was just trying to make pitches. He allowed
just five hits and struck out eight, all on the same day he was
named the NL pitcher of the month.
</P>
<P>
   Said Cox, ``I betcha he's going to be named something else
too.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
