<SLUG> BC-NIRELAND-BLAIR-1STLD-425&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAIR DENOUNCES ARSONIST ATTACKS ON 10 CATHOLIC CHURCHES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDS: Subs to add sentence in 2nd graf about three churches being
destroyed. No pickup.)  (th) 
 By JAMES F. CLARITY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland _ Arsonists believed to be members of
a dissident Protestant group set fire to 10 Roman Catholic churches
in Northern Ireland late Wednesday and early Thursday, causing
fears that wider sectarian violence could return to the British
province.
</P>
<P>
   Police said the fires were probably the work of the Loyalist
Volunteer Force, a Protestant group opposed to the peace effort,
which has produced cooperation between Protestants and Catholics in
a new provincial assembly. Three churches were destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   In a highly unusual move for a British prime minister, Tony
Blair flew here Thursday to try to dispel rising tension in the
mostly Protestant province. Prime ministers normally avoid the
province at such times, leaving the problems to government
officials and the 30,000-member security force.
</P>
<P>
   Blair, standing Thursday in front of a charred and gutted church
north of Belfast, said, ``I think the act of destruction that we
see behind me here _ that is the past of Northern Ireland, and we
are trying to give people a future that leaves acts of barbarism
behind us.''
</P>
<P>
   After consoling parishioners of the church, St. James, in the
hamlet of Aldergrove, Blair spent the day with Protestant and
Catholic leaders of the Northern Ireland Assembly to work out a
compromise in a dispute that seemed to provoke the burnings.
</P>
<P>
   The arsonists were apparently retaliating against Catholics for
a British government decision on Monday forbidding Protestant
marchers next Sunday to pass through a Catholic area. The dispute
threatens more violence, possibly retaliation by Catholics against
Protestant churches and against meeting halls of the Orange Order,
which runs some 3,000 parades in the province.
</P>
<P>
   Officials, both Catholic and Protestnt, fear that Sunday's
parade in the Drumcree area of Portadown, west of Belfast, could
cause violence across the province, as it has for the last three
years.
</P>
<P>
   The officials are trying to arrange a compromise that would
provide for a quiet, token march by the Orangemen through the
Catholic enclave, without the traditional martial airs, loud drums,
bugles and fifes. That way, the government ban could be rescinded
and both Orange and Catholic militants could save face.
</P>
<P>
   If the Protestant marchers insist on sticking to their
traditional route, they risk clashes with police and with angry
Catholics. The Protestants say their marches are a matter of
freedom of assembly, a basic democratic right. Many Catholics
resent the marches: they celebrate the decisive victory of William
of Orange over his father-in-law, King James II, in 1690.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Sinn Fein, the political wing of the Irish Republican Army,
tells people that the Orange marches through Catholic sections are
equivalent to permitting the Ku Klux Klan to march through Harlem.
The leader of the Catholic protest in Portadown, Brendan McKenna,
is a former IRA operative who served time in a British prison for
terrorist offenses involving explosives.
</P>
<P>
   Blair met at Castle Buildings in the Stormont area of Belfast
with David Trimble, the Protestant leader and first minister of the
new assembly, and his deputy, Seamus Mallon, a Catholic leader of
the Social Democratic Labor Party.
</P>
<P>
   Blair congratulated them on the start of the new assembly, which
held its first session on Wednesday. He campaigned for the assembly
in May before the referendum that approved the peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The arson was widely and vehemently denounced by political and
church leaders, Catholic and Protestant. The Rev. Ian Paisley, the
hard-line leader known for his open anti-Catholicism, denounced the
attacks. Trimble performed his first official task Thursday
morning, visiting St. James, where he said the arson was ``an
appalling, dastardly attack,'' adding, ``Only a handful of people
can take any pleasure in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Senior Protestant clerics, from the Presbyterian Church and the
Church of Ireland, arrived at the church to offer their
condemnation and condolences to the pastor, the Rev. John
O'Sullivan, a soft-spoken man who said, ``It is hard to understand
how this is serving any useful purpose to God or to politics''
</P>
<P>
   Monica Kelly, who runs a pub across the road from the church,
said of the vandals, ``I think they think if there were no
Catholics, there would be no problems.''
</P>
<P>
   A very old, feeble man, perhaps in his 80s, dressed in a black
suit and tie, shuffled into the pub for a cup of tea. He grasped a
visitor's arm and whispered: ``Bad show, bad show. We used to have
respect for each other's place of worship.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
