<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIFORNIA-FORECLOSE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORECLOSURE ACTIVITY ON DOWNTURN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Surging home sales plus rising prices equals a
continuing drop in foreclosures.
</P>
<P>
   That equation pushed foreclosure activity, in decline for about
the past 18 months, down 19.5 percent in May from the year-ago
level and 20 percent from April, Acxiom Corp.'s DataQuick Products
Division said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   During May, lenders issued default notices, the first step in
the foreclosure process, on 9,177 residential properties statewide,
DataQuick said. That compares with 11,321 in May 1997 and 11,410 in
April.
</P>
<P>
   May's activity fell below the 10,000 level for the second time
in three years.
</P>
<P>
   The peak activity occurred in March 1996 when 15,475 homes went
into foreclosure.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing like an improving real estate market to head
off those foreclosures. Values are going up and sales are
booming,'' said Ted Gibson, chief economist for the California
Department of Finance. ``It must be an awful lot easier to avoid
foreclosure today than a year ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Foreclosure activity is easing the most in the Bay Area, but
Southern California is also benefiting from the improving real
estate market that has brought a recent upsurge in prices.
</P>
<P>
   During May, lenders issued 2,979 default notices in Los Angeles
County, down 9.4 percent from the year-ago level and 18 percent
from April.
</P>
<P>
   There were 168 notices issued in Ventura County, up 6 percent
from May 1997 and down 4 percent from April.
</P>
<P>
   Lenders on Orange County properties issued 517 default notices
in May, a drop of 33.5 percent on the year and 18 percent from
April.
</P>
<P>
   John Karevoll, a DataQuick analyst, said the current number is
about half way to what would be a normal level. That point should
be reached late this year or early next year, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as prices are going up the trend will continue and
probably get stronger,'' Karevoll said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
