u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-FIRES-ART-790&AMP;ADD     07-02 1102
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-FIRES-ART-790&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
10,000 MORE FLORIDIANS FLEE SPREADING FIRES 
</HEADLINE>
  (With sidebar, FLA-FIRES-GRIDLOCK) 
(Eds.: See SPOT-BJT-FLORIDAFIRES-COX for list of spot Florida fires
stories from Cox News Service; for information, call 404-526-5456.)
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic map is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(ps) 
 By MIREYA NAVARRO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TITUSVILLE, Fla. _ Northeast Florida felt like a war zone
Thursday as wildfires consumed brush and buildings with no
hindrance from nature and thousands of residents emptied towns
threatened by the onrushing flames.
</P>
<P>
   About 10,000 residents Thursday joined the more than 30,000
residents of Volusia and Brevard counties forced out of their homes
Wednesday night after wind-swept embers spread fires that had been
consuming rural areas, state emergency management officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of businesses and homes were destroyed or damaged and the
fires kept a 140-mile stretch of Interstate 95 closed from this
city in Brevard County to Jacksonville near the Georgia border.
</P>
<P>
   The Pepsi 400 stock car race at the Daytona International
Speedway, scheduled for Saturday, was postponed. An estimated
200,000 spectators were expected to attend the race.
</P>
<P>
   Volusia and Brevard counties were experiencing the worst of
about 1,600 fires of varying sizes and degrees of containment that
raged around the state. With neither rain nor lower temperatures in
sight, state officials said the situation may worsen before it gets
better.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is war,'' said Bob Blay, director of emergency management
services for Brevard County, where one fire had burned 30,000 acres
and five smaller ones kept firefighters busy. ``We've got fronts on
the north and the south.''
</P>
<P>
   Scarce rain and record high temperatures this year have caused
the worst drought in 50 years, making Florida vulnerable to fires
started by lightning strikes or arson. On average, such wildfires
burn about 100,000 acres of Florida each year, state officials say.
But since June 1, fires have burned more than 280,000 acres, mostly
in the northern and northeastern areas, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Statewide, an estimated total of at least 86 homes and 54 other
structures have been damaged or destroyed since May, although state
officials continue revising the figure upward. The fires have also
destroyed more than $190 million of commercial timber, Florida
Department of Agriculture officials said, and drought conditions
have caused more than $135 million in damage to crops like corn,
cotton and peanuts.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the danger, no deaths and only about 50 injuries have
been reported. But after burning mostly brush, forest and
commercial timber tracts since Memorial Day, this week the fires
have spread to people's doorsteps, causing the largest evacuations
so far and tremendous dislocation for both residents and tourists
before the Fourth of July holiday.
</P>
<P>
   Haze and stench from smoke chokes areas miles from the fires.
Dozens of city and state roads have been closed, but even on some
passable highways motorists drove with headlights on through thick
smoke.
</P>
<P>
   In Ormond Beach, where officials ordered the mandatory
evacuation of half the city's 35,000 residents and closed access
roads Wednesday night, the fires ate through power lines and left
more than 1,000 people without electricity. Many residents reported
their wells had gone dry or were barely pumping after soaking their
houses for the past two weeks with sprinklers, and firemen pleaded
with them to conserve water to increase the pressure in lines.
</P>
<P>
   Among those evacuated in Ormond Beach was Tracy Marmol, 24, an
exhausted housewife and mother of two children who said she was
going on two hours of sleep. Evacuated residents filled hotels or
stayed with friends or at Red Cross shelters in local schools.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of firefighters were also being pushed to the limit.
`` I haven't been home in two days,'' said Lt. John Pars of the
Ormond Beach Fire Department.
</P>
<P>
   Across the burning areas, dozens of helicopters buzzed carrying
large buckets of water through the sky. Smoke and ash were heavy in
Daytona Beach in Volusia County, where the fires cast a smelly pall
over the few beachgoers.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at attractions like the Kennedy Space Center, which
sits in Brevard County and had a fire in nearby acreage on their
property June 21, say they have experienced a drop in summer
visitors but no evacuations or major air quality problems. The
state's major tourist complex, Walt Disney World in Orlando,
reported no impact from the fires raging some 50 miles away and
said attendance remains strong.
</P>
<P>
   After touring some of the affected areas, Governor Lawton Chiles
told Floridians in a televised message this afternoon that ``we're
experiencing fires like Florida has never seen before.'' He praised
``the spirit'' of the firefighters battling the flames and urged
residents to be ready to quickly evacuate of necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to thank each of you for your prayers as we ask the
Lord to send us some rain,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A few miles south of Daytona Beach, in Brevard County, the first
sign of trouble came Sunday when one rural acre erupted in flames
after a lightning strike, said Assistant Fire Chief Jeffrey Money
of Brevard County, who briefed Chiles on Thursday at a fire command
post south of here. Because of the dryness of the undergrowth that
fuel the blazes, that fire grew first to 800 acres, then 1,800 and
finally 30,000 in four days.
</P>
<P>
   Money said more helicopters, water trucks and other resources
would have made a difference, but he said much state equipment was
deployed in neighboring Volusia county because of the threat to
homes.
</P>
<P>
   The toll to Brevard County so far has been 30,000 acres burned,
more than 6,000 residents evacuated and at least 17 buildings
destroyed or severely damaged, including a gas station and a fast
food restaurant. In addition, seven firefighters have been injured,
three for second-degree burns and the others for dehydration or
smoke inhalation.
</P>
<P>
   As about 500 firefighters worked on the fires in the county,
officials expected winds of 10 to 15 mph to keep moving the flames
east toward residential areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still very, very dangerous,'' Money said. ``This will
probably continue to exist until we get 10 days of rain or a
tropical storm.''
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday, meteorologists predicted neither.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
