<SLUG> BC-GLF-LPGA-OPEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVIES, WILLIAMS SHARE FIRST ROUND LEAD AT U.S. OPEN  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFTON BROWN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KOHLER, Wis. _ Laura Davies is much better at golf than she is
at making predictions.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Davies was asked about her chances at this
week's U.S. Women's Open. She did not sound optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way the year has gone, I'm expecting two rounds and to be
on my way back to London by Saturday morning,'' Davies said. ``I
have got no expectations whatsoever.''
</P>
<P>
   Imagine that. So imagine her delight after Thursday's opening
round of the Open, when Davies shot a three-under-par 68 to share
the lead with Kim Williams. Pat Hurst, Se Ri Pak and Leslie
Spalding were tied for third place at 69. A record Thursday crowd
for the Women's Open, estimated at more than 21,000 by the United
States Golf Association, caused lengthy early-morning traffic
delays on the roads leading to Blackwolf Run Golf Course, this
year's picturesque and challenging site. And the fans were left
with plenty to talk about, including:
</P>
<P>
   _Nancy Lopez, a sentimental favorite trying to win her first
Open, struggled to a disappointing 77. ``I'm disappointed, but I'm
not discouraged,'' Lopez said. ``I figured out a few things and
tomorrow is going to be a better day.''
</P>
<P>
   _Williams, a 35-year-old tour veteran, was a surprising
co-leader. Williams has never won an LPGA event, and her best
finish this year is a tie for 31st.
</P>
<P>
   _Pak, a 20-year-old rookie from South Korea, showed she is a
threat to win her second consecutive major, after winning the LPGA
McDonald's Championship in May.
</P>
<P>
   _Helen Alfredsson had the shot of the day, a hole-in-one on the
14th hole, using an 8-iron from 152 yards.
</P>
<P>
   _Alison Nicholos, the defending champion, is in danger of
missing the cut after Thursday's 78.
</P>
<P>
   Davies was rock solid in a round that included four birdies and
one bogey, using her power off the tee to avoid some of the danger
that found others. A three-time major winner, including the 1987
U.S. Open, Davies is the longest hitter in women's golf, yet on
shorter courses, her advantage is somewhat negated. However, Davies
was in her comfort zone Thursday at the spacious Blackwolf Run
layout, featuring wide fairways and long par-4 holes that allowed
Davies to swing freely. A 3-iron was Davies' primary weapon of
choice off the tee, and she only used her driver on two holes _ No.
2 and No. 7. When you can hit your 3-iron 260 yards like Davies
can, you do not need a driver that often. And she had no sympathy
for her shorter-hitting competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is nice where you hear the girls struggling, whining
about hitting woods,'' said Davies, a native of England. ``I am
enjoying some of the top players having to hit some decent long
irons.''
</P>
<P>
   Power is never a problem for Davies, but putting has been,
particularly this year. Davies has won at least once every year on
the LPGA tour since 1993, and she has 35 international victories.
However, her last LPGA victory was in March 1997, and she has
missed the cut in four of her last five starts.
</P>
<P>
   But Davies has changed her putting approach, relying on instinct
and feel, rather than worrying so much about technique. That
approach worked Thursday, as Davies made an 8-footer for birdie on
No. 5, a 10-footer for birdie at No. 6 and a 20-footer for birdie
at No. 10.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
