<HEADLINE>
MORGAN AHEAD BY ONE IN GHO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CROMWELL, Conn. _ Pete Morgan lived out the first chapter of his
improbable dream Thursday in the first round of the Greater
Hartford Open, rolling in a 15-foot birdie putt on his final hole
to finish off a 6-under par 64 and seize a one-shot lead.
</P>
<P>
   He was a qualifier on Monday, and had he not made it, he'd be
some 50 miles to the southeast of the TPC at River Highlands
Course, playing in a North Atlantic Tour event at Norwich GC.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan, a 35-year-old Harwich, Mass., native, is a former
Massachusetts Open winner, and he spends his winter playing on the
mini-tours in Central Florida. This is the fourth time Morgan has
qualified for a PGA Tour event, but he has yet to make a cut.
</P>
<P>
   When Morgan, who started on the back nine, made his final putt
from 15 feet on the ninth green, it gave him a one-shot lead on
Kenny Perry (34-31_65) and Scott Hoch (30-35_65). The group at 66
on a calm, sunny day when 57 players broke par-70 included Kevin
Sutherland, Brad Fabel, Spike McRoy, Harrison Frazar, and former
champion Paul Azinger. The Rhode Island pairing of Brad Faxon and
Billy Andrade was in a large group at 68 that included PGA Tour
money leader David Duval.
</P>
<P>
   Casey Martin, who made his PGA Tour debut after finishing joint
23d in the US Open at The Olympic Club, shot a 71 and may need to
better that to make the cut. He accepted his first sponsor's
exemption to play the GHO, rode in a cart, and has accepted a
second exemption to play Quad Cities next week. Should he make two
sizeable paychecks, he might be on his way to staying on the Tour
and playing Pleasant Valley in two weeks. He's got work to do here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was OK,'' said Martin. ``I scrambled all day, but it was
the same way at the US Open. I didn't hit it like I know I'm
capable of hitting it. I know I'm capable of playing better. I just
hope it shows up tomorrow. Fortunately I made a lot of big putts
today. It's a tough course. You have to hit it better to have some
birdie chances. The fans were wonderful, but if I'm going to make
it out here, I've got to elevate my game.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin would be exempt on the PGA Tour for the rest of the year
if he earned the amount Connecticut native Brian Claar earned last
year, when he finished 150th on the PGA Tour list ($121,273). ``I'd
have to do really well,'' said Martin. ``In my mind, I'm just going
to play these two.''
</P>
<P>
   For Morgan, who lives in the Tampa suburb of Valirico, Fla., and
attended Jacksonville University after Harwich High School, the joy
ride began when he hit a 3-iron to inside 2 feet on his first hole
to set up the first of three straight birdies. He chipped in on his
second hole from 30 feet and rolled in a 12-foot putt on his third.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually the rest of the front nine was a struggle just to
make pars,'' said Morgan. ``I started the same way on the back
nine.'' Then he birdied his 13th (2 iron, 6 feet), 15th (sand
wedge, 8 feet), and the final hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm getting more comfortable in the bigger events,''
said Morgan. ``I haven't played a lot of Tour events, and I think
my concentration is just getting better on the golf course, and I
block out things. I used to notice everything that was happening
around me. Now I just try and concentrate on the golf course. I've
done the PGA Tour School eight straight years. I've made it through
the first stage every year. I've only made it through the second
stage once. My wife (Karen) is a big inspiration to me. She keeps
me going. She keeps telling me it's going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoch had two bogeys out of the soft sand. ``The course is in
excellent shape,'' he said. ``I think the only part that's iffy
right now are the bunkers. It's not anybody's fault. You can't do
anything about all the rain. The rain collects in the bunkers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
