<HEADLINE>
RED SOX PLUS 17 AT MIDWAY POINT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Halfway home.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday it was 81 down and 81 to go, and anyone who says he
or she foresaw the Red Sox finishing the first half at plus 17
might be worth following around at a Las Vegas sports book or two.
</P>
<P>
   I certainly didn't see it coming.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't see Bret Saberhagen winning 10 by the All-Star break. I
didn't see Mike Benjamin making like a latter-day Gil McDougald. I
didn't see Tom Gordon as Mr. Automatic in the ninth inning. I
didn't see a lot of things, including something I should have seen.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, indeed, it is time for an apology. The following is
directed at the Red Sox outfield: I'm sorry. I was wrong. What a
stupid I was.
</P>
<P>
   Coming out of spring training, I was all hung up on power. I was
thinking like, well, someone who is in his fourth decade of
watching Red Sox baseball. I've been conditioned to think that it
doesn't matter all that much what an outfielder does as long as he
hits 25 home runs and drives in at least 90. I had accustomed
myself to shoddy outfield play to the point where I no longer had
any defensive standards.
</P>
<P>
   I took a look at the outfield quintet of Troy O'Leary, Darren
Lewis, Darren Bragg, Damon Buford and Midre Cummings and I foresaw
disaster. I decided that they'd be lucky to hit a collective 30
home runs and I thought that would be translated into losses. I
didn't see how it would be possible to win without more oomph in
the outfield.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how. You catch the damn ball; that's how.
</P>
<P>
   Buford and Lewis are tremendous fielders. Bragg's not bad,
either. They catch everything they should, and a lot they
shouldn't. They keep singles singles and doubles doubles, and it
didn't used to be that way around here. They make pitchers
comfortable. More than that, they make pitchers better.
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, but they've hit 28 home runs already. Sure, half
of them are off the bat of O'Leary, but that was always going to be
the case. O'Leary might hit 30 all by himself.
</P>
<P>
   These guys have been a delight to watch. We know all the things
they aren't, or, at least, all the things they aren't supposed to
be. But they keep playing sound, smart, intelligent, hustling
baseball, and maybe it's time some of the fans and assorted critics
acknowledge that the manager they love to use as a punching bag
because he isn't exactly the second coming of Winston Churchill
when he opens his mouth might be a pretty savvy baseball guy. Joe
Castiglione says that Jim Leyland told him that the biggest
difference in the Braves last year was the absence of Jimy
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Now that this bunch has gotten themselves into a post-season
thought process, is there help on the way? They still could use at
least one starting pitcher, and the much-discussed right handed bat
likewise remains on the wish list. Perhaps it's time to ask the
general manager about his priorities. Is he thinking pitching or
hitting?
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see who's on the market,'' says Dan Duquette.
</P>
<P>
   It has become a given in baseball that teams who have fallen out
of contention seek to peddle high salary players to teams looking
for that little something extra, and Duquette appears to think that
some interesting names will be popping up before too long.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a Mike Piazza is traded in mid-season,'' Duquette says, ``I
don't think you can be surprised at anybody who's on the market.''
</P>
<P>
   One position that has been a continuing positive is second base.
When Jeff Frye was lost for the season in a spring training
base-running drill, thyere was nothing but doom and gloom. Then
came Mark Lemke, but just when he was starting to hit a little he
sustained that freak concussion when Chad Kreuter ran over him on
the baseline. But no one has really noticed his absence because
Benjamin and Lou Merloni have done the job so well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those guys have done a nice job,'' maintains The Duke.
``Benjamin has done a great job and Merloni is one of our best
clutch hitters.''
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to be told that the Big Three of Pedro Martinez,
Tim Wakefield and Bret Saberhagen ended the first half at 29-10, or
that Mo Vaughn will knock in at least 100 runs or that Nomar
Garciaparra is already the best all-around shortstop the Red Sox
have had since Joe Cronin was young and frisky. You don't have to
be told that Reggie Jefferson is just a born .300 hitter. You don't
have to be told that it stands to reason that John Valentin will
have a better second half than first (and he did have 24 doubles in
his otherwise disappointing first half).
</P>
<P>
   But it doesn't hurt pointing these things out. This, after all,
is Boston, where negativity rules.
</P>
<P>
   They're playing for the wild card, of course, but that doesn't
concern Mr. Duquette, who says he isn't remotely interested in what
the Yankees are doing. ``I don't even think about the Yankees,'' he
insists. ``I don't think about them at all, because the wild card
is going to come from the East.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a wild card world now. The idea is to get into the
post-season, and take your chances. It worked for the Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do believe we can compete with the Yankees in a short
series,'' says Dan Duquette.
</P>
<P>
   He said it. I didn't.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
