<SLUG> BC-VIAGRA-MEDICAID-1STLD-WRITETHRU-850&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDICAID PROGRAMS MUST PAY FOR VIAGRA USE, ADMINISTRATION SAYS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs 1st and 2nd grafs to recast lead; subs 7th graf for
rewriting) 
 (ATTN: N.Y., Wis, Mich, Utah)  (sw) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two states, New York and Wisconsin, said on
Thursday that they would defy a new federal policy that requires
state Medicaid programs to pay for medically approved uses of
Viagra, the popular but expensive new impotence pill.
</P>
<P>
   The directive from the Clinton administration prompted an outcry
from governors, who said they had not been consulted even though
states pay more than 40 percent of Medicaid costs. The National
Governors' Association said that Medicaid coverage of Viagra should
be a state option, not a federal mandate.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to governors on Thursday, Nancy-Ann Min DeParle,
administrator of the Federal Health Care Financing Administration,
said state Medicaid programs must cover Viagra when it is medically
necessary for treatment of male impotence.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Hinckley, a spokesman for the New York State Health
Department, said: ``We disagree with what the federal government is
saying. We have a responsibility to protect the health of Medicaid
recipients. The federal government needs to get a better handle on
potential complications that can arise from use of Viagra before it
requires state Medicaid programs to cover it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hinckley said New York officials were concerned about Viagra's
interactions with other drugs and its effects on people with
chronic conditions including heart disease. The label for Viagra
says it should not be used by people taking organic nitrates like
nitroglycerin, which is often used to treat angina, or chest pain,
caused by clogged arteries.
</P>
<P>
   Zenia Mucha, a spokeswoman for Gov. George Pataki of New York
said on Thursday night, ``The federal government should not be
requiring New York or any other state to pay for Viagra until there
is a better understanding of the impact this drug has on
patients.''
</P>
<P>
   In Wisconsin, James Malone, a spokesman for the state's
Department of Health and Family Services, said: ``We are not
covering Viagra right now, and we don't intend to. We will resist
being forced to cover it. We don't believe that Viagra is medically
necessary. This federal directive is ill advised and ill
considered.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear how the disagreements will be resolved. They
could end up in court if poor people press claims for the drug.
Alternatively, the Clinton administration could try to withhold
Medicaid money from states that refuse to comply with the federal
policy.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said last month that they would
probably require coverage of Viagra. On Thursday they issued a
formal directive requiring such coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. DeParle said states could ``prevent abuse and misuse of
Viagra'' by requiring prior approval for prescriptions or by
limiting the number of refills or the number of pills in a
prescription.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials said they would monitor use of Viagra and
could halt coverage of the drug if evidence showed that it was
being misused or abused. Donna Shalala, the secretary of health and
human services, ``is greatly concerned about the potential for
clinical or financial abuse of Viagra,'' Ms. DeParle said.
</P>
<P>
   The National Governors' Association estimated that Thursday's
directive would cost federal and state agencies more than $100
million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Baxendell, a health policy analyst at the association,
said there had been ``virtually no consultation with states'' to
assess the costs or implications of a nationwide mandate for
Medicaid coverage of Viagra. States pay 43 percent of Medicaid
costs, or roughly $73 billion of $170 billion last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coverage of Viagra should be a state option, not a mandate,''
the governors' association said.
</P>
<P>
   Pfizer Inc., the maker of Viagra, says more than two million men
have taken the pill since it was approved by the Food and Drug
Administration on March 27. It is one of the most popular new
prescription products in history.
</P>
<P>
   Mariann Caprino, a spokeswoman for Pfizer, said the company had
requested Medicaid coverage in all states. As of early June, she
said, 26 states covered Viagra, often with some restrictions. The
other states did not cover it or were considering whether to do so,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   The wholesale price of Viagra is $7 a pill, Ms. Caprino said,
while the retail price at pharmacies ranges from $8 to $10 a pill.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Caprino praised the Clinton administration's decision. Male
impotence ``is a bona fide medical condition that has a tremendous
impact on patients and their partners,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But disability rights advocates expressed outrage that the
government was requiring coverage of Viagra while allowing states
to deny or cut back coverage of medical equipment needed by people
with severe disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Sheldon Toubman, a lawyer at the New Haven Legal Assistance
Association, in New Haven, Conn., said, ``It's very disturbing that
the White House would instruct states that they must cover this sex
pill while allowing states to ration care for quadriplegics and
people with cerebral palsy or Lou Gehrig's disease who need special
medical equipment to keep them alive and to stay out of nursing
homes.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. DeParle predicted that a relatively small number of Medicaid
recipients would qualify for Viagra. Women and children account for
90 percent of the 40 million Medicaid beneficiaries.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For years, the federal government has required states to cover
``family-planning services and supplies,'' widely understood to
include birth control pills and other contraceptives.
</P>
<P>
   Geralyn Lasher, a spokeswoman for the Michigan Department of
Community Health, said: ``We are very disappointed with today's
announcement from Washington. We are still looking at our options,
to see if we have to cover Viagra. We estimate that it would cost
us $14 million a year _ $14 million that we could spend on maternal
and infant services or people with HIV.''
</P>
<P>
   In Utah, Michael Deily, the state Medicaid director, said
Thursday's announcement was ``not a surprise but certainly a
disappointment.'' He said that Utah initially allowed 10 Viagra
pills a month for Medicaid recipients, then reduced the allowance
to five pills and was now considering ``more stringent criteria''
for evaluating a patient's medical need for the drug.
</P>
<P>
   Technically, states do not have to cover prescription drugs
under Medicaid, but all states do so. Federal officials said that
if a state included prescription drugs in its Medicaid program,
then it must cover all medically accepted uses of FDA-approved
drugs manufactured by companies that agree to give discounts, or
rebates, to the government.
</P>
<P>
   The federal Medicaid law says states may deny payment for a few
drugs, including those used for cosmetic purposes and those used to
promote fertility, to treat anorexia or to achieve weight loss.
But, Ms. DeParle said, Viagra does not meet the criteria for any of
these exceptions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
