<SLUG> BC-GART-SPORTS-AUTHORITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GART BIDS $445 MILLION FOR KEY STAKE IN SPORTS AUTHORITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JENNIFER STEINHAUER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Intensifying the battle to consolidate the troubled sporting
goods industry, Gart Sports Co. has offered $20 a share, or a total
of $445.2 million, in cash for 70 percent of Sports Authority Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal by the scrappy but growing company controlled by
the investor Leonard Green comes several weeks after Venator Group
Inc., formerly the Woolworth Corporation, offered a stock swap
worth about $513.6 million based on Thursday's stock price.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think the synergies here are great,'' said John Douglas
Morton, the chief executive of Gart. ``These are two companies with
consistent formats. The are both full-line sporting goods stores,''
he said, as opposed to Venator, which also runs several specialty
stores. ``There would be significant advertising savings,'' Morton
added. ``Sports Authority has very little product overlap with Foot
Locker. But our vendor structure is almost identical. There would
be real big wins in this transaction.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposal, which was made in a letter to Sports Authority
chairman and chief executive Jack Smith by the management of Gart
called for the remaining 30 percent of Sports Authority's
outstanding shares to be publicly traded. These shares would
represent 51 percent ownership interest in the common stock of the
combined companies.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Venator's stock swap offer values the deal at about
$16.15 a share. Venator operates Foot Locker, Lady Foot Locker,
Kids Footlocker and Champs athletic stores.
</P>
<P>
   Sports Authority, with annual revenue of about $1.47 billion,
has 205 superstores. Gart had sales of $700 million last year from
its 122 stores, which are based primarily in the West. Gart
recently purchased Sportmart Inc., another competitor with 59
stores. Under the proposed merger, Gart stores could assume the
Sports Authority name.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman from Venator declined to comment Thursday, saying
that the company's lawyers and investment bankers were consulting
on their next move.
</P>
<P>
   The company was attracted to Sports Authority's larger stores
outside of the malls, where most Foot Locker stores are situated,
as well as access to new suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   Smith of Sports Authority said in a telephone interview that he
was surprised and a bit flummoxed over the Gart overture. ``I am in
a state of amazement,'' Smith said. ``I found out about it 8:30
this morning. Well, OK, 11:30 last night. We were gearing ourselves
toward Venator, and this is a little disruptive.'' When asked if it
was fun to be the center of a potential bidding war, he said:
``It's not that fun. I mean, it's not like they're offering $50 a
share.''
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street's opinion was loud and clear. Shares of Gart rose
$2.75, to $14.75, and shares of Sports Authority jumped $1.375, to
$16.50. At the same time, Venator shares also increased, closing at
$20.875, up 68.75 cents, a sign that investors, who sent Venator
stock down 12 percent after it announced its potential deal with
Sports Authority in May, were glad to hear of its possible demise.
</P>
<P>
   The sporting goods industry is ripe for consolidation. The
segment, which is spread out among many small regional players and
a few big national chains, had grown quickly in recent years,
making it difficult for any single retailer to reap high profit
margins. Many of the companies are run by ex-coaches or athletes
whose product knowledge is not matched with business acumen.
</P>
<P>
   What is more, companies like Nike have found shoppers' interest
waning recently, causing the entire sneaker segment to plummet.
Retailers like Sports Authority, with their large stores, have had
a hard time getting decent returns on equity.
</P>
<P>
   Like many segments of retail that have consolidated in recent
years, it is likely that sporting goods will, in a few years, be
represented by just a few large chains, with almost all but the
most regional of players folding into the larger companies or
closed.
</P>
<P>
   Green, who owns 61 percent of Gart's shares, has often bought
troubled companies. He purchased Payless Drug Stores from Kmart
Corp. in 1994, merged it with Thrifty Corp. and sold to Rite Aid
Corp. last year for $2.4 billion. He also acquired Hechinger Co.
and Kmart's Builders Square unit, which he merged to create a
home-improvement chain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
