<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980702.0411 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8751 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN--WIMBLEDON-HNS &LR;      07-02 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN--WIMBLEDON-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DALE ROBERTSON 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
WIMBLEDON, England _ For Martina Hingis, the lessons in humility in
this season of comeuppances continue.
</P>
<P>
   For Jana Novotna, a chance for redemption and closure beckons in
a single swoop.
</P>
<P>
   For Nathalie Tauziat _ wow, dare she dream?
</P>
<P>
   A chilly, dreary Wimbledon fortnight concludes for the women
Saturday _ as always, weather permitting _ with as unglamorous a
final as the world's most famous tennis tournament has played host
to in ages. But for Novotna and Tauziat, each desperately seeking
her first Grand Slam title as they near the end of unexceptional
careers, it's a match made in heaven.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am so happy,'' said Tauziat, the 16th seed who has been
coming here since 1984 but never had reached a semifinal before
ousting unseeded Natasha Zvereva 1-6, 7-6 (7-1), 6-3 on Thursday.
``I'm not on the moon already, but almost.''
</P>
<P>
   Novotna, twice a runner-up with only bad memories to show for
her many efforts, remains tightly tethered to the earth despite
having upset her doubles partner, the No. 1-ranked and top-seeded
Martina Hingis, 6-4, 6-4. The victory became a payback for Hingis'
win in last summer's final.
</P>
<P>
   ``But for me, the job is not done yet,'' said the third-seeded
Novotna. ``I still have quite a lot of work to do. Let's hope what
the Duchess of Kent told me last year is right. She said,
`Third-time lucky,' and so here I am.''
</P>
<P>
   With the teeny-boppers storming the Women's Tennis Association
Tour, neither Novotna nor Tauziat got much, if any, attention from
the punters when Wimbledon began. The gray ladies presumed to be
primed to reclaim the stage from the Hingis generation were named
Steffi Graf, Monica Seles and Arantxa Sanchez Vicario, the last
having launched the retro trend by taking the French Open last
month.
</P>
<P>
   Most eyes focused on Graf, the seven-time champion who has spent
more than a year trying to come back after reconstructive knee
surgery and a succession of minor injuries. But Zvereva, another of
the suddenly emergent unsung elders, swept away Graf and then took
out Seles, only to be decked by Tauziat, the least likely Saturday
star of all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so tired,'' Zvereva, the holder of five Wimbledon doubles
titles, said of the end of her most memorable singles run. ``I need
a mental-institution break. I've never been in this situation
before, and now I realize what I've done. It's really draining and
disappointing to a point.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Nathalie just kept slowly lurking back into the match. At
the end, I felt like she was beating me from the net and from the
baseline as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Tauziat, the African-born, 30-year-old Frenchwoman, had started
horribly _ ``I was embarrassed,'' she admitted _ but rallied with
much aplomb, turning things her way for good by reeling off seven
consecutive points in the second-set tiebreaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell myself, `Nathalie, you have to fight,''' Tauziat said.
``I do not want to miss this chance to be in the final. And I fight
good. It's going to be a nice present to be there on Centre Court
(Saturday). If I play my best, I think I can win.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite hitting only 46 percent of her first serves, Tauziat
makes her debut final appearance after 43 Grand Slam tournaments,
the longest such drought in the history of the women's game.
</P>
<P>
   Novotna, 29, in turn, has been to Wimbledon 13 times, and in
both of her near misses she failed to hold significant leads.
Against Graf in 1992, she was up 4-1, 30-love in the third set
before suffering a monumental collapse that led to her breaking
down and sobbing on the shoulder of the aforementioned Duchess
after receiving the runner-up's plate.
</P>
<P>
   Against Hingis a year ago in bridesmaid revisited, she won the
first set before folding, although she was plagued by a pulled
abdominal muscle that worsened as the afternoon progressed.
</P>
<P>
   Add to those setbacks a loss in an Australian Open final, and
you have people cruelly snickering about her being a
Choke-oslovakian. Were Novotna now, as the favorite, to lose to
Tauziat, it would cement her reputation forever, overshadowing a
career that has seen her recently surpass $9 million in earnings.
</P>
<P>
   She would no doubt give a few of those bucks back in exchange
for a guarantee of victory over Tauziat. From the sound of it,
Novotna is stressing.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a great comeback Nathalie made in her match,'' Novotna
said. ``I watched a little of it. She's definitely a very, very
dangerous opponent. It would seem that, yes, I should be favored,
but believe me, it's not going to be easy to beat Nathalie Tauziat
when she's already made it to the final.''
</P>
<P>
   But it will be easy if she plays at the same level she exhibited
against the stunned Hingis. The unremarkable score might prevent
the match from being remembered years into the future, but several
of its games were as tense, hard-fought and well-played as any in
Wimbledon's annals.
</P>
<P>
   Novotna survived only by steeling her ever-suspect nerves after
an 0-3, love-40 start and delivering routinely spectacular shots at
crucial junctures the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, her backhand overhead winner off an excellent
Hingis lob to secure the fatal break in the next-to-last game
showed a touch of genius. After hitting that same shot sharply
cross-court repeatedly, Novotna this time knocked it straight down
the line, catching Hingis charging in the wrong direction with no
chance of recovery.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like I'm playing great,'' Hingis said, ``and I almost
can't lose the (second) set anymore, and all of a sudden it was 6-4
for her and I was saying, `Hey, come on, pick it up again.' She's a
great grass-court player, and she was definitely the better player
out there today.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hingis called her performance in the first set ``terrible''
and owned up to not being in the best of condition, a factor
because of the difficult matches she had endured to get into the
semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   After sweeping three of four Grand Slams in 1997, she has been
exposed as vulnerable on a more regular basis this year. She looks
like the teen-ager she is rather than a certain world champion for
years to come. The experience of losing to Sanchez Vicario in the
Roland Garros semifinals and now to Novotna here might be teaching
her a lesson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes it seems like the older, the better,'' she said. ``I
hope it's going to be like that with me also: the older, the
smarter, the cleverer and the better.''
</P>
<P>
   A fitting motto also for the current Wimbledon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
