<SLUG> BC-ARMAGEDDON-DEBUT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROSSES FOR `ARMAGEDDON' BELOW EXPECTATIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
 
  
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The future of ``Armageddon'' dimmed significantly
as its first day took in a somewhat disappointing $9.7 million at
3,090 theaters nationwide, analysts said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Although ``Armageddon'' had the third-largest Wednesday opening
ever, its receipts were far short of the $17.4 million Wednesday by
``Independence Day'' at the start of the Fourth of July holiday
period in 1996. ``Armageddon'' also finished well under the $14
million first day for ``Men in Black'' a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a horrible opening but everyone was expecting more,
particularly since `Armageddon' opened without any new
competition,'' said Robert Bucksbaum, president of the Reel Source
tracking service. He lowered his forecast for the five-day
Wednesday-Sunday total from $75 million to the $68 million-$72
million range, well under the $85 million record ``Independence
Day'' set for the period.
</P>
<P>
   The Disney release, which cost $140 million to make and an
additional $60 million to market, stars Bruce Willis as the leader
of an oil-drilling team assigned to blow up a Texas-size asteroid
before it destroys the Earth.
</P>
<P>
   The end-of-the-world theme and impressive special effects should
draw the core young moviegoers. But appeal to other demographics
might be hampered by mixed reviews and the better-than-expected
performance of ``Deep Impact,'' the comet-vs.-Earth movie that has
grossed $136 million domestically in less than two months for
Paramount.
</P>
<P>
   Bucksbaum said ``Armageddon'' needs to pull in massive grosses
in its first weekend because it will face serious competition
starting July 10 from Warner Bros.' ``Lethal Weapon 4'' and
DreamWorks' ``Small Soliders.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-98 2139EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980702.0413 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8753 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BANKBOS-CARRASCO-BOS &LR;      07-02 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANKBOS-CARRASCO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANKBOSTON DISCIPLINES WORKERS IN LOAN SCANDAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE FAINARU  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ BankBoston Corp. chairman Charles K. ``Chad'' Gifford
said Thursday that about 20 employees have been disciplined for
varying degrees of negligence in a recent $73 million loan scandal
that he said has left him angry and embarrassed.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Gifford said the punishments ranged from a
small number of outright dismissals to reprimands. He declined to
discuss specific employees, but bank sources said among those fired
was Mark E. Linehan, the immediate supervisor of fugitive banker
Ricardo S. Carrasco.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether Linehan continued to work for BankBoston,
spokeswoman Karen Schwartzman declined comment. Linehan had been
temporarily reassigned from his position as director of the tainted
international private banking unit pending the results of an
internal investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Carrasco, general manager of the institution's international
private bank in New York, allegedly made the fraudulent loans to a
controversial Argentine businessman and his companies over a
three-year period, then disappeared in February when the bank
sought to question him. He remains at large.
</P>
<P>
   Gifford said the recently completed internal investigation
determined that no BankBoston employee besides Carrasco
participated in the fraud. However, he said the scheme pointed up
flaws in the international private bank's lending practices and
revealed several instances in which employees failed to heed signs
that Carrasco was making millions of dollars in loans to a
businessman with a long record of criminal and financial misdeeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we feel that people should have known &UR;  &LR; because facts were
in front of them, then we think we have to take action,'' said
Gifford. ``People are accountable when they have
responsibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Gifford's comments were part of an effort by BankBoston to put
the worst fraud in its 214-year history behind it. In a memo sent
to 23,000 employees Thursday, Gifford and president Henrique C.
Meirelles announced: ``We are now ready to put closure to the
embarrassing and painful episode that began in March with our
discovery of fraudulent activities by the head of our International
Private Banking office in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Gifford said the bank has taken specific actions to prevent a
recurrence of the scandal, including relocating management of its
international private banking operations from the United States to
South America, where most of its wealthy clients reside. ``The
responsibility for (international private banking) should be with
the people in Brazil and Argentina that know the markets,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Gifford said he accepted part of the blame for the scandal.
``When something happens which bruises (our) reputation, I'm
angry,'' he said. ``In this case we had one individual who
defrauded our system, with a significant financial loss. It's a
source of embarrassment, and I'd be less than honest if I didn't
say that I'm not proud of it.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The effort to bury the scandal comes as Oldemar C. Barreiro
Laborda, the Argentine businessman who received the loans from
Carrasco, has charged through his lawyer that he met with other
BankBoston officials who were aware of his financial arrangment
with Carrasco. The bank is suing Barreiro in state court in New
York in an attempt to recover the loans.
</P>
<P>
   In court documents filed this week, Barreiro also charged that
the bank had fraudulently induced him into acknowledging that he is
responsible for repaying the bulk of loans. In response, the bank
ridiculed Barreiro's claim and said it was filing a formal
opposition ``at the risk of affording this argument a level of
dignity it clearly does not deserve.''
</P>
<P>
   The bank has said its Argentina employees were aware of
Barreiro's past but were kept in the dark about the loans by
Carrasco. But Edward Griffith, Barreiro's lawyer in New York, said
Thursday that his client claims to have attended meetings in 1996
in Buenos Aires with other senior bank officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact of Barreiro's business relationship with Bank Boston
International in New York was common knowledge and discussed'' at
the meetings, Griffith said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, one of the Barreiro-controlled companies that
received loans from Carrasco, LoJack Argentina, maintained a
separate checking account at the BankBoston branch in Buenos Aires.
Gifford said Thursday he was unaware of that account. But the bank
later confirmed the LoJack account was opened in 1996 and was
closed as the result of court action in April.
</P>
<P>
   Gifford said he believed that BankBoston employees in Argentina
had ``certain tangential contact relationships'' with Barreiro. But
he added: ``To the best of our knowledge, Carrasco kept our people
in Argentina as far away from this as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Carrasco, Gifford said the bank was victimized by an
employee who escaped suspicion largely because ``this was a guy
that seemed to personify what we think this company is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   A 20-year bank veteran who was trusted throughout the company,
Carrasco was able to continue making the fraudulent loans for
several reasons, Gifford said, but the most important was the
confidence that he enjoyed from his superiors.
</P>
<P>
   Carrasco had authority to both write the loans and verify
collateral that supposedly backed them, he said. The bank has since
separated these ``operating'' and ``line'' responsibilities
throughout the bank, Gifford said. Many of the loans, he said, fell
below Carrasco's signature authority of $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, since the loans supposedly were secured by cash,
they were not scrutinized as closely, Gifford said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never want to look at your associates and say, `You might
be the next Carrasco,' because an atmosphere of paranoia could
develop from something like that,'' Gifford said. ``But, having
said that, we must reenforce that policies and procedures cannot
just be overridden by individuals.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
