<HEADER>
A8758 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-MOTORS-COLUMN-LAD     07-02 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-MOTORS-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILLEN WANTS 10
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL SCHLOTTER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It is the second-oldest motor-racing event in the
United States. And if Rod Millen has anything to say about it,
Saturday's 76th running of the Pikes Peak International Hill Climb
in Colorado will be historic.
</P>
<P>
   Millen hopes to be the first to ever to cover the 12.42 miles of
constantly curving dirt road in less than 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the goal,'' said the 47-year-old Newport Beach driver.
``I'm just hoping the weather will cooperate.''
</P>
<P>
   Millen, a three-time Pike's Peak overall champion, has been
close to breaking 10 minutes three times before.
</P>
<P>
   He turned in the fastest run ever in 1994, reaching the top of
the 14,110-foot mountain in 10 minutes, 4.06 seconds. He did a
10:04.54 in taking the overall title last year and had a 10:13.64
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   With more than 20 years of rally, road and off-road racing
behind him, Millen keeps his engagement list short these days. At
its top is the Pikes Peak race, where he has come to be called the
King of the Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's become a favorite of mine,'' Millen said. ``It's one of
the unique classic motor-sports events in the world. How many other
places can you race to 14,100 feet at the top of a beautiful
mountain with no guard rail?''
</P>
<P>
   Millen has a new vehicle to chase the 10-minute mark this year.
After years of outfitting him in a custom Celica, Toyota this year
has provided a Tacoma pickup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I convinced them we could build a truck that would be faster
than the Celica,'' Millen said.``So far, the truck is working
really good. We're really happy with it.''
</P>
<P>
   He should be. Much of the design and production work on the
racer was done by Millen's people at Rod Millen Motorsport in
Huntington Beach.
</P>
<P>
   The project was a labor of love, Millen said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many elements to consider when designing a
vehicle to race up Pikes Peak,'' he said. ``Slippery dirt corners,
extreme altitude changes and lightning-fast down- and up-shifting.
I love the challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon back in front: Jeff Gordon is back on top in the Winston
Cup season points race following his win last weekend at Sears
Point in the Save Mart-Kragen 350K. The victory was Gordon's fourth
of the season and came off his fifth pole start.
</P>
<P>
   Of those disappointed about the cancellation of the Pepsi 400,
Gordon might be the most disappointed. He won the Pepsi 400 in 1995
and the 1997 Daytona 500.
</P>
<P>
   IRL disappointment: Don't look for the Indy Racing League
schedule to include a stop in New Hampshire next year.
</P>
<P>
   Only 20,000 showed up for last week's New England 200 resulting
in a reported $700,000 loss and the loss of Pennzoil as race
sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   Slow down: High speeds at last year's CART Marlboro 500 at
California Speedway, where Mauricio Gugelmin laid waste to the
tour's fastest lap record (previously 234.665) with a 240.942
circuit, made everybody on the tour nervous.
</P>
<P>
   And the concern gave impetus to an effort to find a way to slow
the cars on the tour's speedways.
</P>
<P>
   Engineer Mark Handford of Swift Engineering in San Clemente _
builders of race cars _ seems to have come up with an answer.
</P>
<P>
   Drivers have recently tested a new device called the Handford
wing, that adds drag and reduces downforce on the cars.
</P>
<P>
   Valencia product Bryan Herta, currently sixth in season points
standings, said the device is doing the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt the speeds were too high at Fontana last
year,'' Herta said. ``I think the new wing was the quickest and
cheapest way to reduce the speeds. I think the racing will be close
and very exciting for the fans. We'll probably be about 15 miles
per hour slower.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
