<HEADER>
A8760 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-STARR-NYT &LR;      07-02 0395
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-STARR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: STARR SHOULD NOT TARRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Friday, July 3:
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Starr has every right to appeal the dismissal this week
of the tax evasion charges he brought against former Associate
Attorney General Webster Hubbell. The decision by U.S. District
Court Judge James Robertson seems questionable in several respects.
</P>
<P>
   But Starr should heed the larger message of this and other
adverse rulings of recent weeks. That message is that the
investigations of President Clinton must soon be brought to a
conclusion. Although we are sympathetic to Starr's complaint that
the White House has tried to impede his investigation, the time has
come to lay out his evidence and conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson's central findings that Starr exceeded his authority
under the independent counsel statute and reneged on his immunity
deal with Hubbell are closer questions legally than his harshly
worded opinion might suggest. Starr's use of financial documents
obtained from Hubbell under a limited grant of immunity to build
the tax case against him is troubling. But whether higher courts
will agree that it was a violation of Hubbell's Fifth Amendment
rights is uncertain. Supreme Court decisions on the rule against
self-incrimination have limited its reach.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson mistakenly suggests that the prosecution of Hubbell
strays too far from Starr's legal mandate to investigate the
Whitewater affair. Since Hubbell, a former law partner of Hillary
Rodham Clinton, knows a great deal about the Whitewater matter, it
does not seem unreasonable for Starr to pursue the suspicion that
he received hush money from Clinton friends.
</P>
<P>
   But in seeking further judicial review of these issues, Starr
ought not to lose sight of the broader picture. The various legal
matters involving Clinton need to be resolved. The impatience of
various federal courts with Starr's tactics has added to national
unease about the open-ended nature of his inquiry. The office of
independent counsel was established not only to assure the
unfettered investigation of charges against the highest government
officials. It was also created to insure that a prosecutorial
judgment be rendered in a timely manner. In the case of Clinton and
Starr, that time is rapidly approaching.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-98 2147EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980702.0417 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8761 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-WRAPUP-$ADV05-H     07-02 1177
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-WRAPUP-$ADV05-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE POSITIVE SIGNS, THORNY PROBLEMS REMAIN IN WAKE OF CHINA
TRIP 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Sunday, July 5) 
(Eds.: Name of Richard Haass is cq) 
 
By CRAGG HINES 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ No matter how successful President Clinton believes
his China trip was, the U.S. administration concedes it is not at
all certain about its effect on the future of the world's most
populous nation.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's colorful nine-day trek through the most important
developing country, with 1.2 billion people and economic potential
that defies measurement, was marked by some positive signs.
</P>
<P>
   But thorny problems remain in Sino-American relations as well as
in the establishment of any firmly democratic institutions in China
itself. Even senior Clinton administration China-watchers refused
to interpret the president's trip as a breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   ``As to what happens next, we don't know,'' said Susan Shirk,
deputy assistant secretary of State for East Asian and Pacific
affairs. ``I don't think it would be wise to say this opens up a
whole new era in China.
</P>
<P>
   ``China has had a tremendous transformation in its economic
life, in its social and cultural life,'' Shirk said. ``And I think
that this is certainly stimulating a certain amount of political
debate. Where it ends up, we really don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   There was something of a paradox in the president's journey.
Although Clinton urged China to move forward on the democratic
front as strongly as it has in economics, there is no certainty
that the current Communist regime has the will to make such
historic shifts or the capacity to support the weight of such
changes even if they occurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``We make careful measurements about how much load the political
structure can bear,'' White House spokesman Mike McCurry said.
``And considerable thought has gone into measuring the expectations
of all sides.''
</P>
<P>
   Chief among those administration analyses is that Chinese
President Jiang Zemin has consolidated his position enough within
the government, military and _ most importantly _ the hierarchy of
the Communist Party to make him worth dealing with in such a
high-profile manner.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is some reasonable analysis that says Jiang Zemin ... is
in a position to make some moves and to do some things that might
have been impossible to do a year or two ago,'' McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
   The easy, but not necessarily appropriate, comparison is the
Soviet Union in the last half of the 1980s as authoritarian control
was released, sparking the unraveling of the other Communist giant.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not going to do a Gorbachev,'' said Richard Haass of
the Brookings Institution, a National Security Council staff member
during the Bush administration, referring to the Soviet leader who
first allowed the reforms.
</P>
<P>
   The administration agrees. Shirk, a former political science
professor at the University of California at San Diego, said, ``I
think it would be a real mistake to look at the trajectory of the
Soviet Union and Russia and say the exact same thing is going to
happen in China.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Rodman of the Nixon Center for Peace and Freedom, an NSC
official in the Reagan administration, sees ``some interesting
political ferment'' in China but believes there are definite
limits.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is that this regime will make concessions but on the
margins. They will never make a concession on human rights that
will endanger the nature of the regime,'' Rodman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If things get out of hand,'' he added, more conservative
forces in the ruling Communist Party elite ``will point to the
Gorbachev model and say this is dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   Several analysts contend that the atmospherics of Clinton's
trip, including the Chinese leadership's decision to broadcast live
the Clinton-Jiang news conference, should not be confused with
advances on the substantive agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``The political theater has been first class,'' James Lilley,
U.S. ambassador to China in the Bush administration, told Fox News.
``Now we get down to the hard business of making these deals
work.''
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials took the developments as more
meaningful and encouraging than some of the analysts, especially
the decision to broadcast the Clinton-Jiang news conference in
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   In the 70-minute back-and-forth, the two leaders discoursed at
length on some of the touchiest subjects for the Chinese hierarchy,
including the 1989 crackdown on pro-democracy demonstrators in
Tiananmen Square, in which hundreds of protesters were killed by
army troops, and the troublesome province of Tibet, where Buddhists
face persecution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taboo subjects,'' said the State Department's Shirk, ``that
had not been discussed previously. It's not going to be possible to
bury those subjects again.''
</P>
<P>
   The freewheeling news conference and its emphasis on human
rights issues, however, belied the White House's contention that
the Sino-American relationship had many more components than
personal freedom.
</P>
<P>
   That was true in part because of the unyielding pressure of
American opponents of Clinton's China policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Critics ended up setting more of the public agenda (of the
summit) than the president,'' Brookings' Haass said.
</P>
<P>
   Even the administration conceded that all the atmospherics were
not perfect.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Bader, director of Asian affairs at the National Security
Council, said that although the Clinton-Jiang news conference was
broadcast live, the coverage by Xinhua, the Chinese government news
agency, ``was not complete. They left out significant portions.''
</P>
<P>
   Other administration officials suggested that any loosening of
restrictions at the top has not filtered down, or was not intended
to filter down.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a system which still, obviously, is far from a free
system and which is selective and restrictive in the way it
covered'' the summit, Bader said.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the Chinese government leadership, administration
officials noted what Stanley Roth, assistant secretary of State for
East Asian and Pacific affairs, called ``real evidence of the
growing nationalism of the current generation in China.''
</P>
<P>
   Roth cited questions to Clinton from students at Peking
University critical of U.S. support for Taiwan and of the protests
against Jiang when he visited the United States last fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that reflects a genuine trend that is out there,''
Roth said. ``And that's something we have to deal with in the
future.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics back home contended Clinton was attempting to move
Sino-American relations to a ``post-Tiananmen'' phase before that
was warranted.
</P>
<P>
   When Roth was challenged on the point, he proposed an artful
formula that sought to have it both ways and sum up the
administration view of the post-summit relations with China:
</P>
<P>
   ``If you mean does Tiananmen cease to be an issue, the answer
is: of course not. If you mean are we working to improve the
relationship to increase our strategic dialogue ... overall: of
course.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
