</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-HISPANIC-TV-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOOOAAALLL!!!!!!!!!!!!! UNIVISION'S AUDIENCE SOARS  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD SANDOMIR    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Henry Cisneros looks at the number of Hispanic television
households tuned to Univision's World Cup broadcasts and is bowled
over: 1.5 million for Germany-Mexico, 1.4 million for
Belgium-Mexico, 1.3 million for South Korea-Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   It is not only Mexican games, although Mexican viewers in the
United States comprise the network's largest demographic group.
Argentina-England drew 1.1 million, France-Paraguay engaged 1.0
million and Nigeria-Denmark drew 979,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing to get good ratings and beat ESPN,'' said
Cisneros, the president of Univision and former secretary of
housing and urban development. ``But we're in mourning. If Mexico
had held its one-goal lead on Monday, it would be playing Brazil on
the Fourth of July. Imagine the ratings for that.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 47 games Univision has carried against ESPN or ESPN2,
Univision has outscored them in TV households 40 times. ESPN won
seven times. ESPN2 never won. But each of ABC's nine broadcasts
outdrew Univision's.
</P>
<P>
   Univision's overall World Cup rating is down from an 11.3 in
1994 to a 10.0 this year, but in the four years since, the
network's household reach has grown from 6.5 million to 7.7
million. So despite a lower rating, the average number of
households watching each games has risen 5 percent to 776,000.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, ABC's rating is down from a 5.3 to a 2.3; ESPN's has
fallen from a 1.7 to an 0.8, and ESPN2's has slipped from an 0.8 to
an 0.5.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, ABC, ESPN and ESPN2 had the advantage _ and
excitement _ of a World Cup played domestically and at better
times. That edge may be gone for the three Disney-owned networks
(and the U.S. team faded quickly).
</P>
<P>
   But Univision has the advantage of showing games played by five
Spanish-speaking teams, plus Brazil, the defending champion, and
perennial South American powerhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in Los Angeles on the two Saturdays that Mexico played
in the early morning at 8 o'clock, and it was like L.A. shut
down,'' said Cisneros.
</P>
<P>
   Hispanic fans have had a second World Cup outlet: Radio Unica, a
six-month-old network of 60 stations. On World Cup days, it beams
17 hours of games, analysis and talk shows. Ratings are
unavailable, but thousands of e-mail messages and phone calls
indicate a passionate response, said Nickie Jurado, a spokeswoman.
``We did a poll to see if Mexico would go to the second round and
got 7,000 calls in two days,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Univision and Radio Unica are the beneficiaries of a huge event
that is a great lure to major advertisers like AT&AMP;T, Budweiser and
Honda that want to reach the Hispanic market, which has proven to
be intensely brand loyal.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to reach the Hispanic marketplace in a showcase
medium, this is it,'' said Michael Gutkin, managing partner of Fova
Inc., a Spanish-language advertising agency owned by Grey
Advertising. ``Nothing comes remotely close.''
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros added: ``The World Cup gives them new levels of
identification with the Hispanic audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Radio Unica's games through Tuesday were done by its announcers
watching on a monitor in a Miami studio. But starting Friday, they
will be live in France.
</P>
<P>
   Soccer fans _ Latino and others _ who have experienced games on
Univision and Radio Unica get a tantalizing choice: the fevered
play-by-play emotion of Univision's Andres Cantor or the
incredible, impassioned fervor of Jorge Ramos.
</P>
<P>
   It's like choosing between Pagliacci and Figaro.
</P>
<P>
   Cantor is renowned for his ``Goooaaaaallll'' call, which he
admits he did not invent. The exclamation is traditional among
Latin soccer announcers. Ramos' call of Mexico's first goal Monday
against Germany consisted of three separate ``Goooaaalllls''
totaling 30 seconds, and well, some homer-like comments. (It was
accompanied by Mexican music; each goal is accompanied by music
appropriate to the scoring country, said Jurado.)
</P>
<P>
   ``We get even more excited than Univision,'' said Ramos, who is
45 years old. ``Three times more, maybe four times. I call every
touch, like Andres, but much faster.'' Ramos's rapid calls make
Cantor sound as if he is speaking at 33 1/3 rpm. Ramos has been
gargling with salt water to preserve his voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``In South America, radio is very important,'' he said. ``People
turn the volume down on TV and listen to the radio.'' Hmmm. I wait
for something exciting to happen on ABC, ESPN or ESPN, then flip to
Cantor.)
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``I'm getting letters and e-mail from Argentina and
Mexico telling me that I`m making them cry, I get them so
excited.'' Not surprisingly, he does so by saying, after a Mexican
goal: ``The Mexican team has the power and morale of the Mexican
people _ they are very hard workers like the Mexican people.''
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros listened to Ramos call Paraguay's match against France.
``The Paraguayan goalkeeper stopped a few French assaults and Ramos
was shouting, `We're with you! We love you! You're a patriot!' ''
said Cisneros, who describes his man, Cantor, as an artist. ``He
was un-be-lievable!''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
