<SLUG> BC-CIA-DEMS-PROBE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CIA CLEARED OF WRONGDOING IN POLITICAL-INFLUENCE INQUIRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JAMES RISEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A yearlong internal investigation by the CIA of
unauthorized contacts between a Democratic Party leader eager to
help a wealthy party donor and the CIA has found that no laws were
broken by officials at the spy agency, government officials say.
</P>
<P>
   The findings are included in a report by the CIA inspector
general that also recommends that the agency devise new rules to
insure that employees know to inform senior managers immediately of
any future contacts from political figures.
</P>
<P>
   The report criticizes CIA supervisors for being inattentive to
warnings from lower-level employees that Donald Fowler, the
Democratic Party's national chairman in the last election, was
trying to enlist the agency's help to open White House doors for
the Democratic donor, Roger Tamraz.
</P>
<P>
   The report, which has not been publicly released, cites a
supervising attorney in the CIA's general counsel's office with
failing to notify senior agency officials about the political
contacts, which occurred in late 1995. Investigators were not able
to explain the disappearance of internal memorandums sent to top
CIA officials notifying them of Fowler's efforts to get the CIA to
help Tamraz meet with President Clinton, despite objections from
the National Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   Tamraz's lobbying efforts became public last March in the
congressional investigation into campaign finance abuses. In late
1995, Tamraz, an American financier, was barred by council staff
members from attending White House events for major Democratic
donors because of questions about his background.
</P>
<P>
   But Tamraz had a longstanding relationship with the CIA. He
suggested to the Democratic National Committee that the agency
might help overcome the Council's opposition. Fowler, eager to
please a man who was giving $300,000 to the Democratic Party,
telephoned Tamraz's contact in the CIA directorate of operations,
the agency's clandestine espionage arm, to ask for help.
</P>
<P>
   That contact was identified only as `Bob,' and his actions later
became the subject of a congressional investigation into the
campaign finance scandal. The report cleared `Bob' of any
wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   The inspector general found that `Bob' had been troubled by
Fowler's call and he immediately asked an attorney in the
Directorate of Operations for advice. The attorney told `Bob' to
keep a written record of what happened. Within days of Fowler's
call, the attorney told his supervisor in the general counsel's
office. But the supervising attorney failed to pass word of
Fowler's contacts to John Deutch, the director of Central
Intelligence at the time, or other senior officials, the report
determined.
</P>
<P>
   In late 1995, `Bob' wrote a lengthy memoranum that also
disappeared. Deutch and other senior CIA officials were not aware
of Fowler's efforts to use the agency for political purposes until
just before it became public in early 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The highest-ranking official to receive `Bob's' memo was William
Lofgren, chief of the division in which `Bob' worked. He told
investigators that he had placed it in his outbox for delivery to
senior officials. Investigators say it disappeared, however, and
senior CIA officials never received it.
</P>
<P>
   But the inspector general's report found no evidence of
wrongdoing by Lofgren, who later retired and worked briefly as a
business consultant for Tamraz.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
