<SLUG> BC-EDIT-JAPAN-ECON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: SAVING JAPAN'S BANKING SYSTEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Friday, July 3:
</P>
<P>
   At long last, Japan has put together a credible bank rescue
package that contemplates closing banks that are hopelessly
insolvent while taking bad loans off the books of banks that can
make it. If executed well, the plan should help pull Japan out of
recession and ease Asia's economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Japan has gone from denial to dithering in dealing with the
crisis in its banking system that stems from loans made in the
1980s when the country's bubble economy was inflating property
values. Japanese leaders hoped the problem would go away, but
instead it festered until a financial crisis hit Asia's developing
economies, leaving Japanese banks with more bad loans.
</P>
<P>
   If Japan fails to act effectively, the yen is likely to continue
falling along with the country's economy. That would add to
pressures on other Asian countries, notably China, to devalue their
currencies and would deprive these countries of a strong Japanese
market they desperately need.
</P>
<P>
   The plan announced Thursday calls for bad loans to be sold for
what they can fetch. Doing that will establish market values, which
have been unclear because few such assets have been sold, and may
bring in both Japanese and foreign bargain hunters. Banks that are
able to survive are to get capital infusions, while other banks
will close.
</P>
<P>
   Creating stronger banks, with the capital to lend, is an
essential step toward easing the credit crunch that is hurting the
Japanese economy. Unfortunately, it appears that Japanese
authorities have a lot of work to do in figuring out just how bad
off their banks are, a fact that will delay action.
</P>
<P>
   The first test of the plan will come in the handling of the
proposed merger of the very weak Long-Term Credit Bank with the
stronger Sumitomo Trust. If stockholders in the weak bank are
virtually wiped out, with its managers dismissed, and if Sumitomo
has enough of its own bad loans taken off its books that it emerges
as a stronger bank, that will send the right signals.
</P>
<P>
   Japan remains a rich, productive country. Unlike its Asian
neighbors, it has the wealth needed to solve its financial crisis
and move on. Given the history of Japanese inaction, it is
understandable that the financial markets reacted skeptically to
Japan's plan, with the yen losing ground against the dollar. But
there are reasons to hope the currency markets will soon reverse
course as Japan proves that, finally, it is taking the needed
steps.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
