A8775 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-VERA-CLEMENTE-NYT     07-02 0940
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-VERA-CLEMENTE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HERO'S WIDOW IS NAMED FIRST WOMAN ALL-STAR CAPTAIN  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLAIRE SMITH    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Major League Baseball announced last year it would retire
No. 42 to honor Jackie Robinson, there was universal applause for a
sport rarely credited with hitting the right note.
</P>
<P>
   Let the applause begin again. For baseball will establish
another heartfelt first on Tuesday night when a major league
All-Star team will have a woman as a captain for the first time.
Vera Clemente, the widow of Roberto Clemente, will fill that role
for the National League when the All-Star Game is played at Coors
Field in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   Her selection by the National League president, Leonard Coleman,
not only acknowledges the work performed on behalf of humanity by
Clemente, who perished on Dec. 31, 1972, while on a flight of
relief supplies to earthquake victims in Nicaragua. It also also
acknowledges the strong bonds of marriage that has resulted in
strong partnerships within the game.
</P>
<P>
   Such partnerships have resulted in worthy contributions, such as
the women's scholarship fund set up by Dana and Jeff Kent this year
and the children in crises fund-raisers run by wives of major
league ballplayers, a program inspired by Susan Johnson, the wife
of the former All-Star second baseman and manager Davey Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Vera Clemente's contributions span generations. Though widowed
with three sons aged 2, 5 and 6, Vera Clemente never lost sight of
her husband's mission of making a difference on behalf of humanity
through sports. Nor did she forget his commitment to being a good
parent.
</P>
<P>
   She raised to manhood the boys: Roberto Jr., the oldest, a color
commentator on Spanish-language broadcasts of Yankee games, and
Luis Roberto and Roberto Enrique. Vera Clemente also fulfilled
Clemente's dream of building a sports complex to benefit all the
youth of his island commonwealth.
</P>
<P>
   The Roberto Clemente Sports City, which started on its way to
being a reality when the government of Puerto Rico granted it land
in Catalina in 1974, is a sprawling complex offering sports
instruction, organized team and league play and educational
assistance. About 30 graduates a year go on to earn scholarships in
colleges in the States. All because Vera Clemente never let her
partnership or Roberto's dream die in that fiery crash that killed
the Pittsburgh Pirates' star more than 25 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``She and Roberto were a team and clearly she represents and is
a major part of the Clemente legacy,'' said Coleman, who was also
the inspiration behind the ultimate retiring of Robinson's number
in every major league franchise. ``So I cannot think of a more
inspirational and appropriate captain than Vera.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised and at the same time I felt very honored,''
Vera Clemente said Thursday by telephone from the Roberto Clemente
Sports City, where her two younger sons work as administrators. ``I
lived the last eight years in baseball with Roberto before he died.
I felt very close to the game. And since he died we've continued to
try to develop youngsters.''
</P>
<P>
   Vera Clemente says she especially appreciates the honor of being
an All-Star captain because she, like her husband, almost met a
tragic end, coincidentally close to the anniversary of his death.
For Vera Clemente fell and broke a leg in January. The cast on her
leg caused blood clots that slowly made their way to her lungs,
resulting in embolisms that nearly cost her her life.
</P>
<P>
   ``For three days I couldn't breathe well,'' she said. ``Finally
I called an ambulance. I almost died. I said goodbye to everyone
but I prayed to God for more time because there is still so much to
do. I think that faith, God listened. God gave me another
opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Vera Clemente, more than a grandmother of 10 and mother of 3,
but matron of her island's baseball community, remained in
intensive care for nine days. Only last month was she deemed well
enough to return to her beloved sports city. ``I still am under
care but I am saving my strength to make this trip because it is
such a great honor,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   When she arrives at Coors Field, the Clemente legacy, begun by
Roberto, nurtured by Vera, will be on stage once again in the major
leagues. Not that it ever truly disappeared. For the legion of
players from Puerto Rico who were inspired by Clemente has never
been more impressive, as proved in last year's All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   Eight players born or raised in the Commonwealth dotted the
All-Star rosters, including Roberto Alomar, Juan Gonzalez and Ivan
Rodriguez , all of whom will start for the 1998 American League
team.
</P>
<P>
   Five players from Puerto Rico figured prominently in last year's
American League victory. The Indians' Sandy Alomar Jr. was named
most valuable player after hitting a game-winning homer. His hit
made a winner of the Royals' pitcher, Jose Rosado. Javier Lopez of
the Braves and Edgar Martinez of the Mariners also homered. Bernie
Williams of the Yankees scored the winning run when Alomar homered.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we honored Roberto in January, we also honored all of
those players,'' Vera Clemente said proudly, referring to a
ceremony at the sports complex in conjunction with the 25th
anniversary of the plane crash. ``And when they spoke they all
mentioned Roberto and how they try to follow him. I know that he is
a symbol for him.''
</P>
<P>
   So, too, is Vera Clemente, not only for her fellow Puerto Ricans
but also for all the players, coaches and fans of the game who
understand that contributions to humanity, whether by man or woman,
benefit not only a sport but us all.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
