<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8776 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-FARECARD-200&AMP;ADD-N     07-02 1032
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-FARECARD-200&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NYC TRANSIT SYSTEM TO BEGIN SALE OF UNLIMITED-USE FARE CARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ANDY NEWMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A new era for the New York City's mass transit riders
begins at midnight Friday night, when the Metropolitan
Transportation Authority's unlimited-ride Metrocard passes go on
sale, offering what transit officials hope will be a huge new
incentive to use subways and buses.
</P>
<P>
   Priced at $17 for a 7-day pass and $63 for a 30-day pass, the
new cards could yield significant savings for regular users of the
city's mass transit network.
</P>
<P>
   But more fundamentally, officials and advocates for riders are
hoping that the passes will transform the way New Yorkers use and
think about mass transit and create a much more mobile city, where
people hop on and off buses and subways with abandon because they
no longer have to worry about the cost.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates for riders have questioned whether the system is
prepared to absorb the 100 million new rides a year the passes are
expected to attract, an increase of 6 percent over today's levels.
They contend that the authority has not added enough service to
keep pace with an 18 percent increase in weekday ridership over the
last two years. But the authority maintains that it will be able to
add enough buses and subways should they be needed.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The passes, which were announced by Gov. George Pataki in
December, nearly complete a series of fare breaks that the
transportation authority began last year with free bus-to-subway
transfers in July and continued with an
11-rides-for-the-price-of-10 bulk discount in January.
</P>
<P>
   Those discounts, along with the city's booming economy, have
fueled a 9 percent increase in bus and subway ridership since last
year, to 5.5 million rides a day. A one-day unlimited pass, priced
at $4, is scheduled to be offered in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   The passes are also expected to benefit Pataki, who is running
for re-election and whose best-known piece of transit policy until
a year ago was to reduce state aid to the system in 1995, forcing
cuts in service and an increase in the fare, to $1.50 per token
from $1.25.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki said Thursday that he expected the benefits of the
discounts to be felt beyond the confines of the buses and subways.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know it's going to be good for the economy, we know it's
great for the fare payer and we know it's going to be outstanding
for the environment,'' he said. ``Everyone's been talking about how
congested the city is with too many cars, and by offering these
options we will continue to get people out of their cars and onto
mass transit.''
</P>
<P>
   Interviews with riders this week found them generally welcoming
the new cards, with some planning to buy one pass as a trial to see
whether they get their money's worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it would stop me from taking so many cabs,'' said a
46-year-old advertising buyer on the D train platform at 42d Street
who gave her name only as Valerie. ``It has to do with commitment.
Once I've made that $17 investment up front, I see it as a free
situation, rather than a $5 cab ride minus the dollar-and-a-half
public transportation.''
</P>
<P>
   Alberta Johnson, who lives in Harlem and works in a print shop
in Greenwich Village and who also takes the subway frequently to go
shopping or to the movies, was certain the pass was for her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I'll use it enough,'' said Ms. Johnson, who got off the
A train at the Port Authority Bus Terminal on her way to celebrate
her birthday in Atlantic City. ``I usually buy my $15 Metrocard
every Friday for the week,'' she said, ``but a lot of the time I
have to get a new one sooner so I can get around.''
</P>
<P>
   The new passes look identical to the pay-per-ride version of the
Metrocard, the now-familiar gold card with a magnetic strip that
allows fares to be deducted electronically at the turnstile or the
fare box and is now used to pay for more than 70 percent of all
rides.
</P>
<P>
   They new cards will be sold at all 468 subway stations and at
more than 3,200 newsstands, delis and other stores outside the
system.
</P>
<P>
   Passes bought at token booths must be purchased with cash, but
the authority expects that in the fall, it will begin to introduce
vending machines that take credit or automated teller cards.
</P>
<P>
   The pass is good from the moment it is first used until midnight
7 or 30 days later, depending on the kind of pass. A 30-day pass
does not expire automatically at the end of a calendar month.
</P>
<P>
   The only restriction on the passes is that they cannot be used
more than once within 18 minutes, except for transfers between
buses and subways. This is to prevent people from passing the card
to friends and swiping several riders through the turnstiles at
once.
</P>
<P>
   Holders of monthly passes on the MTA's railroads _ Metro-North
and the Long Island Rail Road _ will be able to buy a new version
of the pass with an unlimited bus and subway pass on the back of
the card.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the pass is a worthwhile investment will depend on how
often it is used. A rider who takes only 5 round trips a week, or
10 rides, would be better off with an 11-rides-for-the-price-of-10
Metrocard, which effectively reduces the fare to $1.36. At 10 rides
a week, a 7-day pass holder would pay about $1.70 a ride and a
30-day pass holder about $1.54 a ride.
</P>
<P>
   But anyone who typically takes even a couple of extra trips a
week would save money. Someone who takes seven round trips a week
on a 7-day pass would pay $1.21 per ride, while a 30-day pass
holder taking seven round trips a week would effectively pay $1.09
a ride.
</P>
<P>
   While there has been some concern that lower-income people would
avoid the Metrocard because of the up-front cost, officials in
other cities have found that such passes are used just as widely by
people at all economic levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lower-income people realize that it's the cheapest way to do
it,'' said Daniel Fleishman, a senior consultant at Multisystems
Inc., a transit consulting company in Cambridge, Mass., ``and those
are the people who use transit most because they use it not just
for work but for all trips.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
