<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAPAN ANNOUNCES A PLAN TO TACKLE BAD BANK LOANS
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese government announced a long-awaited plan to clear
away the nation's $550 billion in problem loans in hopes of
bolstering global confidence in the country and setting its economy
on track for growth.
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of the plan is a mechanism to allow banks to
fail without provoking chaos in the financial system.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS AUTHORITY RECEIVES 2ND BID
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Sports Authority rose 9 percent after Gart Sports made
a $445.2 million offer for 70 percent of the outstanding shares of
the 205-store retail chain. Sports Authority had agreed in May to
be acquired by Venator Group, which operates Foot Locker, Lady Foot
Locker, Kids Footlocker and Champs athletic stores.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS DECLINE IN LIGHT TRADING
</P>
<P>
   Trading of stocks was light as investors started their long
holiday weekend and government reports on jobs and manufacturing
suggested that profits could suffer from a slowing economy. The Dow
Jones industrial average fell 23.41 points, to 9,025.26.
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the 30-year Treasury bond declined to 5.60 percent,
from 5.62 percent on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   WELSH BUYING CENTENNIAL CELLULAR
</P>
<P>
   Welsh, Carson, Anderson &AMP; Stowe plans to buy Centennial Cellular
for about $1.5 billion, marking the investment company's first move
into the phone business.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIAN CONCERN TO PAY BACK TAXES
</P>
<P>
   Gazprom, Russia's largest petroleum company and biggest tax
delinquent, agreed to pay 4.2 billion rubles ($675 million) in
unpaid taxes and to start paying the government about 4 billion
rubles a month. The agreement also requires the government to pay
Gazprom billions of rubles for oil and gas that government agencies
and state companies order but never pay for.
</P>
<P>
   AID TO INDONESIA RESUMES
</P>
<P>
   The World Bank resumed aid to Indonesia for the first time since
President Suharto resigned. It approved a $1 billion loan that was
part of a $4.5 billion contribution from the World Bank that was
promised earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   ORDERS TO FACTORIES FELL IN MAY
</P>
<P>
   Orders placed with U.S. factories declined 1.6 percent in May,
to a seasonally adjusted $333 billion, suggesting that
manufacturing is losing speed.
</P>
<P>
   US AIRWAYS PICKS AIRBUS JETLINERS
</P>
<P>
   In a blow to Boeing, US Airways Group announced plans to buy 30
Airbus Industrie wide-body aircraft valued at $3.7 billion. Boeing
had been the airline's only supplier of big planes suited for
overseas flights.
</P>
<P>
   APPAREL GROUP FAILS TO AGREE
</P>
<P>
   The White House Apparel Industry Partnership, a presidential
task force that includes Liz Claiborne, Nike and Reebok and was
established to set up a code of conduct for apparel factories,
cannot agree on a number of issues.
</P>
<P>
   HAVOC ENDS IN KUALA LUMPUR
</P>
<P>
   Flights at Kuala Lumpur's new airport took off and landed more
or less on time after a computer glitch caused two days of havoc.
Since opening, the $2.25 billion airport has been plagued by
computer network problems.
</P>
<P>
   CITICORP CLOSING SOME OFFICES
</P>
<P>
   Citicorp is closing credit-card processing offices in Salt Lake
City, Denver and Columbus, Ga., to cut costs and improve
efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. MARKETS CLOSED
</P>
<P>
   The stock market and other financial markets in the United
States are closed Friday in observance of the Fourth of July. Most
overseas markets, however, are open. U.S. markets will reopen on
Monday. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
