<SLUG> BC-GLF-WOM-OPEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS, DAVIES LEAD PACK BY ONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KOHLER, Wis. _ There was a telling moment in Thursday's opening
round of the US Women's Open at Blackwolf Run, one of those
sequences that helps describe the mysteries of golf.
</P>
<P>
   Having split the fairway of the difficult 421-yard finishing
hole with a driver, Annika Sorenstam was some 190 yards from the
pin. Lofting a 7-wood approach high into the bright blue Wisconsin
sky, Sorenstam elicited thunderous applause from the large gallery
with a shot that came to rest 18 feet from the pin.
</P>
<P>
   Standing over her tee ball, a 3-iron that was 10 yards inside of
Sorenstam's, Laura Davies ripped into a 6-iron that never lost
track of the pin. It bounced just short of the green, hopped a few
times, and nearly rolled in. ``I don't know how it didn't really go
in,'' said Davies. ``It stopped an inch right in the jaws.''
</P>
<P>
   Davies tapped in to complete a 3-under par 68, which stood as
the lead until Kim Williams, a 10-year Tour veteran who has never
won, put together the afternoon's only sub-par round to tie her.
Davies and Williams lead a group of three _ Se Ri Pak, Pat Hurst,
Leslie Spalding _ by one shot, while five players, including former
champion Liselotte Neumann and LPGA Tour money leader Donna
Andrews, posted 70s on a day when only 10 players in the field of
150 broke par.
</P>
<P>
   Sorenstam had promised herself not to give up as she stalks her
third Open title in four years and following Davies's dramatics at
18, she had a test. The Swede coolly drained her birdie putt for a
71, but her finesse took a back seat to Davies's power.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very impressive,'' said Sorenstam. ``Laura is a strong
player. She is longer with a 3-iron than my driver. To me, she
doesn't hold back anything.''
</P>
<P>
   For sure, Davies may possess the purest power game of anyone,
John Daly and Tiger Woods included. Thursday she used her driver
just twice, on this the second-longest (6,412 yards) course in
tournament history.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I have to hit 3-iron, 3-iron on a par-4,'' said Davies,
``I'd rather do that than try and hit my driver and hit a 7-iron or
8-iron in. This is a long course, and I am long enough with that
3-iron.''
</P>
<P>
   That she is, but Davies would have to string together dozens of
those gigantic 3-irons to accurately measure the length of Nancy
Lopez's afternoon. This is a tournament that has eluded her grasp
21 times and last year's heartbreaking loss to Alison Nicholas left
her with an even greater thirst for it. Lopez will have to wait
another year to possibly quench that desire, for she put up one of
her worst US Open efforts in front of thousands of admirers,
getting her only birdie of the afternoon on the 18th to shoot 77.
More and more it appears that she will join Sam Snead and Kathy
Whitworth as legends who could never win the Open.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Davies isn't legendary, but her power is. The
34-year-old Davies plays a game with which no other woman is
familiar. When it is on, as it was in 1987 when she won the US
Open, it can leave the opposition in her divots. When it isn't (and
she's missed the cut five times on Tour this year), she is left
hopelessly unsure of herself. Despite breaking 70 for just the
sixth time in 45 rounds in the Open, that feeling still grips
Davies, who is as refreshingly honest as she is powerful. ``I am so
low on confidence, that is the trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   If that's true, her pursuers had better hope Davies's troubles
are over.
</P>
<P>
   The trio who shot 69 went out in the morning when the winds, and
greens, were softest. Pak took immediate advantage with birdies at
two of the first three holes, but the LPGA Championship winner
nonchalantly parred the backside, though she broke 70 for the third
time in her five US Open rounds. Hurst won the Nabisco Dinah Shore
in the spring and has played well this year, but Spalding has never
finished better than a tie for 21st in her brief pro career.
</P>
<P>
   Barb Mucha, Jackie Gallagher-Smith, and amateur Brenda Corrie
Kuehn are also at 70, but it is the player lurking in a crowd of
seven at 71 _ Sorenstam _ who commands attention.
</P>
<P>
   For as effectively as Davies can overpower a course, Sorenstam
can manage it to near perfection. She made a triple-bogey at the
par-4 fifth and ``for a few seconds'' she thought of last year at
Pumpkin Ridge in Portland, Ore. Sorenstam was trying for an
unprecedented third straight Open triumph, but the dream died early
when she triple-bogeyed the ninth hole. She never recovered, shot
77, and missed the cut.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, she held her composure. ``I told myself it is only
Thursday, let's try and get this behind you and go from here.''
Which she did. No one made more than her five birdies _ three on
the back nine _ and when she answered the Davies fireworks at No.
18 with her usual precision, Sorenstam had put herself in great
position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I promised myself I won't give up and I won't,'' said
Sorenstam. ``I am going to keep grinding and griding.''
</P>
<P>
   And Davies, for sure, will keep ripping and ripping. Fifty-four
more holes will prove if her power can beat finesse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-98 2201EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
