<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 22:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8792 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FIRES-CERABINO-COX     07-02 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIRES-CERABINO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Trying to get through fire to Grandma's House
 &HT;    By Frank Cerabino
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Getting to grandma's house has never
been such an adventure.
</P>
<P>
   With traveling on I-95 out of the question, the only way to
drive to a holiday weekend with my wife's family in Fernandina
Beach is to take a meandering drive through the rolling midsection
of the state.
</P>
<P>
   And so here we are, two adults, two kids and a puppy who's not
yet toilet-trained, hurtling through one-stoplight towns and
feeling like the crew from Lost in Space.
</P>
<P>
   We've been at it for the past six hours, and best as I can tell,
we're somewhere near Starke. Or Waldo.
</P>
<P>
   Where's Waldo? Don't ask me.
</P>
<P>
   After waking up Thursday morning with the news that 125 miles of
Interstate 95 was closed, we wondered if that meant our planned
weekend in the coastal town north of Jacksonville was out of the
question.
</P>
<P>
   We'd made the trip many times between Palm Beach County and the
Florida-Georgia border. Always on I-95. It's an incredibly boring,
yet reliable, way to travel the 350 miles.
</P>
<P>
   Until Thursday, getting to the northeast corner of the state
without using either I-95 or U.S. 1 was a question too unthinkable
to ponder.
</P>
<P>
   I called the Florida Highway Patrol office in Lantana.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is I-95 still closed from Titusville to Jacksonville?'' I
asked the trooper who answered the phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then how do I get to Jacksonville?''
</P>
<P>
   She told me to take Florida's Turnpike to I-75, and then east on
I-10 to Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's got to be a better way than that,'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   Taking I-75 to I-10 is a great way to get to Tallahassee, not
Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
   She gave me a couple of other numbers to call. The next person I
spoke to was a highway patrol trooper from Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take Highway 301,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Turnpike, to Highway 301, then to I-10, which hooks up with
I-295, the Jacksonville bypass, which then runs into I-95 north of
Jacksonville _ a short 20 minutes from Fernandina Beach.
</P>
<P>
   I drove to Kmart and bought a road map, then loaded up the crew
in the mini-van for the trip.
</P>
<P>
   This drive was bound to put the ``long'' in long weekend.
</P>
<P>
   That was six hours ago. The dog has yet to have an accident in
the car, although she has managed to swallow some unidentified
object on the floor. The kids have had several territorial
skirmishes in the back seat, and my daughter gave her first, ``Are
we there yet?'' sometime before we reached Fort Pierce.
</P>
<P>
   But all in all, the trip's been a success. Unlike the typical
boredom of I-95, we're slicing through the heart of Florida,
rolling through little towns such as Citra, Hawthorne and Sparr.
</P>
<P>
   We've seen strange roadside motels, old women sitting in the
shade in front of piles of watermelons, and pastures filled with
grazing horses. It's a landscape dotted by fast food restaurants,
multiple chances for salvation and miles and miles of sidewalk junk
that my wife insists on calling ``antiques.''
</P>
<P>
   And we're not alone. The road is filled with other travelers
with their pop-up campers and bicycle carriers. And at stoplights,
we take the measure of the amazing number of trucks _ big 18-wheel
rigs _ that were forced to leave the interstate highway to make it
to Georgia and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   My wife just announced we've passed Waldo. Word has it we'll be
on I-10 within the hour, and then, according to my road atlas,
we'll be in the outskirts of Jacksonville in another 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   As long as the puppy doesn't puke.
</P>
<P>
   Years from now, lots of Palm Beach County residents will
remember this Fourth of July weekend because it was the year they
couldn't buy fireworks. But for us, it will be the year the fires
forced us to see a little more of Florida than we usually do.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Kuralt, the traveling journalist, once said that the
interstate highway system was so good it was possible to go
anywhere without actually seeing anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, look at that,'' my wife, who's driving now, says to the
kids. ``Linda's yard arts!''
</P>
<P>
   I glance up and see a shrine of tacky lawn ornaments. With any
luck, we'll get to Fernandina Beach by 9 tonight.
</P>
<P>
   That's eight-and-half hours _ a good two-to-three hours longer
than it usually takes us. But we're not complaining. Not yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we come home,'' my daughter asks, ``will we have to take
this way back again?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' I say. ``I'm sure they'll have the highway open by
then.''
</P>
<P>
   I hope so. I've had enough Kuralt for one weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
