</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-HENMAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HENMAN VS. SAMPRAS: CAUSE MEETS SPECIAL EFFECT 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By ROBIN FINN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ The prayer rugs come with explicit
instructions and have already been mass-produced. Pray for Henman,
command the tacky paper mats, which helpfully provide a pair of
racquets marking the spot for each knee of obedient kneelers.
</P>
<P>
   And there are plenty of them: England, still smarting over the
second-round World Cup loss of its revered soccer team, has turned
its sporting attention and affection toward Tim Henman, the first
British man to reach Wimbledon's semifinals in 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   All Henman has to do to become the first British finalist since
Bunny Austin tried and failed to take the title in 1938 is beat the
incumbent and four-time champion, Pete Sampras, whom he has never
beaten before.
</P>
<P>
   It's a tall order, but the British can't help themselves: they
have already been screaming and waving their miniature Union Jacks,
and now, with the moment near at hand, they're just about kneeling
and praying to the tennis gods to shine on their 23-year-old
favorite son.
</P>
<P>
   Henmania, as the affliction is known here at Wimbledon, where
the host nation hasn't been able to boast of a home-grown champion
since Fred Perry hoisted the trophy in 1936, is nothing new.
</P>
<P>
   Henman has been putting up with the alternate adulation and
devastation of the British public ever since he made his
breakthrough run to the 1996 quarterfinals. He even inspired a
frenzy back in 1995 when, as a bony, whiskerless 20-year-old
prospect, he shamed himself by accidentally hitting a ballgirl with
an angrily walloped missile during a doubles match and found
himself thrown out of the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   That was the same year Sampras, then as now the defending
champion, had already thumped Henman out of the singles competition
in straight sets in the second round. Henman, son of an Oxford
attorney, went home to work on keeping a stiff upper lip in his
matches and adding a 130-mph serve to his repertory. Sampras went
on to capture the 1995 championship, the second of his three
consecutive titles here. They haven't met since, but they have
enjoyed each other's company on the practice court.
</P>
<P>
   According to Sampras, the British No. 2 (he lost his place in
the pecking order when sonic-serving Greg Rusedski drifted across
the Atlantic Ocean from Canada and took up residency in London) is
one of the most complete players in the game. When it comes to
Rusedski and Henman, Sampras is slightly prejudiced in the latter's
favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember playing him four years ago, and he's just a lot
more powerful now,'' Sampras said of Henman, who is still a bit of
a stringbean at 6 feet 1 inch, 155 pounds. But he's a hardy
stringbean. ``He's serving very, very big,'' said Sampras, ``and
he's got a really good all-round court game. He does everything
very well, and there's not that many players that have that.''
</P>
<P>
   To reach his first Grand Slam semifinal after sinking in
straight sets in the quarterfinals for the past two years, the
12th-seeded Henman upset sixth-seeded Patrick Rafter, the 1997 U.S.
Open champion, and third-seeded Petr Korda, this year's Australian
Open champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be in the quarters again for the third year running, I
think I was anxious to go further this year; I think I was in
control of every aspect of my game,'' said Henman, whose Wimbledon
pedigree stretches through the family tree: his grandfather Henry
Billington made six appearances here; and one of his grandmothers
was the last woman to serve underarm.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the enemy is now Sampras, the odds on Henman's
winning Wimbledon have improved to 8-1. That's a far cry from the
odds he faced when he made his debut here with a first-round exit
in 1994, when the odds of Elvis' being alive were 250-1 and the
odds of a British man's winning this championship were 1,000-1.
Henman has not told anyone to bet on him, but he's not conceding
anything, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously you're aware that he's the best grass-court player
in the world at the moment, and I think the way he's come through
his five matches has been pretty effortless,'' Henman said of the
top-seeded Sampras. ``I know it's going to be my toughest test so
far, but having said that, I definitely feel I've got a good
chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras, who has an equal in Henman when it comes to displaying
a dearth of on-court emotion, said he didn't care if the entire
Center Court crowd waved flags and said prayers on Henman's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm expecting them obviously to be rooting for Tim,'' said
Sampras, whose favorite matches have been those where he took on
Boris Becker and his adoring German public in Germany. ``This event
will be watched all over England and all over the world, but I feel
like I'm ready. Hopefully I can get off to a good start and put the
crowd out of the match, but it's still one-on-one, and I think Tim
knows that.''
</P>
<P>
   In the other semifinal, 14th-seeded Goran Ivanisevic of Croatia,
a two-time Wimbledon runner-up intent on shedding his reputation as
the best current player never to win a Grand Slam, takes on
ninth-seeded Richard Krajicek, the 1996 Wimbledon champion intent
on proving he has more than one Slam title in him. Ivanisevic leads
that rivalry, 8-2, and has beaten the erratic Dutchman in their
last six meetings. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
