<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 22:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8794 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLAMAIN-COX     07-02 1099
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLAMAIN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Firefighters struggle at `ground zero'
 &HT;    By Mike Williams and Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORMOND BEACH, Fla._Pastor Roy Hargrave stood in the choking
smoke, watching as a forest service helicopter swooped only yards
overhead, dumping bucket after bucket of water on the wildfire
swarming through the trees a quarter mile from his Riverbend
Community Church in Ormond Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is ground zero right now,'' Hargrave said, mopping his
brow. ``But these firefighters have done an unbelievable job.''
</P>
<P>
   But there were dozens of ground zeroes Thursday as firefighters
struggled to contain the wildfires that rode stiff winds and
threatened the homes of 35,000 evacuees in a three-county area
along Florida's central Atlantic Coast.
</P>
<P>
   The fire and smoke forced postponement of Saturday's Pepsi 400
stock car race and closure of a 125-mile stretch of I-95 from
Jacksonville to Titusville for much of the day Thursday. Northbound
lanes north of St. Augustine were reopened Thursday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Lawton Chiles toured Volusia and Brevard counties Thursday
and asked federal officials for more heavy equipment to create fire
breaks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have almost every heavy bulldozer in the South,'' Chiles
said. ``Now we are reaching outside of that area. It looks like
this is going to be another day of trying to contain the fire and
trying to protect homes.''
</P>
<P>
   The weather forecast _ hot and dry _ didn't bode well for
firefighters. Lightning from a round of afternoon thunderstorms
Wednesday sparked about 70 new fires, state officials estimated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking at the weather for the next few days, it's not a good
sign,'' said Ormond Beach Fire Chief Barry Baker. ``We've got more
west winds. It's incredible the way these fires are moving. It's a
pretty awesome sight.''
</P>
<P>
   By Thursday evening, the series of wildfires, which began
Memorial Day, had burned 283,000 acres and damaged or destroyed at
least 96 homes and 57 other structures statewide.
</P>
<P>
   Daytona Beach Mayor Bud Asher, whose mother-in-law and
father-in-law were among those evacuated from Ormond Beach, said
firefighters held their own Thursday against blazes that forced the
evacuation of a subdivision and apartment complex.
</P>
<P>
   ``Daytona Beach is safe,'' Asher said Thursday. ``Right now, I
think we've got a pretty good hold on things. For now, the worst of
it is over.''
</P>
<P>
   The city, however, cancelled its Fourth of July celebration,
including the annual fireworks display. The pyrotechnics are fired
from the end of the boardwalk pier toward the Atlantic Ocean. Asher
said smoke from the fires, which has limited visibility in the
area, would have caused a crowd control problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't afford to tie up police for a huge fireworks
display,'' Asher said.
</P>
<P>
   Race officials had expected a crowd up to 250,000. Several
thousand already had arrived in RVs, trucks and trailers just
before qualifying. Many left Thursday, jamming westbound lanes of
I-4 toward Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   Acrid smoke plumes forced the closure of I-95 between
Jacksonville and the Bee Line Expressway south of Titusville.
Officials also closed U.S. 1, the other north-south artery on the
Atlantic coast.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Bruns, spokesman for the Florida Division of Emergency
Management, had no estimate how long the highways would be closed.
``No one knows how long the emergency will run,'' Burns said. ``We
don't have a long distance line that extends into the atmosphere.''
</P>
<P>
   Also on Thursday:
</P>
<P>
   At least four new areas were evacuated _ two in northern Brevard
County northwest of Titusville, one in St. Johns County west of
U.S. 1 south of St. Augustine and one in a Flagler County
subdivision.
</P>
<P>
   Delta Air Lines reported delays up to 30 minutes to Jacksonville
and Daytona Beach. Delta has buses standing by in Orlando if
flights are rerouted there because of poor visibility on the coast.
</P>
<P>
   The Flagler County Jail in Bunnell was evacuated. Those charged
with felonies were transferred while inmates charged with
misdemeanors were released, a deputy said. The county's E-911
service based in Bunnell was moved to Palm Coast.
</P>
<P>
   While the most dangerous blazes burned on Florida's Atlantic
coast, the state also reported 150 acres on fire in the
Apalachicola National Forest. Sporadic blazes were reported
throughout the Panhandle.
</P>
<P>
   At the Kennedy Space Center, east of Titusville and separated
from the mainland by the Banana River, officials monitored smoke to
make sure it didn't contaminate ``clean rooms'' where elements of
the space station are being constructed. Filters not normally
monitored over holiday weekends will be watched, said NASA
spokesman Bruce Buckingham. Evacuations and the shutdown of I-95
caused more than 125 Boeing employees to miss work Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, Buckingham can look out his window and see the launch
pad 3 miles away. Smoke obscured his view Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a big fog bank rolled through,'' Buckingham said.
``The smoke is everywhere outside. It's like sitting in front of a
campfire.''
</P>
<P>
   In Titusville Thursday at the Dixie Crossroads seafood
restaurant, there wasn't much of a lunch crowd. ``I can't imagine
that anybody would want to eat,'' said general manager Kathy
Shaeffer, evacuated from her house in Mims two days ago. ``We're
totally devastated.''
</P>
<P>
   The staff brought batches of its signature rock shrimp and corn
fritters to firefighters along with 15 coolers of cold drinks. She
said it's the least they could do for men and women putting in
20-hour days in nearly 100-degree heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``You labor to breathe,'' said Shaeffer. ``At night, you see the
sky glowing in one area and glowing in another area, so you know
it's two distinct areas.''
</P>
<P>
   Cliff Williams normally waits half an hour to be seated at the
Dixie Crossroads but had his pick of tables Thursday. Williams,
director at the North Brevard Funeral Home, has taken to calling
the area north of Titusville the ``war zone.''
</P>
<P>
   During funerals, ``white ash flies all over,'' Williams said. On
the roads and interstates, he passes evacuees _ ``people in the
median strip with half their stuff on top of their cars.''
</P>
<P>
   Back in Ormond Beach, Richard Palmer, 58, packed his belongings
and is ready to evacuate at a moment's notice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nerve-wracking,'' Palmer said. ``It's not like a
hurricane where you can see it coming for days and know when it
will arrive. There's no rain, and nothing changes. It's just more
smoke, more ashes falling out of the sky.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
