</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETPORN-SUIT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Employee sues and denies claim that he a viewed pornographic
images on the net
 &HT;    By Tommy Witherspoon
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO _ A former Raytheon Systems employee has filed a wrongful
termination lawsuit, claiming that he was fired after company
officials falsely claimed that he spent four to six hours a day
calling up pornographic images on his computer.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. White is seeking unspecified damages from Raytheon in
the suit, filed on his behalf in Waco's 74th State District Court
by Waco attorney John L. Bates.
</P>
<P>
   White, a 23-year-old aerospace engineer, was fired Jan. 29 and
told that it was because he spent from four to six hours a day
during a two-week period in October 1997 ``watching pornographic
presentations on the Internet,'' according to his lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   White alleges that he told his supervisors that he was away from
his work station attending classes without access to a computer for
at least two of the days they say he was calling up Internet porn.
</P>
<P>
   He claims others must have used his computer password to log
onto a computer to make it appear that he was using the computer
when he was not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plaintiff further alleges that he had been working on a part
of a project that previously two people had handled and had allowed
to fall behind schedule,'' the suit claims. ``Plaintiff alleges
that with the amount of work done and bringing the program up to
date that there was no way he could have done the work he was doing
and at the same time watch pornographic material four to six hours
per day on the computer screen.''
</P>
<P>
   White failed in an appeal of his termination, according to the
lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Curtis, a Raytheon spokesman, said Raytheon has a ``standing
policy'' to not comment on pending litigation.
</P>
<P>
   White alleges Raytheon officials were ``grossly negligent'' in
the manner in which they investigated the reported Internet
incident and in the security of the computer system.
</P>
<P>
   He also alleges that his professional reputation has been
damaged and that Raytheon officials slandered and libeled him by
making the reason for his termination public, at least throughout
the Waco plant.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
