u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WorldCup-HNS &LR;      07-02 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-World </SLUG>
 Cup-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Italy enters &QL; 
wolves' den &QL; 
to do battle
</P>
<P>
   Rivalry with France &QL; 
transcends Cup match
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN P. LOPEZ &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
PARIS _ Two days ago, there were a pair of bitter rivals and World
Cup arch-enemies fighting it out into the night, giving the Cup
high drama and tense moments.
</P>
<P>
   And that's exactly where we pick up the Cup now, although the
names and stakes have changed.
</P>
<P>
   Vieri
</P>
<P>
   Two days after a memorable England-Argentina clash finished off
group and round-of-16 play, today it will be Italy-France with
similar stories to tell at 80,000-seat Stade de France.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it is Italy and France,'' Italy forward Christian Vieri
said, ``we have no secrets. We don't care if it is the World Cup or
any other tournament. We have to win this game.''
</P>
<P>
   The chance to advance to the semifinals of the World Cup has
brought even more attention to these traditional border rivals who
have played some of the more intense, more memorable soccer games
in history.
</P>
<P>
   The series dates to the 1930s, with each nation claiming
important victories either in the World Cup or European Cup. Since
1980, when Italy and France met at the European Cup, each team has
won three meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Even though both coaches for today's game have tried to downplay
the rivalry, the history of this series is of hard tackles, hard
feelings and end-to-end action.
</P>
<P>
   French fans consider the Italians pompous and conceited.
Italians call the French team, which is known as the ``brave
roosters'' in France, the ``little chickens.''
</P>
<P>
   It also is a series that inevitably brings out the best efforts
from the individual stars and often hinges on a single moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going into the wolves' den,'' Italy coach Cesare Maldini
said. ``France is not new to us. I can honestly say that the
tournament has been great so far, but the best matches are still to
come, beginning with this one.''
</P>
<P>
   Both teams are considered among the favorites to win the Cup
championship. Italian goalkeeper Gianluca Pagliuca went so far as
to say that the winner today will go on to win the Cup on July 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've played hundreds of matches in front of hostile crowds
before,'' Pagliuca said. ``We know we'll be surrounded by French
supporters, but we don't mind. Playing at home should be an
advantage for France, but we suspect it could also turn against
them at difficult stages of the match.''
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the intrigue of today's match is that seven expected
French starters play professionally in Italy. Many Italian players
know players from the other side, but they are not exactly friends.
</P>
<P>
   Several Italian players resent French stars playing in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most important match of my career because we know
them so well and the semifinals are on the line,'' Italy's Fabio
Cannavaro said. ``Ever since they've been in the Italian League,
they've begun to think like winners.''
</P>
<P>
   Many French supporters, meanwhile, believe that Italian club
owners are invading their country and scooping up its best players.
</P>
<P>
   For these rival nations, it has become a question of, which came
first, the ``brave roosters'' or the Italian League?
</P>
<P>
   France considers itself superior no matter whre its best
players sign contracts. Still, the two biggest French stars,
Zinedine Zidane and Youri Djorkaeff, play in the Serie A of the
Italian League.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zidane is the best playmaker in the world, as we've seen when
he's played in Italy,'' Maldini said. ``We will need to adopt
suitable tactics to contain him. He has all the qualities that
great players have but I've been reading what he's been saying, and
he's fairly confident France will win.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Zidane has predicted a victory in his first game back
since being suspended for two games for pulling a red card.
</P>
<P>
   But Italy has won the last two meetings between these nations
and has quite a lineup of stars itself, from Vieri, the leading
goal-scorer of the Cup thus far with five, to Alessandro Del Piero,
Dino Baggio and Roberto Baggio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it will be a typical Italy-France meeting,'' Vieri
said. ``Since they will be playing at home in front of their own
crowd, they will have all the responsibility and all the pressure
on them. They are going to be obliged to attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will counterattack and win. We are inspired to win this
game. The Italian attack is the strongest in the world, and I think
we will show it against them. We are better than them.''
</P>
<P>
   Prepare to pick up Cup action where it left off Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There always is a sense of tension in the air when we play
Italy,'' France coach Aime Jacquet said. ``Hopefully, by the end of
the day we will be able to relieve that tension.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
