<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8797 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALYDAR-CONVICTION-HNS     07-02 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALYDAR-CONVICTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER NIGHT WATCHMAN OF ALYDAR CONVICTED OF LYING 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DEBORAH TEDFORD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A former night watchman at Kentucky's financially
ailing Calumet Farm was convicted Thursday of lying to a federal
grand jury on questions relating to the critical injury of Alydar,
history's most heavily insured racehorse.
</P>
<P>
   Most jurors agreed that Calumet executives schemed to injure
Alydar, who was euthanized two days later, but said that they did
not believe defendant Alton Stone was part of any such conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   The grand jury was investigating allegations of fraud
surrounding now-defunct First City Bankcorporation of Texas. Alydar
was collateral on $50 million in First City loans to Calumet.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was so much sympathy for him (Stone),'' said trial jury
forewoman Sheila Donley. ``It was difficult to just look at (the
inconsistencies) his statements and not think, `but why.' All we
could consider was that he lied.''
</P>
<P>
   All the jurors said Stone was just in the wrong place at the
wrong time.
</P>
<P>
   Stone, 39, faces up to 10 years in prison and $500,000 in fines.
He will be sentenced by U.S. District Judge David Hittner on Sept.
18.
</P>
<P>
   Stone substituted for the regular night watchman on Nov. 13,
1990.
</P>
<P>
   He was convicted of lying about who asked him to fill in for the
regular night watchman and where he was between 9:45 and 10:15
p.m., when Alydar suffered a broken leg.
</P>
<P>
   Stone told the grand jury last summer that Harold ``Cowboy''
Kipp, who normally had the night watch at the stallion barn, asked
him to substitute.
</P>
<P>
   But Kipp testified that farm management directed him to take the
evening off, and that he never talked to Stone or anyone else about
filling in.
</P>
<P>
   Stone also told the grand jury that he went to the snack bar to
get a soft drink about 9:30 or 9:40 p.m. and returned 10 minutes
later to find Alydar injured.
</P>
<P>
   But government witness Keed Highley testified that he discovered
the injured horse _ minutes after spotting Stone's truck pull away
from the stallion barn.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors John Willis and Jamie Whisonant said Stone was not part
of a conspiracy to hurt Alydar.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't see a motive,'' said Whisonant. ``We didn't see any
gain for him. He's (now) a construction worker.''
</P>
<P>
   Farm execs may have asked Stone, actually a groom at the time,
to fill-in that night, figuring he would do a poor job of
performing the unfamiliar duties, jurors said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they probably knew he was not very attentive,'' said
Donley.
</P>
<P>
   Stone received some notoriety when he was interviewed for the
book ``Wild Ride,'' which chronicled the rise and fall of Calumet
Farm.
</P>
<P>
   A high school dropout, he was interviewed by the author about
the events that transpired the evening he said he found the injured
Alydar sweating and whining in his stall.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutor Julia Hyman theorized that Calumet Farm's owners
arranged Alydar's injury to collect a hefty insurance claim and
stave off financial ruin.
</P>
<P>
   First City _ itself then on the verge of collapse _ loaned
millions to Calumet during the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   After Alydar's death, Calumet's owners collected $36.5 million
in insurance claims, with $20.5 million of that going to First
City.
</P>
<P>
   At least five people, including former First City vice chairman
Frank Cihak, have been convicted of fraud in connection with other
loans by the bank.
</P>
<P>
   Hyman said Stone lied to the grand jury to cover up the plot to
defraud the bank and the insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   The weeklong trial revealed little about the nature of the
underlying fraud investigation of First City.
</P>
<P>
   But Stone's conviction _ and heavy hints by Hyman during the
trial _ raised the likelihood of more indictments from the bank
fraud probe that has spanned most of the decade.
</P>
<P>
   Louise Taylor, who writes about the thoroughbred industry for
the Lexington Herald-Leader, said Alydar's death and the farm's
ultimate bankruptcy have been fodder for the rumor mill for nearly
eight years.
</P>
<P>
   But, Taylor said, the trial shed no new light on the
circumstances surrounding Alydar's injury _ save Highley's claim it
was he who found the injured stallion.
</P>
<P>
   Veterinarians and the insurance adjuster who OK'd payment on the
$36 million insurance claim testified the break in Alydar's leg was
probably accidental.
</P>
<P>
   Although there was no known eyewitness, circumstantial evidence
led the vets and adjuster to speculate that the temperamental
stallion kicked the stall door, breaking a rusty bolt that held the
door securely against the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Alydar, who ran a close second to Affirmed in the 1978 Triple
Crown races, broke his right, hind cannon bone when his leg became
lodged in the resulting gap, the witnesses testified.
</P>
<P>
   In a prepared statement after the verdict, defense attorney
Chris Goldsmith contended his client was railroaded by an obsessive
prosecutor who has carried on the First City probe for years.
</P>
<P>
   But jurors overwhelmingly blamed Stone's conviction on
Goldsmith.
</P>
<P>
   Juror Ted Perez said Stone seemed like a hard-working man who
would not be involved in any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we didn't know anything about him from his lawyer,'' Perez
said. ``We didn't hear from any character witnesses, we had nothing
to go on from the defense.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
