<HEADLINE>
OUTBREAK OF TAINTED TEXAS OYSTERS BREAKS NATIONAL RECORD 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Calif., Colo., Fla., La., N.M. and Tenn.) 
 
By CINDY HORSWELL 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GALVESTON, Texas _ Health officials Thursday continued adding up
reports of people sickened from eating raw Galveston Bay oysters as
the total vaulted past the national record with no sign of slowing.
</P>
<P>
   The people who make their living harvesting the popular
shellfish from the bay were also counting as they watched their
financial losses mount.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be a lot of people out of work,'' said Lisa Halili,
chairwoman of the Gulf Oyster Industry Council.
</P>
<P>
   As of Thursday, health officials had recorded 245 people who
have become ill after eating raw Galveston Bay oysters contaminated
with the bacterium ``Vibrio parahaemolyticus.'' That total far
outdistanced the previous record for an outbreak of the illness,
which was recorded last summer when 208 people became ill and one
died from eating raw oysters in Washington state.
</P>
<P>
   That outbreak started in mid-July and the oyster harvesting ban
there did not end until Sept. 15.
</P>
<P>
   The number of reported illnesses from the tainted Galveston Bay
oysters continues to mount at a fast clip, said Kirk Wiles,
spokesman for the Texas Department of Health's seafood safety
division.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's total reflected an increase of 58 new cases from the
previous day, when the total had jumped by 59 cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas oysters have been recalled and the oyster houses have
voluntarily quit harvesting as of June 25,'' Wiles said. ``We have
also worked hard to alert consumers that Galveston Bay oysters
should only be eaten after being thoroughly cooked because that
kills the bacteria. We hope the number of reported cases begins to
drop soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the reported cases, 206 were recorded in Texas, 36 in Florida
and 3 in Tennessee. Restaurants that had received shipments of the
oysters also were alerted in California, Colorado, Louisiana and
New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Although Galveston Bay oystermen voluntarily stopped harvesting
from the 43 oyster beds where harvesting goes on this time of year,
some wholesalers Thursday expressed concern about the accuracy of
some illness reports. They noted that people can learn the symptoms
from media reports and then call a hot-line number that has been
set up to take reports of illness.
</P>
<P>
   Symptoms of ``Vibrio parahaemolyticus'' include diarrhea,
abdominal cramps, nausea, fever, vomiting and headache. The illness
usually lasts up to seven days and is rarely fatal unless the
victim has an immune disorder or liver problems.
</P>
<P>
   People who have suffered such symptoms within a day or two of
eating raw oysters from the bay have been asked to call state
officials at 1-888-883-9997.
</P>
<P>
   ``We harvest and sell about a half-million oysters a day by
ourselves alone. About 90 percent of the product is eaten raw,''
said Halili, 37, of San Leon. ``If this product is so unhealthy, we
should be seeing a lot more sickness than this.''
</P>
<P>
   About 22 of the reported cases have been confirmed through stool
samples and the rest through responses on an epidemiological
questionnaire, state health officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Halili and her husband, John, who operate Johnny's Oyster and
Shrimp, worry about how the Texas oyster industry will recover.
</P>
<P>
   ``My bills are $6,000 to $8,000 a month,'' she said. ``My
husband and I can't go anywhere else and recoup that. I'm loaning
money to my captains, deckhands, packagers and processors to help
them through the crisis, but I can't continue this forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Oysters from the 43 Galveston Bay beds are being tested, as is
water from those sites. The oystermen have voluntarily suspended
harvesting until test results are back.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Nelson, 62, a wholesaler from Smith Point, said much of the
difficulty lies in not knowing why the bacterium has shown up in
such large amounts recently and how long the problem will last.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what's killing us,'' he said. ``The longer it goes, the
worse it gets. We've been down five or six days now and our
employees can't hang around indefinitely. Most of us live from pay
day to pay day.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gone through floods and oil spills and everything
else,'' Nelson said ``Nothing's been this bad, because we knew what
to expect. We fear we're going to lose the confidence of the
consumer for our product over this.''
</P>
<P>
   State health officials stressed that this bacterium occurs
naturally in even the cleanest bodies of water and tends to
increase in numbers during warm summer months.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does not come from pollution or sewage runoff; it's just
there,'' said Wiles. ``We need to research what is causing the
bacteria levels to increase to the extent that they never have
before.''
</P>
<P>
   While some speculate that the increase is linked to the hot, dry
weather, Wiles said he has seen other long, hot summers during his
22 years working for the state but never had seen this happen.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Sample of the U.S. Food and Drug Administration said
scientists are still seeking the cause of the Northwest Pacific
outbreak.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the regulators and experts looked at it. The basic
assumption in the end was, we need to know more about this
organism,'' Sample said. ``But the (Centers for Disease Control)
report thought it was related to the hot temperatures. El Nino had
caused our ocean temperature to rise two or three degrees above
normal.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Texas oyster fishermen worry about what the future
holds for Galveston Bay, which plays the lead role in the state's
oyster industry.
</P>
<P>
   The bay supplies 87 percent of all the oysters harvested each
year in Texas, producing 3.4 million pounds of meat worth $8.7
million in 1997, said Page Campbell, a commercial fishery
specialist with the state Parks and Wildlife Department.
</P>
<P>
   State officials say more than half the oysters eaten raw in the
nation come from Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the oyster houses understand that we want to solve the
problem together and they have done the responsible thing by
closing the bay even though its disrupting their economic
livelihood,'' Wiles said.
</P>
<P>
   He hopes tests done on samples of meat, water and soil taken
from the bay will provide answers to the question of how bad the
problem is and how long it will last. He said the test results
should be completed by next week.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
