<SLUG> BC-WOMEN'S-OPEN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Davies uses 68 to tie for lead
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KOHLER, Wis. _ Expecting to be packing her suitcase by later
today, Laura Davies has been forced to revise her plans. Somehow
pulling a 3-under-par 68 out of the no-confidence funk that has
been her season, Davies Thursday assumed a share of the first-round
lead with Kim Williams in the U.S. Women's Open at the Blackwolf
Run Golf Course.
</P>
<P>
   One shot off the lead at 69 were 20-year-old Se Ri Pak of Korea,
Leslie Spalding and Dinah Shore winner Pat Hurst.
</P>
<P>
   Albany's Nancy Lopez, trying to win her first U.S. Women's Open
after 48 LPGA wins, shot a 6-over 77. Defending champion Alison
Nicholas of England opened with a 78.
</P>
<P>
   Play was suspended at 8:44 p.m. CDT with two threesomes
remaining on the course.
</P>
<P>
   Although Davies, with missed five cuts this year and a mostly
frozen putter, has not declared herself cured, at least for a day
the 1987 Open champion combined her typical power with some
atypical putting prowess.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel pretty much the same way,'' said Davies, who leads the
LPGA tour in cynicism. ''I am serious. I'm so low on confidence.
The whole thing has just been a downward spiral. . . . .Generally,
I've messed up 90 percent of the rounds of golf I've had this
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Pounding her 3-iron off the tee for drives of up to 260 yards,
Davies hit only two drivers Thursday, but made four birdies and a
bogey, hit 15 greens and 13 of 14 fairways.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a long way to go,'' Davies said, ''and I'm just hoping
I'll be playing all four rounds. I guess I'd have to have a really
bad day now (to miss the cut), wouldn't I?''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, of Bethesda, Md., who has never won an LPGA event but
played in the second-last group last year at Pumpkin Ridge and tied
for 19th, wore a back brace for much of her Thursday round,
suffering from disk problems since January. She had not played in
three weeks and ''I was really doubtful that I would even play
here. I was at home basically laying on the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams would like nothing more than to this week alter the
highlight of her biographical sketch. She's known mostly for
getting hit in the neck by a stray bullet in 1994 while trailing by
a stroke in the Jamie Farr Toledo Classic.
</P>
<P>
   Tied for sixth at 1-under 70 are LPGA leading moneywinner Donna
Andrews, Jacqueline Gallagher-Smith, Barb Mucha, Atlanta winner
Liselotte Neumann and amateur Brenda Corrie Kuehn.
</P>
<P>
   Two-time Open winner Annika Sorenstam of Sweden regrouped after
a triple-bogey on the fifth hole and compiled an even-par 71.
Australian Karrie Webb had a 76, two shots better than Atlanta's
Rosie Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
