</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMENS-NOTES03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lopez quest for title on life support
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheely
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KOHLER, Wisc. _ Nancy Lopez's quest for a U.S. Women's Open
trophy probably won't be satisfied this week at Blackwolf Run. Here
in the land of posh plumbing fixtures, Lopez turned on the faucet
in Thursday's first round and came up dry.
</P>
<P>
   Except for the ball she rinsed on the 12th hole.
</P>
<P>
   It was that kind of a day for the winner of 48 LPGA tournaments
from Albany, Ga. In the tournament she most desperately covets,
Lopez left herself inches from desperation in today's second round.
Following an opening 77 Thursday, Lopez could be fighting to make
the cut.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, Lopez birdied the 18th to both help her round and
build some momentum for today. She battled poor club selection and
missed greens all day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed in myself, but I played the last few holes
really well _ the way I thought I was going to be playing all
day,'' said Lopez, 41. ``The big thing here is hitting greens, and
when you're chipping all day, it's hard to make pars.''
</P>
<P>
   Still optimistic despite her poor start, Lopez said, ``I look
forward to tomorrow. I know there are some birdies out there for
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Sorenstam regroups after triple-bogey
</P>
<P>
   For a while Thursday, Annika Sorenstam didn't like the building
scenario. After trying for a three-peat in the U.S. Women's Open
last year and then failing to make the cut, Sorenstam Thursday
triple-bogeyed the 5th hole and bogeyed the 7th to stand 3-over
after seven holes. After never quite crawling out of the Pumpkin
Ridge rough in 1997, this time she recovered impressively. Birdies
on 8, 11, 16 and 18 allowed an even-par 71 and decent position. Did
thoughts of last year's disaster enter her mind after hitting into
the water on the 5th with a fat 7-iron? ``Yeah, for a few
seconds,'' Sorenstam said. ``But I told myself, 'It's only
Thursday. Let's try and get this behind you and go from here.' I
promised myself I won't give up and I won't. I'm going to keep
grinding and grinding. That was the lesson I learned from last
year.'' ... Meanwhile, the defending champion caught the full
effect of what ailed Sorenstam last year. England's Alison
Nicholas, who beat Lopez by a shot in 1997, could end up joining
her on the cut list. With a back-nine 42, Nicholas opened her
defense with a 7-over 78. ``I mean, I haven't been playing very
well recently, anyway,'' Nicholas said. ``I suppose I just got a
bit tight?'' Asked whether she meant ``tense,'' Nicholas said,
``Whatever word you want to use. You're the journalists.''
</P>
<P>
   Pak has a knack for majors
</P>
<P>
   Korea's Se Ri Pak opened with a 69 Thursday, reconfirming her
ability to perform in the major championships, regardless of what
she has been doing elsewhere. Although Pak, 20, hasn't finished
higher than 26th in the four events since winning the McDonald's
LPGA Championship, a tough course and added pressure inspired her
Thursday to a 69, placing her one shot off the lead.
</P>
<P>
   ''I just feel more comfortable in the big tournaments,'' said
Pak, who bogeyed the 7th hole afer a birdie at the 6th and closed
with 12 straight pars.
</P>
<P>
   Record crowds clog traffic
</P>
<P>
   Traffic jams at TPC Sugarloaf during the BellSouth Classic in
May were nothing compared to the mess Thursday leading into
Blackwolf Run. On a day when a record crowd of 21,000 attended,
cars were backed up five miles from the course on Interstate 43 and
Highway 23 because of delays from moving cars into parking lots.
Attempting to help the jam-up immediately, the USGA dispatched
mowers to clear surrounding pasture areas to accomodate an
additional 1,000 cars. By noon Thursday parking spaces for 15,000
spectators were gone. No players missed tee times due to the
delays, but it made for some anxious moments. ... Patty Schremmer
of Sarasota, Fla., withdrew prior to Thursday's round because of a
freak back injury. Playing in a Jimmy Buffet pro-am in Atlanta
prior to the Women's Open, she apparently was hugged by a playing
partner, causing the injury. ... Sweden's Helen Alfredsson aced
Blackwolf Run's 152-yard 8th hole with an 8-iron.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
