<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 22:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8807 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARINE-JET-CRASH-1STL     07-02 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARINE-JET-CRASH-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGHER-LEVEL LAPSES FOUND IN SKI LIFT CRASH
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs 2nd graf to change `the captain' to `the pilot'; subs 6th
graf to fix typo in Englewood) (bl) 
By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Failures by the Marine Corps and the Air Force to
pass along crucial information cast ``substantial doubt'' on
whether the captain of a plane that struck a ski lift cable in the
Italian Alps in February could be convicted in a court-martial, a
hearing officer found in a report released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But the hearing officer, Lt. Col. Ronald L. Rodgers, said the
pilot of the Marine Corps jet should be tried on the most serious
possible charges in the accident that killed 20 people and caused a
rift between Italy and the United States over prosecution of the
four-man crew.
</P>
<P>
   Rodgers made his recommendations after presiding over hearings
in May and in June, when evidence about the accident was presented.
While his report is advisory, it represents an official
acknowledgment of major lapses of people higher in the chain of
command _ many of whom do not face any charges in connection with
the incident.
</P>
<P>
   Citing ``systemic errors,'' the report detailed numerous
breakdowns in communications within the Marine Corps electronic
warfare squadron to which the plane belonged, within the Air Force
and between those two agencies. It also cited evidence of
``noncriminally negligent pilot behavior.'' The report recommended
a court-martial for the navigator, on a slightly less serious
charge, and no court-martial for two other officers aboard.
</P>
<P>
   The plane, stationed at the Aviano air base as part of the
``Deliberate Guard'' mission over Bosnia, was on a low-altitude
training mission in the Alps flown by Capt. Richard Ashby, 31, of
Mission Viejo, Calif. Next to him in the cockpit was Capt. Joseph
Schweitzer, 30, of Westbury, N.Y., who had no flight controls but
planned the mission and handled navigation aloft.
</P>
<P>
   In the rear cockpit of the plane, an EA-6B Prowler, were Capt.
Chandler Seagraves, 28, of Nineveh, Ind., and Capt. William Raney,
27, of Englewood, Colo. They had no view out the front and only
limited information on the plane's altitude and position.
</P>
<P>
   In March, a Marine Investigation Board recommended charges
against all of them.
</P>
<P>
   But the testimony of Col. Tom Blickensderfer, a board member and
director of operations at the Marine Corps Air Station at Cherry
Point, N.C., where the Prowlers are based, contributed to Rodgers'
conclusions that other factors played a role in the accident.
Blickensderfer said he had ``flown'' a computer-based simulator
over the route as part of the investigation. The terrain, he
testified, would have caused the pilot to see an optical illusion
of greater altitude than was actually the case.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Rodgers said that ``reasonable grounds exist that support
the conclusion that Ashby was overly aggressive in the execution of
this training mission; that he thereafter failed to take
appropriate steps to determine the safety of his altitude in the
mishap valley, and, that those factors were significant causative
factors in the tragedy which resulted.''
</P>
<P>
   He said it was reasonable to argue that ``Captain Ashby placed
himself in the dilemma he confronted.'' Even though the group of
six cables did not appear on his map, he bore down much too fast
and too low to do anything about it, the colonel noted.
</P>
<P>
   Rodgers said Ashby should be charged with involuntary
manslaughter, which carries a penalty of up to 10 years
imprisonment. He recommended that Schweitzer, the navigator, be
charged with negligent homicide, which is punishable by up to three
years. Both should also be charged with dereliction of duty, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The decision rests with Lt. Gen. Peter Pace, commander of Marine
Corps Forces Atlantic in Norfolk, who has authority to determine
what charges, if any, the crew would face at a court-martial.
</P>
<P>
   Ashby's lawyer, Frank Spinner, said, ``they need somebody to go
to trial,'' because of the international sensitivity of the
incident.
</P>
<P>
   Rodgers put some of the blame on the Air Force, which has units
stationed permanently at Aviano and was supposed to provide
information on local flight rules to the Marine squadrons that came
through on six-month rotations.
</P>
<P>
   Among the flaws enumerated by Rodgers were these:
</P>
<P>
   _ The Air Force's 31st Fighter Wing created a ``pilot aid''
intended for mission planning and gave copies to the Marines. But
the most current version at the time of the accident did not
mention a 2,000-foot restriction that had taken effect months
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   _ The squadron's officer in charge of scheduling missions
photocopied information on flights over Italy, including one with
the 2,000-foot restriction. But ``he apparently never digested its
contents, or the importance thereof,'' the colonel said.
</P>
<P>
   _ The agency that prepared detailed charts of northern Italy
used by the Marines, the National Imagery and Mapping Agency,
copied information on aerial obstructions from an Italian chart
drawn on the scale of 1-250,000. But, Colonel Rodgers said, other
maps, not those, mark aerial obstructions.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force received a copy of a map using the scale of
1-500,000, which noted the obstruction, in April 1996, but the 31st
Fighter Wing was unaware of that, the report said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
