<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-HARTFORD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILESTONE NO MATTER TO MARTIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By ALEX YANNIS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CROMWELL, Conn. _ Though he dismissed its significance, Casey
Martin reached another milestone with his golf cart Thursday while
shooting a 71 at the Canon Hartford Open.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who won a court case for the right to use a cart on the
Nike Tour this season and in the U.S. Open two weeks ago, became
the first golfer to ride a cart in a PGA Tour event Thursday
morning. He did it when he rode down the fairway of the 462-yard
10th hole, his starting hole, at the TCP River Highlands course.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who needs a cart because he suffers from a rare vascular
affliction in his right leg, earned a sponsor's exemption for this
tournament, where he attracted Tiger Woods-like galleries even
though his 1-over-par 71 left him seven strokes off the lead after
one round.
</P>
<P>
   He had two birdies, three bogeys and a quick response to
questions about making history on the PGA Tour. ``Never crossed my
mind,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Playing with Hugh Royer III and Iain Steel, Martin made par on
his 462-yard first hole and made his first birdie three holes
later, when he and chipped from the right of the green at the
523-yard 13th hole to within 10 feet and made the putt.
</P>
<P>
   Martin's first bogey came holes later when he gambled and lost.
He attempted to drive the 296-yard 15th, but his drive hit a tree
on the right and dropped into a pile of leaves. He punched out and
his approach landed within 12 feet, but he missed the putt.
</P>
<P>
   His other bogeys came at the 431-yard third and the 443-yard
seventh; his other birdie came at the 574-yard sixth hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't hit the ball well, but I scrambled all day,'' said
Martin, who lives in Eugene, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   The leader, Pete Morgan, is a 35-year-old playing in only his
fourth Tour event since turning pro in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan, who had to qualify for this event on Monday, lives in
Tampa, Fla., and grew up on Cape Cod. He had no bogeys in shooting
a 64, one shot better than Scott Hoch and Kenny Perry, who were
tied for second.
</P>
<P>
   Martin did not have to qualify here, but no matter what he does
here or next week at the Quad City Classic in Coal Valley, Ill.,
where he has been given another sponsor's exemption, he has little
intention of playing many more events on the PGA Tour this season,
according to his father, King Martin, and his manager, Chris
Murray.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needs to get back on the Nike Tour to get enough money to
make the regular tour,'' King Martin said, alluding to his son's
17th-place ranking on a tour in which the top 15 finishers will
graduate to the PGA Tour next year.
</P>
<P>
   Martin has earned $60,401 on the Nike tour, where he has one
victory, the Lakeland Classic, which brought him $40,500.
</P>
<P>
   He can also qualify for the PGA Tour by special temporary
membership if he earns enough money this year to equal the amount
earned last year by the 150th finisher on the official money list.
That amount was $121,273. Martin's PGA Tour earnings this season
are the $34,043 he earned by finishing tied for 23rd in the U.S.
Open last month. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
