</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) DUBLIN -- July 2, 1998 -- PROFILE-KENNEDY-BOS, 7-2 -- ``I
feel I was very fortunate to be in the position to do something
positive, to make a contribution to change,'' says U.S. Ambassador
to Ireland, Jean Kennedy Smith, from her residence in Phoenix Park.
``It gave me terrific satisfaction.'' This Sunday, Ms. Kennedy
Smith, the longest-serving American ambassador to Ireland, will
return to the U.S. after three years. (Frank O'Brien/Boston Globe
Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) DENVER -- July 2, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JULY 5 --
HILDEGARD-MUSIC, 7-2 -- On stage at St. John's Cathedral in Denver,
the 12th-century ``Ordo Virtutum,'' or ``Play of the Virtues'' is
performed by Sequentia, a group renowned for their performance of
medieval music. The ensemble Sequentia, which is based in Cologne,
Germany, and has performed and recorded Hildegard's music for
nearly two decades. (Kevin Moloney/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- July 2, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JULY 5 --
SYMPHONIE-FANTASTIQUE, 7-2, -- Basil Twist's puppets do underwater
dances to Berlioz in the play ``Symphonie Fantastique.'' The play
manipulates objects and light within a 500-gallon tank of water,
one side of which, 30 by 40 inches, is visible to an audience of
about 100. ``Symphonie,'' performed to an old Philadelphia
Orchestra recording led by Eugene Ormandy, has its halting moments
and flashes of extraordinary beauty. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- July 2, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JULY 5 --
CANBY-THEATER-2, 7-2 -- From left, Catherine Kellner, Helen Carey
and Saxon Palmer in the Roundabout Theater Company production of
the play ``You Never Can Tell'' in the Laura Pels Theater. This
Nicholas Martin's revival of George Bernard Shaw's play centers
around a woman, whose treatises on 20th-centry life are the rage in
Madeira; her three children, the rich old husband she abandoned 18
years earlier, and Valentine, the dentist. (Sara Krulwich/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- July 2, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JULY 5 --
CANBY-THEATER-1, 7-2 -- Erika Rolfsrud and Stephen Derosa in Tony
Kushner's one-act play ``Terminating.'' Kushner's play is one of
seven one-act plays in ``Love's Fire,'' the Acting Company
production housed in the Newman Theater at the Joseph Papp Public
Theater. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
