<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLORIDA-FIRES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
35,000 MUST FLEE RAGING FIRES IN FLORIDA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By TERRY BLOUNT 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Surging wildfires Thursday forced 35,000
people from their homes, destroyed scores of buildings and closed
freeways as tourist businesses along the coast tried to salvage
what is normally one of the most lucrative weekends of the summer.
</P>
<P>
   No deaths had been reported because of the fires, which have
been raging in several Florida counties for as long as six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   During the past 48 hours, about 30,000 people were told to leave
their homes in Volusia County _ mostly from Ormond Beach and
Daytona Beach _ and about 5,000 were ordered to leave Brevard
County, county officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if you've ever seen napalm,'' Jerry Lefeniere
told The Associated Press after fleeing his home in Mims. ``The
results of napalm, that's what it looks like out there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Mother Nature has turned the barbecue up high. It's
really cooked out here.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Memorial Day, about 1,900 fires have burned more than 425
square miles. In an average year, Florida fires burn less than half
that.
</P>
<P>
   The blazes have damaged or destroyed at least 96 homes and 57
other buildings statewide, according to The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   At least five firefighters were injured in Brevard County _
three of whom suffered second-degree burns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have 20 mph winds blowing west to east and humidity below
35 percent,'' said Dave Bryon, the Volusia County director of
information. ``That is a deadly combination. It is so dry that
static electricity can start a blaze.''
</P>
<P>
   Record temperatures of 98 degrees to 102 degrees coupled with a
lack of rainfall and windy conditions have caused the fires and the
thick, dark plumes of smoke that have sharply cut visibility.
</P>
<P>
   Roads that normally would be packed with beachgoers were
deserted.
</P>
<P>
   Interstate 95, the main north-south artery along the Florida
coast, is closed for more than 140 miles from Jacksonville to
Tollroad 528 south of Titusville. More than 30,000 cars were
gridlocked while trying to detour to other routes.
</P>
<P>
   The conditions forced the postponement of the Pepsi 400 at
Daytona International Speedway, an unprecedented occurrence in
NASCAR's 50-year history. The race was to be run Saturday night but
has been rescheduled for Oct. 17.
</P>
<P>
   Many fireworks displays have been canceled for fear they might
spark more blazes.
</P>
<P>
   Daytona Beach is covered with a veil of smoke that has reduced
visibility to less than 100 yards in some locations. The Indigo
Lakes subdivision near the speedway is under mandatory evacuation,
as is most of Ormond Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of shelters have been opened at schools and churches to
house families who have been forced to leave their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Florida Gov. Lawton Chiles canceled a vacation trip to North
Carolina so he could tour the area of the blaze and appeal for
help.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the worst thing I've ever seen,'' Chiles said in Volusia
County. ``It has gone well beyond Black Friday (the 1985 wildfires
that claimed 200 Florida homes). Florida has never had a situation
like this. It's time for everyone to come together to see what they
can do to help.''
</P>
<P>
   The Florida National Guard has been fully mobilized to join the
emergency workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen anything like it,'' said National Guard
trooper Chad Jenkins. ``The fire is everywhere. It's all around us.
In some places, the flames are more than 100 feet high.''
</P>
<P>
   Airplanes are dropping thousands of gallons of fire retardant,
and helicopters drop water wherever new blazes begin. Hundreds of
bulldozers have been brought in to try to build walls to halt the
flames, but high winds have helped the inferno jump barriers and
fire breaks.
</P>
<P>
   Embers blown from the trees start new fires faster than the
workers can put them out.
</P>
<P>
   The wildfires that are burning have five main areas _ the west
side of Ormond Beach, south and west of Daytona Beach, south of
Kissimmee in Osceola County, and west of Melbourne in Brevard
County.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying our best to protect homes,'' Chiles said.
``That's our top priority. But we need people to leave the
evacuation areas as quickly as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   And many fear the worst is yet to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is anybody's guess what is going to happen the next few
days,'' said Chuck Williams, a lieutenant for the Florida Highway
Patrol.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
