<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 22:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8813 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PLAYBOY-AZR &LR;      07-02 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLAYBOY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHERIFF ARPAIJO CAN'T DENY JAIL INMATES `PLAYBOY,' `HUSTLER,' COURT
SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSIE STECKNER AND DENNIS   
 Wagner  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Coffee and smokes are still out. But Miss July may be
back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playboy, Hustler'' and other publications showing nudity can't
be kept out of jail inmates' hands by Sheriff Joe Arpaio, according
to a ruling Thursday by the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in
San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   A three-judge panel said a ban on such publications could be
used to keep inmates from not only ``Playboy,''but ``National
Geographic,'' art books and medical journals as well.
</P>
<P>
   That, the panel said, would violate inmates' First Amendment
rights.
</P>
<P>
   Arpaio's ban was challenged in 1996 by inmate Jonathan Mauro,
who wanted a ``Playboy'' subscription delivered to his cell. Mauro
is no longer in the county jail.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro's attorney, Nicholas Hentoff, said Thursday, ``They struck
down the policy _ the whole policy _ as it applies to every inmate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally, a three-judge panel . . . has told Sheriff Arpaio in
no uncertain terms that he can't do anything he wants to his
inmates. There is a rule of law.''
</P>
<P>
   But Arpaio on Thursday vowed to fight the ruling, and to appeal
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not going to get ``Playboy''tomorrow,'' he said. ``It's
as simple as that, unless you get out of jail and you go to the
drugstore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not giving back the `Playboy' and ``Hustler.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Jail officials instituted the ban about five years ago in the
name of security.
</P>
<P>
   They argue that magazines like ``Playboy'' are bartered for
goods and contraband, and lead to conflicts among inmates. They're
also used by inmates to intimidate and sexually harass female
employees. Further, the officials say, such pictures should not be
seen by sex offenders, who are working to rehabilitate themselves.
</P>
<P>
   When Mauro challenged the ban, Arpaio said he wouldn't back
down.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can sue all he wants, and I'll tell you what: ``Playboy''
is gone, and it's going to be gone,'' he said then.
</P>
<P>
   In March, U.S. District Judge Robert Broomfield sided with the
sheriff.
</P>
<P>
   In his ruling, Broomfield said that preventing fights and
harassment relate to prison security, and that ``the Supreme Court
has held that prison security is a legitimate, and indeed
compelling, penological interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Broomfield ruled that there was a ``logical connection'' between
banning sexually explicit materials and preventing problems in
jail.
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday, the 9th Circuit overturned that ruling.
</P>
<P>
   The panel noted that, during the legal battle, jail officials
produced affidavits and depositions from jail employees to back up
their arguments.
</P>
<P>
   In one exchange, Hentoff showed Deputy Chief Larry Wendt a
Michelangelo painting of a nude Christ. Would the photo, Hentoff
asked, impact jail security?
</P>
<P>
   Wendt said it could. He offered a scenario in which an inmate
who is an atheist might remark to a Christian inmate, ``look at the
size of the genitals on Jesus Christ. That could incite a fight
between the inmates.''
</P>
<P>
   But Wendt also acknowledged that a picture of a clothed Christ,
which isn't banned, could also spark problems between inmates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We question whether all materials depicting nudity are
`reasonably likely' to be the cause of violence or a tool of
harassment,'' Judge Betty Fletcher said.
</P>
<P>
   The county, Fletcher wrote, simply didn't prove ``that such a
far reaching prohibition is `reasonably related' to legitimate
penological interests.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Regardless of whether the county's policy would be
constitutional if applied to ban ``Playboy'' magazine, it is not
constitutional to ban all depictions of frontal nudity.''
</P>
<P>
   Hentoff said he realizes some will question why a sheriff can't
deny girlie magazines to jail inmates. But the challenge was about
First Amendment rights, not about ``Playboy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Struck, the attorney representing the county, said he will
ask for a re-hearing before the 9th Circuit.
</P>
<P>
   He said the panel ``missed the mark'' in analyzing whether there
is a legitimate need to ban materials showing frontal nudity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just Sheriff Joe being bullheaded,'' he said. ``A
very well respected district court judge agreed that this was
constitutional.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the panel's ruling that the ban was ``overbroad,'' Struck
said: ``The fact is the plaintiff doesn't want to read ``Art and
Auction'' magazine. He wants to read ``Playboy.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Susie Steckner can be reached at 444-2413 or at
susie.steckner(at)pni.com via e-mail. Dennis Wagner can be reached
at 444-8874 or at dennis.wagner(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
