<P>
   (NYT18) ORMAND BEACH, Fla. -- July 2, 1998 -- FLA-FIRES-2, 7-2
-- Mark Rapp of the U.S. Forest Service watches a wildfire burn out
of control near Ormand Beach. Northeast Florida felt like a war
zone Thursday as wildfires consumed brush and buildings with no
hindrance from nature and thousands of residents emptied towns
threatened by the onrushing flames. (Doug Engle/Ocala Star-Banner
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) TOLEDO, Ohio -- July 2, 1998 -- GM-STRIKE, 7-2 -- Jim
Yark, an Oldsmobile dealer, in the back lot behind his showroom in
Toledo. Strikes against GM have greatly depleted his inventory.
``What you see is what you get,'' says Yark, who calculates he has
only enough for another three weeks of sales. (Peter Yates/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) DEERFIELD BEACH, Fla. -- July 2, 1998 --
CHICKEN-SOUP-PUBLISHER, 7-2 -- The quirky best seller, ``Chicken
Soup for the Soul,'' was rejected by 33 publishers before it was
picked up in 1992 by Peter Vegso, president of Health
Communications. ``I didn't know I was the 34th publisher and I
really didn't care,'' he says. Today, more than 30 million copies
of the series have been sold. (Susan Greenwood/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) TALKEETNA, Alaska -- July 2, 1998 --
CLIMBING-MT-MCKINLEY, 7-2 -- Paul Roderrick, right, a bush pilot in
Talkeetna, helps Rick Studley of Fairbanks check his gear Wednesday
before flying to a base camp. Mount McKinley, at 20,320 feet the
highest peak in North America, has claimed 118 lives over the last
65 years. But it is more popular than ever. (Al Grillo/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) GREAT BRINGTON, England -- July 2, 1998 --
DIANA-MUSEUM-2, 7-2 -- Most of the visitors to Great Brington,
where Earl Spencer, Diana's brother, has opened the Diana museum,
were fervent admirers of the princess. Until the end of August,
members of the public who have paid $16 apiece and ordered their
tickets in advance will be allowed to tour the earl's new Diana
museum, which rehearses in vivid, sobering detail the now-familiar
stages of her brief life. (Jonathan Player/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) GREAT BRINGTON, England -- July 2, 1998 --
DIANA-MUSEUM-1, 7-2 -- Could crass money-making be the reason for
the Princess Diana museum, opened by Diana's brother, Earl Spencer?
``I'm embarrassed to be here,'' says Lindy Jamieson, a secretary
who came, she says, only because a friend begged for her company
and gave her a free ticket. ``I know Earl Spencer keeps saying,
'Fancy making money out of her death,' but of course he's done it
to make money.'' (Jonathan Player/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. -- July 2, 1998 -- FLA-FIRES, 7-2 --
Brush fires burning near Interstate 4 west of Daytona Beach on
Thursday. Smoke from fires closed nearby Interstate 95 from
Titusville to Jacksonville. (David Mills/Lakeland Ledger Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEWPORT, R.I. -- July 2, 1998 -- RI-LAWN-TENNIS, 7-2 --
A little taste of Wimbeldon: The Newport Casino Lawn Tennis Club
welcomes the public to its grass courts. ``Even though people are
enthralled by being out there, it's more demanding to play on,''
says Bill Rompf, the club's director of tennis and one of the
country's best coaches. ``You've got to move your feet.'' (Evan
Richman/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
