<HEADER>
A8821 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUTFUND-BENCHMARKS-$A     07-02 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-BENCHMARKS-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINDING A GAUGE CAN BE TRICKY  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 5) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ill., N.J.)   (af)  
 By NOELLE KNOX   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   So, how's your portfolio doing? Good question. The fact is that
you won't have a clue if you measure your mutual fund's performance
against the wrong benchmark. Doing so can lead to Godzilla-size
mistakes, like holding onto losers or selling winners.
</P>
<P>
   The wrong index can be easy to find. Every day, market watchers
talk about the the Dow Jones industrial average or the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500-stock index, leading many to think those are the
benchmarks to beat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody tends to compare their fund to the S&AMP;P 500, and
oftentimes that's a bad choice,'' said James R. Raker, senior
research analyst at Morningstar Inc., the financial publisher in
Chicago. That is because most funds aren't trying to match or beat
those indexes.
</P>
<P>
   For example, to best assess the performance of a fund like
Pennsylvania Mutual, which invests in beaten-down small-company
stocks, investors should look at the Standard &AMP; Poor's 600 Small
Cap/Barra Value index, or the Wilshire Small Cap Value index. Both
take market capitalization into account, as well as valuations.
</P>
<P>
   How to find these style- and capitalization-based indexes? On
the World Wide Web, try investorhome.com, which has links to the
sites of companies that publish various indexes, like Standard &AMP;
Poor's or Wilshire Associates.
</P>
<P>
   A key to determining the best benchmark is a little number
called R-squared, which tells you how closely a fund tracks an
index. If you have invested in funds through a brokerage firm, it
should be able to give you this number, which is between 0 and 100.
And Morningstar publishes a ``best fit'' index for funds along with
the R-squared on the Internet (www.morningstar.net). The rule of
thumb is that a fund with an R-squared of 75 or more in relation to
an index is a reasonably good fit.
</P>
<P>
   Using any index, of course, is far from perfect. Most important,
indexes don't carry the expense ratios or brokerage costs that a
fund does, so its returns are likely to be higher than a fund's.
</P>
<P>
   This leads to a second kind of benchmarking: comparing a fund to
its so-called peer group of similarly managed funds. The advantage
of this link is that an investor can weigh a fund's performance
against real alternatives, not hypothetical returns. (After all, a
fund investor can't buy the S&AMP;P 500 index, only a fund that aims to
mimic it.)
</P>
<P>
   But how to choose the right peer group for your fund?
</P>
<P>
   Lipper Analytical Services in Summit, N.J., pegs a fund to a
category _ capital appreciation, growth and income, or equity
income, for example _ based on the fund's objective as stated in
its prospectus. That seems fair enough: judging a fund by what it
says it will do.
</P>
<P>
   Morningstar also groups funds by objective, but prefers to label
a fund by what is actually in its portfolio. The company determines
whether a fund's stocks are either value or growth in nature and
measures their market capitalizations. It then pegs a fund as, say,
mid-cap value, or large-cap growth, or a blend. Such a benchmark
essentially judges a fund by what it buys.
</P>
<P>
   Each system has its critics. Using a fund prospectus as a guide,
as Lipper's objectives do, has a nice official quality to it, but
fund managers often ignore what lawyers have committed to print.
And categories can be very broad.
</P>
<P>
   The Morningstar approach presents a problem, too. Fund managers
often switch from small to midsize companies, or from value to
growth stocks, based on where they see the best future returns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because the markets are always changing, the funds can move
from one category to another when the underlying investment
philosophy hasn't changed,'' said Susan Belden, Editor of the
No-Load Fund Analyst, an investing newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   A bigger problem in looking at peer groups is called
survivorship bias. Because weak funds tend to go out of business or
merge, the surviving funds tend to be the strongest performers,
which leads to a tough comparison.
</P>
<P>
   ``The longer the time period you look at, the larger the
survivorship bias,'' Raker said. ``You just have to keep that in
the back of your mind.''
</P>
<P>
   One solution to all of this is fairly simple: Use all the
benchmarks, but emphasize peer comparisons for shorter-term results
and specialized indexes for longer-term performance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-98 2222EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
