<HEADER>
A8824 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUTFUND-LIFESTYLE-ART     07-02 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-LIFESTYLE-ART-2TAKES-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO CROWD FOR ONE-STOP SHOPPING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Ill., Mass., N.Y.)   (ART ADV: Graphic will be sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 5)  
 (af)  
 By ABBY SCHULTZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When mutual fund companies started pushing so-called lifestyle
and life-cycle funds, they seemed like sure-fire hits: single funds
that were meant to simplify the decision-making process for
befuddled investors.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, these funds would plunk an investor into a
portfolio with a mix of stocks, bonds and cash tailor-made to his
investing time horizon, eliminating the need to concern himself
with complicated issues like risk or asset allocation.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that investors, by and large, haven't warmed up
to the idea. Since marketing campaigns began in earnest in 1995,
lifestyle and life-cycle funds have grown to just over $10 billion
in assets, from a base of $462 million, a gain that includes market
appreciation for the 70 such funds tracked by Morningstar.
</P>
<P>
   That means that the entire category is still smaller than a
single good-sized index fund _ from a marketing perspective a
pretty dismal total, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will never catch on with the kind of asset growth that a
lot of fund companies had hoped for,'' said Eli E. Neusner, a
senior consultant at Spectrem Group in San Francisco, a financial
services consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, fund watchers can chalk up at least two life-cycle
casualties. Oppenheimer Funds received shareholder approval in June
to close the Oppenheimer Lifespan series of three funds and to roll
the assets into other funds.
</P>
<P>
   And the board of directors of tiny Lifecycle Mutual Funds, which
runs four life-cycle funds with less than $10 million in assets,
plans to seek shareholder approval this summer to liquidate its
family of funds.
</P>
<P>
   Life-cycle and lifestyle funds both aim to provide one-stop
shopping for investors saving for retirement, but in different
ways. The industry often uses the names interchangeably but what
Morningstar defines as life-cycle funds are essentially dressed-up
balanced funds, created to give investors an appropriate mix of
stocks, bonds and cash for their age.
</P>
<P>
   A 25-year-old single man, for example, might choose an
aggressive lifestyle fund that allocates more dollars to stocks
than to bonds or cash. A 55-year-old woman might want a more
conservative fund that leans more toward bonds and cash.
</P>
<P>
   Lifestyle funds, which Morningstar calls target retirement
funds, emphasize the projected retirement date of the investor, so
there usually is a year in the fund's name, like Fidelity Freedom
2030. The asset mix starts aggressively and becomes more
conservative as the fund nears its target date. Fidelity Freedom
2030, for example, now has a target stock allocation of about 85
percent, while Fidelity Freedom 2010 aims for 64 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Some say the idea of life-cycle and lifestyle funds is poorly
conceived. ``They are a one-size-fits-all formula that doesn't
necessarily fit everyone,'' said Alice Lowenstein, associate editor
at Morningstar Mutual Funds in Chicago. ``Many investors would
prefer to take care of the asset allocation on their own.''
</P>
<P>
   Others point to a variety of factors for the lack of popularity.
One detriment to asset growth, for example, is a mismatch between
the funds' objectives and the companies' marketing strategies. The
BT Investment Lifecycle series of funds offered by the Bankers
Trust Corp., for example, has just $314 million in assets; the
funds were started five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   John Huttlin, vice president of funds marketing, says that the
funds were designed for retirement investors, but that the firm's
401(k) business isn't nearly as strong as that of competitors like
the Vanguard Group or T. Rowe Price. ``Our asset growth has not
been as successful as other providers,'' Huttlin said.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, there is also a lack of support from brokers and
financial advisers, who normally are paid handsomely for the
asset-allocation services that life-cycle funds purport to provide
free. If a broker puts a client into one of these funds, where
assets are already allocated, the client might well ask why he or
she is paying a 5 percent load for the broker's services.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Oppenheimer, a unit of the Massachusetts Mutual Life Insurance
Co., found that to be the case after it inherited the load-bearing
Lifespan series when Massachusetts Mutual bought Connecticut Mutual
Life Insurance Co. in 1996, said Ellen Schoenfeld, product manager
at Oppenheimer. Assets in the funds have grown to only $168.5
million from $103 million at the end of 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The bull market has also worked against the conservative
strategies of many of these funds. BT Investment Lifecycle Long
Range, for example, had less than half its assets in stocks at the
end of May, and 40 percent in cash, according to Morningstar. And
that fund is the most aggressive of the Bankers Trust life-cycle
series.
</P>
<P>
   The funds are intended for people who are planning for
retirement, Huttlin noted. ``People are buying these funds because
they are balanced funds, and we have conservative 401(k)
participants,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem for lifestyle and life-cycle funds is that for
products intended to simplify investors' lives, their concept is
fairly complex for the average investor to understand.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a confusing sale,'' said Neusner at Spectrem Group.
``It's hard enough to grasp the concept of asset allocation and
portfolio management and what constitutes an ideal portfolio. Then
if you are going to try and push lifestyle funds on them _ it's
just an issue of the message getting fuzzier.''
</P>
<P>
   Performance hasn't been a strong suit for either fund category.
Kathleen Hartman, a Morningstar analyst, looked at the asset mixes
of both lifestyle and life-cycle funds and created blended indexes
to match them against. The average life-cycle fund posted
three-year annualized returns of 17.6 percent through June 30,
versus 18.5 percent for the index.
</P>
<P>
   The average lifestyle, or target retirement, fund returned an
annualized 18.2 percent, versus 21.1 percent for the benchmark.
</P>
<P>
   Not every fund family is parched for lifestyle and life-cycle
assets. The Vanguard Group has had the most success, garnering $4.6
billion in its Life Strategy series since the funds began in
September 1994. Part of this has to do with the sheer size of
Vanguard. Its phone representatives are trained to guide the
investor to the correct mix of assets for their specific needs,
said Shelton S. Unger, a principal at Vanguard. ``These funds are a
natural for us,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the limited success, investors shouldn't expect
lifestyle or life-cycle funds to go away. Nearly every company that
is putting together a 401(k) plan or adjusting an existing plan
asks providers if they offer lifestyle funds, even if they don't
include them in the final plan, said Robert A. Rudell, president of
Scudder Kemper Retirement Services. Kemper offers the Kemper
Horizon lifestyle funds.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of last year, Morgan Stanley Asset Management started
a series of lifestyle funds in the ``fund of funds'' category _ a
fund that invests in existing mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   Ruth Hughes Guden, a principal at Morgan Stanley Asset
Management, agreed that many 401(k) plans did not adequately
explain how lifestyle funds should be used. But because all 401(k)
participants don't have personal advisers, she said, these funds
fill a niche.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would argue,'' she said, ``that there are a lot of people
who we are empowering to make an important decision that they know
little or nothing about.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-98 2225EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980702.0454 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 22:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8826 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARKET-WATCH-ART-$ADV     07-02 0610
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-WATCH-ART-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EASY LOANS TODAY, BAD LOANS TOMORROW?  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 5) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Mo., Ohio)   (af)  
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Will today's easy-money atmosphere at American banks
lead to hard times tomorrow?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, if the past is prologue. Whenever lenders go from tough
guys to E-Z Credit ``R'' Us, loan losses are almost inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   With the economy perking, lenders are the life of the party.
``Banks always manage for the up part of the cycle, not the whole
cycle,'' said Charles Peabody, bank analyst at Mitchell Securities
in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Bank-stock bulls seem to think the industry is no longer
cyclical. As a result, shares are trading at historic premiums to
book value. The Philadelphia Stock Exchange bank index _ composed
of 24 of the nation's largest money center and regional banks _ is
up 16 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last twelve months, the index has gained 33 percent,
beating the 27 percent rise of the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock
index. But a letter that the Federal Reserve Board sent to the
nation's commercial banks last month indicates that in this regard,
at least, the Fed is not ready to toss traditional standards into
history's ashcan.
</P>
<P>
   The letter, written by Richard Spillenkothen, director of
banking supervision, isn't alarmist. But because it details the
results of an extensive Fed review of bank asset quality and credit
standards, it makes surprisingly interesting reading.
</P>
<P>
   In comparing loans made in 1995 with those made last year, the
Fed found that intense competition for loan customers had led to a
significant relaxation of lending standards. That hasn't resulted
in ugly problems, the Fed said, because of the robust economy _ a
caveat made more pointed by reports last week that manufacturing
activity had slowed in June for the first time in almost two years.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, ugly may come sooner, not later, if some of the lending
practices identified by the Fed are commonplace. Only 20 percent to
30 percent of the several hundred loans reviewed showed any attempt
by lenders to project how a borrower might perform in an economic
downturn.
</P>
<P>
   In nearly half the loans, approval documents did not describe
key financial covenants _ thresholds in financial performance that
a borrower must meet _ that might trigger protective action by a
bank before a loan goes belly-up. ``Management may be inadequately
informed as to the risks'' associated with loans, the Fed wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Another concern was the rapid growth in loans to real estate
investment trusts. Although these loans are now sound, the Fed
warned that they might represent concentrated credit risk at banks.
</P>
<P>
   Singling out REITs, Peabody said, may be a concession to Fed
members worried that rocketing real estate prices are one of the
wealth effects of an overheated stock market. He thinks a schism
may be developing inside the Fed.
</P>
<P>
   In May's Open Market Committee meeting, William Poole, president
of the St. Louis Fed, and Jerry Jordan, president of the Cleveland
bank, dissented from the decision to leave interest rates
unchanged. Arguing for a tighter monetary policy, Jordan cited
asset price inflation as a main concern.
</P>
<P>
   Peabody finds this intriguing, because schisms within the Fed
are unusual. There was a similar divergence on policy between
regional Fed banks and their Washington counterparts in 1928. The
regional members wanted to raise rates, Washington did not.
</P>
<P>
   The split made headlines in March 1929, giving a jolt to stock
prices. They recovered, but what happened later that year is, as
they say, history.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
