<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GAS-TAX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASSEMBLY'S FAILS TO REPEAL GAS TAX ON STATE'S POWER COMPANIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Just as New York begins forcing electric power
plants to compete with each other for business, experts say that
plants in the state will be put at a disadvantage against
competitors in other states because of the state Assembly's failure
to act on a little-noticed bill in the final days of the 1998
session.
</P>
<P>
   The bill _ which was supported by business groups,
environmentalists and a bipartisan group of lawmakers _ would have
repealed a New York tax on out-of-state purchases of natural gas,
the fuel used in most of the plants that supply the state's
electricity. The repeal bill passed the state Senate but never came
to a vote in the Assembly, so the tax will remain in effect at
least until next year.
</P>
<P>
   The tax is structured so that the owners of New York's power
plants usually have not had to pay it. But changes in the industry
are about to take away that protection, forcing gas-fired plants in
the state to begin paying the tax.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the tax say it will give an advantage to power
companies in other states that want to break into New York's newly
competitive market, and to plants that burn coal, which pollute far
more than those that burn gas.
</P>
<P>
   According to legislators, lobbyists and Assembly staff members
who tracked the bill, there was no opposition to it and there were
no disagreements over wording. They say it seems to have died of
neglect.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was so frustrating to us,'' said Carol Murphy, executive
director of Independent Power Producers of New York, a lobbying
group for the state's nonutility power producers, ``because we have
a problem that's happening right now that needed to be dealt with,
and nobody was against this bill, and yet nothing happened.''
</P>
<P>
   After Gov. George Pataki's broad budget vetoes in April,
Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver signaled that he would not allow
passage of any bills that might be considered budget-related, but
people close to the speaker said it was not clear if that category
included the gas tax bill, or if the measure simply fell through
the cracks.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Lynch, the chief spokeswoman for Silver, said she was
not sure why the bill did not come to a vote.
</P>
<P>
   Each year, the Legislature waits until the final days of the
session to take up hundreds of bills. Custom and legislative rules
dictate that by then, nearly everything must go through one of a
handful of committees that are tightly controlled by the leadership
of each house, before reaching the full house for a vote. Lawmakers
say it is not humanly possible for them and their staffs, in those
frenzied days, to get to each bill, and thus many are allowed to
die without a vote.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1991, the state has taxed natural gas purchases from other
states at 4.25 percent. The tax generates $18 million a year,
little more than a rounding error in the state's $35 billion-a-year
general fund.
</P>
<P>
   The tax law exempted the state's giant regional utilities, which
own most of the major gas-fired power plants and produce most of
the state's electricity.
</P>
<P>
   But New York, like many states, is reshaping the power industry,
and one of the first steps will be to force the utilities to sell
their power plants. The first round of sales is scheduled for this
month. Once those plants are sold, their gas purchases will no
longer be exempt from the tax because they will no longer be
utility-owned.
</P>
<P>
   Independent power producers _ plant owners that do not directly
serve customers, but sell their power to the utilities _ pay the
tax. But the law provides that the utilities reimburse the
independent producers for the tax and pass the cost on to
customers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
