<SLUG> BC-NASI-DOWNGRADE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDICAL `SEED' MAKERS' STOCKS CROPPED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEN SULLIVAN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Shares in medical equipment specialist North
American Scientific Instruments Inc. and its main competitor
plunged on concern that supply of their products will soon outweigh
demand.
</P>
<P>
   North American shares on Thursday lost a quarter of their value,
dropping $4.75 to close at $14.25. More than 346,000 shares traded
hands, or five times the issue's six-month average trading volume.
Shares in Norcross, Ga.-based Theragenics Corp. lost nearly 36
percent, closing at $14.81, on eight times its average trading
volume.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies make implantable radioactive pellets, known as
``seeds,'' that are used as an alternative to surgery, chemotherapy
and traditional radiation therapy in treating prostate cancer.
Until recently, supply of the difficult-to-manufacture seeds has
been tight, with the companies able to sell as many pellets as they
could make.
</P>
<P>
   But with production at the companies ramping up and several new
players apparently poised to enter the market, analyst Parice
Halbert at Dain Rauscher Wessels downgraded North American on
Thursday to ``neutral'' from ``strong buy'' and downgraded
Theragenics to ``neutral'' from ``buy.''
</P>
<P>
   North American shares have lost more than half their value since
hitting a six-month high of $30.50 in mid-May.
</P>
<P>
   Two other analysts covering North American, meanwhile, stood by
their endorsement of the company's shares and said Thursday's drop
created a buying opportunity for investors.
</P>
<P>
   Justin Vaicek at Cruttenden Roth Inc. said the $100
million-a-year market for the seeds will likely grow to between
$300 million and $400 million in the next few years as knowledge of
the treatment, known as brachytherapy, spreads. Because there is a
backlog of orders for seeds, manufacturers have not aggressively
pursued new customers, he said. That will change once the product
becomes more plentiful, Vaicek believes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The number of (brachytherapy) procedures will ramp up in
accordance with supply,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Ryan Rauch at CIBC Oppenheimer said that because fewer
than 50 percent of oncology surgeons are currently trained to
perform brachytherapy, there are still ``huge growth cycles'' left
for the seed market as more physicians learn how to use them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brachytherapy is still in the initial stages,'' Rauch said.
</P>
<P>
   CIBC Oppenheimer has a ``strong buy'' rating on North American
shares while Cruttenden Roth has given the issue a ``buy'' rating.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-98 2230EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
