<HEADLINE>
STATE SUPREME COURT JUSTICE UPHOLDS CRACKDOWN ON TAXIS 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By ANDY NEWMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A State Supreme Court justice in Manhattan upheld the
Giuliani administration's crackdown on the taxi and livery industry
Thursday, including steeply increased insurance requirements for
owners and harsher penalties for drivers who commit violations.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Franklin Weissberg ruled that while the Taxi and
Limousine Commission had violated the state's open meetings law by
holding a closed-door caucus before approving 15 new safety rules
on May 28, the violation was not serious enough to warrant throwing
out the commission's votes.
</P>
<P>
   Weissberg did overturn one rule requiring owners of cab
medallions to file financial disclosure forms, noting that the
commission already had that information.
</P>
<P>
   The two industry groups that had challenged the rules in court _
the Metropolitan Taxicab Board of Trade, which represents fleet
owners, and the New York City Committee for Taxi Safety, made up of
medallion brokers _ said they had no plans to appeal the decision.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, David Beier, a lawyer for the Committee for Taxi
Safety, said his group hoped to work with the taxi commission to
modify some of the rules. After the ruling, the group released a
proposal for increasing insurance that Beier said gave riders
better protection than the mayor's proposals, but at a much lower
cost for owners.
</P>
<P>
   Weissberg's ruling surprised the industry groups, which had been
encouraged last week when he criticized the commission for
apparently violating the open meetings law, which is intended to
make sure public bodies conduct their business in public. He had
asked, rhetorically, what harm would be done if the votes were
taken again, in the open.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the purpose of finding a violation of the law if it
doesn't invalidate what's done improperly?'' Beier asked.
</P>
<P>
   But Weissberg ruled that although the open meetings law had been
violated, the ``draconian measure'' of annulling the commission's
votes was unjustified, because the secrecy of the meeting had not
significantly affected those votes.
</P>
<P>
   He said the commissioners had given fair consideration to the
industry's views by postponing voting on two rules that attracted
the most heated criticism in the daylong public hearing preceding
the vote, and by modifying several other rules.
</P>
<P>
   The judge did, however, order the city to pay the fees of the
taxi groups' lawyers as punishment for violating the open meetings
law.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani called the ruling ``a
great victory for all New Yorkers.''
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen of the 14 rules are to go into effect on July 26. The
insurance requirement, which many owners said was so expensive it
would put them out of business, is to go into effect on Aug. 26, to
give the industry time to propose alternative plans.
</P>
<P>
   As passed, the rule requires taxis and livery cabs to increase
the insurance that compensates victims for pain and suffering to
$100,000 from $25,000, and the insurance that covers medical bills
and lost wages to $200,000, up from $50,000 or $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Another proposed rule, voting on which was postponed under heavy
pressure from the industry, requires yellow-cab owners to post an
additional $100,000 bond for accident victims to collect.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-98 2239EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980702.0460 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 22:41 </DATE_TIME>
