</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CHILD-ABUSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME IN CHILD SEX ABUSE CASE WAS DEEMED SAFE BY AGENCY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RACHEL L. SWARNS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Six months before police arrested Daniel Robacker and
Theresa Fremgen on charges of repeatedly raping their two daughters
in a filthy Brooklyn apartment, child welfare officials approved
the home as a safe place for the teen-age girls.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are home with their parents,'' said Esther Simon, a
lawyer for the Administration for Children's Services, as she
recommended during a court hearing in January that the sisters not
be sent back to foster care. ``They are doing fine.''
</P>
<P>
   And even though a city caseworker was assigned to see the girls
twice a month, and a city housekeeper was assigned to clean the
Bushwick apartment each weekday, neither saw signs of the sexual
abuse that occurred routinely, police say. Robacker, Ms. Fremgen,
her ex-boyfriend and her two brothers are accused of raping and
sodomizing their own children and young relatives in apartment 2E
of 232 Linden St.
</P>
<P>
   The details of the abuse, which emerged Thursday as
investigators released snippets of statements made by each suspect,
painted a horrifying portrait of a home where two sisters were
raped amid squalor and stuffed animals along with an 8-year-old
boy, who was a friend of the family, while the household was under
the city's watch.
</P>
<P>
   The five adults, some of whom are mildly mentally retarded or
illiterate, spoke openly to police about the rape and incest that
took place, investigators say. In a graphic but neatly written
statement to police, one of the suspects, Ezra Fremgen, described
the little boy as a willing accomplice and wrote of the assaults
matter-of-factly: ``We had sex every Saturday that his father
brought him by.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the Administration for Children's Services, which
is investigating the case, declined to say whether the caseworker
made all the visits required by law. And even if she had, it was
unclear whether the worker would have detected signs of the sexual
abuse, which is notoriously difficult to spot, especially when it
is a closely guarded secret among the children. Police said the
children kept silent about the abuse for at least three years.
</P>
<P>
   But new information in the case raised disturbing questions
about whether the city had adequately assessed the safety of the
children. The 14-year-old girl and the 8-year-old boy each had more
than 18 absences from school this year, school officials said,
often an indicator of trouble at home. Child welfare officials
declined to comment on whether they had ever looked into the
absences.
</P>
<P>
   And child welfare records indicate that Ms. Fremgen, 35, was
abused or neglected when she was a teen-ager. Helen Robacker, her
aunt, said Ms. Fremgen was raped by a relative when she was 15.
Caseworkers are required to seek out such information about the
parents they monitor, because all too often it increases the risk
of abuse to children living in the household, according to city
records.
</P>
<P>
   But none of the psychological evaluations of Ms. Fremgen, which
were conducted by the city in 1994 and by an agency contracted by
the city in 1997, mention or assess the severity or impact of any
abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Stancik, the special investigator for the city schools,
said that his office was poring over the children's attendance
records and was working with the Brooklyn district attorney's
office. And officials at the Administration for Children's Services
declined to comment about the other issues, saying they wanted to
complete their inquiry first.
</P>
<P>
   ``The matter is under investigation,'' said Leonora Wiener, an
ACS spokeswoman. ``We'll have no further comment until our
investigation is complete.''
</P>
<P>
   As the officials searched for answers to the many troubling
questions, a bleak picture was developing of the suspects, whose
lives were marked by poverty, mental illness and, sometimes,
neglectful behavior toward children, according to court records and
psychological evaluations.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Framgen, 35, is mentally retarded, according to a
psychological evaluation. Robacker, 40, her companion and first
cousin, dropped out of school in the fourth grade. And Curtis
James, the father of the 8-year-old boy, lived on the streets and
had trouble reading a newspaper, even though he completed trade
school, the court records show.
</P>
<P>
   All five adults were arraigned Thursday in Brooklyn Criminal
Court on a total of 82 counts of rape, sodomy, sexual abuse, incest
and endangering the welfare of a child. Included among the suspects
were Vincent and Ezra Fremgen, the brothers of Ms. Fremgen.
</P>
<P>
   Police, who had said on Wednesday that four children had been
abused, said Thursday it appeared there were only three victims.
</P>
<P>
   They said that two sisters, age 13 and 14, were victimized by
their parents, their uncles and a close family friend who lived
with them. The 8-year-old boy was victimized by his father and by
one of the uncles.
</P>
<P>
   All the sexual offenses took place in the same place: Apartment
2E of 232 Linden St. in Bushwick, Brooklyn, a cluttered, filthy
apartment with stacks of trinkets, clothes, garbage and, in the
bedrooms, pornography.
</P>
<P>
   While investigators believe that the sexual abuse went on for
years, the charges cover numerous sexual offenses that prosecutors
say took place between April 1 and June 30.
</P>
<P>
   The case unraveled when the 8-year-old boy told his new foster
mother that he had been sodomized by Ezra Fremgen. Police arrested
Fremgen on June 30, and he admitted he had sexually abused and
sodomized the boy. Police arrested the others the following day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The statements indicate that most knew what was going on and
on occasion they observed each other,'' said a law enforcement
official, who spoke on the condition of anonymity. ``They appear to
be very low-functioning people. It doesn't appear that they tried
to hide it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
