<SLUG> BC-NY-BRAWLEY-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYER IN BRAWLEY TRIAL INSISTS THE PLAINTIFF IS GUILTY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By WILLIAM GLABERSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   POUGHKEEPSIE, N.Y. _ Steven Pagones, the plaintiff in the Tawana
Brawley defamation case, is ``lucky he is not in jail'' for the
rape and kidnapping of Miss Brawley a decade ago, one of the
defense lawyers said in his summation Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Jackson, the lawyer for C. Vernon Mason, told the jurors
that Pagones was a well-connected man who had manipulated the
system for a decade to avoid answering charges. Contrary to a grand
jury report that exonerated Pagones and discredited Miss Brawley's
account, Jackson said it was clear that Miss Brawley had been
sexually assaulted in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is astonishing that in this day and age, people can still
get away with things like that,'' Jackson said. ``And what is more
incredible is that he actually sued. He's lucky he is not in jail.
Don't let him get away with it.''
</P>
<P>
   He urged the jurors to challenge what he called the ``ego,
arrogance, racism'' behind the suit by Pagones, who is white,
against the three Brawley advisers, Mason, Alton Maddox and the
Rev. Al Sharpton, who, like Miss Brawley, are black.
</P>
<P>
   While Sharpton's lawyer, Michael Hardy, used his closing
statement on Wednesday to focus on the constitutional protections
for civil rights advocates, Jackson took a sharply different tack
Thursday. He essentially stitched together the hints, fragments of
evidence and implications that suggested to supporters of Miss
Brawley that Pagones had been involved in an assault. The defense
lawyer urged the jurors to ``correct history'' and vindicate Miss
Brawley by rejecting Pagones' claim of defamation.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's recitation of the facts that he said implicated
Pagones amounted to a repeat of familiar accusations: a postal
worker saw a suspicious car filled with white men near the place
where Miss Brawley was discovered; Pagones hired a lawyer before
the advisers ever named him as a suspect, and medical attendants at
first described Miss Brawley as unconscious and unresponsive.
</P>
<P>
   For a decade before the trial began and for nearly eight months
in the courtroom, such facts have been examined so many times by
each side that they have lost the power to surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's five-hour statement by Jackson contained many
conspiratorial asides. ``Very suspicious and very curious,'' he
said. ``Something to hide.'' Nods of approval from his supporters
and cold stares from supporters of Pagones suggested, though, that
most minds had long since been made up.
</P>
<P>
   There were signs in the courtroom, however, that as the case
builds toward a conclusion, both sides were preparing for the
inevitable continuing battle after the verdict.
</P>
<P>
   Pagones' mother and wife, who have avoided appearing at the
trial, have begun attending, as if to shore up his camp.
</P>
<P>
   But the advisers have had unusual visitors, too, in recent days.
Percy Sutton, the former Manhattan borough president, and Calvin
Butts, the pastor of the Abyssinian Baptist Church in Harlem, have
made appearances, making comments that suggested support for the
advisers.
</P>
<P>
   The jurors remain impossible to read, though they seemed deeply
engaged in their task. As Thursday's proceedings ended, someone
produced a birthday cake at the defense table for Hardy, Sharpton's
lawyer, who turned 43 Thursday. As the jurors filed out, some of
them could be seen joining the advisers' supporters in singing
``Happy Birthday.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
