<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-HERSHISER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW EXPERIENCE FOR HERSHISER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ERIC NOLAND  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It will have the appearance of the most vile
heresy: Orel Hershiser, standing on the mound in San Francisco,
wearing the uniform of the loathsome Giants, pitching against the
Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Brace for it tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Giants manager Dusty Baker juggled his rotation over the past
week and Hershiser, who signed with the club last winter, just
happened to pop up with the starting assignment for the first
meeting of the season between the entrenched rivals. Baker insists
several on-field factors, not sentiment, influenced his decision.
</P>
<P>
   Still...
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser, once the embodiment of Los Angeles Dodgers excellence
and dignity, facing L.A. as a member of !ital!that!off! team? Is
nothing sacred?
</P>
<P>
   Fans of the Dodgers, however, might weigh this event against the
tumult of the last two months and say, ``Well, no, apparently
nothing is.''
</P>
<P>
   This, certainly, is the perspective of Hershiser, who became a
baseball pragmatist 3{ years ago when the Dodgers said they no
longer had work for him. When surveying the dismantling of
tradition that has occurred on the Dodgers in the wake of their
purchase by the Fox Group, Hershiser said of his gut reaction,
``It's a grieving: The old neighborhood is gone. The neighborhood's
been knocked down, they're putting up condos.''
</P>
<P>
   But then his baseball business sense, deeply ingrained since his
departure from the club, kicked in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's right for me to start evaluating Fox,'' he
said. ``You have a changing of the guard in ownership, so I think
all the rules are off _ what's the employment tradition here,
what's the tradition with the uniforms, what's the tradition at the
ballpark, all those different things.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Fox is going to create its own new tradition, just
like Disney is creating its tradition (with the Angels). I have no
problem with what's going on at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ice cream, it's baseball. It's like somebody removed
vanilla ice cream from the menu. I can't still have vanilla.''
</P>
<P>
   It is easier, then, to take Hershiser at his word when he
insists he will experience not one pang of incongruity when he
winds up to deliver the first sinkerball tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think of it as some big sentimental road I'm supposed
to journey down,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be odd to face a lineup of Steve Sax leading off,
Mickey Hatcher batting second _ go right down the line with guys I
played with and had relationships with. But this is just a team,
it's just a uniform. It's not the same. I don't see the uniform, I
see the person.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Giants went looking for a starting pitcher last winter,
they primarily saw rock-steady consistency in Hershiser, even as he
pushed age 40.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't know what kind of person he was,'' said Giants
pitching coach Ron Perranoski, another Dodgers expatriate.
``Playing against him, you look at him, you think he's cocky. But
they didn't know the true person he is _ a tremendous human being.
They learned that right away this spring. He's been a great help
with the young pitchers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been good with the older guys, too,'' countered Baker,
still another former Dodger. ``He's a joker and a prankster _ which
I wouldn't have expected _ and a part-time referee. He brings a lot
to the ballclub.''
</P>
<P>
   In terms of performance, Hershiser has been streaky with the
Giants _ undoubtedly a maddening condition for the team's fans, who
might not have been eager to embrace him.
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser said he got 10-to-15 poison-pen letters a month early
in the season, as he staggered from the gate with a record of 0-3.
Then came a vintage stretch of work _ a 10-year-old vintage, to be
precise: six victories in a row, with only six earned runs allowed
over a span of 48 innings. At the end of May, Hershiser became the
oldest player in baseball history to be named pitcher of the month.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, however, he has struggled, losing his past three
decisions. He'll enter his Dodgers start with a 6-6 record, coupled
with the customarily solid ERA of 3.84.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago. That's when the separation occurred, against
Hershiser's wishes.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the '94 season, he was coming off a rough
three-year period that corresponded to his recovery from shoulder
surgery, and the Dodgers considered him expendable. It was
understandable rationale, since the club was flush with promising
young pitchers _ Ismael Valdes, Chan Ho Park, Pedro Astacio, Darren
Dreifort _ with Hideo Nomo destined to arrive within three months.
</P>
<P>
   But after switching leagues to sign with Cleveland, Hershiser
demonstrated that there was plenty of life in his arm _ and in a
body he has always kept in the picture of fitness. Over three
seasons with the Indians, he averaged 15 victories per year and put
up a winning percentage of .682.
</P>
<P>
   Currently ranked fifth among active pitchers in victories with
185, Hershiser says he hopes to climb above 200 before considering
retirement. He's in no hurry to call an end to any of this.
</P>
<P>
   ``The journey is so much more fun than the results,'' Hershiser
said.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what colors he wears.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was in spring training after I first became a Giant,''
Hershiser said, ``people asked me, `Isn't it odd putting on this
uniform?' I said no. I look around the room, I'm not dressing next
to Matt (Williams), Robby T. (Thompson), Jeff Leonard, Kevin
Mitchell, Will Clark. My pitching staff is not everybody in the
world who throws a split-finger.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is Dusty Baker and Ron Perranoski and a bunch of guys I
know who happen to wear a Giants uniform.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next generation is here. It's not my generation.''
</P>
<P>
   And those aren't his Dodgers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
