u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-ECON-1STLD-WRIT     07-02 1105
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-ECON-1STLD-WRITETHRU-1,000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPAN ANNOUNCES PLAN TO CLEAR BANKS' BAD DEBTS AND SPUR
CONFIDENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS for general rewrite; adds background material at grafs 13 and
14; adds explanatory material at graf 17; updates Tokyo market
information to Friday morning; different hed)   (mk) 
 By SHERYL WuDUNN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ The government announced a long-awaited plan Thursday to
clear away the nation's pile of bad debt in hopes of bolstering
global confidence in Japan and setting the world's second largest
economy on track for growth.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Total Plan,'' which still needs to be approved by
Parliament, amounts to a program for dealing with at least $550
billion in problem &UR;  &LR; loans held by Japan's largest banks. The
centerpiece is a mechanism to allow banks to fail without provoking
chaos in the financial system.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The government would shut down insolvent institutions and turn
over their clients to government-run ``bridge banks'' to keep the
credit flowing. It would also accelerate sales of depressed real
estate held as collateral for bad loans. Shaky companies would
close, thousands of people could be put out of work, and bankers
could be prosecuted for financial misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   Hikaru Matsunaga, the finance minister, announced that the
government was embracing the plan, shortly after it was approved
Thursday by a task force. Markets reacted cautiously to the
announcement, which had been widely anticipated, while foreign
governments urged that it be followed up with strong measures to
put it into effect.
</P>
<P>
   There has been growing apprehension that the Japanese banking
crisis is now at the heart of Asia's financial problems and may
also threaten the economies in the West and the long boom on Wall
Street. And President Clinton and other American officials have
been stepping up the pressure lately on the Japanese. In
Washington, Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin said in a statement
that the plan contained ``potentially significant steps,'' but he
stressed that ``what is important is for the Japanese authorities
to move quickly to translate this approach into concrete actions.''
</P>
<P>
   In Tokyo, analysts warned that because the plan would bring
about a great deal of pain, Japan's leaders faced enormous
obstacles in carrying it out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a great deal of will to clean the bad debt out
of the private sector, and I think the politicians are committed to
that, but I'm not sure the politicians are willing to restructure
the financial sector and restructure the economy,'' said John
Neuffer, a political analyst at Mitsui Marine Research Institute in
Tokyo. ``They are wonderful when it comes to passing around the
pork, but much less willing to pass around the pain.''
</P>
<P>
   The benchmark Nikkei index of 225 stocks, which has soared over
the last seven days on expectations of the plan and in anticipation
of tax cuts, rose again Thursday, though it lost some of its gains
in the afternoon as details of the plan were reported. The Nikkei
finished up 108.69 points, or sixth-tenths of a percent, at
16,471.58.
</P>
<P>
   But currency markets showed hesitancy, weakening the yen to
140.34 to the dollar from 139.17 in early London trading, just as
Matsunaga, the finance minister, was outlining the plan.
</P>
<P>
   (In trading Friday morning in Tokyo, the Nikkei was down
modestly, and the yen was steady against the dollar.)
</P>
<P>
   An outline of the plan, which is expected to be approved by
Parliament in late July or early August, was disclosed by Matsunaga
and other officials. They insisted that Japan would move toward a
market-based economy and pull away from the convoy system in which
all the banks support one another and move ahead only as quickly as
the slowest bank. Masaharu Hino, head of the new Financial
Supervision Agency, suggested that the government would allow more
banks to fail. He said the agency would take ``strict measures''
after it inspected the nation's 19 largest banks over the next few
months.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will recover confidence in the Japanese financial system by
severing ties with the past convoy administration and shifting to
an administration of severe policing, based on clear rules,'' Hino
said. ``That is the main road toward the rebirth of the financial
system.''
</P>
<P>
   Japan's economy has been languishing ever since the speculative
economic bubble burst in the early 1990s, sending property prices
crashing and bad loans soaring. For nearly eight years, both the
government and the banks have been sitting tight in the hopes that
the real estate market would recover and their problems disappear.
</P>
<P>
   Though the banks have been nibbling away at their bad debts, the
problems have worsened with the recession. The government has let a
few banks fail in a controlled, ad hoc fashion, and it has set
aside $214 billion to protect depositors and bolster the capital
strength of the banks. But it has been loath to take drastic
measures to solve the problem _ until now.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, officials used the English words ``Total Plan'' to
describe the new measure Thursday, perhaps because they sound
bolder and more innovative than the equivalent Japanese terms. The
effort appears to be modeled on the U.S. cleanup of the
savings-and-loan crisis of the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   The plan tries to tear off bad debt from the banks through
foreclosures on properties held as collateral and by encouraging
the revival of the real estate market. It also aims to bring about
a more open financial system by increasing disclosure in a
traditionally secretive banking community, and to impose greater
rigor in the system by stepping up inspection standards and
controls.
</P>
<P>
   Insolvent banks will be allowed to fail, using a two-stage
bridge bank. The plan will first put collapsed banks under
government administration, protecting creditworthy borrowers left
in the lurch by the failed bank, while a merger partner is sought.
Then the collapsed bank will either be acquired or, if no buyers
emerge, nationalized with public money, sending the bad debts to an
agency established to collect bad loans.
</P>
<P>
   The advantage of the bridge bank approach is that it insures
that corporate customers of a failed bank will continue to have
access to loans, reducing the shock of a bank failure. The
disadvantage is that it raises questions about whether Japan, which
has overcapacity in its financial system, is truly willing to let
banks fail and whether the bridge bank system is simply one more
way of allowing insolvent institutions to founder a bit longer.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Initially, public money will be drawn from the 30 trillion yen,
or $214 billion, bailout fund set up in March at Deposit Insurance
Corp., which will set up the bridge banks as subsidiaries of a new
holding company. The corporation will then try to transfer the
business to a healthy bank within two years, though that could be
extended to five years. The total cost of the bailout is by no
means clear.
</P>
<P>
   One sticky point is how the distinction between good and bad
borrowers will be made and whether bad borrowers will be rescued
along with the good ones. Naturally, any client of a failed bank
will insist that it is a good borrower and should continue to
receive loans.
</P>
<P>
   Japan is designing a mechanism that appears similar to the
former Resolution Trust Corp. in the United States, which disposed
of bad debts during the savings-and-loan crisis in the 1980s. In
Japan, the Financial Supervisory Agency, which last month split off
about 400 people from the Finance Ministry to inspect the banks,
will be given wide authority to direct the process.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the blueprint, however, say the Total Plan does not
address some of the fundamental rigidities of the economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a Total Plan at all,'' said Chiaki Nishiyama, an
economist at the Hoover Institution at Stanford University who is
now in Tokyo. ``It's a very deceiving term.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if the plan purges the banks of their bad loans, many
economists feel that a broad restructuring and deregulation of
industry are still necessary to bring about a strong economic
revival. One difference between the American experience and Japan's
situation is that the United States embarked on the painful
reworking of the savings-and-loans industry just as the economy was
picking up. In contrast, Japan is beginning its plan as it sinks
into a recession, and it is already spending $120 billion in fiscal
expansion to bolster economic output.
</P>
<P>
   ``They might get a mild recovery out of this, but it will not be
impressive,'' said Peter Morgan, chief economist at HSBC Securities
Japan. ``If there's a promise of a deregulatory effort, they can
use fiscal expansion as a down payment. But a fiscal down payment
by itself, without restructuring, is a waste.''
</P>
<P>
   Some economists, however, are a little bit more hopeful.
Resolving the bad debt is the first step toward improving the
economy, they say.
</P>
<P>
   ``First we have to solve the confidence crisis, and solving the
bad loans is a starting point,'' said Heizo Takenaka, an economics
professor at Keio University. Then, he added, Japan can ``promote a
deregulated, more transparent open-market system.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
