<SLUG> BC-NY-PARK-KIOSKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 KIOSKS TO BRING CAFE CULTURE TO CENTRAL PARK 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVID W. DUNLAP   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The ever-expanding coffee-and-pastry-shop universe
reached Central Park this week with the construction of two lacy,
cast-iron food kiosks under the trees inside the park's Columbus
Circle entrance.
</P>
<P>
   While some critics worried that the kiosks marked the further
commercialization of Manhattan's most public of spaces, Parks
Commissioner Henry Stern said they would be a welcome amenity, one
that may even be repeated at other park entrances if they prove
successful. The stands are to be run by Ferrara, a 106-year-old
restaurant whose original establishment is at 195 Grand St. between
Mott and Mulberry Streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea of a beautiful, Italian-style sidewalk kiosk at
Columbus Circle is one of the most inviting and elegant things I
can imagine,'' Stern said in an interview Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Central Park kiosks are to open in mid-July. Breakfast,
lunch and light dinners will be served seven days a week in warmer
months, along with the more traditional Ferrara fare of coffee,
cakes, pastries and ice cream. There will be tables and chairs for
20 patrons around each structure.
</P>
<P>
   The one-story kiosks _ painted a glistening dark green and
abundantly ornamented with delicate details _ stand on either side
of the Maine Monument, within the Merchants' Gate, the recently
restored southwest entrance to Central Park.
</P>
<P>
   They are the first entirely new structures to be constructed in
the park since 1993, when the Charles A. Dana Discovery Center was
built on the Harlem Meer, near Central Park North and Lenox Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Though they look as though they might date from the Victorian
era, the kiosks were assembled in the last few days from parts made
in Italy and shipped to New York.
</P>
<P>
   Because they went up so quickly, their presence took some civic
organizations by surprise. For example, neither the Parks Council,
a nonprofit advocacy group, nor Landmarks West, an Upper West Side
preservation group, knew about the construction until they were
reached Thursday by a reporter.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Cooke, executive director of the Parks Council, said
the organization was ``not opposed to a concession that enhances a
parkgoer's use and enjoyment of the park.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But we are concerned that there's been a systematic, continued
de-funding of parks,'' she said, ``and a steady, growing dependence
on private sources of income, whether earned or donated, to replace
lost tax dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   Landmark West president Arlene Simon went further in her
criticism. ``When you go into the park, there needs to be some
relief,'' she said. ``You're NOT on Columbus Avenue. Having
Ferrara's tables and chairs _ that's not what we have those 800
acres for.''
</P>
<P>
   A public-versus-private tug-of-war has gone on for decades over
Central Park, where many services and amenities are provided by
concessionaires. A debate erupted in 1996 over a proposal to
install information posts around the park whose corporate sponsors
would be credited in two-inch-tall letters on the structures _ akin
to advertising, opponents said.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, in March, the Parks Department was criticized for
renting Sheep Meadow to Walt Disney Co. for the filming of a
commercial, at a time of year when the meadow was closed to regular
use by the public.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-98 2248EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980702.0466 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 22:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8841 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SCHWARTZ-PROFILE-6     07-02 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SCHWARTZ-PROFILE-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACK ON THE OFFENSIVE FOR CITY CHARTER GURU 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Eight years ago, Frederick A.O. Schwarz Jr. took his
celebrated family name and several shelves of civic accomplishments
and quietly departed from New York City's public arena. He had just
led the commission that rewrote the City Charter, and _ unlike his
old boss, Mayor Ed Koch _ found it unnecessary to comment on how it
was carried out or offer his momentary opinions on Koch's two
successors.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters would seek comments about the Dinkins or Giuliani
administrations, and he would politely beg off. Elected officials
would try to enlist him in their temporal disputes, hoping his
interpretation of the charter would bolster theirs, and he would
say the thing spoke for itself.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, like many New Yorkers, he was deeply ambivalent about
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, delighted at the mayor's success in
reducing crime but worried about the reasons the administration was
loath to release information about city government. But until this
week, he held his tongue.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, with the release of a blistering letter on Monday,
Schwarz has roared back into public life, furious over the mayor's
decision to try rewriting the charter to block a referendum on
moving Yankee Stadium to Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Writing to Peter Powers, the former first deputy mayor and
chairman of Giuliani's hastily formed Charter Revision Commission,
he said the attempt to rewrite the charter to the advantage of the
mayoralty was a ``trivialization and politicalization of charter
revision'' and represented ``awful government.''
</P>
<P>
   Many in and around City Hall reacted as if a stone colossus had
come back to life and was rumbling menacingly in their direction.
</P>
<P>
   Powers declined to discuss the substance of the seven-page
letter and criticized Schwarz for not informing him of it in
advance.
</P>
<P>
   One anonymous official was quoted in The New York Times as
saying that Schwarz, a Democrat, was acting politically. Paul
Crotty, like Schwarz a former city corporation counsel and a member
of Giuliani's panel, said his predecessor was simply trying to
protect his handiwork.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very proud of the charter,'' said Crotty, now a group
president with Bell Atlantic. ``It represents for him a careful
balancing of interests, and he doesn't want it changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Schwarz, whose family sold the eponymous toy store in the 1960s,
has a courtly manner born of prominence and does not have to
struggle to restrain himself at such suggestions. He said that his
political involvement had been minimal (though he did give the
maximum of $7,700 to Ruth Messinger's mayoral campaign), and that
he had no problem with changes to the charter, as long as they were
undertaken thoughtfully.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't fairly consider these issues without an extensive
public process because charter commissions are not elected
bodies,'' he said in his 40th-floor law office at the lofty firm of
Cravath, Swaine &AMP; Moore, where he has been a partner on and off
since 1969. ``If you haven't had a very extensive and open process,
you're dealing with a blunt instrument in referenda that can be
manipulated by money. And that makes the process incredibly
important.''
</P>
<P>
   Schwarz, it seems fair to say, has a passion for process _
checks, balances, the visibly operating mechanism of government _
as a protector of the public good. Having given New York City
mayors broader powers than the president or the governor to spend
money and make policy, his commission also included several
countervailing forces to watch over that power, the various
monitors under which Giuliani chafes and has proposed changing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is in the nature of powerful people in executive jobs,''
he said, insisting he was not referring specifically to the present
mayor. ``With a few exceptions, they feel they can get it done, so
they say, `Why should I face criticism or second-guessing or new
ideas?' And the great lesson of America is that we don't trust one
individual to have so much power.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Though he has often represented some of the country's largest
corporations at Cravath, Schwarz, known as Fritz to a wide group of
friends, has an even longer streak of anti-authoritarianism, which
he said he absorbed from the Kennedy era of vigorous civic
involvement.
</P>
<P>
   At Harvard Law School in 1960, he led a protest against the
local Woolworth's when black students were holding a famous sit-in
at the Woolworth's in Greensboro, N.C. He spent a year in Nigeria
helping apply its new constitution after years of colonialism, and
he was chief counsel to Sen. Frank Church's intelligence committee
in 1975, investigating the FBI and the CIA. He has worked with many
local civic and charitable groups, and even those who disagree with
him on the current matter are aware that it is difficult to assail
him.
</P>
<P>
   Schwarz, whose boyishly flyaway hair makes it hard to believe he
is 63 with three children in their 30s, is the great-grandson of
Frederick August Otto Schwarz, who founded the store in 1862. His
family's only remaining connection to the store is a license fee
the current owners pay for the name, which goes to a charitable
foundation for children. But as with city government, he feels
obligated to drop by now and then to make sure things are running
smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a grandchild now,'' he said. ``I want to make sure
it's still a quality store.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
