<SLUG> BC-NY-BUDGET-APPOINT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYOR PROMOTES BUDGET DIRECTOR TO DEPUTY MAYOR FOR OPERATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By NORIMITSU ONISHI    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani on Thursday promoted his
budget director, Joseph Lhota, to deputy mayor for operations, the
position that has traditionally been second in command at City
Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Lhota succeeded Randy Mastro, who resigned Monday to return to
private law practice.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment of Lhota, a central player in the recent budget
skirmishes with the City Council, is not likely to push the
Giuliani administration in any major new direction.
</P>
<P>
   The deputy mayor for operations is responsible for the
day-to-day management of government, negotiating the city budget
and making deals with council leaders. As the mayor's most trusted
aide and a sort of alter ego, he fights for the his causes in
televised debates and hammers at issues with reporters inside his
office at City Hall's western end.
</P>
<P>
   The predecessors to Lhota in the job were Mastro, a registered
Democrat who was a protege from Giuliani's days as a federal
prosecutor, and Peter Powers, a lifelong friend of the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job is to carry out the goals of the mayor and his
strategic objectives,'' said Lhota, who like Giuliani is a
Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Among the more immediate thoughts on Lhota's mind Thursday was
what shade to repaint his new office. The deputy mayor for
operations is the only one of the four deputy mayors to have an
office in the City Hall building.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear whether Lhota would inherit all the
responsibilities held by Mastro or whether some might be given to
other members of Giuliani's inner circle, which includes Randy
Levine, deputy mayor for economic development; Dennison Young Jr.,
the chief counsel; Anthony Coles, a senior adviser, and Cristyne
Lategano, the communications director. Giuliani gave no hint
Thursday of how power might be divided, saying only, ``I will leave
it up to them.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor did not name a successor to Lhota on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Before joining the administration in 1994, Lhota, 43, worked for
several years as an investment banker specializing in municipal
finance. He was born on City Island in the Bronx, and his father
was a New York City police lieutenant.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
