<SLUG> BC-SOC-ZIDANE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANCE'S ZIDANE TO RETURN AGAINST ITALY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAINT-DENIS, France _ Nobody heads into today's World Cup
showdown at the Stade de France with greater anticipation than
Zinedine Zidane, the great French playmaker who received a red card
and was forced to watch his team's past two games from the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't imagine how stressful it is being on the bench,'' he
said in advance of today's quarterfinal showdown with Italy. ``You
see the guys fighting and you're just a supporter. There's nothing
you can do to help them out.''
</P>
<P>
   His nerves were frayed after France's last match, a sudden-death
triumph over Paraguay that, if not for Laurent Blanc's 114th-minute
goal, could have been the end of the host's Cup hopes.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would have been awful,'' said the midfielder, who has
emerged in the past two years as the world's No.1 playmaker. ``To
lose when you're playing is bad enough, but at least you can say
that you did your best. It's much worse when you don't play.''
</P>
<P>
   Zidane, a Marseille-born offspring of Algerian immigrants, was
forced to the sidelines after impetuously stomping on an opponent
during a 4-0 rout of Saudi Arabia, an action that left him ``angry
at myself... I know I should not have responded to provocation.''
</P>
<P>
   It left him depressed and his teammates did what they could to
lift his spirits.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last few days before the Paraguay match, he felt awful,''
said Philippe Bergeroo, France's assistant trainer. ``You know
Zizou, he hardly ever talks and it's hard to know how he feels. But
you could see he was going through a nightmare. If France had gone
out, he would have felt responsible for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Now he wants to make sure the French, facing their toughest test
of the Cup, reach the Final Four. His influence on whether that
occurs will be immense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all know how important Zizou is,'' captain Didier Deschamps
said. ``Our attacking game depends almost entirely on him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
