<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-AID-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD BANK, A BIT NERVOUS, RESUMES AID TO INDONESIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The World Bank resumed aid to Indonesia Thursday
for the first time since President Suharto was forced from office.
It approved a $1 billion loan and predicted that major industrial
nations would soon announce another $6 billion in aid.
</P>
<P>
   The $1 billion loan was part of a $4.5 billion contribution from
the World Bank that was promised earlier this year, before the
rioting and political upheaval that brought down Suharto after 32
years in office.
</P>
<P>
   But the loan comes at a time when international aid officials
describe the country as standing on the edge of an economic abyss:
Its economy is shrinking faster than anyone expected, its
unemployment rate is soaring and its currency is unable to recover
from a steep fall in value.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Thursday's loan is enormously risky, and World Bank
officials worry that they may not be able to control how it is
spent. They are making only $600 million available immediately; the
rest will come later this year, if Indonesia meets a number of the
economic commitments it has made since Suharto's departure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see this loan as a critical component in the overall
package of assistance provided by the international community,''
James Wolfensohn, the World Bank's president, said in a statement.
``Its objective is to rebuild confidence and help Indonesia make a
new start.''
</P>
<P>
   The $1 billion is for reform of the financial and banking
systems, and to pay for imports of food and other commodities.
Rampant inflation, expected to reach 80 percent this year, has set
off much of the social unrest in Indonesia, including attacks on
the ethnic Chinese minority, which dominates much of the economy.
</P>
<P>
   A week ago the International Monetary Fund announced it had
reached a new accord with Indonesia _ its fourth since October _
that would enable the fund to resume its aid this month, too. Its
disbursements were halted in May, as the rioting worsened.
</P>
<P>
   The new accord allows for more social spending, and permits
Indonesia to run a significant budget deficit, something the
earlier agreements prohibited.
</P>
<P>
   The IMF said last week that the total aid package to Indonesia,
about $43 billion, would not be sufficient. It appealed to other
countries to come up with another $6 billion to help Indonesia
subsidize critical commodities, including food and fuel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very confident that that package will come,'' Dennis de
Tray, the bank's director for Indonesia, said Thursday. He added
that the additional aid would take ``weeks, but not many,'' to put
together.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a time to hold back and wait and see,'' de Tray
said.
</P>
<P>
   American officials say the United States, which has the largest
vote in the World Bank, supported Thursday's decision. It was the
first official vote of confidence in the new government of
President B.J. Habibie, a longtime friend of Suharto's.
</P>
<P>
   But Americans who have dealt with Habibie and his new Cabinet
have come away with mixed impressions.
</P>
<P>
   Several encounters with the president have apparently gone in
surprising directions, with Habibie expounding on unusual economic
theories or regaling visitors with accounts of his efforts to build
a national airplane for Indonesia, a program that the fund halted.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand the finance minister, Ginandjar Kartasmita, is
gaining increasing respect in Washington. He appears serious about
wide-ranging economic reforms, officials say, and he is coming to
Washington next week to seek more aid.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
