<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-FIREFIGHTERS-BRAWL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
11 FIREFIGHTERS ARE FINED FOR FRACAS AT PARK CAFE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By ROBERT D. McFADDEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A month after accounts of a drunken brawl among
firefighters at a midtown restaurant, Fire Commissioner Thomas Von
Essen penalized 11 firemen Thursday with a loss of pay for their
involvement, and closed an investigation into what he called ``a
very sad day in the history of our department.''
</P>
<P>
   While witnesses had initially told of scores of firefighters
battling one another, urinating publicly and harassing patrons in
scenes of chaos that went on for hours at the Bryant Park Grill on
the night of June 3, Von Essen said that his investigators had
found only two who ``were involved in physical altercations'' and
eight who had ``contributed to an embarrassing display.''
</P>
<P>
   The two said to have been involved in fighting, Francis Morrisey
of Engine Company 319 in Queens, and Richard Savarese of Engine 310
in Brooklyn, were fined 30 days' pay each, while the eight others,
who had ``tarnished the good reputation'' of firefighters, were
fined five days' pay each, Von Essen said.
</P>
<P>
   The commissioner also said that a rookie firefighter, James
Bruno, who was dismissed last month, had been reinstated because
``it became evident'' that he ``had no involvement in the serious
allegations of misbehavior.'' But he was fined 30 days' pay and his
probationary period was extended by six months.
</P>
<P>
   ``The charges leveled against those responsible are often
referred to as conduct unbecoming the uniform,'' Von Essen said.
``I hope that this department has sent a strong message about our
uniform and the traditions that members of the New York City Fire
Department are compelled to uphold.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Lynch, the Manhattan trustee of the Uniformed Firefighters
Association, called the penalties ``severe'' and said that his
union believed that the fracas had been ``highly exaggerated.''
</P>
<P>
   The penalties appeared to close the books on the most serious
breach of conduct by firefighters in years, an evening of drinking
and fighting that left faces bloody and city officials deeply
embarrassed. It seemed all the worse because it followed Medal Day
ceremonies in which heroic firefighters were honored at City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   In the days after the episode, investigators quoted witnesses as
saying that 50 to 100 firefighters had attended the celebration at
the awning-draped open air cafe, and that scores had joined in the
raucous conduct.
</P>
<P>
   But the investigators also said it was unlikely that any of the
participants would face criminal charges unless the brawlers filed
complaints against one another, although some might face
departmental sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Von Essen, who had vowed to quickly investigate the incident and
punish those responsible, insisted Thursday that the department's
investigation, led by Assistant Commissioner Lai Sun Yee, head of
the Bureau of Investigations and Trials, had been ``exhaustive and
comprehensive.''
</P>
<P>
   The investigators, he said, set up a ``war room'' with charts
and pictures of the cafe to place witnesses and suspects. Thousands
of pages of testimony were amassed from 70 witnesses, including 37
firefighters, he said. Credit card receipts were used to identify
some of those present.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from applauding the inquiry and imposing the penalties,
Von Essen did not detail the findings. But one investigator said
that no firefighter made a specific allegation against any other
firefighter, and that the investigation had been handicapped by a
dearth of evidence. No one testified to having seen firefighters
urinating in the bushes or running through the women's toilet, as
some witnesses had described, for example.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the investigator said, a picture emerged, and he
characterized it as far less serious than originally depicted by
witnesses, including Donna Simms, the cafe manager. Instead of
hours of sporadic fisticuffs between men of rival fire companies,
he said, the fighting began about 10:15 p.m. with an exchange of
insults, lasted only 10 to 15 minutes and involved two principal
combatants and five to 10 others.
</P>
<P>
   The investigator described a scrumlike skirmish, in which most
participants were on the periphery, some digging to get in and
others holding comrades back. ``We're not saying they were
choirboys,'' the investigator said, ``but they were not all
throwing punches.''
</P>
<P>
   When the police arrived, all but a few firefighters had left,
and the only person arrested was a cafe bouncer, Ethan Kemp, who
was charged with assault and resisting arrest. He was said to have
thrown a police officer over a flower planter, mistaking him for a
firefighter he was trying to subdue. The charges were still
pending, but an official said he was not likely to be prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas De Souza, another manager at the cafe, had no comment
Thursday night. He said Ms. Simms was out of town and unavailable
for comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
