<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEACHER-MARRIAGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CATHOLIC SCHOOL REHIRES TEACHER FIRED FOR MARRYING DIVORCED MAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOSEPH BERGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. _ A Roman Catholic school in Cortlandt Manor
agreed Thursday to rehire a teacher who was dismissed from her job
because she had married a divorced Episcopalian who had never had
his previous marriage annulled.
</P>
<P>
   A settlement to the confrontation between the teacher, Jeanne
Hearty, and Msgr. Patrick Keenan, the director of St. Columbanus
School outside Peekskill, came after it was determined that the
teacher's husband never needed a formal annulment _ which requires
a time-consuming investigation and hearings _ but a lesser
certificate simply confirming that his previous marriage had not
been valid in the eyes of the Catholic Church.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the settlement, Ms. Hearty and her husband, Terry
Barber, who obtained the certificate, were remarried Wednesday by a
Catholic priest in St. Columba Church in Hopewell Junction, N.Y. in
Dutchess County. Their earlier marriage had taken place in an
Episcopal church.
</P>
<P>
   In a stiff but cordial ceremony Thursday at the school, Ms.
Hearty, 36, and Keenan, 62, signed a new employment contract
allowing Ms. Hearty to resume her duties as a fifth-grade teacher
in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's very thankful that she got her contract,'' said Norine
Beaumont, Ms. Hearty's sister, speaking on behalf of Ms. Hearty.
``She did everything that was requested of her.''
</P>
<P>
   Keenan declined to discuss the matter, but confirmed the
rehiring.
</P>
<P>
   Barber filed papers in April seeking an annulment. But the Roman
Catholic tribunal hearing the case in Poughkeepsie was not expected
to reach a conclusion before the start of the next school year, so
Keenan said he would not renew Ms. Hearty's contract.
</P>
<P>
   The breakthrough came when the tribunal discovered that Barber
did not need an annulment. Ms. Hearty's lawyer, Salvatore Lagonia,
and Ms. Beaumont said they were not certain of the intricate church
law involved, but Ms. Beaumont said that the key was that Barber
had previously married a Catholic convert to Judaism in an
Episcopalian ceremony. The tribunal found that the Catholic Church
does not recognize that ceremony, making an annulment unnecessary,
Ms. Beaumont said.
</P>
<P>
   Lagonia said that he understood that Cardinal John O'Connor had
intervened and ``made things happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
