<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 23:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8929 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-CONDO-COMPLEX-575&AMP;     07-02 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CONDO-COMPLEX-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROUP BUYS HELMSLEY STAKE IN TROUBLED BRONX CONDO COMPLEX 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By DAVID M. HALBFINGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A partnership led by the city's largest private
financier of multifamily housing has bought more than half of the
apartments in Parkchester, taking the first step in a $200 million
restoration of the huge condominium project in the eastern Bronx
that many thought was in danger of becoming a slum.
</P>
<P>
   CPC Resources Inc., an arm of the Community Preservation Corp.,
and two real-estate investors, Morton L. Olshan and Jeremiah W.
O'Connor Jr., paid just $4 million for the Parkchester holdings of
Leona Helmsley, whose late husband, Harry, had converted them into
condominiums in the 1970s. The Helmsley stake included 6,362
apartments, five parking garages and 88 retail stores, including
the only Macy's branch in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   The new partners, who completed the acquisition on Wednesday,
intend to borrow $178 million to replace plumbing, wiring and more
than 65,000 windows throughout the 12,271-unit complex, which
sprawls across 130 acres between White Plains Road and Castle Hill
Avenue, just north of the Cross-Bronx Expressway.
</P>
<P>
   First, however, they must convince Parkchester's two condominium
boards to support the restoration plan, under which the $178
million loan would be paid off by owners through increases in their
monthly charges and residents would pay their own electricity bills
for the first time. If the plan wins the approval of the two
boards, said Michael Lappin, president of the Community
Preservation Corporation, condominium owners could vote on the plan
in early October.
</P>
<P>
   The plan has broad political support from politicians in the
city and state as well as community and religious leaders in the
area. But success is not a foregone conclusion. Lappin and his
partners do not control enough votes outright to win the October
election. And an outspoken group of opponents has emerged,
asserting that the proposed repairs are insufficient and that the
plan is too costly for residents, many of whom are elderly people
living on fixed incomes.
</P>
<P>
   Gladys Williams, a member of the group that opposes the plan,
the Parkchester Owners &AMP; Residents Association, said the renovation
scheme omits essential repairs like replacing leaky sewage pipes
and 60-year-old electrical wires, that would have to be made in
future years at additional cost. She vowed a bitter fight over the
summer. ``We're going to lay down in the streets,'' she said.
``We're going to stop traffic. We're going to jump up and down and
scream, `This is not a good deal for Parkchester.'''
</P>
<P>
   Lappin, however, said the plan had been designed to do what was
absolutely necessary while minimizing the cost to residents. Each
owner will have to pay about $95 a month toward the debt and a
reserve fund, he said. But because of an expected real estate tax
abatement, residents could save $53 a month in taxes. A $25 monthly
electricity charge will be eliminated, replaced by individual
electrical bills estimated at $44 a month. All told, barring a
spike in interest rates, the net increase in cost should not exceed
$74 a month on average, Lappin said.
</P>
<P>
   Lappin's Community Preservation Corp., a lending consortium of
New York's major banks, will also offer refinancing to Parkchester
residents, many who bought their apartments at high interest rates
and have been unable to obtain new mortgages because of the decline
in property values in the area.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Parkchester Preservation Corp. could earn substantial profits if
the renovation plan is successful and it is able to sell the
apartments it now owns, 800 of which are vacant and the rest
occupied by renters. Prices for two- and three-bedroom apartments
there ranged between $20,000 and $30,000 in recent years, and a
refurbished Parkchester could drive values higher, Lappin said.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the restoration plan hailed the purchase as the
first step in the revival of a community that once was considered a
jewel of the Bronx. Borough President Fernando Ferrer, who lived in
Parkchester as a newlywed, said Parkchester's slide into decay was
apparent more than a decade ago and had begun to threaten
surrounding communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Parkchester went, so would that whole section of the East
Bronx,'' he said. ``In a minute.''
</P>
<P>
   Conceived as a ``park-like suburb'' when much of the eastern
Bronx remained undeveloped, Parkchester was built on winding lanes
radiating from a sculptured fountain at the Metropolitan Oval
between 1938 and 1940 by Metropolitan Life Insurance Co. Helmsley
bought it in 1968 and, four years later, began converting it from
rental apartments to condominiums. After sales faltered in the late
1980s and early 1990s, Helmsley began leasing its unsold
apartments.
</P>
<P>
   By 1995, Parkchester had fallen into disrepair and the Helmsley
interests were losing money, when Lappin, encouraged by Ferrer and
other political and community leaders, began negotiating the
purchase and planning the rehabilitation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
