A8966 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-POLICE-BRUTALITY-N     07-02 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-BRUTALITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. PROSECUTORS WIDEN PROBE OF POLICE BRUTALITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Federal prosecutors investigating whether a pattern
of brutality or misconduct exists in the New York City Police
Department are seeking access to a deposition in which a senior
police official discussed his inability to have Officer Francis
Livoti transferred in 1991 despite nine brutality complaints filed
against him.
</P>
<P>
   Three years after high-ranking police officials rejected the
transfer of Livoti, he was accused in the choking death of Anthony
Baez during an arrest in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a federal jury in Manhattan convicted Livoti, who was
dismissed from the force in 1997, of violating Baez's civil rights.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by Zachary Carter, the U.S. attorney in Brooklyn,
to seek a copy of the deposition of Deputy Chief William Casey
comes as part of a broad look by Carter's office at how the
department handles abuse complaints. Carter's office requested a
copy of the deposition earlier this week from a Bronx Supreme Court
justice who is presiding in a civil lawsuit the Baez family has
brought against the Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   Carter began his investigation into the department after police
officers in a Brooklyn station house were accused of attacking
Abner Louima last August. The civil investigation is being
conducted under a 1994 law that allows the government to
investigate misconduct by law enforcement agencies and, where it
finds a pattern of wrongdoing, to sue in an attempt to force
institutional change under court order.
</P>
<P>
   Carter declined any comment Thursday on his investigation, which
lawyers outside his office said they believed was looking at
hundreds of cases of officers who have been the subject of multiple
brutality complaints and how those cases were resolved by the
department.
</P>
<P>
   In the deposition, Casey, who was Livoti's commander in the 46th
Precinct at the time, testified that his recommendation that Livoti
be transferred in 1991 was rejected by Louis Anemone, now chief of
department, and by a second official.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials have said that Anemone believed the brutality
complaints were not substantiated, and they also cited Livoti's
status as a police union delegate.
</P>
<P>
   The department's critics, including lawyers for the Baez family,
say that the chief's testimony raises questions about the
department's commitment to combating brutality.
</P>
<P>
   The availability of depositions in civil suits varies from case
to case, but Carter's office apparently had to go to Justice
Douglas McKeon for a copy because parts of the 237-page document
that concern specific brutality complaints against Livoti remain
under seal.
</P>
<P>
   Livoti's lawyer, Stuart London, said that Livoti's 500 arrests
over his 15 years on the force placed him in the top echelon of
police officers, and the number of complaints against him was
extremely low by comparison. Most of the complaints were found to
be unsubstantiated, London said, adding that Livoti denies
wrongdoing in every one of them.
</P>
<P>
   Livoti, who was acquitted on state charges of criminally
negligent homicide in 1996 in the death of Baez, plans to appeal
last week's conviction in the civil rights case, London said.
</P>
<P>
   In the recent civil rights trial, federal prosecutors accused
three officers of lying to protect Livoti. Police Commissioner
Howard Safir elaborated Thursday on the decision to place the three
officers on modified leave until the Police Department completes
its investigation into the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the three _ Sgt. William Monahan and Officers Mario
Erotokritou and Anthony Farnan _ testified that he did not see
Livoti use a choke hold on Baez. Another officer, Daisy Boria,
testified that officers had planned to lie to absolve Livoti of
wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are doing an investigation to see whether or not they were
involved in misconduct,'' Safir said. ``It is my judgment that they
should not be on the street until this has been resolved one way or
the other.'' A separate criminal investigation is being conducted
by the U.S. attorney's office in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The Police Department declined to allow the three officers to be
interviewed Thursday. London, who is also a lawyer for the
Patrolmen's Benevolent Association, criticized the department's
decision to put the officers on modified duty, saying that it would
have a ``chilling effect'' on ``the entire police force.'' He also
said the officers had done nothing wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Safir, questioned about Anemone's decision to reject
Livoti's transfer in 1991, said: ``Let me be clear: we're looking
at all aspects of the case relative to these three individuals. I
am not investigating Chief Anemone.''  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
