<HEADLINE>
STEVEN GALEF, 58, LAWYER AND CIVIC LEADER  
 FRANKLIN POLLOCK, 95, BUSINESSMAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va., Ga., Calif., Pa., N.J., Tenn., Fla., Texas)  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Steven Galef, a Manhattan lawyer who was active in
health and community affairs in Westchester County, died on Monday
at Memorial Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center. He was 58 and lived in
Ossining, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was throat cancer, his family said.
</P>
<P>
   Galef, who was a senior partner in the firm of Wormser, Kiely,
Galef &AMP; Jacobs, was instrumental in turning the county-operated
Westchester Medical Center in Valhalla, N.Y., over to a public
benefit corporation last year. He also was a central figure in
developing the medical center's new Children's Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   He held office in a number of public service organizations,
including the county chapters of the Red Cross and United Way, the
Westchester Health Fund and Jewish Community Services. He was a
Democratic county legislator from 1976 to 1980.
</P>
<P>
   A native New Yorker, he graduated from Washington and Lee
University in 1962 and received his law degree from the University
of Virginia in 1965.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, state Assemblywoman Sandra Galef;
their son, Graig, of Atlanta; a daughter, Gwen Galef of White
Plains, N,Y.; two brothers, Andrew, of Los Angeles, and Victor, of
Radnor, Pa., and a sister, Nancy Shumate of Mendham, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Franklin Pollock, a self-made businessman who rose to vice
chairman of Dart Industries, died June 26 at his home in Holmby
Hills, Calif. He was 95.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Brooklyn, N.Y., in 1903, Pollock began his career as a
salesman for Imperial Cork Co. and later became chairman of the
board. He moved to Thatcher Glass Manufacturing Co., where he
became president and chief executive. In 1966, Pollock merged
Thatcher with Rexall Drug and Chemical Co., which was led by Justin
Dart, creating Dart Industries.
</P>
<P>
   A chairman of the Glass Container Association, Pollock was
inducted into the Packaging Hall of Fame, and was a member of the
board of several companies, including Western Union, Ward Foods,
Dorsey Corp. and Kennedy Valve Co.
</P>
<P>
   A friend and supporter of Ronald Reagan, Pollock was a founding
member of the Ground Floor Committee, which helped the former Gov.
Reagan to his presidential election victory in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Pollock is survived by his wife, Elsie; a son, Jack, of
Chattanooga, Tenn., and Jupiter, Fla.; a daughter, Penny, of
Dallas; seven grandchildren, and eight great-grandchildren. Another
son, Robert, died in 1995.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
