<SLUG> BC-BBO-METS-JAYS-475&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS PLUCK BLUE JAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ The experiment is only two days old. But so far, Mets
Manager Bobby Valentine's juxtapositioning of John Olerud and Mike
Piazza in the heart of his struggling lineup has been nothing short
of promising. And it won't be long now before Todd Hundley arrives
to take a little heat off Piazza, too.
</P>
<P>
   To which, Piazza might respond, it's about time. Ever since the
Mets acquired Piazza from the Florida Marlins on May 22, Valentine
had been reluctant to bat the All-Star catcher anywhere other than
third, where Piazza has batted for most of his career. But after an
initial offensive explosion with the addition of Piazza to the
lineup, the Mets had reverted to their meek-hitting ways until
Wednesday, when Valentine had the slumping Olerud move from cleanup
to third and Piazza take his place batting fourth.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets responded by scoring 10 runs in a loss to Toronto on
Wednesday, and Thursday evening they enjoyed a 9-1 thrashing of the
Blue Jays.
</P>
<P>
   Spurred by eight strong innings of five-hit ball from Bobby
Jones (7-5), the Mets (44-36) won for just the second time in their
last six games, averting a three-game sweep at the Skydome. Only a
two-out seventh-inning home run by Carlos Delgado foiled a shutout
by Jones, who had retired 16 straight Blue Jays in a row.
</P>
<P>
   John Franco pitched the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Olerud and Piazza gave Jones, who won for the first time since
June 11, all the runs he needed in the third. Olerud doubled home
Edgardo Alfonzo from second base just before Piazza drilled his
14th home run of the season to give the Mets a 3-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets scored eight runs off former American League Cy Young
award winner Pat Hentgen in just five innings. And other than
Delgado's homer, all the 27,325 fans had to cheer about was
40-year-old Dave Stieb's return home in his first appearance at the
Skydome since July 29, 1992.
</P>
<P>
   But by the time Stieb came on in the seventh to pitch three
perfect innings, the Mets were already up by 9-0.
</P>
<P>
   Alfonzo and Olerud appear to be the two main beneficiaries of
the subtle lineup switch. Alfonzo homered twice and drove in three
runs in Wednesday's loss, before going 3-for-4 with a double and
three runs scored tonight. Olerud was 3-for-4 with a triple and a
three-run homer Wednesday and then 2-for-4 with a run-scoring
double Thursday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Just as important, Piazza has had some runners on base to drive
in. Coming in to the game, the slugging catcher had just 27 at-bats
with runners in scoring position in 31 games with the Mets. He was
batting just .185 with five hits and no homers in those situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been anxious, which is why I've been swinging at bad
pitches,'' Piazza said before the game. ``I've been trying to do
too much with a runner on third and a runner on second with two
out.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Piazza hasn't seen many chances to drive people in with less
than two out. Imagine, then, how he must have felt in the top of
the first when Shawn Green robbed him of extra bases with a diving
catch in center field with Alfonzo on second and Olerud on first.
</P>
<P>
   But Piazza made sure no one could catch his third-inning shot, a
homer to right. And once Hundley arrives from his minor-league
injury rehabilitation period, which could be next week, Piazza will
have an offensive force behind him to protect him.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH:
</P>
<P>
   During the voluble chewing out he took in the visiting clubhouse
after Wednesday's eighth-inning fiasco, Mel Rojas said Manager
Bobby Valentine told him, ``It didn't look like I want to pitch.''
Rojas, whose earned run average over his last six appearances is
25.07, sounded as confused as anyone by his struggles. It is
obvious that he doesn't trust his fastball anymore. And he admitted
that it would not be good for the team to put him in a set-up role
until he can pitch his way out of his current funk. Rojas said,
however, that the minor-leagues were not an option.
</P>
<P>
   Al Leiter remained optimistic that he would be able to pitch
shortly after he is eligible to come off the disabled list July 12.
``I think I'll miss just one start after the All-Star break,'' said
Leiter, who has a 15 percent tear of the patella tendon in his left
knee. Jim Leyland, who will manage the National League All-Star
team, said on Thursday that he would have named Leiter to his staff
had he not been injured. ... Hideo Nomo (lower back strain) said he
felt a little better and that the Mets would decide after the
All-Star break as to when he would next pitch.
</P>
</TEXT>
