<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-ITALY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ITALIAN STAR LEARNED FROM HIS DAD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAINT-DENIS, France _ He's a loner, unpopular with teammates, or
so it is whispered. He's less than cordial with those who sign his
paycheck.
</P>
<P>
   He's a night owl, preferring to dance the night away at discos
than get the rest his coaches and trainers think he needs.
</P>
<P>
   And he's less than a perfect practice player, accused of not
trying hard enough in training, of not being in the sort of shape
one expects of world-class soccer players.
</P>
<P>
   But Christian Vieri's excesses have been indulged because of his
ability to put the ball in the net, a skill that has made him _ and
not the far more celebrated Alessandro Del Piero or Roberto Baggio
_ the most dangerous striker at this World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   The 24-year-old Vieri will be looking for his sixth goal of the
tournament this afternoon when he leads Italy against France in a
hugely anticipated quarterfinal showdown at the Stade de France.
</P>
<P>
   Del Piero, the reigning superstar of Italian soccer, was
supposed to be the Azzurri's primary striker and Baggio their
deadly old hand. Instead, it's been Vieri with a stirring goal
against Chile, two more goals against Cameroon, another against
Austria, and another in the second-round triumph over Norway. Vieri
has been the difference between a decent Italian side and one that
might capture the title.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is true, at the moment I'm going through a very good
period,'' Vieri acknowledged. ``Five goals is great, and of course
I am very happy. I want to do better, I want to score more goals.
But above all, I want to go as far as possible in the competition
with this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Vieri, who shares the World Cup scoring lead with Argentina's
Gabriel Batistuta, led the Spanish League in scoring last season
for Atletico de Madrid, which spent $20 million to acquire him from
Juventus. His coach, Raddy Antic, accused him of ``shutting the
door at the local disco,'' but he is considered untouchable
because, no matter the situation, he puts the ball in the net.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a striker,'' he says matter-of-factly, ``and scoring goals
is my job.''
</P>
<P>
   He's a burly forward, a direct player who learned the game and
gained his skills from his father, Roberto, a standout with
Juventus, Sampdoria, Torino and AS Roma before heading to Australia
to coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``(My father) always tells me what I'm doing wrong; there's no
point in him telling me what I'm doing right,'' Christian said.
``And after all, he's got the right to do so. He was a great
footballer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've only seen bits of matches he played, recorded on old
tapes, but when I was little we played together in our garden in
Australia.''
</P>
<P>
   It paid off after the family returned to Italy when Christian
was 15. He soon signed his first contract, apprenticed in Italy's
lower divisions, then helped Italy win the European under-21
championships in 1992 and 1994 before earning his big break with
Atalanta. He scored nine times in 17 games and was sent to
Juventus, Italy's biggest club.
</P>
<P>
   The diminutive Del Piero, whose silkier skills complement the
more muscular Vieri's in coach Cesare Maldini's big-little attack,
has received far more of the acclaim, but Vieri's nose for the goal
has been more beneficial in France. His goal against Norway, in a
1-0 victory, was prototypical: He ran onto a throughball from Luigi
di Biagio, outran and outbattled defender Dan Eggen to the box,
then blasted past goalkeeper Frode Grodas.
</P>
<P>
   He had little to say about the goal or any of his goals, but
that's nothing new. ``I'm the silent type,'' he said. ``I don't
talk much and I like it that way. The only time I really enjoy
myself is when I'm on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   It might not seem that way. He doesn't celebrate his goals with
the exuberance of his teammates, but he considers himself more
misunderstood than unapproachable. And scoring goals, he says, is
of secondary importance. Unlike Batistuta, Vieri doesn't care
whether or not he wins the Golden Boot as the World Cup's top
scorer.
</P>
<P>
   ``In years to come,'' he said, ``I shall be happy to say I was
at the most important tournament in football. That's enough.''
</P>
</TEXT>
