<SLUG> BC-NY-COLUMN-COFFEE-ARTIST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: PRIDE IN COFFEE IS ELEVATED TO A NEW ART 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVID GONZALEZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Francisco Rivera Rosa likes his coffee jet black and
jet-fuel strong. He's particularly partial to a bitter blend that's
thick as paste. ``No milk, no sugar,'' he insists. ``No anything.''
Except for the occasional splash of watercolor. Or acrylic. Or mud.
</P>
<P>
   This is no java jive. Rivera Rosa is a Puerto Rican artist who
has been painting and sculpting with coffee for the last three
years. He called the technique Arfe, combining the Spanish words
for art and coffee. Embracing a self-referential realism, he uses
the sepia medium to render lush landscapes of his native island's
plantations and haciendas. His harvest _ as he calls his collection
_ celebrates one of Puerto Rico's most treasured exports, a brew
savored by everyone from popes to peasants.
</P>
<P>
   A number of those pieces are on exhibit at the Union Square
branch of Touro College, held over for an extended run after
finding an audience that has been eager to support a new cultural
endeavor. While the ``Seinfeld'' crowd milked cheap laughs by
burning the Puerto Rican flag in a recent episode, the people who
have discovered Rivera Rosa's paintings know that their community
appreciates the fine arts. Even the fine-grind kind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to use the process of our education to talk about our
roots,'' said Felipe Morales Millan, the college's director. ``Many
of our students are Puerto Rican, and sometimes they know about
their culture, sometimes they do not. I wanted to use this exhibit
to reaffirm this new craft and give them something about their
roots.''
</P>
<P>
   Those of you whose talent is limited to making brown rings on
your desktop or amoebalike splotches on shirts, take heart. Rivera
Rosa also discovered his new medium by accident a few years ago
while doing watercolors in his studio in Humacao, Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was drinking coffee, and I noticed this drop on a scrap of
paper,'' he said. ``It looked like when it fell, it made certain
tones and contours. I had to look into the alternatives with
that.''
</P>
<P>
   He and his wife, Milagros Martinez Schettini, researched the
history of coffee on the island and experimented with different
beans and roasts. They learned that they could coax yellows,
purples and greens with some tinkering.
</P>
<P>
   ``To get different tones, you have to consider how much the bean
has been roasted,'' he said. ``It's like when you prepare a gourmet
coffee, you look at how it has been roasted to achieve different
tastes and colors. It's also important how much water you evaporate
after it has been brewed.''
</P>
<P>
   He uses the resulting paste alone or with other paints. He has
also mixed it with mud for some surrealistic sculptures _ no mugs
yet. His beans come from a local roaster who saves the burned
batches that would have been tossed, although once Rivera Rosa
rushed to a fast-food joint for a cup of really strong espresso
when he ran out of his special brew in mid-painting. Unlike the
stuff he drinks, bitter is better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because coffee is somewhat acidic, that is good,'' he said.
``That way no little animals can eat away at it. Also, when the sun
hits watercolors, they fade from the ultraviolet rays. When we mix
our coffee pigment with it, it's like adding a solar filter.''
</P>
<P>
   For much of last month, Rivera Rosa and his wife were in town to
promote their new technique among galleries and artists. And yes,
he has noticed what some people call coffee, though he has yet to
work with the local stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way they make it, you can almost see through it,'' he
said. ``It's very yellow. It's so clear. They're diluting it too
much.''
</P>
<P>
   Any Latin from Manhattan could have told him that. A few did
this week, when a group from the Lower East Side trooped through
the college's corridor gallery to see scenes of weather-beaten
shacks, pre-Columbian stone carvings and lots of coffee beans
ripening on the vine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to eat those,'' said Rafael Ruiz, recalling with a
nostalgic smile how he used to help his mother grind coffee. ``This
is historic stuff about real life. When you're a kid, you don't
realize its importance, but when you're an adult, you do.''
</P>
<P>
   After the tour, someone asked Rivera Rosa if he ever tried any
of the flavored coffees sold in gourmet shops and espresso bars. He
winced. The man who mixes on his palette prefers purity for his
palate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would never mix coffee with banana or strawberry syrups,''
he said. ``Coffee is coffee and banana is banana. To mix it is to
have a strange combination. That makes no sense.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
