<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CT-JURORS-BIAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT SETS GUIDELINES ON JUROR-BIAS INQUIRIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD _ The Connecticut Supreme Court established new,
rigorous guidelines Thursday for how a trial court should
investigate allegations of racial bias by jurors, after finding in
a decision released Thursday that a judge should have done more to
look into such claims in a murder trial here in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The court ruled, 3-2, that a trial judge must pursue questions
of a juror's racial bias more thoroughly than other types of jury
misconduct because it is so critical to the public's confidence in
the courts.
</P>
<P>
   The decision also means that the case of Adrian Santiago, who
was convicted of murder in February 1996, must be reopened so that
the trial judge can apply the new rules.
</P>
<P>
   About a month after Santiago was convicted, a juror, June
Briere, said that she had heard another juror use a racial slur
against Santiago in the jury room.
</P>
<P>
   After the trial, Ms. Briere became so convinced of Santiago's
innocence that she has paid for his appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The decision requires that when a claim is made that a juror has
racial or ethnic bias, the trial judge should, at a minimum,
interview the person making the claim, any possible witnesses to
demonstrations of racial bias and the accused juror.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Parrent, a lawyer with the Connecticut Civil Liberties
Union, praised the decision. ``These are the most rigorous set of
guidelines I've seen issued by any court for dealing with claims of
racially biased jurors,'' Ms. Parrent said, adding that the rules
should provide a model for other states.
</P>
<P>
   In its decision, the court said that the trial judge, Samuel
Sferrazza, correctly followed the existing guidelines for
investigating possible jury misconduct. The judge had interviewed
both Ms. Briere and the jury foreman before finding Ms. Briere's
account not credible.
</P>
<P>
   But in Thursday's decision, Associate Justice Flemming Norcott
Jr. wrote: ``A trial court must be especially vigilant in
investigating the specter of racial prejudice in the judicial
process. Failure to scrupulously explore such allegations would
seem to enhance the risk of a conviction based on race. Such a risk
cannot be tolerated.''
</P>
<P>
   In a dissent, Chief Justice Robert Callahan said such an
extensive inquiry into even meritless allegations was ``unnecessary
and ill advised.''
</P>
<P>
   Carolyn Longstreth, the senior assistant state's attorney, said
she was disappointed with the decision, but said she was confident
the conviction would stand.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Briere, 62, who continues to drive several hours six times a
month to visit Santiago in prison, said: ``I want it all out in the
open. I don't know what the outcome will be. But I'm in here to
fight till it's over.''
</P>
<P>
   Santiago, a reputed member of the Nietas gang, was convicted of
killing Fernando Ilarraza, 17, a reputed gang member and drug
dealer in Willimantic, in 1993, after two friends said he told them
about the murder.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-98 2321EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980702.0484 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 23:22 </DATE_TIME>
