A9011 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BURNED-BOY-HNS &LR;      07-02 1032
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BURNED-BOY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS YOUTH, 13, IN CUSTODY OVER BURNING OF BOY ON 8TH BIRTHDAY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (See optional trim, ending) 
 
By PAUL McKAY 
and STEVE OLAFSON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPLENDORA, Texas _ A 13-year-old boy, who police say has
admitted being present when 8-year-old Robert Middleton was set
ablaze, was taken into custody Thursday and later escorted to the
scene of the crime.
</P>
<P>
   The heavy-set teen-ager, who has not been formally charged for
the gruesome attack on the boy but will be held in juvenile
detention at least until Monday, may have been angry at the boy for
having tattled about his witnessing the teen molesting a younger
child in the woods, sources close to the investigation said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do have information that Robert told people he saw (the
teen) molesting a child in the woods some time ago,'' said a
Montgomery County sheriff's investigator.
</P>
<P>
   He added, however, that authorities have not confirmed that that
was the motive for the Sunday afternoon attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has not been formally charged, but he has admitted being
there when the 8-year-old was set on fire,'' Sheriff Guy Williams
said. ``We're making progress, but we're now going to have to
question some other people and keep investigating.``
</P>
<P>
   Williams said other arrests are possible.
</P>
<P>
   The teen was accompanied by sheriff's deputies Thursday night as
they headed down the heavily wooded trail northwest of Splendora
where Robert was doused with gasoline and set on fire near his home
on his 8th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Splendora is about 30 miles north of downtown Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Robert, who is being treated at Shriners Burns
Hospital-Galveston for third-degree burns over 99 percent of his
body, was unable to speak but was able to communicate to hospital
officials Thursday morning that the juvenile now in custody was
present when he was burned.
</P>
<P>
   A sheriff's detective said the boy's communication was enough
for officers to pick up the teen-ager for questioning. The youth
was riding in a pickup with his half-sister's father shortly before
noon when officers took the juvenile into custody at gunpoint.
Deputies promptly released the man.
</P>
<P>
   The juvenile's 23-year-old half-sister, who said Thursday night
that she is his legal guardian, said the boy was leaving for a
fishing trip with her father when the police made the arrest.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't have to harass my father the way they did, and I
can't believe they handcuffed a 13-year-old boy,'' the sister said.
</P>
<P>
   She said she and the boy are related maternally and that their
mother died three years ago. Her brother's biological father, she
said, ``is nowhere around.``
</P>
<P>
   The sister and other relatives of the boy were nearby when he
emerged from the woods with the investigators Thursday night on the
street where Robert Middleton lives with his parents and two
siblings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come and get me,'' the boy mouthed repeatedly to his tearful
sister.
</P>
<P>
   The opening in the woods is the same location where Robert,
known around the neighborhood as ``Robby,'' emerged 40 yards from
his house around 5:45 p.m. Sunday. Investigators say Robert was
heading down the trail to a friend's house in another section of
the rural subdivision but was doused with gasoline and set on fire
a short distance down the trail.
</P>
<P>
   The charred boy managed to walk back to the street in an obvious
attempt to get back to his house when a neighbor came to his aid.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors have told investigators that Robert named another
13-year-old boy as the one who had burned him. They said Robert
told them that the boy was upset at him and had thrown gasoline on
him.
</P>
<P>
   But investigators confirmed Thursday that that boy, who lives
with his mother near the Middletons' home, was away from the
neighborhood Sunday around the time of the burning and has been
cleared of any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to explain why that youth's name had surfaced, Williams
would say only that ``that was a goose chase.``
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said they are exploring the possibility that
Robert may have uttered the youth's name shortly after he was
burned because he was scared of further retaliation by the
teen-ager who is in custody. But investigators cautioned that
information they have from Robert himself remains so sketchy that
they can't be certain of many details.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been almost like investigating a homicide,'' Williams
said. ``The boy wasn't able to tell us anything until today.``
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The mother of the youth whom Robert first named said she and her
son are relieved that he has been cleared. She noted that he is an
A-student and athlete at his Splendora school. One of his teachers
confirmed Thursday that the boy ``is a good kid and excellent
student.``
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said they have confirmed that that boy was with a
group of youths and adults at a swimming hole Sunday evening around
the time that Robert was attacked.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Doctors at the Shriners hospital said that Robert underwent four
hours of skin-graft surgery Monday and faces as many as 14 more
surgeries in the coming months.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David Herndon noted that the most critical time for the
boy's survival probably has passed, although the threat of
infection and pneumonia remain.
</P>
<P>
   Robert is under pain and anti-anxiety medications and is wrapped
in heavy dressings that are changed once a day, Herndon said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a very long road to travel,'' Herndon said. ``One
never fully recovers from this kind of burn.``
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He noted that many such child patients go on to thrive as
students by ``overcompensating with their minds. They do better in
school than their peer groups. They're heroes of the greatest
order.``
</P>
<P>
   The boy's parents, Bobby Ray and Colleen Middleton, both 35, and
their other two siblings have been ``sustained by the prayers of
well-wishers and the donations of money and blood,'' said Craig
Middleton, Robert's paternal uncle.
</P>
<P>
   Having learned that an arrest was made in the case, he noted
that ``I had my faith in the sheriff's department all along.``
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
