</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-HOUSE-SKELETONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW HOME SALE LED TO DISCOVERY OF 2 MURDERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ROBERT HANLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   For nearly 14 years, the bodies of two murder victims, a young
man and a teen-age girl, were hidden in a crude and shallow grave
beneath the crawl space of a tiny Cape Cod house near Atlantic
City, N.J. The homicides might not have been discovered, the
authorities said Thursday, but for the sale of the house and the
new owner's plans to remodel it.
</P>
<P>
   After detectives had spent two days digging and sifting dirt
from the crawl space and backyard at the house, Atlantic County
Prosecutor Jeffrey Blitz said Thursday that two skeletons, shreds
of clothing, three bullets, a baseball bat and a wallet were found
in the three-foot grave beneath 402 Ireland Ave. in Northfield,
N.J. Blitz said his investigators were satisfied that there were no
other bodies buried on the property.
</P>
<P>
   The former owner of the house, Ernest Ireland, 51, an unemployed
bachelor who has been living in a trailer park in Pleasantville,
N.J., has been charged with murder and is being held in $350,000
bail at the Atlantic County Jail.
</P>
<P>
   He was charged late Monday, only a few hours after the new owner
of the house, Bruce Trielo, began excavations in the crawl space
and turned up a thigh bone. Trielo, who had bought the house as an
investment in late May, was planning to enlarge it, first by
putting in a full basement, Blitz said.
</P>
<P>
   The house at 402 Ireland Ave. was the first of six built on the
tiny dead-end street. It was named after Ireland's forebears who
were its first settlers, said a woman who has lived on a nearby
street for 33 years. The woman, who spoke on the condition of
anonymity, said Ireland had lived alone since his mother died in
the mid-1970s. ``You saw him alone all the time, walking or riding
a bike,'' she said. ``He never talked to anybody, and I passed him
almost every day on the street.''
</P>
<P>
   Ireland Avenue was an odd mix of images Thursday. Bricks and
cinder blocks brought in for the remodeling were piled outside
Trielo's house, next to mounds of freshly dug dirt. Across the
street, deliverymen came with supplies for a Fourth of July weekend
picnic.
</P>
<P>
   Several neighbors declined to talk about Ireland or the murders.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor refused to say Thursday whether Ireland had made
a statement. But, he said, his staff believed that the murders
occurred in Ireland's kitchen in late January 1985 and that Ireland
dragged the bodies outside and hid them in the freshly dug grave in
the crawl space.
</P>
<P>
   One of the victims has been identified as Barry Dallman, of
Pleasantville, which is adjacent to Northfield. He died of a
gunshot to the spine at age 21, Blitz said. Dallman was identified
through papers found in the wallet discovered in the grave. Blitz
described Dallman only as an acquaintance of Ireland's. He declined
to discuss a possible motive for the murders.
</P>
<P>
   The teen-age girl has not been identified. She died of blows to
the head, Blitz said. The county medical examiner has determined,
through examination of a pelvic bone, that she was in her early
teens, the prosecutor said. He said detectives believed that the
remains might be those of a 14-year-old girl reported missing by
her foster parents shortly after they dropped her off at
Pleasantville High School on Jan. 24, 1985. She is thought to have
been Dallman's girlfriend, Blitz said.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives are now searching the Atlantic City area for dentists
who may have treated the girl and kept dental records.
</P>
<P>
   Blitz said the chances of finding a dentist with such records
were slim. ``After all,'' he said, ``it's been 14 years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
