<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS SIGN FRASER, A WING 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ While they continued negotiations for several
high-profile free agents Thursday, the New York Rangers announced
the signing of one who is lesser known. Agreeing to terms was Scott
Fraser, a 26-year-old who calls himself ``an up and down right
winger.''
</P>
<P>
   In 29 games with Edmonton last season, Fraser _ whose
traditional style blends offense and defense _ cored 12 goals and
had 11 assists. He was an unrestricted, Group 6 free agent because
his contract had expired, he is more than 25 years old and he had
been a professional for three seasons while playing fewer than 80
professional games. The Rangers owe Edmonton no compensation for
his signing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a late bloomer,'' said Fraser, who will earn about $4
million over a three-year contract. His base salary last season was
$310,000.
</P>
<P>
   On another front, there was no announcement regarding the
Rangers' goalie question. The Rangers have been negotiating with
Mike Richter, the incumbent, and Curtis Joseph, who last played
with Edmonton. Both are unrestricted free agents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
