<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUBLIC-LIVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT `RAGING BULL,' BUT IT'S A START 
GOOD-WILL GOSPEL  
 POLITICS INTRUDES  
 A FAMILIAR SCENE  
 BETWEEN POSES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JAMES BARRON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Drew Nieporent, who as an owner of the TriBeCa Grill
and Nobu has had experience in the care and feeding of food
critics, played one in a film. And no, it is not a film by one of
the other partners in the restaurants, Robert De Niro.
</P>
<P>
   The film, ``Vanilla Fog,'' is a comedy starring the heroine of
television's ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer,'' Sarah Michelle Gellar,
and Sean Patrick Flanery. In a scene that was almost certain to
send foodies into popcorn-dropping shock, Nieporent was supposed to
play a food critic for The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   But Nieporent, who is also an owner of Montrachet, had to go to
Aspen, Colo., and Australia, so the scene was shot while he was
away. ``I was replaced by an English actor, Andrew Seear, who
weighs about a third of what I weigh,'' Nieporent said. ``It was
originally Falstaffian or Orson Wellesean. It became English.''
</P>
<P>
   But Nieporent managed to stay in the film. He became a critic
for a fictional food magazine that sounds a lot like Gourmet,
holding court on a set that looks a lot like the Rainbow Room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't flub my lines at all,'' he said, ``which I found
amazing.'' How hard was it to go from being a restaurateur to
playing a restaurant critic? ``I had to have this sort of, what's
the word, huge confidence about what I was saying,'' he said. ``I
had to feel very big.''
</P>
<P>
   The bubble burst when he returned to the TriBeCa Grill. ``Harvey
Weinstein was holding court with Quentin Tarantino,'' Nieporent
said. ``I thought this was my lucky break, that I'd get cast in the
next one.'' But no.
</P>
<P>
   Good-Will Gospel &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Queen Esther Marrow and her Harlem Gospel Singers are
scheduled to leave this weekend to appear at the Montreal Jazz
Fest. They will be the first gospel group to be featured performers
at the Montreal festival.
</P>
<P>
   So what kind of reception does Ms. Marrow, who performed with
Duke Ellington and appeared in ``The Wiz'' on Broadway, expect in
Canada, which just convened a 19-nation conference on how the world
is being overrun by American culture?
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't know; you can't know,'' she said. ``This is
Afro-American culture, but it's spiritual, it's happiness, it's
good news, it's all the things that are good. It doesn't matter
whether you are American or Japanese or whatever, if it makes you
feel good, I would think they would want it.''
</P>
<P>
   Politics Intrudes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ East met West the other night at a show of Indian
fashions in an unlikely setting, the staid Metropolitan Club, at
Fifth Avenue and 60th Street. The hosts, who included Ismail
Merchant, Georgette Mosbacher and Mary McFadden, had brought
together designers from the subcontinent, who had put together a
collection of outfits that mixed the silks and cottons of the East
with the Audrey Hepburn-in-Paris look of the West.
</P>
<P>
   But nuclear politics hovered over the evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``These things weigh on your mind, even at a beautiful event
like this,'' said the Indian Ambassador to the United States,
Naresh Chandra. Merchant said that designing and exporting clothes
were ``much better than a bomb'' and called the nuclear tests by
India and Pakistan in May ``such a backward step.''
</P>
<P>
   A Familiar Scene
</P>
<P>
   There is talk in London that Madonna, who has earned millions
from songs, videos or books that shock as much as they entertain,
is making a video that has something to do with the death of Diana,
Princess of Wales. The Daily Mirror in London said that Madonna was
filmed wading into what appeared to be a pack of paparazzi the
other day. But The Mirror said that the crowd was made up of extras
who had been outfitted with cameras for a scene similar to one
captured by security cameras at the Ritz in Paris, where Diana and
Dodi Fayed stopped before their final, fatal ride together.
Madonna's spokeswoman, Liz Rosenberg, did not return calls for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Between Poses
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Here is how two models with more or less the same
first name spent the same evening: Christy Turlington took her
84-year-old grandmother, Maria, to ``Cabaret'' and had a long
dressing-room chat with one of the stars, Alan Cumming. Christie
Brinkley had a baby girl Thursday. Her spokeswoman would not say
where the girl, Sailor Lee Brinkley Cook, was born, only that she
weighed 7 pounds, 12 ounces. The father, Ms. Brinkley's husband, is
Peter Cook, an architect.
</P>
</TEXT>
