<HEADER>
A9039 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-LILCO-RULING-NYT &LR;      07-02 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LILCO-RULING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE BARS PATAKI'S PLAN FOR EQUAL REFUNDS TO LILCO CUSTOMERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BRUCE LAMBERT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GARDEN CITY, N.Y. _ A federal judge Thursday struck down as
unconstitutional a crucial part of Gov. George Pataki's formula for
refund checks he wants to send to the 1 million customers of the
defunct Long Island Lighting Co.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the ruling, Pataki administration officials said they
intended to make the refunds anyway, using their own calculation.
The checks are expected to be mailed in September.
</P>
<P>
   The disputed refunds stem from the state's takeover of LILCO's
electricity service on May 28. Customers immediately saw an average
20 percent cut in bills. The governor's plan also calls for issuing
refunds totaling $101 per customer in Suffolk County and $232 in
Nassau County and the Rockaways in Queens. To help finance those
refunds, $82 of each check was supposed to come from the remaining
money LILCO owed customers to settle a 1987 racketeering lawsuit
that accused LILCO of fraud in its handling of the abandoned
nuclear power plant at Shoreham.
</P>
<P>
   But in a decision in U.S. District Court in Brooklyn on
Thursday, Judge Jack Weinstein ruled that payment of the settlement
money must continue under the original formula, which is based on
electricity use. That would funnel more of the refund money to
businesses and institutions that are big consumers of electricity.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's plan of fixed refunds regardless of use was intended to
maximize checks to residential customers. Critics have accused him
of manipulating the racketeering-suit money, which was already owed
to customers, in a political scheme to sway Long Island voters just
weeks before he stands for re-election in November. He has denied
such a political motive, saying his plan helps people more.
</P>
<P>
   To show the drastic difference between the two methods,
Weinstein noted that various federal agencies in the LILCO
territory would qualify for only $17,000 in refunds under Pataki's
method, but under the use-based method they would get $441,000. How
much the judge's ruling might reduce the typical resident's refund
check was not immediately clear.
</P>
<P>
   But Pataki's top aide on the LILCO issue said that the state
would go ahead and issue the checks at the promised amounts.
``Regardless of what the judge has decided,'' said Richard Kessel,
the governor's appointee as chairman of the Long Island Power
Authority, the agency that took over the LILCO system, ``we have
delivered on the 20 percent rate cuts, and we will issue the
rebates of $101 and $232, no matter what.''
</P>
<P>
   Kessel declined to say whether the state would appeal the court
decision. He also declined to specify how the checks would be
financed in the face of the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   The suit originated in 1987 when Suffolk County officials sued
LILCO over the Shoreham plant under the Racketeer Influenced and
Court Organizations Act. To settle the suit, LILCO agreed to refund
$390 million to customers through bill reductions stretching to the
year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The power authority had asked the court to modify how the
remaining $110 million would be paid by speeding the timing to this
fall, reducing the amount by 6 percent and allocating it equally to
each customer. The judge rejected the reduction and the equal
payments, saying that the plan would violate the Constitution's
equal protection, contract and due process clauses.
</P>
<P>
   The Pataki plan would mean that customers ``who are to receive
the greatest compensation under the settlement would be relegated
to collecting only a fraction of what is due to them,'' Weinstein
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``The applicants' proposed radical and major restructuring,'' he
wrote, ``would violate the 14th Amendment's protection against
uncompensated takings of private property by a government entity _
here LIPA.''
</P>
<P>
   He continued: ``LIPA may not now reallocate some class members'
shares of the judgment to others simply because it prefers that
someone else receive the money. The framers of the Constitution
considered such methods of expropriation without compensation
beyond the legitimate scope of government action.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that the power authority's ``arbitrary assessment that
residential ratepayers are more worthy of its generosity than are
large commercial and governmental ratepayers cannot pass
constitutional muster.''
</P>
<P>
   The Citizens Advisory Panel, a LILCO watchdog group created by
the court as an outgrowth of the racketeering suit, opposed the
power authority's plans. The group's director, Gordian Raacke,
said, ``The court clearly found that LIPA and LILCO were jointly
attempting to rob ratepayers of monies that are due to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Raacke also criticized the state's plans to issue the refund
checks as planned. ``This is a slap in the face of the judge,'' he
said. ``It's a blatant attempt to bribe ratepayers _ with their own
money _ into believing that the bailout of LILCO is in their best
interest and to re-elect Governor Pataki.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor's office deferred comment to Kessel, who said that
the Citizens Advisory Panel was ``working against the citizens.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
