<SLUG> BC-RAC-SUBURBAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRISK ME NOW AMONG NINE SET TO MEET IN THE SUBURBAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELMONT, N.Y. _ Racing here will fire its customary Fourth of
July flare Saturday when Belmont Park runs the final race in its
``handicap triple,'' the $350,000 Suburban at a mile and
one-quarter.
</P>
<P>
   And although the Suburban will not involve world-class stars
like Skip Away or Gentlemen, it will feature the best of the next
rank of senior horses, notably the first four finishers in the
Brooklyn Handicap three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Nine horses were entered in the Suburban on Thursday, with the
high weight a surprisingly low 118 pounds assigned to Frisk Me Now,
who ran fourth when the handicap series was started May 25 with the
Metropolitan Mile.
</P>
<P>
   He skipped the Brooklyn on June 13, but will be facing the first
four from that race: Subordination, Sir Bear, Mr. Sinatra and
Accelerator. And Subordination, who led all the way to win the Fort
Marcy in May and the Brooklyn in June, figures to go to the post as
the favorite in the Suburban.
</P>
<P>
   ``My biggest concerns for the Suburban,'' said Gary Sciacca, who
trains Subordination, ``are that we are going to be on the lead and
we'll be going an extra eighth of a mile. But my horse has speed
and, because he has speed, that always makes him dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   The Suburban will be joined on the holiday program by two other
stakes: the $75,000 Poker Handicap at one mile on the turf and the
$75,000 Tremont for 2-year-olds at five and a half furlongs.
</P>
<P>
   But Belmont Park will be staging six stakes during the three-day
weekend, beginning today with the $100,000 Prioress for 3-year-old
fillies at six furlongs and the $75,000 Astoria for 2-year-old
fillies at five and a half furlongs.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend closes Sunday with the $150,000 Tom Fool Handicap at
seven furlongs.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
