<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-TICKETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS PURSUE UPFRONT PAYMENT FOR SEASON SEATS DESPITE LOCKOUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By FRANK LITSKY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Tom Malmud, a New York lawyer, said he was shocked
when he received the renewal notice for his three New York Knicks
season tickets. He was angry that, despite a lockout of the players
by the club owners, threatening the start of the season, the Knicks
have raised ticket prices for their 43 home games in Madison Square
Garden and want full payment upfront.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to retain your seats,'' he said, ``you don't have
a choice. They have you by the seat. I have season seats for the
Mets and Yankees, and when they had labor trouble in 1994, they
took token deposits for 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Knicks have ample opportunity for people who haven't sent
in their money to delay the process. I would have no objection to
sending in a nominal amount. And the Knicks keep the interest on
your deposit no matter when the season starts. You don't go broke
from small profits.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Weiller, a Knicks spokesman, said the renewal bills were
mailed over the Memorial Day weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Last year full payment was required by Aug. 13. This year's
bills told season-ticket buyers they could pay the full amount by
July 13, or half by then and the other half by Aug. 17. The bills
also warned, ``If payment is not received by the due date, your
account will be canceled with no further reminders from MSG.''
</P>
<P>
   Weiller said the due dates would not change.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are working under the assumption that we will have a season
as planned,'' he said. ``If games are lost due to the lockout,
appropriate refunds will be provided. If the lockout is going to
change our plans, the determination hasn't been made.''
</P>
<P>
   About 16,000 of the 19,763 seats available for Knicks home games
are bought by season subscribers. The bills to season ticketholders
were accompanied by a letter from Dave Checketts, the president of
the Garden, who said ticket prices were being raised because of the
increased cost of doing business.
</P>
<P>
   The increases range from 8 to 13 percent. The best seats in the
house, the courtside row where Spike Lee, Dustin Hoffman, John
McEnroe and other celebrities sit, have the highest increase in
dollars ($1,250 a seat last season, $1,350 this season), but the
lowest in percentage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
