<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BATBOY PAID A PRICE DURING ORIOLES-YANKEES BRAWL 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The 2-inch fish hook cut across Joe Rocchio's
forehead is six weeks old. The pink gash might fade, but a plastic
surgeon told the batboy that it would not disappear. Guess what?
Tino Martinez was not the only casualty in the brawl between the
Baltimore Orioles and the New York Yankees on May 19.
</P>
<P>
   ``My friends told me I got a story for life,'' Rocchio said.
``When I'm a grandfather, I can use this.''
</P>
<P>
   It was definitely an unforgettable night, one that Rocchio will
be thinking of when the Orioles return Friday night to the visiting
clubhouse at Yankee Stadium for the first time since that series.
Rocchio, 19, said that May evening was almost as unforgettable as
being the ball boy in left field when third baseman Charlie Hayes
caught a popup for the final out of the 1996 World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Rocchio is conscientious, so when he saw Baltimore reliever
Armando Benitez nail Martinez with a pitch between the shoulder
blades and saw the players fill the field, he left his duties in
the Oriole clubhouse for the Baltimore dugout. Get the bats, get
the helmets and get out of the way, Rocchio told himself.
</P>
<P>
   As Rocchio flung pieces of equipment up the runway so the
players would not trip, a tangle of arms and legs moved closer and
closer to him. Rocchio saw Alan Mills punch Darryl Strawberry and
saw Strawberry lunge at Mills. He was worried. Rocchio reached for
some more bats and helmets, but a security guard who was trying to
clear the dugout tossed him aside. Rocchio landed on the concrete
steps, face first.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Stuart Hershon, the Yankees' physician, told Rocchio he
needed stitches. Hershon gave Rocchio the choice of closing the
wound at the Stadium or going to a hospital for it.
</P>
<P>
   After Rocchio received five stitches, he turned into the
Invisible Man. He dodged the eyes of the Orioles and reporters, not
wanting to answer queries about being injured.
</P>
<P>
   Stanton's Suspension Upheld
</P>
<P>
   Gene Budig, the American League president, declined Thursday to
reduce the five-game suspension he imposed on Mike Stanton for
hitting the Orioles' Eric Davis with a pitch on June 16. Budig's
decision irked Stanton and Manager Joe Torre.
</P>
<P>
   Stanton's suspension will begin with Friday night's game with
the Orioles. Stanton had appealed the suspension during a hearing
in Budig's Manhattan office on June 26.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
