<SLUG> BC-OBIT-CRATSLEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
53 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Pa.)  
 DAVID BRUCE CRATSLEY, PHOTOGRAPHER OF STILL lIFES AND GAY LIFE, (bl)  
 By HOLLAND COTTER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ David Bruce Cratsley, a photographer whose subjects
ranged from light-soaked still lifes and portraits of friends to
celebratory documents of gay and lesbian life in New York City,
died June 29 at Beth Israel Hospital in Manhattan. He was 53.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was complications from AIDS, according to Sarah
Morthland, an art dealer who is an executor of his estate.
</P>
<P>
   Cratsley, who was born in Canton, Pa., and graduated from
Swarthmore College, studied with the photographer Lisette Model at
the New School for Social Research in the early 1970s. Working
under the name Bruce Cratsley, he had shows at numerous New York
galleries, Howard Greenberg, Laurence Miller Gallery and Witkin
among them, and was represented at the time of his death by Yancey
Richardson Gallery in Soho.
</P>
<P>
   A retrospective of Cratsley's photographs (which he referred to
as ``snapshots, really, though carefully made'') was mounted by the
Brooklyn Museum of Art in 1996 to critical acclaim. A monograph on
the artist, titled ``White Light, Silent Shadows,'' was published
by Arena Editions earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   For many years Cratsley documented the annual Gay Pride Parade
in New York, as well as the fashion extravaganza known as Wigstock.
More than a thousand of his pictures of those events are in the
permanent collection of the New York Public Library. His work is
also in the collections of the Metropolitan Museum of Art, the Fogg
Art Museum, Harvard University, and the Bibliotheque National,
Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Cratsley is survived by his companion, William Leight of New
York City; his mother, Jane Cratsley, and a brother John, both of
Concord, Mass.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-98 2346EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
