<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-MYSTICS-MCCRAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUMP TO LOSING CLUB HASN'T FAZED MCCRAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Tenn., Ohio)  (lh) 
 By ED GUZMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Until this summer, Washington Mystics guard Nikki
McCray never knew what it was like to play on a losing team.
</P>
<P>
   From 1991 to 1995, McCray was 122-11 under Coach Pat Summitt at
Tennessee, a stretch that included a Final Four appearance in the
women's national basketball tournament. After graduating with a
degree in sports marketing, she spent her first year out of college
on the U.S. national team in preparation for the 1996 Olympics.
That team steamrolled to a 60-0 record and a gold medal.
</P>
<P>
   Then, as a member of the Columbus Quest of the American
Basketball League, McCray led her team to the league's inaugural
championship, in 1997, by averaging 19.9 points per game. Her
slashing, high-scoring style also made her the ABL's most valuable
player.
</P>
<P>
   But McCray realizes basketball is a business, and in January she
became the first ABL player to jump to the rival Women's National
Basketball Association after its well-publicized first season, in
the summer of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in a great position,'' said McCray of her decision to
switch leagues. ``I only had a one-year contract, so it made me
like a free agent. The WNBA had the marketing, the money and the
stability.''
</P>
<P>
   In March the Quest clinched its second consecutive ABL title,
proving there was life after McCray. Four months later McCray, 25,
is still putting up very impressive numbers. She is averaging 19.2
points per game for the Mystics, and is listed among the top 10 in
the WNBA in assists and steals. Instead of being part of a
championship-caliber squad, though, she is a member of an expansion
team with the league's worst record (1-8).
</P>
<P>
   But there is no sign of regrets from McCray. ``I was very happy
for Columbus because nobody expected them to win it again because I
wasn't there,'' McCray said. ``They had very balanced scoring every
game, and when I was there I always led the team in scoring.''
</P>
<P>
   And although McCray is far from content with the way
Washington's season has unfolded, she remains upbeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now the team is very frustrated,'' McCray said. ``We
didn't expect to be 1-8, but at some point it's got to turn around.
But the positive is, we know it and we have the talent to address
it.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, however, the Mystics are the league's worst team at
taking care of the ball, averaging 23 turnovers per contest. More
unsettling, only three of their eight losses have been by fewer
than 13 points.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most painfully obvious sign of the Mystics'
struggles came Monday night against the Houston Comets (8-1).
Against the top team in the WNBA, Washington was held to a
league-record-low 48 points in a 25-point defeat. The Mystics also
set records for turnovers (33) and steals allowed (21).
</P>
<P>
   Being an expansion team is not necessarily an excuse. Detroit,
the WNBA's other first-year franchise, is on a six-game winning
streak and is only a game and a half behind Charlotte in the
Eastern Conference.
</P>
<P>
   The Mystics will venture into Madison Square Garden Friday night
for a 7:30 p.m. matchup with the Liberty (5-5). Washington does not
have a victory on the road, and New York is looking to bounce back
from an 82-65 loss to Detroit on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The two teams seem to be going in different directions. The
Liberty is starting to come together as it nears next Wednesday's
showdown against Houston while the Mystics are grasping for any
sort of victory to build on in a lost first season.
</P>
<P>
   As the frustration mounts, McCray continues to heed the advice
of Summitt, who is known for keeping in touch with her former
players.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's told me to stay positive and continue to believe,''
McCray said.
</P>
</TEXT>
